<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, July 24.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AZERBAIJAN-REFUGEES (Aghjabedi, Azerbaijan) _ A population of 1
million refugees who fled the invasion by neighboring Armenia into
Azerbaijan's mountainous enclave of Nagorno Karabakh in 1992 is
scattered throughout 40 or more camps in this former Soviet
republic where promised oil riches have yet to materialize and per
capita income is less than $2,000 a year. Long after the fighting
stopped, the refugees remain victims of a little-noticed war,
forgotten by the outside world, insufficiently cared for by their
government and on the verge of abandonment by international aid
organizations. They live without running water, electricity or
medical care in railroad cars, tents, temporary prefabricated
houses and holes in the ground, surviving on a few dollars a month,
on handouts and heartache. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   (Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photos [NYT4,7,8)
have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-WAR-VICTIMS (United Nations) _ From the Caucasus to Kosovo,
Congo, Colombia and East Timor, millions of people have been
displaced by civil war or ethnic violence. But almost everywhere,
particularly in Africa, they struggle to survive without
international help because they have not crossed an international
border and are not, strictly speaking, refugees. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TELL-ALL (Mexico City) _ The former girlfriend of the
brother of a former president, Raul Salinas, has written a tell-all
book that has made her a national celebrity. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-LOST-NEIGHBORHOOD (Philadelphia) _ Sparing the
approaching Republican national convention a civic eyesore,
bulldozers are moving in on the last of the 957 sinking homes of
Logan Triangle, a stricken working-class swath of north
Philadelphia that has festered as an urban disaster for more than a
decade. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   NC-HEZBOLLAH (Charlotte, N.C.) _ How a Hezbollah offshoot made
its home in a middle-class southern city. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DROUGHT (Throckmorton, Texas) _ Almost every corner of
Texas knows the grip of drought this year. But here, more than
anywhere else, that grip is a choke hold. In about 50 days, maybe
60, officials say, the lake that provides water for the 1,063
residents here will go dry _ unless there is a miraculous turn in
the weather. So last week the town began a variation of an old-time
barn raising: volunteers are working to dig about 20 miles of
underground pipeline to connect with a water system in the nearby
town of Elbert before time, and water, run out. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Austin, Texas) _ A cardiac surgeon in Houston who
described himself as a longtime friend of the Bush family said
Sunday that both Gov. George W. Bush and his father, former
President Bush, had asked him on Friday to consult by telephone
with one of Dick Cheney's physicians and help determine if Cheney
``was up to a strenuous campaign.'' By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL-CAMPAIGN _ After many years of being outspent and
out-muscled by the National Rifle Association, the gun-control
movement has begun the most ambitious campaign in its history to
raise money, recruit foot soldiers and build public support for
stronger gun laws in preparation for this fall's national
elections. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-POLITICS _ Republicans warn of the dangers of a big,
``one-size fits-all'' prescription drug program for the elderly,
run by the heavy hand of government bureaucrats. Democrats rail
against the prospect of elderly Americans at the mercy of
profit-hungry pharmaceutical companies, and scoff at Republican
efforts to provide drug coverage through the private sector. For
months now, pollsters and strategists in both parties have been
testing and honing these arguments. But as the recent drug bill
passed by House Republicans underscored, all the positioning comes
down to an old philosophical division between the parties, many
analysts say: How big a role should the government play in
providing health care? By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPENDING _ Stung by charges that it is a ``do-nothing
Congress'' that cannot govern, House and Senate leaders have pushed
through a series of spending measures with a speed that has
surprised many long-time congressional watchers. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   WHISTLEBLOWER-MANUSCRIPT _ A whistleblower's manuscript that the
government suppressed on security grounds contains little new
information, but strongly criticizes the FBI for mishandling the
government's investigation into evidence that China stole U.S.
nuclear secrets. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   GARMENT-PROFILE (Washington) _ Leonard Garment and his new book.
Does he identify Deep Throat? By John Files.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT5) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RICHARDSON _ Not long ago, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson's
name was exactly where he wanted it to be, near the top of every
list of likely Democratic vice presidential nominees. A few even
guessed the nomination was his to lose. Then June rolled around,
and a confluence of events _ the Washington version of ``The
Perfect Storm'' _ swallowed Richardson whole. On the heels of a
scandal possibly involving espionage, two computer hard drives
containing nuclear secrets went missing at Los Alamos, gasoline
prices skyrocketed, and Congress turned on the former House member
with a vengeance. Now Richardson's name is no longer on any list.
By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-MIGRATION (Jacksonville, Fla.) _ Companies have been
migrating for decades, moving operations both within the United
States and overseas for many reasons, including the search for
cheaper labor. But since 1996, corporate migration within the
country has soared, roughly doubling to more than 11,000 moves a
year, according to Site Selection Magazine of Atlanta, the only
organization to track the phenomenon. At the same time, the
emphasis has shifted from factories, the traditional migrants, to
every type of service operation, and across a range of jobs. By Lou
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Two graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   STEPHENKING-ONLINE-MEDIA (Undated) _ On Monday, Stephen King
will be offering his new book online _ without a publisher. How
worried is the publishing industry? By David D. Kirkpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-DEVELOP (Undated) _ Individual software developers have
become a hot commodity. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-COMMERCE (Undated) _ Big communications companies are
trying their best to capitalize on Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ACTORS-STRIKE (Undated) _ The actors strike against the
advertising industry is now in its 13th week. Many small businesses
in Los Angeles and New York that make up the commercial production
industry _ from casting directors to talent agencies to editing
studios _ are being battered by the long strike. No one knows just
how much the strike has cost, but the Entertainment Industry
Development Corp., a quasi-public organization, estimates that Los
Angeles County is losing about $1 million a day. The association
that represents camera rental companies figures that that business
is off by 15 percent. Other trade groups say things are even worse.
By Terry Pristin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT1) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CLAIROL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Advertising column: After
years of working with more mature celebrities, Clairol will feature
the pop singer Britney Spears in a new print and television
advertising campaign for its Herbal Essences shampoo line. By
Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: Companies
that sell products in stores and on the Web typically haven't
integrated their customer databases _ so that a person who buys a
Sony TV in a store can't get warranty information about that unit
from the Sony Web site, or vice versa. That's about to change, as
companies including Sony, KMart and Borders are beginning to
install so-called ``customer resource management.'' By Bob
Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The New Economy column: What to make
over the wildly inconsistent public attitudes toward electronic
privacy. By Tim Race.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-TV-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ National Iranian Television, which
features Farsi-language news, lifestyle and cultural programming,
is the fifth Iranian-American TV station to be established in Los
Angeles, which is home to an estimated 600,000 Iranians. But it is
the first to broadcast to a worldwide audience. By Jordan Raphael.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REALITY-MEDIA (Pasadena, Calif.) _ At a television
conference, TV executives talk about the pitfalls of reality TV. By
Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANIMATION-DECLINE (Phoenix) _ It may not be dead, but some are
wondering whether animation's pulse _ at least the traditional,
two-dimensional variety made by anyone other than Disney _ might be
fading, perhaps signaling an end to a costly, five-year cycle that
saw several major movie studios build their own traditional
animation divisions in an attempt to steal a bit of Disney's
thunder. Audiences seem to be demanding up-to-the-minute digital
magic and shying away from the kind of traditional animation they
remember from years past _ unless the movie has the name Disney
attached to it. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FOX-BERMAN (Hollywood) _ A talk with the new head of
entertainment at Fox Broadcasting, Gail Berman. She's an anomaly in
the television business _ an executive with a taste for the offbeat
who is rooted in the New York theater. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   GUERNICA-REVISIT (Guernica, Spain) _ Strolling around the serene
square of this Basque town not far north of Bilbao, it is hard to
imagine the scene as it was some 60 years ago, when an indelible
atrocity took place here on the eve of World War II. Only a few
outward marks of physical devastation are still visible, but the
human damage remains embedded in people's minds. By Herbert
Mitgang.
</P>
<P>
   BLIND-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Janet Maslin reviews ``A Blind Man
Can See How Much I Love You,'' by Amy Bloom.
</P>
<P>
