<SLUG> BC-BOEING-ROLLOUT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING ROLLS OUT NEWEST, MAYBE LAST OF 737 FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a ceremony that spanned the Atlantic, The Boeing Co.
Sunday rolled out the newest, longest and what is likely to be the
final member of its next-generation 737 family, the popular
twinjets that will soon be produced in record numbers to meet
strong sales.
</P>
<P>
   Led by a team of Alaskan sled dogs, symbolic of launch customer
Alaska Airlines, the 737-900 slowly left the Renton factory to the
cheers of several thousand employees.
</P>
<P>
   The event was televised live by satellite to a hotel ballroom in
downtown London, where Boeing executives, including Chairman Phil
Condit and commercial airplane boss Alan Mulally, held an evening
reception for customers, suppliers and guests on the eve of the
Farnborough International air show.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an exciting way to start out the air show,'' Mulally said
as three-time Iditarod race champion Doug Swingley of Montana and
his dogs escorted the new jet from the factory.
</P>
<P>
   The 737-900 program was begun in November 1997 with an order for
10 planes from Alaska, which wanted a jet that would seat about 15
more passengers than the 737-800. The airline has since ordered one
additional jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here today ... because Boeing, like any
industry-leading company, did what is so vitally important _ they
listened to their customer,'' John Kelly, chairman of Alaska
Airlines, said as he watched in Renton with Alaska Airlines
employees.
</P>
<P>
   That first 737-900 will be delivered to Alaska in April after
flight testing.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said Alaska will eventually use the new jets on its
Seattle-Anchorage runs, replacing older model 737-400s that seat
138 passengers. The 737-900 can carry up to 177 passengers in a
two-class configuration.
</P>
<P>
   Because fewer planes will be needed to haul the same number of
passengers, Alaska expects to save $18 million a year on its
Seattle-Anchorage flights, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Alaska kicked off the 737-900 program, Continental
Airlines has ordered 15, Korean Airlines 16 and KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines four, for a total of 46 firm orders.
</P>
<P>
   Like Alaska, the three carriers will take delivery of their
first 737-900s next year.
</P>
<P>
   The 737-900 joins three smaller siblings in the next-generation
family _ the -600, -700 and -800 series.
</P>
<P>
   The 737-700 has the greatest range, and Alaska recently started
using that model to fly from Anchorage to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   This is the last offspring, according to Boeing, though it is
studying an even longer-range version of the 737-700.
</P>
<P>
   The 737-900 is a stretched version of the 737-800. Boeing added
a forward body plug of 62 inches and an aft plug of 42 inches,
which increased the overall length by 8 feet 8 inches. It is the
longest 737 ever.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum seating capacity of the 737-900 is 189, a limit
imposed by federal regulation based on the number of exit doors and
how quickly passengers can get out in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   All four next-generation models have the same wingspan.
</P>
<P>
   The -600 series is the shortest of the four, at 102 feet 6
inches. It carries about 110 passengers in a two-class
configuration.
</P>
<P>
   The 737-900 is 138 feet 2 inches in length. The 737-900
fuselage, which includes everything but the tail section and the
nose radome, is 124 feet 4 inches long. That's 4 feet longer than
the Wright brothers' first flight.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has so far racked up 1,602 orders for its next-generation
737s. So far this year, Boeing has 244 firm 737 orders. That's
better than the 737 did in all of 1999. Last month, on the heels of
a record Southwest order for 94 737-700s, Boeing announced plans to
increase production next year.
</P>
<P>
   The rate will increase from the current 24 per month to 28 with
deliveries in the third quarter of 2001. That will be the most 737s
Boeing has ever produced in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing could announce additional 737 orders at the Farnborough
show that opens Monday outside London. But the Boeing plane getting
most of the attention will be the super-long-range 777X, which was
launched earlier this year. Boeing Monday is expected to announce
up to 30 orders worth more than $5 billion at list prices.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rival Airbus Industrie is expected Monday to announce
the first firm order for its A3XX, the 555-seater that could be
launched by the end of the year if Airbus gets enough customers.
Emirates Airlines could be the first to buy the plane. It
reportedly wants up to 10 of the jets, which will have a list price
of about $230 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
