<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES SHUT OUT METS, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Trades and non-trades haunted the New York Mets on
Sunday. In the morning, General Manager Steve Phillips acknowledged
that the Cincinnati Reds' Barry Larkin had turned down a deal to
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon, as the Mets lounged in their Turner Field
clubhouse, some of them watched on television as the All-Star Jason
Isringhausen _ who was traded by the Mets last July _ closed out a
victory for the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sunday night, the Mets were beaten, 1-0, by the Atlanta
Braves, who got a magnificent pitching performance from Andy Ashby,
who just came over in a trade from the Philadelphia Philllies.
Phillips received even more frustrating news during the game when
he heard that Larkin had signed a contract extension with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby threw a complete game in blanking the Mets on four hits.
The Braves took two of three games from the Mets this weekend and
increased their lead in the National League East to six games. They
beat Bobby J. Jones, whose record fell to 4-5 despite a solid
outing and some sparkling defense from Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who has made diving catches all season, made perhaps his
most dramatic catch yet in the fifth inning. With two runners on
and two outs, Chipper Jones lofted a high fly to right. Bell
drifted back, timed his leap and stretched his arm over the fence
for the catch. Beaming, Bell held his glove high for several
seconds as he skipped in from right field. But the Braves' charge
was only momentarily stopped. Brian Jordan singled to lead off the
sixth, and scored when Wally Joyner doubled down the right-field
line. After a ground out and an intentional walk put runners at the
corners, Dennis Cook came in to retire Keith Lockhart and Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   Jones lasted only five and one-third innings, his shortest stint
since he returned from Class AAA Norfolk a month ago. But with each
start, he is answering more questions. Jones had a 10.19 earned run
average in eight starts before going to the minors; in seven starts
since, he has a 3.25 ERA. Jones is still hittable _ he has allowed
17 hits in his last 111/3 innings _ but has better command of his
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Both starters escaped bases-loaded jams in the early innings.
Jones allowed a one-out single to Javy Lopez in the second, then
walked the next two hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mike Piazza came to the mound, and after Jones threw a
ball on the first pitch to Ashby, the pitching coach Dave Wallace
came out for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   His advice must have worked. Ashby popped out and Rafael Furcal
flied to left to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth _ after Lenny Harris was picked off first by the
catcher, Lopez, following his leadoff single _ Bell walked and Jay
Payton doubled off the left-field wall. Piazza walked to load the
bases, but Todd Zeile bounced to the shortstop, starting a double
play that ended the inning and kept the game scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets spoke to the Phillies about Ashby, but Phillips has
said the talks never got far. Ashby can be a free agent after the
year, and the Mets had no young, major league-ready pitchers they
could spare in the deal, as the Braves did when they sent Bruce
Chen to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby got himself in trouble in the ninth, when he overthrew
first baseman Joyner on Payton's soft leadoff grounder. Payton got
to second, but Piazza grounded out and Zeile lined out after
fouling off four pitches with two strikes. Benny Agbayani just
missed a line-drive hit down the right-field line that would have
tied the game, then grounded to short for the final out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
