<SLUG> BC-CHEAPER-DRUGS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA OFFERS SAME PRESCRIPTIONS AS U.S. AT CHEAPER PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SURREY, B.C. _ Woody Crandall's epiphany came near the
prescription counter at the back of London Drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed and shook his head at the wonder of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes medication that costs 62 cents a pill back home in
Marysville costs only 7 cents a pill in British Columbia. An ulcer
medicine costs him $1.03 a pill at home. He can get the same
medicine for 13 cents a pill in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same damn company and the same damn pills,'' said
Crandall, 64.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall has joined a growing corps of Washington state senior
citizens who are crossing the border and abandoning their
neighborhood drug stores for British Columbia. Saddled with fixed
incomes and monthly prescription bills in the hundreds or thousands
of dollars, they have found a pharmacy haven just across the 49th
parallel.
</P>
<P>
   The savings are enormous. A recent survey by the office of U.S.
Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., shows that the 10 most commonly
prescribed drugs in Washington are an average of 61 percent cheaper
in British Columbia. That includes not only the lower cost of drugs
but also a favorable exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   A trickle of American customers to pharmacies just across the
border has become a stream in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 Americans a day walk into the Peninsula Medical Clinic
to see a doctor and meet the British Columbia requirement of having
a prescription written by a local physician, said Dr. Paul Zickler.
The clinic is in the same south Surrey shopping center as London
Drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey Tichi and his wife, Agnes, both of Seattle, were there in
May and saved nearly $500.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can save $500 bucks every three months, shoot, I can put
that money to better use,'' Dewey Tichi said.
</P>
<P>
   Business for writing prescriptions ``in Canadian'' for the
Tichis and others has gotten so brisk that the Peninsula clinic
will open a second facility a few doors away just to cater to
Americans. At the same time, the clinic is trying to get an
Internet site running so that its physicians can correspond
electronically with the doctors treating the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, a private company may soon make regular bus runs to
Surrey to accommodate cost-conscious seniors, Zickler said.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is startling, especially if you saw the smiles on
the faces of Crandall, his wife, Sylvia, and her sister Jean
Allison as they sat on a bench outside London Drugs. In all, they
saved more than $4,000 on 11 prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of money,'' Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of prescription drugs has gotten the attention of
politicians nationwide in addition to that of the senior citizens
in Washington state. In Washington, D.C., Congress is debating ways
of increasing insurance coverage for prescription medicines.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, consumer, labor and seniors groups hope to
persuade the Legislature to adopt a measure similar to Maine's that
would result in lower negotiated prices or regulated prices for
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The price of prescription drugs in the United States has been
fodder for political debate for at least 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the world's industrialized nations, only the United
States does not control the price of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Drug makers say unregulated prices give them the incentive to
spend more on research and development. Indeed, the U.S. leads the
world in introducing new drugs to the market.
</P>
<P>
   And the pharmaceutical industry is richly rewarded. Typically,
the industry ranks as the most profitable in the Fortune 500
ranking of the largest companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, about one in four Americans don't have
insurance coverage for prescription drugs. Medicare, which is for
older Americans, pays for drugs in hospitals and nursing homes but
not elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly significant because seniors consume about a
third of all the prescriptions filled in the United States. Still,
two of every three seniors have some sort of coverage that helps to
pay for prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Drug coverage varies widely from generous payments to slight
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, for example, gets $1,000 annually for drugs from a
Teamsters union program. That doesn't go far, however, because her
drugs cost her nearly $500 a month in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She gets by. Her sister Sylvia Crandall says they know how to do
that. After all, they grew up in a Connecticut home where eight
children slept in one bed.
</P>
<P>
   Allison and her companion Richard Dupuis live in an RV,
following the sun through the year. Dupuis, 66, said he can pick up
work when he wants it _ fixing a tractor in Marysville or maybe
tending bar in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Crandalls live part of the year in an RV near Marysville and
the rest in their RV in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Crandall says they live happily and without a telephone,
cable television or a computer.
</P>
<P>
   They also sometimes have to live without all the medicine they
need.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall says he would have to pay more than $600 a month for
prescriptions out of his own pocket in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told my doctor, `If I have to pay that, I'm not going to
take it,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to live just to take pills,'' added his wife,
Sylvia.
</P>
<P>
   So they've learned to economize with medicines as they have
learned to economize elsewhere. They might just take a pill every
other day, Sylvia Crandall said.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, who just had cataract surgery, said she sometimes cuts
a pill in half to make one dosage last two days.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only Allison and the Crandalls. ``A lot of people who
come here have not been taking their medications,'' said Zickler,
the Surrey physician. ``They can't afford them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, Americans buy prescriptions in bulk _ enough to last
six months. And they pay the clinic $30 for which they get their
prescription rewritten and a consultation with a physician who asks
about their health and makes sure they understand what the
medicines are for.
</P>
<P>
   That seniors are willing to drive two hours to a foreign country
underscores that something is wrong in the United States, some
people who study the pharmaceutical industry say.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the face of it, it's silly that people have to do this,''
said Thomas Hazlet, an assistant pharmacy professor at the
University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But many senior citizens are too frail or too poor to get to
Canada. That leaves them at the mercy of local drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   Are they too high?
</P>
<P>
   To critics like Art Zoloth, drug companies charge ``whatever the
market will bear'' in the United States. Zoloth is a former
director of pharmacy at Virginia Mason Medical Center and also
served on the state pharmacy board.
</P>
<P>
   ``What jumps out at you is that the system is out of control.
The industry has really taken advantage of the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug industry is secretive about prices. But it's no secret
that it sells its drugs in Canada or France or England for less
than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in prices represents return on investment, which
allows the company to sustain research and development, said Jeff
Trewhitt, a spokesman for the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America.
</P>
<P>
   Research and development has become the drug industry's armor
against price control.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. drug companies are responsible for about half of all new
medicines developed each year. The industry will spend $26.5
billion on research this year, Trewhitt said. But only one of every
five medicines that reaches clinical trials ever makes it to the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations enjoy the benefits of U.S. innovation while
American consumers pay for it, drug companies say.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian drug industry, for example, ``doesn't register on
the radar screen, largely because of price controls,'' Trewhitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had the same rigid Canadian-style price controls in this
country, it would be difficult if not impossible to sustain the
same level of innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton aims to rectify price differences. He has introduced
legislation that would invoke a law against price discrimination.
In theory, it would increase prices abroad and lower them at home.
</P>
<P>
   Zoloth doesn't believe the drug companies' line about research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any sense that a research-intensive industry
is going to say, `Whoops, no more research.'''
</P>
<P>
   The solution for the drug industry is to get people insurance
coverage so they can afford prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Congress may decide to do that later this year.
</P>
<P>
   People like Dewey Tichi don't have a vote in Congress. But
Tichi, who has high-blood pressure, high cholesterol and a
pacemaker, can vote with his pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   When the 90 days worth of pills he and his wife bought in Surrey
runs out, they will head north.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not poor, but I'm not rich either,'' he said. ``Gosh, I
don't want to give all my money to those drug companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
