<HEADLINE>
SPARKS MOVE INTO FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The three-time defending champion Houston
Comets had already lost to New York earlier Sunday, opening the
door for the Sparks to seize first place for the first time ever
this late in the WNBA season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Monarchs tried to steal the opportunity with a
late rush, but the Sparks rose to the challenge and emerged with a
73-68 victory that gives them a 1/2-game lead over the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again we're not looking at this as staying in first place,''
Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. ``We just have to take care of
our business and let other people worry about theirs and if we stay
in first place fine. But I think we set a pattern for what we want
and that's going into the playoffs on a strong note.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks improved to 21-3 on the season, while the Comets
dropped to 21-4, their first loss since losing for the second time
to the Sparks on July 14. The Sparks have two more home games
(Tuesday against Orlando, Thursday against Seattle), before
embarking on a six-game road trip that begins in Houston Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The victory in front of 8,482 at the Forum gave the Sparks their
fifth consecutive win and 15th in the last 16 games. The Monarchs
(15-10) tried their best to snap the WNBA's hottest team's current
streak, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks saw their 12-point margin midway through the second
half evaporate after an onslaught by the Monarchs. A layup by
Yolanda Griffith (19 points) with 3:55 to play tied the score at
66, but she missed a free throw that would have given the Monarchs
the advantage for the first time since early in the game (3-2).
</P>
<P>
   A free throw by forward DeLisha Milton (13 points, 11 rebounds)
and a basket by guard Tamecka Dixon (14 points, seven assists) gave
the Sparks a three-point lead, but Monarch's guard Ruthie
Bolton-Holifield knocked down a 12-footer to bring her team within
one.
</P>
<P>
   Center Lisa Leslie (20 points, eight rebounds) made a 10-foot
jumper to put the Sparks back up by three with 1:09 remaining.
About minute later reserve Allison Feaster, who had a career game
off the bench, came up with a key rebound after Bolton-Holifield
missed a 3-point attempt that could have tied the game with seconds
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon went to the line and made two free throws to seal the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big night for Feaster, who had career-high 18 points,
five rebounds and three assists. She was 6 of 10 from the field,
and 3 of 5 from 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches give me a lot of confidence and my teammates give
me great passes and set me up really well,'' said Feaster, who led
the NCAA in scoring in her final season at Harvard in 1997-98.
``All that's left to do is make the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   And she didn't disappoint.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
