<SLUG> BC-REALITY-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIG BROTHER'S' FIRST CASTOUT SPARS WITH PRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ William Collins, the first houseguest
banished from CBS' voyeuristic ``Big Brother'' show, faced
reporters for the first time Sunday, talking a lot but shedding
little light on his controversial political affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Before his banishment last week, Collins was reported to be a
member of the New Black Panther Party, led by reputed hate-monger
Khalid Abdul Muhammad. Collins, also known as Mega, arrived at the
Ritz Carlton Hotel with a reported five-car security detail.
</P>
<P>
   He was there for the ``Big Brother'' panel of CBS' summer press
tour, three days in which the hot topic was reality TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' has a lock on the summer ratings, but ``Big
Brother,'' airing six nights a week from Studio City, was the
attention-getter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to show books he brought with him, Collins held up a Bible
(``You've seen me with my gun, but you haven't seen me with my
God''), a Webster's Dictionary (helpful, he said, in understanding
and using ``the words of our enemy''), and a copy of ``48 Laws of
Power'' by Robert Greene and Joost Elffers, one of the books he
used ``in manipulating the houseguests.''
</P>
<P>
   His tone turned brusque when asked who he sees as his enemies.
``Those who oppose God. The unrighteous. The evil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He asked to be addressed as ``Will Mega.'' When a reporter from
his hometown, Philadelphia, wanted to ask him a question, he
demanded she first tell him what she had written about him,
prompting other reporters to boo.
</P>
<P>
   He complained that the few ``Big Brother'' shows he has seen
portrayed ``a major imbalance,'' showing only the confrontations
and not the more peaceful Will Mega who prayed at least twice a
day. But Executive Producer Paul Romer said Collins' confrontations
were a compelling part of the daily highlights packed into each
22-minute program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people out there who say this show is boring,''
Romer said. ``What would be boring is if we showed the lowlights.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins refused to elaborate on his comment Thursday about which
of Muhammad's beliefs he still ascribes to and which he has
rejected. He said he was not surprised to learn that the story
about his affiliation came out, saying the New York Police
Department probably leaked it because he has loudly criticized the
NYPD for brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to predict which of his housemates will be the three
finalists, Collins said, ``Cassandra, because she's the smartest
person in the house; Eddie, because he understands that it's a
contest; and Josh, because he's the all-American white boy.''
</P>
<P>
   He also was asked whether he truly hoped to win the $500,000
grand prize or if he was trying to get himself voted out in order
to get a national media platform for his views.
</P>
<P>
   ``My competitive nature makes me want to win everything that I
engage in. (But) there wasn't enough mental stimulus.'' he said.
``That was the major battle _ my will to win combined with not
having enough mental stimuli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm X said in his autobiography that prison was the
second-best place a man could go to get his mind right,'' Collins
went on. ``It was this experience for me that allowed me to really
understand what he meant, in that when all of those things in your
life, all those basic responsibilities are taken care of and basic
needs are met ... when you're quarantined, it forces you to dwell
within yourself and within your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   During the ``Survivor'' panel, Gretchen Cordy said she thinks
living under ``Big Brother'' conditions would be much harder than
what she endured marooned in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather be out in nature,'' she said. ``If B.B.
(Andersen) and I got a little tired of each other, we could walk
off. To be in that nest? No thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, CBS President Leslie Moonves announced that
``Survivor 2: the Australian Outback'' will debut immediately
following Super Bowl XXXV. He praised ``Survivor'' and ``Big
Brother'' for bringing CBS back to the water cooler, something that
probably has not happened since ``Murphy Brown'' and ``Northern
Exposure'' about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, when confronted with questions about the ethical issues
of ``Big Brother,'' or its less-than-stellar ratings, he
characterized it as ``an experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   One time Moonves sidestepped with ``doesn't anybody have a 'Yes,
Dear' question?'' referring to one of his new sitcoms
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
