<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRIALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN COMES UP LAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino Sun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO -- The Sactown Showdown? A meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene each pulled up lame in the
200-meter final on a scorching summer Sunday afternoon in
Sacramento, ruining one of the most anticipated races in years on
American soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world wanted to see a great show,'' Greene said.
``Unfortunately, Michael and myself weren't able to give them the
show they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, because it was a goal of mine'' to win
another 200-meter Olympic gold medal, Johnson said. ``But you can't
have everything .''
</P>
<P>
   The closing event of the 2000 U.S. Olympic Track and Field
Trials turned into a war of attrition won by 21-year-old John Capel
in a fastest-of -the-weekend time of 19.85 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Capel hit the finish line, with Floyd Heard and Coby
Miller close behind, Johnson was lying back on the curve, grimacing
in pain from a cramped left hamstring, and Greene was limping 50
meters further up the track, also a victim of a spasming hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Neither will run the 200 at the Sydney Olympics two months
hence. ``It's frustrating for everybody,'' said Marion Jones,
women's 200-meter champ. ``The fact you have two of the fastest men
in the world and they both go down ... it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning conclusion to a race pitting infrequent
competitors, unfriendly rivals and world-record holders in the 100
(Greene, 9.79), 2 00 (Johnson, 19.32) and 400 (Johnson, 43.18)
meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling you, it's not just Michael and Maurice, Michael
and Maurice,'' Johnson said. ``It ended up (ticking) the other guys
off, and they went out and ran real fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Capel's time was .01 faster than Greene's career best in the
200, and quicker than all but one time Johnson has recorded in the
event this year.
</P>
<P>
   In other action on a day featuring an orgy of 10 finals, Jones
set up her bid to become the first woman to win five track and
field gold medals at the Olympics by winning the 200 in 21.94
seconds; Gail Devers set an American record in the women's
100-meter hurdles; The Clark Family went 1-2-3 in the women's 800;
and pole-vaulter Stacy Dragila set the only world record of the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila cleared 15 feet, 2 1/4 inches, clipping her own world
mark of 15-1 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted was to make the team,'' Dragila said. ``To get
the world record is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The final event of the eight-day meet was also the closest
watched -- the Johnson-Greene duel. They had sniped verbally for
months, each had won an event here earlier (Greene the 100, Johnson
the 400) and were headed for a collision in the 200, the only event
they each run.
</P>
<P>
   Chances of a classic collision took a hit Saturday, when Johnson
reported a cramp in his right quadriceps. But he appeared for his
semifinal heat Sunday and, running carefully, defeated Greene 20.03
to 20.30. It was only the third time they have raced, and Johnson's
second victory.
</P>
<P>
   Capel won the semi in 20.03.
</P>
<P>
   Only 90 minutes later, on an afternoon where temperatures soared
over 100 degrees, Johnson and Greene were out on the track again.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the short turnaround on a torrid day may have been
a factor in his injury. And Greene's. ``You're more likely to cramp
on a hot day,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson began limping only 50 meters into the race, and
eventually tumbled to the track, holding up his left leg. ``It was
a really severe cramp,'' he said. ``It just wouldn't let go.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, running inside Johnson in Lane 2, was unaware his rival
had gone down when he began limping heavily. He clutched at his
left hamstring as he came to a halt at the top of the straight.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was taken off the track in a cart. Greene hobbled off
under his own power.
</P>
<P>
   Each believes his injury is not serious, and should not impede
attempts to win gold in the 100 and 400 at Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   -- Jones appeared to struggle the final 100 meters of the
women's 200, but held off Inger Miller, who clocked 22.09. Nanceen
Perry was third. Jones wants to win gold in the 100, 200, long jump
and both relays. She won the 100, 200 and long jump here, and said,
``It's been a long week, and I'm glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   -- A desperate lunge at the finish line made it an all-Clark
affair in the women's 800. Hazel Clark won in 1:58.97, and
sister-in-law Jearl Miles-Clark, the American-record holder was
second.
</P>
<P>
   Joetta Clark-Diggs, Hazel's half-sister, caught Meredith
Rainey-Valmon on the last stride of the race, and finished in
1:59.49 -- .01 ahead of Rainey-Valmon.
</P>
<P>
   All three women are coached by J.J. Clark, brother of Hazel and
Joetta and husband of Jearl. They hugged and broke into tears.
</P>
<P>
   -- Devers broke her own American record in the women's 100-meter
hurdles, clocking 12.33 (No.4 all-time) and establishing herself as
the favorite to win gold at Sydney. Devers twice won the 100-meter
gold, but has never medaled in an Olympic hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   -- Defending Olympic gold-medalist and American-record holder
Charles Austin, 32, won high-jump qualifying with a mark of 7-7
1/4, holding off the younger generation led by Arkansas junior
Kenny Evans, 21 and Nathan Leeper, 23. Evans and Leeper each
cleared 7-5 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   -- Andy Setliff, a part-timer actor, stole the show in the men's
discus final, winning with a mark of 209-10. John Godina, 1996
silver-medalist in the shot who failed to make the 2000 team in the
event, finished second in the discus at 208-8, and 1999 world
champion Anthony Washington was third at 207-10.
</P>
<P>
   -- Allen Johnson, Olympic gold-medalist in 1996, won the men's
110-meter hurdles in 12.97 seconds, fastest time in the world this
year. Mark Crear was second in 13.11, and rising star Terrence
Trammell third in 13. 19.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mark Everett qualified for his third Olympics, winning the
men's 80 0 in 1:45.67. Rich Kenah and Bryan Woodward ran 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   -- Robert Howard won the men's triple jump in 55-9, followed by
LaMark Carter and Walter Davis. Davis also qualified for the
Olympic team in the long jump.
</P>
</TEXT>
