<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS RUIN SEATTLE SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If this three-game series against Texas proved
anything, it was that the Mariners, as good as they have been in
the 2000 season, haven't quite mastered the art of the kill.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners came into Sunday's game having won the first two
games against an obviously downtrodden Rangers team. Texas is the
defending AL West champion, true, but last year's success won't buy
the Rangers a ticket to the postseason this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had a chance to fit the Rangers for a three-game pine
box, but couldn't get the measurements done. The Rangers did just
enough right and the Mariners just enough wrong to earn Texas a 3-2
win over Seattle, denying the Mariners a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let one get away today,'' left fielder Rickey Henderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Oakland, the team that many picked to win the AL West this
year, comes to Safeco Field to begin a three-game series Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a big series, but it's an important series,''
Henderson said, quickly explaining the difference. ``The big series
don't start for another month or so, when there aren't that many
games left.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you play teams in your division, it's always
important.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are in first place, four games ahead of the
second-place A's, and the outcome of this series could do much to
sculpt the form of the AL West race the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the guys chasing us,'' center fielder Mike Cameron
said of the A's. ``These are the guys we have to battle.''
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for this battle, Seattle has added one game to
its lead over the A's in the West since the All-Star break,
including splitting a pair of games in Oakland last week.
</P>
<P>
   The lead increase would have been two games if the Mariners had
been able to walk away from Sunday's game a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they made a couple of small mistakes that had big
consequences. In the top of the fourth, catcher Dan Wilson let a
pitch from starter Freddy Garcia get past him for a passed ball,
allowing a run to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bonehead play on my part,'' Wilson said. ``I cost us
the game. I guess you could say that about a lot of things, but
Freddy pitched too good for us to lose this one.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the fourth, John Olerud reached third base with
no one out and didn't score. Cameron, Jay Buhner and David Bell
couldn't get the run home against Rick Helling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of chances to get something done,'' Cameron
said. ``I know I had one and didn't come through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we don't worry about that anymore. We've got important
games coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Helling's gritty pitching as much as anything that
brought the Rangers home and kept Seattle at bay. The Mariners,
down 2-0 after the Wilson passed ball and a subsequent run-scoring
grounder by Mike Lamb in the fourth, got single runs in the fifth
and seventh to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Helling's specialty of the day was making sure each rally was
worth just one run. It was just the kind of performance you'd
expect from a battle-tested starting pitcher on a veteran team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it one pitch at a time, one batter at a time,'' Helling
said. ``When you face a lineup like they have in a park where they
rarely lose, you have to. I just focused on doing my job. And if
you can get eight innings out of that, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers actually had a chance to blow the game open in the
sixth and seventh, leaving the bases loaded in both innings. In the
sixth, Garcia struck out Luis Alicea, leaving the leadoff hitter
pounding the ground in front of home plate with his bat.
</P>
<P>
   An error, a double and a walk loaded the bases with no one out
an inning later with Rob Ramsay pitching. Again the Rangers were
denied. Ramsay got former Mariner David Segui to pop out, and Brett
Tomko came out of the bullpen to shut down pinch-hitter Frank
Catalanotto and center fielder Gabe Kapler.
</P>
<P>
   That was sweet relief for Seattle, but it ultimately didn't
prove to be enough. Lefty Arthur Rhodes, pitching with two out and
a man on first in the eighth, twice thought he had Rusty Greer
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes did what he wanted to do, hitting Wilson's glove with a
slider and with a fastball. Neither pitch was called a strike by
umpire Scott Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen that umpire before,'' Rhodes said. ``Either
one of those could have been called a strike. When I see him the
next time, I'm going to ask him where the slider was. Where the
fastball was.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in the strike zone, evidently, which meant that Greer drew a
walk, giving Rafael Palmeiro a chance to hit. Palmeiro looped a
soft single to right, breaking the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just threw me a slider which was kind of tough, actually,''
Palmeiro said. ``I just put the bat on the ball. He's given me
problems. He's very tough on left-handers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes figures to get a chance to prove the truth of that last
statement with very little time elapsing. The A's are stocked from
the bill of their caps to the soles of their spikes with
left-handed sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mariners' bullpen in the next three games, it's a good
bet that all roads lead to Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
