r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-24 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS THEATER EXITED STAGE LEFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - And on the eighth day we learned why the world's
most wondrous athletes should concentrate on running their races
and not their mouths. The U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials, it
was made shockingly clear Sunday, is not like your Madison Square
Garden variety World Wrestling Federation event.
</P>
<P>
   The order of finish is not preordained. Races can't be counted
on to follow any script at all. And when two mouthy marquee names
absorb terrible blows, they hurt, naturally, but nationalism takes
it on the chin, too.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown between Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene in the
200 meters was supposed to provide a colossal climax to these
Trials. Didn't Johnson and Greene say so in the weeks leading up to
their first head-to-head meeting in the event since 1998? Didn't
NBC design it to be so, using its considerable muscle to move the
event to the end of the Trials schedule?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the world-record holder in the 200, warmed up for the
running of the bull-headed competitors by criticizing everything
about Greene but his taste in sneakers (Johnson and Greene both are
paid handsomely to wear the same brand).
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who was crowned the world champion in the 200 last year
in the absence of an injured Johnson, loosened up by accusing
Johnson of skirting him these past two years.
</P>
<P>
   It made for great theater, if your taste runs to melodramas.
</P>
<P>
   In sports, unlike on the stage, it's hard to know who to cheer,
who to boo. Even when you're positive you know where the plot is
going, you often don't.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the script can seem so predictable as to be almost
trite: Tiger Woods takes the lead at the British Open and doesn't
flinch, becoming the youngest golfer to win all four majors; Lance
Armstrong wins the Tour de France for the second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, though, sports gives us endings out of left
field: Armstrong wins his first Tour de France after surviving an
advanced case of cancer; Jeff Hartwig doesn't make the Olympic team
in the pole vault despite owning the American record in the event.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-meter final was more Hartwig than heartwarming; Johnson
pulled up lame 50 meters into the race with a strained left
hamstring and Greene did the same some 100 meters later. As fast as
two muscles can twitch, the Olympic 200 was stripped of most of its
glamour and the U.S. gold medal prospects in Sydney dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   Or did they?
</P>
<P>
   As Johnson and Greene hobbled into the sunset, their readiness
for Sydney suddenly shrouded in doubt, there was a hue and cry to
let this cruel way of assembling an Olympic team die already.
</P>
<P>
   If past performances were part of the selection equation,
Hartwig would be added to the team. So would Bob Kennedy, the
American-record holder in the 5,000 meters, who was slowed in
recent months by injuries suffered in an auto accident and didn't
run well here.
</P>
<P>
   Canoga Park's Larry Wade, who rebounded from a near-death
experience to nearly make the Olympic team in the high hurdles (he
missed a berth by seven-hundredths of a second) certainly would be
headed to Sydney by virtue of his No. 2 national ranking in the
event last year. So would 100-meter hurdler Anjanette Kirkland, who
had the second-fastest time in her specialty this year but stumbled
on a hurdle in the final Sunday and didn't finish the race.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team would be better for having those athletes on it,
right? That's one side of the argument. The other side is this: If
the Olympic team was picked on previous performances, Gail Devers
probably would have been left off; a month ago, the former UCLA
standout had a boot cast on her foot and didn't think she was going
to be able to compete for a fourth Olympic berth.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there Devers was Sunday, breaking her year-old American
record in the 100-meter hurdles, seizing the moment.
</P>
<P>
   If reputations mattered much, Dominique Arnold's coming-out
party probably would have had to wait. The 110-meter high hurdler
from North Hills turned a few eyes by winning a stacked semifinal
heat that included Wade and 1996 Olympic champion Allen Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He stumbled on a hurdle midway through the final and didn't
finish the race. Once Arnold's tears dry, he'll see that he'll be
faster in the future for having experienced the pressure and the
pathos and the pride, the likes of which cannot be simulated
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   If you can make it here, you can make it anywhere. The U.S.
Trials, for all their imperfections, are fair. If they are cruelly
so sometimes, well, then, they are merely mirroring sports itself.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in all the moaning over the misfortune of Johnson and
Greene was this: John Capel, who went on to win the 200, had beaten
both runners in a semifinal heat. Afterward, Capel said a major
part of his motivation going into the final was ``showing the crowd
that I belong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, finally, talk that isn't cheap. To show and not tell; isn't
that why we really tune into sports?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
