<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ PROVES LATIN PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
 OF FAME-PEREZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ For a long time, it seemed the wall that
kept Tony Perez out of the baseball Hall of Fame would be too high
for any Latin player to scale in our time. But clearly, times are
changing.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Perez and onetime Red Sox teammate Carlton Fisk received
their Hall of Fame plaques with pride and dignity. It's about time.
The voting of the Baseball Writers Association of America had, in
recent years, produced mixed results and controversy ranging from
favoritism to racism. And it hurts to point that out.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk was no surprise. As the all-time leader for catchers in
games played, he easily earned enshrinement by garnering 397 votes,
after falling short in 1999 because the ballot was stacked with
Robin Yount, Nolan Ryan, and George Brett.
</P>
<P>
   Perez didn't make it, either. He had failed eight straight times
before finishing second to Fisk last winter. Suddenly, the Latin
curtain had been lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade or so, Latin hopefuls have included Minnie
Minoso, Tony Oliva, Dave Concepcion, Luis Tiant, and Perez. They
all had high-profile careers, but for some reason, the votes were
never there. (Players must get 75 percent for election.)
</P>
<P>
   With the breakthrough by Perez, perhaps the voting can now send
the best players to the Hall of Fame. But if Perez hadn't received
some help from fan groups in Cincinnati and Florida, he still might
be on the outside looking in.
</P>
<P>
   What they did comes under the heading of ``old-fashioned
marketing.'' One fan group did an active mail campaign. T-shirts
with Perez's face could be found in Riverfront and Pro Player
Stadium. Perez always had the statistics to get into the Hall and
the support of his teammates from the Big Red Machine, the
Phillies, and the Red Sox. But until the Latin players conquer the
communication gap, there will still be some who don't get the honor
they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will help,'' said Perez. ``We've got some great
talent coming along _ Alex Rodriguez, Sammy Sosa, Pedro Martinez,
Juan Gonzalez. They're having great years and I'd like to see them
make it into the Hall . . . But it would be nice to also see some
of the older players who were our heroes make it into the Hall.
They belong here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez would like to see Concepcion and Pete Rose, two teammates
on the Big Red Machine, in the Hall. But Cooperstown already boasts
three members from that 1975-76 Reds team, as well as its manager,
Sparky Anderson. Joe Morgan and Johnny Bench couldn't miss. In this
era of power-hitting shortstops, Concepcion pales by comparison.
For Rose to make it, the world would have to change, and to be
truthful, the Big Red Machine doesn't deserve five Hall of Famers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played against Tony in 1975 and I found out why they called
him the top dog,'' said Fisk. ``Unless you're the lead dog, the
scenery doesn't change. But it changed for Tony. He was't just a
big dog. He was the lead dog. And the Big Red Machine would have
sputtered without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most writers will say their voting has nothing to do with race
or origin. Perez was a winner with the Reds, Phillies, and Red Sox
because they were good teams. Fisk and Perez were together in 1980.
Perez, Mike Schmidt, and Rose were teammates in 1983. But there is
such a thing as too much greatness. Carl Yastrzemski, Jim Rice, and
Fisk were teammates in the '70s. Only two are in the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 ballot will include first-timers Kirby Puckett and Dave
Winfield. Rice can't afford another bad year that would put him at
risk of falling off the ballot. The Red Sox can help by finding the
hidden support that has made him a fan favorite since 1974. A good
word from them and his impressive power numbers might do the trick.
If not, he's not going to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that will be awful,'' said Perez. ``The guys whom we're
talking about are the heroes. They should be here because the
feeling is wonderful. It's not a matter of black and white. It's
about the game. I tell players today to respect the uniform you're
wearing. Respect your friends. Most important, respect the game of
baseball. Who knows what can happen to you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fisk dominated the three-hour program that attracted about
25,000 to Cooperstown High School. It was about half the crowd that
showed up in 1999. Perez and Anderson represented the Reds,
although both played with other clubs. Perez was with the Red Sox
(1980-82) and Phillies (1983) before returning to the Reds
(1984-86). Anderson spent nine years in Cincinnati (1970-78) and
moved to the Tigers (1979-95), winning 2,194 games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also inducted into the Hall were Norman ``Turkey'' Stearnes, a
Negro leagues power hitter who won six batting titles and topped
.300 in 14 of the 18 seasons he played, and Bid McPhee, who played
between 1882 and 1899, and was the last of the barehanded second
basemen. He had 2,250 hits, mostly for the Cincinnati Red
Stockings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The J.G. Taylor Spink award for print media went to Hal
Lebovitz, a longtime Cleveland writer. The Reds' Marty Brennaman
was named winner of the Ford C. Frick Award.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
