<SLUG> BC-OLY-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SET EXAMPLE OF CAMARADERIE AT TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Lest one suspect that the elite levels of
track and field are mostly about intrigue, jealousies and
pettiness, a glance at the women's pole vault during Sunday's U.S.
Olympic Trials revealed all the animosity of a teenage sleepover.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of hugs, giggles and a party-down atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge difference between us and the sprinters,'' said
third-place finisher Melissa Mueller. ``Thank God.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever deity or cosmic force is responsible for the
distinctions, a grateful track nation offers its sincere
appreciation. Had the female vaulters been more like the male
sprinters, the carnage might have been unfit for family newspaper
description.
</P>
<P>
   The vault produced a world record in the person of Pocatello,
Idaho, resident Stacy Dragila, destined to be a media darling at
the Sydney Olympics. The sprints, specifically the much-anticipated
200 meters, produced a debacle, destined to make for a months-long
media debate.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene each came up lame
and fell to the track _ a 118-degree surface _ in front of a
stunned sellout of 24,072 sun-blistered fans at Sacramento State's
Hornet Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the most talked-about footrace in years, the 200
instead became the biggest disappointment since ``Harry Potter and
the Goblet of Phlegm.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson last weekend won the 400 meters here and Greene
the 100, meaning both will be in Sydney, neither will run the 200
by virtue of the failures Sunday. They executed the worst nightmare
of USA Track &AMP; Field CEO Craig Masback, who said Thursday that the
endless woofing between Johnson and Greene was fine with him ``as
long as nobody gets hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to say what impact the race's overblown pressure
had on each athlete. It's also impossible to avoid speculation that
the rivalry contributed in some indirect way to the bizarre
similarity and simultaneousness of the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source of the problem, it ended an otherwise
superlative nine-day meet on a downer. But only because it was the
last and most anticipated event. Otherwise, Sunday was full of
wonderful stories, the two most remarkable belonging to the women.
</P>
<P>
   In the 800 meters, the three Olympic berths went to one New
Jersey family. Hazel Clark, 22, won the race; her sister, four-time
Olympian Joetta Clark-Diggs, 37, finished third; and sister-in-law
Jearl Miles-Clark, 33 and a three-time Olympian, finished second.
Jearl is married to the crew's coach, J.J. Clark, a middle-distance
All-America runner at Villanova who now coaches at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat that family tree quickly, and you, too, will win an
Olympic berth. Anyway, it was the first time a family had swept
berths in an Olympic track event.
</P>
<P>
   The other first was watching Dragila clear 15 feet, 2\ inches _
the highest a female earthling has flown aided by mere fiberglass.
While it's true that the women's vault has been around the track
scene only four years _ the event was an exhibition at the '96
Trials _ the improvements have been large.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Mueller and second-place finisher Kellie Suttle,
each of whom reached more than 14 feet Sunday, cleared 11-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us (vaulters) have been through this whole experience
as a group for several years,'' Suttle said. ``The great thing is
that these are people that I would hang out with even if we weren't
pole-vaulting.''
</P>
<P>
   Dare Johnson and Greene to say that.
</P>
<P>
   The camaraderie was evident after Dragila set this meet's only
world record, beating her own mark of 15-1}. Other vaulters rushed
the pit for a group hug. The nearest portion of the crowd _ Dragila
was born and raised in Auburn, Calif., 30 miles away _ cheered
wildly for the hometown hero.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila, 29, came up short three times attempting to elevate her
record to 15-5. That remains for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 16 feet is just around the corner,'' she said. ``But
to set the record and win before the hometown fans, it's a dream
come true.''
</P>
<P>
   As a good but unrecruited track athlete out of high school,
Dragila burned off some of her athletic energy as a cowgirl engaged
in rodeo goat-roping.
</P>
<P>
   She went to Yuba City Community College, where a coach started
her in the heptathlon, then one day asked the heptathletes to pick
up a pole. Dragila said they thought clearing six feet was the
coolest thing. Until they started going upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple trillion times trying to go over the bar were
pretty frightening,'' she said. ``It was scary for me, going upside
down and not knowing where I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear proved not to be a lingering issue. She was recruited by
coach Dave Nielson to Idaho State in Pocatello, where she worked in
virtual isolation, emerging to win the world championship in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Since then she has broken her own world record seven times, has
her own credit-card commercial on TV, is a striking representative
for a potential glamor event at the Olympics and is besieged almost
daily by media requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about today,'' she said, ``was gaining the
confidence to know I can jump even better under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to know if having the full support of your rivals is
helpful. But there was painful evidence as the Trials ended Sunday
that not having it doesn't help a bit.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
