<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISK HAD HELP REACHING HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ The acceptance speech was reminiscent of a
classic Carlton Fisk at-bat. It was meticulous, comprehensive,
precise, methodical, and detailed.
</P>
<P>
   All right, it was long.
</P>
<P>
   Well, so was his career.
</P>
<P>
   Has anyone ever worked harder in the game of baseball to put
himself in a position to be in a circumstance such as this? The
answer happens to be no.
</P>
<P>
   There was no sunstroke issue, either, so if Pudge Fisk chose to
go a wee bit past the recommended time limit for speeches (a
rumored 15 minutes), so what? This is, after all, Cooperstown.
Where exactly was anyone going to go? Oneonta?
</P>
<P>
   Pudge had to touch a lot of bases. After telling Sparky Anderson
he wished he had been able to play for him, he paid immediate
homage to his high school coach, Ralph Silva, and that was the
first of many thank yous, some extremely emotional. So? Do we want
someone to get up there and say, ``I did it all myself''?
</P>
<P>
   Often portrayed as the quintessential flinty New Englander,
Carlton Fisk revealed himself to have a strongly developed, shall
we say, Alan Alda side. He broke down more than Sparky and Tony
Perez combined _ either four or five times, depending on your
personal definition _ and there certainly was nothing forced or
phony about it.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped up to that podium believing he was fully prepared.
And then he found out a harsh truth. You really can't fully prepare
for anything like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you're ready,'' he would later say. ``It sounded all
right in the bathroom. It sounded all right in front of the mirror.
It sounded all right in the garage. But, wow, is it different once
you get up there. It's like taking batting practice. You can take
all you want, but that doesn't prepare you to face Randy Johnson,
Tom Seaver, or Bob Gibson. It gives you groundwork, but that's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk dared to stick his toes into at least one pond in front of
which there is generally a large ``No Swimming'' sign. How often
does a newly minted Hall of Famer thank Curt Flood, Marvin Miller,
Donald Fehr, Andy Messersmith, and Dave McNally? But this speaks to
the extraordinary sweep of his career. Carlton Fisk came into
baseball in one era, with one set of stars and one set of life
circumstances (the minimum salary was still four figures), and
played long enough to see more than one set of new stars take over
the game in an entirely new set of life circumstances that would
benefit, among others, himself.
</P>
<P>
   The contractual mumbo-jumbo that led to his becoming a free
agent in December 1980 was an unimaginable concept when he began
his major league career with a cameo (two-game, five at-bat)
appearance 11 years earlier. And by the time he retired (1993), the
labor-management pendulum had swung even more dramatically in favor
of the players.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and how about this? Pudge Fisk managed to bring up the
Vietnam War. In fact, this is where he first broke down, while
mentioning Sgt. Robert Kenyon and Lt. John Carroll. Again, this is
venturing into normally uncharted territory at one of these
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   But the preponderance of his speech was pure baseball-oriented
and was sprinkled with great baseball names ranging from Rac Slider
to Don Zimmer (``Zimmy, you were the easiest manager I ever played
for''). He said the single most memorable piece of baseball wisdom
he ever got came from Mace Brown in the Florida Instructional
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you somethin' my daddy told me,'' he recalled
Brown saying. ``He said, `If you hadn't wanted to work, you
shouldn't have hired out.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's not as if Pudge Fisk, son of Cecil, was unfamiliar
with the concept of work. We've all heard plenty about his New
Hampshire values. But at this particular point in time, Pudge Fisk
was trying to make his living as a baseball player and he had a
great deal to learn. He needed a boot in the mental fanny, and Mace
Brown gave it to him.
</P>
<P>
   Credit, credit, credit. He gave credit to Darrell Johnson, for
teaching him while they were both in Louisville that ``there was
more to catching than just squatting down and wiggling fingers.''
He gave credit to fitness guru Phil Clausen ``for introducing me
into the world of strength and fitness. I will always remember him
and will be forever grateful.'' He gave credit to Walter Hriniak,
which led to yet another breakdown as he struggled to explain how
much he owed to this oft-maligned batting coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be standing here, Walter,'' he said, dabbing a
handkerchief to his eyes. ``I wouldn't be standing here if it
wasn't for you.''
</P>
<P>
   He went over some of the players he was associated with in both
Boston and Chicago, paying particular tribute to Luis Tiant, ``the
best and most colorful (pitcher) ever in a Red Sox uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was being diplomatic, going into the Hall with a Red
Sox cap and all, but he went out of his way to label his experience
with the 1983 White Sox as ``the most complete season of any team
I've been with.'' That team was beaten by the Orioles in the ALCS,
but Fisk insisted that ``I look back on that, and if only we could
have played a seven-game series, we'd have won.''
</P>
<P>
   The names and remembrances kept coming. He told about the time
he was young and ignorant and found himself making a mound visit to
see crusty Gary Peters, who was in a jam and in no mood for a
conversation with a kid catcher. `` `What the hell are you doing
out here?' '' Fisk recalled Peters saying, only ``those weren't the
exact words.'' He talked about hitting his 300th career homer and
having his son, Casey, then a White Sox bat boy, be the first one
to greet him at the plate. He talked about the thrill of catching
Tom Seaver's 300th victory, which, he said in a mischievous voice,
``was against the Yaaaankees.'' Did he allude to those epic Red
Sox-Yankee games of the 1970s? Is ``Survivor'' a ratings hit?
</P>
<P>
   He talked, time and again, about his love for the game, the
pride he took in playing it so long, and the sheer amount of
drudgery necessary to enjoy the good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I stayed true to my passion,'' he said. `` 'Cause
there's certainly no glory in those weight rooms, I'll tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the glory comes with those three-run homers and in catching
those shutouts and in knowing that you gave everything to help the
cause. And the glory now comes in your induction into the Hall of
Fame. Only Fisk knows everything that took place in order to get
him up on that podium.
</P>
<P>
   Pudge Fisk has never done anything half-assed in his life. What
makes anybody think he was going to start with the most important
speech of his life?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
