<HEADER>
A0894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-USWOMEN'SOPEN-BOS     07-24 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBB RUNS AWAY WITH OPEN CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
 WOMEN'S OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. _ The words come quickly, straight from the soul.
``I still can't believe I've achieved what I've achieved,'' said
Karrie Webb, all of 25 years old. ``It's been like I've been living
a dream the last five years.''
</P>
<P>
   And when question after question was asked about her dominance
of women's golf compared with Tiger Woods's domination of men's
golf, again the words came quickly. Again straight from the soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I don't understand what I'm doing up here (on the
winner's dais),'' said Webb, the mystery evident on her face. ``I
still don't. I just think I was given a gift to play golf and to be
mentally strong. I don't know how this has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But happened it has as Webb won her first United States Women's
Open Championship Sunday at the Merit Club, shooting 1-over-par 73
Sunday to finish with a 6-under 282 when only two of the other 155
women could best par at all, and they were far back at 1 under.
Webb, like Woods, won the third of the last four majors she has
played.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's victory earned her enough points to qualify for the LPGA
Tour Hall of Fame, a very exclusive club of 19 members. That's what
she's most proud of, Webb said, ``because the LPGA Hall of Fame is
so great. Every single person in there was the best player of her
era.''
</P>
<P>
   And so is Webb. At the age of 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, as I look back at what I've achieved, I just shake
my head,'' said the Australian. ``I can't believe that I've done so
much so soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Australian'' in Webb's pedigree must be emphasized. As
excited as she is to win the Open, she will be as excited ``when I
carry the Olympic torch in Sydney the day before the Olympics.''
And if golf were ever included in the Olympic panoply of sports,
said Webb, ``I'd be there with bells on to represent Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first 14 holes Sunday, Webb sensed the distinct feel of
``USA vs. the foreigners'' among the large galleries here in
America's heartland. Indeed, said Natick, Mass., native Meg Mallon,
Webb's closest challenger, ``I wore my (red, white, and blue) flag
colors today. You kidding me? I tried everything today.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the 15th hole, when Webb spotted a giant flag of
Australia, ``I had to calm myself down. I got tears in my eyes,''
she said. ``It was just a great sight. To see that great big
Australian flag just made me feel really good, that there were some
Australians out there supporting me.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, on the seventh and eighth holes, Webb's only supporting
cast was herself, and that support was none too firm. She started
the day four strokes up on Mallon but a bogey on the fourth
whittled her lead to three. Then, on the par-3 seventh, Webb pulled
her drive into a pond to the left of the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't feel comfortable over the ball,'' Webb said of
her errant drive. ``It just was a bad swing and pretty much as soon
as I hit it I knew it was not going to carry the left edge of the
water.'' Webb got onto the green with a hit from the drop area, but
missed the putt for bogey and her lead was down to one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth seemed worse. Once again, Webb pulled her drive on
the 522-yard par-5 and her ball landed in the rough. ``And then I
made a pretty stupid choice on my second shot, to try and hit it
over the tree,'' she said. ``I thought I had a pretty good lie in
the rough but it wasn't as good as I thought. And I hit it into the
tree.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mallon comfortably on the green in three, Webb needed four
strokes to finally reach the putting surface. ``I was really
talking to myself then,'' said Webb. ``I was telling myself, `Just
play smart and hang in there. You're still leading the tournament.'
''
</P>
<P>
   And when Mallon missed her birdie putt, settling for a par, Webb
followed by making a tricky 7-footer downhill, also for a par.
Webb, in pieces only moments earlier, regained her equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon birdied the ninth, tying Webb at 4 under par, and it
seemed the race was on. But Mallon made a horrendous approach putt
on the 10th green, leaving a 75-foot putt 20 feet short of the hole
``and that's Karrie right there,'' said Mallon. ``When she smells
blood, she's like an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mallon three-putting the 10th for a bogey, Webb sank her
birdie putt ``and after that,'' said Webb, ``I don't think I missed
a green the rest of the way.'' Mallon, however, was missing putt
after putt, dropping further and further behind Webb.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's lead was five strokes as she began her victory stroll up
the 18th fairway, and ``walking up 18 was the dream of dreams for
me,'' said Webb. ``And to walk it with a friend (Mallon) made it
even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb earned the highest payoff for a woman golfer in a
full-field event, $500,000, topping the $315,000 won by Juli
Inkster in the 1999 Open. And if there was a shadow to dim Webb's
day, it only could be that her victory happened the same day Woods
was garnering so much acclaim at St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say that about my whole career then,'' said
Webb, who won the Open on her fifth try. ``Because I was rookie of
the year the same year he was rookie of the year and I had a great
year last year and he had a great year last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The USGA's Rhonda Glenn then informed Webb, ``It took Tiger six
tries to win the (US) Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Karrie Webb did have one up on Tiger Woods.
</P>
</TEXT>
