<HEADER>
A0895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-B     07-24 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ MASTERS WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Clear another wall in the Baseball Hall of Artistry for
a masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Turning a tiny hill on the Fenway diamond into a public studio,
Pedro Martinez submitted his tour de force in a dazzling, 1-0
victory Sunday over the Chicago White Sox, a classic he made look
almost as easy as painting by numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, with all but the most distracted of the 33,284 patrons
on their feet, sealed the 15-strikeout performance with a virtuoso
effort that crushed Chicago's last-gasp rally in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   After a freak leadoff double put the tying run on second and the
go-ahead run at the plate, Martinez said afterward, ``I figured it
was time to really bring the best out of me. And the best out of me
is the fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Unleashing 95-mile-per-hour bullets to one of the most dangerous
teams in baseball, Martinez mowed down the last three hitters,
forcing one to pop up and striking out the other two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about you,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said,
``but for me that's as good as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   With his third shutout of the season, tops in the majors,
Martinez (11-3) helped Boston win the three-game series against the
surging White Sox and kept the Red Sox in second place in the
American League East, a game behind the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the two-time Cy Young Award winner shared a
hug on the field with his much-maligned rookie teammate, Izzy
Alcantara, who scored the only run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best,'' Alcantara said, ending three weeks of
self-imposed public silence since his lackluster effort contributed
to an embarrassing loss to the White Sox in Chicago. ``The guy is
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the outcome was in doubt until Martinez's final pitch, his
131st of the game. And shortstop Nomar Garciaparra blamed the
perilous ending, in part, on the condition of the Fenway field.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago slugger Magglio Ordonez, hitless in his first three
at-bats, started the ninth by hitting what looked like a routine
grounder to Garciaparra. The shortstop, who had helped save a
victory Friday night by making a spectacular grab of a bad-hop
bouncer, said he was ``definitely confident'' this play would be
easy.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, the ball hit something in the infield dirt, this
time misdirecting it past Garciaparra and sending it into left for
a bizarre double.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfortunate that the field almost cost us the game,''
Garciaparra said, on his 27th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had no control over the landscaping. But he had the
White Sox within his grasp, paralyzing them with his changeup until
he challenged them in the ninth with his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   With remarkable control, Martinez did not throw three balls to a
batter until the sixth inning. And other than the ninth inning, he
allowed only one runner to reach second base.
</P>
<P>
   That occurred with one out in the second inning, when he hit
Paul Konerko with a pitch and allowed a bloop single to left by
Chris Singleton. But he promptly struck out Carlos Lee and Herbert
Perry to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the premier pitchers in the game, no question
about it,'' said Chicago manager Jerry Manuel, who was ejected in
the eighth inning for complaining that home plate umpire Brian
O'Nora was giving Martinez more strike calls than he merited.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago coach Von Joshua was also ejected when he wagged a towel
at the umps and suggested they were making Martinez's strike zone
as wide as the towel. ``I told them, `If you're going to make it
bigger, let us know about it,' '' Joshua said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Martinez: ``If they made it that big, I would have struck
out 20 of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez overshadowed a superb effort by Chicago's Mike Sirotka
(9-8), who allowed only five hits and two walks. The only Red Sox
run was unearned, made possible when Chicago shortstop Jose
Valentin picked up a routine grounder by Alcantara in the fourth
inning and launched it into the Red Sox dugout, allowing Alcantara
to take second.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Jason Varitek, singled a 1-2 pitch up the
middle to knock in Alcantara.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring the winning run was sweet for Alcantara, who has been
vilified since his abysmal effort in Chicago. He was 1 for 3 Sunday
and is hitting .391 in 23 at-bats since joining the team last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good because I helped Pedro win the game,'' he said,
struggling to speak English.
</P>
<P>
   As for his misdeeds in Chicago, he said, ``I feel good because I
know every player has a bad day. You just keep your head up and try
to do a good job the next time you get a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had several other opportunities to score Sunday, but
Ed Sprague, batting cleanup in place of the resting Carl Everett,
three times hit inning-ending grounders with runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Sprague said. ``But Sirotka pitched me
very well. He pitched a helluva game.''
</P>
<P>
   As did Martinez, who excelled in the ninth when other pitchers
might have come undone after a bad hop became a leadoff double in a
1-0 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shows how big he is,'' said Varitek. ``He didn't let the
moment take him over. He seized the moment instead of the moment
seizing him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
