<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG REPEATS FEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 DE FRANCE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Yellow _ with a splash of red, white, and blue _ was the
color in vogue on the Champs Elysees Sunday as American Lance
Armstrong won the Tour de France for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   His gloves were yellow, his helmet was yellow, and the spokes on
his bike were yellow as he made the journey into Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Standing alone on the podium after the three-week race,
Armstrong took off his yellow cap and put it over his winner's
yellow jersey as ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' played and fans
wildly waved American flags.
</P>
<P>
   Then his wife, Kristin, and 9-month-old son, Luke, joined him on
the stage, and the winner put his son _ also in a yellow jersey _
on his shoulders as he waved to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This little guy gave me a lot of motivation in the past
year,'' said Armstrong, 28. ``It's been a hard Tour de France, but
this is my first as a father, so it's very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who earned more than $300,000 for winning the
21-stage, 2,250-mile Tour by 6 minutes 2 seconds over his nearest
pursuer, was the first rider to win the Tour in consecutive years
since Spaniard Miguel Indurain in 1995 (he had won the previous
four years).
</P>
<P>
   But there was such a difference between Armstrong's two
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I arrived in Paris last year mentally tired, and I'm
arriving this year physically tired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's win was clouded with subplots. First, Armstrong, who
had been diagnosed with testicular cancer in late 1996, became
known as ``Tour leader, cancer survivor.'' Then some of the
European press took it a step further and asked: How could he turn
in a performance like that without being enhanced by drugs?
</P>
<P>
   Hounded by the media, Armstrong seemed to be scowling
constantly. He tried to ingratiate himself to the Europeans by
speaking French, but that didn't work; he said he was
misinterpreted. So he went back to English _ and scowling.
</P>
<P>
   The final zing came when his victory was called hollow because
none of his chief rivals were there. Former Tour winners Marco
Pantani and Jan Ullrich were no-shows, as was former fourth-place
finisher Laurent Jalabert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't control who wasn't here, but I know it made people
critical of my performance, and I thought a lot about that,'' he
said. ``A lot. All winter, all spring, all May and June, and all up
the mountains. There was a whole list of people who thought they
could win the Tour after Lance Armstrong won the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, yes, this is a vindication.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Armstrong seemed at home in the yellow jersey. He
fielded questions about his struggle on the last climb; he admitted
that ``giving'' Pantani the win one day was a mistake, but laughed
it off, calling Pantani ``Elephantino,'' as he's dubbed in the
Paris papers.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong bided his time the first week as he rode well enough
to stay up front, but not enough to take the overall lead, choosing
to let others assume the pressure of wearing the yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the second week, as the Tour arrived at the
Pyrenees, Armstrong made his move.
</P>
<P>
   He plowed up the first mountain stage in the cold and rain to
the summit at Lourdes-Hautacam. He didn't win the stage, but had
ridden well enough to claim the yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   It was, perhaps, his finest moment of the race, he said later.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong never relinquished the yellow jersey, and his lead
would grow to six minutes over second-place finisher Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   Johan Bruyneel, the director of Armstrong's US Postal Service
team, said his star rider is more formidable than he was in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's stronger now than last year, and is still improving,''
Bruyneel said. ``He's pretty scary; if he gets stronger, it's not
looking good for the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said even though he is glad the talk this year focused
more on his racing than on his having survived cancer, he has mixed
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm still part of that family (of cancer survivors) and
will always be part of that family,'' he said. ``And I knew also
that the media were not going to talk about it that much this year,
because it was such a story last year that I didn't think it would
come about.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains, he won two Tours after being diagnosed
with cancer that had spread to his lungs and brain. That's still
the message he wants to get across.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still healthy, and it's always a struggle,'' he said. ``My
health is not guaranteed forever, but the fact that I'm still here
and cancer-free is still the most important thing in my life. That
will always be my message.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he's not ready to talk about what kind of legacy
he'll leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``With one and two (Tour wins), you don't leave a legacy, and
with three, well, I don't know,'' he said. ``And I don't know how
somebody wins this five times.''
</P>
<P>
   But he will be back to go for a third, he said, and to wear
yellow on the Champs Elysees one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll definitely be back next year, I promise you that,'' he
said.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
