<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BACK IN `THICK OF THINGS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Davey Johnson walked into the dugout before
Sunday's game and proclaimed, ``It's a beautiful day in paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers manager didn't have any reason to feel differently
after the game as nearly everything went the Dodgers' way in a 5-0
victory against the San Francisco Giants in front of 47,969 at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dreifort allowed just two hits and struck out nine in
seven innings, Shawn Green hit two home runs and Todd Hollandsworth
added his eighth homer of the season. The offseason stadium
renovations that moved the backstop 25 feet closer to home plate
also played in the Dodgers' favor with an unusual play that
preserved the shutout, as did home-plate umpire Doug Eddings being
hit and keeping the ball close to the plate on another wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Dodgers two wins in the three-game series
against the second-place Giants and pulled the Dodgers within four
games of first-place Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-4 record on the homestand gives the Dodgers their most
wins in a homestand since they won 8 of 12 in a 1998 homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have a big homestand, which we did,'' Green said.
``Now we're in the thick of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, who threw 90 pitches, did not give up a hit until
Barry Bonds singled up the middle with one out in the fourth. The
following batter, Jeff Kent, reached on an error when Green and
Hollandsworth collided on the play in right-center field. A wild
pitch with Bonds on third nearly ended the shutout, but the ball
hit the wall behind home plate and quickly bounced back to catcher
Chad Kreuter, prompting Bonds to return to third.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Estalella doubled in the fifth for San Francisco's only
other hit. He also walked with one out in the third to become the
Giants' first base runner.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (6-7) struck out the side in order in the second to
give him four consecutive strikeouts, all against .300-plus
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started in the top of the first,'' Dreifort said.
``Hollandsworth made a great catch. ... Then he hit a home run and
Green hit a home run. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You jump out to a 3-0 lead, it makes pitching a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   A leadoff home run by Hollandsworth and a two-run shot by Green
gave Dreifort the three-run cushion in the first inning. Gary
Sheffield doubled and scored on a two-out bloop single by Adrian
Beltre in the third inning and Green led off the eighth with his
16th homer for the game's final run.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Adams and Jeff Shaw combined to pitch a hitless final two
innings for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an outstanding ballgame,'' said Johnson, whose team
is just the second to shut out the Giants this season. ``(Dreifort)
really didn't have much trouble. (Green) looks like he's heating
up. There's a lot of good things. Two of three against the Giants,
it sets a good tone going on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco starter Russ Ortiz (5-9), a graduate of Montclair
Prep of Van Nuys, gave up eight hits in seven innings. He finished
with seven strikeouts, including the side in order in the fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
