<HEADLINE>
200-METER DUAL HAMSTRUNG 
</HEADLINE>
 OLYMPIC TRIALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Fighting off the effects of a first-round muscle
twinge that threatened to derail the marquee matchup of the US
Olympic Track and Field Trials, Michael Johnson made it to the
starting line Sunday against rival Maurice Greene.
</P>
<P>
   But in a shocking turnabout, neither he nor Greene could make it
to the finish, leaving both the defending Olympic gold medalist and
the reigning world champion off the US 200-meter team for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world wanted to see a great show, and unfortunately,
me and Michael weren't able to give them the show that they
wanted,'' said Greene, whose 26th birthday was tarnished by the
preliminary diagnosis of a strained left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The standing-room-only crowd of 24,072 in Hornet Stadium
breathed a sigh of relief to see Johnson in the starting blocks for
the semifinal, and both he and Greene, who finished 2-3 behind John
Capel, seemed to come through unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final, Johnson cramped up in the middle of the turn,
grimacing and stumbling as he grabbed his left hamstring in agony
before crumpling to the track. But this would be no reprise of the
1997 Johnson-Donovan Bailey match race, in which Johnson pulled up
midway and Bailey taunted him as cowardly, because even as Johnson
lay there Sunday, Greene slowed to a limp about 60 meters up the
track: His left hamstring, too, had failed him.
</P>
<P>
   Greene was able to walk slowly away, while an obviously pained
Johnson had to be driven off. About 30 minutes later, after easing
himself out of a golf cart and walking gingerly into a news
conference, Johnson said he doubted a pull or tear and cited
cramping in a calf muscle and both hips even before the race,
perhaps a result of the 118-degree temperature on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because it was a goal of mine,'' Johnson
said of the chance to repeat his Olympic double in the 200 and 400.
``But you can't have everything. I'll move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The carnage left the victory to Capel, a 21-year-old who
withdrew this spring from the University of Florida, where he was a
wide receiver on the football team and the 1999 NCAA outdoor 200
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Capel's 19.85 makes him the sixth-fastest American in history
and ninth best in the world. Floyd Heard's 19.88 was good for
second, while Coby Miller's 19.96 gave him third.
</P>
<P>
   To end a bizarre 12 days here, in which Johnson and Greene
jockeyed for a psychological advantage, they met up during postrace
drug testing. As Greene relayed the encounter, ``I told him to get
well.'' Asked what Johnson replied, Greene said: ``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men will still be going to Sydney, Johnson in the 400 and
Greene in the 100, provided there is no lingering physical damage
from Sunday's debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Among the day's other action, and there was other action:
</P>
<P>
   --With a 21.94 victory, Marion Jones fended off a late charge by
world champion Inger Miller to win the 200 meters. Coupled with her
earlier victories here in the 100 meters and long jump, the win
keeps Jones on track to pursue five gold medals in Sydney. Miller
was second in 22.09, with Nanceen Perry third in 22.38. ``I'm just
happy these eight days are over,'' said Jones, noting she was
relieved to make the team in all three events and calling the
victory sweep ``a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   --The finish line of the women's 800 meters turned out to be the
site of a family reunion when 37-year-old Joetta Clark Diggs
(1:59.49) nipped 1990 Harvard graduate Meredith Rainey-Valmon for
third, to join 22-year-old sister Hazel Clark (1:58.97) and
sister-in-law Jearl Miles-Clark (1:59.12) to form a cozy US team
for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   --Pole vaulter Stacy Dragila, who grew up in nearby Auburn,
bettered her own world record by a half-inch when she jumped 15
feet 2 1/4 inches to win the competition. After missing three
attempts at 15-5, she waved both arms in salute to the standing
ovation from her hometown crowd.
</P>
<P>
   --Easing any lingering disappointment over failing to make the
100-meter team so she could defend her two-time Olympic title, Gail
Devers broke her American record in the 100-meter hurdles with a
12:33 win that will make her a favorite in Sydney to win her first
Olympic medal in that event, after three unsuccessful attempts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
