<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRYE RIPS GM OVER STANLEY'S RELEASE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-FRYE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dan Duquette was in Cooperstown watching Carlton Fisk
be bronzed for immortality Sunday afternoon, so he missed out on
the latest from Pedro Martinez, which deserves to be hung across
the Fens in the MFA, alongside the Monets and Renoirs and all the
other Impressionist masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, of course, is the largest bauble in Duquette's
personal trophy case. Nomar? The Duke has to share the credit for
that one with Wayne Britton and the Sox scouting staff. But
Martinez is no less than a career-maker for the Duke, who twice
traded for him, the second time saving the Sox from permanent
post-Rocket burnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans have this . . . they hold the general manager
in high regard because of some of the moves he's made, with Pedro,
Jason Varitek, Derek Lowe,'' said second baseman Jeff Frye, whose
recent back spasms have limited him to the role of spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Frye won't begrudge Duquette his due for some of the deals he's
made. But Frye wants people to understand there is another side to
Duquette, one he believes is illustrated by Sunday's release of
veteran Mike Stanley. The ink had not yet dried on Stanley's
walking papers before Garciaparra, who would sooner bat lefthanded
than invite controversy, called it a ``horrible'' move. That was
Saturday, when the Sox were still pretending they hadn't decided
what to do with Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Frye went even further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an injustice when a veteran player like Mike
Stanley is just thrown out on the woodpile and not treated with the
respect he's earned,'' Frye said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in the league 14 years, he's the leader on this
team, the classiest guy I've ever played with. He comes to the
ballpark ready to play every day, but you're going to get rid of
him and you have the assistant general manager come down here and
tell him? Then Mike asked if he should even bother coming in today
and he gets a phone call in the clubhouse from the assistant
general manager saying, `Don't bother to come.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that how you get rid of your leaders? I've been here for
five years and I've seen Roger Clemens, Mo Vaughn, Mike Greenwell,
Tim Naehring treated that way. Scott Hatteberg and myself, Reggie
Jefferson, Tim Wakefield, Flash Gordon, John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flash and Val, they threatened to void their contracts over
some formality or whatever. I know that players take notice of
that. The fans of Boston deserve a winner, but free agents are not
going to come here when they see how players over here _ whether
they're first-year players or 14-year players _ when they see how
they are treated over here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see Mike Stanley yesterday leaving the clubhouse with
almost tears in his eyes and to know what he meant to this team, it
kills you. I just want (Duquette) to be accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley was batting .222 in 57 games when he was released. He
hadn't played in almost three weeks, held hostage on the disabled
list by a nonexistent shoulder injury. Maybe Duquette was buying
time to try to make a deal for Stanley and thus avoid having to
release him. Maybe he was just buying time until he decided what he
wanted to do with the 37-year-old first baseman/DH, who hadn't
homered since May 30.
</P>
<P>
   But Frye said it was wrong to let Stanley go on the basis of 185
at-bats this season, when he had been such a big-game performer for
the Sox in their playoff runs the last two years. Last September,
as the Sox were fighting for a wild-card berth, he knocked in 17
runs and batted .333, then hit .500 against the Indians in the
Division Series. The year before, after coming back to the Sox in a
deadline deal with Toronto, he hit 12 home runs and drove in 32
runs in 47 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of rookie players that could easily be sent
out instead of just dumping the veteran leader of our team in the
middle of a pennant race,'' Frye said.
</P>
<P>
   Where does Jimy Williams fit in all of this? ``He'll land on his
feet,'' Williams said of Stanley. ``You know how I feel. I like
Mike a lot. He's a special player, a special teammate, a big help
for this ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   Does letting Stanley go undermine Williams's credibility in the
clubhouse?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Frye. ``Mike Stanley is one of my best friends on the
team, he's been keeping me posted as to how things are going,''
Frye said. ``I saw Jimy going up to him Sunday and ask him, `What's
going on?' So obviously, Jimy might not have been in the loop, you
know. You ask Jimy, he probably wants Mike Stanley on the team.
When we come to September and need a big hit off the bench, who do
we want, Mike Stanley or a rookie?''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't all about bashing Izzy, either. Somewhat belatedly,
some teammates, including Martinez, have come to the defense of
Izzy Alcantara, who Sunday started for the second time since his
fiasco in Chicago, reached on Jose Valentin's two-base throwing
error in the fourth, and scored the game's only run on Jason
Varitek's single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Izzy's being blamed for a lot of things,'' Frye said,
``when all he did was have one game where he didn't play up to par.
When he's been in there, he's done a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, Frye believes a choice between keeping Izzy or
Stanley is no choice at all. That could be chalked up to
friendship, too, except that Garciaparra, Bret Saberhagen, and to
some degree Martinez (when asked about Stanley, he said Sunday,
``Go ask Duquette'') obviously feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Frye talked about outfielder Curtis Pride passing up a chance to
go to Japan for big money to come here, then getting to play just
nine games before being designated for assignment. He recalled how
pitcher Kip Gross, who had a finger injury, was told by the team
doctor to wear a brace for two or three weeks. According to Frye,
Duquette ordered him to take off the brace and pitch. When he
didn't, he was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about the circumstances of Naehring's career-ending
elbow injury. ``How can you let a guy like that leave this
organization?'' Frye asked. ``A lot of questionable things happened
when Tim had his surgery. How many guys have had that surgery and
come back to play? This guy was one of the favorites of everybody
on the team, another class guy. He has surgery, he wasn't the same,
they just brushed him off. Now he's moving up the chain in the
Reds' organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timmy told me he wants to be the guy who bridges the gap. He
knows what players think and what the front office thinks. We don't
have anybody to bridge that gap here. We've got people who play the
game and people who never played and look at stats. Stats don't
tell people how much heart a guy has.''
</P>
<P>
   Blasting the general manager, of course, is not usually
considered a good career move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't give a (expletive),'' Frye said. ``I'll let my
abilities determine what's going to happen with me. I just think
it's time somebody lets people know what's going on around here.
I've seen too many of my friends just pushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Stanley is kind of like the last straw. If they can do
this to Reggie and Flash and Val and Timmy and Mo, what's going to
happen when Nomar and Pedro get older? Is the same thing going to
happen to them?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
