<SLUG> BC-BBA-WHITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX BATS SILENCED, NOT MOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is the most potent team in baseball, with a major
league-leading 605 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   It has six players batting .300 or better and a team batting
average of .289. Frank Thomas and Magglio Ordonez have 172 RBIs
between them.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at Fenway Park, though, the Chicago White Sox had those
Murderer's Row bats turned into matchsticks by Pedro Martinez, who
outdueled Mike Sirotka in an all-too-rare 1-0 game.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago had six hits off the Red Sox ace, five of them singles.
The only extra-base hit was a double by Ordonez leading off the
ninth on a ground ball that skidded past Nomar Garciaparra after
hitting the lip of the infield grass.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox batters went down on strikes 15 times _ five of them
called _ and only Chris Singleton, who had two of the five singles,
escaped a Martinez K. Herbert Perry was a three-time victim.
</P>
<P>
   But the masterpiece didn't come without controversy. White Sox
manager Jerry Manuel thought umpire Brian O'Nora was too generous
with the width of the strike zone, and he was given the heave-ho in
the eighth after coming out to question a called third strike
against Ray Durham.
</P>
<P>
   Then third-base umpire Wally Bell ousted hitting coach Von
Joshua after Joshua spread a towel at the foot of the dugout to
weigh in on the strike zone controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just threw the towel down and tried to show him how wide the
strike zone was,'' said Joshua. ``I told him if they were going to
make it bigger, they should let us know.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel had more to say about the issue afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Martinez) didn't need any help, anyway,'' said Manuel. ``But
that's from my point of view. I'm sure from their point of view, we
were probably getting pitches as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing that probably bothers me the most is that
(Major League Baseball) sent out a memo about the batter's box, the
catcher's box, and all these different things. Yet still you have
to bring it to everyone's attention to where the guys are, and
things aren't getting enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy's called to stay in a certain place and then a pitch
is away and everyone can tell it's away, it's a different thing. I
just told them I didn't think our guys could cover both sides of
the plate that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the premier pitchers in the game. Today he came at
us soft early, and then when he needed his fastball, he reared back
and had it at the 90-95 that he's accustomed to. He's the elite
pitcher in the league and I'm not trying to take that away from
him. I'm just talking about the strike zone itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sirotka, the tough-luck loser who fell to 9-8, praised Martinez,
who upped his record to 11-3 and lowered his earned run average to
1.38. Sirotka had no complaints about the umpiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was going to be tough _ that's pretty obvious _ so I
knew I'd have to pitch well,'' he said. ``I haven't seen what he
got, but the umpire was fair to me. I didn't really get a chance to
see what Pedro was doing, but I had no problems with the umpire. He
did a nice job.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Jeff Abbott, who had three hits Saturday, wasn't in
the lineup Sunday, but he still was impressed by Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty amazing when a guy throws 90 the whole game and
gets you out and then all of a sudden in the ninth he has enough to
throw 95,'' he said. ``There's not too many pitchers that can do
that. To gain five miles an hour in the ninth is pretty
incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
