<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL DIGS HIMSELF INTO A HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-DUVAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE BOSTON GLOBE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ When the afternoon began, David Duval
faced a challenge that was almost impossible. It ended with one
just as difficult.
</P>
<P>
   He had failed to overcome a six-shot deficit Sunday against
Tiger Woods in the last round of the 129th British Open, but there
wasn't anyone in the crowd who could say Duval hadn't given it a
spirited run. He had played so well, in fact, that Woods stood on
the 17th green rooting, he said, for ``David to finish second.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the only wish all week that didn't come true for Woods,
because Duval's hopes for second place died a slow, painful death
in a place that has crushed the spirits of golfers for hundreds of
years. They call it the Road Bunker, and if you ignore every other
rule when you tee off on the Old Course at St. Andrews, you must
adhere to this one _ stay out of that dastardly bunker at the par-4
17th.
</P>
<P>
   Fair or unfair? Duval was asked after he had taken four shots to
get out of that bunker. He made a quadruple-bogey 8 and fell from
11 under and a share of second to 7 under and a nine-way tie for
11th. His bank account was noticeably lighter, but his dignity was
intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't judge fair or unfair,'' said Duval, whose frontside 32
was forgotten in his backside 43. ``It is what it is. We can
discuss whether it is fair or unfair, but you know going in you've
got to not hit it in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval stood during the press conference because his back has
bothered him all week, but what really hurt him was the way he
finished. His fourth birdie going out, at the par-4 seventh, had
pushed him to 14 and he trailed Woods by three. Little did he know
it would be his last birdie and as close as he would get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm disappointed with the finish. I thought that
what I accomplished on the front nine was probably exactly what I
needed to do, cut the deficit, and then just start from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But just as everything turned good on the front nine, that's
as bad as everything turned on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   It started at the par-4 10th, when Woods drove the green and
two-putted to get to 18 under, increasing his lead to four shots
when Duval pitched poorly from short of the green and left his
birdie putt dead center, a few inches short.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could have made a difference,'' said Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Woods birdied three of the first five holes on the back; Duval
made bogeys at Nos. 12 and 13, and the deficit was seven shots with
five holes to play. Yes, second place was all Duval had left.
</P>
<P>
   That got buried at the Road Bunker as Duval stared helplessly at
his approach, which had come to rest close to the steep lip. ``I
was figuring out whether it would be smarter to play it left or
right,'' said Duval, who decided that straight ahead was just as
good an option.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. It hit the lip and came back in.
</P>
<P>
   With the second shot out of the bunker _ his fourth on the hole
_ ``you're just trying to look around to figure the best option to
get out,'' he said, but he found none. That, too, hit the wall and
came to rest even tighter against the lip.
</P>
<P>
   Now all Duval could do was backhand it away from the lip, giving
himself a full swing out. He navigated that perfectly onto the
green, but, fittingly, missed the putt for triple bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 181 yards to get by the bunker,'' said Duval. ``That's
what I was trying to do. I hit a poor shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
