<HEADER>
A0902 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISHOPEN-WOODS     07-24 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS SWELL TIGER'S GALLERY 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-WOODS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ They had travel plans, it was cold, they
hadn't played particularly well, and the week had ended. But one by
one, players who had just been knocked silly by Tiger Woods said
they were sticking around for the finish of the 129th British Open
Sunday at St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to witness history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be back here,'' said Mark Calcavecchia after finishing
his round. ``Yes, I will. Probably when he's on 16, I'll sneak out
of the hotel and walk out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``History is probably the last part. But he's my friend. He's
American. And we both work with Butch (Harmon).''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Elkington also stuck around. Mark O'Meara, perhaps Woods's
closest friend on the PGA Tour, changed his clothes after playing
and headed out to walk in the gallery. The groups that finished
right ahead of Woods _ Darren Clarke and Thomas Bjorn, David Toms
and Loren Roberts, and Tom Lehman and Dennis Paulson _ were also in
the vicinity of the 18th green as Woods closed out his historic
win.
</P>
<P>
   To many players, it was a day that validated their firm belief
we are watching the game's greatest player ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't long ago when I said there'd never be another Jack
Nicklaus, but we're looking at one. He is it. He is the chosen
one,'' said Calcavecchia, a Tour member since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   As a young kid growing up in North Palm Beach, Fla.,
Calcavecchia idolized a local resident named Jack Nicklaus. ``I met
him when I was 13. He was great to me back then, and I played with
him when I was 14. I still don't think I've ever been that nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you want my honest opinion, (Woods) is the best player
who has ever played the game. Right now. And he's only 24. Jack
Nicklaus was the greatest of all time and he's got the greatest
record of all time, and by the time all is said and done, maybe
he'll still have the greatest record of all time. But if Jack were
in his prime today, I don't think he could keep up with Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong stuff, but there were similar sentiments from many
players.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson has won five British Opens, two Masters, and a US
Open, some going head-to-head with Nicklaus. So he saw firsthand
the greatness of the Golden Bear. What he has seen in Woods,
however, makes him shake his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone is going to have to use some flubber in the bottom of
their shoes to be able to jump over (the bar that Woods has
raised),'' Watson said. ``He is something supernatural.''
</P>
<P>
   So utterly dominating was Woods that the local bookmaker took
him off the board. Usually you can bet each day on a player to win
the tournament, the odds naturally longer the further back a player
stands. But there was no action being taken on Woods, who went off
at 15-8, the smallest odds ever.
</P>
<P>
   All of which put a damper on a great golf tournament, said Fred
Couples. ``If he wasn't in (the field), it would be a thrilling
finish,'' Couples said. ``This is crazy, shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to O'Meara, who has nurtured Woods since the kid came on the
Tour in the fall of 1996. ``It doesn't surprise me to see what he
is doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara won the Masters in 1998, but Woods already had earned a
green jacket. It was when O'Meara followed that win at Augusta with
a British Open triumph at Royal Birkdale that Woods took note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought the claret jug back on the plane to the States with
Tiger, and he looked at it. He held it, and he knew that he wanted
it someday,'' O'Meara said.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a matter of time, because Woods shatters one of the
great myths that has been perpetuated in golf, said Calcavecchia.
``Nobody has it all, but he does,'' Calcavecchia marveled. ``Jack
had it all mentally, but I think Tiger is even his equal
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   But golf being golf, ``He's not going to do this every major,''
Calcavecchia added. Then he paused. ``At least I hope not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0217EDT &QL; 
