<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FUN FACING WOODS ON COURSE _ OR OFF 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-PLAYERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ It is a tired refrain, one many of them
have heard weekly since January, so it's no surprise that
frustration is setting in for those who must compete against Tiger
Woods. Not only can't they win, they can't turn around without
having a reporter ask about the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one way, it's incredible to watch someone who is so much
better than the rest of the world,'' said Ernie Els, ``but on the
other hand, it's tough to sit down and talk about it all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Els had made a hasty exit Saturday after effectively shooting
himself out of the 129th British Open with a 2-under 70. He was
discouraged and knew that everything would center around Woods.
Nothing personal, but he wasn't in the mood for that.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, after posting a 69_277 that pushed him into a tie for
second, Els relented, though the pain was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm watching on film, seeing Tiger making putts and I'm not
making those putts,'' said Els, a runner-up in all three majors so
far this season. He pondered another question, shrugged, and seemed
to sign the declaration of surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I really played as good as I could, I don't think I
would have got to 20 under like Tiger. I was eight shots behind. I
really did not feel like going out there and trying to fight to
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Els wasn't alone in his exasperation. Davis Love made a quick
exit from the scorer's trailer, waving off requests to talk. Even a
round of 67_281 (he tied for 11th) had not lifted his spirits.
</P>
<P>
   In his pre-tournament press conference, Colin Montgomerie faced
an early question about Woods's domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``First American question,'' snapped Montgomerie, ``first
question about Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   You've got to understand, said Paul Azinger, that frustration
has set in. ``What really stinks about it,'' he said, ``is the fact
that you can't control (Woods). In every other sport you can
control your opponent except for in this sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us, I think, are taken aback by it a little bit,'' said
Azinger. ``If I were in my 20s and knew that I'd never have a
chance to be the best player, or have no hope of being considered
the best player, that would be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kite is not one of those younger guys; he's a member of the
Senior PGA Tour. Though impressed with Woods, he's more
disenchanted with the lack of competition. ``Unfortunately, nobody
is stepping up,'' said Kite, who shot 74_294 here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a dominant player on the US Tour until Tiger
came along. I just wish David (Duval) or Phil (Mickelson) or Colin
(Montgomerie) would win one so people would get off their backs,''
said Kite. He was talking about major championships, of which Woods
has now won four. Duval, Mickelson, and Montgomerie are majorless
and Kite theorizes this is a big reason why these marquee names
have never been able to challenge Woods. ``Jack (Nicklaus) had
Arnold (Palmer) and Gary (Player) _ we don't have that now.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that Woods was handling the pressure this
week, Kite bristled. ``What pressure? He's got a six-shot lead.
There isn't any chance of catching him unless he sleeps in.''
</P>
<P>
   After building a three-shot lead through 36 holes, Woods was
asked what he would think if he were in his opponents' shoes. He
paused, shook his head no, and said, ``I can't say because I'm not
in their shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   They know that. They've been hearing it all year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0219EDT &QL; 
