<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARKES STEPS UP AS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ When John Harkes played the back position
Saturday, it was only the second time in his soccer career he had
done so. The first time? More than 10 years ago, in a University of
Virginia intrasquad scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution captain stepped in for Mauricio Wright, sidelined
with three yellow cards, because the only other center back, Brian
Dunseth, was out with a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were low in the number of backs, so (coach) Fernando
(Clavijo) and I talked about playing there, with me giving some
experience to the young backs that we have,'' said Harkes, whose
Revolution beat the Earthquakes, 2-1, in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed myself back there, although I haven't played the
back position much. The key is being sharp at all times. There's
certainly not as much running back there as there is at the
midfield position.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes, a midfielder by trade, said it takes focus to refrain
from creeping up in the play. ``You have to maintain your
discipline and stay back and pass the ball,'' he said. ``You have
to make sacrifices for the betterment of the team. You have to play
for one another out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory marked two road wins in a row for the Revolution,
who defeated the Kansas City Wizards, 1-0, Wednesday. New England
takes its 9-9-5 record (32 points) into an 11-day All-Star break.
Seven of the remaining nine games are at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had two great wins in a row, and both were hard to come
by,'' Harkes said. ``We happened to catch Kansas City when it
wasn't performing well, while we were. And then with this win
against San Jose, we got the extra three points that we needed and
we're in the (playoff) hunt because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes believes the time off will be good for the Revolution,
giving the injured players _ including newcomer Eric Wynalda (right
calf) _ time to heal. It also will allow newcomer Juan Luis Morales
to get in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good having the time off after taking some long trips,
jumping on planes, and being in hotels. This gives us time to
regroup,'' Harkes said. ``Plus, it gives us more time to work on
things we need to do as a team, like our patterns.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, who have made the playoffs only once in the four
Major League Soccer seasons, look much better now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough spell for us, only making the playoffs
once,'' Harkes said. ``It helps that our team has a better attitude
this season, and the playoffs is in our grasp.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
