<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-lopez-HNS &LR;      07-24 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-lopez-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heard finally benefits from twists of fate in 200
</P>
<P>
   BY JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene came to
rewrite history, but a lesson in perseverance broke out.
</P>
<P>
   If you're disappointed that the vaunted Johnson-Greene 200-meter
showdown limped into infamy, don't be. This was better.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the greatest Olympic story isn't the one you read
about, but the one you forgot about. Sometimes the men with the
golden shoes and the neon running suits can learn something from a
guy with a solid gold heart.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Heard was Michael Johnson before there was a Michael
Johnson. Heard was Maurice Greene when Greene still was running
middle-school meets.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere along the way, Heard, the Texas A&AMP;M ex, became the
forgotten Santa Monica Track Club sprinter and the epitome of
heartbreak and disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic Trials can be cruel,'' Heard, 34, said. ``They can
be the cruelest thing in the world. I know.''
</P>
<P>
   If you considered Johnson's leg cramp and Greene's hamstring
strain in Sunday's 200-meter final a tough break, then you don't
know tough breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Heard was the No. 1-ranked 200-meter man in the world in 1987, a
sizzling sprinter considered a better bet for gold at the 1988
Games than even his world-class Houston training partners _ Carl
Lewis, Leroy Burrell, Michael Marsh and Joe DeLoach. But before the
1988 Trials, Heard suffered a stress fracture in his foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `OK, I'll be there in '92,''' Heard said.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't. Heard underperformed, was outdone in 1992 and
didn't make the team. In 1996, he made it into the 200-meter finals
again but finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The once-golden career seemed over. For nine years, Heard
trained so much in the background of his Santa Monica Club
teammates that his nickname should have been Wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   For nine years, he won so many international sprints and even
performed at the World Championships, but the world's greatest
Games never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to watch the Olympics because it hurt so much,
but I always did because those were my teammates out there,'' Heard
said. ``We had some great ones _ Carl, Leroy, Mike, Joe. But I was
the only one that never made it to the Olympics. It was very
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson and Greene were asking ``Why me?'' after both came up
short on Sunday, they don't know what self-doubt and angst truly
can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Olympics didn't happen, I thought I could have ended my
career still satisfied,'' Heard said. ``This sport has always been
fun and something I love. You don't go through what I've gone
through if you don't love competing. But I guess in my heart I
always would have had a little emptiness.''
</P>
<P>
   But the dream finally was fulfilled Sunday. The most heroic
performance was the one you never thought you'd see.
</P>
<P>
   Some 14 years after bursting onto the international scene as a
phenom every bit as touted and talented as Johnson, Heard did what
Johnson and Greene could not. He finished second behind youngster
John Capel to qualify for the Olympic team in maybe the fastest 200
field ever to perform on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   Some 12 years after first breaking the 20-second barrier and
turning so many heads, Heard finally did it again. Only months
after facing long odds in his attempt to try one more time to
fulfill his Olympic dream _ ``To be honest, I had some doubts
myself,'' Heard said _ the long, solitary hours of training at
Robertson Stadium finally led to the ultimate prize.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hype and contention between Johnson and Greene,
perseverance and maturity won out in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Santa Monica colors are flying again,'' Heard said. ``I
can't explain the feeling. I just ran my very best. I didn't really
know what was going on behind me with (Johnson and Greene). I just
knew that I had to make this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the hype never bothered me at all. At 34, I've seen a lot
of things in my career. I've heard it all. In fact, everything with
those guys (Johnson and Greene) I thought was kind of funny.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you think Heard's making the team was a fluke, some kind
of lucky break considering the tough breaks experienced by Johnson
and Greene, you weren't paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Heard's first-round qualifying time in the 200 was barely more
than one-tenth of a second off Johnson's qualifying time _ and
Johnson was pushed in his race, while Heard cruised.
</P>
<P>
   And in Sunday's semifinal round, Capel, who went on to win the
final, defeated Johnson head-to-head, while Heard's semifinal time
was .15 seconds faster than Greene's.
</P>
<P>
   This was billed as Johnson and Greene's race, but it belonged to
Capel and Heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Floyd run (20.18) on Saturday, I knew he was
ready,'' said Lewis, who flew into Sacramento only hours before
Sunday's final to offer support to his teammate and business
partner. ``The (Johnson and Greene feud), I could care less about
that. That's not why I was here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was here to see Heard finally fulfill a dream. When Heard
walked off the track Sunday, the first person to congratulate him
was Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us that trained together all those years are retired,
so nobody counted (Heard) as a contender,'' Lewis said.``But he ran
the race of his life. For him to go through what he did and do what
he did, it's just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Making history took a back seat to making amends.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I heard from Carl all day was, `You're going to make this
team. . . . You're going to make this team,''' Heard said. ``I
honestly didn't know, but I never gave up, I'll say that. I don't
think anyone here knew better than me that the Olympic Trials can
break your heart. But you know, they can make you feel like you're
on top of the world, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Heard is.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
