<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six-homer binge in-Spiers Astros
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   If asked to pick the Astro most likely to have two homers and
six RBIs in a game that included a grand slam and an unprecedented
curtain call, anyone who chose Bill Spiers would be a candidate for
a straitjacket.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it was a crazy day at Enron Field, where the Astros
walloped the St. Louis Cardinals 15-7 Sunday before the fifth
consecutive sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not me,'' Spiers said of his powerful performance. ``I
was lucky, real lucky. They always kid me around here about having
no pop, which I don't. I just got lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it was more than luck.
</P>
<P>
   Spiers, the utility player deluxe, led a 14-hit attack for the
Astros, who won a series for just the eighth time this season. They
took two of three games from the National League Central-leading
Cardinals and won consecutive games for the first time since June
13-14 at Colorado and for the first time at Enron Field since May
25-26.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the first game of the series by a season-worst 11
runs, the Astros outscored St. Louis 25-12 over the final two
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at this and see how strange this season has been,''
said Astros right fielder Lance Berkman, who had two of the Astros'
franchise-record-tying six home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the talent to play with anyone. We just haven't played
or pitched with any consistency to give ourselves a chance. The
pitching is getting better, and position by position, we're as good
as any team in baseball. We just haven't put it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the past two days can serve as a beginning for the
Astros, who have played .500 baseball over the past 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing some good signs,'' said Spiers, who was 3-for-5.
``Hopefully, we will play better ball for the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a breakout day for Astros righthander Shane
Reynolds, who snapped a career-high-tying four-game losing streak,
not to mention a four-game losing streak at Enron Field dating to
May 27. Overall, Reynolds (7-7) had not won since June 13 at
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely felt good to win again,'' said Reynolds, who
allowed six runs (five earned) in 6 innings. ``The offense and
defense were just great. Those guys did their jobs, no doubt about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio and Julio Lugo joined Spiers in the three-hit club,
while Berkman and Richard Hidalgo each drove in three runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 3-0 lead in the first inning on Moises Alou's
sacrifice fly and a two-run double by Hidalgo. The trouble
continued for Cardinals starter Andy Benes (10-5) in the second
when the Astros scored six runs on six hits, including four home
runs _ a franchise record for a single inning _ by Spiers, Jeff
Bagwell, Berkman and Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   By allowing four home runs in an inning, Benes tied a
major-league record. The infamous feat had been accomplished on 16
previous occasions, most recently by Astros righthander Jose Lima,
who allowed four homers in an inning earlier this season against
the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Benes had not allowed a home run in the 27 innings
leading up to the power surge.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' offense took the next four innings off, allowing the
Cardinals to pull within three runs entering the bottom of the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vina's three-run homer started the Cardinals' comeback
bid in the fifth after Reynolds had held them to just two hits over
the first four innings. St. Louis added another run in the sixth,
and Fernando Tatis' two-run single decreased the Astros' lead to
9-6 in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that point, the momentum had shifted the other way,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   That soon changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros put the game under lock and key with six runs in the
seventh on Spiers' third career grand slam and a two-run homer by
Berkman, giving them a season-high 15 runs for the game.
</P>
<P>
   After going 113 at-bats since his only other homer this season,
Spiers hit two in a span of four at-bats Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The grand slam moved the Enron Field crowd of 42,684 to elicit a
curtain call from Spiers _ the first curtain call in the brief
history of the Astros' new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a curtain call before, and I wasn't going out
there for that one,'' the extremely reserved Spiers said. ``But the
guys kept pushing me out there. It happened so quick, but it was
nice. I'm just trying to do my job and do what they ask me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he went above and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
