<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0908 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISHOPEN-HNS &LR;      07-24 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISHOPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   British Open a Slam dunk for Woods
</P>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ There's no defense in golf. You can't
tackle your opponent. You can't put a hand in his face. And you
can't pick up his ball and throw it in a bunker.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean people haven't thought about it with Tiger
Woods. When he's running into the history books while he's running
away with the British Open by eight strokes, crazy notions enter
their mind. They'll even tell him about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the players, I'm going to say it was Calc (Mark
Calcavecchia), was imitating the Bill Murray line about slicing the
hamstring,'' Woods said. ``He did it so well. It's a funny line.
And he said it just like him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Caddyshack line called for cutting Judge Smails' hamstring.
``He'll leave everything out to the right; he'll quit the game,''
says Murray's character, assistant greenskeeper Carl Spackler.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really stinks about it is you can't control him,'' said
Paul Azinger. ``In every other sport, you can control your
opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   There's not a thing anybody can do about Woods, except try to
get better. A lot better.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' victory Sunday on a cool, cloudy Scottish evening gave
him a career Grand Slam, putting him in elite company with Jack
Nicklaus, Gary Player, Ben Hogan and Gene Sarazen.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval tried to hang with Woods in the final round. But he
faded on the back nine and crashed with a quadruple-bogey 8 on the
17th hole. Runners-up Ernie Els and Thomas Bjorn fired and fell
back, and nobody else could get close as Woods shot a closing 69
for a 72-hole total of 19-under 269.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he had done in winning the U.S. Open by 15 strokes last
month, Woods left everybody in awe again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to do this every major _ at least I hope not,''
said Calcavecchia, a former British champ. ``You just have to take
your hat off to him. The way he has dominated in today's game, when
there are as many good players as there are, is really incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that long ago that I said there would never be
another Jack Nicklaus. But in fact, we're looking at one. He is the
chosen one. He's the best player who has played the game right now.
And he's only 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Nicklaus was the greatest of all time, and he has the
greatest record of all time. And when it's all said and done, he
still might have the greatest record of all time. But if Jack was
in his prime today, I don't think he could keep up with Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Woods' numbers are as good or better as any that have
been amassed in the past 50 years:
</P>
<P>
   At 24, he's the youngest player to complete the career Grand
Slam, beating out Nicklaus, who did it when he was 26.
</P>
<P>
   His 19-under score is the lowest in relation to par in any major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   He has won 13 of the last 23 PGA Tour events he has played,
which means he's winning 57 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   He has won six times in 2000 and 14 times since the beginning of
the 1999 season. The last player to win 14 times in two years was
Nicklaus in 1972-73.
</P>
<P>
   He is only the third British Open champion to shoot four rounds
in the 60s, joining Greg Norman in '93 at Royal St. George's and
Nick Price in '94 at Turnberry.
</P>
<P>
   He's the sixth player to win the U.S. and British Opens in the
same year and the first since Tom Watson in '82.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, he now holds three major championship trophies,
including last year's PGA, which he will defend next month. The
last person to hold three majors at the same time was Nicklaus in
'72.
</P>
<P>
   He's missed only one cut in 83 tournaments as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   There now are only 24 players in history who have more Tour wins
than Woods' 21. If he doesn't win anymore this year and averages
four per year starting next year, he'll pass record-holder Sam
Snead's 81 victories in 2016, when he's 40.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods, who constantly uses Nicklaus as his yardstick,
doesn't feel compelled to make comparisons at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you ever want to be the next Tiger Woods or the
next Jack Nicklaus or the next Michael Jordan or whatever,'' Woods
said. ``Try to be the best you can be. Don't try to be like us. Try
to be yourself. That's something I've tried to do. I will continue
to try to do that, and I hope other kids will try to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there is no way to compare Woods with anybody who is
actively playing and competing on the PGA Tour. And it's getting
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it is,'' said Els. ``In one way, it's incredible to
watch a guy play so much better than the rest of the world. And in
another way, it's tough to sit down here and talk about him every
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I might have to get used to it. I'm probably living in an
era with the next great player. I've got to play really well, and
he has to have a mediocre week (for Els to win).''
</P>
<P>
   Woods mowed down 22 birdies for the week and had only three
bogeys. The one he had Sunday, on the 17th, didn't matter because
he had a nine-shot cushion at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Added Duval: ``It was a spectacular performance to say the
least. He simply did not make the mistakes and capitalized on the
holes you expect him to capitalize on. He's playing very
efficiently. I think that's the best way to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo, whose record of 18 under par at St. Andrews is _
like everything else this week _ history, has some advice for
anybody who plans on taking a bite out of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these 15-year-olds, they have to stop eating the
doughnuts,'' said Faldo. ``He's thrown all these old myths out the
window _ that you can't physically train for golf, that you can't
be strong or you'll lose your touch. It's no good sitting back and
thinking, `I won't go and practice because it's raining.' If you're
going to compete and beat Tiger, you have to be out there doing as
much if not more.''
</P>
<P>
   He's stronger and smarter than everybody else in the game. And,
maybe, than anybody else who's ever played the game.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
