<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0909 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-200METERS-HNS &LR;      07-24 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-200METERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Capel takes 200 as Johnson, Greene go down
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JERRY WIZIG
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Talk about anticlimactic. Even in the
dullest of pre-hyped Super Bowls, they play 60 minutes of football.
</P>
<P>
   But in the hyped-up Super Bowl of the 2000 U.S. Olympic Track
and Field Trials, the men's 200 meters, world-record holders
Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene lasted 50 and 100 meters,
respectively, in Sunday's final event of the closing program.
</P>
<P>
   Before Johnson and Greene hit the track, Marion Jones assured
herself of an opportunity to go for five gold medals at the Sydney
Olympic Games, winning the 200 in a sizzling 21.94 seconds to add
to her previous wins here in the 100 and long jump. Assuming her
inclusion on the 400 and 1,600 relays, Jones finally was able to
take a deep breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use one word, I'm glad it's over,'' she said. ``That's more
than one word, but it explains how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, fastest in history in the 200 and 400, underwent
treatment for what was diagnosed as a cramp in his right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed I won't be running in Sydney in the 200, but
I'm 32 years old and at the end of my career,'' Johnson said. ``But
I have a gold in the 400 and the (1,600) relay, and I can try for
another in the 400 (in which he was first here). I don't think it's
a tear or anything serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had felt a twinge in the left quadriceps in Saturday's
first round of the 200 but declared himself healthy after warming
up for the semifinals, in which he and Greene were seeded
side-by-side in the same heat.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours later, Greene, like Johnson before him, was
transported via golf cart to the press tent. Greene's trainer
diagnosed his injury as a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't know if there is a tear until the doctor looks at
it,'' Greene said. ``I felt OK in the semifinal and just intended
to run my best. I don't know how long it would take for me to get
back if it is a tear. I don't think it was the heat or the rivalry
(with Johnson). My body wasn't ready to do what I asked it to do,
and it stopped me.''
</P>
<P>
   With only five runners crossing the finish line (Brian Lewis was
a scratch), John Capel, a Florida sophomore who gave up his
scholarship earlier this season to start a professional track
career, won the 200 in 19.85 seconds. Earning his first Olympic
berth in second was Floyd Heard, 34, in 19.88.
</P>
<P>
   Both Capel and Heard, a Houstonian, ran their lifetime bests.
Auburn senior Coby Miller was third in 19.96, the first time in
Trials history all three Games qualifiers have cracked 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Johnson said he would not accept a ``wild card''
into the 200 at the Olympics even if offered one as defending
champion, a procedure used in the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it (wild card) was already there, OK, but not now,'' he
said. ``You guys (the press) would kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added: ``I think we all learned a lesson from this
(pre-race hype). Somebody got hurt the last time, too (his own
quadriceps injury during the 1998 match race with Donovan Bailey,
which Johnson also failed to finish). All it did was (tick) all the
other guys off. I've been through these kinds of `showdowns'
before, and once it gets rolling, you can't stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Jones talked briefly with Johnson between the semis
and finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pooped and worried about having time (nearly two hours)
to recover from it,'' Jones said. ``I told Mike, `They're trying to
kill us,' and he said, `Get used to it. It gets worse at Sydney.'''
</P>
<P>
   Inger Miller, the 1999 world champion, was second behind Jones
in 22.09 in just her fourth 200 of the year. University of Texas ex
Nanceen Perry was third in 22.38.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
