<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0910 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     07-24 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Enjoy the ride with `chosen one'
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ This is what greatness looks like.
</P>
<P>
   Its eyes are cold and deadly. Its arms are long and larcenous.
It hangs over the history and the heather like a cloud, and it
hangs around the pins and the record books as if they were a
birthright.
</P>
<P>
   It can have a prickly disposition. An inexorable heart. It
dresses in red and also wears the emotions of a snorting, charging
bull.
</P>
<P>
   It scores in smothering waves _ sudden, shuddering tsunamis.
</P>
<P>
   Greatness looks like the perfection of Tiger Woods'
follow-through on a tee shot and the zero-gravity ease with which
his ball always seems to float toward the hole.
</P>
<P>
   With Woods taking the fabled Old Course at St. Andrews by the
throat for his first British Open title _ does this make him the
Claret Jug-gernaut? _ these major tournaments are becoming less
competition and more coronation ceremony than anything this side of
Westminster Abbey.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's latest roar has made it clear he is as singular a figure
_ in his or any other sport _ as there is on the landscape today.
</P>
<P>
   He dominated the U.S. Open last month at Pebble Beach, and he
mastered the most confounding of games again in the land of its
Scottish roots. And the margin both times was as large as the ocean
that separates the countries.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, he was 19 under par, an all-time best for any
major, and his closest pursuers _ Ernie Els and Thomas Bjorn _ were
eight shots back. At one point, David Duval drew within three
shots, but he slowly cracked and then crumbled at the Road Hole,
spending more time in the bunker than Eva Braun. But those are mere
facts, which no longer define Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   He has gone beyond athlete to the artist's realm now, operating
on a level most of us cannot comprehend, speaking a language that
is pure genius with his clubs, his shots, his unbending, laser-beam
focus, and his sheer will.
</P>
<P>
   By lapping the field, he stripped this venerable event as bare
as the female streaker who did a maypole dance around the pin on
the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's game should not be dissected, merely admired. It should
not be placed in a display case in a museum behind protective
glass, but embraced and enjoyed by an appreciative world that,
because of him, is now flocking to what was once an elitist sport.
</P>
<P>
   The official list now tells us he joins four golf immortals _
Gene Sarazen, Ben Hogan, Jack Nicklaus and Gary Player _ as the
only players to win the modern Grand Slam in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Our own eyes tell us that he stands on a Mount Olympus peak of
his own, because he is only 24 years old. That winning smile is so
young and childlike, yet the whole face seems to possess the
Yoda-like wisdom of a thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny Friday afternoon, the Open bid farewell to Nicklaus,
to date the greatest golfer who has ever lived. In the seaside
chill of Sunday evening, the home of the Royal &AMP; Ancient may have
seen everything we ever thought we knew about the future of golf
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that long ago when I said there'd never be another
Jack Nicklaus,'' said Mark Calcavecchia. ``But we're looking at
one. He's it. He's the chosen one.''
</P>
<P>
   We should not try to dig too deep to find out what makes Woods
tick or what will tick him off. Instead, we should understand that
he possesses a special gift and let him unwrap it and reveal it at
his own pace and time.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger has the aura of Muhammad Ali without the arrogance and
confrontational nature. He has the raw talent, the taste for blood,
the killer instinct of Michael Jordan and, in his sport, no
teammates to occasionally weigh him down.
</P>
<P>
   After conquering the Colonies, he came to Britain and did a
reverse version of the Beatles' invasion. Yeah, yeah, yeah. Like
Lennon and McCartney, he is writing words and music that will
endure, and the key for the rest of us is to let his deeds and
accomplishments sink in, store the images, and be able to say years
from now that we were there. We saw him.
</P>
<P>
   They still talk at St. Andrews of Old Tom Morris and Young Tom
Morris, the father-son combination who were the early Open dynasty.
But they have never, ever seen anything like Woods.
</P>
<P>
   He won the two toughest tournaments in the world by a combined
23 strokes, and he did it without making a single shot that truly
sticks in your mind. That's because he was clean, efficient and
skilled, like a Swiss watchmaker or a surgeon. Yet full of poetry,
listening to his own muse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can eliminate some of the loose shots in my game,'' he said.
``No doubt about it. I can play better.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what greatness sounds like.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
