<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0956 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PRESCOTT-AZR &LR;      07-24 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESCOTT-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-PRESCOTT-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    GROWTH FRIENDLY TO PEOPLE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MARK SHAFFER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back when the Fain family ran cattle on their ranch along
Arizona 69, the last thing people in these parts thought about was
having a high-density, pedestrian-friendly downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, it was a big deal when the first Circle K set up shop
along the highway just more than 20 years ago, when Prescott Valley
was a pit stop of 2,000 on the way to Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the planners of Prescott Valley, now the
fastest-growing town in Arizona outside the Valley, never even
considered having a downtown as subdivisions and stoplights
sprouted like wildflowers around a square mile of grasslands owned
by the Fains.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that is about to change radically.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent urban planners from around the country have praised
Prescott Valley, population an estimated 26,000, for being a leader
in ``new urbanism'' thinking and say the town's planned downtown
area will be much more akin to a European village than Prescott's
Whiskey Row.
</P>
<P>
   The anchors are just about in place.
</P>
<P>
   A large, futuristic, three-story Town Hall was opened last year
on the north side of the property with special emphasis placed on
glass, open areas and atriums.
</P>
<P>
   Harkins Theaters broke ground recently on a large cineplex and
the walls started going up earlier this month on the south side of
the property. The theaters are expected to be open in March.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the area between town hall and the cineplex that has
caught the attention of urban planners.
</P>
<P>
   Walking and biking are in. Cars are out. Merchants living above
their businesses are in. Houses in suburbia are out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis is going to be on large, wide sidewalks with bike
routes, major public squares and open areas,'' said Richard Parker,
Prescott Valley's community development director. ``The intent here
is to have a downtown of pedestrian-friendly businesses like old
Main Street from a town 100 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker and other town officials say they plan to attract a
second hospital to the central Yavapai County area on the east side
of the property, and an existing community college campus on the
west side is expected to be neighboring high-tech research and
development firms in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Town planners are searching for a major hotel chain to build a
large hotel just south of Town Hall. The area around the hotel
would be filled in with apartments and town houses, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said Prescott Valley has a lot going for it, which will
be attractive to business. The key to making the downtown project
go has been having a targeted area with only one landowner. And a
landowner, the Fain family, willing to take chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have cashed out on their place to developers a long
time ago,'' said Joe Brett, a spokesman for the Fain Signature
Group. ``But they've had the ranch in their family since the 1870s
and they want to create a special place where people can enjoy
forever rather than just a bunch of strip malls.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Browning, a Prescott architect who has been involved in
the downtown planning, said it has been a unique experience in
Arizona, creating a downtown area after subdivisions already were
in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prescott Valley hasn't been much except strip development
which accommodated the outflow of people from Prescott,'' Browning
said. ``There has been no defined center. Now, we will be able to
offer people a chance of being in a really special place, one
that's going to be very different from Prescott.''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at Mark.Shaffer(a)Arizona Republic.com or
(602)444-8057.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 08:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0957 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-WASHES-AZR &LR;      07-24 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHES-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-WASHES-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    TAMING DESERT FLOODS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clents)(a) 
 &HT;    By KATHLEEN INGLEY(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Floods in the desert?
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers to the Valley think it must be a joke. After all, this
is a place that goes months without rain and brings in Colorado
River water along hundreds of miles of canals.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding not only happens but it also packs a special fury in
the desert.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's history is punctuated with inundations.
</P>
<P>
   Take 1921, when Cave Creek roared into Phoenix, soaking the
Capitol building, after a storm dumped 6 inches of rain in two
days. Seven large floods drenched central Arizona from 1977 to
1980, and Phoenix was declared a disaster area three times.
</P>
<P>
   Each bout of flooding has typically triggered a rush to build
dams, culverts and other protective barriers of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   The Maricopa County Flood Control District says it make more
sense and costs a lot less to let nature tame the storm water in
many areas of future development.
</P>
<P>
   Cities are starting to go along. In May, Peoria decided to block
large developments along 2.5 miles of the New River so floodwaters
can surge through without causing damage. The Phoenix City Council
voted in June to let natural washes act as drainage for an area
east of Interstate 17.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the pluses and minuses of nature vs. concrete, one
must look at the peculiar behavior of water in the desert: the way
it goes out of control, the flood plains and the enormous power of
erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Navajos divide rain into two types, male and female. They
correspond to the two types of flooding in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Winter brings the gentler female rain, falling steadily for long
stretches in storms that cover large areas. The runoff, especially
combined with melting snow in the mountains, can cause devastating
regional flooding.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy winter rains of 1993 sent the Salt, Gila and Santa
Cruz rivers over their banks, causing $400 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Violent summer thunderstorms, the male rains, bring flash floods
that ravage smaller areas. Three years ago, Tropical Storm Nora
doused northwest Maricopa County with up to 12 inches of rain in 24
hours, a state record. Thundering down washes, the water breached a
dam while central Phoenix barely recorded rain.
</P>
<P>
   The force of floodwater in the desert can be staggering, because
it moves so fast.
</P>
<P>
   Force is the square of the velocity, so if speed doubles, the
power of the water quadruples.
</P>
<P>
   A person standing in waist-deep water running 6 feet per second
will be hit with the weight of a football tackle - 140 pounds of
pressure on each leg. And washes may run at triple that speed.
</P>
<P>
   Flood protection in Arizona generally is designed to handle a
100-year event, the type of severe flooding that has a 1 percent
chance of occurring in any given year.
</P>
<P>
   Many people mistakenly believe that means such floods happen
only once a century. But they can occur back to back: The Salt
River in the Phoenix area had three in a row: 1978, 1979 and 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The area that would be underwater in such a severe flood is
called the 100-year flood plain, and it's difficult to map out in a
recently developed state like Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The East has written records that go back for several centuries
and ``a culture that generation to generation has farmed the
land,'' said Amir Motamedi, Maricopa County hydrologist. ``They
know where not to build.''
</P>
<P>
   As an added complication, the sandy washes and dry riverbeds
that carry the Valley's storm water may move back and forth over
time.
</P>
<P>
   The county uses many tools to map the flood plain and movement
of the watercourses, including historical records, aerial photos,
location of debris, soil analyses and test trenches dug to check
for sediment.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetation gives a clue about where flooding has occurred.
Saguaros, for instance, have shallow roots and can't withstand
strong water flows.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists can trace the irrigation system dug by the
Hohokam Indians from about A.D. 1 through the 1400s and figure out
where and at what level the washes must have run.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional approach to flood plains is to eliminate them by
filling in the low spots next to a wash and riverbed. That allows
development on land that would otherwise be flood-prone.
</P>
<P>
   The drawback is that the storm water can't spread out, so it
runs deeper and faster in the washes and riverbeds, which must be
reinforced with concrete or stone. That's expensive - building a
concrete channel costs $2 million a mile and more plus maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The go-with-the-flow solution, letting natural washes carry
storm water, has a different price: keeping development off the
flood plain.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers is wrestling with that
inescapable fact nationwide as it tries to move away from shunting
water into concrete channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take more property or preserve more land,'' said
Richard DiBuono, a hydraulic engineer with the Corps. ``It's hard
to do in the middle of an urban area.''
</P>
<P>
   The natural approach may also be impractical in areas of the
Valley with sheet- flooding, where there aren't deeply defined
washes to carry large flows so water spreads out evenly over a
broad area.
</P>
<P>
   You won't see another Indian Bend Wash either. The long, grassy
corridor in Scottsdale, combining flood control with ball fields
and parks, couldn't be built under today's water-use rules, which
prohibit so much turf in the public right of way. Flood control
used to focus on the sheer volume of water. But now attention is
shifting to the danger of erosion and sediment.
</P>
<P>
   The erosive power of desert floods was vividly obvious in 1983,
when torrents of water devoured up to 300 feet of river banks in
Tucson, ripping the ground out from under buildings.
</P>
<P>
   When homes were built in that area, no one had paid much
attention to the risk that the dry riverbed would move and erode.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the floods. ``All of a sudden, the bank is under the
living room,'' said Tempe geomorphologist Jonathan Fuller, ``and
the house is toppling into the stream.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency, which runs the national
flood insurance program, has just finished a study about mapping
erosion along rivers, the companion to a study of coastal erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very significant issue,'' said Matthew Miller, chief
of hazards study in FEMA's mitigation directorate.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what Congress decides, FEMA could raise the
insurance rates in erosion-prone areas or it could adopt guidelines
calling for building to be restricted to a certain distance from
the banks of rivers and washes.
</P>
<P>
   Water surging down a wash looks almost alive, like a writhing,
ravenous beast, and that's not far off. Hydrologists think of water
as hungry for sediment.
</P>
<P>
   As water moves faster, it picks up more sand, rocks and debris.
Double the speed of the water, and it has 16 times the carrying
capacity, with the muscle to grab large rocks. Floods at Skunk
Creek in north Phoenix have left melon-sized boulders stuck in the
branches of trees.
</P>
<P>
   A typical stream in the East carries less than 1 percent of its
volume in sand. On flooded washes in Arizona, the concentration of
sediment can go as high as 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When storm water is routed down a concrete channel, it moves
swiftly and remains clear. It will chew voraciously into any
unprotected area it encounters, so banks must be protected the full
length of the watercourse.
</P>
<P>
   Another risk occurs when water slows down and loses some
carrying capacity. Then it begins dumping sediment - so there's
less room for storm water in the future and properties are flooded
that never got wet before.
</P>
<P>
   But predicting just what desert washes or rivers will do is
tricky. ``There are so many unknowns,'' Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   He has a table that predicts how certain variables affect stream
behavior, and there are upwards of 100 factors, from depth and
slope to water temperature and soil type.
</P>
<P>
   The complexity leads Fuller to a simple formula: ``The more we
leave them alone, the less we have to fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at Kathleen.Ingley(a)ArizonaRepublic &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .com or (602) 444-8171.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
