<HEADER>
A0960 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-HISTORIC-AZR &LR;      07-24 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORIC-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-HISTORIC-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    HISTORY'S LOSS SPLITS PHOENIX(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By PAT KOSSAN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   St. Mary's Elementary School is coming down, opening yet another
gap in Jerry Green's already frayed connection to his home town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to hell with St. Mary's, to hell with Phoenix Union, to
hell with Phoenix Tech, to hell with Montgomery Stadium,'' Green
said, ticking off the vanishing landmarks of his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total separation from the traditional, old Phoenix,''
said the 1951 graduate of St. Mary's Elementary and a graduate of
St. Mary's High - itself demolished to make room for the Arizona
Center.
</P>
<P>
   In Green's family, the concern spans generations. Granddaughter
Alicia, 14, attended St. Mary's Elementary, at Fourth and Van Buren
streets, until it closed in 1994 due to lack of enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm heartbroken,'' Alicia said Thursday, when news broke that
the Phoenix Catholic Diocese plans to tear down the 74-year-old
school. ``When we got up this morning, it's all we talked about.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a common sentiment, but only one side of a debate that pits
preservation against progress, a reverence for history against the
spirit of hustle that many Phoenix residents say has always been
central to the city's identity.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, all but four buildings on the Phoenix Union
High School campus came down. Also removed were the 71-year-old
Safeway Bakery in the city's Warehouse District, plus an entire
block once owned by Borden.
</P>
<P>
   Besides St. Mary's Elementary, other Phoenix historic buildings
that could be demolished include:
</P>
<P>
   Adams/Grace Court School, 800 W. Adams St., built in 1911.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe School, N. 215 N. Seventh St, built in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Union's four remaining buildings, built between 1912 and
1921 .
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Feed &AMP; Seed Co. Warehouse, 411 S. Second St., built in
1905.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery Homestead, 1721 S. Seventh Ave., built in 1880.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists insist that historic buildings, even those in
private hands, belong to the city's culture and should be saved and
reused. They are a draw for tourists and a priceless aspect of the
city's identity.
</P>
<P>
   But John Jacquemart of the Phoenix Historic Preservation
Commission notes that preservationists' outrage seldom builds into
political will. That's in part because most of the city's historic
homes and commercial buildings date to the 1920s and 30s - not very
old to residents transplanted from the country's older cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are new,'' Jacquemart said. ``That not saying we're not
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the debate are owners of many of the most
endangered historic buildings who plan to demolish them. They say
their downtown property is more valuable without the structures
because they are too costly to restore.
</P>
<P>
   When Ella Young's Montgomery Homestead made the Phoenix Historic
Preservation Commission's list of most endangered buildings in May,
her response was to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a widow,'' Young said, ``and I have to do what I can and
make money.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Phoenix Feed &AMP;Seed Co. warehouse was equally
blunt when asked about the fate of the building in May, calling
restoration ``economically unviable.''
</P>
<P>
   But if a study group can be seen as progress, maybe the city is
inching toward a compromise. Phoenix officials were embarrassed by
the city-orchestrated demolition of the 78-year-old Phoenix Union
High School industrial arts building in April .
</P>
<P>
   Since then, city managers and several council members, including
Phil Gordon, have been putting together a panel of foes -
preservationists, developers, property rights champions.
</P>
<P>
   The panel will try to plot a new course by fall for saving the
city's grandest landmarks - one all sides can embrace. The city
needs to make owning a historic building an asset instead of a
headache, Gordon said, perhaps with tax and fee waivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is a process to vent, express, propose and make
suggestions for change,'' he said. ``What we have is such a
divide.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a divide that often splits over the bottom line. Despite
pleas from alumni such as the Greens, for example, Diocesan
officials said the Spanish Colonial Revival school is just too
expensive to save and reconfigure into a workable building.
</P>
<P>
   After a one-year moratorium, imposed on all buildings listed on
the Phoenix Historic Register, St. Mary's is coming down along with
the diocese's office building, constructed in 1950, which also
houses a 1926 chapel.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders want to buy and close the part of Fourth Street
that divides the properties and create a campus, which would
include a new Diocesan office building, conference center and
parking spaces, to open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Conference centers and parking lots are important, Ignacio San
Martin said. But if they prevail too completely, Phoenix might end
up with little to offer visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't go to cities to look at suburbs,'' said the Arizona
State University professor, who researches the history of cities
and urban planning. A city that doesn't care about its past, he
added, may not have an interest in its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's just an interest in the here and now,'' said San
Martin, who calls such a city ``a rock candy mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a view the world has of America that everything is for
the taking-now. Taking and not giving,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he wonders if that's not an apt description of Phoenix,
where historic buildings are coming down and freeways are going up.
Meanwhile, he said, many cities around the country and world are
renewing efforts to save, restore, and reuse historical buildings
and landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading the landscape of a city is about understanding where
it is, where it's been and where it's going,'' San Martin said.
``We are very young and unsure of where we're going.''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at Pat.Kossan(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8960.
</P>
</TEXT>
