r e BC-HARRISONFORD-INTERVIE     07-24 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRISONFORD-INTERVIES-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-HARRISONFORD-INTERVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    HARRIS FORD ON ``WHAT LIES BELOW''(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    (REPEATING)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beverly Hills - Harrison Ford may be the star of the modern-day
ghost story (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath(enditalic), but that
doesn't necessarily mean he likes horror movies.
</P>
<P>
   Or even watches them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last scary movie I went to and enjoyed was
(beginitalic)Bambi(enditalic),'' Ford says in a recent interview.
``I was about 6 years old, and it scared the bejesus out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath (enditalic)is Ford's first real
foray into the supernatural, unless you count the occult elements
in the Indiana Jones series. He says he took the role because it's
different from what he's done lately and allowed him to work with
director Bob Zemeckis and co-star Michelle Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   He also liked the script, or as he puts it, ``the quality of the
set-up, the establishing of the relationship and the surprises the
plot holds for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very emotionally truthful film,'' Ford adds. ``And I
think that's one of the reasons you get sucked into it as an
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 58, plays Dr. Norman Spencer, a respected researcher
married to the beautiful Claire (Pfeiffer). The couple's idyllic
life begins to unravel after their picturesque Vermont lake house
is haunted by the spirit of a woman who looks remarkably like
Claire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events are seen from her perspective,'' Ford says. ``It's
her point of view, because she's the one with the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's stylistic camera work smacks a little of Alfred
Hitchcock, though Ford says (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath
(enditalic)takes it up a notch from the ``master of suspense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I admire the tradition of Hitchcock {ellipsis} I
never really believed his characters,'' he says, ``to the extent
that I think these characters are believable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we invested a lot more in the emotional reality of
these characters and less in the plotting elements that were
typical of Hitchcock.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ford's fans, this is a departure from roles like Han Solo,
Indiana Jones and the president of the United States, which he
played in (beginitalic)Air Force One(enditalic). Ford, who thinks
of his fans as customers, says that's the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people who have been my customers over the years
have enjoyed the fact that we don't serve the same meal every
time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains, however, that Ford gained his fame as an
action hero, from (beginitalic)Star Wars (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)Raiders of the Lost (enditalic)(beginitalic)Ark
(enditalic)to films like (beginitalic)The Fugitive (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)Patriot Games(enditalic). But he hasn't done much
action-adventure in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really read anything in the action genre in the last
couple of years I thought was good enough to do,'' he says. ``I'm a
bit tired of the motivations for action that they generally use.
Retribution and revenge bore me now.''
</P>
<P>
   In his films, Ford says, he tries to establish that violence has
costs, both for the victim and the perpetrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate gratuitous violence,'' he explains. ``I hate
indiscriminate gunplay for its entertainment value.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford also talked about recent revelations about the cult classic
(beginitalic)Blade Runner(enditalic), in which he plays a detective
trying to hunt down rogue ``replicants'' - artificial life forms
that resemble humans. After the release of the movie's ``director's
cut'' on DVD, fans began to see more clues that Ford's character,
Deckard, was a replicant himself.
</P>
<P>
   Director Ridley Scott recently removed all doubt, telling the
BBC that Deckard was indeed a replicant.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford says that as far as he's concerned, the character in
the 1982 film was human. He says that during the filming, he
battled Scott to keep Deckard human, ``because I think the audience
deserved one proxy on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was aware that Ridley did not fully agree with me.
{ellipsis} He kept slipping in little details which indicate I was
a replicant,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ford maintains that it would be difficult to replicate
(beginitalic)What Lies Beneath(enditalic), which he considers
top-notch:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary, surprising, unexpected, accomplished and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Contact Muller at Bill.Muller(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
