NYT-07-24-00 0804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 08:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WHAT-LIES-BENEATH-REV     07-24 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-LIES-BENEATH-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-WHAT-LIES-BENEATH-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ``WHAT LIES BENEATH'' WILL RAISE YOUR HAIR(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    (REPEATING)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can always rank a horror movie by how high you jump during
its really scary parts.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath (enditalic)has just raised the
bar.
</P>
<P>
   This taut supernatural thriller is the scariest movie since
(beginitalic)Poltergeist(enditalic), building suspense throughout
with sly camera work and a creepy, claustrophobic feel. Michelle
Pfeiffer is brilliant in the leading role, elevating her already
formidable game to another level.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer plays Claire, wife of Dr. Norman Spencer (Harrison
Ford), a respected researcher with a hidden past. But Claire begins
to learn the truth after she sees the wraithlike figure of a young
woman and hears mysterious sounds echo through the couple's
rambling two-story lake house.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just where this slam-bang ghost story starts. You'll
have to put your head on a swivel to keep up with the twists and
turns in this expertly constructed tale of distrust, betrayal and
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath (enditalic)also contains one of
the most terrifying sequences since the two priests entered the
bedroom in (beginitalic)The Exorcist(enditalic). The movie should
include one of those sensational warnings from the '50s: ``No one
will be admitted in the last 10 minutes of this film!'''
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, the movie isn't that different from others of the
genre, except in its execution. You could have taken the same story
and filmed it with different actors and another director, and you
would have some sad (beginitalic)Amityville Horror
(enditalic)sequel.
</P>
<P>
   But director Robert Zemeckis ((beginitalic)Forrest Gump, Who
Framed Roger Rabbit) (enditalic)takes a simple horror story and
turns it into something special. He steers away from the
slasher-film formula, concentrating instead on Claire's
psychological deterioration during her ordeal, which is
particularly torturous because the ghost looks just like her.
</P>
<P>
   To keep us on our toes while Claire unravels, Zemeckis employs
well-worn cinematic devices: spooky mirrors, billowing steam and
those tight camera shots that have the whole audience yelling,
``Look out behind you!'' He pays homage to several Hitchcock films,
including (beginitalic)Rear Window (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)Psycho(enditalic), but that doesn't distract from or
interrupt the movie's flow.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, you start to get nervous anytime a character
walks into the house and flips on a light switch. There's just no
telling what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen all these moves before, but the camera work, pacing
and acting put this film on a higher plane. The story is quirky and
creative enough to keep the audience interested, even during the
setup.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting actors - especially Diana Scarwid, who portrays
Claire's wisecracking best friend - play their roles with
enthusiastic vigor. Scarwid helps the movie maintain a wry sense of
humor, and Zemeckis uses that light tone to meticulously build
Pfeiffer's character throughout the first hour. When things start
to fall apart, the audience is clearly rooting for her.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer, who is on the screen in almost every scene, deserves
plenty of credit for the movie's success, and perhaps even an Oscar
nomination. Her performance runs the gamut from silly to sultry,
from confused to terrified. She smoothly handles her transformation
from all-American mom to haunted woman.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the first hour, Ford is almost window dressing,
though there is clearly chemistry between Pfeiffer and him while
they cavort as a happily married couple. As Pfeiffer's paranoia
builds and strange things start happening, Ford's character plays a
more pivotal role.
</P>
<P>
   The final 30 minutes are as frightening as it gets. If you're
not scared, you're probably covering your eyes. As far as that
goes, I can hardly blame you.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Contact Muller at Bill.Muller(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
