r e BC-LOSER-AZR &LR;      07-24 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSER-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-LOSER-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ``LOSER'' {ndash} THE TITLE IS RIGHT ON(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    RESENDING(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In (beginitalic)Loser(enditalic), Jason Biggs plays a character
from a small town.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more like he's from Mars. His character, Paul, is so
unfamiliar with common phrases (he's apparently never heard of a
six-pack), it's like he just stepped off a spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   Though supposedly the winner of an academic scholarship, Paul is
an incredible dope. He gets duped by his sleazy roommates so many
times you have to wonder if he has short-term-memory loss. Fool me
once, shame on you. Fool me 27 times, and we're doing a CAT scan.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is a contrived, tangled mess, following Paul as he
leaves home and goes to college in New York. Because he's such a
darn nerd, he's not accepted by his moronic, sadistic roommates
(big loss there), and ends up sleeping in a veterinary clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Dora (Mena Suvari), a street-smart kid trying to work her
way through college. She's also having an affair with her
literature professor (Greg Kinnear), who treats her like a doormat.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we've just got to get those two crazy kids together.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, there's really no one to root for in this movie.
Both Paul and Dora are professional victims, and Paul's roommates
are drug-dealing date rapists. Kinnear's character is equally
creepy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Paul and Dora stumble through a bunch of scenes
ripped off from other movies. The plot dredges up this old
chestnut: He loves her, but she's oblivious despite the fact he
buys her flowers and hangs on her every word. Unlike, of course,
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The only surprise ending is in the credits: This film was
directed by Amy Heckerling, who also did the delightful
(beginitalic)Fast Times at Ridgemont High(enditalic) as well as
(beginitalic)Clueless.
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 0805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 08:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-INCROWD-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      07-24 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCROWD-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-INCROWD-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ``THE IN CROWD'' SHOULD BE COUNTRY-LUBBED(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED IT(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The posters for (beginitalic)The In Crowd (enditalic)are tagged
with the line: ``What would you do to get in?''
</P>
<P>
   After the first 45 minutes, you'll be asking: ``What can I do to
get out?''
</P>
<P>
   It's really not clear what they're trying to accomplish with
this movie, a poor man's (beginitalic)Cruel Intentions
(enditalic)without Sarah Michelle Gellar or even the slightest
shred of a script.
</P>
<P>
   The first half plays like an extended episode of
(beginitalic)Baywatch(enditalic), as we watch snobby
twentysomethings frolic on the beach and make catty remarks to each
other. They're led by Brittany (soap star Susan Ward), a poor
little rich girl who likes to manipulate her friends while she
romances the local tennis pro.
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't sound familiar, I want to congratulate you for
escaping from the gulag.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half the movie turns dark, as Brittany clashes
with Adrien (Lori Heuring), a country club worker who has been just
been released from a mental hospital, where she suffered from
something called ``erotomania.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the movie's only claim on the erotic thriller genre,
since most of the film is neither erotic nor thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany has a dark secret, which we figure out in the first 20
minutes of the movie. She spends the rest of the time scheming
about this and that, but after awhile, we don't care anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The film also suffers from a bad case of (beginitalic)Chariots
of Fire (enditalic)syndrome: Many of the male characters look
alike, so it makes the silly plot that much harder to follow.
</P>
<P>
   And just when we think we'll escape, the movie gives us a
drawn-out ending, punishment perhaps, for trying to join
(beginitalic)The In Crowd(enditalic).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
