<HEADLINE>
SUMO HIP-HOP: ROLL OVER, SHAQ: THIS RAPPER PUTS THE STOMP ON THE
CHOMPY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (editors: please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time was when a professional athlete who wanted a second career
would become a sports commentator, an actor or a restaurateur. Not
anymore. Today, the path off the playing field is leading
increasingly into the recording studio. Shaquille O'Neal of the Los
Angeles Lakers, his teammate Kobe Bryant and Ricky Watters of the
Seattle Seahawks have all recently made rap albums.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most extreme example of this crossover is the former
sumo wrestler Konishiki, whose debut rap/reggae/R &AMP; B compact disk,
``Konishiki KMS'' _ short for ``Konishiki Master Sumo'' _ has just
been released by 125th Street Records. Born as Salevaa Atisanoe in
Hawaii to Samoan parents, Konishiki (pronounced co-NEESH-kee and
meaning Delicate Embroidery) retired from the ring in 1998 after a
16-year career in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his new CD, he says, ``There are aspects of sumo
like the concept of `makenai-desu' _ an attitude of, `I will not
lose' _ which I've used in the ring.'' Indeed, the influence of
sumo, which in its modern form dates to the 17th century, permeates
the album in, well, unusual ways.
</P>
<P>
   _ By THOMAS VINCIGUERRA
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In ``Takamiyama: The World of Sumo''
(Kodansha, 1973), the sumo wrestler Takamiyama stresses the high
value of manners and courtesy: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to imagine a sumotori, no matter how strong and
confident, bragging before a bout about how he was going to
demolish his opponent the way Muhammad Ali might.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) But ``Livin' Like Kings,'' the first cut on
Konishiki's album, betrays no false modesty: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Make way for the Sumo,
</P>
<P>
   Comin' straight out ((of)) Samoa,
</P>
<P>
   Known to shake the ground
</P>
<P>
   When I first touch down. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Built to last like the Energizer Bunny;
</P>
<P>
   Pushin' 700 and still makin' money.
</P>
<P>
   Step into my Dojo, you're bound to get crowned,
</P>
<P>
   Thrown out the line or smashed to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Competition? I'm the biggest, I ain't no rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Overweight lover and still known to boogie.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the house down when I hit the floor,
</P>
<P>
   And sing karaoke for an encore.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Most people eat to live; sumo wrestlers
live to eat, as the authors Andy Adams and Clyde Newton note in
``Sumo'' (Hamlyn, 1989): (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to eating and drinking, many sumo wrestlers could
put to shame such famous gluttons as Diamond Jim Brady.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Konishiki is down with that: (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Next on the menu is a seven-course meal;
</P>
<P>
   Sushi to start, raw tuna and eel.
</P>
<P>
   That's how we do it in the back of the club,
</P>
<P>
   Toast champagne as we get a back rub. . . .
</P>
<P>
   In the limelight, 'cause it's my turn,
</P>
<P>
   All the food I can eat, with the money to burn.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) According to Bill Gutman's ``Sumo
Wrestling'' (Capstone, 1995), these are giants among men: (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   His strength and size make the professional sumo wrestler almost
impossible to move _ except by another sumo wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In ``Settin' 'em Up,'' Konishiki
elaborates: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I'm solid, or do I need to go in detail?
</P>
<P>
   I rain like rock hail, my plan is not to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Sumo, step in the circle, step out the circle, fly out the
circle,
</P>
<P>
   However you go, as long as you know,
</P>
<P>
   You're better off battlin' a bullet train
</P>
<P>
   Or pullin' your head off in a guillotine.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Gutman says the risk of injury is minimal
among seasoned sumo wrestlers, but Konishiki begs to differ in
``Settin' 'em Up'': (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   You battle me, you're gonna need a nurse
</P>
<P>
   Fo' a broken back, a ruptured spleen, right arm fractured clean;
</P>
<P>
   I laugh _ it really don't mean jack to me. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Ha-ha-ha, stick 'em; ah-ah-ah hit 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Honey, smack 'em; hog-slap 'n' I slick 'em. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Don't be lookin' foul, you lose; you choose to
</P>
<P>
   Step in the diameter, I bruise you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-SUMO-SINGER-TEXT-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: bruise you. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In his memoir, Takamiyama describes an
obligatory training exercise: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Shiko, or stamping, involves raising each leg as high as
possible and bringing it down on the dirt with great force.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Konishiki's ``Sumo Stomp'' takes shiko to
another level: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I am, ah, the Sumo Stomper,
</P>
<P>
   The one you stomp.
</P>
<P>
   I put the stomp there on the chompy,
</P>
<P>
   Don't it sound funky?
</P>
<P>
   S-T-O-M-P-S-umo,
</P>
<P>
   Now, how ya like me?
</P>
<P>
   Cold like ice tea,
</P>
<P>
   Good like rice be,
</P>
<P>
   Do it like Nike!
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Sumo Stomp,
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make the party jump.
</P>
<P>
   So if ya diggin' me, let me see your hands.
</P>
<P>
   Get on the floor, and let me see ya dance!
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Where do sumo wrestlers come from? Here's
Doug Kenrick's answer in ``The Book of Sumo'' (Weatherhill, 1969):
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Sumotori are not a special breed; they are young Japanese men of
greater than ordinary physical proportions who have been selected
or have chosen to make the sport their living.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) But in ``Sumo Funk,'' Konishiki sees the
hand of the Almighty at work: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The ancient one, he said,
</P>
<P>
   `You're the chosen one, you see.'
</P>
<P>
   Brother, right then I knew
</P>
<P>
   I had the Sumo Funk in me.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Although the wrestlers work hard, Adams and
Newton explain, they don't get to play hard: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The lower-ranked rikishi [wrestlers) have so many chores and
other duties to take care of that they have very little time of
their own. They must obtain permission from the stablemaster to go
out, especially at night.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) No such drudgery awaits Konishiki in
``Another Day in Paradise'': (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Loungin' with my peeps and my cousins,
</P>
<P>
   Eatin' kiwi by the dozens.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't even go inside today
</P>
<P>
   'cause in the ocean's a-where I like to play,
</P>
<P>
   Sipping on Pina Coladas,
</P>
<P>
   Scoping out the fine-looking models . . .
</P>
<P>
   Day two, here's the plot:
</P>
<P>
   We can hit the spot
</P>
<P>
   Wit' the DJ mixin' on my yacht.
</P>
<P>
   Dancing all day on a 50-foot deck,
</P>
<P>
   Cruising on the ocean, getting soaking wet. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I got a coupe in the back, it's hooked up, it's real tight.
</P>
<P>
   Wit' the top down, let the beat pound,
</P>
<P>
   Wave hello to my fans, step out and just clown.
</P>
<P>
   Fun and games is an everyday thing,
</P>
<P>
   Party 'til dawn, or kick back and just hang.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Finally, can a sumo wrestler find true love
despite his bulk? A July 1997 National Geographic article thinks
so: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   In counterpoint to their slightly built fellow countrymen,
rikishi are fat, but _ with their intense exertions _ not
necessarily unhealthy, and to many Japanese women they are most
definitely not unattractive.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Konishiki says as much _ and more _ in
``Toast the Night Away'': (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   It's you and me all alone,
</P>
<P>
   On a rendezvous made for two.
</P>
<P>
   Loungin' in a suite on the Nile,
</P>
<P>
   Do anything, girl, just to see you smile.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time and the days have passed;
</P>
<P>
   I've been around the world since I seen you last.
</P>
<P>
   It takes two to make a thing go right,
</P>
<P>
   So if you're feeling what I'm feeling, then tonight's the night.
</P>
<P>
   So we can make plans to make things better,
</P>
<P>
   You're my girl for life, so I'm down for whatever.
</P>
</TEXT>
