<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 30)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending July 15 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. TEARS OF THE MOON, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   An Irish songwriter, shut off from the world, finds hope
</P>
<P>
   and happiness with a tomboy.
</P>
<P>
   2. ASHES TO ASHES, by Tami Hoag. (Bantam, $7.99.) Kate
</P>
<P>
   Conlan, a former FBI agent, tracks a serial killer in
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (Perennial/HarperCollins, $14.) Five female characters
</P>
<P>
   narrate a novel set in the Belgian Congo during that
</P>
<P>
   country's fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   4. GRANNY DAN, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.50.) A woman
</P>
<P>
   learns the secrets of her grandmother's past in czarist
</P>
<P>
   Russia.
</P>
<P>
   5. HANNIBAL, by Thomas Harris. (Dell, $7.99.) Seven
</P>
<P>
   years after his escape, the fiendish psychiatrist
</P>
<P>
   Hannibal Lecter is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   6. WHILE I WAS GONE, by Sue Miller. (Ballantine, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A small-town veterinarian, the wife of a minister, begins
</P>
<P>
   a flirtation with an old friend from her bohemian past.
</P>
<P>
   7. LIGHTNING STRIKES, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket Star,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A drama student goes to live with her great-aunt,
</P>
<P>
   whose estate is filled with terrors.
</P>
<P>
   8. TOM CLANCY'S OP-CENTER: Divide and Conquer, created
</P>
<P>
   by Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik; written by Jeff Rovin.
</P>
<P>
   (Berkley, $7.99.) Traitors try to oust the president.
</P>
<P>
   9. DANGEROUS KISS, by Jackie Collins. (Pocket Books, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Santangelo tracks down the killer of a member
</P>
<P>
   of her family.
</P>
<P>
   10. JUPITER'S BONES, by Faye Kellerman. (Avon/HarperCollins,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) Detectives probe the death of an astrophysicist who
</P>
<P>
   became the leader of a cult.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE QUIET GAME, by Greg Iles. (Signet, $6.99.) A
</P>
<P>
   best-selling author and former prosecutor tries to reopen
</P>
<P>
   a 30-year-old race murder case in the South.
</P>
<P>
   12. IRISH HEARTS, by Nora Roberts. (Silhouette, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Two previously published novels, now in one volume, about
</P>
<P>
   Irishwomen's lives in America.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE SAVING GRACES, by Patricia Gaffney. (HarperTorch,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The close friendship that binds four women is
</P>
<P>
   put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE GIRLS' GUIDE TO HUNTING AND FISHING, by Melissa
</P>
<P>
   Bank. (Penguin, $12.95.) The love life of a young New York
</P>
<P>
   woman.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE WHITE HOUSE CONNECTION, by Jack Higgins. (Berkley,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) Tracking an assassin who threatens the stability
</P>
<P>
   of Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) MCNALLY'S DILEMMA, by Lawrence Sanders. (Berkley,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Archy McNally investigates the death of a Florida
</P>
<P>
   playboy who lived a tangled life; written by Vincent Lardo
</P>
<P>
   after the death of Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger. (Perennial/
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.) The story
</P>
<P>
   of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/Simon
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Schuster, $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced
</P>
<P>
   by feelings of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. THE HUNGRY OCEAN, by Linda Greenlaw. (Hyperion, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   A sea captain's account of her 30-day swordfishing
</P>
<P>
   voyage off the northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   4. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   5. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man who
</P>
<P>
   survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   7. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/Simon
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Schuster, $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer
</P>
<P>
   recalls his childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) I'M A STRANGER HERE MYSELF, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) The author describes what it's like to return to
</P>
<P>
   the United States after living abroad for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health Communications,
</P>
<P>
   $10.95.) The author of ``A Child Called `It''' recalls
</P>
<P>
   his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10. THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene. (Vintage,
</P>
<P>
   $15.) A presentation of superstring theory, which is an
</P>
<P>
   attempt to mediate between quantum mechanics and general
</P>
<P>
   relativity.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor, $15.) A journalist explains the instant electronic
</P>
<P>
   global economy.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) THE FIRST WORLD WAR, by John Keegan. (Vintage, $16.)
</P>
<P>
   A historian recounts the 1914-18 conflict from the
</P>
<P>
   viewpoint of the strategists and the men in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor, $13 and
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest
</P>
<P>
   season in history.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (Perennial/HarperCollins, $13.) How a murderer and
</P>
<P>
   certified lunatic helped James Murray complete the
</P>
<P>
   Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) GUNS, GERMS AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance
</P>
<P>
   to geography. (b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways to
</P>
<P>
   lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. RICH DAD, POOR DAD, by Robert T. Kiyosaki with Sharon
</P>
<P>
   L. Lechter. (Warner, $15.95.) Teaching one's children
</P>
<P>
   how to get rich and stay rich.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE FOUR AGREEMENTS, by Don Miguel Ruiz. (Amber-Allen,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) A code of conduct based on personal freedom. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. TAKE TIME FOR YOUR LIFE, by Cheryl Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A seven-step program for enhancing
</P>
<P>
   one's social, financial and spiritual well-being. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5. THE WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL HANDBOOK, by Joshua
</P>
<P>
   Piven and David Borgenicht. (Chronicle, $14.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Coping with nasty surprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
