<SLUG> BC-R-MIDEAST-JERUSALEM-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERUSALEM: THE HOLIEST CITY, THE TOUGHEST CONFLICT, THE HIGHEST
STAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When the late afternoon sun turns the crenellated
limestone walls of the Old City to warm glowing gold, it is easy to
understand the intense emotional hold of this tiny place.
</P>
<P>
   Suleiman the Magnificent, the Ottoman sultan, built these walls
in 1538 _ rebuilt them, really, from the stones left behind by
Romans, Jews, Muslims, Byzantines, Crusaders, the Arab armies of
Saladin and the Mamelukes. They are walls that enclose sites holy
to the three great monotheistic religions.
</P>
<P>
   That well-known fact places Jerusalem at the very heart of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict, an issue so difficult, so sensitive,
that until now peace negotiators simply put it off. The city, and
the idea of it as a capital, is a central icon to both sides. Jews,
after centuries of dispersion and persecution, still end their
Seder each Passover: ``Next year in Jerusalem.'' And in virtually
every Muslim home in every Palestinian refugee camp there hangs a
picture of the Dome of the Rock.
</P>
<P>
   But now the negotiating teams at Camp David are trying to come
to grips with Jerusalem, and they are finding it an extraordinarily
difficult task _ to imagine the unimaginable, a truly united (or
fairly divided) Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   It may be tempting to think that the easiest basis for a
settlement would be to admit that the two sides share a heritage
and guarantee all groups access to the holy sites. But in 50 years
of conflict _ and more than 20 years of peacemaking _ achieving
that kind of formula in Jerusalem has only become harder. That is
because new layers of grievance, resentment and reason for distrust
have been added on both sides. And in many Israeli and Palestinian
minds, these only reinforce the idea that their one best guarantee
of access and security is sole political control of all or part of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, the holy place is the Western (or Wailing) Wall, the
remains of the Second Temple built on Mount Moriah after the return
from exile in Babylon. For Muslims, it is the plateau on the Temple
Mount above the wall, known as the Haram al-Sharif, or noble
sanctuary, from which the prophet Muhammad made a visit to heaven
on his winged horse. The sanctuary contains the Dome of the Rock
shrine and Al Aksa Mosque, the third-holiest site in Islam. It is
exactly the same place, and both Jews and Muslims share the belief
that the rock itself is where Abraham prepared his son for
sacrifice. For Christians, the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, a
short distance away, is where Jesus was crucified, buried and
resurrected to redeem mankind's sins.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem and its holy sites were deemed so unique that, under
the doomed 1947 United Nations partition plan for turning the
British Palestine mandate into Arab and Jewish zones, the city was
to become an international district. It was an idea acceptable then
to David Ben-Gurion and his overwhelmingly secular Zionist
associates, who had more regard for security considerations than
for controlling religious shrines.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arab armies attacked instead, and Israel as born in a
bitter war. Israeli troops fought their way desperately up the
twisting road through the hills to relieve Jews besieged with
little food or water in the new city that had grown up outside the
Ottoman walls. The rusted hulks of their makeshift armored cars
still line the road as monuments. But the Jordanian King Abdullah's
Arab Legion, trained and led by British officers, held the heights
above Jerusalem, captured the Old City and incorporated it into
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   From 1948 to 1967, Jerusalem was a divided city _ half
Jordanian, half Israeli _ with limited passage allowed through the
Mandelbaum Gate, mostly for international officials and Christian
clergy. Most important for the future, the Old City was sealed off
to Jews and many of their religious sites were defiled. Then, in
the 1967 war, Israel took all of Jerusalem and the West Bank, its
triumphant army chaplain, Shlomo Goren (later to become a chief
rabbi of Israel) blowing his ram's horn at the Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 30 years, Israelis created their own facts on the
ground, building settlements in the West Bank, expanding Jewish
neighborhoods into East Jerusalem and neglecting services to the
Arab areas. Even since the Oslo accords, Israelis have continued to
build Jewish housing in Arab neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has made decisions on how to treat Jerusalem in a
peace settlement extraordinarily difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Khalil Shikaki, a Palestinian academic who has advised the
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, said last week that ``the
Palestinian public will not tolerate less than full sovereignty
over all of East Jerusalem, including the Haram al-Sharif.
Palestinians will not tolerate Israeli border police or Israeli
checkpoints. That is not sovereignty, that is not control.
Palestinians no longer want to ask Israelis for permission to build
their homes, to educate their children, to live their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But, at the same time, he said that if they were persuaded that
the Israeli approach was genuine, ``the Palestinian street would
certainly be flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-MIDEAST-JERUSALEM-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; JERUSALEM: be flexible.'' &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Amirav knows this city well. As a young paratrooper who
had already been wounded in the 1967 war, he climbed out of a
hospital window to rejoin his unit when he heard it was trying to
retake the Old City. He entered politics with the hard-right Likud
youth movement, served on the City Council and worked under the
famous Mayor Teddy Kollek on roads, planning and other municipal
matters. His political views moved toward the left years ago, and
he is now one of a handful of Israelis who have been trying to find
solutions for Jerusalem, meeting frequently with the local
Palestinian leader Faisal Husseini, whose forebear died commanding
the Arab force trying to block the road to Jerusalem in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is a two-fold problem,'' Amirav said. ``The
emotional and psychological problem and the very practical
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Old City, he noted, is a mere one square kilometer in a city
that now measures 120 square kilometers. (In 1967, West Jerusalem,
the modern Jewish part of the city, was 37 square kilometers, and
Jordanian East Jerusalem was 7.) And, he said: ``Jerusalem is not a
united city. It is a divided city, one of the most divided in the
world. More divided than Belfast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the euphoria of 1967, we annexed 28 Arab villages that
later on became Arab neighborhoods,'' he said. ``Our aim was to
enlarge the Jewish population, but we did all the most stupid
possible things.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible solution, said Dr. Amirav, who teaches conflict
resolution at Hebrew University, is redrawing the boundaries of the
city to ``enlarge the pie'' and devising ways to share power. As
for the sensitive religious sites, he says Israelis need to be
reminded that since 1967 the Temple Mount has been under the
control of the Waqf, the Islamic charity directed by the mufti of
Jerusalem, a decision made by the Israeli military hero and former
defense minister, Moshe Dayan.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel may well be thinking along
similar lines. Last week, he called Reuvan Merhav, a former Foreign
Ministry official and member of the Jerusalem Institute for Israel
Studies, to join him at Camp David. The research institute had
prepared a report, bristling with complicated maps, showing various
options for enlarging Jerusalem by adding several large Jewish
settlements, including Ma'aleh Adumin in the West Bank, to the
municipality while at the same time giving a kind of ``functional
sovereignty'' to Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal on the table is literally building a bridge between
the village of Abu Dis, where there is already an imposing new
building believed destined to be the Palestinian Parliament, and
the Haram al-Sharif. Thus, Muslims, including Arafat, would be able
to go directly to their holy sites without having to pass through
Israeli territory or encounter Israeli police.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Dis, still a dusty little place, already partly inside
municipal borders, is on the Mount of Olives, directly overlooking
the Dome of the Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as the leaders met at Camp David, Israelis clogged
the phone lines to call-in shows with their own suggestions for how
to resolve Jerusalem's status. Much of the talk was pragmatic. And
yet, the fact of deep distrust and political resistance remains.
Arafat has declared that ``the Arab leader has not been born who is
willing to forfeit the rights of Muslims in Jerusalem,'' and has
reportedly told President Clinton he fears assassination if he is
seen giving up the goal of Jerusalem as a Palestinian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, whose own mentor, Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, was
gunned down for his peace efforts by an ultra religious Israeli,
saw his uneasy coalition government implode even as he departed for
Camp David. He was told last week of a newspaper poll back home
that reported that 70 percent of all Israelis believe that Israel
must not concede any part of East Jerusalem to the Palestinians in
any peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Natan Sharansky, who took his Russian immigrant party out of
Barak's coalition, has declared that ``Jerusalem is the very soul
which unites and fortifies the nation in its entirety.'' And two
former chief rabbis took out a newspaper ad to proclaim, ``Whoever,
God forbid, will lift his hand against the land of Israel and
Jerusalem and the Temple Mount will be written in shame and
disgrace for all generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The way to solve the problem, suggested Professor Rami Friedman,
the director of the Jerusalem Institute, who worked on the options
study, is perhaps not to solve it; that is, not to be too specific,
for each side has too much to lose. For the holy sites, he
suggested, perhaps it is best to muddle along. ``It sounds crazy
conceptually,'' he added, ``but it's very practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much history, so much religion, so much
nationalism embedded in that one square kilometer,'' he said,
``that any solution will create more conflict than you had
already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
