<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making Margin Calls in a Tightening Race
</P>
<P>
   In the album of Campaign 2000 cliches, get ready to paste in
``Too close to call.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a term that Americans are likely to hear frequently this
year, as strategists and journalists weigh in with state-by-state
analyses of the treacherous electoral map that confronts Gov.
George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The early conventional wisdom? It's too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Swing states in the presidential race like New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Illinois, Michigan, Missouri and Washington are
all rated as tossups or moving only marginally toward Bush, who is
strongest in the South and Rocky Mountain states, or toward Gore,
whose support is heaviest on the East and West Coasts. Factor in
the participation of third-party contenders like Pat Buchanan and
Ralph Nader, and it's hard to conclude anything except: It's too
close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The tightness of the race has, if anything, intensified the
guessing game of who the candidates will choose as their running
mates. With the Republican convention set to begin in Philadelphia
in eight days, most of the attention is on Bush's choice, which the
governor said he will make imminently.
</P>
<P>
   A leading contender is Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary
in the Bush administration. Other names mentioned frequently
include the Republican governors of two big industrial states, Tom
Ridge of Pennsylvania and George Pataki of New York, as well as
Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma and
former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is the name with star power, Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, who was reported to be softening in his
opposition to accepting the vice presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gore was making his case for the presidency in
Bush's own back yard, traveling to Texas to criticize his rival's
reign as governor, which got some Texans' dander up. ``Texas isn't
nearly as backward and third world as the Gore campaign would make
us out,'' said Michael Levy, the publisher of Texas Monthly
magazine. Proud of its homegrown candidate, Texas is probably not
too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The Elian of the Animal Kingdom
</P>
<P>
   On one side stands a teary-eyed Russian couple whose Brooklyn
community has vowed to go to any length to help them keep their
adopted pet monkey. On the other side is an adamant state
government backed by a host of monkey experts and the power of the
endangered-species law.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle, oblivious to all the fuss, stands Cookie
Flikshtein, a rare diana monkey who is living the good life, eating
Rocky Road ice cream and wearing frilly red miniskirts, while her
fate is being decided.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks after the conclusion of the Elian Gonzalez custody
battle comes an even stranger scuffle over little Cookie, age 6.
Her adoptive parents, Roman and Inna Flikshtein, have argued
unsuccessfully in court that there is no better place for Cookie
than their monkey-friendly home. The state attorney general's
office, meanwhile, maintains that Cookie is a member of an
endangered species and belongs in a special animal rescue program
at the Detroit Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   There are no immediate plans to wrest Cookie from the Flikshtein
home, where she has lived for five years in such familial bliss
that 13-year-old Michelle Flikshtein refers to the monkey as her
sister. But the Flikshtein's neighbors, many of whom are recent
immigrants from Russia, have closed ranks, promising to protect
young Cookie until the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to sit here and not let people come near,'' said
Lubov Gruber, who lives down the block. ``We will protest this for
as long as it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN FEUER
</P>
<P>
   Congress Approves Tax Cut to Help Married Couples
</P>
<P>
   Congress finished work on a Republican bill to give an
election-year tax break to married couples. But President Clinton,
saying the measure was too costly, promised to veto it. The bill
would provide $292 billion in tax cuts over the next decade, and
was intended in part to address the marriage penalty, the quirk in
the tax code that forces many two-income couples to pay a higher
tax bill than they would if they had remained single. Democrats
said they also want to address the penalty, but do it in a less
expensive way that directs more benefits to low- and middle-income
people.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Better Colon Cancer Test Urged
</P>
<P>
   The test used to screen healthy adults for colon cancer should
be changed, researchers say: Instead of the currently recommended
sigmoidoscopy, which examines the lower two feet of the colon,
patients should undergo colonoscopy, which probes its entire 4- to
5-foot length.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter test fails to detect abnormal growths high in the
colon, scientists warned in the New England Journal of Medicine.
But colonoscopy costs $1,500, and most insurers will not cover it
as a screening test.
</P>
<P>
   And the public has shown little enthusiasm for either test,
which require the insertion of long tubes equipped with cameras
into the rectum.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: DENISE GRADY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Internet Gambling Bill Fails
</P>
<P>
   In a blow to casino owners, the House failed to approve a bill
to curb the exploding $1.2 billion industry of Internet gambling.
Most lawmakers favored banning online casino-style games, sports
wagers and lottery sales. But despite wide backing _ from Christian
evangelists to liquor store owners _ they fell short of the votes
needed to limit debate.
</P>
<P>
   Cybergamblers, meanwhile, relied on an equally odd mix of
Republican governors, online casino operators and administration
officials to keep the largely unregulated industry on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS
</P>
<P>
   Loan to Fight African AIDS
</P>
<P>
   The United States plans to lend up to $1 billion annually to
sub-Saharan African nations where AIDS and HIV afflict 25 million
people. The American loans, which will carry commercial interest
rates, can be used only to buy American-produced drugs, equipment
or medical services. Officials expect Japan and Europe to make
similar amounts available to support their medical exports.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Harmon, the Export-Import Bank president, said the bank
intends to do well for America by doing good for Africa. The effort
was generally praised by charity groups and African nations, but
some Clinton administration officials worried that the loans
undermined efforts to arrange debt relief for the same countries.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
<P>
   Missile Offer by North Korea
</P>
<P>
   America needs a missile defense, some say, because of countries
like North Korea. One solution, according to Russian President
Vladimir Putin, who is rallying opposition to the missile plan, is
to remove North Korea from the equation. So he traveled to
Pyongyang, coming away with a North Korean offer to drop its
missile program _ if other nations provide it with rockets to
launch satellites. But that's a big if. As a former Pentagon
official put it, it's still unclear just ``what is going on in
North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Plan to Breach Dams Delayed
</P>
<P>
   A plan that could have led to the breaching of four dams on the
Snake River in the Pacific Northwest has been postponed. The plan
was aimed at easing the way for endangered species of salmon to
return to spawning grounds. But the White House chose instead to
embrace an alternative course. Trying to balance voters' support
for the salmon with regional officials' opposition to any breach,
it will propose smaller steps to help the species while deferring
until at least 2005 any razing of the dams.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOUGLAS JEHL
</P>
<P>
   2 Charged in Olympic Scandal
</P>
<P>
   Two chief organizers of Salt Lake City's bid to win the 2002
Winter Olympics, Thomas K. Welch and David Johnson, were indicted
on 15 counts of conspiracy to commit bribery, fraud and
racketeering relating to the vote-buying scandal that erupted in
1998. The indictment alleged that the men spent more than $1
million to bribe delegates of the International Olympic Committee.
The men denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Dr. Wade Exum, the former chief of drug
testing for the U.S. Olympic Committee, sued the committee,
claiming that 50 percent of American athletes who tested positive
for performance-enhancing drugs in recent years were not punished.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JERE LONGMAN
</P>
<P>
   Syria Gets a New Leader
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bashar Assad was sworn in as president of Syria, formalizing
the power he has wielded since the death in June of his father,
former President Hafez Assad. Assad, a 34-year-old eye doctor,
quickly tamped down hopes for dramatic change. He said he had no
``magic wand'' to reform the ailing state-run economy, would not
budge from his father's rejection of any compromise with Israel and
invited Syrians to express themselves _ but only with ``positive
criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By SUSAN SACHS
</P>
<P>
   Report on Murder of Gay GI
</P>
<P>
   After a 21-year-old gay Army private was bludgeoned to death
with a baseball bat by a fellow soldier as he slept in his barracks
last July, the Army opened an investigation into the atmosphere at
Fort Campbell, the Kentucky base where the murder occurred. A new
report has exonerated all officers of blame in the murder of Pfc.
Barry Winchell and has concluded that no climate of homophobia
exists at the base.
</P>
<P>
   Winchell's mother, who has sued the Army for the wrongful death
of her son, called the report a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., who is gay, said the report is one
more step in a virtually unbroken pattern of Pentagon contempt for
the rights of gay and lesbian service people.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELAINE SCIOLINO
</P>
<P>
   A Slippery Particle Is Found
</P>
<P>
   An elusive particle that had been on physicists' Most Wanted
list for 25 years has finally been detected, scientists announced
at the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory. Called the tau
neutrino, it is the last of a notoriously slippery family of
particles to be seen. Those particles, all neutrinos of various
kinds, pass through other matter almost without a trace. But they
are crucial elements of the theory that particle physicists believe
explains the structure of all matter.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is just one more particle predicted by the theory that
has not been seen. Physicists plan to begin chasing that particle,
the Higgs boson, next spring.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES GLANZ
</P>
