<P>
   MICHELLE PFEIFFER: ACTRESS, MOTHER, WIFE
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE-PFEIFFER-LIFEBEAT _ Trying to balance the demands of
motherhood, marriage and career, Michelle Pfeiffer swears she's
always out of time. Reportedly, she earns $10 million to 15 million
per movie, but she seems more preoccupied with her family than with
her celebrity. In fact, she apologetically but abruptly ends lunch
with a reporter when she realizes it's time to pick up her two
children from school. By Jeanne Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos of Michelle Pfeiffer are available on Newscom
or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG DECISIONS? THEY'RE OFTEN FALLING TO WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-DECISIONS-LIFEBEAT _ Women today are increasingly
familiar with the challenge, and the agony, of medical
decision-making. Over the past two decades, a revolution in
patients' rights and an explosion of information have enabled
women, and men, to educate themselves as never before. That is both
a blessing and a burden for women, who make choices not only for
themselves, studies show, but also for their husbands, children and
parents. Often, it's an overwhelming task. Some doctors have become
so enamored of a patient's right to choose that they are abdicating
their responsibilities as healers. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   GRUDGES ARE BAD FOR YOUR HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   GRUDGES-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT _ Not only does carrying around
unresolved anger sap your spirits; it also sabotages your immune
system, making you much more susceptible to such stress-induced
conditions as migraines, backache, arthritis and irritable bowel
syndrome. However, the worst threat, by far, is heart disease,
where the risk is 2.2 times greater in those with the highest
levels of the stress chemical homocysteine. Partially as a
palliative, some psychologists are now teaching courses in how to
forgive. By Diane Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   LESSONS FROM A YARD SALE
</P>
<P>
   YARDSALE-LIFEBEAT _ Deciding to participate in a neighborhood
yard sale, the author and her husband clean out their cellar,
unearthing memories and learning that one man's treasure is another
man's junk. By Carol Fleischman.
</P>
