<HEADLINE>
LESSONS FROM A YARD SALE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 By CAROL FLEISCHMAN 
 c.2000 Carol Fleischman
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, our neighborhood puts on a yard sale. All the
families share the cost of advertising, so there's not much to
lose. My husband, Don, and I decided to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a lot of work!'' Don cautioned. It turned out he
was right since he had the chore of hauling stuff up from our
basement. Yet, he couldn't have predicted the agony we'd suffer
sorting through it all. We divided the task of opening those boxes
and bins, but we didn't share the ordeal of determining what should
be sold. Don thought that ``trash and treasures'' referred to my
possessions and his, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's that bowl from Mildred.'' I frowned as I looked at this
gift from a deceased friend. How could I place a value on it?
</P>
<P>
   It was our first sale. It went for 50 cents, minus any sentiment
about our friend. We couldn't put a price on those memories.
</P>
<P>
   I had two favorite items and said, ``They'll fly out of here.''
Both were bought from expensive gift shops. My handmade doll and
the ornate Christmas ornament did not sell. How could 200 people
look at this stuff and not recognize my exquisite taste?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like they hate your hair,'' Don said. ``Don't take it
personally.'' He was right, but I wondered how he felt when his
valued self-help book, ``Miss Piggy's Guide to Life,'' didn't sell.
</P>
<P>
   The parade of shoppers lasted for two days. We took most offers,
especially those from children. An enterprising copper-haired
cherub made a bee-line for a 25 cent stuffed pig with shamrocks on
it. The novice shopper huddled with her parents and then walked
toward us with an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you take a nickel?'' I bit my lip and didn't say, ``Oh
honey, you can just take that toy.'' Maybe those high-finance
negotiations are one of life's lessons because she handed me the
nickel and proudly skipped down our driveway.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the only incident which amused me. Watching someone
guess the function of a gadget or trinket made game-show questions
seem simple. Picking up napkin-ring holders, a customer said, '' I
can use these as earrings for my kid's Halloween costume.'' (I
guess napkin rings aren't as common as they used to be.)
</P>
<P>
   Don had a good marketing technique. He put a table of 25 cent
items strategically at the farthest corner of our driveway. He
borrowed the idea from those remote milk-and-bread displays in
grocery stores. People had to walk past all the other treasures to
find the bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Our biggest sale came from a feisty lady who griped that she had
just fought with her husband. To escape, she went for a drive and
saw the sign at the corner of our street advertising the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take this, and I'll take that!'' She'd point and grin. I
wondered if her husband was as pleased when he unloaded her trunk.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I noticed is that bargain hunters are polite. ``Thank
you'' and ``I love this,'' gave the hope of renewed life to my
gently used stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a bag'' or ``I can give you the instruction booklet for
that,'' always brought a smile. However, there was one thing we
overlooked. Providing refreshments would have been a most
appreciated touch.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing we had missed lunch, I brought out sandwiches for Don
and me. It was bad timing, though. A customer who had decided on an
item dug in her purse for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for the lamp'' she said, looking at our food ``and how
much for your lunch?''
</P>
<P>
   (Carol Fleischman holds yard sales in Niagara Falls, N.Y.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
