<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1024 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-MICHELLE-PFEIFFER-LIF     07-24 2073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELLE-PFEIFFER-LIFEBEAT-ART-1,100&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MICHELLE PFEIFFER: ACTRESS, MOTHER, WIFE
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 (ART ADV: Photo of Michelle Pfeiffer is available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By JEANNE WOLF 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the terrifying new thriller ``What Lies Beneath,'' Michelle
Pfeiffer plays a woman who discovers that her marriage to Harrison
Ford isn't as perfect as it seems. As for her own marriage to TV
producer David E. Kelley (``Ally McBeal,'' ``The Practice''),
Pfeiffer, 42, uses the word ``lucky'' to describe their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The couple met just after she had decided to adopt a daughter,
Claudia Rose, on her own. They got married the day Claudia was
christened; less than a year later, their son, John, was born.
</P>
<P>
   A former Orange County, Calif., beauty queen, Pfeiffer proved
that she had the talent to match her great looks when she starred
opposite Al Pacino in ``Scarface.'' She earned her first Oscar nod
for a tour de force performance in the period costume drama
``Dangerous Liaisons,'' then stole the hearts of millions of males
as the sultry torch singer in ``The Fabulous Baker Boys,'' which
won her a second Academy Award nomination. ``Love Field,'' a
haunting interracial love story, which was the first film from her
own production company, brought her a third nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Like all women trying to balance the demands of motherhood and
career, Pfeiffer swears she's always out of time and out of breath
but all the sacrifices are worth it to have the family she's always
dreamed of. Despite her reported price tag of $10 million to 15
million per movie, she is much more preoccupied with her family
than with her celebrity. In fact, she apologetically but abruptly
ends our lunch at a popular seaside cafe near Los Angeles when she
realizes it's time to pick up her two children from school.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: You've been married for seven years _ a near record in
Hollywood. How do you manage to keep your marriage successful?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE PFEIFFER: I don't like the expression ``work at it,''
but we do tend our marriage. I think you have to spend time away
from the kids and stay up late and talk or go to the movies or do
the crossword puzzle together. We still have date nights, and I
look forward to them all week.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Isn't it hard, though, to even remember to put aside
that time, especially when you have two young kids?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I've seen couples who don't have things like a date
night and they start using their kids to avoid each other. It is
hard to slow down and find time for each other, but you need to.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: You were married once before, to ``Thirtysomething''
actor Peter Horton. You had to learn from that experience.
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I do think that the first thing that makes a marriage
successful is choosing the right somebody. If you're not a good
match, you can fake it for a while, but then it slowly falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Did you fear choosing the wrong person, especially
since you'd been burned a couple of times?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I got lucky. I think that in relationships, when you
say ``Oh, I never saw it coming,'' the truth is there are red flags
all along the way. We just choose to ignore them. The power of
denial may be the strongest thing next to the power of love.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: You were even willing to start a family by yourself, by
adopting a child while you were still single. Was that a turning
point for you?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: Well, it was brewing for a long time _ things don't
just happen overnight. I can see how I was leading up to it over
the years. At a certain point, I knew I needed to have a family and
I'd always wanted to adopt. But I had been waiting to get married
to do the whole family thing. Then, suddenly, it was just like a
lightbulb going off: ``I don't have to wait for that.'' I wasn't
going to marry the wrong person just to be married and have a
family.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: You were in the process of adopting Claudia when you
met David. How did that affect your relationship with him?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I think that her presence is actually one of the
things that bonded David and me. You get to an age where you have
personal baggage that can get in the way and mess things up in a
relationship. I think that Claudia gave us this other focus because
she came into our lives during our relationship. It took the
intensity off the two of us. If Claudia hadn't been around, I might
have messed up my relationship with David, which, of course,
thankfully also brought me my son.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: So loving her together let you open yourself to loving
him.
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I think that when you have your first child, you
become so vulnerable in a way that you never were before that you
let many of your guards drop. Having my daughter really changed my
life, just completely, forever.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: And you got to test your man as Daddy material before
you were married.
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: And David got to test me out as Mommy material.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: You have joked about being the ``designated driver'' in
your marriage. Does that mean you're the one in charge?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: No, David is equally in charge. I'm the designated
driver in the sort of day-to-day drudgery kind of things _ the
doctors the kids go to, taking care of the house, that kind of
thing. But in terms of shaping our relationship, David is equally
involved in that. In fact, he is definitely the more romantic of
the two of us.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: So what romantic things does he do?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I don't think he would want me to share them with you.
I might get in trouble. I will say that we spoil each other. I
can't even believe we've been married for so long because I still
feel like a newlywed. We spend a lot of time together as a family.
We don't have huge social lives and we live pretty simply. We took
the kids to the zoo over the weekend _ we do normal things like
that.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: What has surprised you about motherhood?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I think there's kind of a universal fear among women
about your first child_ you begin to panic about being a good
mother because you feel like you don't know anything. I was
pleasantly surprised that it came very naturally to me. I'm used to
having really high expectations and then things falling short of
those expectations. So I was surprised that being a mother exceeded
my expectations.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Of course there's the bliss of being a mother, but what
are the stresses that go along with it?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I think the worst thing is the sleep deprivation. It's
just awful. And when I think about having another child, that's the
one thing I worry about. I remember being so tired, especially with
my son because he was not a good sleeper. I'm just now getting
caught up on my sleep.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: What about juggling your career with the demands of
being a mother?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: The truth of the matter is that my kids would want me
home all the time. On the other hand, I think I'm a better parent
because I do what I love to do.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Have you always known that you had a gift as an
actress?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I don't really feel that gifted. I've always been a
hard worker and I have a lot of energy and I like to be prepared.
I've never been the type of person who just shows up and fumbles
through my lines. I love immersing myself in details about who the
character is. I feel like that's not necessarily a gift _ that's
diligence.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: What was driving you at the beginning of your career,
when you were just one more actress in Hollywood trying to land a
part?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I'd say I was naive. I think my naivete might have
appeared to be bravery, but in truth, I didn't know what I was
getting into. I would just dive in feet first and basically sink or
swim. The thing that I've always been good at in different stages
of my life is being able to recognize where the opportunity was and
move forward incrementally. Ultimately, my goal was to have control
over my life and have freedom of choice.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Do you know where that determination in you comes from?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: My father and his mother. My grandmother raised five
children during the Depression by herself. When she was 50, she
threw her sewing machine in the back of a pickup truck and drove
from North Dakota to California. She was a real survivor and that's
my stock. I come from that.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: How do you feel about watching your own performances
onscreen?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I'm my own worst critic, and I'm beyond pleasing. It's
hard for me to see my work, ever. Once a movie is completely
finished, I never see it again. Why punish myself?
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: You've done love scenes with just about every major
male star _ Mel Gibson, Bruce Willis, Robert Redford, Al Pacino,
George Clooney. Is it hard to ignite that feeling on the screen?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: The more you are genuinely fond of each other, the
easier it is. Fortunately I've worked with very few people whom I
haven't cared for. Still, it is actually a little embarrassing to
do those scenes. Probably out of nerves, I tend to giggle.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: What surprised you about working with Harrison Ford?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: He's very committed to his work and full of ideas and
very funny. I didn't know that about him. I didn't know he would
make me laugh so much.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Robert Zemeckis, the director of ``What Lies Beneath,''
told me that you can be funny, too, but that you weren't laughing
before the scenes you had to do underwater.
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: I've never been a water lover. I've always been a bit
claustrophobic and afraid of things being over my head and I've
never been able to hold my breath for long periods of time. I kept
saying to Bob in rehearsal, ``I panic in water.'' And he would say,
``We'll take care of that. Don't worry, it will be safe.'' But
after I mentioned it a few times, he finally said, ``Now I'm
getting afraid that you're going to panic and we're not going to be
able to shoot the scenes. How about we give you scuba diving
lessons?''
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK. Did that terrify you?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: At first it did. I had to practice going underwater,
and I would panic. Finally I got to the point where I was okay
breathing in a mask _ I actually began to enjoy that. Then they
would say ``Action!'' and take my mask and breathing tube away. You
open your eyes and you can't really see, so that's a whole other
panic. But we did it and they didn't make me feel like a complete
jackass just because I was afraid of the water.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Are your kids afraid of it, too?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: John doesn't love the water that much but my daughter
is a fish. She is really the swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Do you see big differences in the way each of them is
developing?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: Yes. My son and daughter were different from the
beginning. He likes trucks and she likes kitty cats, and he was
eating bugs and she wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   REDBOOK: Have you told Claudia that she's adopted?
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE: We don't keep any secrets from her. We always talk
about it openly so that the word ``adoption'' is not taboo. She
also has a lot of friends who are adopted, and she goes to a very
diverse school. She realizes that families are made up in different
kinds of ways and started in different kinds of ways. I think she
represents what's good in the world and what's hopeful about the
world.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeanne Wolf is an editor-at-large of ``Redbook'' magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
