<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRUDGES-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT-1100&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 GRUDGES ARE BAD FOR YOUR HEALTH
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 By DIANE GUERNSEY 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I listened to my friend ``Sylvia'' rage furiously at me over
the telephone, I felt a mix of anger, hurt and, above all,
bewilderment: why on earth had she waited three months before
letting me know that she'd been upset by something I'd said?
Unfortunately, no answer emerged over the following weeks. No
matter how we approached the issue, we couldn't seem to agree on
just what had taken place _ or what was meant by it.
</P>
<P>
   As our relationship sputtered along, the only certainty was that
I had joined Sylvia (at least temporarily) in a grudge-fest.
Ultimately we rebuilt our friendship, but I felt shaken enough to
want to take a look at grudges _ their ins and outs, causes and
cures. My delvings were eye-opening: I feel sure that Sylvia and I
would have tried harder to settle our differences had we known how
they were threatening our health.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does carrying around unresolved anger sap your spirits;
it also undermines your physical well-being. ``The effect of
internalizing anger is massive. It impacts your whole immune
system,'' says marriage and family therapist Dr. Jane Greer, author
of ``Gridlock: Finding the Courage to Move on in Love, Work and
Life.'' (Doubleday; $23.95; to order, call Books Now at
800-962-6651). ``It makes you much more susceptible to any
stress-induced condition.''
</P>
<P>
   These ailments include migraines, backache, arthritis and
irritable bowel syndrome _ but the worst threat, by far, is heart
disease. ``Physiologically, a chronically angry state can lead to
increased risk of heart attack,'' says Dr. Barton Sparagon, medical
director of the San Fran- cisco-based Meyer Friedman Institute,
whose groundbreaking research first identified the irritable,
aggressive Type A personality and the unhappy effects of type A
behavior on cardiac health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irritation causes the body to secrete stress hormones,
especially cortisol and norepinephrine, in excess.'' If these hover
at chronically high levels, they greatly increase your risk of
atherosclerosis _ the biggest cause of coronary artery disease.
They also spur the body's fight-or-flight response, says Sparagon.
``The heart rate and blood pressure go up, the blood gets thicker,
and its clotting time gets faster. All of this contributes to the
risk of heart attack or stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter whether you're young or old, male or female. A
large trial published in the ``Journal of the American Medical
Association'' found that among men and women under 60, the risk of
vascular disease was 2.2 times greater in those with the highest
levels of the stress chemical homocysteine; the risk was also
``notably higher'' in people with high blood pressure. As if this
weren't enough, excess cortisol in the blood also depresses the
immune system, making the person who packs a grudge ripe game for
any passing cold or flu bug.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the emotional fallout. ``You feel a sense of
emptiness when a relationship is severed without any resolution,''
Jane Greer points out.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends taking steps to break the impasse, even it's the
other person who's feeling offended. ``If a friend or colleague
suddenly is not returning your calls or talking to you, confront it
directly by making a phone call and saying,'I get the impression
you're upset with me, and I'm really interested in hearing what
you're feeling.' That can make a huge difference in whether people
get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if, as with Sylvia and me, the tried-and-true approach
_ talking things over, airing your grievances in a nonaccusatory
way, hearing out your friend, offering or accepting an apology _
doesn't work? You may need to consider the possibility of
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who's tried it knows, forgiveness is no quick-and-easy
procedure. Dr. Robert Enright, a professor of educational
psychology at the University of Wisconsin-Madison and president of
the International Forgiveness Institute
(www.forgivenessinstitute.org), divides the process into four
phases: uncovering (during which you become aware of how the
original injury and your reaction to it have affected your
psychological health); decision (you realize your old strategies
are ineffective and make a commitment to work at forgiveness); work
(reframing, through empathy and compassion, your view of the
offending person); and outcome/deepening (finding a new sense of
meaning through your suffering and forgiveness).
</P>
<P>
   These phases often overlap, says Enright, and the process is
exquisitely individual; but with time and dedication, forgiveness
can be achieved. Enright's upcoming book, ``Forgiveness Is a
Choice'' (APA Books), due out this November, ``details how to
forgive, with lots of practical exercises. We've used this model
with considerable success, even with people with deep trauma, like
incest survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frederic Luskin, director of the Stanford Forgiveness
Project (www.learningtoforgive.com) at Stanford University,
approaches forgiveness somewhat differently. He first got
interested in the subject 10 years ago as a student at Stanford.
``A friend of mine abandoned me and I didn't have a clue what to do
about it. I decided to do my Ph.D. thesis on forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   In crafting the approach he now teaches, Luskin drew both on
time-tested psychotherapeutic techniques and on the Buddhist ideal
of ``loving kindness.'' He says, ``I wanted to cast that concept in
psychological terms so that people could see the value of
open-heartedness as a strategy in life.''
</P>
<P>
   If you do decide to forgive someone, the evidence is very clear
that you'll be doing your health a favor too, says Enright. ``In
one recent study, we took college students and their middle-aged
parents _ all of whom had suffered a deep family hurt _ and
measured their health via two physical-health indexes: one lists
self-reported ailments; the other, physician-diagnosed illnesses.
We also measured their hostility levels, using a standard hostility
index. Among both students and parents, the least forgiving
individuals had more physical problems across the board _ both
self-reported and physician-diagnosed. We then looked at which was
a better predictor of heart disease: lack of forgiveness or
hostility,'' he continues. ``Lack of forgiveness scored far
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   The emotional benefits extend far beyond a sense of relief, says
Frederic Luskin. ``It's not just a weeding out of negative
emotions; it facilitates positive emotion. In one study, we took
people who were normal, not excessively angry, and taught them the
forgiveness method; they got better than normal _ they felt more
spiritually open, more hopeful. That's what fascinates me about
forgiveness; it's so much more than just anger control.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of the blessings forgiveness brings, both Enright and
Luskin caution that it's important to be careful how you try to
forgive. ``For instance, take the abused wife who hears the word
'forgiveness' and thinks she must blindly reconcile with her
abusive spouse. But to forgive and to reconcile are two different
things,'' Enright says. ``Forgiveness comes from an inner decision
on your part; reconciliation involves two parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, people think,'If I forgive someone, I give up my right
to a fair solution, to justice.' That's untrue. You can forgive and
then go about seeking justice. Forgiveness comes from a position of
moral strength, not weakness. It's not excusing or condoning; it's
saying,'What the person did was wrong, but I will act out of a
sense of mercy and an inner wish to forgive.'''
</P>
<P>
   Having finally struggled back onto friendly ground with Sylvia,
I have no intention of re-entering the murky waters of
recrimination anytime soon; but if I ever do, I'll chart my way
back to shore more quickly this time, grateful of my newfound
ability to heal my grudges _ and my health.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   SEVEN STEPS TO FORGIVENESS
</P>
<P>
   _ Participants in the Stanford Forgiveness Project's workshops
are taught the following steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Figure out how you felt during the traumatic moment. ``Think
carefully about it until you know exactly what happened that wasn't
OK for you,'' Frederic Luskin says. ``To clarify this for yourself,
you should discuss it with one or two people (though not
necessarily the person who's wounded you).''
</P>
<P>
   _ Acknowledge that forgiveness is for you. ``It's not to get
back with someone or at him. It doesn't mean you'll ever speak to
him again or guarantee you'll get justice. It's for your own
healing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Begin the process today. ``If a person, thing or event has
hurt you, and you've let that override the other good things in
your life, you need to remind yourself of them. At the moment
you're feeling upset, practice deep breathing _ two or three deep
breaths, inhaling and exhaling slowly _ then let your mind stay on
something beautiful or lovely. If you do this, you can't stay
upset. And over time, it changes how you experience your life.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Change your expectations. ``It sounds a bit harsh, but really,
nobody owes you anything; the good things you get are a gift.
Instead of expecting things to go your way, be appreciative when
they do.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Find your positive intention. ``Learn what it was that you
wished for but didn't get from the person, whether it was love,
friendship, validation or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Find a new way to achieve your positive intention. ``Seek out
another arena in which your wish can be gratified.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Go back and tell your story again. ``Tell it in a way that
reflects your positive intention _ so that it becomes a story of
how you were disappointed or hurt but managed to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   (Diane Guernsey is senior editor of ``Town &AMP; Country''
magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
