<HEADER>
A1028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX     07-24 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: U.S. Star Wars plan is insane by any definition
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The definition of insanity is doing the same thing over and
over and expecting different results.'' This wisdom _ variously
ascribed to Einstein, Unknown, Anonymous and other great thinkers
of our time _ would seem to fit the persistent Star Wars delusion.
</P>
<P>
   The scaled-down version that the Pentagon and a slew of
contractors and their political hangers-on are pushing recently
failed its third test, the one ballyhooed as the most telling.
That's three out of three, and for this one the Pentagon gave
itself months of careful run-up and even delayed the deal another
two hours at the last minute just to fiddle a little more, luxuries
unknown in combat.
</P>
<P>
   Any enemy lobbing nukes at us is unlikely to ready an attack,
then stand down until our Star Warriors signal they are ready to
intercept the incoming.
</P>
<P>
   Most flops this famous and costly are abandoned. Just try to buy
a Tucker automobile.
</P>
<P>
   This is a relatively modest technology compared to Prsident
Reagn's original all-encompassing fantasy. Its repeated failure
would hardly seem a firm basis for spending incalculable billions
more on a limited anti-missile shield of dubious efficacy even if
it more or less works, for abandoning nearly 30 years of successful
nuclear deterrent policy and for risking the creation of a renewed
nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
   But wait!
</P>
<P>
   Military and industry experts are forming up to chant, get this,
that the tests don't matter after all. What did you expect of a
new, fussy system? Success? The fact that the technology hasn't
worked so far is no proof that it won't eventually work, they say.
</P>
<P>
   This is true, and the fact the Sharon Stone hasn't called me for
a date doesn't mean they she won't ever, but I'm not making
reservations on the Costa del Sol just in case.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is brooding his way toward a decision about
whether to build a famcy radar system in the Aleutians, essential
if some 100 interceptors are to be deployed by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   This would have two great defensive purposes. It would defend Al
Gore from GOP charges that he is part of an administration that is
soft on Star Wars and it just might defend the crucial 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty from the rash impulse of President
George W. Bush, should it come to that, to scrap it outright.
</P>
<P>
   But even Clinton's more restrained option would undermine the
ABM treaty, elbowing Russia, China and other potentially nuclear
nations that mean us no good toward revving up missile production,
multiple warheading, decoy development and other tricks for
flummoxing the new U.S. defense.
</P>
<P>
   We have a technology here that we haven't proved. The nation
most cited as justifying its deployment even so, North Korea, has
said it would give up its long-range missile program in exchange
for technology help from others' programs. And we have a president
tempted to press on mainly for domestic political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   What do you suppose Einstein, Unknown and Anonymous would call
that?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
