<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-PORK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL MANNA FALLS ON CAMPUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colleges received more than $1 billion this year in
congressional earmarks for so-called pork-barrel projects, ranging
from studies of cranberries and forests to research on the best
ways to debone salmon, a survey has found.
</P>
<P>
   Such gifts to academe exceeded $1 billion for the first time,
according to the study, released this week by the Chronicle of
Higher Education, a weekly newspaper. The grants amounted to 31
percent more than last year.
</P>
<P>
   These funds are mostly research and construction grants that are
not reviewed by peers or awarded by competition, but rather
inserted into congressional budget bills at the urging of
politicians or college officials.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts institutions took in $49 million, up from $30
million last year. Among the earmarks were a $3 million Harvard
study of public housing and $3.4 million to Tufts University and
other campuses for shrimp research.
</P>
<P>
   Federal spending observers said the continued earmarking was
attributable to politicians' glee over the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these projects go to schools that simply can't manage
them,'' said James D. Savage, a government professor at the
University of Virginia and author of the book, ``Funding Science in
America.'' ``There's no accountability, and we don't know how the
money is being spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts ranked ninth this year, with $26 million in grants
for state schools and $23 million shared by campuses in
Massachusetts and elsewhere. Massachusetts also ranked 9th last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Many colleges, including Harvard, deny that they try to get such
grants. Others say earmarks help develop their research capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Casey, Harvard's senior director of federal and state
relations, said he could not explain why the university had been
listed with three grants totaling $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest, according to the Chronicle, was for Harvard and a
federal research center to conduct a $10 million study on disease
treatments that are least invasive for patients. Casey said the
money might be going to a teaching hospital affiliated with
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   California, with about $83 million in academic grants, led the
nation. The top recipient was Loma Linda University, a private
campus in California with a well-connected congressman,
Representative Jerry Lewis. Loma Linda received $36 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other colleges that received the 25 biggest grants,
Dartmouth College ranked eighth with $15 million to establish the
Institute for Security Technology Studies, which researches
cyberterrorism and has developed encryption technology.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth's provost, Susan Prager, said the school had worked
with Senator Judd Gregg of New Hampshire to land the money. She
said that many institutions receive earmarks, and that
peer-reviewed sources would have been more difficult with the
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other New England states, New Hampshire ranked 11th with
about $23 million in campus-specific earmarks; Connecticut was 25th
with $8.5 million; Vermont was 40th with $4.3 million; Rhode Island
was 43rd with $3 million; and Maine was 47th with $520,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
