<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURING FOX: MEXICAN HEADED AWAY FROM ELITISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In the three weeks since his historic election as
president, Vicente Fox Quesada has pledged to eliminate widespread
government corruption, increase global trade, reduce the nation's
chronic poverty, and end a six-year-old stalemate with rebellious
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But what the country's most eligible man hasn't done yet is
declare who will be his first lady. There are lots of contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's 20-year-old daughter, Ana Cristina, has said she would
gladly take on the duties of official hostess while finishing her
law studies. But there are rumors swirling in Mexico City _ which
his daughter has tried to quash _ that Fox might marry his press
secretary and confidante, Martha Sahagun. There have even been
stories linking Fox with Lucia Mendez, a popular singer and soap
opera actress.
</P>
<P>
   And there's another candidate: his former wife. In recent weeks,
Liliana de la Concha has been quoted in interviews as saying she
would like to get back together with Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The who-will-be-first-lady chatter is just part of what will
make Mexico's new first family one of the most untraditional in
modern history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not one of your typical families from power, and they
don't belong to the elite,'' said Luis Miguel Rionda, a political
scientist at the University of Guanajuato, Fox's home state. ``This
could change the very nature of how we define ruling families.''
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old president-elect divorced seven years ago, and _
in a first for a Mexican leader _ was elected despite running as a
bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   Also new for a Mexican president is that all four of Fox's
children are adopted. And Fox, a member of the conservative
National Action Party, is an openly practicing Catholic, something
Mexicans haven't often seen since the country's 19th-century
reformist constitution that largely excluded government ties to the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's stunning victory on July 2 ended 71 years of uninterrupted
power by the Institutional Revolutionary Party, also known as the
PRI. For decades, the governing party has been identified more with
Mexico's elite families, which produced most of the country's top
political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But the new first family, which will take over the Los Pinos
presidential residence when Fox is inaugurated on Dec. 1, will be a
dramatic break from the tightly wound network of PRI families, less
oligarchical and more reflective of real Mexican families,
observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox and his family are different from the structures that have
typically produced political leadership, like the military,
lawyers, or technocrats,'' said Jose Antonio Crespo, a political
analyst who has written on presidential affairs in Mexico. ``Fox
comes from a small business and rancher background that more people
can identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most visible early signs of the new first family may
be Ana Cristina, who remained at her father's side throughout the
campaign and now sees herself as someone who could influence
everything from youth and women's issues in the incoming government
to the decor at Los Pinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have themes of conversation with anyone, whether a
street kid, an indigenous person, a married woman, a young person,
king, or president,'' she told the Reuters news agency last week.
</P>
<P>
   When word spread soon after Fox's election that he might marry
Sahagun, his 47-year-old divorced aide, who hasn't publicly denied
the reports, Ana Cristina quickly dispelled those suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately right now it's impossible to tell who is after
Vicente the human being or who wants him because he is Vicente Fox
the president,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Adoption advocates in Mexico are also hoping that the Fox first
family will help shed a more accurate and positive light on the
relationship between adopted children and their parents in a
country where almost one-third of all adoptions last year were by
foreign couples. Some adoption experts say an antiadoption stigma
still shrouds the country; some schools still refuse to admit
adopted children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the new president will be more sensitive to
adoption issues,'' said Aurora Torres, director of Nueva Vida, a
Mexico City association of adoptive parents. ``And we'll be
counting on him to help improve the image and to help streamline
our adoption processes.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Beatriz Avila is glad to see a prominent political
family that more closely resembles her own. Avila, a 27-year-old
bank teller in the Mexico City neighborhood of Coyoacan, and her
husband have considered adopting a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel better about my own situation to see that
we're not that different from our country's top family,'' said
Avila, who voted for Fox. ``I use to feel like my family was so
different from the old elite families of the PRI, but now I can
better identify with Fox and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is concern among some residents and analysts about how
Fox's personal life might influence his public policies, it is
mostly around his devout Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   Fox attended Mass last Sunday with his family in his hometown
and received Communion as cameras flashed. Afterward, he called for
a ``spiritual revolution'' in Mexico, ``where everybody has the
opportunity to be happy, live better, and in less pain.'' It was
the first time most Mexicans could remember seeing a
president-to-be making such a public religious display.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue which will generate controversy,'' Crespo said.
``There may be more flexibility toward the church under a Fox
government, but he'll be cautious and tolerant of other ideas and
faiths, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most pressing personal issue these days continues to be
his love life and whether the president-elect might have a romantic
honeymoon to go along with the political one he's enjoying now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he gets married soon, especially if it's with someone
he feels comfortable with,'' said Rionda, the political scientist
in Fox's home state, adding that he'd like to see Fox marry his
aide. ``There's nothing better than a man in love who's in
government. I think it makes him a better leader.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
