u f BC-MONEY-STOCK-OPTIONS-B     07-24 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-STOCK-OPTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES HELP OPTION HOLDERS LEARN HOW TO USE THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With employees at everything from Internet start-ups to
blue-chip firms wanting stock options these days _ or at least on
the days the market's going up _ it was only a matter of time
before Web sites emerged to target this audience.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Brookline-based company launched
myStockOptions.com, a comprehensive site promising to help the up
to 10 million Americans with stock options figure out complicated
tax questions and maximize their options.
</P>
<P>
   In the few weeks since it became available publicly, the site
has gotten more than a million hits, said Bruce Brumberg, chief
executive of the company and owner of a legal and financial
publishing company. And private tests of the site by option holders
at more than 40 companies, including Staples, eToys, and Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, have also been successful, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has been tremendous,'' said Brumberg, an
attorney, who cofounded the site with Jesse Brill and Peter Van
Ness. ``We have deep original content, online tools, online
record-keeping, and community features . . . and it's free.''
</P>
<P>
   The site joins other Internet destinations reaching out to
``optionaires'' _ people who are rich, or hoping to get rich, off
their stock options. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   www.StockOptionsCentral.com, www.optionwealth.com,
www.Stock-Options.com, and www.MyOptionValue.com.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the proliferation of sites is a response to the
democratization of stock options.
</P>
<P>
   No longer are the options just for highly compensated
executives, and no longer are they just available at Internet
start-ups. Secretaries and other rank-and-file employees are being
offered them, and large publicly traded companies that make
something as old-economy as dental floss are granting them.
</P>
<P>
   As of this year, according to the National Center for Employee
Ownership, there are 3,000 plans nationwide that grant stock
options to 50 percent or more of full-time employees, with a total
of 7 million to 10 million participants. The plan assets amount to
at least several hundred billion dollars, according to the
California-based nonprofit organization, which outlines the data on
its Web site, www.nceo.org.
</P>
<P>
   Stock option plans differ legally from employee stock purchase
plans (or ESPPs) and employee stock ownership plans (or ESOPs), and
involve an employer granting stock to employees with a certain
vesting schedule and exercise price. Figuring out whether to
exercise an option and what the tax consequences are can be
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a review of some of the sites that want to help you
maximize your options:
</P>
<P>
   --www.myStockOptions.com: This features the most inviting home
page of the sites reviewed, with plenty on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Want to know what it means when your stock options are
``underwater''? You'll find the answer in the glossary of terms. Is
it better to get nonqualified stock options or incentive stock
options? The answer is in the ``frequently asked questions,'' or
FAQs. And if there's a question that isn't answered on the site,
you can e-mail an expert.
</P>
<P>
   There are sections on the nuts-and-bolts of options, taxation,
and vesting, as well as on the very human emotions of greed and
envy and the implications of divorce for option holders.
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of online tools here to help you calculate
how much in taxes you'd pay if you exercised now; how many shares
to exercise if you need a certain amount of cash; and whether you
should sell, hold or look at other investments.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the features are available for anyone visiting the
site, some require registering for free membership. There are no
ads on the site. Brumberg said the company is exploring such
possible revenue sources as licensing of the technology and private
labeling of the site with financial service firms.
</P>
<P>
   --www.MyOptionValue.com: Promising to help you ``know your
options,'' this site aims to help employees who are getting stock
options for the first time learn how to get the most value without
having to hire lawyers and accountants.
</P>
<P>
   A regular annual subscription of $29.95 to this site lets you
estimate the value of your options based on exercise date,
expiration date, whether they're vested or unvested. It also lets
you create what-if scenarios, and figure out what a prospective
employer's options might be worth to you if you were to switch
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   During a limited introductory period, the site is providing the
first three months of membership for free, then charging $29.95 for
the next 12 months. Visitors to this site can also tap into a
demonstration without cost.
</P>
<P>
   The site, a registered investment adviser, also provides links
to articles, books, and other resources about options.
</P>
<P>
   --www.StockOptionsCentral.com: A free site that promises to
``keep it simple, accurate, and thorough, while answering your
thoughts, dreams, and `what-ifs' about your company stock
options,'' this lets you track value and tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   There's some original content and links to a few outside
articles and books about stock options, but the site says it
purposely doesn't have ``complicated razzle-dazzle.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though the site is free, it does want to sell you
something.
</P>
<P>
   According to the site's ``media kit'' for advertisers, people
who use the site and exercise their options ``must find a home for
the proceeds. If you're a mutual fund company, an e-broker, a
brokerage house, a bank, or any other financial institution, you
will want to be in front of these folks the entire time they are
running their what-ifs and contemplating changing the location of
their money.''
</P>
<P>
   --www.Stock-Options.com: A free service of New Jersey-based
financial and investment firm Krieger, Ruderman &AMP; Co., this site
provides a stock options calculator and a way to keep track of your
stock splits, vesting schedule and other records. Just press the
``show me the money'' key to save the data and see calculated
totals for your options.
</P>
<P>
   A guest registration lets you take a tour of what the site
offers before you decide whether to take the time to enter your
options data here. The site also provides a discussion forum and
links to outside articles about options.
</P>
<P>
   But again, the site wants to sell you something. ``Who will
exercise and sell the stock for you? Online forms are provided for
opening an account with KR Securities, LLC,'' according to the
site.
</P>
<P>
   --www.optionwealth.com: This site promises to provide real-time
values for people's stock options, so employees don't waste time
trying to figure out their wealth at work, and employers don't see
company productivity decline as a result.
</P>
<P>
   But the site's real-time tracker, options value forecaster, and
strategy section haven't come online yet. They were to have gone
live in June, according a check of the site on July 14. As of this
Monday, however, the site was updated to say the launch will happen
on Sept. 7, 6:30 p.m., in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not easy figuring out whether the site will be free or
not when it's fully operational. In a paragraph found in a part of
the site featuring press clippings about the company and its chief
executive, Rick Schultz, the revenue model is described this way:
``The core business of OptionWealth is the sale of subscription
account services to employers for use by their optioned employees.
Corporate customers will have secure, private access to
www.optionwealth.com. Private portfolio accounts with password
protection will be established for each optioned employee with the
client company.''
</P>
<P>
   --www.fairmark.com: This online tax guide for investors just
came out with a new book, ``Consider Your Options: Get the Most
From Your Equity Compensation,'' which you can buy here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
