<HEADLINE>
A SLOWER FAST LANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, is the economy slowing down, or what? And should we care?
</P>
<P>
   Just about every day some economic seer makes a pronouncement
about the numbers inching up, or inching down, or sitting there
doing nothing. It's as if the entire business world were hanging on
this thing, Hamlet-like, pondering what is to be, or not, on the
slowness front.
</P>
<P>
   The average American isn't sure what side to root for. Slower is
good, says Alan Greenspan, as long as it's not too slow, because
that keeps inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   But if slower is good, how come it always sounds bad? ``Job
growth sluggish,'' say the headlines, or ``Retail sales
disappointing.'' A responsible citizen sees that kind of negativity
and wants to get out there and take one for the team _ buy a
washing machine or something, maybe come up with a couple of new
job titles, or start a department to keep the economy standing
tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sluggish'' or ``disappointing'' is not where we want to be
after things have been so hot, hip, and fast for so long, which
really sounds good and as though we all got A's on the econ exam,
even though too much heat is supposed to be bad.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to get revved up about leaving a party, which may or
may not be over. What if the kitchen has simply run out of hot hors
d'oeuvres, and the caterers have ordered more? How is a person
supposed to figure out what's going on, not to mention what to
wear, in a constant buzz of contradiction?
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the economy is still growing,'' Ken
Goldstein, economist for the Conference Board, told the financial
press this month after announcing that his organization's index of
leading economic indicators dipped 0.1 percent in May. ``It's not
as fast as it was, but it's still growing. Yes it's losing steam,
but it had to lose steam.''
</P>
<P>
   So, there's a slowdown but we won't feel a thing, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start looking at the individual components, there's a
sort of musical chairs aspect to it,'' Goldstein told The Wall
Street Journal. ``What the report doesn't show is weakness in a
particular area that's starting to fester and grow and ooze out
into other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   So, there's a slowdown, and it's going to get ugly?
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying strength in the economy is good,'' Cary Leahey,
US economist at Deutsche Securities, told the Journal. ``It's not
great, but it's good.''
</P>
<P>
   How good is ``good''? And if it's competing with ``great,''
could it feel more like bad?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the interesting possibilities we have to face is that
slowing down could still be too fast,'' William Dunkelberg, chief
economist for the National Federation of Independent Business, told
The Boston Globe, commenting on June's piddling job growth.
</P>
<P>
   If a slowdown can pass for speed, does it count?
</P>
<P>
   And what of the Federal Reserve's ``beige book''? That's the one
that takes the economic pulse of 12 regions in the country. In
June, the data showed that things were cooling off a bit _ except
in Minneapolis, where things were still sizzling.
</P>
<P>
   Makes a person want to get on a plane and join the party animals
in Minnesota _ bring the whole wild bunch back East again, shouting
``ToGA! ToGA!''
</P>
<P>
   But would that be redundant if the party is still going strong
here, even though it seems as though people are heading for their
cars?
</P>
<P>
   Only the Fed knows for sure _ unless it doesn't. We follow the
endless ``Will he or won't he?'' speculation about Greenspan
raising interest rates, waiting for him to ``send a signal'' as
they say on the Street _ and the Street is Wall, not Main. Speaking
to the Senate Banking Committee last week, , he said, basically,
``Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   We watch the people who watch the Fed, and the exercise is
reminiscent of the way we used to wait for the geopolitical
crystal-gazers to interpret what was going on inside the Kremlin
during the Cold War. Did the premier have a cold? How bad was his
congestion? Who was standing where at Lenin's tomb during the
full-dress parades? More importantly, who was not standing there?
</P>
<P>
   Is the economy slowing down? Yes and no, unless it's just on
vacation, which is OK, since a lot of us could use one, especially
if we're in the economic analysis business. Take a break, people _
you're overheating!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
