<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING WRONG WITH PREFERRED, IF YOU DO YOUR HOMEWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 37 and work 40 hours a week. I recently bought 100
shares of a Chase Manhattan Preferred stock paying 10.96 percent. I
would like to know the risks of preferred stock and why I should
not build a portfolio of well-known corporations' preferreds for
income.
</P>
<P>
   W.H., Portland, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The risks aren't terribly high, but even though you have held
this security only for about six weeks, some of them are probably
already apparent.
</P>
<P>
   First, preferred stocks tend to follow the bond market more than
the stock market _ rising in value when interest rates fall (or
when investors anticipate they will) and falling in value as a
climate of lower interest rates comes on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   You bought your shares at a total cost of $2,609.50 The current
market value is $2,393.75, and of course you would pay a broker's
commission if you sold them. The shares have a stated yield of
10.96 percent, but the price you paid gives you an actual yield of
10.5 percent. The downside can be viewed more dramatically. The
shares traded at a high of more than $33 in the early '90s; a
person who paid $33 a share is getting a yield of only 8.3 percent
_ with a substantial capital loss, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The second disadvantage _ something you should have checked out
before you purchased the shares _ is they can be ``called.'' That
means Chase Manhattan may redeem them for $25 a share anytime after
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   To answer your broader question, there's nothing wrong with
building a portfolio of preferred stocks. Yields are higher than
with bonds, largely because preferreds have a lower standing than
bonds: Bondholders must be paid before owners of preferred can be
paid, and preferred dividends must be paid before a common stock
dividend can be paid. Most preferreds these days, including yours,
are called cumulative preferreds, which means that if the dividend
on a preferred issue is skipped, the arrears must be repaid before
any common stock dividend can be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with solid institutions such as you contemplate
investing in, those factors are not likely to give you much pause.
More important is to view the interest-rate climate carefully, and
to make sure that if you pay a premium to the call value of your
shares, the call date is pretty far in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Before building a portfolio, you also should differentiate
between convertible preferreds and other preferred issues.
Convertible preferred stock can be exchanged for common stock at a
predetermined exchange rate, at the owner's option. Thus, when the
value of the common stock reaches a level at which it seems that
conversion is soon likely to be profitable _ either because of the
stock price of the common or because the common stock obtained
through conversion has a higher yield than the preferred offers _
those preferred shares will tend to follow the stock market (and
particularly the shares of the issuer's common stock) rather than
the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there's nothing at all wrong with preferreds, but you
need to do the homework to know the precise terms that relate to
them. And remember that when an issue can profitably be called by
the issuer, it invariably will be. Your issue of Chase Manhattan
10.96 percent preferred is one of its most expensive securities
(from Chase's point of view), and my guess is that this will not be
a long-term holding for you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are buying a house for $160,000, with
anticipated occupancy Nov. 1. We plan to start a family soon. The
financing options include taking a mortgage for $130,000 with
interest payments only due during the first five years, and then
with higher payments that would amortize the loan balance over the
remaining 25 years. An alternative is a $100,000 traditional
30-year mortgage, which would entail a bigger down payment and
liquidation of more of our savings. We are able to afford monthly
payments of $1,050 for all costs, including taxes and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   P.A., Worcester, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems that the last sentence would more or less dictate
that you go with the traditional mortgage. Suppose the interest
rate on both means of financing is the same _ 8.13 percent, the
national average for a 30-year mortgage at the beginning of last
week. The cost of the $130,000 interest-only mortgage would be $880
a month. Add in taxes and insurance, and the chances are strong you
would exceed $1,050 a month, the maximum you have budgeted.
Moreover, after five years, your payment would rise to $1,014 a
month. With a deal like that to look forward to, five years can
elapse very fast. Moreover, with your plan of starting a family
fairly soon, it seems likely the hike in housing costs might come
at a time when you can ill afford it.
</P>
<P>
   At 8.13 percent, though, a traditional 30-year mortgage would
entail a payment of $742 a month, probably leaving you with enough
for taxes and insurance to stay within your budget. You would have
to sell more of your securities, but your overall family budget
would be more comfortable. And finally, short-term prospects for a
value-oriented stock portfolio aren't all that bright, so you may
not be giving up all that much upside potential if you sold now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We have decided to invest $50,000 as soon as possible for our
son's education. Will that be enough of an initial investment,
given the time we have until he enters college, and are our funds
and allocations appropriate?
</P>
<P>
   D.G., Sutton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You should be in great shape. Since you didn't specify when
the additional $22,500 of investments will be made, I simply ran a
projection over 17 years, presuming that you began with $50,000. If
you achieve 10 percent average annual portfolio growth, you would
amass $271,743. (The longer you delay the additional $22,500
investment, the smaller the accumulation will be.)
</P>
<P>
   A more conservative scenario: If you achieve 10 percent
portfolio returns for 12 years, then adjust the portfolio with more
conservative allocations _ reducing returns to 8 percent for five
years _ you would have $246,071.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it should be plenty.
</P>
<P>
   The editors of the 2000 edition of ``Paying for College Without
Going Broke'' are projecting 5 percent annual inflation in college
costs. Their figures run only to 2014, but I continued the
projection, coming up with a cost for a private four-year college
education in 2017 of $51,244 _ escalating to $59,321 by 2021.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year total would be $220,867. If your son were to go to
a public school, you are saving much too much. The cost for a
public institution would be $19,637 in 2017 and escalate to $22,733
by 2021; the four-year total would be $84,639.
</P>
<P>
   As for your investments, I'd suggest a little more
diversification. Funds concentrated in one market sector represent
duplication, not diversification. All your funds are solid, but
focus on large-cap stocks, although Pimco Innovation specializes in
technology issues. Munder Index 500 is a blend of growth and value
stocks; your other three funds all operate in the large-cap growth
arena. My suggestion: Limit the Index fund investment to $5,000,
putting a similar amount each in mid-cap, small-cap, and
international funds. I know large-cap growth funds have been the
stars of the last few years, but the worm eventually will turn, and
17 years is a long time. A more broadly diversified portfolio
should serve you better in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
