<HEADLINE>
TELECOM COMPANIES TAKING OLD-FASHIONED APPROACH TO SALES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best way to sell today's most advanced telecommunications
services turns out to be the most old-fashioned way: face to face
and door to door.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Broadband and RCN Corp. are both discovering that
one-on-one meetings with customers are the most effective way to
sell packages of high-speed Internet access, cable TV, and local
and long-distance phone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best way to do it,'' said Daniel E. Somers, chief
executive of AT&AMP;T Broadband, the nation's largest cable TV company.
</P>
<P>
   While AT&AMP;T's one-on-one sales approach is just one aspect of a
marketing plan that includes direct mail, telemarketing, and other
promotions, RCN is relying almost exclusively on its team of sales
representatives who make house calls. In fact, it's almost
impossible for a would-be RCN customer to sign up for a service or
even find out what a service costs without meeting with a sales
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Movsessian of Lexington said a friend had convinced him to
give RCN a try, but when he called the company to place an order
for cable TV and high-speed Internet access he was told he would
have to meet with a sales representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of skeptical,'' Movsessian said. ``I don't have a
lot of time and I wasn't hot about having a salesman come to my
house. But it actually turned out fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The RCN sales rep showed up on time and spent a half hour going
over all the options. Movsessian ended up buying a package that
included not only cable TV and high-speed Internet access, but also
local phone service. He estimates RCN is saving him about $50 to
$60 a month over his previous providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the usual type of service you get nowadays,''
Movsessian said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Adams, RCN's president, said one-on-one meetings result
in a sale more than 70 percent of the time. And since RCN's sales
representatives are pushing packages that bundle a variety of
services together, customers usually end up buying more than one
service. Adams said the average customer buys 3.4 services,
dramatically reducing the cost per sales call.
</P>
<P>
   RCN sales reps typically work from 11 a.m. to 8:30 p.m. They
dress casually, usually a red RCN golf shirt and a pair of shorts.
They carry an RCN briefcase, a cell phone, and a device that works
as a pager and can receive e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   The typical sales rep focuses on 100 potential customers every
two weeks. The customers first get a mailing from RCN talking about
the company's offerings, which is followed up by a letter from the
sales rep seeking to arrange a meeting. Customers who don't make
appointments are called on individually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction right now is very positive,'' said John McGeough,
RCN's senior director of sales, who often pounds the pavement
himself. ``Customers enjoy it and they feel it's a little more
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   RCN started offering bundled packages nine months ago in
Waltham. The bundles go by metal names (bronze, silver, gold, and
platinum) and offer significant savings over buying a la carte. The
$139-a-month deluxe platinum package, for example, would cost $233
a month on an a la carte basis.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is headed in the same direction, but its bundles don't have
catchy names yet and they don't always offer you as much for your
money.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's TV-telephony package, for example, costs $66 for nearly
100 digital video channels, 45 music channels, and one phone line
with 15 special calling features. The phone line lets you make
unlimited calls in your hometown and all contiguous towns.
</P>
<P>
   RCN's silver bundle charges $4 more for nearly as many analog
video channels and seven premium movie channels for which AT&AMP;T
charges extra. The silver package also has 31 music channels and a
phone line with two special calling features. The line lets you
make unlimited calls in all four Eastern Massachusetts area codes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being an effective sales technique, RCN's
one-on-one approach also puts a face on a company that most
consumers aren't familiar with. RCN is trying to simultaneously
build a new fiber-optic network and sell service to customers as
parts of that network are completed.
</P>
<P>
   The company has had customer-service problems in the past, but
it seems to be bringing those under control. Adams said RCN has
hired an outside polling firm to develop a customer-satisfaction
index. He said employee compensation will be tied to the rise and
fall of that index.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Adamik, chief operating officer of the Yankee Group in
Boston, said he's been impressed with RCN on both a personal and
professional level. A Lexington, Mass. resident, Adamik signed up
last week for RCN's platinum package. He said RCN's sales approach
seems to be working, since most of his neighbors signed up as well.
</P>
<P>
   Adamik also likes the way the company has rapidly increased
staffing across all areas of its business, including customer
service. ``It's looking like a good news story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Stella of Framingham, Mass., who signed up for RCN's
silver package, is also pleased. ``I was surprised they wanted to
come to my house, but I kind of liked it,'' she said. ``It's a
little easier to ask questions and all the information is right in
front of you in black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean she was happy with everything. She was
promised a $20 rebate for signing up that week and another $20 for
every customer she referred. When the rebates didn't show up on her
bill, she called RCN customer service. Representatives there, who
operate out of Pennsylvania, said they hadn't heard about the
rebate but eventually credited her the money because other
customers had complained.
</P>
<P>
   She said she called the customer service rep who came to her
house looking for help on the rebate problem, but she never heard
back from him. ``After the sale, it's like forget it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Citibank protection _ or gouging?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Citibank is offering its 40 million customers a service that
protects them when they temporarily lose their income, but one
customer who received the solicitation sarcastically says
protection is not the word he would use to describe it.
</P>
<P>
   The service, called credit protector, basically lets the
customer put their Citibank credit card account on hold if they
lose their job through no fault of their own, are hospitalized,
take unpaid family leave, or can't work because of a disabling
illness or injury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1090 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR;      07-24 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... or injury.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under those circumstances, customers can freeze their account.
They can't add any more charges, but they don't have to make any
payments, no interest or late payments accrue, and their credit
rating is unaffected. The freeze can last up to two years, or three
months in the case of unpaid family leave.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch letter said credit protector costs 69 cents per $100
of average daily balance each month the customer has a balance,
which doesn't sound like much. But the consumer who contacted me,
who asked that his name not be used, said it's actually quite a bit
when you think about it.
</P>
<P>
   His card comes with a 19.4 percent interest rate. He calculated
the 69-cent cost bumps that rate up to 27.68 percent. ``The
customer is getting screwed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Mindler, a spokeswoman for Citibank, said the bank doesn't
see it that way. ``It's an optional feature that we believe brings
high value to cardmembers, especially when they need help the
most,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mindler noted the maximum monthly fee for credit protector is
capped at $24.50, which works out to a $3,500 balance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
