<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-EUROPE-EXECUTIONS-BOS     07-24 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-EXECUTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIS MAN MUST NOT DIE.' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ On the plate glass window of a building on Rue La
Fayette, a 3-by-4-foot poster shows the dreadlocked face of Mumia
Abu Jamal, a former Black Panther and radical journalist now on
Pennsylvania's death row, convicted of killing a policeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice pour Mumia Abu Jamal'' the poster pleads, describing
him as a journalist and declaring that international opinion is
squarely against his execution.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal's face is plastered on walls across Europe, from Dublin to
Rome. It is probable that more Europeans than Americans know about
his case.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, executions have become so common that most
are not even mentioned in newspapers. But in Europe, the fate of
prisoners on America's death rows is followed closely.
</P>
<P>
   The execution in Texas last month of convicted murderer Gary
Graham, on the uncorroborated word of a single witness whose
account was challenged by others, was just the latest to capture
widespread attention and cause deep anger across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans see themselves in the vanguard of trying to persuade
countries to ban the death penalty. Many ordinary people can tell
you that only China, Saudi Arabia, Iran, and the Congo execute more
people than the United States, which in 1999 executed 98 people.
</P>
<P>
   Most Europeans are Roman Catholic, and their church is at the
forefront of calls to end the death penalty. But religious
conviction is hardly at the root of the vehement, visceral
opposition of many ordinary people. Having survived two world wars
in one century, many Europeans see the death penalty as barbaric,
the earmark of a brutal, less enlightened society _ and one more
example of how Europe is morally superior to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Executing people, they believe, is an unfortunate reflection of
America's two-tiered society where the gap between rich and poor is
the greatest in the world, and where the poor and minorities
receive the death penalty far more often than those who are rich or
white.
</P>
<P>
   But others who are not at all motivated by anti-Americanism say
they want to use their influence to persuade their American friends
that the death penalty is an insult to America's position as the
world's only remaining superpower.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a boat that doubles as a cafe on the Seine, Marc
LePlante, 40, an engineer, said America needs to consider its
position if it wants to continue to act as world leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hypocrisy for the United States to tell (Yugoslav
President Slobodan) Milosevic that he is a murderer but allow the
state to act as an executioner,'' said LePlante. ``It is just not
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans' embrace of the death penalty allows some Europeans to
deflect attention from their own moral shortcomings. When the
far-right Freedom Party became part of the coalition government in
Austria, the 14 other members of the European Union slapped
diplomatic sanctions on Austria to show their disgust at the
party's anti-immigrant rhetoric. But when the party leader Joerg
Haider sat down for an interview with The Boston Globe in February,
he turned aside questions about past statements praising Nazis by
saying, ``I am not a monster. Unlike your president, I have not
executed anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider's remark was not just the riposte of an embattled
politician. The decision by Bill Clinton, then the governor of
Arkansas, to interrupt his 1992 presidential campaign to preside
over the execution of Ricky Ray Rector, a black man convicted of
killing a police officer, is regularly cited by Europeans. Before
his capture, Rector had shot himself in the head, leaving him
mentally incapacitated; as he was being led to his execution, he
asked his jailers to leave the pie from his last meal to the side
so he could have it later.
</P>
<P>
   That Clinton would allow the execution of a brain-damaged man,
and do so for what Europeans believe was simply to prove that
Democrats weren't soft on crime, is seen by many Europeans as
disgraceful.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has put its money where its mouth is. One
condition of entry to the 15-nation union is that applicants must
outlaw capital punishment. Turkey, which desperately wants to gain
membership, would like nothing better than to execute the Kurdish
rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan. But its application to join the EU
would be put aside, if not thrown out forever, were he to be
executed.
</P>
<P>
   More far-reaching is the EU's proposed bill of rights, one
section of which would bar EU members from extraditing suspects to
countries that have capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   American diplomats say they are frequently confronted by
Europeans and asked to justify capital punishment. Felix Rohatyn
and John Kornblum, the US ambassadors to France and Germany
respectively, are constantly asked to explain the situation. The
standard diplomatic response is that it is what a majority of the
American people want in a majority of the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Many Europeans acknowledge that their indignation seems to be
have little impact. German officials were furious when their
attempts to halt the executions of two German-born brothers
convicted of the 1982 murder of an Arizona bank manager were
ignored. Despite appeals for clemency by German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder, Karl LaGrand was executed by lethal injection in
February, and Walter LaGrand went to the gas chamber in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans did more than get mad. They sued the United States
in the World Court, saying the executions violated international
laws and treaties. Justice Minister Herta Daeubler-Gmelin called
the executions barbaric, and said, ``We want to prevent this from
happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1,300-page dossier submitted to the World Court, Germany
argues that the executions violated the 1963 Vienna Convention,
which requires US authorities to tell German-born suspects of their
right to assistance from German consulates in the United States.
Germany contends Arizona prosecutors knew the LaGrands were German
but did not notify German consular officials until 10 years after
their arrest.
</P>
<P>
   While opposition to the death penalty runs right across Europe,
the French, Germans, and Italians are the loudest in their
condemnation. In Rome, whenever a death sentence anywhere is stayed
or commuted, the Colosseum is bathed in golden light.
</P>
<P>
   Frederique Andreani, a writer for Le Point, a French magazine,
said many French are staunch republicans and are reluctant to tell
Americans what to do. ``They realize that the US is a democracy,
and that the majority of Americans want it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the French government rejects that argument and has led the
chorus to ban capital punishment. In 1981, when President Francois
Mitterrand abolished the death penalty, more than half of his
countrymen still wanted capital punishment. Since then, polls show
that support for the death penalty has fallen. Its supporters are
now in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, parliamentarians are no less opposed, but many seem
more resigned to the fact that European outrage means little or
nothing. Roger Godsiff, the member of Parliament who represents
Birmingham, suggests there is a fundamental misunderstanding of the
separation of federal and state power in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Britons, and indeed most Europeans, who oppose capital
punishment will tell you that President Clinton should end this
barbaric practice,'' said Godsiff, a member of the ruling Labor
Party. ``President Clinton can't do anything about it. It's up to
the individual states. But bringing political pressure on
individual states is much more difficult than lobbying a friendly
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Bell, who abandoned his career as a BBC war correspondent
to become an independent parliamentarian, said he regularly gets
letters from constituents demanding that he do something to get the
Americans to end capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them there's nothing we can do,'' said Bell. ``It's a
question of American sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   French politicians are not so retiring. Jack Lang, education
minister and a candidate for mayor of Paris, took his opposition to
the belly of the beast in February, visiting Odell Barnes on death
row in Texas. Barnes, 31, had been convicted of raping, beating,
and shooting a woman. After the meeting, Lang announced that he was
convinced that Barnes was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Lang's impassioned appeal on Barnes's behalf was front-page news
in Paris, France, but not Paris, Texas. When Barnes was executed
two weeks later, he again was front-page news in France, but barely
mentioned in the American press.
</P>
<P>
   Many Europeans believe their pressure will eventually yield
results. They point to the decision in January by Governor George
Ryan of Illinois, a staunch supporter of capital punishment, to
impose an indefinite moratorium on executions after questions were
raised in several cases.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, as Germans contemplated and celebrated the 10th
anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall, Stefan Mueller, a
student who has protested against the death penalty, sat at a bar
in the newly rebuilt Potsdamer Platz, which 60 years ago was
headquarters for the Nazis, the most prolific murderers of the last
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me 10 years ago that the Berlin Wall would be
down, I wouldn't believe you,'' Mueller said. ``I feel the same way
about the death penalty. The world changes. The world moves on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kevin Cullen is chief of the Boston Globe London bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
