<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BROTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIG BROTHER' PLAYER FACES CRITICS AFTER LEAK OF TIE TO BIGOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ The rewards of ``reality TV,'' an
unpredictable and unscripted genre embraced by viewers, have become
apparent this summer to the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, they have been forced to confront the risk of
negative publicity stemming from that very unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives and the producers of ``Big Brother'' were thrust
on the defensive by revelations that a contestant on the reality
program, William Collins, of Philadelphia, had close ties to a
militant leader who has espoused anti-Semitic views. Critics have
also accused the network of exploiting the personal pain of another
``Big Brother'' contestant, Karen Fowler, of Columbus, Ind., who
has openly discussed her unhappy marriage in front of a national TV
audience that includes her four children.
</P>
<P>
   Such issues have renewed doubts, first raised earlier this year
by the debacle surrounding Fox's ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?,'' about whether the networks can adequately
police the reality genre to which they have grown addicted. ``We
are all playing with fire,'' Fox chairman Sandy Grushow said last
week. ``And someone is going to get burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, a 27-year-old youth counselor, was a top aide to Khalid
Abdul Muhammad until he left the latter's organization, the New
Black Panther Party, several months ago. Muhammad has called Jews
``bloodsuckers,'' and last week said ``the white woman is the
devil.'' A CBS background check failed to turn up Collins's
affiliation with Muhammad, and he did not disclose it to producers.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance Sunday before TV critics, Collins, who was
accompanied by ``Big Brother'' executive producer Paul Romer,
claimed that law enforcement officials leaked the story of his ties
to Muhammad because they wanted to undermine ``one who stands up
against police brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he subscribes to anti-Semitic or anti-white views,
Collins replied: ``I consider all people who are evil and
unrighteous and against God my enemy. . . . If white people or Jews
fall in that category, they would know that.'' He added that he
makes ``individual judgments based on your deeds and your
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Romer and Leslie Moonves, president and chief executive
officer of CBS Television, said they were unaware of Collins's past
affiliation with Muhammad until it was reported in the (N.Y.) Daily
News. Moonves said CBS may hire a different firm to do background
checks for the next installment of ``Big Brother.'' As for the
controversial show, Moonves insisted the network has no regrets
about taking a chance with ``experimental'' programming. ``We have
nothing to apologize for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The program features 10 strangers living together in a house
while being monitored by dozens of cameras and microphones. Last
week, Collins became the first contestant to be ejected from the
``Big Brother'' house by a vote of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   He chided the show's producers Sunday for editing decisions that
showed only his ``confrontational, argumentative side.'' However,
he said he believes he was able to kindle a discussion of race
while on the show, helping his housemates (and TV viewers)
``understand the black man, black people, and the reality from
another perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   On the question of Fowler's nationally publicized marital
problems, Moonves said he feels ``bad that the family is going
through a certain amount of anguish,'' but he insisted that CBS is
not responsible for that anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, qualms about the excesses of reality programming
seem to be growing _ even among some of its participants. Sonja
Christopher, a contestant on CBS's ``Survivor,'' in which one
contestant is voted off a remote island every week, said: ``I hope
that this program doesn't teach the young people of America that
the way to win is to be duplicitous. That's a concern of mine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN0725-COX     07-24 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Have a good what?
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I'm trying to pinpoint a pivotal moment in
the decline of the service economy. It's when clerks, waiters, and
counter help started telling you to ``have a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as though they know something you don't and are
being coy. They won't commit to wishing you an entire good day.
``Have a good ... well, one.''
</P>
<P>
   Why this ambiguity? Do they suspect you are likely only to have
a good 10 minutes, aren't at liberty to warn you and don't want to
admit to an exact period of time?
</P>
<P>
   What's this ``one'' bit?
</P>
<P>
   As a reporter, I get uncomfortable when people around me start
getting pointedly vague and fling around the most indefinite of
indefinite pronouns. So maybe this is just my own occupational
sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe everybody else likes the phrase. Maybe most folks are
having a good one and are pleased when someone behind the counter
notices. But I doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard not to notice that customers started being
invited to have a good one at about the time waiters became
``servers,'' introduced themselves by Christian name _ which was
always something like Ashlie with an IE or Bif with one F _ and
started calling you by first name. Coincidence or what?
</P>
<P>
   Or did it start as a protest against having to say, ``have a
nice day,'' an invitation that lost its invitingness by the close
of the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The answer remains a mystery inside an enigma.
</P>
<P>
   People who are very close can handle this level of ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard couples speak cheerily in a steady stream of
indefinite pronouns unintelligible to anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you get me the thingy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing in the place?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. The thing by the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the stuff in the place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the big stuff in back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it. What about the other thingy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples such as this are using something that sounds a little
like language but they actually are communicating entirely though
mental telepathy.
</P>
<P>
   Someday will we evolve beyond this and just beam thoughts at
each other as the mutant X-Men do. For now, however, it's behavior
entirely too cuddly for an outsider to need to witness.
</P>
<P>
   I would suggest telling them to have a good one and excusing
oneself.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Good one?' What did he mean by that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dunno, I thought he said, 'cold one.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny, just like that person out at that place we went to.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what bothers me about being told to have ``a good
one.'' You should only be that vague with someone to whom you are
reasonably close. Otherwise _ to meet ambiguity with ambiguity _
who would get where you're coming from?
</P>
<P>
   Cheerful servers who ask you for your first name, inquire as to
what you do and introduce themselves by name, always tell you to
have a good one. As though you have somehow bonded and would know
exactly what they mean. It is part of the whole over-familiar act.
</P>
<P>
   I resent this particularly when I am not having a good one. By
which, I mean a half-decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   But lest you think I'm just being grouchy and oversensitive to
the widespread use of this vague valedictory, know that it has
gained an acronym in Internet messages _ HAGO. Yes, people use it
enough to recognize it by its initials alone. It has me LOL,
laughing out loud, but not in a pleasant way that you'd wish to
listen to.
</P>
<P>
   Any phrase that has an understood Internet acronym is beyond
complaining about. HAGO is here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope it does not have a lengthy one.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
