<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exercising the body while warping the mind
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Physical exertion has never been high on my
list of priorities. Inertia is my favored motion. I never stand
when I could be sitting, and lying down is even better. That's why,
when late last summer some unknown force urged me to put down the
book, roll my rope-plaid backside out of the Pawley's Island
hammock and get it to a gym, no one was more surprised than I was.
</P>
<P>
   I still can't believe it, but it's a fact _ four or five days a
week I hit the treadmill for a quick three-miler, and then go out
and embarrass myself for half-an-hour on the weight machines. My
form may not be the greatest, but the exercise is getting the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   Quite by accident the other day, I discovered that my kneecaps
are back where I remembered them being before gravity did me a
dirty trick. Even my fanny muscles have tightened up to where I
almost bounce when I sit. The trainers promise that before the
first snow flies, I will have rediscovered my waistline.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is the television set in the cardio-vascular
workout room _ it's always on and it's always trash _ and since
everyone else seems to be getting into the action, I can't very
well stomp over and turn it off. Could be that was my inspiration
to break the 15-minute mile and get the heck out of there.
</P>
<P>
   This week we've been watching the Jerry Springer Show. You've
seen that one, right? The one where Mama comes out and starts
hollering at everyone, calling folks nasty names because her
boyfriend has run off with his parole officer and baby daughter has
been picked up for soliciting at the local truck stop.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Springer, I've noticed, always looks real surprised when the
free-for-all begins, even though he's got a couple of guys the size
of my old Bronco, with biceps bigger than their cumulative IQs, to
step in and break it up before anybody starts yelling LAWSUIT!.
</P>
<P>
   A few months back, I discovered books on tape. That helps, but
there are times when even Anne Rivers Siddons and her tales of the
uncomfortably new-old south can't keep me from momentarily focusing
on that lively little screen just above my treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened this morning. George Stephanopoulos is
talking to me through my earphones about tarnished ideals and the
Clinton White House. Next thing I know, two barely pubescent twerps
on the telly are bashing one another over an already shopworn young
thing badly in need of a shampoo and someone to suggest she stop
buying her clothes at Harriet's for Hookers.
</P>
<P>
   The guy on the stationary bike next to me is breathing through
his mouth, less from exertion, I suspect, than stupidity. And the
blonde angel on the stair step machine is taking it all in, nodding
agreement every time the moron in the Fu Manchu beard pounds
another lump on the head of the kid with his belly button hanging
out.
</P>
<P>
   I can't help wondering how long these two have been watching
trash television. The mouth-breather answers my unasked question.
``Hey,'' he says to the young lady on my right, the one climbing
the Empire State Building and then some, ``my mom used to tape this
for me when I was in school so I could watch it when I got home.''
</P>
<P>
   That nearly threw me off my treadmill. I turned and stared.
Couldn't help it. The climber hollered back saying, ``Like, WOW!
You got a cool mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure.
</P>
<P>
   But it makes me wonder _ who are the real dummies here? Not
Springer. He's making big bucks on this gig _ a lot more than he
took home as mayor of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The morons he's exploiting? They don't seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, after swiping a glance at the mesmerized kids on
either side of me, I'm thinking the biggest dummies of all are the
folks who watch this trash. But I suppress the urge to suggest to
either one of them that just maybe they're exercising all the wrong
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
