<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soothing from a distance
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   If you've got yourself a newborn-to-36-month-old light sleeper,
you might be interested in Fisher-Price's Slumbertime Soother with
Remote Control ($35; www.fisher-price.com). Basically a colorful,
softly twinkling electronic music box, free-standing or strapped
onto crib rails, the Slumbertime offers lullaby melodies or
``peaceful'' nature sounds to waft your wee one off to dreamland.
The unit will turn itself off after a preset two or 10 minutes, but
if that's not be enough, or should the peaceful sleeper awaken,
there's a handy dandy remote control that will activate the box
from a discreet distance. The remote requires line-of-sight
targeting, so while you don't have to walk right into the nursery
to turn the Soother on, you do have to open the door . . . just
make sure the hinges are well oiled.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
