<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Java aids Web input
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Often on the Internet you see ``loading Java.'' What is that and
why, once loaded, does it not remain and not have to be loaded
again?
</P>
<P>
   _ Harold Jones, Elberton, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Sun Microsystems invented Java, a computer language that
makes it easier and safer to deliver programs over the Internet.
Java allows the same software to work on many types of computers,
gadgets and electronic toys. It doesn't matter if you are using a
Mac or PC; Java runs anywhere. It lets computers communicate better
than ever and allows a Web site to do complex things.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Major Web browsers incorporate Java. To keep the browser
running efficiently, Java is loaded only when a Web site requires
it.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Say a Web site makes credit card transactions available,
for example; it might need Java to create that kind of interaction
with you. So the browser would load Java for that session. Once you
left the browser, it would disappear until the next time it was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Java's a cool program that lets all kinds of interaction
happen between you and your computer via the Internet, such as
audio, video, games and interactive educational programs. Without
Java, some Web sites wouldn't be nearly as much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: You can disable Java in your browser preferences if you
want, but then you'd miss out on all the cool stuff it does.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Mac Netscape users should go to File/Preferences. Click
Advanced and turn Enable Java off. Mac Internet Explorer users go
to Edit/Preferences. Open Web Browser and click Java and turn
Enable Java off. PC Netscape users should go to Edit/Preferences
and open Advanced. Click to turn Enable Java off. And PC Explorer
users go to Tools/Internet Options. Select Internet. Click Custom
Level. Scroll down to Java Permissions and select Disable Java.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Readers:
</P>
<P>
   When we get feedback on a column we'll do our best to relay more
information to you. Some folks wrote in some shortcuts for creating
an umlaut, which we wrote about in a recent column. Here are some:
</P>
<P>
   Sue: For the PC, hold down the ALT key and select an umlaut with
your number keypad. For example, A &QC; 129, U &QC; 132, O &QC; 148. You'll have
to remember which number goes with which umlaut, though.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Mac users should hit Option U. Then type the letter you
need. You'll have to hit Option U before each character.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Using Microsoft Word on a PC? Use Control, Shift, Colon and
the umlaut key. On a Mac or PC using Word, go to the Insert menu,
scroll to Symbol and select ``normal text'' from the font menu.
Select the umlaut. If necessary, you can create a shortcut key.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
