<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Macintosh program gives worldwide radio
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few sights are as rare as the review of a Macintosh
program in this space.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, that's what we're going to do today.
</P>
<P>
   I am not fond of the Macintosh _ and I'll thank you to refrain
from bombarding me with e-mail in protest _ but it falls to my lot
to use one at work.
</P>
<P>
   A publicist from Aladdin, which generally produces its little
programs first for the Mac and later, if they prove popular, for
the PC, interested me in something called the Aladdin Tuner.
</P>
<P>
   This is a really neat little application that presents the user
with a world map from which he can select a country, or, in the
case of the United States, a state, and get a list of plugged-in
radio stations and, in some cases, television stations there.
</P>
<P>
   You can go to the stations' home pages from the list, or just
click to begin receiving their broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   All of this, of course, requires RealPlayer, but most of you, I
imagine, have already got a version of that.
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned that some of the stations seem to require a pretty
recent version of RealPlayer, which can be downloaded at
www.realplayer.com/.
</P>
<P>
   The list of stations is broken down into formats _ jazz, heavy
metal, even, where available, that most unusual of formats,
classical. There is a search function that, for instance, allows
the user to find all the available gospel stations in Georgia or
all the talk stations in China.
</P>
<P>
   On my Power Macintosh G3, television comes through in a window
too small to be useful except in the most extreme emergencies.
Radio, for the most part, comes through pretty cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   If there's an available station that's not on the list, you can
ask Aladdin to add it, and the company promises updates once a
month.
</P>
<P>
   You can set up a menu of your own favorite stations. Aladdin
Tuner will also play CD and MP3 music.
</P>
<P>
   You can download a free version of the tuner that will work for
30 days before you have to register it or let it die. The price of
registering is $30.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, and downloading, go to the company's Web
site at www.aladdinsys.com.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's available now only for Macintosh computers
running System 8 or better. One hopes it will be forthcoming for
the PC in due time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
