<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Packing, moving your computer is a do-it-yourself project
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I calculate that I've purchased 18 washing machines,
12 lawn mowers, eight refrigerators and countless leaf blowers in
my long life.
</P>
<P>
   I've moved from apartment to house, house to house, city to
city, so many times that it might have been cheaper to rent a
storage building somewhere around Carbondale, Ill., and store those
appliances rather than sell them for a nickel on the dollar so many
times.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one good thing about all that moving. I have
learned many valuable lessons, including the fact that it is better
to hire others to do the moving. That's true for futons that need
to be carried down winding stairs, for washing machines possessed
by devils that desire to crush my toe, and for my antique china
cabinet that cracks and breaks a little more each time I move it.
</P>
<P>
   However, when it comes to moving computers _ especially if it's
a long-distance move _ you're better off doing the work yourself.
Let's talk about how to do that. If experience is any guide at all,
I promise you expert advice.
</P>
<P>
   Preparation for moving your computer starts on the day you bring
it home brand new. The temptation is to rip open the boxes _ like a
10-year-old at Christmastime _ and get that sucker out and running.
But the best of all packing materials for your computer is the
packing that it comes in new. So do your best to save every last
bit of Styrofoam and cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who aren't psychic (believe me, I know how a
move can sneak up on a person unexpectedly) and who didn't save all
the packing material, you can always try to drop by a computer
retail store. Sometimes stores may have some boxes that came with
some of their floor models. Failing that, you'll want a box of
about the same dimensions as the original packing box.
</P>
<P>
   Then you'll need to stop by an arts-and-crafts store to buy some
Styrofoam. You'll need enough to use it for padding on all sides of
the box. You'll need at least an inch of Styrofoam (2 inches is
better) on all sides of the box. But don't put the computer in the
box yet. There's still some stuff to do.
</P>
<P>
   First, especially if you're not exactly a computer whiz, it's a
good idea to label all the connections. That way, you'll know where
to plug in your modem, keyboard, mouse, etc. Many new computers
have made this task simple by doing the labeling for you. But if
that isn't the case with your machine, use transparent tape to
attach labels to the machine and to the cables.
</P>
<P>
   Next you'll want to make some final preparations with the
machine itself. To protect your floppy disk drive, cut a small
piece of cardboard (the kind that dry cleaners use for folded dress
shirts is perfect) into the shape of a floppy disk and insert it
into the drive. That'll keep the head for that drive from banging
around while the computer is in transit. (The really well-prepared
among you may have kept the original cardboard packing material
used by the computer manufacturer. Congratulations, but take a
moment to ponder your compulsiveness.)
</P>
<P>
   Now you're ready to pack up the computer. But there's something
important to keep in mind, especially this time of the year. Really
high temperatures can damage a computer. And extreme jolts _ the
kind that a computer might experience in a moving van or a rental
truck _ are also bad for the machine. So strongly consider moving
the computer in the back seat of the family car. If you do need to
move the computer in the truck, steal a trick from professional
movers and double box the machine. Box it as I've described, then
locate a box that is big enough to offer about 3 inches of
clearance on all sides when the packed box is inserted. Then pad
each side of the box with balled-up newspaper or bubble packing
material. Besides protecting the box from jolts, you'll also
provide some insulation from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   That should take care of moving your computer. Now all you need
is some help unpacking everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
