<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To buy the best new gadget, do some research on Web
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So it's finally time to buy a new cordless phone. Or
now's the time to replace the family VCR with a newer model that
doesn't spit out tapes or record your favorite programs with those
wacky lines across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   No problem _ you just head off to the nearest electronics store
and pick up a new one that fits into your budget, possibly a newer
version of the one you've used and loved all these many years,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, my friend. You could not possibly be more wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Since you last forked over the plastic for a new cordless phone,
do you you have any idea, even the remotest inkling, of the
unbelievable advances in phone technology? The same goes for VCRs,
toasters and even television sets. There's a bewildering array of
products out there, offering a myriad of options, features and of
course, prices.
</P>
<P>
   What should you do? A little Web surfing, of course, to bone up
on cellular phones, VCRs, DVD players, blenders or anything else
you are considering purchasing for your home.
</P>
<P>
   A good starting place is a nifty (and free) Web site called
MySimon (www.mysimon.com).
</P>
<P>
   MySimon isn't an online store. It doesn't sell anything. While
it does have deals with online merchants to help you shop for
products, what you will be using MySimon for is to find out which
product you want to buy.
</P>
<P>
   The way it works is simple: You click on a product category,
like VCR, and are taken to a product page. The site just went
through a redesign, so it's got more information than it used to,
but you want to scroll down to the ``Interactive Buyer's Guide.''
</P>
<P>
   Here you'll be walked through a series of steps to help you pick
the perfect product for your budget and your particular needs. The
process takes about 10 minutes maximum, and it's all based on user
input. You decide how much you want to spend, what features you
believe are most important and what trade-offs in terms of features
or price you are willing to make to get the best deal and the best
product for your needs.
</P>
<P>
   If you are like a lot of people and it's been awhile since you
went shopping for electronics, the range of options for the newest
home audio systems, cameras and even telephones is mind-boggling.
But as you go through MySimon, you can get explanations of what all
these newfangled gizmos will do. You can decide if they are right
for you.
</P>
<P>
   Do you really need a dual Super-VHS player? Does your cordless
phone really need to have digital technology built into it?
</P>
<P>
   MySimon has pop-up boxes that will explain any unfamiliar terms,
so by the time it comes up with recommendations, you will have a
good idea what is available and even desirable in your price range.
</P>
<P>
   All MySimon asks in return is some generic information including
nothing more personal than your age and ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   So now that you know there are three kinds of VCRs with three
different types of recording capabilities or that you can get a
cordless phone with more range and more gizmos on it than you ever
thought possible, it's time to see what the experts and people who
actually own the recommended products think.
</P>
<P>
   Continue evaluating products at Productopia
(www.productopia.com). It has the same organizational structure as
MySimon, in which you click on a category and a specific product.
Productopia will give you its best product picks in three criteria:
quality, style and value. Productopia doesn't just show you its
cool picks, it tells you why one DVD player was selected over
another and what other models from a particular manufacturer might
also fit your needs and your budget.
</P>
<P>
   You can also search the customer reviews section to find out
what people who have actually bought that new blender think of
their purchase. You can also follow links to the manufacturer's
home page or search the Web for more information and reviews.
</P>
<P>
   By now you should be armed with enough info about the products
you're interested in to make a truly intelligent purchase of
quality merchandise. However, before you spend a dime, there's just
one more stop on your information mission, Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's right _ Amazon.com. No, you're not going off to buy
anything there, unless of course you want to and the price is
right. The reason you are going to Amazon is for the product
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Most online shoppers and Amazon addicts already know that the
Amazon.com Web site has at least three or four detailed reviews on
everything from the new Harry Potter book to the latest in MP3
players.
</P>
<P>
   Surf the site until you find the item you are thinking of
buying. Some Amazon users write fairly detailed reviews that will
really give you the inside scoop. They'll tell you that a certain
model of Panasonic VCR is pretty noisy and some cordless phones,
while outfitted with the newest features, make the process of
placing a simple call or storing a number next to impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The entire online comparison shopping process shouldn't take
more than an hour or two if you visit every site and really delve
into the process. The result of all this free online research is
that you will become a smarter consumer ready to make an
intelligent purch
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
