<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fun with monsters and fiends
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Draconus: Cult of the Wyrm ($45; www.cravegames.com; for the
Dreamcast) offers Action/Adventure in the truest sense. Play as a
sardonic knight in shining armor or a swashbuckling sorceress in
hot pants through a fantasy world full of cheeky monsters and
typically foul fiends. A third-person/chase camera game, there are
a few minor glitches with perspective and frame rate, but nothing
to detract from gameplay, which is a splendid mix of exploration
and sword play with a few nifty magic spells thrown down for good
measure. Role-playing elements augment the two characters' skills
and abilities as the story unfolds without swamping the game with
tedious inventory management. Simply an easy-to-play, beautifully
rendered and wonderfully animated adventure with lots of action.
</P>
<P>
   Playing classic video games from the early 1980s on a pumped-up
Sega Dreamcast is like putting out a kitchen fire with one of the
Great Lakes. But that doesn't necessarily make it a bad thing.
Midway's Greatest Arcade Hits Volume 1 ($30; www.midway.com; for
the Dreamcast) offers six classics _ Joust, Defender, Defender II,
Robotron, Bubbles and Sinistar _ in the latest regurgitation of
Atari-era games for newer console systems. The game package has a
few handy features, like the ability to center and resize the game
screen and configure your controller for each game. The
translations are arcade-perfect using the original game code,
including sound effects and graphics. However, the initial thrill
of hearing the alien-blasting sounds of Defender or the pat-pat of
your bird's feet on the ground in Joust is short-lived. Because of
this, the $30 price tag seems a bit much _ after about 30 minutes,
you'll probably be ready to play something a little more apropo--
of your game system.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   It's been three years since gamers first wore out their
mouse-clicking fingers with Diablo. Now that the much-hyped Diablo
II ($60; www .blizzard.com; for Windows and Macs) is here, the
question is, was it worth the wait? Yes. The game improves on the
original Diablo, making it deeper, more playable and just as
addictive to novices as to hardened Diablo veterans. With a
much-improved storyline and fantastic cinematics, the game could
have just been a rote follow through, but the gameplay itself (even
with its low-resolution graphics) is still intuitive and amazingly
fun. While the initial launch of the game has been marred by some
multiplayer server problems, the lengthy, three-disc single-player
version is more than enough to satisfy fans until those glitches
are resolved. Get it. Play it.
</P>
<P>
   As a follow-up to the pinnacle motocross mud-mucking video
games, Microsoft's Motocross Madness ($45; www.microsoft.com; for
Windows) not only retains all of the righteous excitement of its
predecessor, it surpasses it in every way with much enhanced
graphics, depth of play, variety, optional complexity and
spectacular animated acceleration. Fully interactive environments
with trees that hurt and dump trucks that'll mow you over add
true-to-life predicaments to otherwise insanely aggressive virtual
dirt bike racing. A tremendous single-player game in its own right,
Motocross is fully realized as an online multiplayer racer where
the world's best are ranked and registered and the world's worst
simply cackle, scream with delight and perhaps pine for a place in
the upper echelon. This is the epitome of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
