 &HT;    Pocket this mouse
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   An unconventional piece of peripheral hardware that's got
``novelty'' and ``niche market'' written all over it, InterAct's
Pool Shark ($30; www. interact-acc.com) offers the real deal when
it comes to imitation billiards. Essentially an inverted and
mutilated mouse that coddles a lightweight imitation cue stick (you
can also use a real cue), the Pool Shark offers a better way to
play a PC game of pool than with the conventional mouse. A
plug-and-go USB device bundled with THQ's ``Ultimate 8-Ball,'' the
Pool Shark could be considered a must-have for aficionados save for
the fact that billiards fanatics are more likely to hang out in
pool halls, not hunker around a PC monitor. Then again, the Pool
Shark is a catchy little ``party'' device even if you're really
into the idea of essentially real strokes in a virtual game of
pool, the Pool Shark might be a winner.
</P>
