<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Vatican meddles in roiling waters
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, July 26, 2000
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if the Middle East negotiations weren't tangled enough, the
Vatican has decided to insert itself into this most difficult of
situations. Last weekend, Pope John Paul II suggested that
Jerusalem, the heretofore unfixable sticking point of any
negotiations, be internationally controlled.
</P>
<P>
   No Israeli control, no Palestinian control. Someone else in
control.
</P>
<P>
   It has a familiar ring to it, a quite familiar ring. This is
what was first decided by the United Nations in November 1947 when
Palestine was partitioned into separate Jewish and Arab states with
Jerusalem as an international enclave.
</P>
<P>
   How Jerusalem was to be administered never was quite clear. I
suppose it could have been done by a United Nations force but
history has shown us that United Nations' forces have not been the
bedrock of peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter because Jerusalem never got to enjoy any
international control. As soon as Israel declared its independence
in 1948, based on the U.N. partition, the Arabs attacked and
captured Old Jerusalem, including all the sites holy to Christians,
Jews and Moslems.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 19 years, the Old City was ruled by Jordan, much of
the time by the now revered, late King Hussein. One need not go
into discussing all the atrocities committed against the Jewish
sites under Jordanian control, or the denial by Jordan of Jewish
access to their holy sites all those years. It's been well
documented but now is seen as a bygone stigma inasmuch as Hussein,
having lost the city in 1967, later dropped his animosity to a
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Vatican to stick its nose into the situation in 2000
rankles me. Where, during the 19 years of Jordanian occupation, was
the cry from the Vatican to internationalize the city? To allow
Jews to worship there? To demand the Jordanians stop vandalizing
Jewish grave stones?
</P>
<P>
   The reigns of three popes, Pius II, John XXIII and Paul VI,
covered the period of Jordanian occupation, an occupation that not
only denied Jews their religious sites but also defied the original
United Nations' decision to internationalize the city.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with well-intending people seeking ways to heal a historic
impasse (and others hoping to sabotage it), the Vatican joins in
and says that neither the Jews or Moslems should control it, that
an international force should. This actually is not a new Vatican
position. Relations between Israel and the Vatican have been
strained in recent years as a result of the Vatican's persistent
insistence that Israel's occupation of the city was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh words from a 1948-1967 bystander.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, the Vatican admits it does not know a formula to
maintain an international Jerusalem. I don't know that anyone does,
or ever could _ maybe the folks at Disney would have the best
chance. We are dealing with the highest of emotions, a bubbling
lava buildup that shows no signs of cooling off.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an internationalized city would be ideal, flanked by
cooperative Israeli and Palestinian states. But, as we learned in
1948, and learn every day in Northern Ireland, India, Pakistan,
Fiji and dozens of other flashpoints, you can't make people love
each other if they don't want to love each other.
</P>
<P>
   And the Israelis and Palestinians, no matter what their
leadership maintains, have a deep dislike for each other.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what is decided at the top, the carrying out of any
agreements will have to be performed by people below _ and they
don't want to. From those heady days at the close of the 1967 war,
when the Israelis took and annexed Jerusalem, it was said that the
city was not a negotiable item in any dealings with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they are negotiating it, or trying to -- and without success
because no formula will be well-met by the more radical folks back
home. Now, along comes the Vatican to tell the Israelis, whose
cause they ignored for 19 uncaring years, that they should turn the
city over to, to...what? To whom?
</P>
<P>
   Impasse will remain the operative word.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)ail.mom.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
