<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1135 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0725-COX     07-24 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q &AMP; A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have been searching for a 1975 quarter for our daughter.
We are at our wits' end since this search has been going on for
over a year. Why is the 1975 quarter so scarce?
</P>
<P>
   _ Doris E.
</P>
<P>
   A: Because there are no 1975 quarters. In 1975 and 1976 the U.S.
Mint produced the Bicentennial Quarter. There is no difference
between the coins minted in those two years _ all have the same
dual dating (1776-1976). About 2.3 billion quarters were minted in
1975 and 1976. The customary annual production is 1 billion to 2
billion quarters. So even the bicentennials are relatively scarce.
The bicentennial quarter's reverse has a colonial drummer and a
victory torch circled by 13 stars representing the states in the
Union when the Declaration of Independence was signed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently I had ceramic tile installed. The installer set up
his equipment on my sidewalk. Later, I discovered an evergreen
shrub and rose bush were covered with tile dust that I cannot wash
off with a hose. Even heavy rain has not removed the dust. Is there
a solution that I can spray to remove this dust?
</P>
<P>
   _ N. Kalish
</P>
<P>
   A: Austin's own green thumb, Hank Howard of Howard Nursery, said
this dust, like cement dust, has adhered to the leaves. His
recommendation? Spray a bath of vinegar and water ( 1/4 cup vinegar
to 1 gallon water) on a few leaves. Let sit for five minutes. Rinse
thoroughly. Test a few leaves on each plant before spraying, since
some sensitive leaves may be burned by the mixture, warns Howard.
If the leaves do not respond well to the vinegar bath, wait for new
foliage to sprout and remove dusted leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently, I went to a popular Bulgarian hangout (restaurant
and bar) in downtown Sofia _''Eddy's Tex Mex Diner'' (4 Vitosha
Blvd., Sofia, Bulgaria). To my surprise, a large Confederate flag
was behind the band on the wall and was a focal point to everyone
there. Obviously, they don't know the difference between the
Confederate flag and the Texas flag! Would it be possible to get
someone from Texas tourism or state government to send them an
official Texas flag? Alternatively, where can one get a Texas flag?
</P>
<P>
   _ David R. Kincaid
</P>
<P>
   A: Of course, Eddy was obviously well-intentioned. A flag of the
Confederacy was one of the six flown over Texas. (The others?
France, Spain, Mexico, Republic of Texas and United States.)
</P>
<P>
   Through the magic of this column (and some aghast Texans
interested in tourism and Tex-Mex food abroad), a Texas flag flown
over the Capitol on July Fourth is winging its way to Eddy's in
Bulgaria. The flag is accompanied by a certificate of authenticity
and a note that it is compliments of the Texas House of
Representatives. Flags can be purchased from state representatives
or the sergeant at arms at the Capitol. P.S. How were the
enchiladas?
</P>
<P>
   Q: A question about many of the very old bridges in the New
England area. Why did the builders cover the bridges with a roof
and side?
</P>
<P>
   _ W.A. Castille
</P>
<P>
   A: To save money. Those practical colonials knew what they were
doing. Wood was plentiful (read ``cheap'') and bridges built of
stone did not respond well to the cold winters (stone pavers could
be damaged by the ice). The addition of a roof and sides protected
the wood from the elements, so covered bridges lasted longer. Of
course, more romantic reasons have been proffered. Youngsters could
hide from elders and kiss. Settlers could seek protection from
marauders; travelers, from the harsh winters. Oxen hauling loads
were easily spooked, and the sides of the bridge protected them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find a two-headed coin?
</P>
<P>
   _ M. Hooks
</P>
<P>
   A: Call Jake's Marketplace at (888) ITS-JAKE to purchase
two-headed or two-tailed coins. Prices begin at about $3 for the
penny; the popular half-dollar, about $9. These are genuine coins
that have been machined into double-sided coins. Fun, but I still
prefer ``Heads I win, tails you lose'' with a standard minted coin.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a house with white mini blinds on every window. They
need cleaning bad! What is the easiest way to get the dust, dirt
and smoke off them? Hopefully without taking each one down.
</P>
<P>
   _ K.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: White metal blinds? (These methods are not recommended for
bamboo or fabric mini blinds.) Since you are beyond vacuuming, put
on an old pair of socks, and use your favorite cleaner (always test
on an unobtrusive spot to make sure your cleaner will not scratch
or remove the finish). Wipe thoroughly on both sides. Wipe again
with clean socks. Sounds like they need a good soaking (I know you
don't want to, but maybe if you do a room a day, it will not be so
dreary). Protect the tub with a towel and soak the blinds in a
sudsy solution (mild soap and warm water, or even laundry
detergent). Rinse thoroughly, dry (do not hang wet blinds made with
natural fiber strings, lest the strings stretch). Some prefer to
remove blinds and hose them off outside _ in the yard or at an
automatic car wash. Once they are clean, regular vacuuming will
keep them looking good.
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR:
</P>
<P>
   Reader Linda Miles shared her quilt-washing tips. Put a sheet in
the bottom of the tub. This reduces the strain on the stitching
when lifting the quilt out of the tub. A wet quilt is a heavy
quilt. Roll the quilt in towels to remove excess moisture. Place it
on a clean sheet (upside down) in a shady part of the yard to speed
drying.Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
