A1139 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-HISPANIC0725-COX     07-24 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-HISPANIC0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many Georgians have new Hispanic neighbors _ let's learn more
about them
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're old enough to read this, then it's safe to
say that a lot more Hispanics live in Georgia today than when you
were born. In fact, the number of Hispanics in the state has
doubled in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   So who is ``Hispanic''?
</P>
<P>
   That term refers to people who were born in Latin America or
whose parents or grandparents were born there. Most speak Spanish.
Latin America is made up of more than 20 countries south of the
United States _ countries such as Mexico, Colombia, Argentina, Cuba
and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of Hispanics began moving to Georgia in the early 1990s.
Estimates of Georgia's Hispanic population differ greatly,
depending on whom you ask. The U.S. Census Bureau says it's about
220,000. The Center for Applied Research in Anthropology says it's
about 480,000. Georgia has about 7.8 million residents total.
</P>
<P>
   Many Hispanics come to Georgia to work. Many help build new
houses and businesses in metro Atlanta. Others open stores and
restaurants. In other parts of Georgia, Hispanics work in carpet
factories and chicken plants.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the grown-ups brought families with them. The number of
Hispanic boys and girls in Georgia schools has increased to nearly
46,000 last year from 34,000 three years ago. (Even so, only three
of every 100 students in Georgia schools are Hispanic.)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Hispanic children have a tough time adjusting to life
in Georgia. Some are learning English in addition to studying other
subjects. Some immigrants in American schools for the first time
must figure out what to do in the cafeteria _ how much food to
take, where to get it, how much it costs _ and how to ask
permission to go to the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   You might be confused, too, if your parents moved you to a
foreign country and enrolled you in a school with its own rules for
catching the bus, going to recess and eating lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Most Hispanics in Georgia are from Mexico. Some came here
straight from that country. Others moved here from states with
large Hispanic populations such as California, Texas or Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Their arrival is changing Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the changes when you turn on the television or go to
the grocery store. A lot of houses in metro Atlanta have
televisions that receive one or two cable channels that air
cartoons, sports and other shows in Spanish. And lots of grocery
stores have started to sell foods and drinks that are popular in
Latin America, such as corn tortillas and fruit-flavored sodas. You
also may notice more signs in Spanish all around Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
