<HEADER>
A1140 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0725-COX     07-24 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sen. Coverdell dies
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgians mourned the death of their senior U.S.
senator last week. Services were held Saturday in Atlanta for Paul
Coverdell (right), 61. The Republican senator died Tuesday at
Piedmont Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had operated on his brain the day before to relieve
swelling caused by a stroke. A stroke happens when the blood flow
to some part of the brain is greatly reduced or when there is
bleeding in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell was one of the top Republican leaders in the U.S.
Senate. Senators in both political parties said he was a tireless
worker. He also worked closely with Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
presidential campaign. He would have played a key role in next
week's Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell was active in politics for about 30 years. He was
first elected to the U.S. Senate in 1992. The senator is survived
by his wife, Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   A special election will be held in November to fill Coverdell's
seat. Gov. Roy Barnes can pick someone to fill that seat until the
election is held.
</P>
<P>
   PEACE TALKS CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat stayed on at Camp David in Maryland after peace talks nearly
broke down last week. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
has been meeting with each leader to try to move the talks forward.
They remain divided on issues such as creating a completely
independent Palestinian state and who will control certain
neighborhoods in the Israeli capital, Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Barak indicated that he might be willing to give
up some control of the Arab sections of East Jerusalem.
Palestinians have wanted those neighborhoods returned since Israel
took them over in the 1967 Israeli-Arab war. But this potential
compromise has its problems. Palestinians in East Jerusalem fear
that they could lose their jobs, Israeli medical benefits and
access to various areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
   FASTER THAN SPEEDING LIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Albert Einstein may have gotten something wrong. The famous
scientist's ``theory of relativity'' says that nothing can travel
faster than light in a vacuum, or empty space. That is really,
really fast _ about 186,000 miles per second. But scientists in New
Jersey have found a way to break the light speed barrier, at least
in a laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   They used a glass chamber filled with a chemical vapor, instead
of a vacuum. They sent a pulse of laser light through it. The light
left the chamber before it finished entering it. The scientists say
the beginning of the pulse has all the information it needs to
produce the light on the other end. So the entire laser pulse
doesn't have to enter the chamber for it to appear on the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   But don't start thinking that you could travel through time
because of this discovery. The ability to exceed the speed of light
is limited to things that have no mass, such as light waves. Right
now, it's just a really cool experiment, though scientists hope
they can find a use for it, such as making computers work faster.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
