r f BC-TECH-FAMILY0725-COX     07-24 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FAMILY0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Receiving offensive e-mail no joking matter to many
 &HT;    By Anne Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a recent trip we stayed with friends. My girlfriend
was showing me her computer, and an e-mail joke appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The joke contained references to drunkenness, adultery and
public indecency. It was not a very funny joke and seemed even more
tasteless considering the source was a 15-year-old relative.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail prompted a conversation about the unwanted e-mails
that she receives from friends. She described one e-mail with
cartoon images of President Clinton involved in unpresidential
activities and another e-mail with naked men in baseball caps.
</P>
<P>
   The bad jokes put her in an awkward position. Should she ask the
senders to refrain from sending jokes, or should she just delete
them without insulting anyone?
</P>
<P>
   I believe she should request to be taken off her friend's and
family's joke mailing lists. Why should anyone feel obligated to
accept unwanted and offensive e-mails? This computer, like many
family computers, is shared among the two adults in the home and a
grade-schooler. Her daughter does not need the added education
provided in these e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Bad jokes traveling through cyberspace end up in businesses as
well as homes. Many people complain about receiving these offensive
e-mails at their work addresses.
</P>
<P>
   These jokes are more alarming to some computer users than spam
because they know the senders. They should also be easier to
eliminate than mass mailings.
</P>
<P>
   There should be required cyber-education to tame the reckless in
cyberspace. One key lesson would be to treat your e-mails as if
they were your conversation. Would you walk into a luncheon with
friends and pass around cartoons of naked men? Would you put them
in envelopes and send them through the U.S. Postal Service? Why
would you e-mail them? Would you tell dirty jokes at the
playground? Why would you send them to those same people from your
home computer?
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect other drivers to observe the rules of the road, and
the same is true as we travel through cyberspace,'' according to
LearntheNet (www.learnthenet.com) on its netiquette page.
</P>
<P>
   Netiquette, or etiquette for the Internet, should begin with
basic courtesies. E-mail users should not waste time and space
sending unwanted messages. Senders should refrain from mailing
dirty jokes to every e-mail address they know.
</P>
<P>
   The inappropriate use of e-mail is growing, and someone ought to
tell computer users to follow a decent code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   There are many Web sites with advice on Internet etiquette,
including www.albion.com/netiquette/introduction.html.
</P>
<P>
   I have asked to be removed from these lists and have maintained
relationships with the jokesters. Tell your friends how much you
enjoy their actual conversation. Then ask them to take you off the
jokes, prayers or other nonsense lists if you do not wish to be
included. Good friends will find a better way to communicate with
you.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not getting enough jokes, you can sign up for joke
mailing lists or read them at Web sites. The Jokester's joke list
(www.jokester.com/listinfo.html) is a free subscription-based
service (intended for mature audiences).
</P>
<P>
   Try JokesEveryday (www.jokeseveryday.com/) for its clean sense
of humor. Join the more than 70,000 subscribers at JokesEveryday
and receive three jokes each day for free.
</P>
<P>
   Choose from clean or dirty jokes, or subscribe to receive both
at www.emailajoke.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Read jokes without subscribing at Fat Days
(www.fatdays.com/jokes/) where favorites are noted with a star.
Services like these are advertising-supported, so expect to read
promotional material between laughs.
</P>
<P>
   If you were hoping for a laugh today, here is a sample joke from
the archives of EmailAJoke.com:
</P>
<P>
   PC Language
</P>
<P>
   A computer was something on TV from a science-fiction show of
note.
</P>
<P>
   Window was something you hated to clean.
</P>
<P>
   And ram was the cousin of a goat.
</P>
<P>
   Meg was the name of my girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   And gig was a job for the nights.
</P>
<P>
   Now they all mean different things.
</P>
<P>
   And that really mega bytes.
</P>
<P>
   An application was for employment.
</P>
<P>
   A program was a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   A cursor used profanity.
</P>
<P>
   A keyboard was a piano.
</P>
<P>
   Compress was something you did to the garbage, not something you
did to a file.
</P>
<P>
   And if you unzipped anything in public, you'd be in jail for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   Log on was adding wood to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Hard drive was a
</P>
</TEXT>
