<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIKE-POST-OFFICE-ART-     07-24 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-POST-OFFICE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING A LIFT TO SALES AND SPIRIT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GREG WINTER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Racing through
<TEXT>
the Alps in a teetering bus, cheering on packs of professional
cyclists jockeying for position at 50 miles an hour, Gail
Sonnenberg has one thing in mind: increasing sales at the United
States Postal Service.
<P>
   As senior vice president of sales for the quasi-independent
agency, Sonnenberg began overseeing its sponsorship of the United
States cycling team in 1997. That was just as Lance Armstrong
emerged from his bout with cancer to join the squad _ whose
uniforms are emblazoned with the Postal Service logo.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sonnenberg, based in Arlington, Va., treks to races in this
country and abroad, drumming up new business _ especially from the
team's many other corporate backers. ``Like any other sponsorship,
it's about building our brand,'' she said last week over the blare
of loudspeakers announcing that the team still had the lead in the
Tour de France, which ends Sunday. ``This is not something we do
because it feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Postal Service landed the title sponsorship for the
team in 1996, it hoped to grab international business away from
competitors who operate overseas, where cycling is adored. But the
team's success _ last year, it was the first American squad to win
the Tour de France _ has also been a point of pride at the post
office, a place historically short on morale.
</P>
<P>
   The tour gives Sonnenberg access to executives of sponsors like
Nike and Bike.com _ companies whose online sales can be shipped
through the post office _ as well as Visa, which does much of its
marketing by mail. In 1999, relationships with sponsors brought the
post office $10 million, she said, more than offsetting the cost of
being the team's title sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   After the victory last year, the Postal Service slapped its logo
on biking paraphernalia and started selling it over the Internet.
But that extra revenue may pale in comparison with the exposure
that its best-known cyclist, Armstrong, brings to an otherwise
banal brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like traveling with the Beatles,'' Sonnenberg said,
referring to the crowds that encircle Armstrong at races. ``This
was an awfully lucky venture for us.''
</P>
<P>
   slot  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
