<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1172 &Cx1f; sci-z
u l BC-CELESTIAL-LIGHT-SHOW-     07-24 1768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELESTIAL-LIGHT-SHOW-DISCOVER-$ADV18-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING THE LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., Tue., July 18, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Five color slides are included. They are FREE OF CHARGE to
newspapers that purchase this article as a oneshot.) 
 &HT;    
 By KAREN WRIGHT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    There's a lonesome outpost in the Alaskan interior where
scientists work in wool slippers and all-nighters are standard
procedure, where sunlight is scorned and darkness cherished for the
promises it holds.
 &HT;    That outpost is the science center at the Poker Flat Research
Range, a rocket-launching facility in the hills 30 miles northeast
of Fairbanks. Poker Flat is one of the world's premier centers for
studies of the aurora borealis, the electromagnetic light show that
graces the subarctic firmament almost every night of the year.
 &HT;    Perched on top of a low rise with a uniform view of sky, snow
and spruce, the center sometimes teems with researchers. Tonight,
though, it's the regulars from the Geophysical Institute of the
University of Alaska at Fairbanks. They'll while away the wee hours
swapping stories, watching movies, trading computer tips and
waiting for a phantom stream of light.
 &HT;    At peak aurora season, fanatics such as Hans Nielsen, a
fiftysomething Dane, keep vigil in this place every night for weeks
on end.
 &HT;    ``When I get on this schedule, I can't remember one night from
the next,'' he confesses. ``It all becomes a blur.''
 &HT;    Not that he's complaining. Like most of his colleagues, Nielsen
has a special fondness for the northern lights.
 &HT;    In the 1950s, scientists began to understand that the aurora
