<HEADER>
A1176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-ENRIGHT-BOS &LR;      07-24 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-ENRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH ENRIGHT, 89; CAPTAIN OF FAMOUS WWII SUBMARINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT S. GREENBERGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Enright, a World War II Navy captain who commanded the
submarine that torpedoed the largest warship ever sunk, died
Thursday in Fairfax, Va. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Enright, who spent his post-Navy career in New England, was
born in North Dakota. He graduated from the US Naval Academy in
1933 and entered the submarine service several years later. In
September 1944, he took command of the USS Archer-Fish.
</P>
<P>
   When the Archer-Fish departed Saipan on Nov. 11, its primary
mission was to rescue downed B-29 pilots. But on the evening of
Nov. 28, the submarine's radar picked up what some crew members
believed at first to be an island. In fact, it was the Shinano, a
Japanese aircraft carrier that weighed at least 60,000 tons and at
the time was the largest ever built.
</P>
<P>
   Once the crew identified the blip on the screen as a ship, the
Archer-Fish gave chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were racing as fast as we could, going over the rated
capacity of both of our engines, trying to keep up,'' recalled Carl
Wilken, who was in charge of one of the engine rooms that night.
``It zigged away from us. When it zigged back, we shot it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Archer-Fish fired six torpedoes, crew members recall. All
six hit their target. A ball of fire climbed up the side of the
Japanese ship and crew members heard a series of explosions as the
ship broke apart and sank.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer-Fish escaped from the encounter unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mr. Enright's spectacular success, Wilken said, the
captain ``wasn't as aggressive as some of the skippers who are now
on the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked after his boat and his crew, and I think he was
proud of that,'' Wilken said. ``He told the wives of the members of
the crew that their husbands were in good hands and that he'd bring
them back, and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Enright earned the Navy Cross and the Archer-Fish received
the Presidential Unit Citation for sinking the Shinano. Mr. Enright
later commanded the USS Boston, the world's first missile cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring in 1963, Mr. Enright settled in Dover. He worked
on defense contracts for the Northrop Corp. in Needham and the
Sanders Corp. in Nashua. After retiring from the defense industry,
he worked part time approving construction permits for the town of
Dover. In 1987, he co-wrote ``Shinano! The Sinking of Japan's
Secret Supership.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Enright's wife of 49 years, Virginia Enright Robertson, died
in 1987. His son, Joseph Jr. died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves a a sister, Marion Enright Gross of Spring Hill, Fla.;
two grandchildren; and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
