<HEADER>
A1213 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     07-24 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, July 24, 2000      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
   
 (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COSMOS (San Francisco) _ Alien universes might be stacked
alongside ours like slices of ham and cheese in a Dagwood sandwich,
according to a bizarre new scientific theory. This hypothesis is
one possible implication of a radical concept of physics championed
by scientists from UC-Berkeley, Stanford and New York University.
By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   HYDROPONIC-MARIJUANA (San Francisco) _ Firefighters battling a
three-alarm fire at a San Francisco warehouse uncovered a large
marijuana-growing operation which may have started the blaze.
Authorities found evidence of more than 1,000 young marijuana
plants at the warehouse, which appeared to be a hydroponic nursery,
said San Francisco police narcotics Inspector Martin Halloran. By
RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TAMMY-FAYE (New York) _ Time has not eroded Tammy Faye's belief
in her ex-husband's innocence, or in the sanctity of mascara. But
the 12 years since the collapse of the PTL ministry run by Tammy
Faye and Jim Bakker have given her new perspective on their place
in tabloid culture. By RON DICKER.
</P>
<P>
   AGING (San Francisco) _ Comedia George Burns, whose recipe for
longevity seemed to be martinis and cigars, died in 1996 at the age
of 100. When asked in his late 90s if his doctor knew he still
smoked, Burns said, ``No . . . he's dead.'' Burns is the featured
photo in Scientific American's publication, ``The Quest to Beat
Aging.'' By DAVID STEINBERG.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``['' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SENATE (San Francisco) _ Republican Tom Campbell has
gained no headway in his bid to unseat Democratic U.S. Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, according to an Examiner-KTVU poll showing that
one-third of state voters still don't recognize his name. By MARSHA
GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOT-COMS-LAYOFFS (San Francisco) _ Since last December, 122
dot-com firms have announced staff cuts leaving a total of 7,952
new economy workers out of a job, according to a survey released
Monday. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TECH (Bangalore, India) _ It's a familiar scene here: A
young software engineer with dreams of big bucks and a recruiter
representing a U.S. high-tech firm sit across the table from one
another, talking about careers, opportunities and, most
importantly, money. Of the estimated 300,000 Indian high-tech
workers employed abroad, about 80 percent work in the United
States. By MATTHEW YI.
</P>
<P>
   ADA-BUSINESSES (San Antonio) _ Even before the Americans With
Disabilities Act became law 10 years ago this week, it touched off
waves of protests from the business world. Today, though, attitudes
have changed. While not every business leader is a wholehearted
booster of the law _ called ADA for short _ many say that
compliance has been less onerous than they feared. By BILL DAY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DEION-SANDERS (Ashburn, Va.) _ Just five months ago, Deion
Sanders was one of the most hated members of the Dallas Cowboys,
the chief rival of the Washington Redskins. But these days,
Redskins fans who used to curse the cornerback/kick returner when
he was a Cowboy flatter him with shouts of ``Deee-on.'' By TOM
ORSBORN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS-RECEIVERS (Wichita Falls, Texas) _ Receiver Joey
Galloway gives you the ``stretchability'' that you need,'' Dallas
Cowboys Coach Dave Campo said of probably the fastest Cowboys
receiver since Bob Hayes. The Cowboys' other starting receiver,
Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail, has jets himself. So who's faster? By
BRENT ZWERNEMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-FISHING (Jucaro, Cuba) _ Only 20 visitors per week are
allowed into this 3,000-square mile marine park by the Cuban
government. I was there to check out the fishing. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL-FOOD (Stockton, Calif.) _ The San Francisco 49ers are
in training camp on the campus of the University of Pacific. And as
usual, one of the most awesome sights in camp is the training table
groaning under the load of food intended to satisfy more than 80
hungry football players, many in the 280-to-320-pound range. By
BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ My brother and I share an
understanding of ``chick'' vs. ``guy,'' an American cultural
distinction greater than Republican vs. Democrat, highbrow vs.
lowbrow or sports utility vehicle vs. minivan. After all, both
minivans and SUVs are chick cars, the SUV being ``the new station
wagon,'' as Dave Barry once put it. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The German historian who has
made a specialty of defending Nazi Germany rationalized Hitler's
persecution of the Jews as part of the Fuhrer's war against
Bolshevism. Ernst Nolte has been at it for years, but only now has
been rewarded with the prestigious Konrad Adenauer Prize,
considered Germany's top literary honor. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   MARY-McCARTHY (San Francisco) _ I recently wrote about famous
writers who cut each other up under the guise of thoughtful essays.
I noted Mary McCarthy's zap at Lillian Hellman: ``Every word she
writes is a lie, including `and' and `the.''' Although I enjoy
reading about literary feuds, an enduring literary friendship is
equally appealing. In Mary McCarthy's case, such a friendship
bloomed with Hannah Arendt. By BOB ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   SON'S-MURDER (San Francisco) _ My son was murdered in San
Francisco. Perhaps the ugliest stain of all is the way police,
press, politicians and people doing business in that neighborhood
will blink, wink and turn away until another young person dies
there. Then another round begins. By JIM SEGAL.
</P>
