<SLUG> BC-KOMANDO-COLUMN-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KOMANDO REPORT: PLAYING THE NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: are available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez
at 212-499-3355.) 
 By KIM KOMANDO 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The early days of online shopping were pretty close to
traditional shopping. Yes, you could (and still can) do it all from
your favorite computer chair, but the process was really no
different than doing it the old-fashioned way. You went to the
store (virtually, in this case), found what you wanted, checked the
price and made the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, to the delight of buyers and sellers, Internet shopping
developed another, more exciting venue: virtual auction sites such
as eBay. Sure, auctions have been around for centuries, but how
many of you have actually participated in one? These auction sites
brought the concept into mainstream, everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are a few other shopping models taking hold on the
Internet, and most of them revolve around the idea of group buying
power. The basic idea is nothing new. For example, how many of you
already have membership cards for those huge stores _ like Sam's
Club or Costco _ where you can buy everything you've ever dreamed
of in bulk? What's different is the manner in which the group
buying concept is being applied to Internet shopping.
</P>
<P>
   One shopping model that's been adopted by at least two companies
is based on the idea that more buyers of an individual product can
drive the price down. Both Mercata (www.mercata.com) and MobShop
(www. mobshop.com), formerly Accompany.com, operate on this
principle. The idea is simple. The more people who buy a specific
product during a specific time period, the lower its price goes.
However, each of these sites handles the matter a little
differently.
</P>
<P>
   On the Mercata site, you're never quite sure _ at least not
until the buying period closes _ how much you're likely to pay for
a product. When you find a product you like, you agree to purchase
it at the then-current price and hope that the price will drop even
lower before the deal closes. The problem I see with this approach
is that you have no idea if or when the price is likely to drop, or
to what level it may drop. It's my hard-earned cash and it's a
funny thing, but I like to know where my money goes before my
wallet is empty. There really should be a minimum price for any
item, and Mercata should be able to tell you the price.
</P>
<P>
   MobShop is more straightforward. The pricing structure for each
item is presented in a four-bar graph. The first bar shows the
MSRP, and each of the three other bars represents a price based on
the number of buyers who participate. For example, I looked at a
Toshiba SD1200 DVD player. The MSRP for this item was $299.95.
However, the starting price for up to 25 buyers was $199.95. The
price for 26 to 50 buyers _ $199.95 _ was the same as for the first
25. For 51 to 101 buyers, the price was $189.95.
</P>
<P>
   For me, MobShop's more open approach to pricing makes sense. (I
should point out that both Mercata and MobShop allow you to specify
a maximum price for your purchase.) If the item doesn't drop to the
price you specify, your order is canceled. The flip side is that
once you place an order, on either site, there is no way to cancel
it yourself. That's because the final price is based on the total
number of buyers, and your cancellation could conceivably drive the
price back up.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind these sites may be compelling, but the true test
is in the final pricing. Do these sites really offer the best
deals?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, my research shows that the answer is a big fat
``No.'' Although the online prices are almost always competitive
with store prices, they are not always the best you can find.
</P>
<P>
   I broke my CD player last year in Maui. I'm getting ready to go
again this year so I did some looking on the MobShop site and found
an Audiovox CE-150R personal CD player. It had an MSRP of $79.95, a
starting price of $75.95 and a minimum price of $64.95. At the
time, the actual price was still at $79.95. However, a quick check
at PriceScan (www. pricescan.com) located the same CD player at The
Big Store (www.thebigstore.com) for $61.70. I didn't need to call
all my friends to get the price that low. That's the standard
price.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, I put in an order for ``The Matrix'' on DVD through
MobShop, but stipulated that the price drop to $16.95. That seemed
like a fair price even without considering that the starting price
was over $18. To see if it was a deal or not, I went over to the
price-shopping site Mysimon (www.mysimon.com). I didn't feel so
good after seeing that www.samgoody.com had ``The Matrix'' for sale
and in stock for $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   There's another problem with these sites. As I mentioned
earlier, consumers are given only so much time to take advantage of
any given offer. This works against you if, for example, you want a
CD player right now. The buying periods typically range from one to
five days. That means if you happen to order an item just as it's
put up for sale, you may have to wait five days before the order is
processed. This seems counter to the instant-gratification promise
of most Internet shopping sites.
</P>
<P>
   Another group-buying concept becoming popular on a number of
sites is one in which the sites serve as merchant aggregators. In
other words, with one of these Web sites as an intermediary,
several merchants offer their goods for sale and compete against
each other for your business. These are similar to auction sites,
except that there's no bidding. Instead, the seller sets his price,
and you either buy the item or not.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the skinny on a few of these sites.
</P>
<P>
   BazaarE (www.bazaare.com) is similar in some ways to Mercata and
MobShop, but very different in others. Here, you can either join an
existing ``shopping group'' or create one of your own. The purpose
of these groups is to identify people who are all interested in
purchasing the same product.
</P>
<P>
   These groups are formed for specific periods of time, and while
they're active, multiple merchants supposedly submit bids to the
group. The interesting thing is that each individual group member
can then decide which bid to accept. In other words, all group
members aren't necessarily forced to buy the item from the same
merchant. Vive capitalism!
</P>
<P>
   NexTag (www.nextag.com) offers a similar, but more direct
approach to online discount shopping. Like BazaarE, it works like
an aggregator for merchants. However, when it comes to purchasing,
you're totally on your own.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: First, you identify a product that you want
to buy. Then, you're presented with a list of participating
merchants who offer that product, along with their prices and other
terms. At this point you have two options. You can either purchase
the item from one of the merchants, or if you're a haggler, you can
tell them all the price is too high and ask for a lower price. The
big advantage here is that there's no waiting _ you make your own
deal and close on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Again comes the question: Is it the best deal? At NexTag, I
found a great digital camera _ a Nikon CoolPix 950 _ for $701.07,
including shipping and handling. At my local BestBuy, the same unit
sells for $899, but there is a $100 rebate coupon available making
the grand total $799. One thing to remember: At BestBuy, you can be
snapping pictures in less than 15 minutes. You'll have to decide
which is best for you.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is changing the way we shop, and I have to applaud
all these sites for at least trying something different. However,
in my opinion, the Internet is supposed to make life easier, not
more complicated. That's an area where these sites tend to fall
short in one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
