</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A photo of the Sphinx, a photo of an image cast in stone,
a photo of a land mine deactivator in use, a photo of a CPPI
automated lab and a photo of workers building a wing are available
on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPHINX GETTING A FACELIFT
</P>
<P>
   Austrian scientists have unraveled one of the great mysteries of
the Sphinx: how to save it from further erosion. Several thousand
years in the desert has taken its toll on the 190-foot-long,
66-foot-high natural rock carving. European do-gooders did even
more damage by trying to restore the mysterious statue at Giza,
near Cairo. In fact, human-inflicted damage was so bad that the
United Nations financed an eight-year effort to undo the damage
caused by these ``repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The task at hand is to preserve the structure. Egyptian
antiquities experts were impressed with an idea from the Austrian
College of Trade and Technology. Researchers there developed a
silicate treatment that will shield the stone from sun and water
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Instructors from Austria have traveled to Egypt to familiarize
restoration workers with their technique.
</P>
<P>
   PICTURES NOW CAN BE SET IN CONCRETE
</P>
<P>
   Why leave your footprints in wet concrete when you can leave
your picture instead? A new variation of silk-screening lets you
cast complex images in stone.
</P>
<P>
   The process works like this. A black-and-white photo of the
image to be transferred is converted into a traditional silkscreen
stencil. This stencil is placed on a freshly poured concrete
aggregate base that has been coated with colored cement. The
stencil is then ``inked'' with a chemical that temporarily prevents
the concrete directly beneath it from drying.
</P>
<P>
   After the slab has hardened, the retardant is washed away.
Washing also removes the top layer of cement, exposing the
different color aggregate. The technique was developed by Pieri, a
French company.
</P>
<P>
   LAND MINE DEACTIVATOR
</P>
<P>
   A device that detects and then disables plastic land mines has
been developed by Ohio State University researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike land mines of the past, today's are made of plastic,
which makes them invisible to metal detectors, says Chi-Chih Chen,
one of the system's developers. To detect them, Chen uses
ground-penetrating radar.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, these systems have to be placed directly on the ground
to work, which is generally a bad idea when working with landmines.
Chen side-stepped the problem with a novel antenna design. In
tests, the system correctly identified two common types of land
mines buried as deep as 2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has applied for a patent on a companion device that will
shoot a chemical agent into the soil, deactivating the land mines.
One chemical agent would solidify the triggering mechanism,
rendering the mine temporarily safe. Another chemical would
solidify the mine and soil permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Then, you could just shovel the mines out and throw them away.
</P>
<P>
   ROBOT LAB LESSENS ASTRONAUTS' WORK
</P>
<P>
   An orbiting robot laboratory will speed drug development.
</P>
<P>
   Growing protein crystals for X-ray analysis is an essential
first step in creating new drugs. Low gravity in space produces
nearly perfect specimens. The Crystal Preparation Prime Item, or
CPPI, prototype built by Oceaneering Space Systems of Houston, lets
scientists control crystal growth from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The CPPI lab has been shipped to the University of Alabama at
Birmingham where it will be the centerpiece of the X-ray
Crystallography Facility to be installed on the international space
station. Both are now under construction.
</P>
<P>
   NEW WAY TO BUILD WINGS
</P>
<P>
   Shipbuilding begins with laying the keel. Airplane construction
starts with building the spar, an internal wing-support structure.
</P>
<P>
   For its next generation of 737s, the 177-passenger 900 series,
Boeing's Renton, Wash., factory will largely automate spar
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The spar will be encorporated into the first 737-900. The
177-passenger plane is scheduled to be delivered to Alaska Airlines
in April 2001.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
