<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-WITHOUT-AN-ITINERARY-TRAVEL-ENDPAPER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING THAT PLANS ARE MADE TO BE SCRAPPED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Free to clients of Way to Go!) 
 (FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES) 
 BY AURELIA C. SCOTT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    The moment of truth came at an outdoor table in the Plaza Nueva
in Granada, although neither of us admitted it. Instead, my
husband, Bob, and I continued to sip our glasses of vino tinto and
roll green olives between tongue and teeth, ejecting the pits with
newly acquired expertise.
 &HT;    The evening sun was refracted through dusty air, gilding the
Gypsies and multinational youth in the plaza. Homeward-bound
Granadans threaded through the crowds carrying grocery bags topped
by market-fresh fruit. Tourists whose fanny packs made them look
bustle-bottomed clustered around displays of postcards, fluttering
lace fans and trays of castanets.
 &HT;    As the shadows lengthened, the day's deafening traffic dwindled
to the whine of motor scooters loaded beyond their capacities with
three, even four clinging passengers. We sipped and watched and
rested our feet, wondering how we would stay awake until Spanish
dinner time at 8:30 p.m. _ 8 p.m. in restaurants that cater to
tourists.
 &HT;    And we wondered, although still not giving voice to the thought,
what to do with the rest of our trip. Not that we didn't have
plans. The plans for this first trip to the land of sun and saffron
and tapas had been made in meticulous detail weeks before our
departure.
 &HT;    I had spent a fine meal's worth of money on Frommer's, Fodor's,
Eyewitness and Let's Go guides and other aides, including
Learn-Spanish-in-Your-Car CDs. We had combed newspaper travel
sections and reread articles clipped from food magazines.
 &HT;    I had followed Internet links from one Spanish travel site to
another until I was bleary-eyed and lost. We had begged friends and
relatives of friends for memories of their own trips.
 &HT;    Finally, knowing too much and not enough, we developed a
two-week itinerary. Not all of Spain, of course. Just what called
to us as we shoveled our way out of yet another Maine winter.
 &HT;    Barcelona because 30 years ago Bob had read Orwell's ``Homage to
Catalonia''; Quatretondeta in the mountains above Alicante for the
small-town experience; Agua Amarga to dip our feet in the
Mediterranean in a still-pretty seaside town; Granada for the
Alhambra; Ronda because it is the most accessible of the Moorish
pueblos blancos; Cordoba for its mosque and old city; Cuenca for
its perilously hanging houses and its location in Castilla-La
Mancha; and Barcelona again to rest before the flight home.
 &HT;    I typed it all up _ flight numbers, hotel names, telephone
numbers, dates of arrival, dates of departure. One copy faxed to
our nearest and dearest, another hand-delivered to friends who
would water our houseplants; a copy in Bob's carry-on; the copy in
my carry-on stapled to a sheaf of hotel confirmation letters and
directions.
 &HT;    Too much? Well, I like lists. Besides, we were heading on the
cusp of high season to a country whose language we do not speak. We
think of ourselves as flexible and adventurous. Yet we have reached
the stage at which we no longer wish to trail our suitcases along
foreign streets looking for a hotel with a vacancy.
 &HT;    And to be honest, Bob does not want to traipse along a dark
corridor to reach the bathroom and I need a mattress that does not
sink to the floor.
 &HT;    Munching on an olive as the sun set on the Plaza Nueva, I
reflected that thus far the plans had been executed practically
perfectly. Barcelona's light and space and elegance had made us
giddy with pleasure.
 &HT;    Arm in arm, we joined the perambulating throngs to walk up and
down, and again up and down the Rambla, the grand tree-lined
boulevard to the sea. Standing before Antoni Gaudi's famous
wave-shaped building, whose wrought-iron balconies writhe like
wind-tossed seaweed, Bob said, ``I could live here.'' Not Casa Mila
specifically, but Barcelona. I agreed.
 &HT;    Once out of Barcelona our rented silver Opel whizzed easily
along the roads, nudged only slightly by the turbulence of passing
BMWs.
 &HT;    Climbing into the mountains, we entered the Spain of my
imagination, all olive trees, grapevines and rock. Quatretondeta's
terraced almond, olive and cherry groves seduced us as much as
Barcelona had. We felt embraced by the welcome at Hotel Els Frares
and by its blissfully comfortable beds.
 &HT;    Walking among the olive trees, we inhaled air scented by
waist-high rosemary growing wild on the hillsides. We greeted
black-clad grandmothers as they stood by their scrubbed doorsteps
on pristine village streets too narrow for car traffic.
 &HT;    ``Buenos dias,'' we said, exaggerating the Castilian
pronunciation in our enthusiasm. No wonder they smiled in response.
 &HT;    On toward the south to Agua Amarga, a fishing village on the
southern coast. It was as pretty as advertised _ a tumble of low,
white buildings leading down to a quiet beach and the bluest blue
Mediterranean. The trip down the mountain took longer than planned;
plotting the mileage in Maine, I had forgotten to take the
slow-going curves of mountain roads into account.
 &HT;    We were at the edge of our patience by the time we pulled up to
the front door of our hotel, the MiKasa. But a cosseted night there
(it felt more like a private villa than a 20-room hotel) restored
us.
 &HT;    Yet now, as the first of our three scheduled days in Granada
sighed to a close, we began to feel burdened by our planning. The
structure of those lists constricted rather than comforted. We were
tired, of course, suffering from a midtrip weariness that is
signaled by a longing for one's own washer and dryer. It's the time
when I want nothing more than a cup of tea made by steeping real
Darjeeling leaves in water that has reached a full rolling boil.
 &HT;    Walking slowly toward a barely 8 p.m. dinner, Bob said, ``I wish
we could have more time in Barcelona,'' just as I said, ``I cannot
remember why we are going to Cordoba.'' We stopped and stared at
each other.
 &HT;    Over lamb chops and garlic grilled chicken at the Restaurante
Gallio on the Plaza Bib-Rambla, we dithered.
 &HT;    ``We'd have to cancel all those reservations.'' ``Immediately,
right away, now,'' I agreed, checking my watch as if it were
already too late.
 &HT;    ``The Barcelona hotels are bound to be full.'' ``Where would we
stop along the way?'' ``We can't make it back in one day.'' ``The
rental-car people might penalize us for returning the car early.''
 &HT;    This last brought us up short. Unable to change our plans
because Avis might punish us?
 &HT;    A shiver of excitement made us grin. We would be on the lam,
playing hooky, leaving at intermission, absent without leave. We
toasted each other with what was left in the bottle.
 &HT;    In the end, it was almost easy. Phrasebook in hand, we called in
our cancellations. We were sorry, sorry, sorry, but, ``si, por
favor, quiero cancelar. Muchas gracias.''
 &HT;    That done, we fretted when our Barcelona hotel proved full for
the new nights we wanted. I flapped the sheaf of canceled hotels at
Bob. ``We've done it now.'' I didn't quite wail, but I was fierce,
as if my sudden loss of mooring were his fault rather than our
shared adventure.
 &HT;    Ultimately, we handed the search over to Barcelona's hotel
reservation bureau, which found what we wanted within an hour.
Amazing.
 &HT;    The next day, we toured the Alhambra with rediscovered
enthusiasm. The day after that we tried two new tapas bars and
succeeded in staying awake for an 8:30 dinner.
 &HT;    On the fourth day, silly with excitement, we pointed our silver
Opel north toward four unencumbered, ribbon-tied days in Barcelona.
 &HT;    And the unplanned night on the road? We consulted the map. What
about visiting Elche, which claims to have the largest palm grove
in Europe? In the land of Quixote we had learned to follow our
hearts, not a schedule. 
 &HT;    ----- &HT;    (Aurelia C. Scott lives in Portland, Me.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Aurelia C. Scott 
