<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: REPOSITIONING CRUISES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    The days of the great ocean liners may be long gone, but there
are dozens of other ships making trans-Atlantic crossings that
don't reach the headlines. They're on repositioning cruises, and
major cruise lines such as Celebrity Cruises, Holland America Line
and Seabourn Cruise Line offer them every year.
 &HT;    Cruises lines that sell Mediterranean cruises in summer
typically offer Caribbean cruises in winter. To get their ships
from the Mediterranean to the Caribbean, they take them across the
Atlantic in September or October. In spring, come March and April,
they take them back. The ships are literally repositioned twice a
year, hence the name.
 &HT;    From the Mediterranean, these voyages tend to begin in Greece,
Italy or Spain, sometimes stopping in the Canary Islands before
ending up in the Caribbean. But these itineraries change as well.
Some ships may include stops in Morocco or the Cape Verde Islands
and may end in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., or even New York.
 &HT;    Because each cruise typically has a few ports of call at the
beginning and end of each voyage, the length of a trip is usually
10 to 14 days. Within the business, they're known as ``blue water''
cruises, because the ships may spend a week or more on the open
ocean.
 &HT;    ``They attract well-traveled people who've already been to many
ports,'' Anne Scully explains. Scully, a certified travel counselor
and a vice president at McCabe Bremer Travel (1491 Chain Bridge
Road, Mclean, VA 22101; 800-747-84011; www.mccabebremer.com), adds,
``They get the ship at its best and get to play on it for five or
nine days. It's really a crossing, not a cruise. You get to read a
book from beginning to end.''
 &HT;    Scully sells many such cruises and says the major difference is
that ``on a traditional cruise, you're trying to keep up with the
shore excursions and ports. On a repositioning cruise, you keep up
with your own schedule.''
 &HT;    Traditionally, these cruises offer some of the best values in
the business. They're harder to fill because they're longer and
they occur in shoulder season. That means empty cabins that are
routinely discounted.
 &HT;    Scully speculates that ``people are afraid of them because of
open ocean. But these are big ships with stabilizers. Rogue waves
and rough water do occur, but the QE2, for example, regularly sails
trans-Atlantic from April to December.''
 &HT;    Repositioning cruises have traditionally afforded a prime
opportunity to sample luxury ships at middle-of-the-road prices.
Scully maintains that by shopping carefully, the seagoing public
can get a six-star ship for the price of a three- or four-star
vessel.
 &HT;    ``My rule of thumb is to go for the least expensive cabin on the
best ship,'' Sculley says.
 &HT;    Here's a sample of repositioning cruises this fall. Unless
noted, these are list prices, per person, based on double
occupancy, without airfare. A travel agent or cruise-only agent
should be able to find a good discount on these fares.
 &HT;    Celebrity Cruises (1050 Caribbean Way, Miami, FL 33132;
800-437-3111; www.celebrity-cruises.com) has a 12-night sailing on
the 1,950-passenger Millennium that departs Genoa, Italy, on Nov. 3
and then calls at Livorno, Italy; Villefranche, France; Barcelona
and Cadiz, Spain; and finishes in New York City. Prices start at
$3,209.
 &HT;    Holland America Line (300 Elliott Avenue West, Seattle, WA
98119; 800-426-0327; www.hollandamerica.com) offers a nine-night
cruise on the 1,214-passenger Noordam that departs from Lisbon,
Portugal, on Nov. 28 and calls at Ponta Delgada and Horta in the
Azores, Half Moon Cay, Bahamas, and ends in Fort Lauderdale.
Holland America's ``Early Savings Fares'' start at $1,099.
 &HT;    Seabourn Cruise Line (6100 Blue Lagoon Drive, Suite 400, Miami,
FL 33126; 800-929-9391; www.seabourn.com) has a number of ships
that make trans-Atlantic crossings. Among them is the 116-passenger
Seabourn Goddess II, which departs Oct. 30 from Santa Cruz de
Tenerife, Canary Islands, and calls at Porto Grande, Cape Verde
Islands, before ending at Bridgetown, Barbados. Prices start at
$4,840 for the 10-night cruise. 
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
