</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASK THE TRAVEL EXPERT 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: The word AT in parentheses has been used in an e-mail
address instead of the symbol, which cannot be interpreted by many
computer systems at newspapers.)  
 &HT;    
 By WILLIAM T. TOMICKI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;     Q:  I am planning a trip to Tuscany, Italy, this fall and would
like to stay at a very special place. Can you find one for me?
 &HT;     A:  Palazzo Terranova is in Umbria, a 90-minute drive from
Florence. Perched at 1,800 feet overlooking the Tiber Valley, this
eight-room aerie is quite possibly the best and most beautiful
country-house hideaway in all of Italy.
 &HT;    Palazzo Terranova, which was built in the 18th century, has been
restored by Sarah and Johnny Townsend, a dazzling English couple
who have filled the rooms with family heirlooms, rare antiques, the
work of local artisans and laughter.
 &HT;    The Townsends' passion for Umbria and their wish to share their
experiences is apparent from the moment guests check in. Rooms are
spacious and each is named after an opera. There are no minibars
here, no televisions, no gadgetry. Instead, guests find four-poster
beds, great shuttered windows, 18th-century paintings, beamed
ceilings, trompe l'oeil, soft linens and total peace.
 &HT;    The Townsends have created a sweet retreat here _ each salon is
a work of art done in Old Master colors, and the library is crammed
with books affectionately inscribed by grateful guests.
 &HT;    Each day, the Terranova staff prepares delightful breakfasts to
be enjoyed on the fragrant terrace. Dinners celebrate the fresh
bounty of the Umbrian countryside. The wine cellar holds remarkable
Italian and French wines. A pool, three kitchens for culinary
instruction, a vineyard, an orchard and gardens await visitors.
 &HT;    Umbria's ancient treasures _ its churches, villages, trattorias,
wine country and friendly people _ are just minutes away as are
golf, horses, bikes, painting classes and hot-air balloons.
 &HT;    For all this quality, rates start at an astonishingly low $300 a
night, including breakfast. For more information, call
011-39-075-857-0083, e-mail sarah(AT)palazzoterranova.com or visit
www.palazzoterranova.com on the Web.
 &HT;     Q:  My wife and I are planning to take our school-age children
to North Carolina's Outer Banks this summer. We keep hearing about
an outdoor drama that tells the story of Roanoke. Do you have any
information?
 &HT;     A:  ``The Lost Colony,'' America's longest-running outdoor
drama, was written in 1937 by Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright
Paul Green. It was originally intended to run for one season, but
success has propelled it into its 63rd.
 &HT;    ``The Lost Colony'' uses song, dance, drama and special effects
to tell the story of America's first English settlement (1584-1587)
and its eerie and mysterious disappearance. Impressive costumes and
the voices of the prestigious Westminster Choir College add special
touches to the performance.
 &HT;    The drama is staged at the Waterside Theatre, inside historic
Fort Raleigh. Ancient oak trees, laced with Spanish moss, frame the
theatre, and balmy ocean breezes help set the scene.
 &HT;    The production runs Monday through Saturday every summer from
June through August. Tickets range from $8 to $18, and children are
admitted for half-price on Monday nights. For reservations or more
information, call (800) 488-5012.
 &HT;    Another option is to purchase the Roanoke Island Queen's Pass,
(252) 475-1500. The pass, which costs $27 for adults and $14 for
children, includes admission to ``The Lost Colony,'' as well as the
North Carolina Aquarium, the Elizabethan Gardens and the Roanoke
Island Festival Park.
 &HT;    A great place to stay is the Tranquil House Inn on Manteo's
waterfront. Summer rates range from $149 to $189, and reservations
can be made by calling (800) 458-7069. Don't miss dinner at 1587,
located in the inn.
 &HT;     Q:  I am going to be in the Bahamas with a friend later this
year. While she loves nothing more than lying in the sun, I need a
little more stimulation. What else can one do there?
 &HT;     A:  While the Bahamas are typically known for their
sun-drenched beaches, bronzing bodies and exotic beverages, there
are also a number of other activities to keep you busy. For
example, between Sept. 22 to 24, try your luck at the Fall Black
Jack Tournament held at the Princess Casino on Grand Bahama Island.
 &HT;    The North Eleuthera Sailing Regatta will be held Oct. 12 to 15.
Spectators can watch as locally built sloops sail between Harbour
Island and Three-Island Bay, North Eleuthera.
 &HT;    During the second week of November, both visitors and locals can
take part in the 14th Annual Grand Bahama Conchman Triathlon _ a
.5-mile swim, a 20-mile bike ride and a 3.5- mile run.
 &HT;    And if you're still standing after that, why not get a head
start on your Christmas shopping at Nassau/Paradise Island's
Christmas Jollification Festival. Or try out your fishing skills at
the Annual Bahamas Wahoo Championships. Both events will be held in
early November.
 &HT;    For more information on these and other activities in the
Bahamas, visit www.bahamas.com on the Web.
 &HT;     Q:  I have heard rumors about a series of art exhibits
featuring Los Angeles artists at the Bel Age Hotel and was
wondering if you could give me more information.
 &HT;     A:  Throughout the summer, the Wyndham Bel Age Hotel in West
Hollywood is presenting several eclectic art shows under the banner
``Art &AMP; Soul.'' The shows showcase the latest works from three L.A.
artists combined with live acoustic and jazz music.
 &HT;    The works of two artists can still be viewed this summer season
_ Michael Spalt, until Aug. 15, and J.C. Jaress, from Aug. 16 to
Sept. 12.
 &HT;    Each month the Wyndham Bel Age hosts a ``Meet the Artist''
reception in their La Brasserie Restaurant &AMP; Club, which has been
hailed as ``the best jazz room with a view'' by the Los Angeles
Times. These monthly receptions will also feature tantalizing
appetizers, fine wines and champagne.
 &HT;    For more information, please call La Brasserie at (310)
358-7776. For reservations at the Wyndham Bel Age Hotel, call (800)
WYNDHAM.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions to William Tomicki, P.O.
Box 5148, Santa Barbara, Calif. 93150. Although he cannot answer
each query individually, selected questions will be included in his
column. Mr. Tomicki, who logs over 150,000 miles each year, is the
publisher of ENTREE, a travel newsletter. 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 William T. Tomicki 
