r l BC-TAMMY-FAYE-HNS &LR;      07-24 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMY-FAYE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD ACCORDING TO TAMMY FAYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON DICKER  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time has not eroded Tammy Faye's belief in her
ex-husband's innocence, or in the sanctity of mascara.
</P>
<P>
   But the 12 years since the collapse of the PTL ministry run by
Tammy Faye and Jim Bakker have given her new perspective on their
place in tabloid culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened to us is bigger than O.J.,'' she said
during an interview at a Manhattan hotel. ``I think we were the
first of the rag-magazine television, the rag-magazine mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they realized how much people love it and will eat it up
and will buy papers and magazines and watch TV, I think (the media)
went after some others.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief, private interview, Tammy Faye blurted out answers
not always pertinent to the question, but with the same enthusiasm
she employed when the PTL was at its zenith in the 1980s. It
reached more than 20 million people via a 24-hour satellite
network.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Faye has been a publicist's dream in New York, bouncing
through a promotional blitz for ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye,'' a
kitschy documentary about her by Fenton Bailey and Randy Barbato.
</P>
<P>
   The film, narrated by drag queen RuPaul, reinforces Tammy Faye's
status as a camp goddess among gays. Tammy Faye likes to remind the
skeptical that the PTL embraced the gay community despite venomous
criticism from the religious right. She spent Thursday night at a
mostly gay bar in Manhattan's Chelsea district before taking in a
Broadway show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like to be hated by everybody,'' she said.
``I know what it's like to be misunderstood. I know what it's like
to be lied about and watched and criticized. And I know they
understand. I know where they're at, and that's why they love me.
I've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Her small blue eyes misted up behind eyelashes as thick as palm
fronds, thanks to a daily coating of L'Oreal mascara.
</P>
<P>
   Her ensemble was enough to make a discounter speak in tongues:
She bought her low-cut lavender sweater set from Marshall's, her
matching skirt from Ross Dress for Less, and silver pumps with
glass heels from Pic n' Save.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Faye wants to write a book about how to look like a
million for a lot less.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was a bargain-shopper even when she and Bakker were
raking in millions as the first couple of televangelism. Now her
coffers are filled by whatever an occasional congregation can give
as a ``love offering,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Faye recently preached to a women's group in New York and
the love amounted to $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Faye and Jim Bakker parlayed a Christian puppet show in
the 1960s into an evangelical juggernaut in the '70s and '80s.
Mixing Lawrence Welk wholesomeness with Vegas-lounge garishness,
the Bakkers reigned over fire-and-brimstone rivals such as the
Revs. Jerry Falwell and Oral Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the PTL crumbled beneath a wave of scandal. In 1989,
Jim Bakker was convicted of defrauding 116,000 followers out of
$158 million for not delivering on a promise that the PTL would
provide lodging at its theme park and complex to anyone who pledged
$1,000 or more. He served five years in prison. Tammy Faye
maintains that the PTL was in the process of fulfilling its pledges
when Falwell, as part of a conspiracy, swooped in to seize control
of the PTL.
</P>
<P>
   But the story's sizzle came from Bakker's tryst with a PTL
employee named Jessica Hahn, whom the organization reportedly had
paid hundreds of thousands of dollars to keep quiet. Hahn later
whittled out a career as a pinup and personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for Jessica,'' Tammy Faye said. ``She got herself
into something bigger than her. I don't blame Jessica for what
happened. I blame Jim. Jim is a man of God and a leader of a large
Christian organization. If it wasn't Jessica, it could have been
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye'' takes a soft look at its
subject, there is no denying her resilience. A supermarket-tabloid
frenzy didn't get her _ she even invited the Globe to her second
wedding. Drug addiction didn't get her _ a visit to Betty Ford took
care of that. Colon cancer couldn't claim her either _ she's been
disease-free for more than five years.
</P>
<P>
   The imprisonment of her second husband, Roe Messner, on
bankruptcy fraud is now tucked neatly in the past, too. Messner was
serving as Tammy Faye's Guy Friday in New York, and the couple
lives in Charlotte, N.C., near Tammy Faye's daughter, Tammy Sue,
and two grandchildren. Tammy Faye's son, Jamie Bakker, runs a safe
house for the tattooed, pierced and disenfranchised in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A new generation knows Tammy Faye as the mother of the
eye-shadow queen Mimi on ``The Drew Carey Show.'' But this being
the multimedia 21st century, Tammy Faye is striving to be more. She
is selling a bath-products line on tammyfaye.com. She serves as a
spokeswoman for a traveling flea market, and she is planning a
country album.
</P>
<P>
   But Tammy Faye scoffed at the notion that she yearns to make a
splash in the secular world.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is always with the ministry,'' she said. ``I have a
calling, I believe, from God to preach. I'm a good preacher. If I
can't live it, I don't preach it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
