<SLUG> BC-HYDROPONIC-MARIJUANA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE BURNS WAREHOUSE CONTAINING MARIJUANA PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RYAN KIM  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Firefighters battling a three-alarm fire at a
warehouse uncovered a large marijuana-growing operation that may
have started the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found evidence of more than 1,000 young marijuana
plants at the warehouse in the city's Bayview section. The
operation appeared to be a hydroponic nursery, said Inspector
Martin Halloran of the San Francisco police.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an advanced, sophisticated system,'' Halloran said.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran said many of the marijuana plants were burned in the
fire. He would not elaborate on what equipment was recovered from
the site, but typically, hydroponic operations include tiered
planters, water pumps, ultraviolet lamps and fans.
</P>
<P>
   The operation had been going on for at least several months,
Halloran said. He said the tenants of the unit were being sought
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials indicated that the source of the fire, which
erupted Saturday morning, was electrical equipment at the
warehouse. It was unknown if the equipment was connected to the
marijuana operation.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke was first reported coming from the building shortly before
10 a.m. Some 100 firefighters, investigators and paramedics
descended on the two-story commercial warehouse, part of a larger
warehouse district several blocks from the Candlestick Park
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured in the fire, but it caused about $100,000
damage to the building. Halloran did not have an estimate on the
street value of the seized pot plants.
</P>
<P>
   Jin Lee, who owns an electrical contracting company next door,
said he had no idea of the marijuana nursery. Lee, who has operated
at that location for four years, said he was told earlier by an
employee at the warehouse that his company repaired refrigerators
and freezers. Lee said he had no reason to suspect otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really nice people,'' Lee said. ``We didn't have any
conversations, just `hi' and `bye.'''
</P>
<P>
   Halloran said marijuana growers tend to use warehouses because
they do not arouse much suspicion. He said he has seen marijuana
nurseries set up in garages, attics and lofts as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Bayview nursery was the largest marijuana operation he has
seen all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its appears to be a sophisticated operation, but I've seen
larger,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
