<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, July 25:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ Developments in the peace talks
at Camp David. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (With)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS-JERUSALEM (Jerusalem) _ A look at new divisions in
this already divided city. By John Kifner and Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PRISONERS (Ulster) _ Michael Stone, one of Northern
Ireland's most ruthless guerrillas, was released early from prison
on Monday under an accord intended to cement the uneasy peace
process. He is one of about 80 guerrillas who will be freed this
week. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ Members of Indonesia's Parliament
tried to push President Abdurrahman Wahid on Monday to explain why
he had fired two economic ministers. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   NY-WELFARE-WORK (New York) _ In a setback for a centerpiece of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's welfare policy, a federal judge has
continued to bar welfare centers from being converted to job
centers. By Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   VT-SHEEP (East Warren, Vt.) _ The U.S. Department of Agriculture
has announced that because of a potential threat to public health
it plans to kill 400 sheep from three Vermont flocks. Tests on four
sheep from a related flock showed signs of found signs of a family
of fatal disorders that includes mad cow disease. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-FIRE (Denver) _ Hundreds of firefighters struggled against
hot weather and rough terrain Monday as they battled a wildfire
that continued to rage through the nation's largest archaeological
preserve. By Mindy Sink.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-MEDICARE (Washington) _ Senate Democrats are prodding
Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Finance Committee, to
take action on his own proposal to establish prescription drug
benefits under Medicare. They say he is dragging his feet because
of pressure from Senate Republican leaders. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   FBI-INTERNET (Washington) _ On political reaction to the FBI
Internet surveillance plan known as Carnivore, the subject of a
hearing Monday before a House subcommittee. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Austin, Texas) _ On the relationship between the
Bush family and the former defense secretary, Dick Cheney, who is
leading the search for a vice presidential running mate for Gov.
George W. Bush and is himself thought to be a possible candidate
for that post. By Frank Bruni and Eric Schmitt. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONVENTION (Philadelphia) _ Reinventing _ or in some
cases abandoning _ the rituals of past political party gatherings,
the Republican National Convention that begins next week will more
than ever amount to a lavish multi-media spectacle that pushes
controversy to the sidelines in favor of an unabashed celebration
of the goals and vision of the party standard-bearer, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas. By Peter Marks. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   WASH-PA-HOUSE (Seattle) _ A look at the two House districts in
the United States that swing frequently between the Republicans and
the Democrats: Washington state and Pennsylvania. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTIONS-MARKETING (Undated) _ For many, the political
conventions have little to do with politics and much do with
business _ polishing civic and corporate images, making money,
exploiting marketing opportunities and turning what has been an
exercise in democracy into a huge corporate fest. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
