<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS SLEAZE IS HER GUILTY `RHAPSODY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I didn't mean to spend the weekend with ``American Rhapsody,''
much less write anything about it, but here I am, still aglow with
guilty pleasure even though I finished reading the thing hours ago,
at 6:20 a.m., to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   Guilty pleasure is the very best kind. It's been many years
since reading a book made me feel so thrillingly ashamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Rhapsody'' brought me back to preadolescence,
sneaking my mother's copy of ``Peyton Place,'' looking for the
dirty parts. Back then, I was far from certain exactly which were
the dirty parts. It didn't matter. The guilty pleasure came from
knowing I was doing something nasty and that if my mother found
out, she'd whale the stuffing out of me.
</P>
<P>
   Why, at my age, should I feel guilty about reading Joe
Eszterhas's overwrought, overhyped, semifactual, quasifictional
account of our president's lifelong love affair with his willful,
wayward willard? True, the book is one long, dirty part. No
question where the sleaze begins, or where it ends, because it's
pure dirt, start to finish. But that's not why I felt guilty. I've
seen my share of sleaze, including some of the movies Eszterhas has
written (``Basic Instinct,'' ``Showgirls''). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the guilt was triggered by a small internal voice (the
introjected mother?) that, on the rare occasions I put the book
down, kept asking me if I should be doing something more
constructive with my time, reading Proust or helping someone in
need or laboring on behalf of the presidential candidate of my
choice, although there is no choice, really.
</P>
<P>
   The small voice asked: ``Why are you reading this trash?''
</P>
<P>
   And I replied: ``Because it is trash, and it's fun. Why are you
trying to make me feel guilty?''
</P>
<P>
   Only a man who has ingested as many drugs as Eszterhas claims he
has could have written this book. I have tried to imagine the
pitch: ``It's `Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas' crossed with `The
Starr Report' crossed with `Hollywood Babylon.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas, a former writer for Rolling Stone, thinks he
intuitively understands ``the first rock 'n' roll president.''
They're of an age _ they shared a passion for sex and drugs and
rock music. As we've come to know, in Clinton's case the main
passion was, and doubtless is, sex. With Eszterhas it was drugs,
although he was no slouch in the sex department, as he reports in
prurient, yet rueful, detail. Now, though, he's a born-again
monogamist, capable of writing about the president, ``He was using
women's bodies still the way he and we had callously and selfishly
used one another's bodies in the sixties.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``American Rhapsody'' Eszterhas's monumental ego gets aired
almost as often as the presidential penis. The book's title is the
author's homage to himself. One definition of rhapsody is ``exalted
or excessively enthusiastic expression of feeling in speech or
writing.'' Eszterhas's rhapsody is far from exalted but it is
enthusiastic, especially when he's dishing dirt, and when isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   Where did he come up with some of this stuff? Ron and Nancy
Reagan toking up with Alfred and Betsy Bloomingdale? Bob Dylan and
Elizabeth Taylor together? Say it ain't so, Joe. But maybe it is.
As we've seen, so many things that beggar belief have proven true,
and Eszterhas seems to know them all.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there's nothing more satisfying than wallowing in
garbage, and ``American Rhapsody'' is about as good as garbage
gets. Others more qualified than I will judge its literary merits
or lack of it, and maybe even its political and social
implications, if any. All I want to say is that as trash,
``American Rhapsody'' gets four stars and two thumbs up from me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
