<HEADER>
A1310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BENDER-BOS &LR;      07-24 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BENDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIMEE BENDER'S NEW NOVEL HAS ALLURING CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AN INVISIBLE SIGN OF MY OWN 
By Aimee Bender. Doubleday. 246 pp. $22.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gorgeous allure held out by the world of mathematics is not
part of a universe that just anyone can love. It strikes fear in
some hearts, boredom in others, and perhaps only a curious regard
in those of us who take emotional succor from, say, the binomial
theorem. But what most mathophobes don't realize is that math can
organize the cosmos into a bearable place of grace _ where one is
one, three is prime, and zero is an outlaw who changes everything.
</P>
<P>
   As a numerophile, I was enchanted from the start by Aimee
Bender's sui generis novel, but the quirky charms of ``An Invisible
Sign of My Own'' may convince even the most math-reluctant of
readers. With one collection of stories (``The Girl in the
Flammable Skirt'') behind her, Bender has achieved a kind of
underground regard for her warped universe and fiercely exact
prose. Her first novel should widen that appreciation, for she has
taken an achingly idiosyncratic story and rendered it with
eloquence, hilarity, and ominous precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my twentieth birthday, I bought myself an ax.'' Who can
resist a first chapter that begins this way, poised somewhere
between the laconic punch of James M. Cain and the dark humor of S.
J. Perelman? The ax-wielding narrator is Mona Gray, a second-grade
math teacher whose view of the universe is cluttered neither by
sentimentality nor excess. A girl who understood early on that
``there's an equation for the way the wind shifts or an axiom for
the movement of water,'' she has spent her adolescence renouncing
her passions: running, dessert, piano, sex. Anything that presents
itself as wonderful to Mona, she cauterizes from experience. ``To
quit well requires an intuitive sense of beauty,'' she announces
with alacrity. ``You have to feel the moment of turn, right when
desire makes an appearance, here is the instant to be severed,
whack . . ..''
</P>
<P>
   Well, this is immensely sad and funny at once, which is no small
challenge, and it's little wonder our screwball ascetic proves as
charming to her 7-year-olds as she is to us. Recruited at the last
minute to replace a teacher who fled to Paraguay to become a
revolutionary, Mona finds herself facing the most demanding
audience of all: children too young to fake being interested.
Daunted by their honesty, she has them body-bend into eights and
pluses and threes. She institutes a game called Numbers and
Materials, where they search the natural world for perfectly drawn
digits. Their classroom is a microcosm of the greater, scarier
world beyond: where nice teachers can disappear, friends can fail
you, or mothers can die of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The truth of it is that ``An Invisible Sign of My Own'' is full
of suffering and odd menace from its opening pages, but it delivers
the grim reality of its subject with such hard-bitten elegance that
you hardly notice where you are until it's too late. Mona's fine
art of quitting was developed when she was 10, the year her
physician father got sick _ an illness never named but bearing all
the qualities of clinical depression. Deserted on the path of
normal by a father (he, too, a former track star) who refused to
walk it anymore, Mona proves her loyalty by creating her own
version of anhedonia: If the peach tastes good, she will throw it
away; if the turf under her feet makes her feel as though she can
fly, she will stop short. Her excursion into the world of sexual
passion ends when she makes herself sick; having experienced
pleasure, she must cancel it out with an equivalent amount of pain.
</P>
<P>
   We would call much of Mona's behavior _ knocking rituals,
counting, self-abnegation _ obsessive-compulsive disorder, but no
such diagnoses appear in her story, which has the self-contained
and timeless quality of fable. The town has no name; its residents,
with their insular rules and reasons, seem like a citizenry out of
a fairy tale. And delivering this novel as Bender does, from the
inside out, enables her to create an oddly perfect, upside-down
universe _ where bedtime stories feel as real and likely as the
noonday sun, where town eccentrics seem wiser and more trustworthy
than anyone else. Fear is all over the place in ``An Invisible Sign
of My Own''; so, too, are death, illness, spiritual poverty, and
the misfires of a child's efforts to grow up. But all these themes
are effortlessly blended into a tale of addition games and
bittersweet desires, delivered in finely understated dialogue and
prose. The novel is so true to its own internal laws, so stripped
of unnecessary ornament, that I started a little when the word
``quietly'' appeared _ that adverb, so incongruous among a forest
of nouns and verbs, stuck out like a neon sign on an oak tree.
</P>
<P>
   Mona Gray would appreciate the distinction; she is not someone
who messes around with superfluity. Instead she keeps things clean
and starkly metaphorical: 51 is the smallest number ``with no magic
inside of it''; the ax is a perfect 7; elevator doors are
courteous, as they ``accommodate last-minute decisions.'' The world
is less frightening when perceived as an orderly place _ and, given
that messy humans live within it, that's a dream that cannot last.
When Mona's system is disrupted by someone who understands it, a
science teacher who is equally eccentric but less afraid, she has
to choose between right answers and the larger, less rigorous world
of maybes.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Invisible Sign of My Own'' is a charming novel, but I don't
mean that in a diminutive way. It's charming the way a sorcerer's
incantations can charm: full of power and whimsy and other-worldly
flight. Armed with mathematical clarity, Mona is on to her own
power: ``All you really need to do is write 100,000 _ 56,899 on the
board,'' she tells us, ``and people will flee in droves, horrified
by the sight of all those zeroes in the minuend.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the minuend, of course, that makes that sentence so precise
and captivating. Depicting a world that might as well be called
``The Joys and Sorrows of Numbers,'' Aimee Bender has reduced this
novel to pure elixir, and the result is something even Mona Gray,
with all her pain-pleasure stoplights, would have trouble
resisting: beguiling and chilling at once.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of the Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1408EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
