<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-SUMMER-BOS &LR;      07-24 1588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER MOVIES ARE TALKING ABOUT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not as if there's nothing to be said about race in America
in the year 2000. And it's not as if movies aren't saying it, one
way or another. As usual, the divergence between what movies think
they're saying and what they're really saying is instructive.
What's surprising is that ``Shaft'' covers a few more bases than an
update of black cool in the person of Samuel L. Jackson, that the
Farrelly brothers should weigh in with the summer's most trenchant
slant on the subject of race in ``Me, Myself and Irene,'' that
Keenen Ivory Wayans should yank the gross-out market away from the
Farrellys, partly by playing a few race cards in ``Scary Movie,''
and that a documentary called ``American Pimp'' should actually
have found its way to a screen or two in a season traditionally
given to eye candy and costly noise.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly because he has loved the original 1971 ``Shaft'' since
boyhood, John Singleton knew he couldn't remake that blaxploitation
classic, but would have to reinvent it in terms of what's gone down
in the intervening years. A lot has gone down, and not enough has
gone down. Back then, the racial divide was more pronounced. Now
it's more of a shared quagmire, crystallized by the new film's
image of two cops and partners in corruption, one black, the other
white. Richard Roundtree's original Shaft stood outside the white
world. He had to in order to operate in Harlem the way he did.
Roundtree has said in interviews that director Gordon Parks told
him that it was essential that Shaft should occupy his space as if
he owned it. It was a novel idea in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   It's less novel now. Nobody had to tell Jackson to carry himself
as if he were in charge. The new Shaft is a New York City cop,
though the movie quickly makes it apparent that he isn't going to
bring Christian Bale's rich white psychopath to justice by working
within the system. So he drops out for a while, into a Harlem whose
turf is partly controlled by a Dominican drug dealer (played by
Jeffrey Wright, in a performance that would steal the movie away
from anyone less commanding than Jackson). The new film works for a
few reasons, not the least of which is that it's driven by a smart,
gritty script (by Richard Price, Singleton, and Shane Salerno, with
contributions from Jackson). In it, character counts for more than
car chases.
</P>
<P>
   It's also less stylized, more gnarly, more realistic than the
original, with more street feel. Roundtree's Shaft was more
flamboyant. Jackson's Shaft, although as boldly contoured, also has
more shadings. There's been a lot of water under the bridge since
1971 _ and a lot of realistically textured TV cop shows. The new
film builds on them, and owes as much of its street feel to, say,
``NYPD Blue'' and ``Homicide'' as to the original ``Shaft.'' But
one of the smart things Singleton has done is to bond with the
original. He brings Roundtree back as the new Shaft's private-eye
uncle. And if you scan the tables in the Lenox Lounge scene, you
can spot Parks at one of them, repeating the cameo he contributed
to his original film. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A different target &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the biggest difference, and perhaps the film's ultimate
statement about the difference between 1971 and 2000, is the target
audience for each film. The original ``Shaft'' was targeted at
black audiences. The new ``Shaft'' clearly was conceived as a
crossover proposition _ and is, to judge by its box-office take.
Part of what made Shaft Shaft the first time around was those fly
clothes he wore with such authority. They wouldn't fly in 2000 any
more than a classic Afro would. Fashions change. What's interesting
is what they've changed to _ with Jackson's say-so, if not his
insistence. Namely, Armani _ the working uniform of choice for
Hollywood executives under 40, and quite a few over 40.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, a black man seeking justice has it no easier now
than then. But as the last century has taught us, there's a certain
potency and a measure of cultural validation in a big Hollywood
image. African-Americans, whose status was crystallized by Ralph
Ellison when he called his 1952 novel ``Invisible Man,'' have long
been aware that visibility is a building block of respect. That
Jackson, Denzel Washington, Laurence Fishburne, Wesley Snipes, and
other African-American actors now are impressively in command of
their own images is progress. The original ``Shaft'' cannot be
underestimated as a catalyst in black pride. The new ``Shaft'' _
grimmer, more efficient, more clear-eyed about the new shapes of
racism, but no less unequivocal in its determination to portray a
black man fighting the right kind of fight _ continues what the
first ``Shaft'' started. Shaft is still a man of the streets, but
he has come in from the margins.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, who'd have expected those erstwhile gross-out kings,
the Farrelly brothers, to laser in on the source of a lot of our
racial muddle in ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene.'' Their new Jim Carrey
comedy isn't quite as envelope-pushing as we hoped it would be,
but, taking a cue from Ellison, they really tee off on the
inability of whites to see blacks. The liveliest element of ``Me,
Myself &AMP; Irene'' stems from white denial, white inability to see
blacks in terms other than stereotypical. In the film, Carrey's
run-in with the driver of his wedding limo says that although the
latter may be a Boston Mensa Society chapter chairman, with a
stratospheric IQ, we can handle his presence only if he's served up
in the subservient role of a uniformed chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey's sweet-natured dimwit character ends up bruised by the
encounter. After the guy runs off with the wife of the state
trooper played by Carrey, but not before fathering triplets that
Carrey raises as a single dad, we're forced to ask ourselves if the
trooper's subsequent color-blindness is the result of
large-heartedness or obliviousness. The triplets, grown to high
school age (played by Anthony Anderson, Mongo Brownlee, and Jerod
Mixon), steal the movie. Like their biological father, they're
geniuses. Like their adoptive father, they're loving. What gives
them their comic edge is their way of reminding us that we can
handle young black geniuses only if they're served up as street
rappers. There's no word on a new Carrey-Farrelly brothers
collaboration. ``Irene'' isn't doing as well as expected at the box
office. But those triplets will be back, having earned a film of
their own, reminding us of our limited capacity to perceive
African-American ability. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Teen-scream sendup &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The summer's gross-out champ isn't ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene.'' It's
``Scary Movie,'' a comic concoction by Keenen Ivory Wayans, who
directed, and his brothers Marlon and Shawn, who wrote the film and
appear in it. It's a crude but sometimes very funny parody of
teen-scream movies that had begun to parody themselves. Like
Carrey, Wayans was a mainstay of ``In Living Color.'' The fast and
furious envelope-pushing humor of that trail-blazing series
surfaces here. Good thing, because the movie is frankly pretty
rickety. But some of the takeoffs are hilarious. The opening one,
for instance, in which Carmen Electra goofs on the Drew Barrymore
victim sequence from ``Scream,'' but also Cheri Oteri's turn as an
opportunistic TV reporter, shamelessly raking in material so she
can get rich from the pileup of student corpses.
</P>
<P>
   But as with ``In Living Color,'' a good part of the humor plays
the race card in ways that only black humorists could employ in a
day when the knives of political correctness are out. Marlon plays
the shrimpy horror-movie buff and resident pothead. Shawn plays the
buff athlete who likes men and becomes the focus of the film's most
outrageous sight gag, involving a misadventure with a piece of male
anatomy in a restroom stall. Time and again the Wayans brothers
help themselves to dollops of over-the-topness that few white
writers would feel comfortable running by a studio exec. Although
``Scary Movie'' is hit and miss, the hits will encourage you to
overlook a lot of the misses, especially when they up the racial
ante, as they do in a great sight gag that's almost too true to be
funny when cops overreact to the radio call ``White woman in
trouble!''
</P>
<P>
   Given the bull's-eyes scored by Hollywood studio entertainments,
you'd expect the Hughes brothers' documentary, ``American Pimp,''
to be dynamite. But all you can do is sit through it _ as Allen and
Albert Hughes allow the fast-talking pimps to charm and seduce them
out of asking any really tough questions _ and think about the film
that might have been. To hear the pimps tell it, they and the women
they exploit are one big happy family, with never so much as a bad
hair day. You wish that, instead of simply presenting at face value
what every instinct tells you is a lie, the Hugheses had dug in and
done some real investigation. All the pimps are black except one.
The sole white subject operates in Nevada, where prostitution is
legal and there are no police obstacles to his prosperity. The
clear implication is that there is an unspoken complicity involving
the mostly black pimps, the powerless women who work for them, and
the mostly white establishment that allows prostitution to exist in
the shadows for the convenience of a mostly white clientele. But
the Hugheses leave this avenue of inquiry untraveled. Sounds like a
job for Shaft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
