A1316 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FAMILY-DNA-BOS &LR;      07-24 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-DNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA CHALLENGES FAMILY LAW PRINCIPLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ DNA testing, which is transforming criminal
prosecutions and death penalty appeals, is also reshaping reality
in family courts, as the scientific procedure is increasingly used
to determine paternity and to challenge child support orders.
</P>
<P>
   Activists for fathers' rights applaud the testing trend. They
said it will help alleviate an institutional bias in the US legal
system in favor of women, whose word about paternity is usually
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Child-welfare advocates, however, have voiced alarm at the
prospect that even more American families will find themselves
struggling without a father's support. And they fear that children
will be forced, sometimes years into life, to suffer with the news
that the man they called Dad is not that man.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that increased public awareness of the DNA
option has led to a surge in such tests.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Blood Banks, an accrediting
organization, estimates that 250,000 paternity screenings were
conducted in the United States in 1998, the last year for which
final tallies were available.
</P>
<P>
   That amounts to more than triple the number reported a decade
earlier, and officials at testing facilities said the trend line
continues its rapid climb.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the increase is attributable to other factors, from
people settling inheritance disagreements to adoptees searching for
their birth fathers, to parents trying to resolve mix-ups when
babies are thought to have been switched at hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But child-welfare and fathers'groups, often at odds on custody
and support issues, both attribute the bulk of the increase to men
who balk at the demand by a wife, a girlfriend, or a judge to pay
child-rearing expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good example of an area in which technology has simply
moved more quickly than the law,'' said David Westfall, a
specialist in family law at Harvard Law School. ``We have yet to
sort out what that means or what we should do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The root problem is a knotty one: Should the ``best interests of
the child,'' a powerful presumption in family law cases, still
trump biological fact? Or should support cases hinge simply on the
fact of fatherhood, balancing the rights of the man with those of
the child?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think many dads are going to abandon kids who they've
been supporting just because they find out they're not related by
blood,'' said Diana Thompson, executive director of the American
Coalition for Fathers and Children. ``But everyone has a right to
know whether a child is biologically theirs or not, and there
shouldn't be a time limit on that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a society,'' she added, ``now that we've got tests to prove
these things conclusively, we're just going to have to learn to
deal with the truth whenever we learn it and whatever it brings.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent ruling by Maryland's highest court offers a vivid
illustration of how the new technologies are forcing a rethinking
of old issues like child support in almost every state.
</P>
<P>
   The state Court of Appeals held, 4-3, that there is no time
limit on when a man can seek to challenge paternity through DNA
testing. The court also set aside the idea that the ``best
interests of the child'' must be considered in weighing a
determination of paternity.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was based on the efforts by two men to terminate
support payments for children they had acknowledged as their own a
decade ago. They now know better, because of DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases began as narrow financial disputes, but engendered a
debate raising far-reaching questions, such as: How decisive should
biological proof of parenthood be in a time when so many Americans
live in unconventional families?
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland ruling has drawn raves from groups such as
Thompson's, as well as from proponents of conventional families.
They say it both affirms the importance of blood ties and chips
away at institutional discrimination against men in child-custody
and -support cases.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of nontraditional families, however, are troubled by
the decision. They say that particularly at a time when adoption
and foster care are increasingly promoted as positive parenting
options, the judges' acceptance of genetics as the bottom line on
parenthood indicates there is still a lingering social bias against
alternative families.
</P>
<P>
   But the harshest critics of last month's decision are advocates
for children.
</P>
<P>
   They are upset, generally, because the majority held that the
``best-interests-of-the-child'' standard does not apply. And they
worry the result will be a run on DNA testing facilities by men who
want to avoid paying child support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will cause a great deal of disruption . . . and not
only because it will increase the number of children who will lose
their economic support,'' said Joan Entmacher, director of Family
Economic Security at the National Women's Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children will also be hurt when genetic tests disprove
something that was a cornerstone of their identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Robert Bell of Maryland made a similar point in a
scathing dissent: ``It is not inconceivable, and, indeed, quite
probable, that there will be a number of requests for blood and
genetic tests made by men who agreed to paternity'' but are now
``behind in payments or perhaps regretting the initial decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to children's advocates, is not that men
might want to know if they fathered a child. They agree that an
early, definitive finding on paternity may benefit all parties.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the critics say, the problem is the open-ended nature of
the Maryland court's decision, and its holding that the interests
of the child are subordinate to those of the adult seeking the
test.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law gives men 60 days to rescind voluntary
acknowledgement of paternity, after which states set their own time
limits for challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The common practice nationwide has been to allow a maximum of
two years, with some states offering far less. Massachusetts
imposes a limit of two years.
</P>
<P>
   Such limits have resulted in cases like that of Gerald Miscovich
in Pennsylvania, which fathers'-rights groups point to as a prime
example of the unfair treatment of men in American courts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, two years after getting divorced, Miscovich decided to
check his paternity because both he and his ex-wife had blue eyes
but 4-year-old Gerald Jr.'s were brown. That fact made it unlikely
that Miscovich was the biological father, and the DNA test
confirmed as much.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a 500-year-old English common-law doctrine, which holds
that a man is considered the father of children born during a
marriage, a state court nevertheless ordered Miscovich to pay $537
in child support.
</P>
<P>
   Miscovich tried for seven years to reverse the judgment, but
gave up when the US Supreme Court refused to hear his appeal last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, after a state resident received considerable
publicity for being ordered to pay child support despite DNA proof
that he was not the father, the Legislature passed a statute in
1995 allowing courts to modify paternity orders in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Appeals Court ruling in late June was the first test of the
law, and it is expected to reverberate nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Marie Nee, the lawyer for one of the men who brought the
case, said she shares the concern that the ruling will lead to
similar challenges to paternity and the obligations that flow from
it.
</P>
<P>
   She voiced hope that fathers do not view DNA testing simply as
an ``an excuse to get out of their responsibilities . . . and
realize their children have an emotional attachment, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Gelb of New York, who runs one of the most active
paternity consulting and testing businesses in the country, said he
has seen a marked increase in the number of men coming to him for
DNA screenings relating to child support since the tests became
nearly 100 percent accurate in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that in his experience, few of his customers use
their newfound knowledge to try to skirt making payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a moral issue and not a financial one anyway,''
Gelb said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a father's been there a long time, he should remain the
daddy. Whatever he does with the information, though, he has a
right to know if he's the biological father.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1413EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
