<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1317 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-24 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDE PROVIDES STRENGTH, REBIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a matter of no small amount of pride that, more than a
third of her way across America, Mary Wargo has yet to be
``sagged.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sagged, in the vernacular of the cross-country bicyclist,
is to be hoisted aboard a ``support and gear'' truck and driven to
that night's campsite. It would hardly seem a cause for shame,
considering the 81 miles she is averaging every day on a 3,250-mile
ride from Seattle to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think refusing to be sagged is about proving that I'm
stronger than I think I am,'' says Mary, a reference to the inner
challenge as much as the physical one posed by her participation
with 200 or so other cyclists in the Big Ride Across America for
the American Lung Association. She was calling from Minnesota to
report on her progress.
</P>
<P>
   Cycling through strong headwinds between Owatonna and Winona,
Minn., last week is not where Mary Wargo ever expected to find
herself. This time a year ago, she was packing up her Denver
apartment to come home to Wellesley, Mass. to help care for her
65-year-old mother, suddenly stricken with lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words `Mary, Mom has cancer' are ones that will always be
with me,'' she wrote to friends this summer, soliciting the
required $7,000 in pledges, 90 percent of which goes to the lung
association. ``Unfortunately, my time spent taking care of her was
marked by days, not months, as planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Peg Wargo died last August, only six weeks after her lung cancer
was diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to do something as I was, figuratively, dying
myself,'' Mary said. ``I missed her so much and felt so helpless
and alone. The smile on my face was hers and when she died it also
died.''
</P>
<P>
   We treat a parent's death, even a premature one, as part of the
natural order of things, but Mary saw nothing natural about her
mother's loss. ``The last time my mom smoked a cigarette was 20
years ago. Her doctor stated she died from smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary was sad, but she was also angry. She decided to join the
Big Ride to raise awareness about the danger of smoking after
seeing a 13-year-old puffing on a cigarette on his way home from
the Wellesley Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   At 31, she was in fine physical shape, but her idea of exercise
leaned more toward walking the family's aged mutt, Mickey, around
the block than a grueling cross-country cycling trip. That turned
out to be part of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom taught me I could do anything I set my mind to. I
wanted to prove she was right,'' says Mary, who now rises at 6 a.m.
and pedals seven or eight hours, burning 6,000 to 9,000 calories a
day. ``I've discovered muscles in places I didn't know I had
them.''
</P>
<P>
   A week out of Seattle, she ran into a woman she had met on June
19, the first day of the 48-day trip. The other rider told Mary she
was surprised but relieved to see her still along.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said I seemed so unhappy the first day, she didn't think
I'd make it,'' Mary said. ``I hadn't realized until she said it how
much what I was feeling inside showed. I feel like I am being
transformed on this trip. It sounds melodramatic, but I am coming
back to life on this bike. When you are grinding every day, pushing
yourself, you feel every muscle and every breath. You are tired but
you feel really alive. The harder my day out here the more I
appreciate everything that's around us. I realize there is no
reason to be angry or sad, that it is a waste of energy and of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling has been reinforced by the company she has keeping.
Some riders are along just for the adventure, but most, like Mary,
have a personal story to share: a father dead of emphysema, a
mother struck down by lung cancer, a sister stricken with
debilitating asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to share your story,'' she says. ``You feel less
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary has encountered the spirit of her mother daily along the
ride. In the mountains of Wyoming, the wheat and sunflower fields
of South Dakota, at water stops and campsites, where local women
arrive carrying homemade pies and cakes so like the ones Peg Wargo
could be counted on to bring to a neighborhood party at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so sad at home, I couldn't get past it,'' she says,
``but I feel my mom is with me out here. Sometimes a butterfly will
stay with me for a long time. I think, `That's her,' and I talk to
her while I ride. I talk to the birds, to the butterflies. I must
look really strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Only to the birds, Mary. The other riders must know just how you
feel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
