<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1330 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WOMEN-BOOKS-BOS &LR;      07-24 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-BOOKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING BETWEEN THE GENDER LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you can't tell a book by its cover, you can tell a book group
by its gender _ and that, in turn, reveals something fundamental
about America's literary interests.
</P>
<P>
   From Oprah's Book Club to the reading groups that gather monthly
in the nation's living rooms, the conversation about modern
fiction, at least, is a discussion by, of, and for women. Indeed,
women have claimed the imagined world as their own in ways that,
while echoed in history, have a distinctly contemporary cast.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in reading groups,which are among the few social
organizations that have not declined in recent years, is 80 percent
female. That, at least, is what Harvard professor Robert Putnam, he
of ``Bowling Alone'' fame, has found in his painstaking new
examination of American social life.
</P>
<P>
   For all the important issues Putnam's larger work raises, that
single statistic demonstrating distaff dominance of book groups
opens some equally interesting questions about gender psychology
and differences, such as why men don't come together to talk about
books.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when evidence points to a blossoming of book groups,
some observers agree it is women who buying, reading, and
discussing books, and especially novels, in America.
</P>
<P>
   In an interesting way, today's majority female literary salon
replicates a role women have played at various points throughout
history.
</P>
<P>
   Literary discussion in revolutionary France revolved around the
salon of Germaine de Stael. A renowned author and coruscating
conversationalist, Madame de Stael thought male talk trite _ and
Napoleon a boor for answering, when asked to name history's
greatest women: ``The one who has made the most children.'' So
sharp (and seditious) were her sallies that Napoleon banished her
from Paris, so intriguing her literary ability that her works later
captivated the erstwhile emperor when he was in exile.
</P>
<P>
   It's a line of heritage that would run through the American
critic and writer Margaret Fuller, who made women's discussion
groups part of the American scene in the 1840s; to expatriate
Gertrude Stein, whose early 20th-century Paris salon drew artists
like Sherwood Anderson, F. Scott Fitzgerald, and Ernest Hemingway;
to caustic critic Dorothy Parker, part of the nucleus of the
Algonquin ``Round Table'' of the 1920s and '30s.
</P>
<P>
   If those trends influenced their day, the disproportionate
female interest in fiction is just as clearly affecting the
literary world today, as publishing houses cater to women's
interest in reading, and talking about, novels.
</P>
<P>
   In fall 1997, Ballantine Books began including a reader's guide
_ some questions to focus the discussion or an interview with the
author _ with some of its paperback fiction.
</P>
<P>
   They became so popular, says Maureen O'Neal, the editorial
director, that the Ballantine Reader's Circle logo dramatically
increased the sale of books. Other publishers quickly followed
suit.
</P>
<P>
   The novels chosen for the program are aimed squarely at female
readers, says O'Neal, who describes the typical selection this way:
``It is not too dark, it has great female characters, it is not
going to be a thriller or a mystery. It is more about relationships
and the emotional lives of women.''
</P>
<P>
   The desire to discuss relationships and emotions and to relate
to a novel's protagonist marks a fundamental difference separating
male and female readers, others say.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it shouldn't be a surprise that women are apparently
much more willing to engage in what Coleridge called ``the willing
suspension of disbelief'' necessary to read fiction intelligently.
</P>
<P>
   To discuss an emotionally complex novel is to reveal a part of
yourself, to open to others a part of one's inner being, and that's
something women are more willing to do than men.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the intuitive sense of several psychologists,
who emphasize they are speculating.
</P>
<P>
   ``A novel is like an inkblot, a Rorschach test: The way you
respond will reveal something about you, and that may be
threatening for men in groups because masculinity is a front they
have to keep up,'' says Shari Turner, a clinical psychologist,
Boston University professor, and 25-year-member of an women's
Beacon Hill book club. ``Books trigger an emotional response and
women are much more able to talk about emotional issues than men.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sargent, a Boston-area psychologist, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking about your reaction to and thoughts about a book is a
kind of sharing that is sometimes a bit more comfortable for
women,'' Sargent says.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly that's the perspective from several Boston area book
groups. Sara Butterfield, member of Norwell/Scituate women's book
group, thinks women's greater taste for fiction speaks to gender
difference reinforced by life roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think men have a more difficult time putting themselves
outside of their realm and into a character's position and dealing
with that on an emotional level,'' says Butterfield. ``I think
women think more in terms of emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly in our therapeutic age, book-group discussions seem to
wander with some regularity from the printed page to a discussion
full of real-life antecedents, and thus are fraught with greater
personal meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Book groups are not just about reading the book,'' says Kathy
Lehan, member of an 8-year-old women's group that has migrated with
its members from Boston to the suburbs. ``It seems to me that book
groups are about relating yourself to a character, and that in turn
brings out problems you have faced in the past, problems you face
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, to be sure, not everyone considers book-group discussion
the acme of analytic activity; the same extrapolation from
literature to life that attracts some women repels others, who say
comparing an author's imagined world to a reader's real life tends
to blur the fictive purpose of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kaffeklatsch with a college education,'' sniffs one
literary type. She said she recently suffered through a discussion
that condemned a novel because the protagonist treated his wife
callously. ``There are reasons to be affronted by misogyny but not
because you have trained your husband and sons not to act that way,
so the author should have trained his characters not to act that
way,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does everyone endorse the idea that a willingness or ability
to relate a character's life or experience to one's own is a
prerequisite to perceptive reading.
</P>
<P>
   Among the skeptics is Harold Bloom, definer and defender of the
Western canon and author, most recently, of ``How to Read and
Why.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I reread `Moby-Dick' every year and don't find much of my
cloistered life in Melville's wonderful wildness,'' Bloom says.
</P>
<P>
   But though he rejects the view that fiction is a prism through
which we analyze our own lives, Bloom, a professor of humanities at
Yale University, agrees that women are more eager and acute fiction
readers than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many, many years now,'' Bloom says, ``the majority of my
best students _ that is to say, the most sensitive and brilliant
and dedicated readers _ have been women. I would say two-thirds,
perhaps 70 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bloom's leviathan example aside, book-group favorites
tend to be novels that allow some sort of psychological analysis
and identification, such as ``The Book of Ruth,'' ``The Liars'
Club,'' ``The God of Small Things,'' ``Stones from the River,''
``Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood,'' ``She's Come Undone,''
``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' ``Bridget Jones's Diary,'' and ``Charming
Billy.'' Virginia Woolf's ``Mrs. Dalloway'' and Michael
Cunningham's ``The Hours'' are a favorite pairing.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly it is hard to quarrel with the assertion that
women as a group seem to be more interested in discussing emotions
and relationships than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think that men get together to talk about
intimate things, do they?'' Lehan says.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt some do, but it also seems fair to say that to stay
afloat in the daily flow of male conversation is to spend a
mind-numbing amount of time discussing professional sports
(physical struggle) or politics (metaphorical struggle) or golf
(obsession?), away from the emotional conflict or psychological
issues at the core of most satisfying fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Further, when it comes to men, genre may follow gender.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, books like ``The Perfect Storm,''
``Into Thin Air,'' ``The Greatest Generation,'' or ``The
Endurance,'' about the travails of polar explorer Ernest Shackleton
seem to have had particular appeal to the average male reader.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from marveling at the fury of nature, the folly of man, or
the destiny of character, those kinds of books do not necessarily
lend themselves to enlightening analysis.
</P>
<P>
   But before members of one gender grow too smug, or members of
the other become too defensive, it is worthwhile to consider
Sargent's experience with discussion groups.
</P>
<P>
   More than decade ago, the psychologist and some women friends
started a professional group to talk about career and family
issues.
</P>
<P>
   And their husbands? They met as a result of their wives'
organization _ and promptly formed a book group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Scot Lehigh is the Boston Globe Focus writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
