<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT BREAKTHROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The ``suitcase move'' is so much a part of
Israeli diplomatic history that you can imagine courses in it for
fledgling foreign service officers.
</P>
<P>
   The wrinkle here last week was that President Clinton was the
one to make the move, ordering his bags packed, a motorcade
assembled in front of his lodge at Camp David, even putting out a
statement that the Middle East summit had ended without an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis certainly understood the gambit's seriousness; they
were doing the suitcase move themselves, which above all means
letting it be seen you're literally preparing to leave.
</P>
<P>
   But according to American brokers here, the ``hey, wait a
minute,'' counter-gambit came from the people who set the endgames
in motion by not having a proportionate response to a historic as
well as generous Israeli set of ideas about Jerusalem _ the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat did not have a
proportionate response to Clinton's ideas about how the two sides
might negotiate about the city.
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat did decide that it was far better to stay here than
return home to deal with the consequences _ worsening tensions and
strife, combined with the evaporation of hope that a viable
Palestinian state is possible.
</P>
<P>
   In non-diplomatic terms, Jerusalem _ the third rail of Middle
East religion/politics _ has been touched for the first time by the
parties involved and it has not been fatal.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to understand that until this summit, no Israeli
nor Palestinian official had ever negotiated about the city, whose
Arab, eastern sector was occupied by the Israelis 33 years ago.
This ``taboo'' is similar to two shattered by Israel under Yitzhak
Rabin and Arafat seven years ago _ the acceptance of the concept of
exchanging occupied land for real peace and the acceptance of the
concept that there was going to be a Palestinian nation on that
land.
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to the current summit, the two sides made
considerable progress on the remaining, so-called final status
issues: borders, water and other infrastructure resources, even the
return of Palestinians displaced by the conflict that followed
Israel's birth 52 years ago to Israel itself and to the envisaged,
Palestinian nation. But beyond exchanging boilerplate, what the
diplomats call declaratory positions, about East Jerusalem (as in,
``It's ours''), they never negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have, which at least implies a willingness to go beyond
boilerplate _ in effect to shift gears on the S word, moving from a
shouting match about ``sovereignty'' to concepts that really mean
``sharing'' administration of an area with about a quarter-million
Palestinians living in it.
</P>
<P>
   Barak made the dramatic gesture, confirmed by the so-called
bridging refinements quickly suggested by Clinton. But Arafat
balked at a similarly creative response, which is why first Barak
and then Clinton began to believe that there was no point in
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   The analogy is imperfect, but it exists between the positions of
Arafat and the late Hafez al-Assad of Syria five months ago. Assad
looked real peace in the face in Geneva _ the real thing, land in
exchange for it and then acceptance of Israel _ and blinked before
he went home to his economic basket case of a country to die.
</P>
<P>
   Given all that Barak has done with his extraordinary election
mandate, it is still not clear that Arafat is fully prepared to end
the dispute, which has to mean an end to claims.
</P>
<P>
   What the summit was really about up until the dramatic events
early Thursday morning was taking a long look at the detailed
meaning of failure (unilateral declarations, annexations, economic
deprivation, extreme tensions and even violence) in order to
establish the case that however wrenching the adjustments required
by peace, they are preferable. That look, what all sides have come
to call peering into the abyss, has held the final status talks
together for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage to Clinton's journey to the eight-nation summit in
Japan is that it can give Arafat time to understand better what
failure would mean in terms of what has been achieved just since
March _ a loss of the chance at all but about six percent of the
West Bank; a loss of any right or economic ability of longtime
refugees and their families to return; no chance at anything better
than the status quo in Jerusalem; little change of significant
economic aid from the West, much less the Americans; and perhaps,
most ominous of all, a gradual erosion if not collapse of US
goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   All this, as well as an American effort at mobilizing Arab,
Western, and US congressional assistance, is what is on the line,
in return for mature and creative discussion about East Jerusalem,
where the reality on the ground is already not what the negotiating
positions imply.
</P>
<P>
   Phase I of the summit rejected failure and broke the last taboo.
From this Americans are justified in inferring that settlement is
indeed possible and thus in insisting on it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
