<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1333 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-WGBH-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-ART     07-24 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WGBH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... he says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New PBS president Pat Mitchell acknowledges that WGBH has ``a
substantial amount of the real estate'' on PBS, which she
attributes to both ``a longtime buildup there of the best talent''
and to the unique structure of PBS, which relies heavily on member
stations as program suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, when there wasn't so much money to go
around, 'GBH built this strong unit of filmmakers and producers
that just did really quality work,'' says Mitchell. That remains
true, in her view. ``If you were naming the top producers in almost
any field,'' she says, it would have to include McGhee; Apsell;
Margaret Drain, executive producer of ``The American Experience'';
and David Fanning, executive producer of ``Frontline.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at some other PBS stations concur. ``The WGBH logo is
on some of our finest prime-time programs,'' says Barbara Goen,
senior vice president of KCET-TV in Los Angeles. ``WGBH embodies
quality, and stands for all the real significant values of PBS.''
Adds Allen Harmon, general manager of WBSE-TV in Duluth: ``They
have succeeded in striking the always delicate balance between
providing information and education, and producing entertaining
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, WGBH's dominance could be in for a challenge. Many
local stations are hoping Mitchell will follow through on her plan
to give more stations a crack at producing programs and to ``look a
little more diverse.'' Goen, of KCET, says stations ``would love to
see an increase in the number of producing stations.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Mitchell is moving to appoint regional programming
executives in Miami, Los Angeles, and the Midwest to help PBS
stations give documentaries more of a local voice. Since
documentaries are central to WGBH's identity, that could
potentially weaken its grip on the PBS schedule. Mitchell says that
one of her goals is to ``bring more stations into the
producing-station lineup,'' but hastens to add that that ``doesn't
mean you push something from 'GBH off'' the schedule. She says WGBH
executives have agreed to help forge a ``local-national model.''
</P>
<P>
   Becton says he welcomes both the competition and the opportunity
to ``pool resources'' with other PBS stations. WGBH is taking steps
in that direction, he says, with a documentary on the history of
Chicago the ``American Experience'' team is producing with WTTW-TV
in Chicago, and with a series of local election-themed programs
``Frontline'' is producing with 16 PBS stations as part of the
quadrennial series ``The Choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond inspiring envy, there are other ways in which WGBH's
prominence can be a double-edged sword. The station's stature added
to the size of the black eye PBS suffered when WGBH was among
dozens of stations found to have swapped donor lists with political
groups, and also when two appraisers on ``Antiques Roadshow'' were
discovered to have staged an on-air appraisal of a Civil War-era
sword.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, lamenting the lack of a local newscast since WGBH
canceled ``The 10 O'Clock News'' in 1991, argue that local
programming has suffered because of the station's focus on national
production. Becton disputes that, contending that another newscast
is less vital nowadays than the ``analysis and context and depth''
he says are provided by the nightly public-affairs program
``Greater Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   McGhee maintains that local programs (``Greater Boston,''
``Greater Boston Arts,'' ``La Plaza,'' ``Basic Black'') benefit
indirectly from national production because the latter helps pay
general overhead costs at WGBH. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Not always a powerhouse &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The role of programming powerhouse that WGBH now enjoys did not
come easily, according to McGhee, who arrived at the station in
1969. ``Boston was never a favorite child (within PBS) as New York
and Washington were,'' he says. ``So Boston had to develop its own
muscles and resourcefulness.''
</P>
<P>
   With WNET-TV strong in drama and the performing arts and WETA-TV
in Washington, D.C., supplying political programs, the chief
opening WGBH saw for itself was in documentaries. McGhee and others
at the station talked frequently in the early 1970s about the
dearth of public-affairs documentaries on television. ``A lot of
people had proclaimed the documentary dead,'' recalls McGhee.
</P>
<P>
   So the station sought to bring it to life on PBS. In doing so,
McGhee says, two factors were key: the universities in Boston that
supplied a wealth of academic expertise for documentaries on
history and public affairs, and the host of ambitious young
producers, including McGhee, who had cut their teeth on WGBH's
1960s public-affairs show, ``The Advocates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a knit-together group, which allowed us to operate in
a competitive environment,'' he says. ``Maybe we were quicker off
the block in the beginning. We learned how to raise money.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, after a WGBH producer on a visit to London saw the
plethora of science programming on the BBC, WGBH created ``Nova.''
In 1983, the station introduced ``Frontline,'' and five years later
it rolled out ``The American Experience.'' Those programs emanate
almost entirely from WGBH, whereas a show like ``Masterpiece
Theatre'' is coproduced with the BBC or Channel 4 in Britain, and
filmed abroad. But all final editorial control rests with WGBH.
</P>
<P>
   As for children's programming, the continued strength of WGBH
was underscored last week when its newest offering, ``Between the
Lions,'' was named the best children's program by the Television
Critics Association four months after the show went on the air.
</P>
<P>
   If WGBH has laurels aplenty, the station doesn't appear to be
resting on them. Despite current pressures to decentralize
production, chances are PBS will still depend on the Boston station
to keep it competitive in a TV world dominated by ``Survivor'' and
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' _ and the people who work there
seem to know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to figure out what the right thing is for public
television to do,'' says Brigid Sullivan, vice president of
children's programming. ``And then we do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
