<HEADER>
A1335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-WGBH-ART-2TAKES-BO     07-24 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WGBH-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WGBH'S STARRING ROLE IN THE PBS LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Images of ballerinas are flickering across a computer
monitor just 2 feet away from Paula Apsell, but it is words, not
images, that preoccupy the ``Nova'' executive producer as she edits
a documentary on anorexia.
</P>
<P>
   Her pen darting from sentence to sentence as she hunches over a
script in an editing suite at WGBH-TV (Channel 2), Apsell searches
for les mots justes with producer Larkin McPhee: ``Uncommonly
thin'' or ``bony''? ``At risk'' of developing an eating disorder,
or ``in danger''? Amid the semantic hairsplitting, they toss around
names of prospective narrators for the film: Kevin Bacon, Susan
Sarandon, Alfre Woodard, Camryn Manheim.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour of rewriting and rewinding, Apsell is still not
satisfied with the film's prologue. ``We need to work on this,''
she mutters. ``I don't have a great idea, but we will.'' After all,
she says, ``we have a large constituency out there.''
</P>
<P>
   She is speaking of ``Nova,'' the science documentary series, but
Apsell could as well be describing WGBH. The station on Western
Avenue in Allston constitutes one of the paradoxes of Boston
television. Locally, WGBH is often a quiet bystander, overshadowed
by the noisy ratings battles and big-name personalities at the
commercial stations. But nationally, WGBH is a heavyweight whose
call letters are familiar to PBS viewers from Mobile, Ala., to
Duluth, Minn., from Topeka, Kan., to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston station produces or coproduces nearly 35 percent of
PBS's prime-time lineup _ an output rivaled only by WNET-TV in New
York _ and also generates roughly 20 percent of the children's
programs. The advent of the Internet has expanded the station's
reach: More than one-third of all visits to PBS Web sites are for
WGBH programs. As for the numbers that matter most _ ratings _ WGBH
accounts for more than half of PBS's 10 most-watched shows in any
given month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sitting in this city on the most amazing public resource
in the history of television: the producing arm of WGBH, without
which a lot of people might throw out their television sets,'' says
longtime TV activist Peggy Charren, who joined the WGBH board of
trustees in the past year, after championing the station for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone sees 'GBH in as favorable a light. William Hoynes,
an associate professor of sociology at Vassar College and author of
a book on public television, says that WGBH and WNET ``occupy so
much space on the schedule'' that they ``squeeze out other
producers who may be able to produce innovative, challenging
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoynes says that while WGBH deserves credit for ``pioneering the
long-term documentary, and being an important player in maintaining
that style,'' the station's production role means ``they can throw
their weight around on PBS, and local stations find that
frustrating, that some stations are more equal than others.''
</P>
<P>
   WGBH's dual role _ member station and major program supplier _
is unique to public television, and has no parallel within the
world of commercial network television. In that realm, affiliates
are on the receiving, not sending, end of programs from NBC, CBS,
ABC, and Fox, and even the most powerful West Coast production
studios rarely have more than a handful of shows running
simultaneously on one network.
</P>
<P>
   Yet WGBH either produces or coproduces many of the marquee
titles on PBS: ``Nova,'' ``Antiques Roadshow,'' ``The American
Experience,'' ``ExxonMobil Masterpiece Theatre,'' ``Mystery!,''
``Arthur,'' ``Zoom,'' ``Between the Lions,'' ``Frontline,'' ``This
Old House,'' ``Victory Garden,'' ``P.O.V.,'' and ``The New Yankee
Workshop.''
</P>
<P>
   WGBH's hegemony over public television is no accident, but
rather the product of a carefully crafted strategy over the past
two decades to identify gaps in the PBS lineup and fill them. With
shrewd program development, WGBH established a twofold niche for
itself: as a producer of serious documentaries (enabling the
station to ride, and to some extent create, growing public interest
in history and medicine), and as a producer of children's
programs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A new strategy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WGBH president Henry Becton says the station embarked on ``a
deliberate strategy to build up a competence in children's
programming'' a dozen years ago because ``when we looked around the
(PBS) landscape, there hadn't been anything new for quite a
while.'' For the same reason, the station moved full throttle into
documentaries in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we're opportunistic,'' says Peter McGhee, vice
president of national programs and a key architect of the strategy.
``If we see an opportunity, we go after it.'' Over time, that
opportunism paid off in an increasing share of the PBS schedule.
``We had a track record,'' says McGhee. ``We kept the promises we
made, and people came to believe in the promises we made.''
</P>
<P>
   The cachet and clout WGBH enjoys come in handy when the station
is pushing a new show. For instance, when WGBH first proposed an
American version of the BBC's ``Antiques Roadshow,'' PBS executives
said it should be a half-hour afternoon show. ``We said, `No, no,
you don't understand. This is a prime-time show that has to run an
hour,' '' recalls McGee.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH won that argument, and ``Antiques Roadshow'' is now
consistently the top-rated program on PBS, so popular that in May,
four episodes of the show (including a rerun) drew larger audiences
than any other PBS program. Similarly, when WGBH first proposed
``Arthur'' in the mid-1990s, some at PBS balked at the idea of an
animated program rather than the live-action or puppet-based shows
with which PBS's children's fare was identified. WGBH prevailed,
and ``Arthur'' has been the highest-rated children's program on PBS
_ and one of the most popular on television, period.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, none of the WGBH programs on PBS originated with a
request for a new show in a particular genre from PBS. In each
case, according to McGhee, WGBH brought the idea to PBS after
developing it on its own (either original, as with ``Zoom,'' or
derived from an existing show, as with ``Antiques Roadshow''),
after hooking up with a foreign production partner (as with
``Masterpiece Theatre'' and ``Mystery!''), or after acquiring the
show. The station receives around $40 million per year from PBS to
pay the costs of national production, and raises the rest from
outside funders.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH's omnipresence does not always endear it to the other 345
PBS stations, some of which would like a piece of the national
programming action themselves, or a chance to air more local
programs rather than be tied to a WGBH-dominated schedule. ``We
take such a big piece of the pie that it's politically
uncomfortable for PBS,'' admits McGhee.
</P>
<P>
   Hoynes says WGBH ``makes use of a great deal of the resources
within public television, which makes it contradictory.'' Eugene
Williams, general manager of KTWU in Topeka, says that while
``there are a lot of great shows that come out of'' WGBH, there is
``a lot of truth'' to assertions that smaller stations feel there
is too much dominance of the schedule by a handful of large
stations. ``The resources seem to be more available to the stations
in the larger markets for them to go out and secure programming,''
he says. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
