<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1337 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-GIULIANI-BOS &LR;      07-24 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GIULIANI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDY, FROM TWO SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
RUDY! 
An Investigative Biography of Rudolph Giuliani 
By Wayne Barrett. Basic Books. 498 pp. Illustrated. $26. 
 
 
RUDY GIULIANI 
Emperor of the City 
By Andrew Kirtzman. Morrow. 333 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the authors of these two biographies signed their
contracts, it was assumed that their protagonist, Rudy Giuliani,
would by now be well into the nation's hottest Senate race _ the
feisty and famous mayor of New York vs. the first lady of the
United States _ and that their printed revelations might alter the
course of the election.
</P>
<P>
   Best-laid plans, and all that. In May, facing health and marital
crises, Giuliani pulled out of the race; the authors rapidly
rewrote their last chapters; and the publishers moved up the
release dates, fearing that, before too long, the public might lose
interest in the man altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a shame, were that to happen. Giuliani remains one
of the most fascinating figures in politics; the much-touted
revival of New York City under his watch is one of the remarkable
sagas in urban America; and these books offer compelling, if often
conflicting, accounts of both.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Barrett's ``Rudy!'' has made the bigger splash, thanks to
an excerpt in the Village Voice _ for which he has long been chief
political reporter _ revealing that the great crime fighter's
father was a Mafia thug who did time in Sing Sing. It's an amazing
tale, and it says much for Barrett's peerless investigative prowess
that Giuliani has been in the public eye for 20 years _ many of
them in law enforcement, as the number-three man in President
Reagan's Justice Department, then as the US aattorney in Manhattan
_ and yet, till now, this dimension of his background has never
been rumored, much less known.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani's childhood takes up only a couple of chapters in
this tome. The rest amounts to a detailed dissection of his entire
life _ personal and professional _ and a wholesale assault on every
positive claim that comprises his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   As he admits up front, Barrett has a peculiar history with his
subject. The two were friendly in the 1980s, when Giuliani was
prosecuting mobsters and corrupt politicians; Barrett's book about
the scandals of Ed Koch's mayoralty, ``City for Sale,'' portrayed
Giuliani as the unabashed hero. Then, when Giuliani entered
politics and reversed his stands on so many issues, Barrett _ a
deeply moral journalist _ became his chief antagonist.
</P>
<P>
   There is a venom to this book. Rudy's whole life is summed up as
``a mesh of half-truths, double agendas and secrets . . . his
family life a fraud, his achievements a boast, his integrity a
whim, his judgment a memory . . . his beliefs a mirage.'' Barrett
paints Giuliani as a hollow man who has switched principles,
throughout his career, strictly to advance his ambition. The last
chapter _ detailing the backroom deals and cronyism of the man who
once opposed the mildest forms of patronage _ is as disheartening
as anything written about city politics. The accounts of his
brutality against anyone who dares betray him, or steal his
limelight, are full of meaty new morsels.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a way like Rudy himself, Barrett goes too far in his
prosecutorial zeal. He's loath to give Giuliani credit for anything
_ especially for the main source of his acclaim, the slashing of
New York's crime rate. Barrett argues that (a) crime didn't really
drop that much and (b) if it did, Giuliani's predecessor, David
Dinkins, deserves more accolades.
</P>
<P>
   He correctly points out that crime started to come down under
Dinkins, but overlooks that crime fell faster the first year of
Giuliani's reign than in all of Dinkins's years combined. Barrett
argues that crime was falling in cities across the country, with
New York just part of the trend. But 18 months into Giuliani's
first term, crime nationwide was down 1 percent, while in New York
it was down 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's attempt to deconstruct the New York Police
Department's crime statistics, while intriguing, is sometimes
beside the point. For instance, he muses on possible manipulations
in the data on arrests for felonious assaults, but ignores that the
incidence of such assaults fell by more than a third.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the numbers, he understates the fear of crime, once so
prevalent and now nearly evaporated. (As Andrew Kirtzman notes, the
word ``mugging,'' once ``a staple of daily conversation,'' has
fallen ``into disuse.'') One cause of this decline, surely, is
Giuliani's crackdown on ``quality of life'' crimes _ the open-air
drug deals, the aggressive panhandling, the thievery, and public
urinating that made daily life in the city so fatiguing.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologist Fred Siegel, in his book ``The Future Once Happened
Here''(which Kirtzman cites as a model), recounts that in 1993, a
TV interviewer told Dinkins that she had moved out of the city, fed
up with the fear. ``Sorry you left us,'' the then-mayor replied, on
camera. ``Sorrier still that we can't raise your personal income
tax.''
</P>
<P>
   That sums up the indifference that Dinkins conveyed, and
explains much of why Giuliani beat him later that year. Barrett
states Dinkins lost solely because he was black. He paints a tawdry
picture of Giuliani playing the race card in that election, and it
was certainly a factor. But one could as easily argue that, with
his record, Dinkins might have lost by a still larger margin had he
been white (and thus not attracted nearly every black voter and
many white liberals who felt too guilty to boot out the city's
first black mayor).
</P>
<P>
   Barrett cannot bring himself to admit that Giuliani was popular
in his first term. He derides as a media myth the idea that
Giuliani's 1997 reelection victory was a ``landslide,'' noting that
he won 172,000 fewer votes than he had four years earlier. He does
not note that Giuliani defeated his opponent, Ruth Messinger, by a
16-point margin _ a landslide by any definition _ or that one
reason for the low turnout was that many people figured, from
preelection polls, that Giuliani was so far ahead, there was no
point to voting.
</P>
<P>
   Where Barrett gives the mayor too little credit, Kirtzman, in
his book, ``Rudy Giuliani: Emperor of the City,'' gives him too
much. He repeats the fictions _ which Barrett properly debunks _
that Rudy scrubbed graffiti off the subways (that era ended in
1989, four years before he became mayor), got rid of the squeegie
men (Dinkins did that in his final days), and signed the contract
with Disney that revitalized Times Square (ditto).
</P>
<P>
   If journalism is the first draft of history, Kirtzman _ a
political reporter for New York 1, the city's all-news cable
channel _ has written a second draft: a solid condensation of what
the New York media have reported the past six years, plus a few
interesting new details, but little that would alter anyone's
outlook. One notable exception is his account of how Al Sharpton
came to control the protests over the police-killing of Amadou
Diallo _ including an eye-opening explanation of why Diallo's
mother spurned Giuliani's efforts to contact her.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Barrett delivers more startling revelations, Kirtzman
recognizes the city's sorry state, and Dinkins's clueless response,
as the basic context for Giuliani's rise and, at least initially,
his appeal. As late as 1997, even a majority of blacks approved how
he was handling his job; 20 percent of them voted for his
reelection, a stunning figure for any New York Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Kirtzman also treats more seriously the role of the Manhattan
Institute, especially George Kelling's theory of ``broken
windows,'' in shaping Giuliani's views on the links between crime
and public disorder. Barrett dismisses these ideas as ``trendy''
and the mayor's adoption of them as mere opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, both authors view Giuliani as a tragic figure, done
in by his own arrogance and insularity. Kirtzman sees him as a man
of ``strength, resolve and vision'' whose tragedy is that ``he
could have accomplished so much more.'' Barrett sees him as a
pretender who never had a clear idea of what he wanted besides
power. A full picture requires reading both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-WATER-BOS &LR;      07-24 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND FEWER DROPS TO DRINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WATER 
The Fate of Our Most Precious Resource 
By Marq de Villiers. Houghton Mifflin. 288 pp. $26. 
 
 
LIFE'S MATRIX 
A Biography of Water 
By Philip Ball. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. 417 pp. Illustrated. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not hard to understand why humanity, especially in the
developed world, sees water as ubiquitous and eternal. It covers
most of the planet. It has existed for at least 3.8 billion years,
emerging less than a billion years after the planet was formed, and
well before anything resembling people turned up, at most a mere 6
million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And it has imbued humanity like nothing else, physically
sustaining life, but also in the last several thousand years
orienting every aspect of human endeavor and expression, from
science to philosophy to art. How could it not be everywhere and
always?
</P>
<P>
   But the world is running out of water, thanks to humanity
itself. We have devised the technology to pump water at a rate
faster than can be sustained to serve an increasingly urbanized and
industrialized population that is itself growing at a stunning pace
and polluting all the way. There were 3 billion people on the
planet in 1970. There are 6 billion now. There will be more than 9
billion by 2050, when the population is expected to crest.
</P>
<P>
   In very different, equally informative, but ultimately
problematic books, Marq de Villiers and Philip Ball strive to show
how imperiled water has become. Ball takes a more scientific
approach in ``Life's Matrix,'' while de Villiers takes a more
journalistic approach in ``Water.'' But both seek to send roughly
the same message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble with water _ and there is trouble with water _ is
that they're not making any more of it,'' writes de Villiers, a
former editor and publisher of Toronto Life and author of six
books. ``They're not making any less, mind, but no more either.
There is the same amount of water on the planet now as there was in
prehistoric times. People, however, they're making more of _ many
more, far more than is ecologically sensible _ and all those people
are utterly dependent on water for their lives (humans consist
mostly of water), for their livelihoods, their food, and
increasingly, their industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a survey of the global crisis, touching on hot spots
from the plummeting Dead Sea to the expanding Sahara Desert, de
Villiers discusses the concepts behind, history of, and problems
with water, from contamination, to irrigation, to desertification.
He then begins a series of case studies, taking him to such exotic
places as the Tigris and Euphrates rivers in the Middle East and
the Nile River in Ethiopia, Sudan, and Egypt, focusing on the
mounting political tensions over water bringing these regions to
the brink of war. He then offers solutions: developing new water
supplies; conserving existing supplies; curbing population. None is
especially convincing, even to him.
</P>
<P>
   Ball, a consulting editor for Nature and author of three books,
spends much of his time exploring water's physical, chemical, and
biological characteristics, as understood now and through history.
In a jarring shift, he then examines some recent, bizarre theories
scientists have offered on water, like the supposed discovery of
cold fusion in 1989. He does so ostensibly to show that water in
its ubiquity and mystery unfortunately lends itself to such folly,
but he seems more intent on attacking what he considers colloquial
science. In yet another shift, he surveys some of the threats
facing water in a short and less than compelling epilogue, one that
seems almost an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``With future increases in population, industry, and
agriculture, things will get worse,'' Ball writes at the epilogue's
start. ``UNESCO predicts a serious worldwide shortage by around
2020, which is consistent with the figures quoted earlier. The
implications for human health and for political stability are
immense. Determining where the problems arise, considering what
might be done about them, and anticipating what might happen if we
ignore them _ these are issues that lie outside a survey of the
science of water. But it seems fitting, indeed essential, to
conclude water's scientific biography with a coda that looks at the
aspect of water that none of us can ignore: we all need it, yet it
is getting scarcer, per capita, by the day.''
</P>
<P>
   What is most problematic in both books is a fatal presumption
each author makes about his readers _ a presumption of alliance by
de Villiers, and of interest by Ball. De Villiers's sarcasm, even
cynicism, toward the environmentalists, scientists, journalists,
government officials, and others on whom he reports assumes the
reader feels the same way, and so fails to let the reader decide
for himself on the veracity of the reporting. It is an assumption
that undermines de Villiers's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the diverse opinion over the years on climate
change, de Villiers goes so far as to presume an ``us'' _ author
and reader. ``So either the world's scientists, as synchronized as
a school of fish, are darting hither and yon in overreacting to the
latest ambiguous data, or they aren't nearly as unanimous as the
media reports, politicians, and Greens would like us to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of Ball's intent to elevate the subject of water to
artful biography _ sprinkling his narrative with quotes from Kurt
Vonnegut and Gaston Bachelard, for instance, to evoke literary and
philosophical allusion _ he has by and large written a textbook. It
examines in the driest imaginable terms topics from cloud formation
to cell structure. It lacks even the elegance of history of
science, in that much of the discussion of water through the ages
lacks cultural context. Rather, it is generally what luminaries
from Descartes to Da Vinci asserted in a purely conceptual way
about water. And it is not enough to sustain interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A plant's vascular system can be regarded as a bundle of tubes
divided at each juncture into smaller bundles,'' Ball writes.
``These tubes are long cylindrical cells joined end to end, either
open or with sieve-like caps. In contrast to the human
blood-circulation system. . . .'' Such dead prose limits Ball's
readers to devotees of the physical, chemical, and biological
nature of water, or requires them to convert. It is elitism of
sorts _ underscored by his views of scientists who do not, in his
opinion, practice the profession as rigorously as they should _
that is no less undermining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
