<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      07-24 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
!!!! ``Chuck &AMP; Buck'' One of the year's most original and merciful
films. Mike White is unforgettable as geeky Buck, whose life went
on hold during preadolescence, and Paul Weitz neatly covers a few
complex bases as the now-grown Chuck, who isn't thrilled to see
Buck when the latter tracks him down in LA after years of
non-communication. The film is by turns creepy, funny, moving _ and
never predictable. (R) 
 
!! 1/2 ``The In Crowd'' As formulaic, teen-targeted thrillers go,
``The In Crowd'' is entirely harmless and, on occasion, genuinely
amusing. The clothes are terrific, the beach is a gas, and
archetypal characters abound: the evil clique leader, her passive
sidekick, a clueless hunk, and the innocent victim. Tension builds,
barely, and then justice is done. (PG-13) (Joan Anderman) 
 
!! 1/2 ``Loser'' Mena Suvari and Jason Biggs entrench themselves on
the acting A list. They play misfit coeds at a college very much
like NYU in Amy Heckerling's comedy about nice kids trying to
survive their own innocence. In Suvari's case, there's also Greg
Kinnear's exploitative prof; in Biggs's, three slick sleazoid
roommates. Predictable, but it goes down smoothly enough. (PG-13) 
 
!!! ``Set Me Free'' Lea Pool's rich semi-autobiographical
coming-of-age story, set in Montreal, is powered by Karine
Vanasse's luminous performance as a 13-year-old girl trying to
steer a course between a misfit father and an ailing mother. Her
support system consists of a simpatico brother, an understanding
teacher, and a generous girlfriend. (Unrated) 
 
!!! ``Shower'' In Zhang Yang's tender, humane film, a hard-driving
Chinese yuppie backs up a few steps and reconnects with the
important things in life when he's called home to look in on his
ailing father, who runs a bathhouse-cum-community center in
Beijing. The prodigal who didn't realize he was one undergoes a
spiritual cleansing when he's plunged back into a way of life he
thought he had outgrown. (PG-13) 
 
!! ``What Lies Beneath'' Michelle Pfeiffer, Harrison Ford, and
director Robert Zemeckis never really get comfortable. It should
have been a slick screamfest about a wife (Pfeiffer) who sees dead
people, including a woman her geneticist husband (Ford) slept with.
Instead, it plays like a lame Hitchcock spinoff, more cerebral than
primal. (PG-13)
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
