<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NSYNC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'N SYNC REMAINS TRUE TO ITS PURPOSE OF BRINGING JOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear 'N Sync,
</P>
<P>
   I totally understand that you haven't had time to respond to the
letter I wrote after seeing your concert at the Tweeter Center last
summer. I bet you guys have had a super-busy year, what with
selling a record-shattering 2.4 million copies of your new album,
``No Strings Attached,'' its first week out, rehearsing for a major
stadium tour, and deflecting rumors about Justin and Britney
getting engaged.
</P>
<P>
   All your hard work showed on Saturday at Foxboro, and so did the
work of your voice coaches, choreographers, special-effects
designers, fireworks engineer, scenic artists, videographers,
lighting technicians, and Regis Philbin _ who filmed a re-creation
of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' with Lance in the hot seat
answering a question about Pokemon. Some people say your
connect-the-dots pop tunes cater to the lowest common denominator,
but asking the audience to be Lance's last lifeline showed how much
you respect your fans' intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   The glitzy production values paled in comparison to your
deepening sense of symbolism and irony, though. At last year's show
you were airlifted high over the audience during the finale _
innocent young men reaching for the stars. A mere 12 months later,
you descended from the heavens at the very start, like deities
bestowing a visit on the devout. Your canny self-knowledge is a
real thrill. And the song from ``Pinocchio'' that was playing made
us realize that the free-spirited mavericks in 'N Sync have got no
strings to hold them down, either.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the entire show has been retooled to emphasize the
whole amazing idea of 'N Sync instead of just the plain old music
of 'N Sync. Turning the interactive MTV show ``Total Request Live''
into Total 'N Sync Live _ complete with an appearance by VJ Ananda
Lewis and running ticker-tape comments from fans like ``Justin is
such a hottie'' and `` 'N Sync is da bomb'' during ``Tearin' Up My
Heart'' _ reminded us of how popular you guys are. And the cozy
living room set you lounged on during ``Drive Myself Crazy'' was a
dream come true. I bet all the girls have thought about curling up
with one or more of you guys on a sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Your fashion sense is evolving, too. Chris has traded his wacky
dreadlocks for weird makeup, and Justin wore sequin-encrusted
bandanas over his mass of blond curls _ the sight of which on the
night's one scarfless song seemed to strike much of the audience
(if shrieking is any indication) as just as poignant and moving as
the song itself, ``It's Gonna Be Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, telling the audience when to scream seemed a
little beside the point because everyone was screaming the whole
time anyway. And it sort of made you guys seem sort of bossy, which
obviously isn't true because the gentle and beautiful ``I Thought
She Knew'' let us see your vulnerability and true inner sweetness.
Plus, when you journeyed over the crowd on that moving metal
platform during ``This I Promise You'' and poured water that might
have touched your lips from your plastic cups onto our heads . . .
well, baptism is one word that comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   You may be teen idols, but don't let anyone call you false gods.
You guys are nothing if not true to your purpose of bringing joy to
the hearts of girls everywhere. If a little product is moved in the
bargain, so be it. Hire a few more choreographers and effects
designers, and see you next summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOVE, JOAN &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
