<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MOVIES-ESZTERHAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BASIC INSTINCTS OF JOE ESZTERHAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ On yet another perfect day on Point Dume, the
beach-hugging community that Streisand, Dylan, and a host of other
members of the entertainment elite call home, the Eszterhas
admiration society was in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi, Joe was saying, was his all _ his typist, his sounding
board, his moon, his stars, his sun. Make that sunlight, which is
how he describes his wife in the dedication to ``American
Rhapsody,'' the hotly awaited book that mixes fact and fiction to
mess with the reader's memory of Bill Clinton's dalliance with
Monica Lewinsky and 50 years of political history.
</P>
<P>
   Joe in turn, was serious, insightful, certain his 1960s-inspired
take would turn conventional wisdom on its head, Naomi said. He
was, in fact, such a brilliant writer-thinker that she found
herself pitying the president of the United States' penis. Known
throughout the 432-page tome as ``Willard,'' the appendage is as
integral a part of the plot as Linda Tripp or Kenneth Starr. He/it
even merits his/its own chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He so personified him that by the time you get there, you've
heard about what Willard likes and what Willard's done and who he's
done it with,'' said Naomi, due to give birth soon to her and Joe's
fourth son. ``I said to Joe, `This is ridiculous, I'm feeling sorry
for a penis. You've really humanized an inanimate object, for lack
of a better word.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The pet name Willard, allegedly created by the commander in
chief, was supplied by Gennifer Flowers, whose book on her
involvement with Clinton represented just a small part of the
copious research Eszterhas said he did in preparing to write
``American Rhapsody.'' There were scores of other sources, from
biographies of every celebrity he mentions in the book (and there
are plenty) to each of the footnotes in the Starr Report. Then
there was the TV, to which the Hollywood screenwriter behind
``Basic Instinct'' and ``Showgirls'' stayed glued from the start of
the scandal to the conclusion of the impeachment hearings,
sometimes putting in entire days on the couch, often having to be
told by his wife to come to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Legal pads covered with longhand aside, Eszterhas said, he
didn't set out to write a book. He just couldn't put down the
remote, couldn't turn off Geraldo or Larry or any cable channel
where the conversation kept coming back to Clinton and the former
White House intern. Only later, when it was all over, did he
realize he wanted to offer up his take to a nation already
inundated with books by many other participants and observers of
the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Riveted by the drama
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched every day, 24 hours a day, and at times I felt
totally grizzled, red-eyed, obsessed,'' said Eszterhas, who twice
voted for Clinton. ``Just the pure theater of it, the drama, all of
the human elements. This was not a policy-wonk crisis. This was a
psychosexual crisis, and that drama absolutely gripped me.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, released by Knopf last week with an initial print
run of 200,000 hardback copies, is a book that purports to get at a
greater truth by climbing inside the heads of numerous characters,
among them John McCain, George Bush, and Hillary Clinton, whose
made-up monologue is a particular pride of Eszterhas's. In this
world, Ken Starr lusts after Gennifer Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas defended his approach by stressing that the author's
note clearly identifies the chapters based on research (those in
standard typeface and written by the man responsible for movies
such as ``Music Box'') and the ones born in his imagination (those
in boldface and written by what the note describes as his alter
ego, ``the twisted little man inside me'' whose other movies are
drenched in sex). Yet the claim that Democratic political
consultant James Carville is gonzo journalist Hunter Thompson's
``bastard brother'' appears in plain old type. Even Naomi conceded
it can get confusing. For his part, Eszterhas said he enjoyed
playing literary hoaxster a la Mark Twain, a pose enabled by the
book's lack of footnotes or bibliography.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a Hollywood book,'' said Eszterhas, who lamented the
pre-publication focus on his dish about celebrities and Hollywood
insiders. ``It's a book about our values, our society, a
generation's view of itself. . . . I don't presume to speak for the
American people. I speak for people who grew up in the '60s, and I
think I have that absolute right because I grew up in that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas's '60s and early '70s were wild, to put it mildly. A
Hungarian native who grew up in Cleveland, he left newspapering to
become a writer for Rolling Stone. Soon he was living the rock-star
life by proxy: drugs, sex, drugs, sex, drugs. But he outgrew it, he
said, while Clinton still wants to be Mick Jagger cutting a swath
through his groupies. In person and in print, he made clear that he
believed the women in Clinton's past, from Flowers to Lewinsky to
others whose names are not as well known. He also made clear he
felt they were used if not sexually abused by the president.
</P>
<P>
   As Eszterhas, 55, put it, ``I have a theory that most of the men
in my generation, no matter what we ended up being, wanted to be
rock 'n' roll stars. Some of us have outgrown that and we've
matured and realized our own humanity. (Clinton) doesn't seem to
have done that. He seems to be as controlled by his Willard as he
was when he was 12 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Menage a quatre
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some might say that Eszsterhas's use of the Mick Jagger analogy
is throwing stones. Eszterhas himself, after all, is no stranger to
scandal. He starred in one that went something like this: During
the filming of ``Basic Instinct,'' actress Sharon Stone began an
affair with producer Bill MacDonald, who was married to Naomi
MacDonald at the time. Eszterhas, who also has two grown children,
then separated from his wife of 25 years and went on to woo Naomi,
now his sunlight. Stone later dumped the producer.
</P>
<P>
   These days the Eszterhases seem like any couple, albeit one with
a housekeeper to fetch drinks and a nanny to romp with the three
boys and limos to deliver them to events. Filled with oversize art,
bookshelves overflowing with leather-bound scripts and
videocassettes, and pale green furniture with a Native American
motif, the main room of their house says family more than fame.
Photographs of the children are on almost every shelf and wall,
along with mementos of Eszterhas's rock 'n' roll past and one
(unflattering) picture of Stone above a nasty headline.
</P>
<P>
   Still, hints of a Hollywood-size ego were evident. Eszterhas
clearly feels his retelling of oft-told facts was masterful. He
related the reactions of people who called ``American Rhapsody''
genius. He dropped names, mentioning that the enormous bouquet in
the kitchen was from a studio head wishing him well and that editor
Tina Brown had thrown him a party for ``300 of Hollywood's heaviest
people'' to celebrate Talk's excerpt of ``American Rhapsody.'' He
said he expects the Clintons to read his book and that the
president will laugh at parts, be outraged at others.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Eszterhas's mountain-man looks, flowing hair, and full
beard, the bear of a reputation that precedes him was mostly in
hibernation. At times, he even seemed the slightest bit worried
that ``American Rhapsody'' will be held up to ridicule and that his
lifetime love of politics will be lost on readers, that they will
see the book as outrageous rather than outrageously funny at times,
as smutty rather than sexually revealing.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, he said he just wants to return to scriptwriting
and head to Maui with the family after Naomi gives birth next
month. One movie he won't be making, however, is ``American
Rhapsody.'' He said he put all of his creativity into it already,
although he doesn't rule it out for another, perhaps quirkier
screenwriter. But the tale may be too unbelievable for the big
screen, according to the man who had a hand in ``Flashdance,'' in
which a young woman welds steel by day and dances provocatively by
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impossible for (the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal) to
be a script,'' Eszterhas said. ``They would have said, `Nah, it's
not believable. How is it possible the president of the United
States could have this kind of relationship with Monica Lewinsky?'
Some good script doctor would have said, `Rewrite, rewrite,
rewrite.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
