<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' by J. K. Rowling
(Scholastic, $25.95). The fourth installment of the boy wizard's
adventures keeps up the high and charming standard of the series. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Saint'' by Hannah Green (Random House, $25.95). An
intense travel memoir and meditation on a village in southern
France and the fourth-century saint whose relics are there. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I Know Just What You Mean'' by Ellen Goodman and Patricia
O'Brien (Simon and Schuster, $25). Two friends reflect on what
friendship means in women's modern lives. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Circus Fire'' by Stewart O'Nan (Doubleday, $24.95). An
accomplished fiction writer turns his attention to examining the
1944 big-top fire in Hartford that took more than 160 lives and
changed thousands of others. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Obedient Father'' by Akhil Sharma (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $23). A novel about the dark side of politics in India, and
the even darker side of the man at the story's core. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
