<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CONSPIRACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PORTRAIT OF HARRY STEIN, FROM LEFT TO RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HOW I ACCIDENTALLY JOINED THE VAST RIGHT-WING CONSPIRACY 
(And Found Inner Peace) 
By Harry Stein 
Delacorte, 274 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harry Stein used to possess what he calls ``impeccable liberal
credentials.'' Then his first child was born, and he took a turn to
the right. His experience is far from uncommon: Some people call it
``growing up.'' But reading ``How I Accidentally Joined the Vast
Right-Wing Conspiracy (And Found Inner Peace),'' I had the
impression that the author must be the only person in the world who
has ever ever produced a kid and then turned conservative. He
criticizes his contemporaries for being narcissistic, but he's
Exhibit A.
</P>
<P>
   Any review of this book is bound to seem superfluous, since
Stein has done such a swell job of reviewing it himself, devoting a
chapter to imagining the overheated pans his book will get in
liberal publications (`` `A mishmash of bitterness, ideological
gibberish and frenzied self-justification.' _ New York Times'').
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a real review in The New York Times Book Review was
brief but flattering, which must have vexed Stein, whose proudest
moments, apart from the paternal, seem to occur when liberals are
calling him a fascist. He fondly describes the first time someone
flung the F-word at him, when he dared to defend Dan Quayle's
``Murphy Brown Speech.'' He fell back, he writes, ``on a lifetime's
worth of my own moral superiority,'' and asked, quietly, in the
manner of one of his early (liberal) heroes, Joseph Welch, ``That's
how you argue? By calling me names?''
</P>
<P>
   Stein used to write a column called ``Ethics'' for Esquire. To
give the devil his due, as my dear mother would say, he's a funny
writer. He's perceptive and amusing about the excesses of political
correctness in schools and universities, about the media's
left-wing bias, and about moral relativism, among other subjects. I
found his take on feminism (``A movement that, since the
achievement of equality, has poisoned the culture by a relentless
war on nature'') totally nuts, but it got my dander up. So did some
of his humor, so-called, like these lines from a list ``How to Tell
You've Joined the Vast Right-Wing Conspiracy'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Black history month seems to last from February to July.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's going on about how fantastic San Francisco is, and
it suddenly hits you that's the one place on earth you never want
to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein lambastes liberals for intellectual dishonesty. He has his
own collection of cheap tricks. One example: He thinks a voting
test might be a good idea, arguing that most women are too
uninformed and emotional to be trusted with decisions about
government. (Is he joking? I don't think so.) As evidence, he
writes about an unnamed female ``friend'' who is a nice person but
doesn't keep up with the news. To bolster his argument, he provides
a list of 14 schmaltzy movies that were shown during one week on
Lifetime, ``the network for women.'' (Would a list of programs on
ESPN2 suffice to prove that men are too uninformed to vote? Or
would we have to produce the World Wrestling Federation schedule?)
</P>
<P>
   Since his book is an ideological autobiography, I guess it's
fair to review the author. Stein comes across as something of a
jerk. How big a jerk? In a coy attempt to establish his credentials
as a veteran of the sexual revolution, he devotes a chapter to
listing the women he slept with in the 1960s and '70s. His wife,
Priscilla, advised him to drop it. ``Pathetic'' was her word for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Priscilla is responsible for his turn to the right, having
introduced him to ``the universe of kids.'' She had been a liberal
too, but even before they met she had begun to question the wisdom
of her involvement with a group called Women Against Right-Wing
Scum.
</P>
<P>
   When the first of their two children was born, Stein was stunned
by his wife's decision to quit her job and stay at home. Having
assumed that ``babies were basically slightly more animate
shrubs,'' he was surprised by his own response to his daughter (``I
couldn't believe how fascinating this tiny being was''). Before
long he was reading conservative magazines, making new friends
``wiser than most I've left behind.'' These friends had also been
pushed to the right by parenthood and were committed to raising
their kids right, unlike all the liberals who ``by the millions''
have been ``neglecting'' their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I Accidentally Joined the Vast Right-Wing Conspiracy''
appears to be aimed at readers who have made a transition from
liberal to conservative. So why does Stein keep prefacing his
opinions with phrases such as, ``Please don't get me wrong. . . .''
and ``Excuse me, but . . .''? These are not serious apologies,
obviously. But if, as he writes, one of the big advantages of being
a conservative is that you don't have to apologize, why does he
keep apologizing? And who is he apologizing to?
</P>
<P>
   If it's this reader, I accept. Just don't do it again. Please.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
