<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S COOKS AGAINST THE OFFENSIVE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE ADAMS  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ A few years ago former San Francisco 49er
Dana Stubblefield combined eloquence and indulgence when he came to
the aid of a baffled cafeteria worker, who didn't know how to fit a
slab of ribs, three chicken breasts and two fish fillets onto a
single plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all going to the same place,'' he said. ``Pile it on.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are in training camp on the campus of the University
of the Pacific. And as usual, one of the most awesome sights in
camp is not Jerry Rice putting the moves on a rookie cornerback,
but the training table _ tables, really, several of them _ groaning
under the load of food intended to satisfy more than 80 hungry
football players, many in the 280-to-320-pound range.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlike anything most people have seen. Consider the dinner
menu one night this past week. New York steaks, ribs and chicken
breasts cooking on an outdoor grill. Hamburgers and turkey burgers
sizzling on an indoor grill. Nearby, a wok turned out cashew
chicken, stir-fried vegetables and chow mein.
</P>
<P>
   Want more? Try baked potatoes, rice pilaf, fresh vegetables,
potato salad, a green salad bar with 20 items such as peas, beets,
cheese and hard-boiled eggs, along with a selection of fresh fruit,
a deli bar with the fixings for sandwiches _ turkey, ham, roast
beef and cheese, and a pasta bar featuring Alfredo and marina
sauce, along with fresh baked bread sticks. The desert table held
peach cobbler and chocolate cake, each piece topped with a cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Is there no end?
</P>
<P>
   ``I took out the ice cream,'' said Richard Gleason, who runs the
food service operation at the University of the Pacific. ``They
just weren't eating it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh really? No room for a little dish of ice cream after feasting
off the above menu?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gleason subbed frozen yogurt because the players were
avoiding high-fat ice cream. And that's the key to surviving the
training table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to eat as healthy as I can,'' said Dave Fiore, a
295-pound offensive tackle. That means trying to stay away from
foods with a high fat content. At dinner, Fiore had ``a couple
steaks, four or five chicken breasts and lots of vegetables and
rice.''
</P>
<P>
   And here comes what should be the killer for most normal people.
``It's hard not to lose weight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiore, recovering from knee surgery, isn't even taking part in
the two-a-day practices yet. He's rehabbing the knee _ doing lots
of cardiovascular work, weight lifting and special drills.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Deese, another offensive tackle, is taking part in both
daily practices. He lost eight pounds last Wednesday, gained three
back by the next morning, then lost seven pounds Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made him eat and drink,'' coach Steve Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Over-eating usually isn't a problem in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Barnes, the team's strength development coordinator, turns
to the precise language of his craft to explain how these behemoths
manage to gorge and still lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes more caloric expenditure to move 300 pounds from
Point A to Point B,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said Fiore was the biggest eater on the team, yet he
always battles to keep weight on. Barnes said it's a common problem
on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can go overboard,'' he said of the
breakfast, lunch and dinner-time trips to the training table.
``With two-a-day practices they're putting out more calories than
they're taking in.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said the team did insist on a ``well-rounded training
table,'' with a healthy representation of the basic food groups _
foods such as no-fat dairy products, lean cuts of meat, whole wheat
grains and fresh fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Greg Clark, 251 pounds, said he is careful in his food
selection. ``You have to eat the right way,'' he said. ``I stay
away from the pizza, fried chicken and ice cream. You get in
trouble with that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pizza? Yes, that's one of the daily fixtures at lunch. Along
with _ on a recent day _ two entrees, such as Philly cheese steak
and chicken strips, roasted potato wedges, spicy beans and
sausages, fried rice, French fries, broccoli and corn. Plus the
usual hamburger grill, salad bar, pasta bar and desert bar.
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast menu is equally diverse with French toast, Belgium
waffles, western scrambles, biscuits and gravy, grits, oatmeal,
corn beef hash, breakfast burritos, hash browns, fruits and
berries, 10 varieties of cereal, Danish, biscuits, donuts and
yogurt. Gleason also offers eggs made to order. ``Many of them will
order five or six cooked the way they like, and many now will ask
for just the egg whites.''
</P>
<P>
   Gleason said not everyone digs in with gusto. He described Rice
and retired quarterback Steve Young as ``finicky eaters who often
would just have salad and cottage cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   The team doesn't have many of those. In planning the menus,
Gleason figures 1 1/2 to two portions for each person. And that
average is skewered because the training table serves as many
``normal eaters'' _ coaches, office workers, support people,
writers and visitors _ as it does football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating is really important,'' Fiore said. ``That's how you
replenish yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
