   Science and health stories from The New York Times News Service
for Tuesday, July 25.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-LIFE (Undated) _ When Mariner 4 flew by Mars 35 years
ago, experts were surprised and disappointed: the planet appeared
bleak and dead. But now, Mars is suddenly showing new signs of
life. By William J. Broad. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SEALS-SURFERS (Undated) _ The recent birth of an endangered
Hawaiian monk seal on a popular public beach in Kauai, Hawaii, has
pitted conservationists against the organizers of a surfing event.
Biologists fear that the added noise, light and traffic from the
festival will cause the mother to abandon her two-week old pup
before it has weaned, leaving it to die. &UR;  &LR; By Rachel X. Weissman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MADCOW-DEATHS (Undated) _ Deaths from the human form of mad
cow disease appear to be increasing, British health officials said.
But they added that it is still unclear whether the increase is the
start of an epidemic or merely a statistical blip. By Sandra
Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXPLODING-STAR (Undated) _ Astronomers have found a star
that they believe will explode soon, at least in astronomical
terms: in 200 million years. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTERS-LEARN (Undated) _ Scientists programmed a computer
with the basic information to play checkers, and the computer
taught itself how to be a good player. In the future, this same
sort of evolutionary strategy could help spacecraft stay in contact
with Earth. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARTHQUAKES-HOMES (Undated) _ Scientists testing wood frame
houses with earthquake simulators are finding that wood is not as
earthquake resistant as previously thought. Houses built with
stucco did surprisingly well in the tests. By Kenneth Chang. (With
photo NYT4)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPIDER-WEB (Undated) _ Details of a bizarre web-building
process used by a Costa Rican spider. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EVERGLADES-FOREST (Everglades National Park, Fla.) _ Nearly
all the remaining hammocks _ forests of hardwoods rising among
pines, marshes and old shorelines _ once common throughout southern
Florida are now found only in the region's parks and preserves. By
Mark Derr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARTH-WOBBLES (Undated) _ A new theory that the Earth
wobbles because the atmosphere and oceans are pushing it is being
published in the Geophysical Research Letters by a NASA
geophysicist. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH &AMP; FITNESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHILD-VEGETARIANS (Undated) _ More and more children are
becoming vegetarians. Some doctors are wary, but others say it can
be done, though there must be sufficient planning to ensure that
children get proper nutrition. By Mindy Sink. (With photo NYT3)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANOREXIA-GENDER (Undated) _ A 15-year-old boy became a
victim of anorexia nervosa after watching his beloved grandfather
die of a heart attack. By Howard Markel, M.D. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERNET-HYPOCHONDRIAC (Undated) _ The Internet, with its
wealth of health information, can be a hypochondriac's dream or
nightmare. An essay by Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPINAL-INJURY (Undated) _ ``Inside the Halo and Beyond: The
Anatomy of a Recovery,'' by Maxine Kumin, offers a crystal-clear
description, in layman's terms, of spinal cord injuries and the
harrowing methods used to help patients regain the use of their
bodies; also, a look at a similar book by Christopher Reeve. By
Leslie Berger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Leading dietary experts offer
advice on which fats to consume and which to avoid. By Jane E.
Brody.
