   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT _ THURMONT, Md. _ Spot coverage as President
Clinton, who returned from the G8 summit in Okinawa Sunday, rejoins
the final status peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians at
Camp David. There is no official deadline for the talks, which seek
to reconcile some 52 years of enmity and agreement on issues
ranging from a Palestinian state to sovereignty over Jerusalem.
Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Expected to move by 7 p.m. (EDT) on the NYT wire in (i)
International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SUMMIT-ASSESS _ THURMONT, Md. _ After two grinding weeks,
President Clinton's Mideast peace summit at nearby Camp David is
teetering somewhere between triumph and disaster. The outcome rests
on a single question: Can Clinton and his diplomats, working with
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, find a way for the two
adversaries to share the ancient city of Jerusalem? In diplomatic
terms, that translates into an unholy morass of contradictory aims
and immovable intentions. The quest for elegant solutions to
seemingly
</P>
<P>
   intractable political problems, however, is the heart and soul
of statecraft. And when Clinton speaks of his role as an honest
broker in the talks, serving up
</P>
<P>
   proposals for such a solution ? then trying to sell them to the
parties _ is precisely what he means. MAY FOLD IN DAY'S NEWS,
DEPENDING ON EVENTS. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BEREAVED TEL AVIV _ Maybe it's not so unusual that
Israeli Yitzhak Frankenthal would know that it has been exactly
2,206 days since his son Arik was killed by Hamas terrorists. What
may surprise you is the company he keeps. Throughout the Camp David
peace talks, Frankenthal has hosted gatherings among Israelis who
lost family members to war and terror with Palestinians who lost
loved ones to Israeli guns. They are literally under one large tent
in a downtown plaza where Frankenthal leads the Family Forum, a
group of ``bereived'' Israelis and Palestinians showing their
support for the talks and their hope for a peace agreement.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Expected to move by 3 p.m. (ET) on the NYT Wire in both
International and Washington categories.
</P>
