<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-BEREAVED-0725-     07-24 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BEREAVED-0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BEREAVED FOR A SON, ISRAELI FATHER PRESSES FOR PEACE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With MIDEAST SUMMIT-0725.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ You might expect Israeli Yitzhak Frankenthal
to know that it has been exactly 2,206 days since his son, Arik,
was killed by Hamas terrorists. But, you might be surprised by the
company he keeps.
</P>
<P>
   While peace talks have continued at Camp David, Frankenthal has
hosted gatherings that mingle Israelis who lost family members in
war and terror with Palestinians who lost loved ones to Israeli
guns.
</P>
<P>
   They are literally under one tent. It's a large one in a
downtown plaza where Frankenthal leads the Family Forum. The group
of ``bereaved'' Israelis and Palestinians are showing their support
for a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I lost Arik, I had a choice to let my feelings lead me or
let my intelligence lead me. I decided to let my brain lead me,''
Frankenthal says. ``As a father I failed. I brought a child into
the world and he did not live. But, I have four other children and
I do not want it to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, dozens of Palestinians and Israelis met to share
stories. Two young Israelis opposed to the peace talks wandered in.
</P>
<P>
   They entered a polite debate with a Palestinian who spent seven
years in Israeli jails for a bombing. No one died in the bombing
and he now supports the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenthal, heavy set with wavy gray hair topped by a gray
yarmulke, or skull cap, worked his mobile phone, smoked his pipe,
and did a live interview for Israeli television.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped outside to pray by himself, rocking back and forth,
behind the huge generator providing light and air-conditioning to
the tent. A 49-year-old religious Jew and father of a son killed by
Arabs, he is not your usual leftist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has two things that are very touching, convincing to
Israelis. He is religious and his son was killed,'' said peace
talks supporter and tent visitor Meir Meshel. ``Normally, you would
think such a man would want revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the public here slightly in favor of the talks. But,
by local stereotypes anyway, religiously observant Jews tend to be
more opposed to the peace talks than secular Jews. Two religious
political parties dropped out of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's coalition when he departed for Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the most outspoken opponents of any peace deals with
the Palestinians have been the families of terror victims. They say
peace agreements weaken and endanger Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenthal's son Arik was a 19-year-old Israeli soldier in
1994. He was hitchhiking home from a tank training course when he
was abducted on an Israeli road by Hamas gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled and was shot three times in the head. Three of his
captors were later killed, one is in jail and another is missing.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenthal said both he and Arik wanted peace with the Arabs.
But, in the mourning period of his son's death, friends urged
Frankenthal to conclude that Arabs only understood violence.
</P>
<P>
   He rejected their position. Having just sold his business, a
radiation testing company, before Arik's death, he decided to work
full-time for peace.
</P>
<P>
   He founded the family group, which now has 120 Arab and 140
Israeli members and backing from influential Israelis. He is also a
leader of the Meimad political party, a small religious party still
in Barak's government.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Barak called the tent and spoke to Frankenthal,
trying to assure him of the efforts he was making for a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   The tent has support from other peace groups. Passersby can get
bumper stickers and make donations. In the evenings, Frankenthal
helps host town meetings, where people can talk about their lost
loved ones or why they support the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes members of the Israeli parliament show up. They sit
among Palestinian visitors, some of whom used to attack Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenthal says the important thing is that they have made the
transition to peace. The past is not forgotten, he says, it's just
not dwelled upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not forgiving anybody for murdering my son,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He neither forgives or forgets what happened, but wants to focus
on the future between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about reconciliation,'' he says. ``Reconciliation
means I am willing to go forward from where I am and they are
willing to go forward from where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.washingtoninstitute.org (Washington Institute for Near East
Policy)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
