<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, July
25.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT and CULTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW-THEATER (Moscow) _ In a city that takes theater very
seriously, Kama Ginkas was arguably the most successful director of
the season that just ended. He certainly was the busiest. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   COMICS-FILM (Undated) _ Critic's Notebook: On adapting
comic-book superheroes to film. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-TANGLEWOOD (Lenox, Mass.) _ On the performance of Peter
Lieberson's new piece, ``Red Garuda,'' with pianist Peter Serkin
and the Boston Symphony on Sunday at Tanglewood. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   BACH-CHORAL-WORKS (Undated) _ Critic's Notebook: On Bach choral
works as performed at festivals in Vermont and Connecticut. By
James R. Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSELFISH-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ As high tech spreads
outward from Silicon Valley to American society at large and we
spend more and more time in cyberspace, the journalist Paulina
Borsook steps back to look at the digerati and their view of the
world in ``Cyberselfish: A Critical Romp Through the Terribly
Libertarian Culture of High-Tech.'' Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   NEST-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ You know this movie is in trouble
when you find yourself rooting for the killer cockroaches. The
humans in this insufficient melodrama, ``They Nest,'' on USA
Tuesday night, warrant neither sympathy nor interest. Reviewed by
Ron Wertheimer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE and HEALTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-LIFE (Undated) _ When Mariner 4 flew by Mars 35 years
ago, experts were surprised and disappointed: the planet appeared
bleak and dead. But now, Mars is suddenly showing new signs of
life. By William J. Broad. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SEALS-SURFERS (Undated) _ The recent birth of an endangered
Hawaiian monk seal on a popular public beach in Kauai, Hawaii, has
pitted conservationists against the organizers of a surfing event.
Biologists fear that the added noise, light and traffic from the
festival will cause the mother to abandon her two-week old pup
before it has weaned, leaving it to die. &UR;  &LR; By Rachel X. Weissman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MADCOW-DEATHS (Undated) _ Deaths from the human form of mad
cow disease appear to be increasing, British health officials said,
but they added that it is still unclear whether the increase is the
start of an epidemic or merely a statistical blip. By Sandra
Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXPLODING-STAR (Undated) _ Astronomers have found a star
that they believe will explode soon, at least in astronomical
terms: 200 million years. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTERS-LEARN (Undated) _ Scientists programmed a computer
with the basic information to play checkers, and the computer
taught itself how to be a good player. In the future, this same
sort of evolutionary strategy could help spacecraft stay in contact
with Earth. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARTHQUAKES-HOMES (Undated) _ Scientists testing wood frame
houses with earthquake simulators are finding that wood is not as
earthquake resistant as previously thought. Houses built with
stucco did surprisingly well in the tests. By Kenneth Chang. (With
photo NYT4)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPIDER-WEB (Undated) _ Details of a bizarre web-building
process used by a Costa Rican spider. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EVERGLADES-FOREST (Everglades National Park, Fla.) _ Nearly
all the remaining hammocks _ forests of hardwoods rising among
pines, marshes and old shorelines _ once common throughout southern
Florida are now found only in the region's parks and preserves. By
Mark Derr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARTH-WOBBLES (Undated) _ A new theory that the Earth
wobbles because the atmosphere and oceans are pushing it is being
published in the Geophysical Research Letters by a NASA
geophysicist. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHILD-VEGETARIANS (Undated) _ More and more children are
becoming vegetarians. Some doctors are wary, but others say it can
be done, though sufficient planning must be done to ensure children
get proper nutrition. By Mindy Sink. (With photo NYT3)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANOREXIA-GENDER (Undated) _ A 15-year-old boy became a
victim of anorexia nervosa after watching his beloved grandfather
die of a heart attack. By Howard Markel, M.D. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERNET-HYPOCHONDRIAC (Undated) _ The Internet, with its
wealth of health information, can be a hypochondriac's dream or
nightmare. An essay by Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPINAL-INJURY (Undated) _ ``Inside the Halo and Beyond: The
Anatomy of a Recovery,'' by Maxine Kumin, offers a crystal-clear
description, in layman's terms, of spinal cord injuries and the
harrowing methods used to help patients regain the use of their
bodies; also, a look at a similar book by Christopher Reeve. By
Leslie Berger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Leading dietary experts offer
advice on which fats to consume and which to avoid. By Jane E.
Brody.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `s' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-NY-TICKETS (New York) _ The Manhattan district attorney,
Robert Morgenthau, and the New York state attorney general, Eliot
Spitzer, on Monday announced the indictments of more than a dozen
people on ticket-scalping charges involving the Yankees and Mets.
(Byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-CHASS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of the Times column on the
Yankees and Mets, who have virtually identical records. But the
Yankees are in first place in the American League East, while the
Mets are six games back in the National League East. By Murray
Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES (Baltimore) _ Yankees at Baltimore, 7:35 p.m.
EDT. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-COLUMN (St. Andrews, England) _ An On Golf column on Tiger
Woods' overwhelming 8-stroke victory in the British Open. By
Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-COLUMN-TV (Undated) _ An On TV Sports column on weekend
coverage of Tiger Woods' romp through Scotland. By Richard
Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; TOUR-DE-FRANCE (Paris) _ Lance Armstrong celebrated his second
successive Tour de France victory in ways expected _ a glass or two
of Champagne, a party with hundreds of his closest friends and
sponsors _ and unexpected _ with nine other cancer survivors. The
big question Monday was how long his annual celebration will
continue. By Samuel Abt.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RUN-U.S. (Sacramento, Calif.) _ On the U.S. Olympic
track-and-field trials and what looms ahead in Sydney in September.
By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `l' category)
</P>
<P>
   AMERICANA-MALL-FASHION (Undated) _ On the Americana Mall in
Manhasset, NY. By Guy Trebay.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at
888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
