<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: A photo with TV-WGBH is being transmitted to NYT Photo
Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-EXECUTIONS (Paris) _ From a continent bloodied by world
war, Europeans follow more closely _ and deplore more vehemently _
the executions of US convicts than do Americans. By Kevin Cullen.
1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FOX (Mexico City) _ A few months ago she was a
20-year-old law student whose father was making an admirable
challenge to unseat the world's longest-ruling party. Today Ana
Christina Fox stands poised to be Mexico's next first lady now that
her divorced father, Vicente Fox, is about to become Mexico's
president. By Richard Chacon. 1070 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-VOTERS (Gettysburg, Pa.) _ After months of apathy
American voters are starting to pay attention to the presidential
race. And because the two major candidates are indistinguishable to
many voters, interest in the upcoming political conventions could
be significantly higher than in recent elections. By Michael
Kranish. 1150 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-NADER (Washington) _ The small but geographically
diverse political support for Ralph Nader _ up to 9 percentage
points in one poll in California _ has some liberals wondering
whether the longtime consumer advocate will sap strength from their
traditional ally, the Democratic Party. By Glen Johnson. 1200
words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-PHOTOS (Minnetonka, Minn.) _ It's a public-relations
battle bewteen Gore and Bush: Setting up the most effective
campaign photos. By Jill Zuckman. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-DNA (Baltimore) _ A Maryland court has ruled there can be
no time limit on a man denying paternity if DNA tests back him up,
even if the result undermines the standard of the ``best interests
of the child'' rule. States will have to deal with this
development, with potentially immense repercussions for children.
By Adam Pertman. 1450 words.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-BOOKS (Undated) _ Add this to the list of gender
differences: reading. Women are claiming the world of thoughtful
literature as their own in ways that, while echoed in history, have
a distinctly contemporary cast. By Scot Lehigh. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ If the Democratic National Convention
is even remotely reminiscent of the 1968 convention in Chicago, it
could spell as much trouble for Al Gore as it did for then Vice
President Hubert H. Humphrey. By Robert A. Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Thurmont, Md.) _ The ``suitcase move'' is so
much a part of Israeli diplomatic history that you can imagine
courses in it for fledgling foreign service officers. By Thomas
Oliphant.
</P>
<P>
   MCNAMARA-COLUMN (Undated) _ A cross-country bicycle ride
provides strength, rebirth. By Eileen McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE &LR;   &UR; (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Guilty pleasure is the very best kind.
It's been many years since reading a book made me feel so
thrillingly ashamed. By Diane White.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-WGBH (Undated) -- Viewers in Boston might take WGBH for
granted, but not the rest of the country. The TV complex is the
creator of 35 percent of the PBS lineup. By Don Aucoin. (2 takes)
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   TV-BROTHER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ CBS executives and ``Big
Brother'' reel from revelations that a contestant on the reality
program had close ties to a militant leader who has espoused
anti-Semitic views. By Don Aucoin. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-BENDER (Undated) _ The quirky charms of ``An Invisible Sign
of My Own'' may convince even the most math-reluctant of readers.
By Gail Caldwell. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WATER (Undated) _ In very different, equally informative,
but ultimately problematic books, Marq de Villiers and Philip Ball
strive to show how imperiled water has become. By Robert Braile.
1150 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GIULIANI (Undated) _ Rudolph Giuliani remains one of the
most fascinating figures in politics; the much-touted revival of
New York City under his watch is one of the remarkable sagas in
urban America. By Fred Kaplan. 1440 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-CONSPIRACY (Undated) _ Reading ``How I Accidentally Joined
the Vast Right-Wing Conspiracy'' you feel the author must be the
only person who ever ever produced a kid and then turned
conservative. By Diane White.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TIPS (Undated) _ What's hot on the just-published list.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-MOVIES-ESZTERHAS (Undated) _ The screenwriter of ``Basic
Instinct'' and ``showgirls,'' Joe Eszterhas, talks about ``American
Rhapsody,'' his book about Bill Clinton. By Lynda Gorov. 1600
words.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-NSYNC (Boston) _ `N Sync remains true to its purpose of
brining joy. By Joan Anderman. 620 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SUMMER (Undated) _ One of the quiet trends in this
summer's crop of movies is the color-blind approach to casting and
the star power behind it. By Jay Carr. 1640 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-GUIDE (Undated) _ Globe critics review current movies.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-VIDEOS (Undated) _ Good and bad in video films. By Globe
staff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL FINANCE (f)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-COLUMN (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T Broadband and RCN Corp. are
both offering customers bundles of advanced telecommunications
services at prices that easily beat an a la carte approach. By
Bruce Mohl. (2 takes; includes bundling text table.)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-TRAUSCH (Undated) _ So, is the economy slowing down, or
what? And should we care? By Susan Trausch.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-HOOKER (Undated) _ What are the risks of preferred stock
and why not build a portfolio of well-known corporations'
preferreds for income? By Kenneth Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-STOCK-OPTIONS (Undated) _ With employees at everything
from Internet start-ups to blue-chip firms wanting stock options
these days, it was only a matter of time before Web sites emerged
to target this audience. By Dolores Kong. 1350 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
