<HEADER>
A1451 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV30-NY     07-24 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TERMS OF PHILANTHROPY CAN BE LESS THAN ENDEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
Jack Rosenthal, former editor in chief of The New York Times
Magazine, has pinch-hit for the vacationing William Safire since
1982. 
 By JACK ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the first things that struck me when I started as
president of The New York Times Foundation this year is the
language of philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably inevitable. Years as a writer and editor at The
Times had sharpened my eye for jargon, much of it from government
and politics. It took only a few weeks of reading grant
applications from educational, cultural, social, environmental and
even journalistic groups to realize that the foundation world is
equally burdened with limp, lazy usages.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a difference. In grant applications, trite, trendy
or vague terms do more than glaze the reader's eye. They invite
grant denials.
</P>
<P>
   Here is our Word of the Month, from an application for a
learning center:  &UR; empowermation &LR; . Here is our Phrase of the Month,
from an educational reform organization: ``convening stakeholders
to develop action plans to promote standards reform, and initiating
implementation of those plans.'' And here is a collection of trendy
terms, drawn from our experience and that of others on both sides
of the grant-making business:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; accountability &LR; ,  &UR; bench-marking &LR; ,  &UR; challenge &LR; ,  &UR; collaborative &LR; ,
 &UR; constraints &LR; ,  &UR; cutting edge &LR; ,  &UR; extrapolate &LR; ,  &UR; integrate &LR; ,
 &UR; learnings &LR; ,  &UR; leverage &LR; ,  &UR; linkage &LR; ,  &UR; paradigm &LR; ,  &UR; parameter &LR; ,
 &UR; pro-active &LR; ,  &UR; resources &LR; ,  &UR; strategy &LR; ,  &UR; synergy &LR; ,  &UR; targeting &LR; ,
 &UR; time frame &LR; ,  &UR; zero-based &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Many of these terms are objects of comment in a booklet just
published by the Edna McConnell Clark Foundation, ``In Other
Words'' (available while copies last from the foundation, 250 Park
Ave., New York, NY 10177).
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bailin, its president, having heard just about all the
ways people ask for money, sometimes finds himself recoiling from
such terms of beseechment. So he decided to do something about it,
in just the way you'd imagine a foundation executive would. He
commissioned Tony Proscio, a foundation consultant and former
editorial writer, to write a report.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Other Words'' is the result, and in it Proscio performs
skillful verbal archaeology. For instance, he traces the term
 &UR; throughput &LR;  back to industrial engineering before World War II.
``After some years of disciplined life describing the pace and
scope of work on old-fashioned assembly lines,'' he says, the word
became popular in the infant computer industry. ``But the computer
pioneers soon lost control of the word ....  &UR; Throughput &LR;  is now the
universal metaphor for any interval between the moment anything is
put into anything else and the moment it re-emerges, presumably
altered.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the same process of dilution, Proscio notes, that has
afflicted its parent words,  &UR; input &LR;  and  &UR; output &LR;  (as in ``the
family pet recently output on the living-room carpet''). En route
to being emptied of meaning altogether, terms like these become
buzzwords, Proscio says, and ``a policy paper simply isn't serious
if it doesn't include the latest exotic technical term or chic
business school phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuses can be made for some jargon, some of the time. One is
the need for shorthand. Experts in community-development
corporations are surely entitled to say ``CDC'' to one another.
Likewise, it is understandable when people asking for money curry
favor by parroting back language they think foundations like.
Bailin recently instituted a funding category called ``institution
and field building.'' Soon, he says, he got back inquiries
dutifully using the term ``even though I myself wasn't entirely
sure what I meant by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuses aside, by using lame or impenetrable terms,
organizations that serve laudable public purposes do not advance
their chances in the competition for foundation funds _ not when
most jargon and cliches can be avoided with a little effort.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a round of applause to Chubb Insurance Co. for telling
customers: ``In this policy, we use words in their plain English
meaning. Words with special meanings are defined in the part of the
policy where they are used.''
</P>
<P>
   The offending terms cited here are hardly limited to
philanthropy. They befog language in the academy, the Pentagon, the
laboratory, the corporate office. Glazing the eye, they dissolve
into invisibility, discourage reading and defeat comprehension
completely.
</P>
<P>
   SPINICISM
</P>
<P>
   Bill Safire, the regular proprietor of this space, once
generously identified me as the coiner of the term ``spin
doctors,'' referring to faceless campaign aides who work
ceaselessly to impart favorable interpretations to their
candidates' harried pronouncements. Let me offer another neologism
to describe a related attitude that has been evolving over the last
decade and more.
</P>
<P>
   Why, as demonstrated by dismal voter turnout, has the public
become so indifferent to government, politics and public life? The
most likely answers include private preoccupation with affluence
and the excrescent excesses of campaign finance. There's another,
equally plausible possibility: a huge overdose of spin.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of spin, like radiation, are probably cumulative
over a lifetime, and in recent years, people have been subjected to
an ever-rising tide of it. Think of all the speeches written by
ghosts, the talk show appearances rehearsed with consultants, the
TV ads edited down to the last microsecond by creative directors
and imagery and icons devised by professional design teams. What
reality remains?
</P>
<P>
   At some point, one is tempted to think, people will
instinctively recognize how little these media manipulations
resemble the real candidates. And at that point _ a point that may
have already arrived _ people will have learned to discount all the
spin and to react with skepticism, even cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   Hence  &UR; spinicism &LR; . And hence the public's appetite for recent
television inventions like ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother.'' The
settings may be contrived, but paradoxically in our rehearsed
world, the participants' behavior is reassuringly real.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
