<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1459 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-BROTHERSGARCiA25-C     07-24 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BROTHERSGARCiA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nickelodeon breaking ground with three Latino-themed shows
 &HT;    By Kevin Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ When Jeff Valdez pitched a Latino sitcom to
one of the broadcast networks, the meeting didn't last very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told in so many words that they weren't going to do a
show with all Latino people,'' Valdez recalls. ``Well, not even in
so many words. That's what was said.''
</P>
<P>
   Another commercial network, however, bought ``The Brothers
Garcia,'' a coming-of-age story about three Mexican-American
brothers growing up in San Antonio, Texas. Then it never returned
Valdez's follow-up phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `OK, cool,''' he remembers. ``We'll go where people
... are showing the real fabric of America.''
</P>
<P>
   That place is Nickelodeon. Not only will the popular cable
channel for kids air ``The Brothers Garcia,'' which debuted Monday
at 8:30 p.m., but later this year it will also feature two other
Hispanic-themed shows. ``Dora the Explorer'' is a play-along,
animated adventure starring a 7-year-old heroine who lives inside a
computer. The series is scheduled to premiere Aug. 14 on Nick Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``Taina'' will chronicle the life of Taina Morales
(Christina Vidal), a 15-year-old, Jennifer Lopez-like wannabe
balancing her traditional family life with dreams of being a star.
That series is expected to debut Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Three Latino-based shows on one network at the same time is
definitely a television first. And, as Maria Perez-Brown,
``Taina's'' executive producer, notes, each shows a different side
of Latino culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the disadvantages of never having had Latino shows like
this is that the first one out of the box is going to have the
burden of proving Latino-ism'' is viable, says Perez-Brown, a
former lawyer who created ``Gullah Gullah Island,'' Nickelodeon's
popular preschool series. ``But having three shows is going to show
you three different points of view and three different approaches
to what is Latino in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon admits the move was long overdue. ``As we took
inventory of our shows, we thought we were doing a pretty good job
reflecting images of blacks and whites and Asians, but we really
felt we had underrepresented Latino kids,'' said Albie Hecht,
Nickelodeon's president of film and television.
</P>
<P>
   Cyma Zarghami, Nickelodeon's executive vice president and
general manager, points out that kids' lives are vastly different
than they were 20 years ago. The world they live in today is rich
with culture and diversity. And TV shows need to do a better job to
keep pace with those changes.
</P>
<P>
   While broadcast networks often pay weak lip service to beefing
up Latinos' presence on television, such cables,'' says Valdez,
whom the Los Angeles Times once dubbed the ``Ed Sullivan of Latino
talent.'' ``They haven't said, `Hey, let's put everybody in
sombreros.' I've had network executives say those kinds of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the burden on minority shows is immense. When
shows with all-white casts fail, you don't hear panicky network
suits saying, `Well, we won't do one of those shows again.' But
that's what happens with shows that have predominantly black casts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do one Latino show or pilot a year,'' says Valdez. ``And
they go, `See, we told you that wouldn't work. Let's try again in
five years.' Then they'll do six shows of Two Guys, A Girl, A
Pizza; Two Girls and a Bottle of Perrier and A Guy with a Dog and
Two Guys, A Dog and An Order of French Fries.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valdez's ``The Brothers Garcia'' is breaking new television
ground. It's the first English language sitcom with an all-Latino
cast and creative team of writers, directors and producers. From
his witty, now adult perspective, Larry Garcia (Alvin Alvarez)
fondly recalls his attempt as an 11-year-old to fit in with his
older brothers, 13-year-old Carlos (Jeffrey Licon), a stud athlete,
and 12-year-old George (Bobby Gonzalez), a walking encyclopedia.
Emmy-winner John Leguizamo narrates the show as the adult Larry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the Latin Daniel Stern,'' Leguizamo cracks, referring to
the actor's narration role on ABC's ``The Wonder Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon believes The Brothers Garcia should offer all kids a
sense of belonging. After all, timeless tales of kids anxious to
grow up and facing tough challenges should resonate with all
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that although this is about an American Latino family
where the culture is part of the fabric of the show, there are
these universal truths about family and sibling rivalry, so that
when you watch those scenes and those gem moments, you can say,
`Oh, I remember that!,''' Hecht says.
</P>
<P>
   While Leguizamo is known for such gritty fare as ``Summer of
Sam'' and ``Freak,'' his one-man, Emmy-winning HBO stage play, the
versatile performer says the time is right for him to act in
something his kids can watch
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm 34 and have kids, I want to do something (for
them) and be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Leguizamo is thankful ``The Brothers Garcia'' has nothing to
do with his tortured childhood. ``I don't wish my life on
anybody,'' he says. ``That's why I write ... I'm trying to exorcise
demons. Now, this is a great, middle-class, normal Latin family. It
shows kids that, when you're growing up, you have choices. Not
everybody is ghetto, and not everybody is doing drive-bys. It's
nice to see such a normal show and something sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
