<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ANSWERED ON BIRDING IN TRINIDAD AND TOBAGO; THE 600TH
ANNIVERSARY OF CHAUCER'S DEATH; AND TRAVEL IN CENTRAL BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRDING IN TRINIDAD
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I would like to go birding in Trinidad and
Tobago. Can you help us find companies that organize such trips? _
Rachel Schmidt, St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. The West Indian republic of Trinidad and Tobago is becoming
increasingly popular among wildlife enthusiasts, particularly
birders. The country's dense rain forests and mangrove swamps are
teeming with more than 400 species, including scarlet ibises,
toucans, parrots, hummingbirds and yellow orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Nature Expeditions International, in Plantation, Fla., has an
eight-day package for groups of two or more people, with weekly
departures throughout the year. The itinerary includes four nights
at the Asa Wright Nature Center and Lodge, a former coffee
plantation on Trinidad that has been converted into an inn and a
200-acre nature reserve. Birding expeditions to the Caroni Bird
Sanctuary on Trinidad's west coast and visits to waterfalls and
swamps are among the activities. Three days are spent at Blue
Waters Inn on Tobago's Atlantic coast; from there you'll take a day
trip to Little Tobago Island, a seabird breeding area. The price is
$2,390 a person, double occupancy, excluding air fare. Information:
(800) 869-0639.
</P>
<P>
   A similar eight-day package is offered by Caligo Ventures, based
in Armonk, N.Y. Visitors stay at the Asa Wright Lodge and Blue
Waters Inn; on Trinidad, they will take birding trips to Nariva
Swamp and the Caroni Bird Sanctuary; outings on Tobago include
visits to King's Bay, the island's mountainous forests and Little
Tobago Island. Through Dec. 15, the cost is $1,525 a person, double
occupancy, including air fare from Miami or New York; from Dec. 16
to March 31, 2001, the price is $1,895. Information: (800)
426-7781.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to include another bird-watching paradise _ the
Orinoco River delta in northern Venezuela, some 15 miles south of
Trinidad _ Clipper Cruise Lines has an eight-day excursion on the
138-passenger Yorktown Clipper, departing Dec. 29 from Port of
Spain. The itinerary has a naturalist focus and includes birding
expeditions to the Caroni Bird Sanctuary, the Asa Wright reserve
and Little Tobago, as well as visits to sites along the Orinoco
River, including Angel Falls. Depending on the cabin, prices range
from $1,980 to $3,500, double occupancy. Air fare is not included.
Information: (800) 325-0010.
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATING CHAUCER
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm going to England this fall and hope to attend some of the
events associated with the 600th anniversary of Chaucer's death. Do
you have a schedule of events? _ Howard W. Eden, Sacramento
</P>
<P>
   A. Exhibitions, performances, festivals and readings will
commemorate the death in 1400 of the author of ``The Canterbury
Tales.'' In some cases, details have not been made final, so it's
best to check in early September with the organizers of the various
events.
</P>
<P>
   Southwark in London was the starting point for the pilgrims'
60-mile journey to the Canterbury shrine of St. Thomas a Becket in
``The Canterbury Tales,'' so it's fitting that this year's
Southwark Literature Festival, from Oct. 26 to Nov. 3, will feature
Chaucer's work. Readings and discussions are planned, and on Oct.
26, at Southwark Cathedral, George Dyson's cantata ``The Canterbury
Pilgrims'' will be performed, at a time to be announced.
Information: (44-20) 7403 7400.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chaucer's tomb, in the Poets' Corner of Westminster Abbey, will
be the site of a wreath-laying ceremony at 5:30 p.m. on Oct. 25,
with readings from Chaucer's writings. Information: (44-20) 7222
7110. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Canterbury, the two-week Canterbury Festival will open on
Oct. 14 with a procession at 6:30 p.m. of actors playing Chaucer
characters. Throughout the festival, modern Canterbury Tales will
be read by their authors at various places around Canterbury.
Admission is $7.45, at 67 pence to the dollar. Information:
(44-1227) 452 853. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin Starkie, a playwright, actor and director of the Chaucer
Heritage Trust, will present a Chaucer-themed performance of mime,
music and dance on Oct. 22 at 4:30 p.m. at the Chaucer Center at 22
St. Peter's Street in Canterbury. Information: (44-1227) 470 379. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Sept. 30 to Nov. 4, ``Passing Tales'' will be on view at
the Royal Museum and Art Gallery on High Street in Canterbury.
Highlights include a 16th-century portrait of Chaucer and
late-medieval pilgrims' badges. The museum is open 10 a.m. to 5
p.m.; closed Sunday. Admission is free. Information: (44-1227) 452
747.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VISITING GOIAS VELHO IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   Q. On a trip to central Brazil, I'd like to drive to Goias Velho
from Goiania, where I'll be based. What are some of the principal
sights there, and can you name a few hotels, in case I decide to
spend the night? _ Catrina Rubinski, Rochester
</P>
<P>
   A. Goias Velho, about 90 miles northwest of Goiania and 125
miles west of Brasilia, is a former gold-mining town that served as
the state capital of the state of Goias until 1937, when Goiania
became the capital. The town is an architectural gem, with
well-preserved colonial buildings, cobbled streets and lovely
baroque churches like the Igreja de Paula on Praca Zaqueu Alves de
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Among the places worth visiting are the mid-18th century Conde
dos Arcos Palace, 1 Praca Dr. Tasso de Camargo. Visitors can tour
the ornate rooms, in which the original colonial furniture is on
display. Open Tuesday to Saturday from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m; Sunday from
8 a.m. to noon. Entrance is 55 cents. Information: (55-62)
371-1200. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the same block, the Sacred Art Museum in the Igreja da Boa
Norte, contains an 18th-century collection of carved wooden images.
It is open Tuesday through Saturday from 12:30 p.m. to 5 p.m;
Sunday from 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. Entrance is also 55 cents.
Information: (55-62) 321-1207.
</P>
<P>
   The Museu das Bandeiras, in a former government building on
Praca Brasil Caiado, is dedicated to the 18th-century gold rush,
with old mining implements and other exhibits. Hours are Tuesday to
Saturday, noon to 5 p.m.; Sunday, 8 a.m. to 1 p.m.. Admission is 55
cents. Information: (55-62) 371-1087. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Vila Boa Hotel, Avenida Dr. Deusdete Ferreira de Moura, is a
modern, two-story inn with 29 rooms. Doubles are $73 on weekends;
$55 on weekdays. Information: (55-62) 371-1000. The Pousada do Sol,
a 21-room colonial-style inn at 17 Americano do Brasil Street,
offers doubles at $19, including breakfast. Information: (55-62)
371-1717. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
