<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HISPANICPAY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanics have golden opportunity but must buck trends
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hispanic Americans are the fastest growing ethnic group in the
United States. At the same time, a new study finds that Hispanic
workers are disproportionately concentrated in low-wage jobs that
offer few benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The income disparity for Hispanic workers has hardly improved
even during the past eight years of economic prosperity, according
to the study.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many American employers are being forced to
import workers with the skills necessary to program, install and
maintain the equipment used in America's burgeoning high-tech
industries.
</P>
<P>
   There's something amiss when one portion of American society is
heavily underemployed or unemployed while another segment of
society is scouring foreign nations to find workers for good-paying
jobs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers who helped prepare the 230-page report for the
National Conference of La Raza correctly observed that these income
disparities are troubling for the entire nation as Hispanics form a
greater share of the nation's work force.
</P>
<P>
   If the situation is not reversed, government programs funded by
income taxes will be hurt. Social Security and Medicare are two
such programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about being nice to Latino people,'' a labor
researcher told the Washington Post. ``This is about America's
future and our best interests as a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, per capita income for Hispanics was $11,434 compared to
African-Americans at $12,957 and Anglos at $22,952.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed that the median income for Hispanic married
couples with families was $34,826 compared to $54,736 for Anglos
families.
</P>
<P>
   There are several factors responsible for this disparity. Some
researchers note the influx of Hispanic immigration, which is about
50 percent of total immigration. Many Hispanic immigrants have
limited education and poor language and job skills.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is the high dropout rate for Hispanic Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Education has always been the single best avenue out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts such as Waco Independent School District's new Career
and Technology Education program should help guide young people
toward good-paying jobs currently available in the marketplace and
higher learning venues available to them, like Texas State
Technical College.
</P>
<P>
   District officials are making earnest efforts to curb dropouts
and guide students toward educational and career opportunities
following graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Employers should join federal, state and local officials in
putting effort and resources into the education and training that
matches American citizens to good-paying American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
