<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVALUATING RISK OF ALZHEIMERS, EXERCISE AND THE ELDERLY, BACTERIA
AND STROKES, FISH ALLERGIES, AND THE SCIENCE OF THE GOLF SWING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Maine, Mass., Minn., Ill., Spain)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Science Times)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alzheimer's disease, which robs people of their most basic
neurological functions, may give subtle clues to its approach years
before clear symptoms emerge.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study in The Archives of Neurology suggests that
cognitive tests may allow doctors to know if a patient is
developing the disease. While there is no treatment for Alzheimer's
now, the technique could be useful as drugs become available.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the report, Dr. Merrill F. Elias of the University
of Maine, drew on data compiled in the Framingham Heart Study, the
52-year health assessment of residents of Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   From 1975 to 1979, as part of the study, psychologists gave a
number of tests meant to gauge the participants' brain functions.
</P>
<P>
   The study participants were tested for learning and immediate
recall, visual reproduction from memory and abstract reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, all appeared free of Alzheimer's disease. But those
who developed the disease later, researchers found, were more
likely to have had lower test results in the cognitive studies.
Less retention of verbal material and lower abstract reasoning were
the strongest predictors, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The journal noted, however, that the lower scores did not
necessarily mean a person would develop Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIEW ON OLDER PEOPLE EXERCISING
</P>
<P>
   Urging older people to have stress tests before they begin
exercise programs, a common medical practice, is not only unfounded
but may even discourage people from getting the physical activity
they need, a new study reports.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of older people do not need the test, in which
heart function is measured as a patient uses a treadmill, the
researchers wrote in a recent issue of The Journal of the American
Medical Association. Instead, they said, the patients should simply
have complete physical examinations.
</P>
<P>
   The lead author of the study, Dr. Thomas M. Gill, a professor of
internal medicine and geriatrics at Yale, noted that only about a
third of elderly people are considered physically active.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's discouraging to us,'' he said, ``because in the past,
there has been a wealth of new evidence demonstrating the benefits
of physical activity and exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   The study said a review of the evidence suggested that the risk
of heart attack related to exercise might be overstated, and the
researchers suggested that the overall benefits of exercise
outweighed any risk.
</P>
<P>
   In a 79-year-old woman, vigorous exercise like slow jogging,
speed-walking or tennis appeared to raise the annual risk of a
heart attack to 1.6 percent from 1.3 percent. In a 90-year-old man,
the risk rose to 4.8 percent, from 3.9 percent. Less stressful
forms of exercise carry even less risk, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidelines of the American Heart Association and the
American College of Sports Medicine, doctors are advised to conduct
stress tests routinely among older people who want to start
exercising. The goal is to detect asymptomatic heart blockages. But
often, Gill said, older people cannot complete the treadmill test
satisfactorily, and so require more elaborate tests to determine if
there is a blockage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, older people who have not been active should
begin slowly, with activities like walking and balance exercises.
</P>
<P>
   BACTERIA SEEN AS CONTRIBUTING TO STROKES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Common bacteria, already found to have a possible association
with heart attacks, may also play a role in strokes, a new study
has found.
</P>
<P>
   People infected with the bacterium, Chlamydia pneumomiae, appear
four and a half times as likely to suffer a first ischemic stroke
than uninfected people. The findings are reported in the July issue
of the journal Stroke. Dr. Mitchell S.V. Elkind of Columbia
University based the findings on a study of 89 stroke patients.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that people with signs of recent infection
were the most at risk, but that people who had been infected in the
past several years were also at higher risk.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria are not those that cause the sexually transmitted
disease chlamydia, but instead affect the respiratory tract. Almost
everyone is infected at one point or another. Researchers believe
the bacteria may cause an inflammation that leads to stroke and
heart attacks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALLERGIC TO FISH? AVOID AIR AROUND THEM
</P>
<P>
   Most people who are allergic to pollen presumably make it a
point to avoid blooming fields of ragweed or goldenrod.
</P>
<P>
   But most people allergic to fish probably figure that to avoid
an unpleasant reaction, they need only avoid eating anything that
contains fish.
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have found that for people allergic to fish, it is
enough just to inhale some of the allergens wafting off the skin to
have a reaction. And that, the study says, means that the
piscatorial equivalent of the field in bloom is the fish market.
</P>
<P>
   The report was published earlier this year in the Journal of
Allergy and Clinical Immunology, and was prepared by researchers
from the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., and researchers from a
hospital in Madrid, Spain. Mayo researchers released details of the
study this month.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted at an open-air fish market in Madrid,
where allergy patients have reported reactions. Hypersensitivity to
fish is a significant problem in several European countries, the
study said.
</P>
<P>
   On 41 different days, researchers took air samples in the
market, and consistently found fish allergens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXPLORING THE SCIENCE OF THE GOLF SWING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is the perfect golf swing, that elusive marriage of grace and
strength that separates the duffer from the pro, about to yield its
secrets to science?
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely, but researchers at the University of Chicago, using
brain-imaging equipment, are studying how professional golfers
prepare to swing, in the hope that it will help in physical
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, volunteers from the LPGA Tour, in Chicago for a
tournament, agreed to let doctors examine them with MRIs while the
players visualized their swing. The machines track small movements
of blood in the brain, and researchers say they hope the study will
allow them to understanding the nature of rapid body movement.
</P>
<P>
   The test requires the subjects to remain still. ``We have to
study an aspect of movement, without the person moving,'' said Dr.
John G. Milton, a neurology professor at the university.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers hit on the idea of using golfers because the
best ones are known to fully visualize their swing before they hit
the ball. Indeed, said Milton, who has played golf for six years,
the swing is so fast that golfers have no time to reposition
themselves once it has begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant to me that everything has to be preprogrammed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers plan to examine three groups of women: the pro
golfers, competent amateur ones and those who have never hit a golf
ball, Milton said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the third group will then be given golf lessons for
16 weeks and re-examined, to see if there are any change in their
brain patterns.
</P>
</TEXT>
