A1475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-UNIVERSITY-RESEARCH25     07-24 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-RESEARCH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNIVERSITIES SUBSIDIZE FEDERAL RESEARCH, SAYS REPORT
 &HT;    Eds: See Cox-state inserts at end of story.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Far from ripping off the federal government,
research universities pick up between $700 million and $1.5 billion
of the overhead costs for the $15 billion in federal research
contracts that they get each year.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings from an 18-month congressionally mandated study
were released Monday by Rand Corporation researchers at the
National Science Foundation's Science and Technology Policy
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the university community has been saying for
years _ that universities are subsidizing federal research,'' said
Richard J. Turman(cq), director of federal relations for the
Association of American Universities, which includes 60 major
public and private research institutions.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes the Rand report will help universities resist
efforts in Congress to make them pick up a bigger portion of the
overhead costs for federally financed research.
</P>
<P>
   Federal grants are supposed to cover the direct and indirect
costs of scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   Direct costs include such items as salaries, materials and
special equipment for a project. Indirect costs include such
overhead items as wear and tear on facilities, administrative and
accounting costs, and even janitorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, about 70 percent of a project's expenses are direct
costs and 30 percent are indirect, according to the Rand report. It
said the average federal grant covers all of the direct costs, but
only 70 to 90 percent of the indirect costs.
</P>
<P>
   Rand economist Charles A. Goldman, a co-author of the report,
said he could not calculate similar figures for research contracts
with private companies, because the Department of Defense, which
issues the bulk of such contracts, told him it considers such data
to be the private property of the contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Although dozens of federal agencies sponsor some scientific
research, most grants to universities are awarded by Defense, the
National Institutes of Health or the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, American universities spent about $26 billion on
scientific research. That included $15 billion in federal funds, $5
billion from university funds, $2 billion in state and local funds,
and $4 billion from private sources, including corporations and
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said the $5 billion in university funds included the
$700 million to $1.5 billion needed to cover the shortfall in
federal reimbursements for indirect costs.
</P>
<P>
   Universities have been willing to absorb such expenses as part
of the price of competing for prestigious federal research
projects. In addition, some see other benefits. The state
comptroller in Texas estimated that each dollar spent on research
stimulates $3.62 in economic activity within that state.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, some members of Congress tried to cut overhead
reimbursements for federal research projects at universities by 10
percent. As a compromise, Congress instead ordered the White House
to issue recommendations by July 1999 on whether changes were
needed in order to keep universities from claiming excess expenses
for overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The White House commissioned the Rand report, which was released
Monday. The Rand data was used as the basis for recommendations to
be released Tuesday _ one year late _ and posted on the Web site of
the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations include opposition to efforts to recover
additional overhead costs from universities, according to a letter
to members of Congress from Neal Lane, the president's science
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``These additional costs could end up either reducing university
spending for research and education, or being passed on to students
through increased tuition rates,'' Lane wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Rand report - www.rand.org/publications/MR/MR1135.1
</P>
<P>
   White House Office of Science and Technology Policy -
www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/OSTP/html/OSTPHome.html
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
