<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY-OIL (Washington) _ If Texas Gov. George W. Bush
selects Richard Cheney as his running mate, the Republicans might
face criticism that they are offering America the ``Big Oil''
ticket. Democrats could revive questions about Bush's ties to
Harken Energy when it won an exclusive offshore oil-drilling
contract with Bahrain in 1990 and about Cheney's leadership at
Halliburton Co., a Dallas-based oil and gas drilling and supply
firm. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD-CHENEY (Washington) _ Since leaving office in 1993 as
President Bush's secretary of defense, Richard Cheney has earned
millions of dollars in private industry. Cheney, whom George W.
Bush is considering as his running mate, received $1.2 million last
year as chief executive officer of the Halliburton Co. In 1998 the
oil firm paid him a salary of $1.18 million and a bonus of $1.15
million. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-SIERRA (Grand Rapids, Mich.) _ The Sierra Club, one of the
nation's leading environmental groups, endorses Vice President Al
Gore even though some environmentalists say Gore has been a tepid
supporter of their causes. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBI-INTERNET (Washington) _ Congressional Republicans question
FBI officials on their new program to police the Internet. The
e-mail-sniffing system, known as ``Carnivore,'' allows agents to
sift a suspect's messages out of the full stream of data passing
through an Internet service provider (ISP), like America Online.
Once installed, Carnivore has the ability to monitor all of the
e-mail on a network. Critics say the FBI could use the program to
invade people's privacy. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HMO (Washington) _ The Department of Health and Human
Services reports that 934,000 of Medicare's 39 million
beneficiaries next year will lose the coverage they now have under
managed-care health plans. The HMOs say they are abandoning
Medicare patients because federal reimbursements are too low. HHS
says 83 percent of those slated to lose coverage will be able to
join another HMO in their area. Those who don't will return to
Medicare's traditional fee-for-service program. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ President Clinton takes over the
negotiating with Israel Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-HOUSING (Houston) _ A close look at the financing plan
for the Victory Apartments, a 100-unit public housing development
in Houston, provides a glimpse into the convoluted mechanisms of
building public housing in an era when the federal government will
no longer simply write a check for it. A patchwork of federal
grants, state bond funds and tax credits, strung together with
complex lending and repayment plans, is financing the project,
which officials admit is costing far more than it would cost a
private developer to build comparable apartments. By MIKE SNYDER
and MATT SCHWARTZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (Houston) _ After two weeks of solo flight, the
Russian-made crew module for the international space station is
ready to link up with the other components of the slowly developing
orbital outpost. The automated rendezvous is scheduled for Tuesday
night. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   FAITH-LAWSUIT (Austin, Texas) _ A lawsuit accuses a faith-based
program aimed at helping the poor of being unconstitutional because
of its affiliation with evangelical Christians. The suit, filed in
a Texas district court by the American Jewish Congress and Texas
Civil Rights Project, is believed to be the nation's first
constitutional challenge to a government program that relies upon
religious leaders to manage taxpayer dollars. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Despite all the pledges about
government cost-cutting and returning federal funds to the
taxpayers, members of Congress are graciously willing to make one
exception to their stingy mood: themselves. The House quietly gave
itself a $3,800 pay raise last week. In the past such
self-aggrandizement has prompted a public outcry, but now lawmakers
think the voters are so contented they won't mind. Have times
really changed that much? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
