<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TIGER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger survives as fittest in sporting
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta's Bobby Jones, the greatest golfer of his era, was once
asked his thoughts about a young golfer named Jack Nicklaus. His
response became part of the Nicklaus legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays a game with which I am not familiar,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The world has turned a time or two since then. And in the way of
such things, the 60-year-old Nicklaus, now winding down his career,
is saying much the same thing these days about another young man,
Eldrick _ better known as Tiger _ Woods.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to describe what Woods has accomplished. You
could point out that he has won the world's last two major golf
tournaments by a combined 23 strokes, an average of three strokes a
round better than the world's best golfers, playing at the top of
their form. You might also note that Woods has become a household
name even in households that wouldn't know a driver from a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no more telling indicator of Woods' dominance than
his impact on his fellow golfers. Professional athletes have to
nurture a sense of arrogance in themselves, but Woods, at the age
of 24, has beaten that natural arrogance out of his colleagues.
They have been forced to acknowledge, publicly and often, that he
is simply much better than they are, and that they are helpless to
close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most intriguing thing about Tiger is our own
eagerness to turn the man into an icon. While he is the best in the
world at what he does, his particular skill amounts to using a
stick to knock a ball into a hole some 400 yards away. Why should
that obscure ability command such fame and monetary reward?
</P>
<P>
   While golf, by its nature, is perhaps the most abstract and
absurd of all the major sports, most of the other games we humans
play are also arbitrary contests. There is no real-life counterpart
to swishing a 30-foot basket, turning a double play, heading in a
goal or tossing a touchdown pass either. But millions love to watch
those feats nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Some might claim that our culture's fascination with sport is
evidence of its superficiality. However, sport transcends both time
and culture. The ancient Aztecs, the Greeks and Romans, Mongolian
tribes and Native Americans _ they too manufactured physical
challenges and then celebrated those who mastered them.
</P>
<P>
   So sports are universal, appealing to something fundamental in
human beings. Perhaps they are at some level a metaphor for life, a
ritual and drama of success and failure, of effort rewarded and
sometimes cruelly unrewarded.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Tiger and his competitors play a game with which
we are all familiar.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
