<HEADER>
A1497 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-JAMES-CAMERON-LOOKS-A     07-24 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-CAMERON-LOOKS-AHEAD-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND `TITANIC': JAMES CAMERON LOOKS FOR NEW WORLDS TO CONQUER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of director James Cameron on the set of
``Titanic.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 EDITOR'S NOTE: Possibly objectionable language in 5th and 22nd
paragraphs. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    James Cameron is not David O. Selznick.
 &HT;    The legendary producer spent a huge chunk of his career trying
in vain to top ``Gone With The Wind'' (1939), which had won eight
Oscars and become the most successful film ever made to that time.
Even winning a second straight Best Picture Oscar for ``Rebecca''
(1940) didn't ease Selznick's futile compulsion to top himself.
 &HT;    Writer/director Cameron famously declared himself ``the king of
the world'' when ``Titanic'' (1997) copped a Best Picture Oscar of
its own, capping a triumphant run for the film which now stands as
the most successful ever made. But he insists that no pressure to
top himself lies behind his three years of inactivity since then.
 &HT;    ```Titanic' was definitely a once-in-a-career kind of thing,''
Cameron says. ``Steven Spielberg has spent a career trying to top
`E.T.' (1982), and he's done it. He's done it artistically and done
it financially. So I'm not saying it's likely to happen, but I
don't think it should stop you from trying.
 &HT;    ``Here's the thing,'' Cameron says. ``When you make a feature,
you try to do the best damn movie you can do, bar none, hands down.
It's not like you hold back 5 percent. You are always trying to do
the best _ and the best, in my book, is not just that the movie
satisfies me, but that the movie will satisfy the most people. So
every time I've gone out there, I've tried to do `Titanic.'
 &HT;    ``It just so happens that one time I did it.''
 &HT;    What he'll finally take on as an encore to ``Titanic'' remains
to be seen. In the meantime, though, another ship has come in:
Cameron _ along with Charles Eglee, a longtime friend and Emmy
Award-winning writer and producer _ co-created and will serve as
co-executive producer for ``Dark Angel,'' a sci-fi television
series that will debut on Fox in October. The two-hour pilot has
been penned by Cameron and Eglee.
 &HT;    Set in post-apocalyptic Seattle in 2020, ``Dark Angel'' will
introduce audiences to Max (Jessica Alba), a genetically enhanced
young woman who's been on the run since escaping the compound in
which she was engineered. Though she's kept a low profile working
as a bike messenger, her life forever changes when she encounters
Logan Cale (Michael Weatherly), a cyberjournalist fighting the
corrupt establishment.
 &HT;    Max would prefer to dodge trouble, but joins Cale in the hope of
discovering the truth about herself, staying one step ahead of the
relentless military man (John Savage) who's trying to recapture her
and locating others like herself.
 &HT;    ``The drivers for every episode, and there are two, will be
emotional and moral,'' says Cameron, who's friendly, upbeat and
talkative during a telephone call from his production company's Los
Angeles offices. ``The emotional driver for Max is that she doesn't
have a family and so she wants one. She's the ultimate orphan. She
doesn't even have biological parents _ she has gene-sequence
donors. The only family she's ever known are the other transgenic
children in her group at the clinic.''
 &HT;    As for the moral driver, Cameron explains that Max has been
hardened by her past experiences and by her sense of herself as
different. It's a universal feeling, he says _ all kids, to a
greater or lesser degree, endure a period in their teens when they
feel different from everybody else and think they'll never fit in.
 &HT;    ``They haven't found their place in life yet, don't know what
their values are and don't know what they want to do with the rest
of their life,'' Cameron says. ``Certainly there was always the
head of the football team and the head cheerleader, and they don't
feel like they need to evolve any beyond what they are, but I think
those are the exceptions.
 &HT;    ``So I think what you do with a character like Max is tap into
teen angst, but in a way that's serious drama and not of a cutesy,
lightweight, fun-in-high-school nature,'' he says. ``That's a
distinction between us and `Buffy,' to which we've been compared.
We're dealing with the problems from a psychological basis a little
more seriously.''
 &HT;    That's all well and good, but millions of people out there are
probably scratching their heads and wondering why the
self-professed ``king of the world'' is doing television. After
all, this is the same medium that gave us ``Manimal'' and
``Supertrain'' _ heck, the same network that brought the world
``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?''
 &HT;    ``It would seem to be an odd choice if I was just a director on
it, because television is not really a director's medium,'' Cameron
says. ``But I really was a screenwriter first, last and always. As
a writer, television makes a lot more sense.
 &HT;    ``I think of the first season of `Dark Angel' as a 14-hour
movie,'' he adds. ``In a 14-hour movie you can do a lot more with
the depth of character than you can in, say, a
three-hour-and-15-minute movie, like my last one.
 &HT;    ``Film characters tend not to have a past,'' he says, ``and tend
to rely heavily on casting to create a sense of character. Sandra
Bullock in a movie is a certain character, and the writer doesn't
have to do much. For television, you have much more time to develop
the character, take it on various kinds of journeys and have it
interact with other characters.''
 &HT;    Cameron will be ``pretty involved'' with ``Dark Angel'' after
the pilot airs, but intends to leave the day-to-day line producing
to Eglee. Chances are, however, that he'll pen a future episode or
two, and perhaps even direct one.
 &HT;    Back on the feature front, a ``True Lies'' sequel remains very
much a possibility. On the other hand, Cameron says, ``Terminator
3'' is a dead issue _ even though Arnold Schwarzenegger, after
signing to reprise his signature role, publicly proclaimed his
desire that Cameron call the shots again.
 &HT;    ``That would be wise on his part, but it's not up to him,'' says
Cameron, who also flirted with directing a big-screen
``Spider-Man'' and a new take on ``Planet of the Apes.'' ``It
reached a point where I've moved on. There are other things I want
to be doing.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to hold him up for years and years until I just
one day decide it will be a good idea,'' the director adds. ``I
don't really own it, so there's no real economic imperative for me
to do it, other than pride of authorship.
 &HT;    ``And so I've sat down with Arnold and said, `Look, just go do
the character. You've earned it. You are this guy. Everybody
associates him with you. Go kick ass.'''
 &HT;    Had ``Titanic'' tanked, Cameron acknowledges, he would have
dived back into action in order to prove something to himself.
 &HT;    ``But,'' he says, ``it didn't.''
 &HT;    As a result, Cameron is following his game plan, which involved
making ``one big score'' and then taking some time off to enjoy
life's pleasures.
 &HT;    ``What, I'm going to first enjoy life when I'm 70?'' asks the
46-year-old director, who embarked on his fifth marriage when he
wed ``Titanic'' co-star Suzy Amis in June. ``I don't think so. I
won't be able to do all the things I like to do, fly helicopters,
scuba dive. So I'm going to do all that stuff now and get it out of
the way.
 &HT;    ``And then I can go make movies when I'm 70, because you just
sit in a chair and bark out orders.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
