<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATCHING-UP-WITH-CAT-STEVENS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPRISE: THE UNEXPECTED RETURN OF CAT STEVENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer/songwriter Cat Stevens.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    After more than 20 years of living quietly in England as a
devout Muslim and a spiritual educator, Yusuf Islam has decided to
be Cat Stevens again. Kind of.
 &HT;    The 52-year-old Islam, who hasn't had much to say since retiring
from pop music in 1978, is openly talking about those days again to
promote an ambitious reissue of his 1970s albums, which include
still-popular songs such as ``Wild World'' (1970), ``Morning Has
Broken'' (1971), ``Peace Train'' (1971) and ``Moonshadow'' (1971).
 &HT;    The endeavor also includes a greatest-hits collection, a
boxed-set compilation and possibly an archival live recording.
 &HT;    ``It's an interesting time,'' Islam says. ``For me, it's like
rediscovering perhaps a few of the treasures that I buried in the
past. It's quite a delightful time, in a way _ I'm revisiting the
whole past with more of a perspective, I think, these days and
maybe a little more maturity.
 &HT;    ``I'm quite enjoying this moment.''
 &HT;    Islam hasn't been entirely out of the spotlight since 1978, of
course. In 1988 he prompted a boycott of his records after he sided
with Muslim fundamentalists who had called for the murder of author
Salman Rushdie over his book ``The Satanic Verses.'' The group
10,000 Maniacs protested Islam's stance _ which he had since
retracted _ by pulling its cover of ``Peace Train'' from its album
``In My Tribe.''
 &HT;    More recently, he was denied entry to Israel by government
officials who labeled him a threat to national security because of
his past financial contributions to Hamas, the Palestinian
terrorist organization.
 &HT;    Islam, who had been headed to Israel to film a portion of an
upcoming VH1 ``Behind the Music'' episode about him, denied ever
knowingly supporting terrorists. He claims his contributions were
to aid orphans in the Hebron region and other humanitarian causes,
and calls the accusations ``an attempt to cast doubt again on my
character and good intentions.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, Islam _ who's active in interfaith concerns in
London through his Islamia School, founded in 1983 _ says that he's
now working to help bring about understanding and tolerance between
peoples divided by religious and spiritual issues.
 &HT;    ``I don't necessarily believe that you're going to be able to
merge religions,'' he says, ``but principles certainly can be
agreed upon, and those principles are so clear and so well
understood that I see no difficulty at all in coming to those kinds
of conclusions and agreeing with other of different faiths on those
_ and that is to do with spiritualness itself, to do with divine
presence, with consciousness and mortality, and to do with
accountability.''
 &HT;    Religion wasn't a big part of the life of Stephen Georgiou, who
grew up in London as a bit of a loner, the son of a Greek
restaurateur and a Swedish mother. Smitten with music, he began
performing _ using the name Steve Adams _ while attending
Hammersmith College in London, where he also absorbed early
performances by Cream, Pink Floyd and American acts such as Jimi
Hendrix, James Taylor and Paul Simon.
 &HT;    ``It was a time of great creativity,'' recalls Islam, who admits
that he dabbled in drugs and drink, but not heavily. ``(The
Beatles) had opened so many what you might call windows of
opportunity.
 &HT;    ``I used to go down to a club in London that was frequented by a
guy called Paul Simon,'' Islam says. ``He used to come to our thing
and try a few things out there, and later these became worldwide
hits, like `Homeward Bound' (1965) and `The Sounds of Silence'
(1964). It was an amazing, amazing time for everybody.''
 &HT;    Islam began performing as Cat Stevens in 1966, and scored his
first hit that fall with ``I Love My Dog,'' which reached No. 28 on
the British charts. He logged several other pop hits, but his
career shifted after he contracted tuberculosis in 1968 and, while
recuperating, decided to make a more earthy, folk-tinged kind of
music that also began to reveal a spiritual quest.
 &HT;    ``It was extremely conscious,'' says Islam, who says he was
raised with ``a basic Christian upbringing'' but was turned to
other religions after a friend gave him a Buddhist book, ``The
Secret Path,'' while he was in the hospital. ``At that time there
was definitely a surge of interest in things spiritual and
mystical, you may say. There was flower power and transcendental
meditation going on. There were more questions to life, I felt,
that needed answers.
 &HT;    ``I was looking for the truth,'' he says. ``I suppose Einstein
had a little to play in that, because he'd thrown everything into
the area of relativity. So you think, `Well, can there be absolute
truth?' But I did believe that it existed, somewhat.''
 &HT;    Three decades later, Islam can hear his quest clearly in songs
such as ``I Wish, I Wish'' (1970), ``Miles From Nowhere'' (1970),
``The Wind'' (1971) and ``Morning Has Broken'' _ the latter of
which he found in an old hymn book.
 &HT;    ``It's like a journey,'' he says. ``If you analyze them, in many
places they describe the journey I was on ... I wrote down and
recorded my emotions, my development, my evolution, I would say. I
began as a human being, and I just developed.''
 &HT;    The clearest link to that evolution, Islam says, is in his 1971
hit ``Peace Train.''
 &HT;    ``If you look at the name of my faith, Islam itself, the basic
root of that word is `salaam,' which means `peace,''' he explains.
``Now, when I was writing that song, `Peace Train,' I didn't know
exactly where it was going, but I believe today it's landed in
Islam.
 &HT;    ``And in that song, I realize in some ways that it's not always
going to be easy, even with those who hope for peace,'' Islam adds.
``I said in one of the lyrics, I think, `Why must we go on
hating?/Why can't we live in bliss?' _ in other words, accepting
and realizing not everybody is going to be on that train.''
 &HT;    But after his years in the limelight, Islam is happy simply
being a passenger on that train these days. He almost performed at
the London Live Aid concert in 1985, but was bumped when organizers
told him there was no time _ though he suspects that they were also
afraid of what he might say to the crowd.
 &HT;    He did, however, play last year in Sarajevo, Bosnia, to
commemorate the end of the Bosnian civil war.
 &HT;    But Islam says that he has no interest in being a performing
artist again, and that the new music he's recording _ such as his
latest release, an album and book project called ``A is for Allah''
(2000) _ will be spiritual in nature and focused towards children.
 &HT;    ``I think that they do need more help in understanding this
world than they are being given now,'' says Islam, who notes that
his own five children are ``quite interested'' in the history of
Cat Stevens. ``Look at what's happening in America today, the
killing of one schoolchild by another. It's telling us, isn't it,
that you've got to look at this issue and see what you can teach
children.
 &HT;    ``So instead of teaching `A is for apple' and `Go get it, boys,'
let children learn a little bit more about the creator of apples,''
Islam says, ``and perhaps what might happen is we can help them to
guide their lives a little bit more.
 &HT;    ``I think that's a greater calling than trying to have a hit on
the radio.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
