<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERRY-BRUCKHEIMER-PRODUCES-COYOTE-UGLY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR MOTION PICTURES: BEHIND THE SCENES WITH JERRY BRUCKHEIMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jerry Bruckheimer on the set of ``Coyote
Ugly.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    War is hell. And producer Jerry Bruckheimer couldn't be happier.
 &HT;    Bruckheimer is busy filming one of the most expensive, most
anticipated movies in history, the $200 million ``Pearl Harbor,''
due out on Memorial Day, 2001, and he isn't pulling any punches.
 &HT;    ``We had 70 actual survivors of the attack present so we could
make sure we were completely accurate,'' he says over breakfast at
the Ritz-Carlton in Marina Del Ray, Calif. ``It's not a
documentary, but you can get it right.''
 &HT;    Bruckheimer is on a furlough from the Hawaii set, supposedly in
town to promote his latest film, ``Coyote Ugly.'' But ``Pearl
Harbor'' is clearly foremost in his mind.
 &HT;    ``I'm standing there with bombs going off overhead,'' he
recalls, ``and I'd catch a glimpse of the faces of real-life
retired Army men or nurses who were there in the 1940s and maybe
lost someone they loved. You could feel their pain and sorrow at
having to watch this again. You could see their sadness.
 &HT;    ``Just walking around our set, all you needed to do was look
down and it hit you,'' he says soberly. ``You saw the real bullet
holes from the attack still lodged in the ground.''
 &HT;    Ben Affleck and the film's other stars were also given a chance
to experience the reality of it all.
 &HT;    ``We had the real Army Rangers set up a little boot camp for the
actors,'' Bruckheimer says, laughing. ``The sergeant who trained
the cast of `Full Metal Jacket' (1987) scared them half to death.
Ben kept joking, `Don't you know I'm an actor? Don't you know I'm
famous?' It didn't matter.''
 &HT;    As for ``Coyote Ugly,'' opening nationwide on Aug. 4, it's been
dubbed an updated ``Flashdance'' (1983) or ``Cocktail'' (1988) with
girls. Bruckheimer cast unknown Piper Perabo as Violet, a
21-year-old who comes to New York to become a song writer, but
winds up working as a bartender at Coyote Ugly, a bar run by sexy,
young women who tantalize customers with their outrageous antics.
Supermodel Tyra Banks and former ``E.R.'' star Maria Bello play
fellow barmaids.
 &HT;    The bar is a real place, one which Bruckheimer first learned of
in a 1997 GQ article titled ``The Muse of the Coyote Ugly Saloon.''
 &HT;    ``It was about these women trying to survive in the big city,
and it did have elements of `Flashdance' in it,'' Bruckheimer says.
``I also thought it would be great to go out there and hold a
nationwide casting call and find new talent.''
 &HT;    If ``Coyote Ugly'' is heavy on the estrogen, testosterone is the
name of the game in Bruckheimer's fall film, ``Remember the
Titans.'' Set in 1971, it's the story of a high-school football
coach (Denzel Washington) who leads one of the first integrated
football teams in Alexandria, Va.
 &HT;    Throw in his recent hit ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' and it's clear
that Bruckheimer is one prolific producer _ all the more impressive
in light of the fact that many in Hollywood thought he was finished
after the 1995 death of his longtime partner, Don Simpson.
 &HT;    Bruckheimer was on the set of their co-production ``The Rock''
(1996) when he got a call on his cell phone: ``Don is dead.''
 &HT;    The 52-year-old Simpson, who with Bruckheimer had grossed $1.4
billion worldwide with movies such as ``Flashdance,'' ``Beverly
Hills Cop'' (1984) and ``Top Gun'' (1986), had overdosed from a
lethal combination of cocaine, sedatives, antidepressants and
antipsychotic medications.
 &HT;    It was not an unexpected end for Simpson, one of the most
flamboyantly self-destructive men in Hollywood, but it still came
as a shock to his partner of 13 years.
 &HT;    ``The call was very traumatic, but not a surprise,'' Bruckheimer
says. ``It was a phone call that you hoped you would never get.
But, considering the way Don lived his life, you knew that someday
you would get that call.''
 &HT;    The producer admits that he had his own doubts about his ability
to go it alone.
 &HT;    ``Besides losing a dear friend, it's always great to have
another mind around,'' Bruckheimer says. ``I think it takes more
than two intelligent people to make a successful film. Now I don't
have as much IQ around. And Don was a very smart man.''
 &HT;    Smart, but hardly wise. Freewheeling, free-spending and reckless
in business and in his private life, Simpson had provided the team
with its splash and dash. Bruckheimer was always depicted as the
calm, quiet and sane one, spelling out the contracts for the deals
that Simpson threw together.
 &HT;    ``Don was more high profile,'' the producer says. ``But the
media coverage wasn't always fair. Many journalists didn't check
their sources and just believed what people told them.''
 &HT;    At the time of Simpson's death, the duo was ironically in the
midst of a major career comeback after a rocky stretch in the early
1990s. They'd scored their first hit in years with ``Crimson Tide''
(1995), then continued with a string of blockbusters including
``Dangerous Minds'' (1995), ``Bad Boys'' (1995) and ``The Rock,''
which combined to earn a staggering $376 million.
 &HT;    And then Bruckheimer was suddenly on his own. It would be
understandable if he were angry with Simpson, but today he shows
only sadness in recalling his partner.
 &HT;    ``People end up doing what they want,'' he says. ``Nobody was
going to stop him. You can only guide someone so far.''
 &HT;    It turned out that Bruckheimer was more than capable of carrying
on under his own aegis. ``Con Air'' (1997) was a hit, and
``Armageddon'' (1998) earned more than $300 million worldwide. Not
bad for a man once written off as a paper-shuffler riding on his
partner's coattails.
 &HT;    More to the point, not bad for a shy boy who grew up in Detroit
living for Saturday afternoons at the movies. Today he's immersed
in the world of film, and he says that it doesn't get old _ that,
after nearly 20 years making movies, he's happier than ever doing
it.
 &HT;    ``I love to juggle all the balls at the same time,'' Bruckheimer
says. ``I love to be in the thick of things.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
