<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRATING-THE-SIMPSONS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRAISE OF HOMER: SALUTING THE IRREPLACEABLE SIMPSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Bart Simpson in a scene from ``The
Simpsons.'') 
 By KEN CARRIERE  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before July 30. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few months ago, after another badly played hockey game, my
teammates and I were in the locker room getting changed. It was
late, and we were tired.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the cheap beer or the mild concussions, but we all
started talking about Homer Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, now there's a way to ease the pain.
</P>
<P>
   This was a room full of guys from different backgrounds with
different jobs, but Homer appealed to us all. We repeated favorite
quotes and discussed favorite episodes. Some guys tried to prove
that they were Homer, or claimed that the producers must watch them
to get ideas for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Even after 11 seasons, ``The Simpsons'' is as popular as ever.
And, let's face it, that's largely thanks to the Big Guy. Homer's
where the heart is. He may be fat, bald and dimwitted, but how many
television personalities can get every guy in a locker room talking
excitedly? Outside of some ``Baywatch'' actresses, perhaps, only
Homer.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, some of Homer's biggest fans work on the series.
Mike Scully, who joined the show in 1993, has written seven
episodes and is currently an executive producer, adores the
character as much as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homer represents the kid that exists in every adult male that
we're always being told to leave behind,'' Scully says. ``Homer so
clearly embraces the child within him. I think that's why men in
particular enjoy watching him. I think kids enjoy watching him
because they love watching adults who are idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``The Simpsons'' debuted in 1989, Homer was secondary. The
star was little Bart, an underachiever and proud of it. Homer
existed only to react angrily to Bart. In fact, in the first season
or two, Homer was a responsible grownup and at times even
approached intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   That changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speculate on it, because I was not with the show at
the time, but I think the general feeling was that he was coming
across too mean and too insensitive,'' Scully says. ``They made him
a little softer and a little more loving toward his family.''
</P>
<P>
   As Homer softened and became the lunatic we know and love, he
also became the star. Basically every episode featured him on a new
adventure. Any episode that featured another character in the lead
was surely meant only to cleanse the palate _ we could rest assured
that Homer would be back next week in fine, foolish form. Bart
joined the other characters _ Marge, Lisa and Maggie Simpson, plus
the other Springfield citizens _ in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was never a conscious change,'' Scully says. ``I think
the show was so focused on Bart in the beginning that a lot of Bart
stories were burned up in the first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``An adult doesn't have the limitations that a kid has,'' he
adds. ``You don't have to stretch believability as much to get him
into certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, almost every episode has starred Homer. He became an
astronaut _ and got into a fistfight aboard the space shuttle. He
drove his multimillionaire half-brother into bankruptcy, then
joined a traveling show because he was willing to take a cannonball
in the gut.
</P>
<P>
   Marge: ``Just because you were invited to join a freak show
doesn't mean you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Homer, staring blankly: ``You know, in some ways you and I are
very different people.''
</P>
<P>
   As Scully says, Homer represents the kid inside every man, the
kid we try not to reveal to our wives or girlfriends, even though
they know. As sad as it may be, men can live vicariously through
this beloved yellow blob. He's our Holden Caulfield _ Holden
ditches school, Homer ditches work, but they both do what they
want.
</P>
<P>
   As the Great One says to Marge in a 1998 episode: ``I don't
think anything I've ever done is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In some episodes, that abounding confidence has led Homer into
strange territory. Does Scully think that the writers ever took
Homer too far?
</P>
<P>
   ``As a moron?'' he says with a laugh. ``I'm sure we've crossed
the line with Homer a few times in terms of how stupid he might be
in a given situation. I think whenever you're doing a character
like Homer and you're walking that line of idiocy, you can't help
but cross it here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Simpsons writers have some rules about how to
deal with the Big Guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My basic rule is that he should always at least know his
name,'' Scully says. ``John Swartzwelder, who has written for the
show since the first season, says that he writes Homer like a dog
who can talk. In one scene, Homer can go through seven or eight
different emotions, just like a dog. He can go from sleeping to
eating in a matter of seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it: The ``Simpsons'' writers think about a
talking dog when they write for Homer, and then men the world over
strive to measure up.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, for anyone who loves Homer, Harper Collins will
release the book ``Homer's Guide to Being a Man'' in April 2001. It
will include quotations from the series and some newly written
material.
</P>
<P>
   Next season is sure to offer more classic Homer episodes. In the
Nov. 5 season premiere, for example, which happens to be the
series' 250th episode, Homer grows enraged when the telephone
company splits Springfield into two area codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What infuriates Homer,'' Scully says, ``is that he has to
memorize three new numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Homer incites a civic civil war. To the rescue,
thank goodness, come the classic British rockers The Who to restore
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they have done for so many cities,'' Scully adds.
</P>
<P>
   Although Homer is crazy, stupid, selfish, inconsiderate and
drunk most of the time, he's still a nice guy. That's why we really
love him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's well-established now that Homer really does love
his family,'' Scully says. ``No matter what he says or what he
does, you know where his heart is.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken Carriere is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Simpsons,'' consult the
official Web site at www.thesimpsons.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
