<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, July 25. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ In their 14th day, the Camp
David peace talks moved back into overdrive Monday as President
Clinton pitched himself into the issue-by-issue deliberations,
meeting until almost dawn with Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
and then cutting short his morning staff briefing to plunge back
into nitty-gritty talks. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REVOLUTION (San Vicente Del Caguan, Colombia) _ The
dream of a Marxist-Leninist revolution remains improbably alive
amid the rolling cattle pastures and steamy coca fields of southern
Colombia. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Austin, Texas) _ On the relationship between the
Bush family and the former defense secretary, Dick Cheney, who is
leading the search for a vice presidential running mate for Gov.
George W. Bush and is himself thought to be a possible candidate
for that post. By Frank Bruni and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION-POLL (Undated) _ Results of the latest New York
Times/CBS News poll on voter support for the presumed presidential
candidates Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush. By
Richard L. Berke with Janet Elder.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONVENTION (Philadelphia) _ Reinventing _ or in some
cases abandoning _ the rituals of past political party gatherings,
the Republican National Convention that begins Monday will more
than ever amount to a lavish multi-media spectacle that pushes
controversy to the sidelines in favor of an unabashed celebration
of the goals and vision of the party standard-bearer, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEROISM-RECONSIDERED (West Paducah, Ky.) _ Ben Strong was said
to have displayed remarkable courage when he disarmed Michael
Carneal, the 14-year-old killer who opened fire on a prayer group
at Heath High School here on Dec. 1, 1997. But as new information
about the events that morning emerges because of a civil lawsuit,
some people here are openly challenging the portrait of Strong as a
hero. His story shows how chaos and panic can distort the accounts
that witnesses give of the rampage killings that periodically
horrify the country. It may show, too, how the stories of the
killings are often shaped by the powerful desire of reporters and
everyone else involved to find some good news in horrible,
inexplicable events. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DIABLO-PUBLICITY (Undated) _ It came out just a couple of weeks
ago, a highly anticipated sequel to a hit best-seller filled with
stories of wizards and sorcerers. Revenue has topped $50 million so
far, reviews have been good, and fans, who waited impatiently for
their new heroes to arrive, are thrilled. But Diablo II, a computer
game designed for older teens and adults, has hardly registered on
the media radar screen. While Harry Potter and his creator, J.K.
Rowling, have won praise around the globe for drawing
videogame-crazed and television-besotted young people back to
reading, games like Diablo II draw condemnation for ensnaring
players in a morbid worldview and gluing them anti-socially to a
computer screen. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
