<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE `BIG NAME' RESURFACES FOR VEEP
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The speculation continues about George W. Bush's choice of a
running mate. Former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is believed to
be the latest front-runner - but Bush aides say there could still
be a surprise choice. Like Colin Powell. Dan Rather reported on CBS
Radio that two sources who are ``close in on the negotiations''
said that both the Texas governor and his father, the former
president, have been in touch with Powell ``very recently'' and
that Powell's wife, Alma, apparently has dropped her objections to
his running for national office. CNN and Reuters, however, report
that Powell's office denied the CBS report. The Washington Post
reports Bush has settled on Cheney. We may know for sure any time
now.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DOES SENATOR MILLER SOUND?
</P>
<P>
   Zell Miller, the popular ex-two-term Democratic governor of
Georgia, is expected to be appointed by Gov. Roy Barnes to the late
Republican Paul Coverdell's Senate seat and run for the remaining
four years of the term in November. The Associated Press reported
that Barnes would make the announcement tonight. Georgia law gives
the governor the right to appoint a successor. Coverdell, 61, the
first Georgia Republican since Reconstruction to be re-elected to
the Senate, died of a stroke last week. The appointment of Miller,
68, would reduce the Republican edge in the Senate to 54-46.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA CLUB PICKS ITS MAN
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has formally picked up the support of a major
environmental group. Accepting the Sierra Club's endorsement in
Grand Rapids, Mich., Gore promised to ``to protect the air, the
water and the planet God gave us. I want you to know that's a cause
I have held for my entire life, long before I entered public
service.'' The Sierra endorsement was a product of a six-month
process that reviewed the records of all the
</P>
<P>
   candidates and surveyed all chapters nationwide. The
organization's president, Robert Cox, said Gore would be ``the most
pro-environment president in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   LOG CABIN EFFORT PAYS OFF
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona is set to make history next week when
he'll become the first openly gay member of Congress to address a
Republican convention. Kolbe will have a prime-time speaking slot,
addressing the GOP on trade issues for three minutes between 8 and
8:30 p.m. on Tuesday. First elected in 1984, Kolbe is the most
senior openly gay member of Congress and is the only openly gay
Republican in the House. Having Kolbe speak at the convention was
an idea first raised by District of Columbia Councilman David
Catania in April, when the Log Cabin Republicans met with George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   OLD FRIENDS ON FINAL NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Jan Bullock, the widow of Texas Democratic political icon Bob
Bullock, will be one of several fellow Texans who will speak about
George W. Bush on the final night of the Republican convention.
``On Thursday night, we will have people speak who know him well
and know different aspects of him, and Jan is part of that,'' the
Associated Press quoted an unnamed official as saying. Bob Bullock,
who died in June 1999, was a former powerful Democratic lieutenant
governor who forged a close relationship with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY UNIONS, CITY STILL BARGAINING
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia city officials resumed talks with two unions today
with a strike deadline approaching and less than a week before the
Republican National Convention. Talks with District Council 47 of
the American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees,
the white-collar union, and District Council 33, the blue-collar
workers, bargained until after midnight, then resumed at late
morning after the negotiators got some sleep. In 1986, a three-week
municipal workers strike left museums, libraries and recreation
centers closed, streets piled with garbage, and water-main repairs
and other services delayed.
</P>
<P>
   TWO IDEAS HEADLONG IN CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press interviews with most of the 2,066 Republican
convention delegates show that tension over abortion rights is
deeply embedded in the party despite a wish by both sides to avoid
an argument that could complicate George W. Bush's chances of
becoming president. When Republicans meet in Philadelphia this week
to write party policy, some of them will be energized by two
opposing ideas that are long on conviction but short on
practicality: One is that the nation might be persuaded to amend
the Constitution to ban abortion. The other is that the GOP might
actually be persuaded to stop calling for that goal.
</P>
<P>
   POPULIST THEME FOR CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign laid out a theme for the convention that
credits the vice president for the nation's prosperity and casts
him as a populist fighter against powerful interest groups, and
attempts to define George W. Bush as a tool of the oil industry and
other special interests. Still, Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said
the main focus would be on the Gore's agenda and personal
background. Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Republicans ``will
welcome their theme as an opportunity to highlight the failures of
the Clinton-Gore administration.''
</P>
<P>
   MONEY THE STRONGEST MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   With billions of dollars in profits on the line, the health care
industry is waging the largest national ad campaign conducted by a
political special interest, with a price tag for this election
cycle that could approach $90 million. Already, leading
pharmaceutical companies have spent about $34 million on ads since
last July. The drug makers are fighting a plan to expand Medicare
by adding prescription drug coverage. Managed-care companies
opposed to proposals such as a right for patients to sue are also
pouring lots of cash into political ads.
</P>
<P>
   THINNER GOP SENATE EDGE?
</P>
<P>
   Republican candidates have more money to spend on close Senate
races this fall, but Democrats are financially competitive in most
of the tightest contests, according to recently filed midyear
fund-raising reports. Coupled with the fact that the death last
week of Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) has thrown another seat into
contention for the November elections, the new reports reinforce
widely held expectations that Democrats will pick up several Senate
seats. Some analysts say the Democrats could gain as many as four
seats, reducing the GOP edge to 51-49.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS DON'T KILL PEOPLE, BULLETS DO
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans heading to their national conventions
stand far apart on whether gun controls should be tougher, yet many
from both sides agree handguns should come with trigger locks,
according to interviews by the Associated Press. Four in 10
Republican delegates and eight in 10 Democratic delegates back the
safety devices. On gun control laws, however, 68 percent of
Democrats say current measures need to be stronger, while nearly as
many Republicans _ 61 percent_ say the laws are ``about right.''
</P>
<P>
   NO, NOT THE SOUP, THE CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Tom Campbell has gained no headway in his bid to
unseat Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein, according to a San
Francisco Examiner-KTVU poll showing that one-third of state voters
still don't recognize his name. Campbell campaign officials said
they planned to unleash ads this summer that will help the moderate
Silicon Valley congressman turn the numbers around. The poll,
conducted by Research 2000 of Maryland with a 3.5 percentage point
margin of error, showed Feinstein with a formidable 57-34 percent
lead. The poll also found that 26 percent of Republicans said they
preferred Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   YOU KNOW THOSE CLINTONS (WINK, WINK)
</P>
<P>
   The chief campaign strategist for New York Senate candidate Rick
Lazio said he believes Hillary Clinton's assertion that she did not
use an anti-Semitic slur in 1974, but he added that she has a
``credibility problem.'' Said Mike Murphy: ``I have no way to know.
I will believe her denial, but I will say, and I think most New
Yorkers will say, there's an unease about trustworthiness of Mrs.
Clinton, because there's such a history of spin taken to the
ultimate with the Clintons, that she has a credibility problem.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
