<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HEROISM-RECONSIDERED-     07-24 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROISM-RECONSIDERED-2TAKES(1085)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PORTRAIT OF HEROISM IS REDRAWN, WITH THE SUBJECT'S HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PADUCAH, Ky. _ He was the teen-age hero who turned a
horrifying school shooting into a parable of good against evil. His
name is Ben Strong, the gregarious son of a preacher who was said
to have displayed remarkable courage when he disarmed Michael
Carneal, the 14-year-old killer who opened fire on a prayer group
at Heath High School here on Dec. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after the shooting, Strong, an appealing high school
senior, was a regular on national television, where he was
portrayed as a symbol of hope. His inspirational story of
confronting the killer was repeated in newspapers across the
country, including this one. Since then, he has been the subject of
cover articles in magazines and has traveled the country preaching
to young people. Now 20, and working at his father's Assembly of
God Church, he is often introduced as the hero of Heath High.
</P>
<P>
   But as new information about the events that morning is starting
to emerge because of a civil lawsuit, some people here are openly
challenging the portrait of Strong as a hero who rushed up to a
killer as he was firing and persuaded him to drop the gun he had
used to murder three girls and wound five other students. In a
brief interview recently, even Strong acknowledged for the first
time to a reporter that the heroic picture of him might have been
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he said in the interview, ``people get the wrong
idea.'' In terse answers to questions, he agreed that he had not
taken the gun away from Carneal, as he sometimes suggested after
the shooting, and he agreed that he might not have influenced
Carneal at all in his decision to stop shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Ben Strong story shows how chaos and panic can distort the
accounts that witnesses give of the rampage killings that
periodically horrify the country. It may show, too, how the stories
of the killings are often shaped by the powerful desire of
reporters and everyone else involved to find some good news, even
signs of heroism, in horrible, inexplicable events.
</P>
<P>
   A striking finding from a New York Times examination of rampage
killings, published in April, is that long after the news media
depart, a different story of the events often emerges. Usually, the
first accounts present inaccurate information about the killer, the
crime, the victims or the roles of bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   After the Columbine High School massacre in 1999, for example,
one student, Cassie Bernall, was widely described as having
answered ``yes'' when one of the two killers asked her whether she
believed in God. She was killed, it was said, for her faith.
</P>
<P>
   After that account put her in the realm of martyrdom and spawned
a best-selling book, some news accounts last year reported that the
``yes'' most likely came from another student, Valeen Schnurr, who
survived.
</P>
<P>
   At Heath High School, the news media took their lead from Bill
J. Bond, the principal at the time of the shooting. Bond was the
first person to tell reporters that a prayerful senior who was a
football player, Benjamin Scott Strong, had probably saved lives,
including Bond's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world wants a hero,'' Bond said in a recent
interview. ``It is natural to look for some goodness in a tragedy
and I probably contributed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In testimony filed in McCracken County Circuit Court here this
spring, Strong said he had won praise for his bravery ``because of
what people said, how things were portrayed'' after the shooting,
not what really happened.
</P>
<P>
   In the deposition for the civil suit filed by the families of
the three murdered girls, Strong testified this winter that the
killer had discarded the gun on his own. ``He just got done, and he
dropped it,'' Strong said. His testimony has received little public
notice.
</P>
<P>
   Carneal, who is serving a life sentence after pleading guilty
but mentally ill to murder, also testified in the suit. When a
lawyer asked whether Strong had stopped him from shooting he
replied, ``No sir.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bond was told in a recent interview about Strong's newly
released testimony, he said information about Strong's actions had
come from Strong initially and had always been somewhat imprecise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him what he did,'' Bond said, ``and he said, `I told
him to lay the gun down,' and I took that at face value.''
</P>
<P>
   With scores of reporters pressing around the school the
afternoon of the shooting, Bond said, the story of Strong's actions
may have been exaggerated and ``it probably developed a life of its
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong helped the story along. Within hours of the shooting, he
was giving interviews and standing by as reporters described him as
the leader of the prayer group, a title he no longer claims.
</P>
<P>
   His descriptions of the shooting varied in the early interviews.
But in some accounts he suggested there had been a tug-of-war over
the gun. ``And then I went for him and I grabbed him, you know,''
he said on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' the day after the
shootings, ``and he put down the gun and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he simply stood by or denied he was a hero, which
some of his new admirers took as humility. On CNN's ``Larry King
Live'' a week after the killings, Strong listened silently while
another guest, the Rev. Jerry Falwell, called Strong a ``major
hero'' and repeated the widespread story. Falwell described how
Strong ``literally walked right up to the young man in the face of
a firing gun and said, `Give me the gun.'''
</P>
<P>
   In Strong's deposition, on Jan. 20, a transcript shows, the
lawyer for the victims' families, Mike Breen of Bowling Green, Ky.,
read him a Time magazine article published the week after the
shooting. Time, which had interviewed Strong, said that Strong
``turned his eyes'' on the killer ``and, forcefully said, `Put down
the gun.''' In his deposition, Strong said he could not guarantee
that he had actually said any of that out loud. ``Now the
forcefully part,'' he added, ``that was written by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong was questioned under oath by the lawyer for the victims'
families, partly because they had sued him, as well as school
officials and many other people here who they said could have
prevented the killings. Strong has always acknowledged that Carneal
warned him not to come to the prayer group that Monday because
something was going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   But Strong has denied that he had any reason to suspect that
Carneal would commit murder. The judge dismissed the case against
Strong and most of the other defendants.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is clear from the deposition testimony that Strong did
eventually go to Carneal while some other students ran away. He
might have reached Carneal at the same time as Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Carneal, according to the testimony, had by then stopped
shooting, discarded his gun and was slumping to the ground, perhaps
in tears. It is undisputed that when Strong and Bond arrived,
Carneal was distraught and asked Strong to ``kill me, please kill
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Carneal said in his testimony that Strong did speak as he
approached. He quoted Strong as saying: ``What are you shooting
people for?'' Then, Carneal said, Strong groaned, gritted his teeth
and took Carneal by the shoulders and shook him.
</P>
<P>
   Strong ended two brief interviews recently by saying that he was
not comfortable talking about the subject any longer. But he was
accepting of the idea that the story of what happened the day of
the shooting might be different from the one that is widely known.
``Truth is truth,'' he said very quietly. ``That's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition, Strong suggested that he wanted to be brave.
But in shock, he said, ``Your body doesn't function like it
normally does.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first days, the story of Strong as a hero may have
been beyond his ability to control it. In large ways and small, the
story was being used by other people who wanted a hero in a
tragedy, including the news media. But in West Paducah, the
families of the murdered girls seethed because they believed Strong
was profiting from their daughters' deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got some problems, some reason he has to think of
himself as a hero,'' said Joe James, whose daughter Jessica was
killed in the shooting. The parents of the three girls who were
killed all said they were infuriated by a Web site, bstrong.com,
that advertised a CD with a song by professional artists titled
``BStrong'' and included remarks from Strong. In the recent
interview, Strong said he had not received any proceeds from the
sale of the CD. The producers of the CD have said it was a
fund-raising effort for the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever part Strong played in perpetuating his story, his
public image has quietly divided people here. To some, he remains a
young man who, no matter what, represents positive values in stark
contrast to those of the killer.
</P>
<P>
   But some here say the Ben Strong story has overshadowed the
tragedy itself and they are bitter about him. In May, about 30
students from a parochial school near here, Christian Fellowship
School, traveled to an intramural event at Oral Roberts University,
the Christian college in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   In a large meeting for all the high school students, a speaker
told the assembled crowd that teen-agers today should be more like
Ben Strong, the student who confronted the killer in West Paducah,
said Cathy Davis, a parent from here who was with the group as a
chaperone.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, the parochial school group rose and left the room, said
people who were there. ``Some of the kids were terribly offended,''
Davis said, ``because they know Ben Strong is not the hero he was
played up to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
