<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1510 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SPINAL-INJURY-NYT     07-24 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPINAL-INJURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FINE MINDS, TESTED BY FAILING BODIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 By LESLIE BERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her 1961 poem, ``Grace,'' Maxine Kumin described hens pecking
on gravel and the invincible armor one might gain by similarly
ingesting small stones. ``I find it good to line my gut,'' she
wrote, ``with tidy octagons of grit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four decades later, as she lay immobilized in the
hospital with a nearly fatal spinal cord injury, Kumin's kernels of
redemption were the words she managed to connect to her thoughts
and ultimately commit to paper, at first dictating them when her
own hands were incapable of typing. Although ``Grace'' didn't
specifically come to mind as she kept her journal, Kumin said in a
telephone interview, she has no doubt that writing (and her
daughter Judith, who helped her to write) was her salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's what saved me, really. But words have always been
what saved me,'' she said from her New Hampshire farm.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting book, ``Inside the Halo and Beyond: The Anatomy of
a Recovery'' (W.W. Norton &AMP; Co.), offers a clear description, in
accessible terms, of spinal cord injuries and the harrowing methods
used to help patients regain the use of their bodies. Though Kumin
is an avowed atheist, this memoir is nonetheless a testament to
self-discipline and the power of creative expression. For those
interested in the life of one of the country's pre-eminent poets,
``Inside the Halo and Beyond'' is filled with insights into her
childhood, her marriage, her relationships with her children and
the deep connection she feels to nature.
</P>
<P>
   The title of her memoir comes from the metal bird-cagelike
contraption that was literally pinned into her skull to keep her
head and neck from moving and give her spinal cord a chance to
heal. An avid equestrian, Kumin regained consciousness inside the
device after her beloved horse Deuter bolted on July 21, 1998,
throwing her from the carriage she was driving and fracturing the
top two vertebrae of her spine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine a human head inside the cage fastened by four titanium
pins that dig into the skull,'' she writes. ``The pins are as sharp
as ice picks. I wake up in this cage, disoriented, desperate,
sicker than I have ever been. No feeling in my arms or legs, but a
vague sense that my head is entrapped forever. No movement left or
right, up or down. I am a stationary parrot inside my strict cage.
... Some orthopedic wag dubbed this form of axial traction a
halo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer Prize-winning poet remained in the halo for three
excruciating months, until X-rays and other tests showed the
vertebrae had fused back together on their own. She was spared the
life-threatening surgery that the actor Christopher Reeve, for one,
was forced to undergo after his own 1995 horseback riding accident.
In Kumin's case, her mystified would-be surgeon pronounced her
condition a miracle; most people who suffer her type of injury
either die or, like Reeve, become paralyzed. Today, she is hiking
again, driving, carefully riding Deuter, cooking and trying to wean
herself from painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   During her recovery, the fiercely independent Kumin, who was 73
at the time of her accident, endured constant pain, grueling
therapy, the fear that she might always be impaired, and the
indignities of being catheterized. Exposing herself in a memoir
seemed easy by comparison, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything becomes so public when your body is almost
destroyed,'' she said. ``You have no autonomy. You're full of
tubes, your bodily functions are not within your control. You're
completely infantilized, you just become a piece of flesh. By
writing about it, it was a way of regaining some small piece of
autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kumin also forced herself to read, sometimes only a paragraph at
a time because of the awkward position of her head, and she drew
upon her memory bank of poems. Inside the claustrophobic tube of an
MRI, for example, she recites A.E. Housman's ``A Shropshire Lad''
to the medical machine's thumping beat. She was fearless, almost
masochistic, in her choice of reading materials, which included
medical articles and Reeve's own heartbreaking 1998 memoir, ``Still
Me'' (Random House).
</P>
<P>
   Like Kumin, Reeve was supported through his injury by a loving
and resourceful family. While Kumin's kin sustained her with
baskets of fresh vegetables from her garden, Reeve's relatives
faithfully served up fan mail to nourish his spirit through the
worst of his depression. With his spinal cord completely severed (
Kumin's was merely ``dinged'') it was immediately clear he faced
life without the use of his arms and legs and would need a
ventilator to help him breathe.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, the actor best known as Superman candidly
chronicles his suicidal thoughts and the constant dread that he
would suffocate. ``A large part of the fear was because I couldn't
take a single breath on my own,'' he writes. ``And the connections
of the hoses on these ventilators are tenuous at best. The nurses
put tape over the joints, but they don't always hold very well, and
you lie there at three in the morning in fear of a pop-off, when
the hose just comes off the ventilator. I had several. After you've
missed two breaths, an alarm sounds. You just have to hope that
someone will come very quickly. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Reeve's fine mind and education kick in when his
body fails him and, like Kumin, he finds salvation in his work. His
book culminates with his directing, from his wheelchair, the HBO
movie, ``In the Gloaming.'' He concludes that ``a hero is an
ordinary individual who finds the strength to persevere and endure
in spite of overwhelming obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these authors is ordinary, of course; but, as their
books attest, their use of their talents in response to their cruel
accidents make them all the more remarkable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
