<HEADER>
A1513 &Cx1f; sci-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-NETHERLANDS-LE     07-24 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NETHERLANDS-LEIDEN-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEIDEN, WHERE REMBRANDT WAS BORN, EVEN THE PILGRIMS VISITED FOR A
WHILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: 3rd take is a 600-word guide to lodging and museums.) 
 (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By CHRISTOPHER HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leiden, a walkable city on two small branches of the Rhine
River, is something more than a nice little Dutch town, as it was
once described to me by a friend who lived there. Although
unmistakably Dutch in appearance _ with quiet neighborhoods of
gabled, canalside houses and a small open-air market selling North
Sea herring and wheels of Gouda _ Leiden's window on the world is
larger than its population of 117,000 would indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Almost since the founding of its university in 1575, the city
has attracted some of the brightest minds in Europe, and these days
scholars from around the world go there to teach and conduct
research. The 11,000 students who attend the University of Leiden
and fill the city's dark, smoky coffeehouses keep things from
getting too fusty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of its academic tradition and the Netherlands'
historic role as a crossroads of international commerce, Leiden is
a city of museums. With the exception of Amsterdam, which is 35
minutes northeast by train and has a population nearly seven times
that of Leiden, no other city in the Netherlands has such a broad
range of museums _ a dozen, large and small, covering everything
from classical antiquities to the history of medicine, to
windmills. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For its size, Leiden is unusually rich in historic sites.
Rembrandt was born there; the city was an early center of
publishing and medicine, and the first tulips in Holland were
planted in the university's botanical garden. In the 17th century
America's Pilgrim Fathers took refuge in Leiden before leaving for
the New World. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given our brief two days there in March, my partner, Mac, and I
decided to limit our museumgoing to three or four institutions and
our historic sites to those we could see on a leisurely walk around
Leiden's compact city center. It proved to be a good plan, although
we had to make several adjustments when confronted with unexpected
closures and renovations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that many of the museums are closed on Mondays, we
arrived on a Tuesday. It was a cold and gray morning on the cusp of
spring at the city's modern glass-and-steel train station. Exiting
through a sea of bicycles parked outside the station, we walked 10
minutes to the Rapenburg, a handsome tree-lined canal along which
some of Leiden's most prosperous citizens built stately homes in
the 17th century, when the city was flush with money from the
production of woolen cloth. We stopped briefly to leave our bags at
the Hotel De Doelen, a converted 1638 neo-Classical mansion where
we were spending the night, and then continued to the university
and its botanical garden. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The origins of the university and of Leiden's eventual
prominence lie in a Spanish siege of the city in 1574 during the
Protestant Dutch revolt against the iron rule of Catholic Spain.
Thousands of its citizens died of starvation and disease during the
siege, and popular belief has it that the mayor, one Van der Werf,
convinced a ravenous mob not to surrender only by offering his own
body as food. A nice story, but as noted with admirable candor in a
booklet I picked up at Leiden's tourist office, ``its accuracy is
dubious, since the annals show that Van der Werf had to be
dissuaded from opening the gates to the Spaniards on more than one
occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The booklet also casts doubt on another popular belief, that the
university was a gift from William of Orange in appreciation for
Leiden's successful resistance. Instead, it appears, the Protestant
Low Countries needed their own university, and Leiden made sense
because it was freed early on from Spain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main ceremonial building of the university, the Academy
(Academiegebouw), occupies a former Dominican convent on the
Rapenburg. A dignified, two-story brick structure with a steep
slate roof and a domed bell tower, the Academy still resembles a
church, although it is now used for lectures and official
university functions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behind the Academy is the university's Hortus Botanicus, a
botanical garden originally laid out in 1590 as a place to grow and
study medicinal and poisonous plants. In the 16th century such
gardens were common at universities with medical schools, but the
first curator of Leiden's garden, the Flemish botanist Carolus
Clusius, eventually had the novel idea of creating a place where
all known plants would be collected and studied. As a result,
imports from the New World _ such as the tomato, the potato,
tobacco and corn _ were introduced into Northern Europe through the
Leiden garden. Clusius also introduced tulips to Holland (they were
originally from Turkey), first planting them in the Hortus in
1594. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the centuries, Clusius' garden has grown into a large oasis
of old trees, flowers and thousands of plant species from around
the world, although on the day we visited the entrance was torn up
by the construction of a new winter garden (which opened in May),
and the garden still had its bare, winter look. As we walked
around, however, we did come across a few signs of spring _ several
beds of crocus, swelling nodes on an ancient wisteria, and a
scattering of solitary daffodils, whose yellow blooms looked
particularly vibrant under the steely sky.
</P>
<P>
   A light drizzle eventually drove us into the garden's extensive
greenhouses, where we happily wandered through the heavy, warm air,
passing under towering tree ferns and stopping to examine a
carnivorous plant from Borneo or cerise-colored blooms sprouting
like miniature feather boas from the branches of a New Guinea
euphorbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back outside, we retraced our steps along the Rapenburg to the
National Museum of Antiquities (Rijksmuseum van Oudheden). It's the
principal archaeological museum in the Netherlands, and we'd been
looking forward to seeing its outstanding collection of Egyptian
and Classical Greek and Roman artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, we found the museum in the midst of a major
renovation (scheduled to be completed next spring), and most of its
permanent collection was on loan or in storage. What we did see
whetted our appetites _ papyrus manuscripts, beautifully
proportioned Greek vases, translucent alabaster cups and solemn,
marble busts of eminent Romans. We both enjoyed a small display
devoted to the ancient Egyptian love of beer, and also managed to
peek into the museum's most dramatic gallery (which was closed): a
covered courtyard filled with heroic-sized statuary and an entire
temple of Isis rescued from the rising waters behind the Aswan
Dam. &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1514 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-NETHERLANDS-LE     07-24 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NETHERLANDS-LEIDEN-$ADV30-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Aswan Dam.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We ate a light lunch at Camino Real, a cozy, two-level
restaurant that occupies a former stable just around the corner
from the Academy. Surrounded by an animated university crowd of
professorial types in worn tweed jackets and students in jeans and
T-shirts, we split a bowl of flavorful celery-onion soup and a
sandwich of cheese, smoked salmon, avocado and mixed greens on
Italian flatbread. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the time we finished, the overcast sky had yielded to
brilliant blue with billowing white clouds, so we spent the rest of
the afternoon walking around Leiden's center, stopping frequently
to investigate a shop or a historic building, or to admire spring
blooms placed in the front window of a house. Here and there were
mural-sized poems painted on the sides of buildings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Pieterskerk, a large old church a block off the Rapenburg,
now used for concerts and other nonreligious functions, we saw a
memorial plaque dedicated to John Robinson, the Pilgrims' spiritual
leader. The Pilgrims arrived in Leiden in 1609 and left for America
in 1620, in part because they feared that cosmopolitan Leiden would
corrupt their morals. Robinson intended to join them later but
never made it, dying in Leiden in 1625. We weren't able to see
inside the church since it was closed, but on a nearby pedestrian
lane of pleasant shops and restaurants (Pieterskerk-Choorsteeg) we
did spot a plaque marking the site of the Pilgrims' printing
press. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across from the church, at Kloksteeg 21, we sat for a while in
the quiet, grassy courtyard of the 1683 almshouse that replaced
Robinson's residence. During Leiden's golden era, well-to-do
individuals _ some getting on in years and worried about the
salvation of their souls _ built small houses where elderly poor
people could live for free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The almshouses are known in Dutch as ``hofjes,'' or ``little
courtyards,'' because they were traditionally built around a common
court that had a single opening onto the street. While many of
Leiden's 35 existing hofjes are now private residences, some
courtyards are open to the public; the visitors center has a
brochure outlining a walking tour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day we arrived at the National Museum of the History of
Science and Medicine, known as the Boerhaave Museum, just as it was
opening. It had not been high on our list of museums, but our
friend Oliver Moore, who had recently moved to the city, had
convinced us that it had more to offer than pickled brains and
scary old surgical implements. It is housed in a beautifully
renovated building where Herman Boerhaave (1668-1738), an innovator
in clinical medicine, founded one of the first teaching hospitals
in the world. The collection is quirky _ ranging from exquisitely
crafted microscopes of polished brass to an amusing display of
antique apothecary shop signs from Amsterdam, each depicting a
human head with mouth agape. I was particularly fascinated by a
reconstruction of Leiden's Theatrum Anatomicum, a steeply raked
anatomical theater where Boerhaave and others performed human
dissections while skeletons and other memento mori loomed
overhead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Later that day we toured a collection of old Dutch tile,
household furnishings and paintings at the Lakenhal Municipal
Museum (Stedelijk Museum De Lakenhal), which occupies the city's
1640 cloth hall. In the galleries we saw one of Rembrandt's
earliest dated paintings, ``An Unidentified Historical Subject,'' a
fussy mythological scene from 1625 that is far more detailed and
far less striking than his mature works. Although Rembrandt first
studied painting in Leiden, he became famous only after settling in
Amsterdam in 1631. His boyhood home no longer exists, but other
sites connected with his youth in Leiden _ such as the street
(Weddesteeg) where he grew up and the Latin School on
Lokhorststraat where he studied _ still survive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the day, while on our way to the train
station, we stopped at the restored 18th-century windmill that now
houses the Valk Municipal Windmill Museum (Stedelijk Molenmuseum De
Valk). The Valk is one of about 950 windmills left in the
Netherlands, down from 10,000 about 100 years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's wife, Ts'ai Ch'in, had encouraged us to visit the Valk,
and once inside I could see why. After a brief look at the
informative historical displays, we clambered up ladder-like steps,
passed the massive grinding wheels and stepped onto the outside
platform, where the mill's huge sails swooped precariously close to
our heads. Although we had a train to catch, we lingered a few
minutes, enjoying a bird's-eye view of Leiden and the bracing feel
of North Sea wind on our faces.  &QR;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
