<HEADER>
A1517 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-XFILES25-COX     07-24 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-XFILES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    X-Files gets its character transfusion
 &HT;    By Kevin Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ One of the keys to ``The X-Files' `` success
is that the show always raises more questions than it answers. Who
or what got Scully pregnant? Is she really pregnant? Will she have
the baby? Is Cigarette Smoking Man dead? Can Mulder still eat
sunflower seeds in outer space? OK, you get the point. The moody,
paranormal drama always leaves you wanting more.
</P>
<P>
   No one teases audiences better than series creator Chris Carter.
He did it again after Fox officially announced that Robert Patrick,
who played the shape-shifting killing machine in ``Terminator 2,''
will join the cast as special agent John Doggett. As part of his
agreement to return for an eighth season, David Duchovny will only
appear in only 11 of the 20 episodes, including Nov. 5's season
opener. Patrick, however, will be in all 20.
</P>
<P>
   So, just who is this Doggett guy?
</P>
<P>
   Carter says that Doggett, unlike Mulder, is an insider at the
FBI, a by-the-book agent and former New York City detective. Like
Scully (Gillian Anderson) used to be, Doggett will be a skeptic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a person who's doubting by nature,'' Carter says. ``He
really is one of these people who needs to see it, touch it, smell
it, taste it, feel it, in order to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   While Doggett will team with Scully to find Mulder, they will
not become partners _ not immediately, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a gradual, hopefully, realistic integration of
the character into the series,'' Carter says.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly more than 100 actors were considered for one of TV's
most coveted roles. But Carter says Patrick stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Patrick embodied this character,'' he says.
``Everything from the timbre of his voice to his presence, to his
intensity. Because he's going to be on screen with Scully a lot, I
saw them as worthy adversaries and worthy partners. He was not
going to be a person that would shrink because she's a very
powerful person and actor.''
</P>
<P>
   If you remember Patrick's menacing Terminator character in T2,
you know exactly what Carter's talking about. Not many guys can
convincingly throw Arnold Schwarzenegger through a wall. Patrick
was also effectively creepy as an alien teacher in ``The Faculty.''
I say give Patrick some macho fight scenes with the beefy alien
bounty hunter.
</P>
<P>
   When I first heard in May that Duchovny would be in only half of
next season's episodes, I was concerned. After all, this
still-stellar drama is built around the chemistry between Mulder
and Scully. But change is good. Like all long-running shows,
sometimes ``The X-Files'' is a tad stale. Adding new blood should
give it a boost. Bringing in new cast members certainly hasn't hurt
``Law &AMP; Order.'' ``NYPD Blue'' always gets better for a few weeks
after a new detective joins the squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's afraid of change,'' Carter says. ``But that doesn't
mean you can't threaten the paradigm, or that you can't threaten
the model.''
</P>
<P>
   What has been threatened was Carter's relationship with
Duchovny. Last year, the actor filed a multimillion-dollar lawsuit
against Twentieth Century Fox Film Corp. Duchovny claimed the
company cheated him out of millions in X-Files-related profits. On
top of that, Duchovny's suit alleged that Carter (who was not a
defendant) conspired with Fox to keep quiet about the depleted
profit sharing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still am yet to understand, truly, what it is I was accused
of doing and have it articulated to me in any kind of
understandable way,'' Carter says. ``There's still a little bit of
a mystery to me, but lawsuits are mysterious. I'm happy just to
move on and try to do the good work that we've done together.''
</P>
<P>
   The X-Files isn't Carter's only series. ``The Lone Gunmen,''
based on the X-Files' geeky trio of conspiracy theorists, is
scheduled to debut next year. But don't expect another dark drama.
Carter, it seems, has learned his lesson from ``Millennium'' and
``Harsh Realm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like Mission: Impossible on laughing gas,'' he
says, ``It's a light touch and approach, and I think that we're
doing some things we would never have done on ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fox announced ``MAD TV'' will add two cast members this fall.
Comedians Nelson Ascencio and Christian Duguay will join the
late-night sketch comedy for its sixth season. Ascencio appeared in
several episodes last season, including one in which he played
Ricky Martin. This will be Duguay's national television debut.
</P>
<P>
   The list of celebrity voices on ``King of the Hill'' keeps
getting longer and longer. This year you'll hear Lisa Kudrow,
Brendan Fraser, Snoop Dogg and former Texas Gov. Ann Richards on
Fox's hit comedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quote of the weekend: ``Has anyone else noticed that we
basically, blatantly ripped off the HBO series ``OZ'' with our
structure? Anybody? I mean, except we're a lot funnier and (we
have) no prison rape scenes ... yet. We have opening titles that
look like they were thrown together in a garage in Van Nuys in
about four hours. They were, except it took two hours.'' _
Christopher Titus on his hit comedy ``Titus.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
