<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1518 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-24 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING OUT FOR THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite all the pious promises of government
cost-cutting and taxpayer refunds, members of Congress are happily
willing to make one exception to their stingy budget mood:
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The House quietly gave itself a $3,800 pay raise last week,
upping the annual salary to a tidy $145,5000, plus the usual perks
and special benefits. Why are we not surprised? Our legislative
worthies have always known how to look after their own financial
interests.
</P>
<P>
   What is a surprise, however, is how little a fuss this is
causing so far. In the past, congressional pay raises have been
about as popular as a bawling child in a small theater.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Congress was so desperate to raise members'
pay without taking the political consequences that it cowered
behind a presidential commission, which predictably embraced the
notion of a regular windfall for Capitol Hill. Conservative
talk-show audiences went nuts, turning the issue into raw material
for incumbents' next campaign opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was that Congress created a clever mechanism in 1989
that would automatically grant cost-of-living raises unless
Congress specifically voted to block them. That's what happened in
the House. Without technically going for the gold, lawmakers
granted themselves their third pay raise in four years, their
second in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is likely to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   This boost will cost taxpayers an additional $2.5 million a
year. Not a budget-busting sum in a year with a projected budget
surplus of $100 billion. And it does not reflect partisan greed. A
majority of both Democrats and Republicans were for it.
</P>
<P>
   So should we care, really, how much Congress pays itself?
</P>
<P>
   We have no tradition of rewarding our elected representatives on
the basis of merit. We pay the dummies, the demagogues and the
hard-working, well-meaning policy-makers the same. You get elected;
you get paid.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot less than Dick Cheney's annual salary as boss of the
Halliburton Corporation in Dallas, which was $1.2 million last year
plus a $1.15 million bonus plus income from all his company stock.
If he becomes the Republican vice presidential nominee and wins,
Cheney will take a big pay cut. (Included in the congressional hike
is a boost in the vice president's $175,000 salary, bringing it to
a little less than $180,000).
</P>
<P>
   That's less than the next president's salary, which will go up
to $400,000 next year, double the present $200,000. But it's a lot
more than most American families earn. The median family income in
1998 was $46,737.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Congress wants a pay raise, somebody argues that a
hefty income is necessary to keep attracting the best-quality
candidates. This, of course, is a joke. There is never a lack of
ambitious men and women clamoring for the opportunity to find good
times and glory in Washington. And often their congressional pay
amounts to more money than they were making back home.
</P>
<P>
   Legally lining one's own pockets may not be politically lethal
any more, but it's still nothing to brag about. Hillary Rodham
Clinton, for instance, was quick to attack her New York Republican
rival for the U.S. Senate seat, Rep. Rick Lazio, for not voting to
block the pay raise bill. She pointed out that Lazio had campaigned
against House pay raises in principle but backed away when the
question applied to himself. Lazio responded that, golly, gee, the
pay raise was embedded in a big budget bill and he was really just
voting for the other items included in it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mystery why voters are not furious about this backdoor
pay hike. One theory is that people are so contented with the flush
economy no one begrudges the lawmakers taking a share. Another is
that conservative talk-radio hosts are not as enthusiastic about
dumping on a Congress controlled by Republicans as they were when
the Democrats were in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The days are apparently past when callers shouted, ``Why don't
all those stuffed shirts just live off their bribes?'' Maybe,
however, all this good-natured calm is merely temporary. Wait until
the next recession hits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the income disparity between our national lawmakers
and their constituents continues to grow. This is not healthy. It
is easy to lose touch with reality when you are surrounded by
perquisites of power unavailable to the rest of the country.
Members of Congress sometimes deserve our respect and honor. But
they also need to feel our pain, as a certain president would say.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
