<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-JUDGES-JUNKETS25-COX     07-24 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-JUNKETS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CORPORATE SEMINARS FOR JUDGES INFLUENCE CASES, GROUP CHARGES
 &HT;    550&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A number of rulings in recent federal environmental
cases appear to be influenced by corporate-sponsored seminars
attended by the cases' judges, a judicial watchdog group said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A study released by the Community Rights Council found that in
10 of the most dramatic departures from precedent in the last
decade, the judge striking down an environmental protection
attended one or more seminars hosted by a group the council
believes had an interest in the cases.
</P>
<P>
   In six of these cases, the judge attended a corporate-funded
seminar while the case was pending in court. In at least three, the
litigant who won a favorable ruling was ``bankrolled'' by the
seminar's sponsors, the CRC said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate special interests are attempting to buy judicial
influence at the highest levels, and it appears to be working,''
said Doug Kendall, executive director of the CRC. ``Although we
cannot say for sure the seminars had an impact on the judges'
decisions, we have compiled very compelling evidence that appears
to be more than just coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether corporations and special interests
should be able to buy influence in the courts by hosting lavish and
biased educational seminars for judges, and we believe the answer
is no,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at more than 60,000 financial disclosure
reports of federal judges between the years of 1992 and 1998. The
number of judges attending seminars increased significantly over
the course of the study, with the value of the average trip
estimated at $5,000, Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A record 88 judges attended a seminar from the three biggest
seminar-sponsoring organizations _ and with about 800 active
federal judges, that is about 10 percent of all judges taking these
trips every year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also found that only 9 percent of judges disclosed the
value of the seminar trips they are taking, but one judge reported
a corporate-sponsored trip valued at $7,367.''
</P>
<P>
   The CRC posted a database on its Web site showing privately
funded trips taken by federal judges between 1992 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall cited a District of Columbia Circuit Court judge who
changed a previous decision on habitat protection after attending a
corporate-sponsored seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stephen Williams joined an opinion to uphold habitat
protection in 1993, and two weeks later attended a week-long
seminar held by the Foundation for Research on Economics and the
Environment, a non-profit organization that has several timber
company executives on its board, Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning, Williams granted a rare rehearing, switched his
vote and wrote an opinion striking down a portion of the Endangered
Species Act prohibiting habitat modifications that would harm
endangered species, Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the Foundation for Research on Economics and the
Environment refuses to disclose who funds their organization, it is
hard to say for certain that FREE received money from timber
companies at the time of Judge Williams's case,'' Kendall said.
``But I do suspect that FREE was receiving money directly from
timber companies, at the time when Judge Williams was hearing the
suit by the timber companies over the Endangered Species Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The study also cited U.S. District Judge Kenneth L. Ryskamp of
Jupiter, Fla., as taking one of the largest number of
corporate-sponsored trips in the study.
</P>
<P>
   Ryskamp, who stepped down from his Southern District of Florida
post at the beginning of this year, was cited for taking nine
seminar trips from 1992 to 1998, the sixth highest number for any
federal judge during that time, the report said. Ryskamp also could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall called for Congress to bar federal judges from attending
these corporate-sponsored seminars, and urged the Federal Judicial
Center, which conducts continuing education programs for judges, to
ask Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist to apply a similar ban.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., announced Monday he will introduce a
bill in the Senate that would ban privately funded seminars for
judges, create a travel fund for the Judicial Center so that judges
could participate in educational seminars, require approval by the
Judicial Center for all seminars attended, and require public
disclosure of the seminar after it is approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a minimum, these seminars create a perception of improper
influence that erodes the trust that the American people must have
in our judicial system,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry expects to introduce the legislation soon, after a
Republican agrees to co-sponsor it, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Community Rights Council: www.communityrights.org
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry: www.senate.gov/(tilde)kerry
</P>
<P>
   Federal Judges Trip Database: www.tripsforjudges.org
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
