<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1525 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MARY-McCARTHY-HNS &LR;      07-24 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARY-McCARTHY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITERARY FRIENDSHIP AND THE BANALITY OF EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB ARMSTRONG  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I recently wrote about famous writers who cut
each other up under the guise of thoughtful essays. I noted Mary
McCarthy's zap at Lillian Hellman: ``Every word she writes is a
lie, including `and' and `the.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although I enjoy reading about literary feuds, an enduring
literary friendship is equally appealing. In Mary McCarthy's case,
such a friendship bloomed, but only after she was foolish enough to
get in a scrap with Hannah Arendt, whose writings on the dynamics
of totalitarian regimes, terror and revolution are considered
seminal works in political philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1945. A party in Manhattan is packed with intellectuals.
With World War II coming to a close, the conversation turns to the
twisted mind of Hitler. McCarthy, always inclined to stir up a
hornet's nest, casually remarks she feels pity toward Hitler
because he is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Arendt, who was driven out of Germany in 1933 and emigrated to
the United States in 1941, is deeply offended. She snaps at
McCarthy, asks her how she could make such a noxious remark, walks
away.
</P>
<P>
   They ran with the same brainy crowd, but avoided each other for
three years. Then Arendt approached McCarthy. ``Let's end this
nonsense,'' she said, ``We think so much alike.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a close friendship the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Their letters to each other, in ``Between Friends,'' edited by
Carol Brightman, show a lively exchange between the novelist's
concern with rage in the bedroom and the political philosopher's
concern with same in the totalitarian mind.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy pours it all out. Arendt is aloof. She seeks Arendt's
advice on the studly brainiacs coming and going, including three
husbands. McCarthy expects her men to change. Arendt is more in
tune with the hard wiring embedded in the heterosexual male and
suggests Mary either leave them ``as is'' _ or leave them.
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, both came under heavy critical fire
within a few months of each other in 1963. McCarthy's novel about
eight girls at Vassar, ``The Group,'' hit the best-seller list, but
got trashed as low-brow pulp. Even worse, according to Norman
Mailer, it was merely a ``lady-book.''
</P>
<P>
   Arendt's troubles were far greater after the publication of her
book with an ominous phrase in its sub-title: ``Eichmann in
Jerusalem: A Report on the Banality of Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   In attempting to comprehend the incomprehensible _ the Holocaust
_ Arendt argued that Adolf Eichmann was not a monster or sadist
like those in the SS, but a friendly guy, a perfect family man with
the careerist ambitions of a mid-level manager, a terrific
facilitator who coolly assisted in directing the flow of ``cargo''
in cattle cars moving east.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as McCarthy said of Eichmann in an essay defending Arendt,
``Had Mein Kampf been his `Bible,' he might have pressed a flower
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the banality of evil.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Arendt's striking formulation is generally accepted in
intellectual circles, but at the time it raised howls of protest.
Jews were especially upset because Arendt noted the Jewish
Councils' compliance with Nazi demands to turn over the names of
those in their congregations, which greased the wheels for their
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charged she had trivialized Eichmann's role, exonerated
him from responsibility and slandered Jews. Her character came
under attack _ whispered asides about the ``self-hating Jewess,''
calculated slips of the tongue calling her ``Hannah Eichmann.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the letters to McCarthy she wrote: ``What a risky
business to tell the truth on a factual level without theoretical
or scholarly embroidery.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is theory in her report on Eichmann's trial. Not
embroidery, but careful stitching which can't be seen, for it is
theory grounded in the reality of the 20th century's darkest time.
</P>
<P>
   And I can't help but wonder if the seed for Arendt's thoughts on
Eichmann was planted at a party years earlier when she turned her
back on McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   After all, doesn't the intemperate remark about feeling sorry
for Hitler, on grounds of absurdity, illustrate perfectly the
banality of evil?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
