<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-24 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INDEFENSIBLE DEFENSE OF NAZI GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The German historian who has made a specialty of
defending Nazi Germany rationalized Hitler's persecution of the
Jews as part of the Fuehrer's war against Bolshevism.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst Nolte has been at it for years, but only now has been
rewarded with the prestigious Konrad Adenauer Prize, considered
Germany's top literary honor.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte argued that as so many Jews were communists, Hitler's
anti-Semitic policies should be regarded as part of praiseworthy
efforts to combat the Red Menace to Western civilization.
</P>
<P>
   This assertion is hardly new, having been made by the Nazi
themselves, who also, however, contrived to explain their
persecution of the Jews in terms of fighting international
capitalism as well.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte's interpretation would be laughable were it not for the
literary prize and the support that betokens among at least a
significant segment of the German establishment. Of course, that
same stolid establishment climbed aboard the Nazi bandwagon with
alacrity when Hitler was building his power.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently overlooked in the recognition of Nolte's work is
that virulent German anti-Semitism preceded the rise of communism.
Furthermore, history reveals that the German government itself did
more to foster Bolshevism than any number of Jewish adherents
possibly could have done.
</P>
<P>
   During World War I, it was the regime of Kaiser Wilhelm that
bent extraordinary efforts to build communist power. It did so by
sending Vladimir Lenin, the man who made the Bolshevik revolution
and led it through its formative years, from his Swiss exile back
to Russia in a sealed railway car, with the specific expectation
that he would foment revolution to undermine the czar and take
Russia out of the war.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the most important victories Germany ever won.
</P>
<P>
   If the Nolte logic is to be applied, then Hitler should not only
have singled out Jews as a target, but all of Wilhelmine Germany,
as well as the more numerous people of Christian background who
contributed so much more to the rise and early success of
communism, such as it was.
</P>
<P>
   What a farce this whole Nolte matter is. There is no conceivable
rationalization for the racist policies, whose end was murder _ not
of Jews, not of Christians, not of imperial Germans, nor any one
else. The very idea is absurd. What, except the power to do so,
could possibly justify the pitiless slaughter of children, women
and men who had never been communists or anything else?
</P>
<P>
   Having been the foremost target of czarist persecution, having
been denied entry to preferred occupations, education and areas in
which to live, it is little wonder that some Jews supported
movements _ not only communist ones _ that sought to overthrow that
oppressive tyranny. But once the Communists attained control, Jews
in the Soviet Union, just as in Germany and then Nazi Germany, in
the first instance were persecuted and discriminated against for
being Jews. They needed to have committed no other offense to
qualify for this treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that those who would recast the horrors of Nazi Germany
in a softer light, and excuse Germany from history's judgment, have
developed enough confidence to assert their sentiments publicly, in
Germany, Austria, even in France, is a telling sign. While many
German academics condemned Nolte, at least one well-regarded
historian, Horst Moller, director of the what is described as the
``highly respected'' Institute for Contemporary History, defended
Nolte's work.
</P>
<P>
   I write on this subject from the perspective of having lived the
first 10 years of my life in Nazi Germany, escaping Hitler's
``anti-Bolshevik'' campaign at nearly the last minute. My wife also
lived as a child in Nazi Germany. Our relatives who could not
emigrate were slaughtered. Not a one was a Communist.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Karksi died 10 days ago. His was not a household name, but
it is in mine. He was the Polish diplomat who saw with his own eyes
what the Holocaust was doing to Poland's Jews and brought word of
it to the West to seek help. Few believed him; it was too
incredible. Help was not forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Today we know too much to disregard warning signs. As
right-wing, racist policies gain respectability in Europe, alarm
bells should disturb our self-satisfaction and tranquility, lest
before we know it, it will be too late again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
