<SLUG> BC-CYC-OLYLANCE0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Next competition for Armstrong will be Sydney Olympics
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - What's left and what's next for Lance Armstrong
might be one and the same.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's next high-profile cycling competition will be at the
Olympics in Sydney. The two-time Tour de France champion is also a
two-time Olympian, but without the same measure of success.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, Armstrong finished 14th in
the men's individual road race behind winner Fabio Casartelli of
Italy. At the Atlanta Games in 1996, he was 12th behind champion
Pascal Richard of Switzerland, and finished sixth in the individual
time trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance really wants to win an Olympic gold medal,'' said his
coach, Chris Carmichael. ``It's driven him for a long time, and
he's in good shape for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States formally will announce its five-man road-race
team on Aug. 1. The only entry officially on the squad is Antonio
Cruz of Long Beach, Calif., for winning the May 20 Olympic trials
road race in Jackson, Miss. But it's a certainty Armstrong will be
included, barring anything unforeseen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be naming the team, and I'd be a pretty stupid coach if
he wasn't on it,'' Jim Ochowicz, the U.S. men's road cycling coach,
said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men have had little success in Olympic individual road
racing. Their best finish was third in 1912 by Carl Schutte. In
more recent times, George Mount's sixth-place showing in Montreal
in 1976 has been the highest by a U.S. representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being an Olym and be a medalist, not just a member of the
team. His goal is to win a gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   The road racing portion of the Olympics will be held Sept.
26-27, with individual time trials on Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Randy Riggs at rriggs(at)statesman.com or
445-3957.
</P>
