<HEADER>
A1535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOWS-RECEIVERS     07-24 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOWS-RECEIVERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' GALLOWAY OFFERS MORE THAN JUST SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRENT ZWERNEMAN  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Receiver Joey Galloway has big hair,
fleet feet and Dallas Cowboys coach Dave Campo making up big words
about his big-time speed.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Cowboys expect big things from their $42 million
addition who sports a sprouting Afro.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt Joey Galloway gives you the `stretchability'
that you need,'' Campo said of probably the fastest Cowboys
receiver since Bob Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' other starting receiver, Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail,
has jets himself. So who's faster?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess that Joey is, but he's deceptively faster
because he doesn't look like he's moving as quick as Rocket,'' said
quarterback Troy Aikman, who knows better than anyone. ``That's
taken a little bit of getting used to.''
</P>
<P>
   A little bit of getting used to? Compared to last year, when
injuries racked an already-thin receiving corps, it's like Aikman
traded in a compact for a Corvette, and now must adapt to the new
accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are subtle changes when you've got that kind of speed,''
Aikman said. ``The angles of the throws are different and where
you've got to lay the ball becomes different.''
</P>
<P>
   And apparently Campo has inherited a different Galloway, or at
least one unlike the one portrayed last year as a super-selfish
Seattle Seahawk after an eight-week holdout while still under
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``That perception is something as a player you can't do a whole
lot about,'' Galloway said. ``People are going to have their
opinions, I just have to go out and do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said Galloway, whom the Cowboys acquired in February for
two No. 1 picks, is better than advertised, and gives Dallas a
receiver who can catch outside and inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's been given enough credit on his ability to
catch the ball over the middle,'' Campo said. ``He's as fast a guy
as I've ever been around when he comes out of his cut and
accelerates. And he's not a small guy. Rocket is more slight and is
more of a deep outside-type of receiver, whereas Galloway can come
inside for the football.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cowboys offensive coordinator Jack Reilly: ``Joey can run
good patterns for a fast guy. He's not some big `track guy,' who's
just stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry signed the 28-year-old Galloway to a $42
million contract over seven years and included a $12 million
signing bonus, in an effort to crank open the closing window of
another shot at a Super Bowl in the era of Aikman, who turns 34
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway played five seasons with the Seahawks, showing flashes
that he could join the league's elite. But he's never quite reached
the level of Tampa Bay's Keyshawn Johnson, another high-profile
off-season free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Three times, Galloway surpassed a thousand yards receiving in a
season _ although never more than 1,049 _ and he's made a couple of
Pro Bowls. His best season came in 1997, when he caught 72 passes.
</P>
<P>
   Jets cornerback Aaron Glenn knows Galloway all too well, having
surrendered 70- and 57-yard touchdown passes to him in the same
game two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said the Cowboys must tap into the versatility of
Galloway, who played collegiately at Ohio State and was the No. 8
overall pick in the 1995 NFL Draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be looking to use his speed and his ability to go
across the middle,'' Glenn said. ``Because he's the type of guy who
will go across the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Cowboys hope for, since Michael Irvin has
retired. Like Irvin, Galloway has endured a poor perception in the
league, although for entirely different reasons. While Irvin was
loved on the field for his leadership, his off-the-field escapades
got him in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As for Galloway, his long holdout last year _ he finished the
season with only 22 catches after finally being activated Nov. 13 _
earned him a reputation for selfishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that your franchise-type players understand how
necessary it is for them to conduct themselves a certain way for
the sake of the football team,'' Seattle coach Mike Holmgren said
early in Galloway's holdout last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Campo said his new receiver has become every bit the leader
early in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about him as well as anything is that he's
talking to the other receivers, and talking about things he needs
to do, and what we need to do as a group,'' Campo said. ``He's
really a team guy. We knew he was a talented player, but I think
some of the intangibles are some of the things we're really
learning right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway said he's grown into his role as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the league for six years now, and any time
there's a young guy who's doing some things that maybe I can help
with, then I try to do that,'' he said. ``When I first got to
Seattle, I had Brian Blades there, and that was sort of his job at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's time for me to pass some things around.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of passing, Aikman has underthrown Galloway on several
occasions in camp, showing the two still have much timing work
before the season opener Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway shook off the idea Aikman's passes may not match his
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very strong-armed quarterback, and there are going to
be ones that I don't get to and some that he underthrows,''
Galloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman jokingly tells a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey has made it clear I can't overthrow him,'' Aikman said
with a grin. ``So the first time I do, write about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
