<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DEION-SANDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS FANS LEARNING TO LOVE THE MAN THEY ONCE REVILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM ORSBORN  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHBURN, Va. _ Cornerback Darrell Green and defensive end Bruce
Smith are locks for the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Johnson is a Pro Bowl quarterback. Rookie tackle Chris
Samuels just signed a $30 million contract and looks every bit like
a future All-Pro.
</P>
<P>
   All four of those big-name players have had their fair share of
autograph requests since the Redskins opened training camp
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But none has even come close to attracting the kind of attention
that's been showered on one Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Just five months ago, Sanders was one of the most hated members
of Washington's chief rival. But these days, Redskins fans who used
to curse the cornerback/kick returner when he was a Dallas Cowboy
flatter him with shouts of ``Deee-on.''
</P>
<P>
   Once reviled as ``that showboating Sanders,'' the seven-time
Pro-Bowler now is the man the Redskins faithful expect to shut down
the likes of Dallas' Joey Galloway and Tampa Bay's Keyshawn
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would be wearing a Deion Sanders jersey,''
said 70-year-old Redskins fan Bill Glacken, shaking his head. ``My
two sons can't believe I'm wearing one either. But I think he'll do
our team good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Redskin now, and we've taken him in,'' said Glacken's
wife of 50 years, Fae.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we look at is, he's an ex-Atlanta Falcon, not an
ex-Cowboy,'' Mark Coran, 31, said. ``We don't claim him as being
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who turns 33 on Aug. 9, is in his 12th NFL season. He
signed a seven-year, $56 million contract with the Redskins on June
6 after spending the past five seasons with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered one of the greatest cover corners in NFL history
and called ``the ultimate weapon'' by Redskins owner Dan Snyder,
Sanders helped San Francisco win a title in 1994 and Dallas one in
'95.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams won the Super Bowl the season after acquiring
Sanders. The Redskins _ thanks to a huge off-season spending spree
by Snyder _ have been tabbed as the favorite to win Super Bowl XXXV
by many Las Vegas oddsmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the potential to win a championship,'' said Sanders,
who received an $8 million signing bonus. ``We have the potential
to do something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season wasn't one of the best of Sanders' illustrious
career. He missed the first two games with a toe injury and was
troubled by groin and hamstring problems later in the campaign. In
January, he underwent arthroscopic knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he's now injury-free and is expected to replace
17-year veteran Darrell Green as the club's starting right
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be an exciting year,'' said Sanders, who will
earn a base salary of $500,000 this season, followed by $3.5
million in 2001. ``I'm looking forward to it. I wish the season
started in a couple of weeks. I feel good. I feel like a young
Darrell Green, and Darrell is the godfather of NFL cornerbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders got burned for some long receptions last season, and
that trend continued on the first day of camp, when wide receiver
Michael Westbrook blew by ``Prime Time'' with a nifty fake and made
the reception about 40 yards downfield.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders laughed off the play, saying a fake by Johnson in the
backfield froze him.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Redskins coach) Norv (Turner) game-plans against me,''
Sanders said with a smile. ``I told him, `Just run it on the other
teams just like you ran it on me.'''
</P>
<P>
   First-year Redskins defensive coordinator Ray Rhodes didn't
exactly shower Sanders with praise after a recent practice. Rhodes
is counting on Sanders to help improve a defense that last season
ranked 30th among 31 NFL teams in total defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is running back into shape, getting his timing back,''
Rhodes said. ``He'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry-wise, Sanders seems to have fit in nicely inside the
Redskins locker room. One of his biggest fans is Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an exceptional player, an exceptional athlete,'' said
Johnson, who was Sanders' college teammate at Florida State. ``I
tell you this, I'd rather play with him than against him. He's an
exciting player, and he'll definitely make our team better.''
</P>
<P>
   Even wide receiver Albert Connell, a fourth-year pro from Texas
A&AMP;M, has embraced Sanders. Connell got into an altercation with
Sanders late in the Cowboys' 38-20 victory over the Redskins last
Oct. 24 at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Connell told reporters the week before the game that Sanders
couldn't cover him. Sanders responded by popping Connell in the
jaw. Minutes later, Sanders shook off the effects of a concussion
and returned a punt 70 yards for the game's final touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Connell said afterward that he had lost all respect for Sanders.
But now all is forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love going up against him in practice,'' Connell said. ``He
said the other day that I was really fast, and that means a lot to
me, especially when it comes from one of the fastest men on our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the most popular.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
