<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADA-BUSINESSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN EARLY CRITICS SEE THE POSITIVE SIDE OF DISABILITIES ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL DAY  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Even before the Americans With Disabilities Act
became law 10 years ago this week, it touched off waves of protests
from the business world.
</P>
<P>
   Making changes to accommodate disabled people, business leaders
said, would be prohibitively expensive, spark frivolous lawsuits
and prove especially burdensome to small business.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, attitudes have changed. While not every business
leader is a wholehearted booster of the law, known by the initials
ADA, many say that compliance has been less onerous than they
feared. Others candidly acknowledge that ADA has even been good for
business.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Decker understands how far business has come. The executive
director of a national advocacy group, Decker took part in the
enactment of ADA a decade ago. Today he continues to negotiate with
companies about providing full access to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   He recently was involved in talks between federal regulators and
Greyhound Bus Lines about making bus travel easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it would bankrupt them and put them out of
business,'' Decker said. But the bus line eventually agreed to
provide disabled-accessible buses. As it turns out, it was a
victory not only for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, I saw a letter from Greyhound that said their ridership
was up, due to disabled people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ADA, which celebrates its anniversary on Wednesday, has been
hailed as sweeping civil rights legislation. It required public
buildings and businesses to be accessible to people with limited
mobility, sight, hearing or speech.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some expense involved with compliance and
business leaders always chafe when the government dictates rules.
But fears about having to lay off workers or even being forced into
bankruptcy have not materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the employers' perspective, the ADA has not turned out to
be the practical nightmare that some predicted,'' said Dallas
lawyer Mike Abcarian, whose firm, Winstead, Sechrest &AMP; Minick,
represents employers in ADA-related matters. ``There are some
fairly definite things you have to do as an employer, and if you do
those things, you'll avoid problems with the ADA.''
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses in particular fretted about being required to
install elevators where none existed, or the burden of disabled
workers who couldn't perform basic functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``An overriding fear we had 10 years ago was, `Will we have to
hire someone to sit next to people who can't see to type for
them?''' said Linda Schoonmaker, an associate with the Dallas
office of the Seyfarth Shaw law firm. ``Little did we know that it
wasn't going to be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The implementation of ADA hasn't been entirely problem-free.
When Maverick Video Productions built a new $2 million,
20,000-square-foot headquarters in Hollywood Park two years ago, it
encountered a surprising amount of ADA-related regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building is on a lot that's slanted, so we couldn't have
any steps,'' said Maverick co-owner Pat Iverson. ``The hallways had
to be slanted, and in the dressing rooms, the hallways had to be
wide enough and we had to have a bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the requirements, she said, were easily folded into the
cost of new construction. The shocker was the $600 fee to have the
building's plans scrutinized for possible ADA violations.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Lamkin, with Dallas-based Brown Reynolds Watford
Architects, said businesses that build new headquarters often have
an easier time with ADA than those that renovate old buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting in a handicapped-accessible ramp doesn't cost any more
than putting in a non-accessible walkway,'' Lamkin said. ``You just
have to plan it from the get-go.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamkin's firm has been authorized by the state of Texas to
oversee ADA compliance in buildings. She said that immediately
after the act's passage in 1990, she saw a spate of compliance
construction in old buildings. Now, business owners usually wait
until they are renovating, then work compliance into their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Retail establishments likely would feel compelled to increase
access even without a shove from the ADA. Estimates on how many
Americans have disabilities range from 40 million to 60 million,
and that number will grow substantially as baby boomers age.
Businesses that exclude disabled customers will suffer financially,
Decker said.
</P>
<P>
   The law also has helped with employment in an era of tight labor
markets. In the decade since the ADA was passed, the nation has
experienced an economic expansion. Many employers looked to the
disabled to fill in the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   The economic expansion has alleviated some of business' pain at
having to open access. The long-running bull market started not
long after ADA was signed into law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
