charged with vehicular manslaughter. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   NURSE-SHORTAGE _ WASHINGTON _ The growing shortage of nurses can
be remedied only if hospitals make big improvements in their work
environments, officials of a nurse placement firm said Monday. Not
just higher pay but also greater job satisfaction is required,
according to officials of a Boca Raton, Fla., firm that supplies
nurses for hospitals nationwide. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES-JUNKETS _ WASHINGTON _ Corporate-backed seminars for
federal judges have been linked to a number of recent hostile
environmental rulings, according to a study released Monday by the
Community Rights Council. (O'Dell, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NUDE-DANCER _ An exotic dancer won $2.5 million from the
coordinators of the 1997 Miss Nude World International contest for
fraudulently disqualifying her because she refused to do sexual
favors. (Smith, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-TIGER _ Tiger Woods becomes the youngest player top
win golf's four major tournaments. (The Atlanta Constitution). 8.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-HISPANICPAY _ A new study finds that Hispanic workers
are disproportionately concentrated in low-wage jobs that offer few
benefits. (Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GOTTLIEB-COLUMN _ Here's why TV network executives should
realize covering political conventions is important: Since
television started covering conventions, conventions have been
pivotal in presidential elections. Never since 1948 has the lead in
a presidential election clearly switched hands after the
conventions. (Gottlieb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED Saturday, July 22.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Physical exertion has never
been high on my list of priorities. Inertia is my favored motion. I
never stand when I could be sitting, and lying down is even better.
That's why, when late last summer some unknown force urged me to
put down the book, roll my rope-plaid backside out of the Pawley's
Island hammock and get it to a gym, no one was more surprised than
I was. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I'm trying to pinpoint a
pivotal moment in the decline of the service economy. It's when
clerks, waiters, and counter help started telling you to ``have a
good one.'' (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   PC-SALES _ Sales of personal computers are down, but why? Is it
a short-term blip or a long-term trend? Digital divide? Market
saturation? Theft of customers by new technologies? Talk with
experts, analysts and those on the retail front line -- plus a look
at the numbers. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POSTAL-REVENUE _ Postal Service projects that first-class mail _
about half of its revenues _ will start delcining after 2002
because of competition from e-mail and electronic bill-paying.
Postal Service launches itw own bill payment with Atlanta-based
CheckFree, but going has apparently been slow, and will be for some
time to come because many people don't see the value and fear
security and privacy issues, say analysts. (Grantham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DIGITIAL-MUSIC _ NEW YORK_ Record companies resist digital
download, arguing it's all about rights and protecting the right to
get paid for your work at a digital conference in New York. They
actually booed the Napster guy. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
