<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JAKES _ ATLANTA _ TD Jakes is once again bringing his
ministry to Atlanta, a week-long even including two conferences and
a play. The events are expected to draw people _ over 100,000 _
from across the south. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MENDENHALL _ Laura Mendenhall, pastor of Westminster
Presbyterian Church, will be the new president of Columbia
Presbyterian Seminary in Atlanta. After Princeton, it is the most
prestigious Presbyterian school. The third most prestigious is in
Chicago, and that seminary is now run by a former teacher at Austin
Presbyterian seminary. They will be the only two Presby seminaries
run by women and both came from Austin. Mendenhall had no
intentions of leaving Austin but she was aggressively pursued by
Columbia. (Perkes, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TV _ Get ready for an avalanche of Olympics. NBC and its
cable partners will air 441 1/2 hours of coverage from the Sydney
Games _ more than 100 more than the network devoted to the
Barcelona and Atlanta Games combined. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIMP-BIZKIT _ The successful hip-hop-influenced rock band Limp
Bizkit plays a free show at the Tabernacle Monday night. The tour
is sponsored by the controversial Napster, putting Bizkit squarely
in the pro-Napster camp. Tickets are available at 10 a.m. Monday
morning, and we'll be there to ask the fans for their views on the
band, the software and the tour. (Harrision, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-XFILES _ The X-Files gets its character transfusion as Robert
Patrick joins the cast. From Pasadena, it's the fall TV tour.
(Thompson, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BROTHERSGARCIA _ Cable network debuts ``Brothers Garcia,''
one of three new Hispanic shows. From Pasadena, it's Fall TV Tour.
(Thompson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   ESHRINKS-MAIN _ Psychotherapy online is here as psychologists
and social workers provide therapy via e-mail and chat rooms. How
how good or dangerous is it for patients? Can the safeness of
anonymity and the intensity of focus make up for a lack of human
contact? A look at the methods, popularity and ethical
implications. (Kicklighter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ESHRINK-TIPS _ Tips, links to sites and how to check out your
e-shrink with accredited agencies. (Kicklighter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBO-WOHLERS _ LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Former Braves reliever Mark
Wohlers has found that life goes on, despite one setback after
another. After losing his control, then his job, with the Braves,
Wohlers is trying to make it back to the bigs with the Cincinnati
organization after elbow surgery. No longer does he have trouble
throwing the ball over the plate. But batters are having little
trouble hitting him. At least his home life is better. He will be
married in November. (Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BRAVES-HOMERS _ ATLANTA _ In 1973, the Braves set a record
by having three players with 40 or more homers (Hank Aaron, Darrell
Evans and Davey Johnson). Now Chipper Jones, Andruw Jones and
Andres Galarraga are on pace to also hit 40. But the feat no longer
means as much. Toronto could have four players reach 40. The Braves
open a three-game series with Florida on Tuesday. (Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   PROS
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS-SMITH _ Feature on Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith
who says he is the ``last of the Mohicans.'' His observations on
the 2000 offense and why he thinks it will be successful. (Cantu,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-GATTECH-PREVIEW _ Reader on Georgia Tech football coinciding
with ACC Football Kickoff. Life After Joe Hamilton begins in
earnest for the Yellow Jackets, who enter the 2000 season without
any realistic hopes of ACC Championships or BCS bowl berths. (Arey,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). W
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-STODA _ More on Tiger . . . nobody is even
</P>
<P>
   close. (Stoda, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   CYC-ARMSTRONG _ Lance Armstrong had the opportunity to spend
only a few hours at his part-time home in Nice, France, late
Monday, leaving the City of Lights a day after clinching his second
straight Tour de France championship. This morning he starts his
whirlwind publicity tour of the United States, flying to New York
and then Los Angeles before returning to France on Friday. Bill
Stapleton, Armstrong's Austin-based attorney, said Armstrong is
scheduled to appear on ``Good Morning America'' and ``Live with
Regis and Kathie Lee'' on Wednesday. There is a possibility
Armstrong will appear on other network talk shows, but those
interviews had not been set by Monday evening. (Halliburton, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CYC_OLYLANCE _ What's left and what's next for Lance Armstrong
might be one and the same. Armstrong's next high-profile cycling
competition will be at the Olympics in Sydney. The two-time Tour de
France champion is also a two-time Olympian, but without the same
measure of success. At the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, Armstrong
finished 14th in the men's individual road race behind winner Fabio
Casartelli of Italy. At the Atlanta Games in 1996, he was 12th
behind champion Pascal Richard of Switzerland, and finished sixth
in the individual time trial. (Riggs, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
