<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plenty of hype-free substance to all the Potter-maniaDon
O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adults who have dismissed the Harry Potter books as fairy tales
for children may want to change their minds after reading Joan
Acocella's assessment of J.K. Rowling's novels in The New Yorker
($3).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she notes, the Potter stories are fairy tales, but they
also are ``a bildungsroman, plus a murder mystery, plus a cosmic
war of good and evil.'' Acocella finds elements of the Arthurian
legend, the Superman comics, ``Star Wars,'' ``Cinderella,'' ``The
Lord of the Rings,'' ``The Chronicles of Narnia,'' Genesis, Exodus
and ``Paradise Lost,'' all with a touch of Jane Austen and Charles
Dickens. Rowling is not only a good psychotherapist, Acocella says,
she teaches excellent morals. ``Those parents who have objected to
the Potter series on the grounds that it promotes unchristian
values should give it another read.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Politics and personalities: In a special pre-convention issue,
George ($2.95) puts a photograph of a smiling Ronald Reagan on the
cover with the pertinent political question, ``Who will make us
proud again?'' Apparently no one in this batch of candidates. In
addition to retrospective pieces on the last two presidents who
made us feel good _ John F. Kennedy and Ronald Reagan _ the
magazine includes a viewer's guide to the conventions. If anyone
watches, that is. As the editors point out, the Democrats averaged
18 million viewers and the Republicans attracted 16.6 million in
1996. An episode of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' draws around
23 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Going with the grain: Time ($3.50) weighs in on the debate
over genetically engineered crops this week with a cover story on
Swiss professor Ingo Potrykus and his beta-carotene-enriched rice.
This golden rice could save a million kids a year, Potrykus says,
and so could other genetically improved crops. But there are a
number of concerns, including the fear that transgenic foods are
potential sources of allergens and could cause genetic pollution.
Plant scientist Florence Wambugu dismisses protests as ridiculous,
noting that nearly half the fruit and vegetable harvest is lost
because it rots on the way to market. ``If we had a transgenic
banana that ripened more slowly,'' she says, ``we could have 40
percent more bananas than now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Entertainment Weekly's ($3.50) 10th-anniversary
issue features 10 years of the best pictures from the magazine.
Photos range from the glamorous (Drew Barrymore in lingerie) to the
grotesque (a closeup of a blood-splattered Christian Bale from
``American Psycho''). ... In a revealing photo spread and interview
in W ($3.95), Jennifer Lopez talks about Puff Daddy (``he and I do
understand each other,'') her infamous dress (``I couldn't believe
it was such a big deal.'') and her prominent backside (``A little
bit of jiggly is OK if that's what your boyfriend likes.'').
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
