A1550 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JAKES25-COX     07-24 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JAKES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women breaking loose at this week's conference
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brace yourself, Atlanta. More than 80,000 women are
coming to the city this week to get loosed.
</P>
<P>
   The women are traveling from as far as England and South Africa
to attend Bishop T.D. Jakes' third annual ``Woman, Thou Art
Loosed!'' conference at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``When women get full of God, you guys step back,'' said
Paulette Fisher-Wong, 43, who is traveling from Toronto _ an
18-hour bus ride _ to listen to Jakes.
</P>
<P>
   What Fisher-Wong will hear is one of America's hottest
preachers. Last year the dome's single-day attendance record set by
the Rev. Billy Graham was broken when Jakes' attracted 81,000. The
full three-day conference drew more than a quarter-million.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes' storming of Atlanta begins today at 10 a.m. at
Underground Atlanta during a book signing at The Enterprise
bookstore and tonight at 8 at the Atlanta Civic Center when his
play, ``Behind Closed Doors,'' premieres.
</P>
<P>
   The week's activities kick into overdrive Thursday when Jakes'
three-day religious revival opens. It will offer a blend of
preaching and gospel music and center on one theme _ empowering
women.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes is a preaching pioneer. He combines theology and therapy
with a Pentecostal preaching style. It's not uncommon for women to
cry and dance at his services _ even, on occasion, collapse.
Fisher-Wong recalled one of Jakes' sermons when he explored the
issue of rape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to bawl for the people around me,'' she said. ``You
have to go around and hug people in the crowd and say, `It's OK
now, the Lord is taking over.' You become the minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes is holding a second conference this year, a ``Woman Thou
Art Loosed Plus'' revival. The three-day event, which also begins
Thursday and will be held in the World Congress Center, focuses on
economic empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes, 42, said that while the Bible's message does not center
around finances, the Bible considers it important.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heard bleeds when I meet people who have good moral
integrity but poor business principles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes, the senior pastor of the Potter's House in Dallas, a
nondenominational megachurch with 26,000 members, has not had that
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes is a savvy businessman who has created a cottage industry
that includes the ``Woman Thou Art Loosed'' revival, a best-selling
book of the same name, a special-edition Bible and a CD, ``Sacred
Love Songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher-Wong said she can't wait to shake off her Canadian
reserve this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women will be laying on the ground, crying out to God,'' she
said from her home in Toronto. ``We don't do that up here. We're so
proper. But Americans don't care who's around them. They're just in
love with God.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
