<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, July 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exceptionally cool weather for late July will linger in much of
the East. A wavering front will be the focus for clouds and
clusters of showers from the Southeast to the Middle Atlantic
States. The steadiest rain will be in the Carolinas and
southeastern Virginia as low pressure moves north along the front.
On Tuesday night and Wednesday, showers will reach most areas from
the east slopes of the central Appalachians to southern New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonable warmth and ample sunshine will cover a large area
from the Plains to the interior Southeast. After some morning
showers dissipate in the upper Mississippi Valley, a jet stream
disturbance will ignite afternoon thunderstorms in the northern
parts of the Dakotas and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be sunny and hot. A few thunderstorms will
erupt on the peaks of the central Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MISSING WARMTH
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, record low temperatures were set in several spots
from the Mississippi Valley to the upper Middle West where
overnight readings in the 50's were common. In parts of the
interior Northeast, July is averaging among the coolest in the past
100 years. In the past, unusual summer chill has been connected to
volcanic eruptions which spew fine dust into the stratosphere. In
New England, the summer of 1816, which followed the eruption of
Tambora in Indonesia, had many cool spells and was later dubbed
``the year without a summer.'' This year's chill has no volcanic
connection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
