<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CRAMER-COLUMN-STREET &LR;      07-24 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAMER-COLUMN-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SIMPLY FRUSTRATING EARNINGS SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Financial Commentary)  
 (Editors: Please note disclosure at end.)  
 
 By JAMES J. CRAMER   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This market must be driving the big boys crazy.
Time-honored patterns that made you money for years are totally
failing now, and the only people who can make money are those who
are so nimble and have so little religion that they are willing to
switch sides on a dime.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, during earnings week, I am huddled in the trenches,
checking on conference calls, listening to analysts and monitoring
the ups and downs on a minute-by-minute basis. This time I am
following it from afar, but I see something happening that is so
extraordinary that I have to pen a piece despite my vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, during the first week of earnings a whole set of
companies set the bar too high for the rest of the reporting
companies:
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! blows out numbers, so we figure America Online will blow
out numbers. Wrong!
</P>
<P>
   Altera hits it out of the park, so we guesstimate that Xilinx
will do the same. Wrong!
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsysystems advances so won't Hewlett-Packard? Not a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Unisys stumbles, so shouldn't we be short IBM? Really wrong!
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase ramps, so shouldn't Lucent? Nope, no way.
</P>
<P>
   Novellus looks great, so why not take some Teradyne or some
Applied Materials? Oops!
</P>
<P>
   For fund managers used to predicting what will happen based on
patterns of other companies, this summer is one of the most
frustrating periods in memory. You simply can't forecast. You can't
make a judgment right now from one company to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this forecasting problem is no big deal if you are an
individual who owns a handful of stocks for the long term. But it
is a nightmare if you are a mutual fund manager who owns millions
of shares of a company and have no hope of even remotely getting
out after one of these Xilinx-like disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, capital gets ground down and managers get
increasingly antsy. They can't seem to get it right. But they have
to be in, they have to own a lot of stocks, and they can't just
stay away from the casino.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot? We go nowhere. We don't have that surge of capital
that takes us to new highs. We don't have that exodus that takes us
to new lows. We just muddle along between highlight and
disappointment. Nothing great; nothing bad.
</P>
<P>
   In this environment you want to be a stockpicker par excellence.
You want to own only what you know is good, and you want to own
that big.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't extrapolate and you can't just buy based on an
industry's strong fundamentals, because there is no industrial
rising tide. Sun's ability to blow away the numbers can't help
Hewlett. Yahoo's strong quarter can't benefit AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, this is another one of those periods where it is
better to be an individual unconstrained by the need to own dozens
of stocks, because only a few stocks are really working. Count your
blessings, individuals, and be ultraglad you aren't on the
receiving end of the mutual fund flows right now.
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, I would rather be Sisyphus.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (James J. Cramer is manager of a hedge fund and co-founder of
TheStreet.com. At time of publication, his fund was long AOL calls
and short AOL common, long IBM, long Yahoo! calls and short Yahoo!
common, long Applied Materials calls and short Applied Materials
common, long Lucent calls, long JDS Uniphase and short Sun
Microsystems common and against Sun Microsystems calls. His fund
often buys and sells securities that are the subject of his
columns, both before and after the columns are published, and the
positions that his fund takes may change at any time. Under no
circumstances does the information in this column represent a
recommendation to buy or sell stocks. Cramer's writings provide
insights into the dynamics of money management and are not a
solicitation for transactions. While he cannot provide investment
advice or recommendations, he invites you to comment on his column
at jjcletters(at)thestreet.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
