<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1561 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-EVERGLADES-FOREST     07-24 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EVERGLADES-FOREST-ART-(1400)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURE IMPERILS RARE PLANT MENAGERIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Science Times)  
 By MARK DERR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
   EVERGLADES NATIONAL PARK, Fla. _ On a clear, warm day recently,
Dr. Thomas Armentano picked his way through a stand of red
mangroves near the southern edge of the Florida peninsula and
stepped into a bone dry stretch of marl prairie littered with
scores of uprooted, sun-bleached buttonwood trees.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With tangled roots spanning six feet and trunks approaching
three feet in diameter, the weathered relicts were of a size seldom
found among living South Florida buttonwood.
</P>
<P>
   Not more than 100 yards from where he stood, the desiccated
trees faded into a tropical hardwood hammock, one of a vanishing
few coastal hammocks that exist only around Florida Bay in
Everglades National Park and parts of the Caribbean, including the
Yucatan.
</P>
<P>
   This particular hammock is unique in the United States because
of its size, its marl substrate and its orchids, said Armentano,
chief biologist for the South Florida Natural Resources Center,
located in Everglades National Park. Marl is a clay-like limestone.
</P>
<P>
   Covering just over 200 acres and lying less than a mile north of
Florida Bay, the hammock hosts a mind-numbing profusion of wild
bromeliads and orchids, some of breathtaking dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   To protect them from plant thieves, who have nearly stripped
other areas bare, Armentano asked that the hammock's precise
location be kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   Hammocks _ basically forests of hardwoods rising on elevated
ground from among pines, marshes and old shorelines _ were once
common throughout South Florida, especially along the coasts. For
much of the past century, they fell to loggers, developers and
charcoal makers, who leveled vast stands of buttonwood. Nearly all
of the remaining hammocks are now found only in the region's parks
and preserves.
</P>
<P>
   Covered head to toe to guard against the sun, poison plants,
thorns and mosquitoes that define walking in the Everglades,
Armentano led a reporter and photographer on a tour of the fallen
buttonwood forest and its neighboring hammock to illustrate the
forces that threaten the survival of some of the nation's rarest
plant communities.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant of those threats, he said, pointing
to the bleached buttonwoods, are hurricanes that can remake whole
landscapes. ``These coastal hardwood communities are uniquely tied
to tropical storms,'' Armentano said. ``Storm effects in Florida
Bay have helped create them, and yet extremely violent storms can
also destroy them.''
</P>
<P>
   This buttonwood forest was toppled by the 1935 Labor Day
hurricane, a Category 5 monster with winds estimated at 200 to 250
miles an hour. That storm battered the Florida Keys, killing an
estimated 800 workers on the Overseas Highway, before churning
across Florida Bay into the Everglades. Hurricanes Donna in 1960
and Betsy in 1965 uprooted the trees left standing. Mature
buttonwood is so hard and dense it does not rot in the hot, wet
South Florida climate, and so the dried-out trees remain, dotting
what in the aftermath of those storms became a low-lying prairie of
cactuses and other succulents growing precariously from salty
ground and inundated for much of the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to hurricanes and their storm surges that can drive
saltwater, sand and mud far inland, other threats to coastal
hammocks are fire, invasion by exotic plants, sudden freezes and
rising sea level, Armentano said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists agree that the $7.8 billion plan to restore what
remains of the freshwater Everglades, the historic ``river of
grass,'' now under consideration in Congress, will do little to
save coastal hammocks. ``It's hard to put a finger on something,
like hydrological restoration, you can do to preserve them,''
Armentano said.
</P>
<P>
   Everglades hammocks are the region's uplands, standing high
enough that they escape flooding for much, if not all of the year.
In this flat and subtle land, high enough means anywhere from
several inches to about six feet for those on Indian middens, or
refuse heaps.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 164 woody species native to these forests, Armentano
said, 135 are tropical, of West Indian origin. The rest are
temperate North American trees and shrubs at the southern end of
their range. Many of the 14 distinct types of hammocks that
botanists have identified are named for their dominant vegetation,
like thatch palm, mahogany, gumbo limbo, live oak (a temperate
tree) or tropical hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   Most biologists believe that the Caribbean plants were brought
to the North American mainland by migrating birds, winds and tides.
They took root in the last 5,000 years, when the Florida peninsula
became warmer and wetter, and the Everglades were formed.
</P>
<P>
   The precious hammocks bordering Florida Bay occupy old sand
ridges, marine marl deposits, or dead coral that seldom stand more
than three-feet above sea level. ``Hammocks like this are only
found in Caribbean areas where the soils and moisture conditions
are similar,'' Armentano said. ``But the islands are overdeveloped
and there have been quite a few hurricanes in those areas in recent
years, so we don't know their condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way into the hammock, he pointed out that as the
land rose barely more than an inch, the vegetation began to change
from ground-hugging succulents to grasses growing under scrub
buttonwood and manchineel, a plant considered more noxious than
poison ivy. In the dappled shade also grew wild hibiscus, wild
cotton, wild cinnamon, limber caper and three types of rangy
cactuses.
</P>
<P>
   After a rise of another few inches, that vegetation faded into
full hammock, a nearly impenetrable, multilayered forest with vines
reaching high into the tree tops. A riot of Spanish stopper,
blolly, and various hardwood saplings formed a thick understory
beneath a canopy of Jamaica dogwood, mastic, sabal palm, mahogany,
gumbo limbo, pigeon plum and wild lime, including one Armentano
called the largest he had seen. The presence of many of these
plants, he said, showed that the hammock was free of the salt
permeating the marl prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical hardwoods usually have short trunks and vast canopies,
the better to shed limbs while remaining upright in hurricanes,
Armentano said, but here, because of past storms, there was a lack
of such big trees. Instead young trees rose straight for 20 feet or
more through the riotous tangle, seeking sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Armentano said that there were about a dozen canopy species
represented in the hammock, with another 20 or so found in the
understory and among the epiphytes, or air plants. The plants put
down horizontal roots, reaching no deeper than a foot, in the thin,
nutrient-poor soil, created from decaying hammock vegetation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Plants grew on top of and around other plants. A strangler fig
entombed a tall sabal palm, leaving only the fronds visible. On an
ancient buttonwood, its outstretched limbs covered with epiphytes,
a cactus grew out of a bromeliad. A shriveled resurrection fern lay
waiting for rain to revive it on a 20-foot-long limb of a Jamaica
dogwood.
</P>
<P>
   Bromeliads and orchids _ cowhorn, mule ear, dollar, ghost and
butterfly _ crowded dead and weathered but still living
buttonwoods, their favorite host, and spilled onto other trees.
Some of those epiphytes were three to four feet in diameter. The
flowers had dropped from most of the orchids, but after a search,
Armentano found a large mule-ear orchid with a long cascade of gold
and rust colored blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   This tropical hardwood hammock has remained remarkably free of
destructive exotics, like Brazilian pepper, a shrub that grows so
densely it crowds out all other vegetation, and Colubrina asiatica,
a vine that covers the canopy, shading out all plants beneath it.
But colubrina has already invaded nearby hammocks, and park
biologists fear its advance.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 years the hammock has also escaped freezes, like the two
in the 1980's that destroyed orchids in much of the park. But this
and other coastal hammocks that are already rare may ultimately
fall to hurricanes and rising tides, especially if, as many
scientists believe, global warming is accelerating sea level rise,
while intensifying hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Already, saltwater is undercutting sand ridges holding thatch
palm hammocks on the north shore of Florida Bay and has destroyed
mangrove and hardwood forests on several islands in the bay itself,
Armentano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tidal gauges in Key West have recorded a nine-inch rise in sea
level, since 1930,'' said Dr. Harold Wanless, professor of
geological sciences at the University of Miami. ``Even if you add
just one foot in the next century to what we have already _ and I
think that is a ridiculously conservative estimate _ you see that
these coastal hammocks are pretty well doomed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
