<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEB-TOMBSTONES-NYTR &LR;      07-24 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-TOMBSTONES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES ARE THE TOMBSTONES OF THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID SIMS   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I found myself in the virtual cemetery of the future last week.
It was my first time, but it isn't likely to be the last.
</P>
<P>
   A friend and colleague with whom I worked for two years in San
Francisco died in his sleep a few weeks ago. He was relatively
young, but suffered from several congenital conditions that made
his death, although unexpected, not unexplained.
</P>
<P>
   He shared several groups of friends _ people from his
neighborhood, from his childhood, a Hollywood group he hung out
with, and the one to which I belonged, his Web friends and
colleagues. We reacted to his death in the only way we really know
how to acknowledge anything: We made a Web site:
www.garybrickman.com.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the site was live and we all added pieces to it
that I realized this was the tombstone of the modern age: A
memorial prominently marked and easy to find in a place where we
all work and visit every day: cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The stories, pictures and links we leave there are like the
flowers or messages our ancestors might have left on the tombstones
of their friends when they passed the churchyard on their way to or
from work.
</P>
<P>
   They are our way of showing our respect and reminding each other
that we are still thinking of him. Gary's memorial is bookmarked,
and any time I miss his wisdom or his humor, I know that his
knowing smirk is just a click away.
</P>
<P>
   I don't pretend that these memorial sites are permanent. But few
memorials are, with a few notable exceptions for pharaohs and
emperors.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and wind, those material agents of time, wear down stone
and metal. A change in operating systems or network infrastructure
may make Gary's site unreachable. But for now, in our time, it's a
solid marker.
</P>
<P>
   I can imagine that in the future there will be virtual plots of
friends and families, and that each of our memorial sites may
belong to several of these sites _ your family network, your
network of friends, your professional network. Each of these plots
may have a portal page linking the members' sites together, a
funeral portal, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   There may even be a business in hosting such sites in
perpetuity. Pay an extra $1 per month to your Internet service
provider, and the ISP will in return guarantee to host your site
for 99 years after your passing.
</P>
<P>
   The site MyFamily.com already has earned a position in the Top
20 most visited Web sites by making it easy for families to set up
intranets that help them share recipes or schedule time at the
family cabin. It's not too much of a stretch to imagine them
extending this service beyond the pale. (I know what you're
thinking, but don't bother: familyplot.com is taken.)
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where Gary's remains are today. But I know where
his memorial in cyberspace is. And I can visit it any time. I hope
someday someone does the same for me.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
