A1564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-PRISONERS-(T     07-24 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-PRISONERS-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTANT GUERRILLA FREED FROM BELFAST PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Michael Stone, a Protestant paramilitary member who
killed three mourners in a Belfast cemetery during an Irish
Republican Army funeral in 1988, left prison Monday, the first of
88 guerrillas who will be freed this week in the last wave of early
releases mandated by the Northern Ireland peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Stone's solo gun and grenade attack during the burial service of
three IRA members who had been shot by British soldiers in
Gibraltar was captured on television and is one of the enduring
images of the sectarian violence that has cost more than 3,600
lives in the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   He served 12 years of six life sentences imposed for the three
murders and three others that he was convicted of in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The early releases of more than 400 men are meant to bring
guerrillas who fought for and against British rule in line with the
1998 peace settlement that has created a power-sharing government
in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   The provision applies only to fighters from groups that have
maintained cease-fires in recent years and whose crimes were
committed before the signing of the pact. The releases can be
revoked for any new criminal involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, 45, passed through a turnstile exit at the Maze prison
near Lisburn in County Antrim on Monday morning and was greeted by
50 cheering supporters carrying the gold and black flag of his
Protestant paramilitary group, the Ulster Freedom Fighters.
</P>
<P>
   He looked grim and said nothing outside the jail, but later at a
news conference at a Protestant prisoner rehabilitation center, he
expressed his commitment to the peace accord that had brought him
his freedom. He added, ``My war is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was sorry for his activities, he said: ``I was a
volunteer with the Ulster Defense Association involved in a 30-year
war, and it was not of my doing. They were military operations. I
was a volunteer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's release Monday touched a raw nerve with one victim's
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very bitter, because I think people look at him as a
hero, and to me he's a devil,'' said Sally McErlean, whose son
Thomas was one of three Catholics killed at the Milltown Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Among other prisoners being freed this week are Sean Kelly, an
IRA bomber responsible for the attack on a fish store on the
Shankill Road, the main street of the Protestant part of Belfast,
in October 1993 that killed nine people; James McArdle, who has
served two years of a 25-year sentence for the bombing of London's
financial center at Canary Wharf in February 1996 that killed two
and wounded 40; and Michael Caraher, an IRA sniper implicated in
the 1998 killing of Lance Bombardier Stephen Restorick, the last
British soldier to die in the conflict, which is commonly called
the troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The Maze prison held some 800 paramilitary fighters during the
1980s, but by next week only 16 will remain. By year's end,
officials hope to close down the building, which was segregated by
religion and often commandeered by the prisoners themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The dispute in Northern Ireland is a territorial and tribal one
rather than a purely religious one, but those people who want to
see Ulster united with Ireland, called republicans and
nationalists, are largely Catholic, while those who want to keep
the province British, called loyalists and unionists, are almost
all Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland was in the grip of systematic violence in 1988,
and the cemetery attack led to two more deaths days later when a
pair of British soldiers drove into the funeral cortege of Stone's
victims and were dragged from their car, beaten and taken to a
waste dump, where they were shot dead as they pleaded for their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   In a chilling reference to changing times in Ulster, Stone, a
father of nine, noted that Martin McGuinness of Sinn Fein, the
political party representing the IRA, was now the Education
Minister in the new Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is in charge of my grandchildren, which is ironic,'' Stone
said. ``I tried to assassinate him as he took his own daughter to
primary school, but I didn't, because his daughter was holding his
hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
