<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN EXPRESS TOPS ESTIMATES BY A PENNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Stock prices are not up-to-the-minute) 
 By CAROLYN KOO   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ American Express (AXP:NYSE) reported earnings on
Monday that exceeded Wall Street's expectations by a penny, largely
because the financial services giant garnered higher fee revenue on
money it manages for investors and because of increased usage of
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of American Express fell 2 3/4, or 4 percent, to 56 1/2
in Monday afternoon trading after reaching a 52-week high of 59
3/4.
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter ended June 30, net income rose to $740
million, or 54 cents a diluted share, from $646 million, or 47
cents a share, a year earlier. The consensus estimate of analysts
polled by First Call/Thomson Financial was 53 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 16 percent to $5.6 billion from $4.8 billion a year
ago. Its travel-related services unit posted a 17 percent revenue
increase to $4.3 billion and its financial advisers unit posted an
18 percent increase to $1.1 billion, while the American Express
bank/travelers cheque unit recorded only a 1 percent gain to $262
million.
</P>
<P>
   The travel related services business, which reported net income
of $472 million, up from $411 million a year ago, benefited from a
12 percent increase of cards used and higher average spending per
card member. The American Express financial advisers business,
which reported net income of $275 million, up from $242 million a
year ago, gained because of increases in sales of mutual funds,
annuities and life and other insurance products.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the American Express bank/travelers cheque unit
reported net income of $40 million, up from $38 million a year ago,
because of greater commission and fee revenue. However, the unit
also experienced a decrease in net interest income because of
higher funding costs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
