<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1571 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BIZMAGS0725-COX     07-24 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is employee loyalty a thing of the past?
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Is employee loyalty a thing of the past? Several
publications look at this and other workplace issues, without
arriving at a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   In a Context (August/September) interview, former Labor
Secretary Robert Reich asserts that ``employers aren't loyal to
employees'' and ``employees aren't loyal to employers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's because of technology, which gives consumers more options _
including switching to other brands, Reich says. Since companies
must be ready to adjust as needed when they lose customers, ``they
cannot provide job security.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All their costs have to be variable. Inevitably, every
employee in the future is walking on very thin ice,'' Reich says.
</P>
<P>
   Barron's (July 24) says job-hopping has become ``a national
sport'' in the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   But contrary to Reich, Barron's finds that ``many chief
executives are beginning to care more about loyalty and are shaking
their heads at candidates who have a record of jumping jobs every
18 months or so.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money (August) looks at how one popular device adopted by
companies to build loyalty has backfired bigtime this year _ stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   An option to buy shares of the company you work for at a
discount to the market only works if the market price is higher
than the option price. In this year's down market, it hasn't worked
that way, to the dismay of thousands of rank and file workers. Some
$22.7 billion of options wealth was wiped out this year in Silicon
Valley alone, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's nightmare
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan is haunted by a threat
that ravaged the economy in the 1970s _ soaring oil prices, says
Business Week (July 31).
</P>
<P>
   ``An old-fashioned oil price shock could disrupt the otherwise
smooth running of the New Economy by pinching profit margins and
pushing up wages,'' says the magazine. Most of Greenspan's
colleagues think this is not a problem, since oil accounts for
about 1 percent of the economy now compared with 6.5 perncent at
the end of the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   But since it usually takes about 18 months for the full impact
of an oil price rise to be felt by consumers, Greenspan thinks it's
too early to conclude that the economy has weathered this year's
runup in energy costs, Business Week says.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning...
</P>
<P>
   Two magazines with ``personal finance'' subtitles, Kiplinger's
and Bloomberg, offer mutual fund advice in their August editions .
. . The newest Georgia Trend (July) is worth filing away for future
reference because of its annual list of Georgia-based public
companies. . . If there's a ``bubble'' on Wall Street, it's in U.S.
debt to foreign investors, says Forbes (Aug. 7), noting that
foreign holdings of Treasury bonds has risen 38 percent since 1960
and corporate bonds by 20 percent. Foreign ownership of sticks is
up 8 percent. . . A degree of sanity has returned to the stock
market, but as Worth (July/August) puts it, some stock valuations
``are still just nuts'' _ most of them in technology.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
