u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NY     07-24 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN PARLIAMENT AND PRESIDENT IN STANDOFF OVER DISMISSALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A surly standoff between Parliament and its
first democratically elected leader dragged on Monday as more than
200 members rejected President Abdurrahman Wahid's explanation for
why he had ousted two popular cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The members signed a petition demanding that Wahid go before the
House of Representatives again to explain his actions. Wahid
outraged the lawmakers in an appearance on Thursday, when he
refused to give an account of the dismissals, saying the House had
no right to interrogate him.
</P>
<P>
   The action Monday raises the heat in what has been a long summer
of discontent. The president is scheduled to face a pivotal meeting
of the People's Consultative Assembly on Aug. 7, in which he is
quite likely to face sharp questions about his often turbulent nine
months in office.
</P>
<P>
   As the supreme legislative body, the People's Consultative
Assembly could remove the president from office. Five hundred of
its 700 members are from the House.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, experts said, the lack of viable alternatives makes it
highly unlikely that the assembly will oust Wahid _ at least for
now.
</P>
<P>
   But the deeply poisoned atmosphere has stirred fears that
violence could mar the meeting next month. The government plans to
deploy 29,000 army troops and police officers in this capital.
</P>
<P>
   The tension has also hobbled the economic recovery. The
currency, the rupiah, has tumbled 25 percent since January and now
trades at levels reminiscent of the Asian economic crisis. Economic
policy is paralyzed, as domestic and foreign investors wait for
Wahid to reshuffle his economic ministers after the Assembly
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless Wahid fixes the economy, he can't fix all these other
things, because they flow out of people's sense of well-being or
lack of well-being,'' said Gustav F. Papanek, a professor emeritus
of economics at Boston University who is advising the government on
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Wahid apologized to the House for his remarks and
pleaded with lawmakers to lay the matter to rest. But in a sign
that his quirky charm is wearing thin, 252 members rejected the
overture and mounted a scalding attack on his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should not issue any more baseless or
controversial statements, because it could negatively affect the
stock market, cause recklessness or confusion or trigger disputes
among the public,'' the legislators said in their petition, which
was handed to Speaker Akbar Tandjung.
</P>
<P>
   Tandjung said the House would debate the petition after the
Assembly had ended its session in the middle of next month. That
all but guarantees that Wahid will remain under siege for the rest
of the summer, though few political experts here say they believe
that he is in danger of being ousted.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the sparks between the legislature and the
president are a symbol of how far Indonesia has come. Under the
country's longtime leader, Suharto, the House was a rubber-stamp
institution that did the president's bidding. Since Wahid was
elected, the lawmakers and the Indonesian people have begun to
demand openness and accountability from their politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, a Muslim leader with frail health but a whip-sharp sense
of humor, began his term with a wide-open style that suggested a
break from the past. But in the last several months, his
administration has been sullied by charges of corruption and
arbitrary rule.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Wahid abruptly dismissed two respected ministers,
Laksamana Sukardi and Jusuf Kalla. He appointed his brother to a
senior post at the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Authority. And his
masseur was implicated in a scandal that involved money stolen from
the State Logistics Agency.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with political leaders, Wahid has said the cabinet
ministers had been tainted by allegations of graft. But he has not
produced evidence to support those assertions. Indeed, Sukardi is
still mentioned as a possible candidate to be governor of the
central bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
