<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1582 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-EARTH-WOBBLES-NYT     07-24 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EARTH-WOBBLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR AND SEA LEND EARTH ITS WOBBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Earth wobbles because the atmosphere and oceans are pushing
it around.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the Aug. 1 issue of Geophysical Research Letters, Dr.
Richard S. Gross, a geophysicist at NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory, reports that a mysterious motion known as the
``Chandler wobble'' is caused by changing air pressure at the
Earth's surface and changing water pressure at the ocean bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   As first observed in 1891 by Seth Carlo Chandler Jr., an
insurance actuary turned astronomer, the Earth's axis sways back
and forth about 20 feet every 14 months. The Chandler is one of
several wobbles in the Earth's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a famous problem in Earth rotation studies,'' Gross said.
``It's just taken so long to fully understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the simplest level, the dynamics of the Chandler wobble are
easy to understand. ``If you're not a good Frisbee thrower, it'll
be wobbly as it flies,'' said Dr. Clark Wilson, a professor of
geophysics at the University of Texas at Austin. ``That's the
Chandler wobble of the Frisbee.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Earth is not a perfect sphere _ squashed in slightly
at the poles and squished outward at the Equator _ it spins a bit
like the wobbly Frisbee. A Swiss mathematician, Leonhard Euler,
first predicted the wobble in 1765, but there has been a lingering
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The sloshing motion of the Earth's molten interior should
quickly damp out the wobble. According to recent calculations by
Wilson, the Chandler wobble should dissipate after only 68 years.
</P>
<P>
   Thus scientists now had to explain why a phenomenon they had
predicted _ and observed _ should actually exist at all. What force
was continually banging on the world to maintain the wobble?
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the pressure of air and water pushing on the Earth
were also candidates. ``That pushing down on the ocean floor is not
symmetrical,'' Gross said. Imagine a large beach ball with children
pushing on it from all directions. If some of the children pushed
harder and some less, the ball would tend to tilt. Because the
Earth is spinning, the tilt turns into a wobble.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 paper in the journal Nature by Dr. Rui Ponte, a senior
staff scientist at Atmospheric and Environmental Research in
Cambridge, Mass., found that the ocean and atmosphere pressure
changes were the primary causes of several of the Earth's wobbles.
</P>
<P>
   Gross refined the earlier analysis to focus specifically on the
Chandler wobble. Using the latest computer models of the atmosphere
and ocean, he calculated that two-thirds of the Chandler wobble is
caused by changes in ocean-bottom water pressure and the remaining
one-third by changes in atmospheric pressure. The results of the
computer models matched the observed wobble between 1985 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's certainly a plausible explanation,'' said Dr.
John M. Wahr, a professor of physics at the University of Colorado.
``My own feeling is that is what's probably doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping track of the Earth's wobbles is more than an
intellectual curiosity. ``It's needed in navigating interplanetary
spacecraft,'' Gross said. Like looking for a star on a rocking
boat, NASA needs to take the wobble into account when pointing
radio antennas on Earth at spacecraft hundreds of millions miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out one of the biggest sources of uncertainty in
navigating interplanetary spacecraft is not knowing how the Earth's
rotation changes,'' Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   Isolating the wobble's driving force will also allow for more
precise measurements of the period, and that will give geologists a
better idea of how viscous the Earth's interior is. ``The period of
the motion tells you about the interior structure of the Earth,''
Wahr said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as geologists have now nailed down the Chandler wobble,
there are still other mysteries of the Earth's spin. Besides the
wobbles, the rotation axis has moved about 30 feet since 1900,
probably because the Earth is still rebounding from the crushing
force of the glaciers that covered much of the Northern Hemisphere
during the last Ice Age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rotation axis is not at the North Pole any more,'' Wilson
said. ``It's drifted off toward Kansas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
