<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BROWN-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      07-24 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIE BROWN KIDS THE VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cable comedy diva Julie Brown finds the makings of over-the-top,
absurdist humor in almost anything caught in her crosshairs.
</P>
<P>
   There's been Madonna (``Medusa: Dare to Be Truthful''), Tonya
Harding, Delta Burke, Carnie Wilson and, on the big screen, alien
invasion movies (``Earth Girls Are Easy''), for example.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time before this longtime San Fernando
Valley resident hit on that Southern California retail phenomenon:
the mini- mall.
</P>
<P>
   To many locals, the thousands of mini-malls here are eyesores,
architectural mistakes that exemplify everything wrong with zoning
laws, blights on the neighborhood to mutter about even as we are
pulling in to drop off our dirty laundry, get our nails retipped
and scarf a doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   To Brown, the mini-mall is the perfect setting for her newest TV
show, Comedy Central's ``Strip Mall.'' The series is a send-up of
prime-time soap operas, with a serial format involving murder,
intrigue, lust, betrayal, Chinese food and gift baskets.
</P>
<P>
   The strip mall in question, the fictional Plaza del Toro, is set
in Northridge, but Brown insists she didn't do that just to make
fun of the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Valley, I grew up in the Valley,'' she said during
a recent interview outside the Burbank mini-mall that's used for
the exterior shots. ``I was born in Burbank, so I don't feel that
I'm just picking on the Valley. I still live here, in Studio City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writers write about what they know, and to me, one of the
funny elements of growing up here is sort of the strip-mall
consciousness that's just come all over the Valley. It's just
everywhere,'' Brown said. ``I feel like this is a reality for me
that I'm finally getting to play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Valley's this great sort of suburban place, but
the thing that's unique about it is it's right next to Hollywood,
so the element of Hollywood is in the consciousness of the Valley.
It's always been there.''
</P>
<P>
   It definitely is there in the plot of ``Strip Mall.'' Brown
plays Tammi (say it ``tah-MEE'') Tyler, a former TV child star who,
at the peak of her popularity on the `70s show ``Here Comes
Corky,'' stabbed her co-star, Cap'n Billy, to death after eating a
PCP-laced cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   Now a waitress in the strip mall's dive cocktail lounge, she
wears rhinestones by her eyes, right next to fake lashes that look
like carwash brushes. There's very little in her wardrobe that
doesn't involve maribou or spandex. Tammi still refers to the
bloody slaying as ``an accident.'' And she desperately wants to be
rich and famous again.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's that other Hollywood angle. One of the shops
is We Shoot You, a special-occasion videography shop that is a
front for a pornographic film production house.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that was one of the first story angles she came up
with when creating ``Strip Mall'' with her longtime writing
partner, Charlie Coffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to think of something for cable specifically that
was funny and sexy, and I knew that there's more porno shot in the
Valley than anywhere in the world,'' she said. ``And so I thought,
'That's sort of sexy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I always really loved `Mary Hartman,' the show, so the
idea of doing a soap opera that's set in a strip mall _ the most
normal place, we see a million of them _ that there would be this
much insanity, intrigue, sex, lust, bizarreness going on in a strip
mall just seemed funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she and Coffey started to brainstorm the other characters
and situations in their Plaza del Toro microcosm: Patty (Victoria
Jackson), the ditsy barmaid with a metal plate in her head; Harve
Krudup (Jim O'Heir), the obese owner of the Star Brite cleaners
whom Tammi marries impulsively in her quest for wealth; Rafe and
Bettina Bellingham (Maxwell Caulfield and Eliza Coyle), owners of
the failing Good Things gift basket shop; and Fanny and Althea (Amy
Hill and Loretta Fox), the sex-crazed lesbians who run the Wok
Don't Run Chinese restaurant. Sergei Solokov (Greg Itein) is the
porno king who hooks two recent film school grads _ Josh (Jonathan
Magnum) and Barry (Chris Wylde) _ to make his ultra-cheap movies.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't been with ``Strip Mall'' from the beginning last
month, have no fear. Each episode's intro can bring you up to speed
before you can say ``Erica Kane's getting married again?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the show has continued to evolve throughout its first
season. For instance, Blunt was Tammi's dull-witted, vain, ex-con
boyfriend whose character came and went in the pilot episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved him and suddenly the character is dead, so while
we're shooting the pilot we decide we love him so much he has to
come back,'' she said. ``So we go, 'OK, what if he has a twin
brother?' _ a soap-opera convention. So he'll be a gay twin brother
named Blair. Then, what if he has another brother who's straight,
so now he's identical triplets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just evolved because we love Bob (Koherr) so much and
thought he was so funny, so we thought, 'What if we just keep
giving him more brothers to play?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tammi meets Blank, brother No. 3, while he's waiting in the
getaway car for his girlfriend, who is robbing Wok Don't Run. ``And
there's even a possible fourth brother we've thought of named Blurt
who has Tourette's,'' Brown said, laughing at her own joke.
</P>
<P>
   Brown started working with Coffey when both were studying acting
at San Francisco's prestigious American Conservatory Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have been a writer at all if I hadn't felt a
need for material,'' she said. ``Even when I was in high school, I
wrote material. I remember when I was a little kid doing shows for
my parents, thinking, 'What should I do?' feeling the need for
material always. Is that weird?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she and Coffey, in creating ``Strip Mall,'' set out
to push the humor envelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you know you're doing a show for cable, you want to make
it outrageous because who's going to watch it if it's like
'Caroline in the City?' That's my model for what I don't want to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of network sitcoms that you go, 'I don't
understand this.' I think there are a lot of talented people on
those shows, but comedy by committee doesn't work very well. And
that's what it's a result of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had to go through it and it's really hard and it
doesn't come out funny, because comedy is a point of view. Is it
going to be 25 people's points of view? What is that? It's usually
watered down, people have taken the edges off it, and it's not that
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Strip Mall'' definitely has its edges. There's the time Tammi,
being interrogated by police, attempts to distract them by taking
off her underwear a la Sharon Stone and instead attracts the
attention of a bomb-sniffing dog. Or the time she is struck by a
tranquilizer dart and falls asleep in a dumpster, then awakens from
a lusty reverie with a rat nibbling her ear.
</P>
<P>
   Brown says now that she's a mother of a 6-year-old boy, there
are some things she won't do in the name of comedy, such as nudity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I guess some of this ('Strip Mall') stuff seems so
outrageous, people go, 'What's your son going to think when he sees
it?' I hope he thinks it's funny and he's proud of me for doing
something I want to do.'' &QL; 
---The show: ``Strip Mall.'' &QL; 
What: Situation comedy series set in a Valley mini-mall. &QL; 
The stars: Julie Brown, Jim O'Heir, Victoria Jackson, Bob Koherr,
Maxwell Caulfield, Greg Itein, Jonathan Magnum, Chris Wylde. &QL; 
Where: Comedy Central. &QL; 
When: 10:30 p.m. Sundays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
