<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1599 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-OLYTV0725-COX     07-24 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYTV0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Get ready for an avalanche of Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and its cable partners will air 441 1/2 hours of coverage
from the Sydney Games _ surpassing by more than 100 hours the
coverage of the Barcelona and Atlanta Games combined.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to 162 1/2 hours on NBC, the network will put 214
hours on MSNBC and 65 hours on CBNC. It will be the first time
Olympic coverage has been offered on basic cable.
</P>
<P>
   The last time NBC went beyond network programming for a Summer
Olympics was the ill-fated pay-per-view Triplecast in 1992 at
Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   ''The financial disaster aside, editorially the Triplecast was a
terrific concept,'' said Molly Solomon, NBC Olympics Cable
coordinating produce, ''and we're kind of going back to that model.
The programming (on MSNBC and CNBC) will not be repeats of the
network broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   The two cable networks will provide start-to-finish coverage of
such sports as softball and soccer, which usually receive just
cursory coverage on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC's main event will be boxing. MSNBC's coverage will be built
around men's and women's soccer and basketball, women's softball
and equestrian. It also will have doses of baseball, beach
volleyball, rowing, tennis, water polo and weightlifting, and
limited air time for such virtually invisible sports as archery,
canoeing, field hockey, table tennis and team handball.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cable side will be for people who are enthusiastic about a
particular sport,'' Solomon said. ''It will definitely be more
event-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the MediaOne cable system does not carry MSNBC.
However, its Channel 33 will pick up all of the MSNBC coverage,
which runs during daytime hours for the run of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's success, however, will be defined by the coverage on NBC,
specifically the 84 hours in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The network paid $705 million for the rights to the 2000 Games,
57 percent higher than the fee for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought we would lose $50 million to $75 million,'' NBC
Sports chairman Dick Ebersol said. ''Due to advertising sales and
affiliates contributions, we're now looking at making a little
profit. We had a record $680 million in sales in Atlanta, but we've
already crossed $800 million in Sydney, and we may reach $900
million by September.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC, having met the challenge of the network's accountants,
still must produce ratings that will meet the expectations of
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The network concedes that the average rating of 21.6 for the
Atlanta Olympics is an unrealistic goal for Sydney. NBC is
projecting ratings of 17.5 to 18.5.
</P>
<P>
   The network never considered showing any of its coverage live,
because of the 15-hour time difference.
</P>
<P>
   ''An event at 8 p.m. in Sydney is taking place at 5 a.m. in New
York, and who's going to be watching then?'' Ebersol asked. ''To do
live coverage at that time of morning would dissipate what we're
doing. Also, the results will not be in most newspapers before
they're on our air. The Olympics are pretty expensive, and the only
way to justify that expense is to try and draw the widest possible
audience in prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC's first week will be anchored by gymnastics, swimming and
diving, with an emphasis on track and field in the second week. The
network plans to devote less time to features than it did in
Atlanta,
</P>
<P>
   ''But our mantra is still story-telling,'' said David Neal, head
of production for NBC Olympics. ''It's the same principles Roone
Arledge used at ABC in the '60s and '70s. It's not enough to
present the competition, because the audience for the Olympics is
diverse. It's not just a sports audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's crucial to make a connection between viewers and
athletes, because it's not so much about sports as it is the human
drama.''
</P>
<P>
   According to NBC Research, the audience makeup for regular
sports programming is 54 percent male, 34 percent female and 12
percent children under 11.
</P>
<P>
   For the Summer Olympics, those numbers are 49 percent female, 39
percent male and 14 percent children.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that pattern, NBC thinks that televising an Olympics
during baseball pennant races and early weekends of football season
will not have a dramatic effect on its prime-time ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ''The football may draw away some of the male audience, in which
case we're only talking about an impact on a third of the Olympics
audience,'' Ebersol said. ''But to give you an idea of what the
Olympics mean, our competitors went to Nielsen and made sure the
new season would not begin until Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''That way the Olympics will not count in the overall average
for the new season. But on the other hand, it also means our
Olympics programming will not face any of the new fall programming
on the other networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
