<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON DIGS IN, SEES POTENTIAL FOR MIDEAST DEAL
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-BEREAVED-0725.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ With Mideast peace talks teetering somewhere
between triumph and disaster, President Clinton plunged into the
heart and soul of statecraft on Monday, rolling up his sleeves for
around-the-clock talks centered on nuts-and-bolts diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Just off of a 15-hour flight from Japan, Clinton dove into
hand-to-hand negotiations that stretched until 5 a.m. (ET) Monday
at nearby Camp David. He caught five hours of sleep and spent the
rest of the day trying to shepherd the talks through what appeared
to be a make-or-break moment.
</P>
<P>
   With Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat at loggerheads over the fate of Jerusalem, Clinton _
pen and notebook in hand _ held extended, detail oriented
negotiations with working-level officials from each side.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the two sides might be finding at least some
common ground, the White House released a photograph showing
Clinton and his top Mideast envoy, Dennis Ross, seated around a
small black table in Clinton's cabin at the presidential retreat
with an Israeli negotiator and two members of the Palestinian
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the negotiators were all writing down notes, as Ross
looked on, a binder bulging with documents perched across his lap.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart cast the activity as evidence
that talks had intensified and were focused on specifics.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear, though, whether that was a sign of progress, an
attempt to rescue the talks from stalemate or an effort to
consolidate a partial agreement in preparation for an inconclusive
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the president is using his time to sit down and
work through each and every issue is a decision that he and his
team do not take lightly,'' Lockhart said. ``And as long as we're
here and discussing things, there is a prospect for reaching
agreement; but it's impossible to predict the likelihood of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart described the talks as both ``exhaustive and
exhausting,'' but added ``it remains to be seen whether exhaustion
will help the process or hurt the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks were expected to reach deep into the night Monday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was preparing to lead
the talks into their third week on Tuesday. Clinton was scheduled
to travel to Fayetteville, Ark., to attend memorial services with
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton for a close friend of the couple,
Diane Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was expected to return to Camp David around midnight
Tuesday, said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton convened the summit July 11 in hopes of brokering a
treaty to end 52 years of often bloody Israeli-Palestinian
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators have been hacking away in the Catoctin Mountain
retreat at the core territorial and security issues dividing the
two parties, including the fate of Jewish settlers and Palestinian
refugees and the question of Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most contentious issue in the talks, though, has
been the question of Jerusalem. Barak has sworn not to sign an
agreement that would divide the city. And Arafat has vowed to
secure Palestinian control over East Jerusalem, more than half of
the city and the location of many of the holiest sites in the
Christian, Muslim and Jewish worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has floated a proposal to share at least part of East
Jerusalem with the Palestinians, by, in at least one such plan,
extending the boundaries of the city to take in a number of
predominantly Arab communities already effectively under
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   With echoes of the Israeli-Palestinian interim accord Clinton
brokered two years ago at the Wye River Plantation in eastern
Maryland, Lockhart said that Central Intelligence Agency chief
George Tenet had spent at least one day at the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart declined to discuss the substance of Tenet's visit. The
CIA is closely involved in U.S. efforts to monitor security
arrangements in the region in connection with a series of previous
Arab-Israeli accords.
</P>
<P>
   The agency would almost certainly be involved in similar
activities to safeguard a comprehensive Israeli-Palestinian treaty,
should one be agreed upon here, and it's easy to imagine any number
of reasons why Tenet's input could be useful to both Arafat and
Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet, though, became a key figure during the Wye talks after
Israeli sources claimed that Clinton had given then-Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu assurances that he would release Jonathan
Pollard _ convicted in the United States of spying for Israel _
from prison in exchange for Israeli concessions to Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department denied the claim, Clinton said he had told
Netanyahu only that the Justice Department would review the case.
Pollard _ a former U.S. Navy intelligence officer _ pleaded guilty
in 1986 and remains in federal prison, serving a life sentence for
espionage. Tenet opposes Pollard's release and reportedly
threatened to resign if he were set free.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart suggested that the Pollard case has been up for
discussion at Camp David, though he stressed that there had been no
shift in the U.S. position on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has not come up that I know of, but I know it frequently
comes up when the president talks to the prime minister of
Israel,'' Lockhart told reporters gathered in this town five miles
from Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister raises it on a regular basis,'' Lockhart
said. ``We're certainly aware of what the government of Israeli's
view on this subject is.''
</P>
<P>
   Successive Israeli governments have pressed for the release of
Pollard, who is widely seen in Israel as a national hero.
</P>
