u w BC-MEDICARE-HMO-HNS &LR;      07-24 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HMO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEARLY A MILLION MEDICARE BENEFICIARIES TO LOSE HMO COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Department of Health and Human Services
reported Monday that managed care providers plan to drop coverage
for 934,000 Medicare recipients, most of them senior citizens, next
year.
</P>
<P>
   That represents 200,000 more Medicare patients scheduled to lose
coverage than the managed care industry forecast last month. In a
dire warning in June, the American Association of Health Plans
(AAHP) said that low federal Medicare reimbursement rates would
lead its members to drop coverage for a record number of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors who lose managed care coverage still qualify for
Medicare's traditional fee-for-service program. And according to
the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA), a unit of HHS that
oversees Medicare, 83 percent of those affected live in areas where
other health plans offer service.
</P>
<P>
   About 6.8 million of the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries get
their health coverage through managed care programs, also known as
HMOs, according to the HCFA.
</P>
<P>
   The number of seniors affected by the HMO cuts for the 2001
calendar year is almost three times the number that lost coverage
this year. Last year at this time, health plans announced coverage
cuts for 2000 that affected 327,000 Medicare beneficiaries. The
year before that, 407,000 beneficiaries lost coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the AAHP, said the number for 2001
``reinforces the magnitude of this crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, she added: ``It's time for Congress and
the administration to put aside partisan politics, to commit $15
billion to fully fund this program, and to end the rhetorical
gamesmanship that has come to substitute for real action.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the tactical sparring over their separate Medicare
prescription drug plans, neither the Clinton administration nor the
Republican-led Congress is anxious to commit big dollars to raise
reimbursement rates for HMOs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drug coverage is one of the main attractions of
Medicare HMO plans. About 63 percent of beneficiaries in Medicare
HMOs receive drug coverage, which dramatically lessens the
skyrocketing cost of medications. Regular fee-for-service Medicare
does not offer prescription coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care under Medicare is similar to the coverage offered
in the private sector. Patients are limited in terms of selecting
doctors and hospitals but receive treatment at a reduced cost.
</P>
<P>
   Under current Medicare rules, senior citizens may choose to join
an HMO or retain fee-for-service coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Under fee-for-service, patients may choose the doctor or
hospital they want and Medicare pays a set rate. Patients pick up
the balance either through extra ``Medigap'' insurance or out of
their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, HCFA Administrator Nancy-Ann DeParle attributed
the high dropout number to ``the volatility of the Medicare managed
care market.'' She downplayed the effect of the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   About 775,000 Medicare HMO beneficiaries _ some 83 percent of
the 934,000 slated to lose coverage _ live in areas where there are
alternative HMOs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle used release of the numbers to urge passage of President
Clinton's Medicare prescription plan, saying it would ease the
financial burden on HMOs that insure purchase of expensive
medications.
</P>
<P>
   Losses of Medicare HMO coverage are nationwide. In San
Francisco, 1,948 beneficiaries will be affected. The health plans
and the numbers of dropped patients are: Aetna U.S. Healthcare of
California Inc., 1,219; Blue Cross of California, 272; AND
California Physicians' Service Corp., 457.
</P>
<P>
   In Beaumont, Texas (Jefferson County), 5,088 beneficiaries will
be affected. The health plans and the numbers of dropped patients
are: Cigna Healthcare of Texas Inc., 603; Humana Health Plan of
Texas, 998; Methodistcare Inc., 100; Nylcare Health Plans Inc.,
3,387.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio (Bexar County), 3,319 beneficiaries will be
affected. The health plans and the numbers of patients dropped are:
Nylcare Health Plans Inc., 2,986; Prudential Health Care Plan Inc.,
333.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle (King County), 15,738 beneficiaries will be affected.
The health plans and the numbers of patients dropped are: Aetna
U.S. Healthcare Inc., 8,175; First Choice Health Plan, 2,268;
Healthplus, 3,527; Regencecare, 1,768.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
