<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME MINISTER'S CONFIDANT SPINS INTO THE BRITISH SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LONDON _ Alastair Campbell, the press spokesman for Tony Blair,
has a job that has traditionally been cloaked in anonymity, but the
onetime ``source close to the prime minister'' has now gone high
personal profile. He is the subject of a book, the focus of probing
newspaper articles and broadcast pieces and the star of a BBC
documentary that has just aired.
</P>
<P>
   As the voice of the most information-management-minded British
leader in history, Campbell has become a closely observed public
figure and is credited with such influence that he is commonly
portrayed in the press as the second most important official in the
government. He is the first spokesman to sit in on cabinet
meetings, and no one in the Blair administration spends more time
with the prime minister on a daily basis. His partner and the
mother of his two children, Fiona Millar, is the personal aide to
Blair's wife, Cherie.
</P>
<P>
   So dependent on his favor are the reporters who regularly cover
10 Downing St. that one of them, George Jones, political
correspondent of Blair's Conservative tormentor, The Daily
Telegraph, this month wrote a personal essay of complaint headlined
``Alastair Campbell stops me from doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   A specialist in labels and sound bites, Campbell likes to call
himself ``his master's voice,'' but to the growing number of
government critics, he is a master ``spin doctor.'' The distinction
is a crucial one now since Blair's popularity is falling, and much
of the decline is being ascribed to the manipulation and massaging
of news to give it a twist favorable to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has always advocated keeping the message simple and
succinct and repeating it with numbing frequency to make sure it
lodges with the public. Blair used the strategy effectively in
constantly tagging the scandal-ridden previous Conservative
government with the word ``sleaze,'' but his opponents have turned
the tactic on Blair and Campbell with equal success, and the word
that has become their mantra is ``spin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Real people in pubs and on buses really do believe that spin
is a dastardly business and that its practice is New Labor's
downfall,'' said Sion Simon, associate editor of The Spectator. ``I
find it bizarre that the nation should be gripped by a common
hatred and fear of spin doctors when hardly anybody has ever met
one, nobody really knows what they do and the reality of what they
do is actually so mundane. But such is the power of the press.''
</P>
<P>
   The press is enjoying exercising that power now after three
frustrating years of trying to break free of the grip of Campbell,
43, who uses his athletic six-foot presence and a brash and
intimidating manner to cow reporters and their editors. He is a
former political writer for The Mirror who once did a
much-commented-upon turn as an author of soft-porn fables for a
magazine under the nom de plume Riviera Gigolo.
</P>
<P>
   One of Campbell's first steps on taking office was to cull the
senior civil servant information officers in government departments
and install political appointees in key spots. The number of these
``special advisers'' has doubled to 79 since Labor took power, and
the cost of the unit devoted to policy promotion and swift rebuttal
has risen tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   Employment rules were recast to free him from strict civil
service neutrality, and his resultant salary, $150,000, brings
weekly protests from Conservatives on the floor of the House of
Commons.
</P>
<P>
   The language of apology or admission of error does not figure in
Campbell's vocabulary, and his habit of responding to lapses and
criticism by going on the attack long protected the government from
being harmed by bad publicity. But now that same practice has
earned the government a reputation for smugness and insensitivity
to public opinion at a time when the number of blunders has been
increasing. It has put his relations with the press on a war
footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had _ and I particularly had _ got myself into a situation
where combat was the only language that was being spoken, which is
not necessarily terribly sensible either way,'' Campbell told
Michael Cockerell, the filmmaker who made the BBC documentary shown
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out to get the government's voice heard properly as it
is,'' Campbell said. ``I'm out to make sure the public understand
the reality of this government and this P.M. That's what I'm out to
get, and the political press often _ not always, but often _ are
the barrier to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The British press is highly aggressive and competitive, with 13
national dailies selling a startling 14 million copies. Front pages
are unblushingly partisan, and proportionality can get lost in the
headline emphasis on ``clashes'' and ``storms'' and ``rows,'' which
are always ``bitter'' ones.
</P>
<P>
   The conduct that has drawn the most scornful comments about 10
Downing St. in recent months is the tendency of people in the
government to say damning things about their internal rivals. These
dismissive comments get widespread circulation because of the
willingness of the press to report them promptly and hide the
accuser's identity with vague sourcing.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell argues that the press is obsessed by trivia, spats and
personalities, that it treats politics as soap opera and neglects
what the government is really doing. ``He believes that he is more
spinned against than spinning,'' said Cockerell.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Prescott of The Sunday Times protested that view in the
film. ``We're not spin doctors; we are professional decoders,'' he
said. ``Politicians speak a strange language, and it's for us to
decode it. That leads to clashes with Campbell.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked on camera whether he thought his spokesman was doing a
good job, Blair said, ``I like to think I have hired the best in
the business.'' But apparently recognizing the level of mutual
abuse that has arisen, he said he had decided to relieve Campbell
of the daily briefing chore so he could devote his time to
behind-the-scenes preparation of the government's message.
</P>
<P>
   Much as the journalists have complained about him, though, they
did not welcome word that they would cease having their combative
encounters with him every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Alastair is not there with that kind of access that he has
that reflects the prime minister's instincts and personality as
well as the policy lines,'' said Robin Oakley, the BBC's chief
political correspondent, ``then we simply don't believe we're
getting the voice of Downing St.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
