<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BOOTLEGGERS-AR     07-24 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOOTLEGGERS-ART-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUSSIAN TALE: WHEN MOM IS A BOOTLEGGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Foreign Journal) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITKYARANTA, Russia _ You could scour the earth from Beaver
Cleaver's hometown to this northern burg of 15,000, a pinprick on
the vast shores of Europe's largest lake, and be hard put to find a
more typical-looking housewife than Lena.
</P>
<P>
   Lena has two adorable little towheaded boys. She wears a loose
cotton housewife's dress, properly mid-calf. She has an innocent
young mother's face set in long honey-colored tresses and framed
with an almost prim pair of glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the still in her kitchen, you might not be
surprised if Lena had the Good Housekeeping Seal of Approval.
</P>
<P>
   But to be perfectly frank about it, she is not even a good
housekeeper. Lena is a bootlegger. She makes, bottles and sells
illegal booze.
</P>
<P>
   When you sell up to 400 half-liter bottles of hooch every month,
you do not have much time to keep house, not that anyone would want
to visit. The living room is so redolent of eau de hooch that you
can almost get tipsy just sitting there, provided you don't choke
first.
</P>
<P>
   But the aroma would never be mistaken for cologne. It could well
be mistaken for the bag of kitchen scraps you forgot to dispose of
before leaving on a two-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very simple recipe: sugar, yeast, water,'' Lena said as
she chatted in her spectacularly cluttered living room, in a
clapboard apartment house on what might be called Pitkyaranta's bad
side. ``People come and make orders for weddings, birthday parties,
funerals _ we had a lot of orders for the New Year's celebration.
People know what I sell, and they know it's strong.''
</P>
<P>
   These people do not seem to include the militia, which is
supposed to arrest her, fine her and confiscate her still should
they stumble across her enterprise. ``We know the stoolies who
inform the police, and we just tell them `No, we don't sell it,' ''
Lena explained, as if that answered all questions.
</P>
<P>
   Though she told her story on condition that her last name not be
used, this reporter nevertheless managed to find Lena by getting
into a car, asking the driver where he could buy some hooch and
sitting back contentedly as he was driven there.
</P>
<P>
   Russians don't call it hooch, of course. They call it samogon, a
piece of slang that literally translates as ``run by myself,''
which is just how the business is run.
</P>
<P>
   They make a lot of samogon in Pitkyaranta. In fact, a lot is
made nearby. Lena's girlfriend, who lives upstairs, is a
competitor. Across the courtyard, a maze of footpaths tramped
through unmown weeds, another family sells bootleg vodka from
another clapboard house.
</P>
<P>
   Why is a good question, seeing as Russia has no shortage of
legal alcohol. Bootlegging is a risky business, and bad samogon has
been known to kill people _ thousands, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   One reason may be that flouting the samogon law is an entrenched
habit. Stephen White, a University of Glasgow scholar and author of
the sad and fascinating book ``Russia Goes Dry'' (Cambridge
University Press, 1996), suggests that the samogon craft gained in
the mid-1980s, in Mikhail Gorbachev's furious anti-alcohol
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet authorities closed thousands of liquor stores and razed
distilleries, breweries and vineyards, leaving truly dedicated
drinkers scrambling for alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   People drank cologne and even brake fluid in search of
refreshment. Air force pilots took to drinking the exceptionally
pure alcohol used as a de-icer in MiG-25 jets, White noted, a
practice so popular that the MiG-25 acquired the nickname ``the
flying restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Some covered up their tippling by replacing the de-icer alcohol
with water. This worked until their jets iced up in flight.
</P>
<P>
   Samogon, however, became the overwhelming choice of drink.
Soviet militia made great shows of wrecking stills and hauling away
bootleggers. But it eventually became clear that wiping out samogon
would mean locking up much of the nation, including party officials
and members of the All-Union Voluntary Society for the Struggle for
Sobriety, the government's anti-booze organ.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the industrial-size packages of yeast Lena regularly
buys contain instructions for making samogon, under the discreet
heading ``A recipe for Russia's traditional national beverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before communism collapsed in 1991, distilling samogon for
home use became legal, and production skyrocketed again. That
selling it remained illegal made little difference: by 1994, one in
every six drinks downed in Russia was samogon.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the fact that the Soviet Union's demise has left
millions jobless and frantic for money, and it is not hard to see
why bootlegging still thrives.
</P>
<P>
   Pitkyaranta, about 75 miles east of Finland on the glacial Lake
Ladoga, was hit by Russia's economic woes. Until the local paper
mill began cranking up to meet a growing export market a year ago,
many were desperate. Lena's family was among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved here in '95 to this barracks of a house,'' she said.
``My husband worked on the railroad. We had our second kid, and in
a year, the railroad shop shut down without any warning _ not even
severance pay _ and my husband lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was with two kids, 1 and 4, and no income. My husband
found a job at the paper mill, but the pay was very bad. So I tried
the shuttle trade _ go to Moscow; buy some goods; come back here
and sell them. But then came the '98 crash, and I lost everything.
We didn't have food _ just a pot of fried potatoes. My oldest son
would say, `Mama, is that for me?' '' and I'd have to tell him,
`No; it's for the whole family.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``And so I came to this business.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lena's inspiration was across the courtyard, where bootleggers
were buying pure alcohol, diluting it with water and selling it as
vodka for 80 cents a bottle. ``But it was weak stuff, only 30
proof, and the quality was bad,'' she said. ``Sometimes they'd add
sleeping pills, so it would knock you out quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   She figured she could do better. So she bought a small still _ a
pot, roughly wastebasket-sized, with a curlicued pipe sprouting
from the top _ and began making real samogon. Today an ordinary
bottle sells for 80 cents, a bottle spiced up with a skin-peeling
combination of herbs and orange peel, among other things, costs 90
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important to her clientele, Lena's samogon is
considerably stronger than the watered-down vodka across the way.
She tested a batch for a visitor, using a thermometer-like device
that floats at varying levels determined by the amount of alcohol,
and announced proudly, ``Forty-six proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Word soon spread, and now Lena has a supplier of clear glass
bottles and six distributors who take most of the orders in
exchange for a small cut.
</P>
<P>
   In a good month, she takes in $325 or so. An average month's
gross is closer to $225 _ a handsome income in a small Russian
town, compared with her husband's $100.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may take in 6,000 rubles,'' she says. ``A nurse makes 425.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the cost of raw materials must be deducted from that.
Lena usually buys yeast and sugar with a wink and a nod from a
grocer who can use the business himself.
</P>
<P>
   It takes more than 6{ pounds of sugar and three ounces of yeast
to make a quart of samogon. The water, fortunately, is free, though
Lena must pump it from a well a few hundred yards away. Her house
has no running water.
</P>
<P>
   It does not take Julia Child to make samogon. Mostly, it takes
patience. The stew of sugar and yeast, called braga, must sit and
ferment for at least a week, changing from stomach-churning brown
to crystal clarity, before it is ready for distilling.
</P>
<P>
   The still itself must be heated, to turn the braga to steam, and
then cooled so that distilled samogon condenses and drips into a
container.
</P>
<P>
   Lena takes a certain pride in her work, though she confesses
that she does not particularly like it. She says she is assiduous
about keeping the mixture clean, though one look at her kitchen
will cast that into serious doubt.
</P>
<P>
   She says she will sell no samogon before its time. ``I don't
want to poison anyone,'' she said. ``If we drink, we drink our own
homemade stuff,'' Lena said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But thank God,'' she added, ``we don't drink much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
