<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EXPLODING-STAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HUNK OF STARRY DYNAMITE BURNS IN CYGNUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Science Times) 
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The future appears to be very bright, though brief, for a star
known as KPD1930+2752, in the constellation Cygnus. According to
astronomers at the University of Southampton in England, the
peculiar star is destined to explode in a supernova.
</P>
<P>
   Located within the Milky Way galaxy about 2,000 light-years
away, KPD1930+2752 is distant enough not to pose any danger to
Earth but close enough that it would provide a dazzling display.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it went off now, it would be easily visible in the daylight
sky,'' said Pierre F.L. Maxted, a postdoctoral research assistant
at the University of Southampton and one of the researchers whose
report on the doomed star will be published in Monthly Notices of
The Royal Astronomical Society.
</P>
<P>
   KPD1930+2752 is an unusual star that consists almost entirely of
helium, not hydrogen, the most common element in the cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   The observations of the University of Southampton astronomers
turned up another oddity: telltale wobbles in the frequency of
light that are caused by the gravitational pull of an unseen
companion, the burnt-out core of a Sun-like star known as a white
dwarf.
</P>
<P>
   From the quickness of the wobbles _ one full orbit lasts only
137 minutes _ the astronomers calculated that the two stars were
less than a million miles apart and would eventually crash into
each other in about 200 million years. On cosmic time scales, that
is the very near future. The Sun, by comparison, is expected to
live about 4 billion years.
</P>
<P>
   Because the combined mass is too great for a stable star,
astronomers say, a supernova will be the result.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of this double-star system could result in an
explosion known as a type Ia supernova. Type Ia supernovae have
been immensely useful to cosmologists as cosmic candlesticks,
because they all burst at roughly the same brightness. Just as one
can calculate how far away a 60-watt light bulb is by how bright it
appears, astronomers use type Ia supernovae to calibrate cosmic
distances.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is sure exactly what is exploding in a type Ia
supernova. The spectrum of light emitted is devoid of signs of
hydrogen, which is odd since stars are generally made almost
entirely of hydrogen.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, astronomers hypothesize a type 1a supernova may
be the explosion of a white dwarf that has exhausted its hydrogen
fuel. But a white dwarf cannot explode by itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a hunk of dynamite,'' said Robert P. Kirshner, an
astronomer at the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics in
Cambridge, Mass. ``It's perfectly OK as long as you don't detonate
it.''
</P>
<P>
   One idea for how the white dwarf detonates is that it siphons
off gas from a Sun-like companion until it becomes gravitationally
unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is that the white dwarf collides with another star
_ which is the fate of KPD1930+2752 _ and then blows up.
</P>
<P>
   Kirshner, for one, is not convinced that a supernova is
inevitable. The collision could eject some of the mass, leaving
behind a stable star.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logic there is not perfect,'' Kirshner said. ``On the
other hand, it's a very intriguing system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
