<SLUG> BC-NEST-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THEY NEST': IT'S THE INSECTS WHO STEAL THIS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know this movie is in trouble when you find yourself rooting
for the killer cockroaches. The humans in this insufficient
melodrama warrant neither sympathy nor interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They Nest,'' which USA is allowing to escape tonight, does
have the germ of an idea and a few scenes of squirm-inducing
tension that may remind you of those dependable 1950s horror
movies. But these few scraps of the old formula don't add up to
successful story.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins on a dark and stormy night out on the Atlantic,
where a poor seaman is thrown overboard by his shipmates. It then
moves to a Boston hospital, where Ben Cahill (Thomas Calabro), a
surgeon who has some ill-defined competency issues, is dispatched
on a forced leave. Ben retreats to the creepy house he recently
bought on a creepy island in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   He probably should have made other travel plans. See, the body
of that unfortunate sailor has washed up on that very same island,
containing a colony of hardy African bugs. The bugs nest in the
guts of people, who then vomit larvae and die. This is graphically
depicted, over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Ben, who is rather smug for a surgeon with ill-defined
competency issues, gets off on the wrong foot with several of the
islanders, especially Jack Wald (John Savage). He's the drunken
dolt who operates the island's electrical system and harbors a
gnawing grudge against Ben because that creepy house was his family
homestead before the bank foreclosed and sold it. There are lots of
other dolts on the island, and a few OK people as well, principally
the levelheaded Sheriff Hobbs (Dean Stockwell) and the pretty,
witty storekeeper, Nell (Kristen Dalton). These two actors deserve
better vehicles. But then, so do the roaches.
</P>
<P>
   The bugs soon start multiplying like there's no tomorrow,
turning unfortunate island dwellers into roach motels. Jack is one
of the first victims. But when, on another dark and stormy night,
Ben drives into Jack's body on the road, some locals don't believe
that Jack was already dead.
</P>
<P>
   You can gauge the level of the film's wit from what the sheriff
tells Ben: ``The good news is you weren't drinkin'. The bad news is
the entire town thinks you killed Jack on purpose. Either way,
you're in a heap o' trouble, son.'' By the time everybody becomes
aware of the bugs' appetite, the island is in a heap of trouble,
too. . The film hurtles to a conclusion that makes even less sense
than the beginning. If you are, unaccountably, still watching this
film when the credits roll, tip your hat to the special-effects
people (and one insect wrangler). They, at least, seem to have met
their challenge.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THEY NEST'
</P>
<P>
   8 pm ET Tuesday on USA
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ellory Elkayem; Peter Locke, Donald Kushner and Eric
d'Arbeloff, executive producers; Jeff Barmash and George
Erschbamer, supervising producers; Simon Abbott, line producer and
production manager; John Claflin and Daniel Zelman, co-producers
and writers. Presented by the Kushner-Locke Company; produced by
Roadside Attractions for USA Network.
</P>
<P>
   With: Thomas Calabro (Dr. Ben Cahill), Dean Stockwell (Sheriff
Hobbs), John Savage (Jack Wald), Kristen Dalton (Nell Bartle) and
Tom McBeath (Eamon Wald).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
