<SLUG> BC-RICHARD-CHENEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY HAS AMASSED A FORTUNE FROM OIL INDUSTRY JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG and STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Richard Cheney, Texas Gov. George Bush's reported
choice to be his vice presidential running mate, has amassed $41.1
million in stock in the Halliburton Co. of Dallas, his corporate
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has served as an executive of Halliburton, the world's
largest oil and gas services company, since 1995 and is currently
chairman and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cheney drew a $1.28 million paycheck and was awarded
options on 300,000 shares of Halliburton stock. The year before,
Cheney received a salary of $1.18 million, bonuses worth $2.6
million and options on 100,000 shares of stock, according to
company filings with the Security and Exchange Commission. In 1997,
Cheney earned $1.1 million in salary and $1.9 million in bonuses
and options on 100,000 Halliburton shares.
</P>
<P>
   He also received other Halliburton compensation over those three
years totaling $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to an April 3 company filing with the SEC, Cheney held
1.08 million Halliburton shares. He then sold about 100,000 shares
last month when the stock price edged over $50 a share before
slipping back into the $40s, according to a document filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission. The remaining shares are worth
$41.1 million at Monday's closing price of about $42 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has had an up-and-down ride over the last
year. Last September, the stock traded at around $50 a share but
dipped to $35 by October. It peaked again at around $50 this May
when oil prices began climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also serves on the boards of several other firms,
including Union Pacific Corp., Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. and Electronic
Data Systems Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's reported selection of the former Wyoming congressman
would put two oil industry veterans on the GOP ticket, a fact that
is likely to attract criticism from Democratic opponents. Bush got
his start after graduate school in the oil fields of West Texas
where he founded an exploration firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aide Karl Rove defended a Bush-Cheney ticket against
suggestions that it represented ``Big Oil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Dick Cheney's leadership in running a construction
and oil service company to be a problem at all when compared to
this (Clinton-Gore) administration's failure to have a
comprehensive energy policy,'' Rove said on CBS News' ``Face the
Nation'' over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is telling voters that he has ``never
been afraid to take on big oil.'' Gore says that Bush ``comes out
of the oil industry'' with experience as an oil company executive
and has offered proposals that in effect would foster ``higher oil
prices to boost the oil companies' profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in turn, blames the Clinton-Gore administration for
skyrocketing gasoline prices. Gasoline prices jumped in early June
in key Midwestern states when new Environmental Protection Agency
regulations required low-pollution gasoline to be sold in 15
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``seems to forget who's been in office for seven years,''
Bush says to counter Gore criticism, adding: ``This is an
administration that's been in charge and the price of gasoline has
risen steadily.''
</P>
<P>
   While with Halliburton, Cheney has supported Republican
campaigns and causes across the country.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents filed with the Federal Election
Commission, since 1997 Cheney has donated a total of $10,000 each
to two political action committees associated with the company that
in turn wrote checks to numerous GOP campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney and his wife Lynne contributed another $20,000-plus
directly to Republican campaigns and political action committees
since 1997, including $2000 each to George W. Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg and Stewart M. Powell can be reached at
202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
