<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1653 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SON'S-MURDER-HNS &LR;      07-24 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SON'S-MURDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PARENT'S PLEA: MY SON'S MURDER DEMANDS JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM SEGAL  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was every parent's worst nightmare: the phone call
in the middle of the night. Saturday night. November 1998. A voice,
saying: ``I'm sorry. Your son. Bludgeoned by assailant. Skull
cracked open. Not expected to live. Come quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   As out-of-towners, while the hours, weeks and months unfolded,
we came to see San Francisco in awesome and awful shades of good,
bad and ugly.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Good.
</P>
<P>
   Our 28-year-old son, Anton, had come to San Francisco only
months earlier, full of confidence and capability. A National Merit
Scholar, a Harvard honors graduate, a Junior Olympics medalist,
fluent in Arabic, Japanese, French, Italian and English, Anton was
a world traveler, an adventurer/writer.
</P>
<P>
   He'd worked in Japan, dived among hammerheads in the Red Sea,
vagabonded across land-mined Cambodia and Vietnam, hitched through
war-torn Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest satisfaction lay in working with the needy, the
underprivileged, the handicapped; from kids in Boston's inner city
to paraplegic divers in the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   When Anton finally returned to the safety of the States, he
could have lived anywhere. He had friends everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   He chose San Francisco. Now he lay dying in San Francisco
General Hospital, slowly going brain dead.
</P>
<P>
   Grief-struck, we marveled even then at the tender care and
concern shown him by the doctors and staff of one of our nation's
best trauma centers.
</P>
<P>
   There was virtually no hope for Anton, right from the beginning.
His head had been staved in by a car club, and the blow had not
only ripped open his skull but had driven the brains from his right
hemisphere into the left.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary Dr. Martin Holland and his neurosurgical team
tried everything, including drilling a hole to relieve pressure in
the brain. It was to no avail. But for the compassionate care given
him by complete strangers, we say thank you, and bravo, San
Francisco!
</P>
<P>
   More of the Good.
</P>
<P>
   As the tragedy unfolded, the question was not whether our son
would die, but when. Enter more heroes _ and heroines: Genie Kozak
and Monique Gillett of the California Transplant Donor Network.
</P>
<P>
   Anton had wanted to give his organs and tissues to others, so
that, with his death, others might live. The transplant team, in
the gentlest of ways, explained the procedures; gathered our
consent; contacted the recipients, from San Francisco north to
Alaska; arranged for various teams of surgeons to harvest Anton's
different organs, then transport them to where other surgical teams
were waiting.
</P>
<P>
   We all waited three days for that fragile moment, that blink of
God's eye, when our son's brain finally died but his heart and
other organs still, momentarily, lived. Even in death, Anton gave
all he had to others.
</P>
<P>
   To the transplant teams, we say thank you, and bravo, San
Francisco!
</P>
<P>
   Heartfelt thanks as well to your often-unsung cops. Within days
of the assault, Inspectors Kervin Silas, Napoleon Hendrix (now
retired) and John Hennessey (now a lieutenant) had gathered
evidence, interviewed witnesses, located the suspect's vehicle,
found the murder weapon and arrested the suspect as he was working
at the San Francisco airport where we had arrived only days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Bad.
</P>
<P>
   The man who is accused in the murder of our son must also be
someone's son. So I can't help but wonder: Who read him ``The Cat
in the Hat''? Who played rubber ducky with him in the tub? Did
anyone drive him to piano lessons on Tuesdays and Thursdays after
school? Check his homework every night?
</P>
<P>
   How do these wild things grow up, where and when does evil take
root? The suspect is alleged to have struck Anton while our son's
back was turned _ an act both murderous and cowardly.
</P>
<P>
   More of the Bad.
</P>
<P>
   I understand that beat patrolmen, the linchpins of street crime
prevention, had been recalled shortly before Anton's murder. In an
apparent effort to save money, the walk-the-beat cops had been
replaced by fewer, cheaper, less intensive patrol-car drive-bys,
and this on a Saturday night in a high-crime area. Which brings us
to . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Ugly.
</P>
<P>
   In a city of as much beauty and promise as San Francisco, I've
been warned to stay away from certain blocks of Sixth Street and
Seventh Street. Stretches of Geary and Polk in the Tenderloin. The
seedy, seamy side to your city. I would add yet another street to
the list: Broadway near Columbus Avenue in North Beach. That is
where our son was murdered. In front of a strip club. It is an area
of high crime _ of money, drugs, sex, booze and young people: a
lethal mix.
</P>
<P>
   But it is generally considered an entertainment section, a red
light district to which San Francisco gives a green light.
</P>
<P>
   The same week Anton was fatally bludgeoned, another young man
was shot dead at a nearby club. The murders made headlines for a
couple of days. Then the smell of money and the sound of coin swept
away remembrance of things past.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ugliest stain of all is the way police, press,
politicians and people doing business in that area will blink, wink
and turn away until another young person dies there. Then another
round begins.
</P>
<P>
   It's been almost 20 months since our son's murder. Justice
delayed is justice denied.
</P>
<P>
   Anton's mother and I wait for another phone call from San
Francisco, telling us again to come quickly, this time for the
trial. We ask you, San Francisco, wait with us. Follow the trial
with us. Through it, you will discover for yourselves your good,
your bad, and your ugly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Examiner contributor Jim Segal is a Houston business executive
who says his most satisfying job has been fathering three
children.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
