<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-ASBESTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASBESTOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 PRELIMINARY WTO RULING UPHOLDS FRANCE's IMPORT BAN ON CANADIAN By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A recent ruling by the World Trade Organization that
upholds France's ban on Canadian asbestos imports has caught the
attention of environmentalists and labor rights advocates, who say
it indicates the global trade group may be growing more sensitive
to their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which affirmed the validity of a French law
prohibiting imports of hazardous materials, is also another blow to
the global asbestos industry. Other WTO members might now use the
ruling as a precedent to justify similar bans.
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos, a fibrous mineral, was once widely used in building
materials such as insulation and floor coverings, but demand for it
has shrunk drastically the last few decades because of scientific
studies that show it causes cancer and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions on the use of asbestos have been in effect for
years in the United States, where billions of dollars in
health-related claims by workers exposed to asbestos have long
clogged the court system. The European Union, following France's
lead, is soon expected to outlaw asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by a three-person WTO dispute panel is the first time
the Geneva-based trade group has upheld a member nation's trade
restriction to protect human health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time that they supported common sense, not
narrow-minded, short-term corporate interests,'' said Remi
Parmentier, a spokesman for Greenpeace, the environmental activist
organization. The International Confederation of Free Trade Unions
has also welcomed the WTO ruling as a victory for worker safety.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups, which are prominent critics of the WTO, share
concerns with a broad alliance of activists who disrupted the WTO's
meeting last December in Seattle with demonstrations accusing the
trade group of favoring business interests over the environment and
workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   WTO officials have declined to comment on the asbestos ruling
because it is not final. The final ruling is expected next month or
in September, after both sides submit their comments.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian and French missions to the WTO have also declined
to comment. But no interim ruling has ever been reversed in the
trade group's five-year history, and it is expected to be
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The asbestos case was filed two years ago by Canada on behalf of
its mining and export industry against France, which two years
earlier had banned asbestos and asbestos products as hazardous to
humans. Canada has long been a leading exporter of asbestos, most
of it mined in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Canada had sent nearly 30,000 metric tons of asbestos yearly to
France before the 1996 ban, said Denis Hamel, a spokesman for the
Asbestos Institute, a Montreal-based trade group.
</P>
<P>
   In arguments at the WTO, the Canadians said newer, safer forms
of asbestos did not release fibers into the air as older products
did. They argued that France could have adopted controls less
restrictive than a ban.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the WTO ruling will lead to restrictions
on asbestos by other member nations. Some of the initial approval
of the ruling by WTO critics has also tempered a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Lucien Royer, health and safety officer for the International
Confederation of Free Trade Unions, said the asbestos ruling
provided little guidance to how the WTO might rule in similar cases
where the safety of an export is challenged because the trade
organization's dispute-resolution process is not public
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``How the panels select and incorporate information in these
rulings is very, very murky,'' Royer said.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the ruling might actually be more confusing than
helpful in resolving other trade disputes arising from health and
environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Parmentier said it was ``too early to say whether this ruling
will affect other cases or the EU's precautionary principle.'' He
was referring to the European Union's effort to establish a
principle to justify bans on imports considered harmful to the
environment or public health.
</P>
<P>
   The test of that principle has been at the center of the
continuing trans-Atlantic trade fight over hormones in American
beef.
</P>
<P>
   The trade organization has ruled that the beef is safe and the
union's ban is illegal. But the union says that its scientific
studies establish that the beef represented enough danger to human
health to warrant not complying with the organization's ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
