<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HMOS-MEDICARE-NYT &LR;      07-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOS-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., Conn., Fla., Ill., Texas, Md., Mass., N.J.,
N.Y., Ohio, Pa.)  
 HMOs TO DROP NEARLY A MILLION MEDICARE CLIENTS  
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than 900,000 elderly and disabled people will
soon be dropped by health maintenance organizations pulling out of
the Medicare program, the Clinton administration said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The number, which is substantially greater than estimates last
month by the HMO industry, underlines the turbulence and
instability of the market in which Medicare beneficiaries seek
private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   After a preliminary survey last month, the American Association
of Health Plans, the chief lobby for the industry, predicted that
health plans would cancel insurance coverage for 711,000 Medicare
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's count, 933,687, is almost a third greater;
it represents nearly one-sixth of the 6.2 million Medicare
recipients in HMOs. Altogether, 39 million Americans are enrolled
in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries being dropped by HMOs have until Jan. 1
to make new arrangements for their health insurance. They can
enroll in other managed care plans, if any are available in their
area, or return to Medicare's original fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   Most HMOs offer prescription drug benefits and other services
not provided in the fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people affected by the new withdrawals far exceeds
the number in either of the last two years. In those years, HMOs
pulled out of more than 400 counties in at least 33 states,
directly affecting 734,000 Medicare beneficiaries _ 407,000 in 1999
and 327,000 this year. The withdrawals have touched or will touch
27 percent of all beneficiaries enrolled in managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the pullouts are a subject of debate. While the
administration says current payment rates are adequate, or more
than adequate, it says Congress needs to approve President
Clinton's proposal to pay HMOs for providing prescription drug
benefits. Under current law, health plans do not receive an
explicit or separate payment for drug benefits, though many offer
such coverage, sometimes for an additional premium.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the new figures, Nancy-Ann Min DeParle,
administrator of the Health Care Financing Administration, which
runs Medicare, said, ``The volatility of the Medicare managed care
market underscores the need for Congress to enact the president's
legislative proposal to modernize and strengthen Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karen M. Ignagni, president of the American Association of
Health Plans, said HMOs were pulling out of Medicare because they
were ``over-regulated and underpaid'' by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Ignagni said the administration underestimated the problem for
two years, but now ``shows a growing recognition of its urgency.''
She said Congress should increase direct payments to HMOs by $15
billion over the next five years _ an increase of 5.5 percent. That
sum does not include the billions of dollars that HMOs would
receive for providing drug benefits under Clinton's plan and most
congressional proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people being dropped by HMOs varies greatly from
state to state because companies typically do business in some
states, but not others, and they may withdraw from selected
counties or states. Texas, for example, will see almost three times
as many Medicare recipients dropped as New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The government figures show the withdrawals will affect 24,327
people in Arizona, 52,464 in California, 51,185 in Connecticut,
87,727 in Florida, 18,144 in Illinois, 53,038 in Maryland, 21,781
in Massachusetts, 12,411 in New Jersey, 64,329 in New York, 65,617
in Ohio, 89,641 in Pennsylvania and 180,749 in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration said that 65 HMOs chose
not to renew their Medicare contracts next year, while 53 health
plans decided to withdraw from selected counties.
</P>
<P>
   About 775,000 of the affected beneficiaries, or 83 percent, live
in areas served by other HMOs and could enroll in them if those
health plans were accepting additional Medicare patients. About
159,000 beneficiaries, or 17 percent of those being dropped by
managed care plans next year, will be left without any HMO options.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it expected to pay HMOs an average of $573 a
month, or $6,876 a year, for each Medicare beneficiary they serve
next year. Payments are somewhat lower in counties from which HMOs
are pulling out. In those counties, Medicare will pay an average of
$541 a month, or $6,492 a year, representing 94 percent of the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare payments to HMOs vary from county to county, reflecting
differences in the cost of care provided by doctors and hospitals
in the fee-for-service program. The administration said that people
in high-paid urban areas as well as low-paid rural areas would be
affected by the HMO withdrawals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
