<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG WILL DETERMINE HOW LONG THE CELEBRATION CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Lance Armstrong celebrated his second successive Tour de
France victory in ways expected _ a glass or two of Champagne, a
party with hundreds of his closest friends and sponsors; and in
ways unexpected _ with nine other cancer survivors, he signed the
Paris Charter Against Cancer, an information service.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is how long this annual celebration will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stop a lot earlier than people expect,'' the
leader of the U.S. Postal Service team said even before he wrapped
up his latest success. ``I don't want to stretch out my career.
When it's time to stop, I'll know it, the people around me will
know it, and I'll just go and quit.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Although the 28-year-old Armstrong has many peak years left in
principle, he sounds dubious about trying to match the record of
five Tour victories held by Jacques Anquetil, Eddy Merckx, Bernard
Hinault and Miguel Indurain, the dominant riders of the 1960s,
'70s, '80s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For that matter, Greg LeMond, with three Tour victories, still
outranks him among Americans. ``That's a great accomplishment,''
Armstrong said of LeMond's record, adding that it was no motivation
to him to try to match him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I don't know if I have the desire to try to win five because
I now have a wonderful family that ultimately I want to spend a lot
more time with,'' Armstrong said during the Tour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It would be crazy for me to think I can win five in a row
because there are many talented people in the sport. So that would
mean that if I were to win five, I would have to do a total of
seven or something like that. You can't win every year _ you have
accidents or somebody comes along that's better than you.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have the motivation for all of those years, then I'll try
to do it. The way I ride, the way I train and race, is based all on
motivation and love of the sport. If I love the sport and love what
I do for five more years, then I'll try.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can't guarantee it. When you put so much into it, pack
so much into it, I don't think it's good for longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Longevity is a major concern in his recovery from cancer and
his campaign, as head of a foundation, to increase awareness of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It's still my main objective,'' he said. `'I need to prove
not only that I came back one time but that I'm surviving the
illness for another year, for another five years, for however many
years I can survive _ that's the issue I like to push forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year that I come back to the Tour de France is another
year that I survived this illness.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that not finishing first would not discourage him. ``If
I don't win next year, I think I'll still come back and try again
the following year. That won't drive me from the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his domination, Armstrong still has room to grow
stronger, said Chris Carmichael, his trainer for the last 10 years
and a former rider himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's about 2 percent stronger this year over last year, based
on tests before the Tour,'' Carmichael said, ``but 2 percent is
enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael thought the Texan was 10 percent stronger now than
before his testicular cancer was diagnosed in 1996. ``That doesn't
sound very much, but it's an awful lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael also tried to explain his protege's power in the
mountains the last two years. Before then, Armstrong was not
regarded as a leading climber.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all subtle things,'' he said. ``Now they look
glaringly different, but they're really not. His pedal speed and
things like that _ that's work that's been taking a long time to
get to the point where he is now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Alps and Pyrenees during the last two Tours, the Texan
has been using a smaller gear and more pedal strokes a minute to
push it than he did before. ``Most of it is between 85 to 90
revolutions per minute when he's climbing,'' Carmichael said,
``which is about 10 r.p.m. more than is traditional, what he used
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who said Monday that he would enter both the time
trial and the road race at the Olympics in Sydney, Australia, in
September, also credits his increased time spent training on the
hills near his home in Nice and improved eating habits to bring his
weight down to 73 kilograms (161 pounds) from 82 kilograms in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do eat some red meat, but not a lot,'' he said. ``I eat a
lot of fish in Nice, more fish than I eat chicken. They catch the
fish right there in Nice, fresh out of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of tricks to losing weight,'' he said,
including his occasional habit of weighing his portions down to the
gram before they are cooked.
</P>
<P>
   So, after his autobiography was published this spring, will his
next effort be ``The Lance Armstrong Diet Book''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
