<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1663 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS &LR;      07-24 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON KEEPING WHEELS OF NEGOTIATION TURNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Anxious to cobble together pieces of an
Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement, President Clinton worked
through the night after his return from Japan and then resumed
negotiations Monday with small groups on the most difficult issues
dividing the sides.
</P>
<P>
   On the 14th day of the summit, in talks that are now longer than
the original Camp David negotiations in 1978, White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart portrayed Clinton standing in the vortex of the
negotiations, saying that the president would press on unless the
proceedings collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart refused to say whether the negotiators were writing
parts of a document, saying only that the negotiators had been
taking notes. But he confirmed that all issues, including the
potential dealbreaker of Jerusalem, were being hashed out Monday in
``exhaustive and exhausting'' discussions.
</P>
<P>
   With pressure mounting against a peace agreement from right-wing
Jewish and Islamic factions in the Middle East, Clinton met
separately late Sunday with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, and then held discussions with
their top aides from midnight until 5 a.m Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After five hours' sleep, he reconvened the small group in his
Aspen Cabin for four more hours of discussions. Sometimes Clinton
met with both sides, sometimes with one side alone. After a
midafternoon break, he again brought together the sides Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat were kept abreast of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   As long as ``the president believes that discussions are
substantive and have the potential of leading to an agreement, he
will remain here, and he will keep the parties here, to keep
working,'' Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``I think the fact that he was up until 5 a.m.
working through the issues should lead you to believe he thinks
staying here for the time being is worthwhile.'' But ``it's
impossible to predict the likelihood'' of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The president is scheduled to attend a memorial service for a
family friend in Arkansas Tuesday, leaving Camp David around noon
and returning at midnight, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   That means two things: Either the talks break up before Clinton
leaves, or nothing substantive will be announced until Wedneday at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 24 hours after his arrival from Japan on Sunday, the
president was neither more nor less hopeful for a deal, Lockhart
said. ``I think he's right where he was when he left Japan,'' the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Two US officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said
the US negotiators were upbeat about returning to talks following a
15-hour flight from Japan, where they had attended a Group of Eight
summit. But the officials said it did not mean that the US team was
optimistic about their chances of pulling out a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea, obviously, is that with the pressure, the
exhaustion, and the sheer proximity will get them to make
compromises, to start horse-trading,'' said one of the officials.
``If the deal wasn't so difficult, it would be more sane to allow
them to go out. But we're not going to allow that here. It's really
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Former US ambassador to Israel Samuel Lewis, one of the ten US
negotiators assisting President Carter at the 1978 Camp David
summit that led to an Israeli-Egyptian peace deal, said Monday that
signs pointed toward an eventual agreement _ partial or complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer it goes on, the more difficult it is to leave
without anything,'' Lewis said. ``They have been there two weeks
now, so I think there will be something, barring second thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   While a news blackout has kept a lid on the substance of the
talks, it has been clear from officials in the Middle East who have
talked with negotiators that the main problem at Camp David has
been the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israel captured and annexed East Jerusalem from Jordan in 1967
and now insists on a unified Holy City, under Israeli control. The
Palestinians are demanding sovereignty over East Jerusalem, under
which they would allow unfettered access to holy sites for Jews,
Christians and Muslims. Israel now permits free access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question was whether Arafat was going to begin to
negotiate about a partial arrangement on Jerusalem,'' Lewis said.
``A few clues have slipped out that maybe that's been happening. If
it does happen, in around three or four days they will break up
with a deal, or they'll break up (Monday) without a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   One clue came from the travels of Arab leaders around the Middle
East, notably Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who visited Saudi
Arabian King Fahd and Crown Prince Abdullah on Sunday. Mubarak, a
strong US ally, also was expected to talk in coming days with
Syria's new President Bashar Assad and Jordan's King Abdullah II.
</P>
<P>
   Many US analysts believe that Mubarak is attempting to rally
support for Arafat around a partial sovereignty deal for east
Jerusalem. But Lebanese political commentator Hisham Melhem said
Arab leaders would not advise Arafat on his decision regarding the
fate of the city, which contains the third holiest site in Islam
behind Mecca and Medina in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Arab world, this issue is extremely emotional and
combustible,'' Melhem said. ``If word got out that the Egyptian
leaders, or the Jordanian leader, or any of the Arab leaders,
counseled Arafat to be flexible, it would cause great domestic
trouble with the Islamists.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, too, faces intense domestic pressure not to give up any
part of Jerusalem to the Palestinians. Likud leader Ariel Sharon
said Monday that no Israeli prime minister had the power to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The only deadline looming over the talks was next Sunday's
presidential elections in Israel, which Barak has said he wants to
attend. To make the vote, Barak would have to leave by midday
Thursday to land in Israel before the beginning of Shabbat.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the lack of a firm deadline, Lockhart said that the
president has told both sides that they would only stay if they
made progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot give you a precise formula, except to say that the
president has got this very issue foremost in his mind and he will
remain here as long as he believes we have some prospect of
success,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
