<SLUG> BC-NIEMAN-CURATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER EDITOR OF DETROIT NEWS TO HEAD NIEMAN GROUP  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Mass., Calif.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert H. Giles, a veteran newspaper editor, will be the next
curator of Harvard University's Nieman Foundation for professional
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Giles confirmed Monday that Harvard President Neil L.
Rudenstine had told Giles last week of the appointment to head the
62-year-old program, which brings 24 United States and foreign
journalists to the university for a year's study. The appointment
was first reported by Editor &AMP; Publisher magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment follows weeks of uncertainty that followed a
strong union challenge to the candidacy of Giles, whose actions as
editor of The Detroit News earned him the contempt of striking
journalists. A wave of letters to Harvard in June, from union
representatives arguing that Giles slanted the News' coverage, was
followed by a second wave from editors and newspaper executives
from around the country vouching for him. One called him ``an
innovative and ethical journalist and leader throughout his
distinguished career.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles will replace Bill Kovach, who served as curator for the
past decade. He becomes the second journalist named this summer to
a highly visible academic post. In June, Jim Bettinger, a former
city editor at The San Jose Mercury-News was named director of
Stanford University's Knight Fellowship Program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
