<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-HOME-SALE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF PARENTS' HOME MAY BE A HEARTACHE TO ADULT OFFSPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, July 24, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With five photos of Lia Lopez cleaning her girlhood closet
(NNS1), Lopez and mother in Lopez's bedroom (NNS2), Lopez and
mother walking (NNS3), Bob Laney (NNS4) and Rob Laney walking with
parents (NNS5). 
 (Note to editors: Lia in lede is cq) 
 By MICHELE M. MELENDEZ  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESANING, Mich. _ Lia Lopez walked through the doorway of her
old room and stepped into her childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Goofy, girlish memories sprang from all sides -- the crevice in
the closet where she'd hid her secret letters; the deep-pile,
burgundy carpet where she'd clumsily spilled countless bottles of
Coke; the lamp clamped to her brass headboard, whose bulb had
warmed her always-cold hands.
</P>
<P>
   It had been years since Lopez, 30, had visited the family home
in Chesaning, a farming town 100 miles northwest of Detroit. But
the house where she grew up had drawn her back. Her parents had put
the tri-level home up for sale, and Lopez wanted to soak in the
surroundings one last time.
</P>
<P>
   When parents sell the family home, their adult children might
feel a twinge, a sense of loss. A childhood home lets you cling to
younger days, more playful days, a time when you didn't have the
faintest clue about credit card statements or stress headaches.
</P>
<P>
   It can be a confusing and uneasy transition on various levels.
It can nudge you into realizing that your parents are aging, or
make you believe that you're forfeiting your childhood. The hardest
part may be figuring out how to feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing a home which is so much a part of our past can be
discomforting, because in a sense losing this concrete and visible
reminder of our past symbolizes the loss of opportunity to go back
in time and reminisce,'' said Joseph Tecce, a Boston University
psychology professor. ``Not being able to stroll through our old
bedroom or the back yard where we played or had family celebrations
is tantamount to diminishing the reality and significance of these
special times.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez's parents, Bob and Kerry Laney, both teachers, retired
this year. In their mid-50s, they're itching to build a custom home
in an active retirement community in the Smoky Mountain foothills
of eastern Tennessee. The couple will have golf courses, 40 miles
of lake shoreline and all sorts of diversions within easy reach.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, older Americans stay put. A U.S. Census Bureau
report released in July says that between March 1998 and March
1999, just 6.7 percent of people ages 55 to 64 moved and only 4.5
percent of people 65 and older did. (People in their 20s moved the
most -- 32.4 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of homeowners 65 and older have lived in
their homes for at least 10 years, and about half the owners in
that age group have lived in the same house for 20 or more years,
census figures say.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that her parents planned to sell their house, Lopez
wanted to show her husband, Jose, where she grew up. The two
recently made the trip from their home in Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez recalled sneaking out with her friends at night to spook
each other at a nearby cemetery, walking for miles beside her
mother amid the wheat and soy fields surrounding the house, and
watching the progress of an evergreen tree she helped plant outside
her window.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny how a place can make you remember certain times in
your life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Until they put their house on the market, the Laneys had left
their children's rooms untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Their son, Rob Laney, said it was bizarre knowing that his
boyhood room would be gone. With its brown shag carpet, National
Geographic world map and shelves of comic books and Hardy Boys
paperbacks, the surroundings always felt familiar and natural to
the 33-year-old now living in a Detroit suburb -- an easy fit.
</P>
<P>
   About his parents' move, he said, ``It hasn't really sunken in
yet. I try not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adult children react in every which way to the selling of their
childhood home, said Tony Morganti, a real estate agent in Cuyahoga
Falls, Ohio. Some are eager to get their parents out of the house,
especially if the parents are ill. Others feel so strongly about
the house, they'll buy it to keep it in the family.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotions that people deal with can be as different as the
people themselves,'' Morganti said.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Lipovan Holan doesn't know how she should feel.
</P>
<P>
   She's helping her father sell the family's ``nondescript
three-bedroom ranch'' house in Middleburg Heights, Ohio, the
Cleveland suburb where she and her siblings grew up.
</P>
<P>
   As she cleared out the house, Holan, 32, found precious tokens
of the family -- love letters her parents wrote to each other in
their native Romanian, crude pot holders she and her siblings
fashioned at summer camp, report cards, old photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange to know that house won't be ours anymore,'' she
said. ``I can't put my finger on what the emotion is, but it
definitely is uneasy and unsettling.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Judith Levy, a Minneapolis psychotherapist, said that losing the
family home can represent a further separation from your parents, a
step toward becoming more of an individual. The loss also can make
children realize how much they had depended on their parents to
store childhood memories, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation of yuppies are mobile, in the moment,
ambitious,'' said Levy, 53. ``It's been a reliance on the parents
to maintain the homestead and the past and the history.''
</P>
<P>
   Adults can become devoted to their childhood homes ``the way
kids get attached to blankies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Levy speaks from experience. When her parents sold the beige
stucco house in which she grew up on Long Island, she didn't know
how to react.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could not bear the thought that that house was not
going to be ours anymore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   On separate occasions, she, her two sisters and her brother
stopped by the house. They all knocked on the door to tell the new
owners they had grown up there, but none went in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the house would be different inside, that the new
owners would have changed it,'' Levy said. ``We wanted to preserve
the memories of how it looked when we lived there.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Bette Sparago, 54, cannot bring herself to see her parents' old
house, a Scarsdale, N.Y., colonial where they lived for 50 years.
They moved to the Osborn Retirement Community in nearby Rye almost
two years ago, and Sparago has driven past the house just once.
</P>
<P>
   As a girl, she would hide behind the porch's wide pillars and
snoop on the neighborhood. She'd spend hours there, sometimes
giggling at the thought that the passersby didn't know she was
watching and listening. She fondly remembers her mother's dinner
parties and her father's part-time dental office on the first
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Sparago knew that her parents needed a smaller place. Her father
had been ill for several years, and her mother couldn't keep
maintaining such a spacious house. Before they moved, Sparago
snapped pictures in every room and from every window. She said she
still can't look at the
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so traumatic,'' she said. ``I loved that house, but my
mother was right. The house had given us all it could. It was time
for them to move. ... I feel silly talking about this. I don't know
why I'm so emotional about it.''
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   David Lawson, who teaches educational psychology at Texas A&AMP;M
University and counsels families at his private practice, said
those unclear feelings are typical: ``The emotions (about a house)
can sometimes run so deep and wide that we're not even aware of
them until the specter of losing it comes along.''
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The Laney children said they're not sure how they will feel
after their parents move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll never be back here,'' Lopez said. ``It's strange
to know that. It's kind of sad to say goodbye.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
