u a BC-DRUG-REIMPORTS-NEWHOU     07-24 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-REIMPORTS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RE-IMPORTING' U.S.-MADE MEDICINES EITHER A PAIN OR A CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, July 24, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By J. SCOTT ORR  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Imagine millions of pills bouncing back and forth
across U.S. borders like tennis balls.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has consumers of prescription drugs anticipating deep
savings and the pharmaceutical industry fearing a wave of cheap and
possibly dangerous imports of their own products flooding the U.S.
market.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate last week approved legislation that would allow
pharmacies and drug wholesalers to ``re-import'' U.S.-made
pharmaceuticals that have been exported to other countries --
Canada, for instance -- that have price controls to restrict the
cost of drugs to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates, including many in Congress, argue that the
legislation will force reductions in both drug prices and border
crossings by Americans who buy drugs in Canada and other countries
in which U.S. drugs are discounted.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure, led by the pharmaceutical industry,
believe lifting the ban would create health risks by exposing
Americans to drugs that have been outside U.S. control.
</P>
<P>
   They also argue that there is no guarantee that pharmacies and
drug wholesalers would pass savings along to consumers and that
profit margins must be maintained to fund expensive research toward
the next generation of miracle drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate's action may be well-intended,'' said Alan F.
Holmer, president of Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America. ``But the (legislation) could jeopardize patient safety
and would not ensure any savings for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmer said re-importation of drugs is just as dangerous now as
it was in 1988 when the Congress voted to prohibit the practice as
a safeguard for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, innovative prescription medicines can be cheaper in
Canada than in the U.S., primarily because the government of Canada
controls their prices. But importing medicines from Canada would
pose unacceptable health risks to Americans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry is not alone in questioning the
safety of re-imported drugs. In testimony this year to the Senate,
former Food and Drug Administration Commissioner Jane Henney said
allowing re-importation could cause Canada ``to somehow be used as
a front for counterfeit products becoming available.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The trackability of a pedigree of a drug is more than in
question. Where did the bulk product come from? How was it
manufactured? You're just putting yourself at increased risk when
you don't know all of those things,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another former FDA commissioner, David A. Kessler, wrote in a
letter to Congress last year that the Internet has increased the
risks of importation of ``adulterated and counterfeit products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Repealing the prohibition on re-importation of drugs would
remove one of the principal statutory tools for dealing with this
growing issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for every voice predicting that repealing the ban on
re-imported drugs will lead to new dangers, there are dozens, if
not hundreds, of voices decrying the high cost of drugs in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is long overdue that people in this country are able to get
drugs at the much more affordable prices that they are available in
Canada, Europe and elsewhere,'' said Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of
Public Citizen's Health Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that the industry keeps charging price-gouging
prices to afford research is a major-league lie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major step towards making the basic right to
affordable prescription drugs for all Americans a reality,'' said
Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., a key sponsor of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``By improving competition and promoting free trade, we can
lower drug costs in this country while still making sure that the
drugs are safe and effective. ... It's time to end the
pharmaceutical industry's rip-off of American consumers,''
Wellstone said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher T. Rhodes, a professor of applied pharmaceutical
sciences at the University of Rhode Island, said the FDA and other
agencies ``possess the necessary personnel, equipment and expertise
so that samples of re-imported products could be subjected to
appropriate laboratory testing should such action be thought
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of using re-imported prescription drugs in the
U.S. need not place the American public at any increased risk of
ineffective or dangerous products,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The measure still faces a variety of hurdles, first in Congress
and then in the administration before any savings could be felt by
consumers, particularly the elderly at which the measure is aimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very difficult,'' said Richard Tarplin, assistant
secretary of the Department of Health and Human Services, referring
to the language inserted into the bill at the last minute to
require HHS to certify that re-importation poses no additional
risks to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate the additional protections, but they're only
workable if Congress provides additional resources to implement
them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
