<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE FINDS `RUNNING MATES' IN SIERRA CLUB, UNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Vice President Al Gore's campaign has known for some
time that it would have to come up with something pretty good to
dampen the bounce Texas Governor George W. Bush hopes to get from
the GOP convention next week.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Democrats' convention doesn't begin until Aug.14, they
will probably try to contain Bush's expected gain in the polls by
announcing Gore's running mate, shifting focus from the governor to
the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats might not have counted on the phenomenon
confronting them right now: Pre-convention bounce, fueled by the
wild speculation and eager anticipation about Bush's running mate,
who is expected to be named Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   All weekend long the pundits and the public have been all over
the Republican guessing game: Friday's front-runner fever for
Senator John McCain gave way to Saturday's for former Pentagon
chief Dick Cheney, followed by another wave, for former Senator
John Danforth, who by Monday was succeeded yet again as
front-runner by Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   So, to compete for airtime on issues, like the Sierra Club's
endorsement of Gore, Gore and his aides, ever adaptable, seem to
have simply siezed on the Republican vice-presidential brouhaha to
help make their case against Bush, working it in at every
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A word about running mates,'' Gore began as he stood by the
Grand River in Grand Rapids, Mich., accepting the Sierra Club's
endorsement. But he wasn't going to give anything away. ``Right
now,'' he said wryly, ``I just want to say how proud I am to be
running with the Sierra Club.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland later in the day, Gore used the same technique,
except this time his ``running mates'' were union workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk these days about running mates,'' he
told a group of construction workers at the site of the New Federal
Courthouse in Cleveland, his shirtsleeves rolled up. ``I'm proud to
be running with the construction trades and working men and
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his unscheduled show of solidarity with the workers on
his way to a Democratic National Committee fundraiser with almost
50 supporters at the English Oak Inn. It netted $200,000 for the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsing Gore at the Grand River, Sierra Club president Dr.
Robert Cox said Gore, if elected president, would be ``the most
pro-environment president in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You and I know that in the long term there really is no such
thing as a prosperous economy ringed with pollution,'' Gore told
supporters. ``Our opponents still claim that somehow pollution is
the inescapable price of prosperity. They cling to the old way of
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke of his longtime commitment to the environment, which
began when he was a child on his family's farm in Carthage, Tenn.,
and his mother gave him a copy of Rachel Carson's ``Silent
Spring,'' which warned of the dangers of pesticides. He pledged to
fight global warming and pollution as president, and to create jobs
while doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wove the topic on most people's minds throughout his
speech, sometimes more gracefully than others:
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm told in these days leading up to the Republican
convention, Copies of `Earth In the Balance' are selling quite well
in Philadelphia,'' Gore said, referring to the book on the
environment he authored in 1991. ``And I know that the polluters
and the special intersts are coming after me, and I wear their
attacks as a badge of honor!''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has also taken shots at Bush for failing to
conduct his running-mate search with dignity. The frenzy over
Bush's selection of a running mate, Gore spokesman Chris Lehane
said, demonstrated both that Bush was having trouble finding a
suitable partner, and that he lacked sufficient discretion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't turned the process into a sound bite, a photo-op
and a parade,'' Lehane said. ``Bush's (search) is like a frat party
rush. There are different names everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   That point was made less directly by Gore himself, in an
interview with a Grand Rapids Television Monday: ``I have tried to
handle the process in a different way,'' he said. ``And keep it
private.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett dismissed the criticisms Monday as
``more silly attacks from a campaign that can't stop attacking.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Republican convention, Gore will disappear from view.
On Thursday, he heads for the seaside near Wilmington, N.C., for a
weeklong vacation with his family. The Vice President's campaign
workers will make themselves scarce, too _ each campaign usually
allows the other to have its moment in the sun with little
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Their usual public activities will be taken up by surrogates
coordinated by the Democratic National Committee. The DNC is
currently coralling a slew of members of Congress and other
prominent democrats from around the country to form a kind of rapid
response team, or a ``truth squad'' in current campaign parlance.
They'll be ready to pepper reporters with counterpoints to
Republican messages during the convention, just as the Gore
campaign does the rest of the time.
</P>
<P>
   After the fundraiser, Gore met with members of steelworkers'
unions from swing states across the Midwest, and vowed to protect
their rights to organize and strike. His support among unions is
not unanimous: the United Auto Workers, for one, have withheld
their outright support, flirting instead with Green Party nominee
Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, as he has been saying for over a week, that he
understands voters' disillusion with government, and that he thinks
he can remedy it. He asked the union members to ``take a chance''
on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ask you to allow yourself to believe, without
reservation, that we can do the right thing in this country and be
the better for it, and not stay back, not stay at arm's length,''
Gore said. ``Don't be afraid and disapointed about being let down _
I will not let you down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
