<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLUMN-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ABC'S DEDICATION TO WOODS PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC Sports' broadcast of the British Open provided ample
evidence that it devotedly followed the hitherto secret ``Official
Network Guide to Covering Golf When Tiger Woods Leads the
Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Rule 1: Don't worry about fairness. Being unfair means showing
him as frequently as possible, and that's why we're in this
business, isn't it? During his final round on Sunday, ABC cut to
Woods 247 times, totaling 69 minutes and 19 seconds of Tiger
face-time. It would have been more but ABC wasted time enduring the
four shots David Duval needed to depart a pot bunker at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 2: It is not impolite to talk about the strategy for
another golfer while the camera stays on Tiger. On the 10th hole,
while ABC's Judy Rankin and Steve Melnyk analyzed the upcoming
second shot for Duval, the camera remained on Woods for 43 seconds
as he sipped water and walked. Perfect execution.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 3: You can dump any golfer, no matter what he's doing, to
go to Tiger. Thomas Bjorn was just starting his backswing _ in an
attempt to blast out of a pot bunker _ when ABC cut to Tiger
marking his ball on the fourth green. Woods then talked to his
caddie, ambled about and watched Duval walk. We never learned what
became of Bjorn.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 4: If Tiger's partner is putting _ or clipping his
fingernails _ include Tiger in the shot. Four times, BBC cameras
used by ABC zoomed out to keep Tiger in the frame with Duval even
though Tiger was walking away and it was Duval's turn to putt.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 5: Avoid showing any other golfer walking. Oh, Duval
occasionally slunk into the shot if it was wide enough. But
invariably, ABC closed in on Tiger as he walked heroically from
green to tee and tee to fairway. When Tiger birdied 10 to extend
his lead to four strokes, ABC followed Woods solo for 25 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ABC/BBC brilliantly followed this rule on the 18th, when a
nearly crazed mob almost overran the fairway, interrupting Woods'
march to the green. It was a dangerous scene. But for a stretch of
1 minute 53 seconds, ABC showed Tiger patiently making his way. For
one brief moment, Duval appeared in the corner of the screen. After
that, he could have been buried up to his goatee in a pot bunker.
Duval was next seen, thankfully healthy, from a high shot taken
from the Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 6: Anything Tiger does is of paramount importance. On the
13th, Duval was lining up his putt. For 19 seconds, ABC believed
his protracted analysis of the green was of secondary importance to
Woods reading his yardage chart. Excellent decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 7: Cut to other golfers, risk your job. A heretic brazenly
felt that a birdie try by Ernie Els on the 10th hole superseded the
importance of a a short Tiger putt on 7 _ an unnecessary gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 8: Do not pre-empt Tiger shots for updates. Don't worry
that Duval's tee shot on the 13th (into a bunker) was shown on tape
when ABC reported on Lance Armstrong's victory in the Tour de
France. Be fortunate that a Tiger shot was not sacrificed to an
update.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's dedication to the Tiger rules contributed to Sunday's 7.5
overnight Nielsen rating, up 32 percent from last year's final
round. When the national rating is calculated, it will rank as the
highest rated British Open since 1972 and will likely have been
seen by more TV households than have ever watched it.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods won the U.S. Open last month, the final round rated
an 8.8, owing in part to the late afternoon broadcast time. The
British Open on Sunday started at 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, NBC showed 89 minutes of Tiger Face-Time over a
similar four-hour time period, which could have tipped the balance.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMERALL NOT REALLY RETIRING
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to industry reports and a press release by Fox Sports,
Pat Summerall is not retiring from Fox's National Football League
broadcast booth in two seasons. Monday, Summerall and Fox said the
announcer has signed a one-year extension through the 2001 season,
which will let him call the 2002 Super Bowl in his 50th year in pro
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't mean it's a retirement,'' said David Hill,
chairman of the Fox Sports Television Group, refuting a Fox press
release, which said Summerall's ``remarkable and legendary NFL
broadcasting career'' will end with Super Bowl XXXVI. Even
Summerall was quoted as saying his ``NFL broadcasting career is
coming to a close.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is it? It will be up to Summerall to stay in the booth
with John Madden past 2002, take an unspecified job at Fox, or
retire.
</P>
<P>
   By conference call _ not press release _ Summerall said, ``More
than anything, 50 years meant a lot to me.'' He added: ``If I don't
have any health problems, and I feel as good as I feel now and I'm
as enthusiastic as I am now, I may continue.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Summerall had his left knee replaced, ending years of
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't affect my thinking, but things weren't getting
better, they were getting worse,'' he said. ``That's a
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   HYPE EQUALS RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's much anticipated 200-meter race showdown between
Maurice Greene and Michael Johnson at the U.S. track and field
Olympic trials fizzled when both runners pulled hamstrings. But the
hype yielded a strong 7.8 rating from 8:30 to 9 p.m. ET, its final
half-hour, up from a 6.4 for the previous half-hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
