<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Tuesday, July
25, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Larry
Johnson on the Post-Intelligencer's National/Foreign Desk at (206)
448-8035.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-FARNBOROUGH (London) _ Boeing announces orders at the
Farnborough International air show for more than 110 new jets worth
about $12 billion at list prices, but the Seattle-based aerospace
giant still finds itself being elbowed out of the spotlight on the
world aerospace stage by Airbus and its A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE-POLICE (SEattle) _ Gil Kerlikowske, deputy director of
the Justice Department's community policing program, is named
Seattle's next police chief. He is former head of the Buffalo
police department.
</P>
<P>
   By Kimberly A.C. Wilson. (Story will move in the ``a''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-TOUR-SITCOMS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Actor Michael Richards is
reed thin. Actor John Goodman is not. But the two have something
very much in common: Each has a new sitcom on the fall schedule,
and neither had much to bring to show-and-tell at the TV critics'
press tour in Pasadena. After shooting pilot episodes, each has
scrapped the first draft and gone back to the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Seattle Mariners host Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   By John Hickey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Laura Vecsey column on the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
