<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS, BOEING ANNOUNCE ORDERS FOR JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle for supremacy of the skies heated up in Britain
Monday when Airbus Industrie announced it had received an order for
its super jumbo jet, the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Co., however, also announced a spate of orders for its
777, the 300- to 350-seat airplane officials at the Seattle-based
company believe will keep the need for 550-seat aircraft low
because the airplane will fragment the market by flying between new
city pairs, like Boston-Tokyo, rather than established trunk routes
like Tokyo-Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But when Airbus Industrie announced Monday at the Farnborough
International Air Show outside London that it has orders for 17 of
the A3XX, it signaled the end of Boeing's monopoly of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus said Emirates, the international airline of United Arab
Emirates, placed an order for seven aircraft and options for five
more, for the 550-seat double-deck A3XX. Airbus also announced that
Air France signed a letter of intent to purchase 10 A3XX airplanes,
with options for more. The first A3XX are scheduled to be delivered
in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, Airbus and Boeing have orders worth about $15 billion.
Of those orders, about $11 billion goes to Boeing, including 33 777
models to International Lease Finance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ILFC and Airbus have scheduled a press briefing for Tuesday,
which will likely include new orders for Airbus aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly turning out to be a better year than
anticipated,'' said Mike Bair, Boeing vice president of marketing
management for airplane programs. ``The simple reason is the
economy is doing well and air travel is almost entirely linked to
how well economies around the world are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And Boeing officials also unveiled their annual market forecast
that indicates the market for new planes in the next 20 years will
be worth some $1.5 trillion. Boeing estimates about 55 percent will
be for regional jets and single-aisle aircraft, while the need for
super jumbos represents 6 percent of the total market.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the small demand, Boeing has said it cannot afford to
invest anywhere near the $12 billion to $15 billion that Airbus
will need for developing a new aircraft model.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Boeing plans on offering a derivative of the 747, which
will seat up to 522 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feedback to our future 747 models has been extremely
positive,'' said John Roundhill, Boeing's vice president of
Commercial Airplanes Product Strategy and Development. ``With our
customers, we have developed a wonderful large airplane solution.''
Boeing expects the first 747 derivative to enter service in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first year that Airbus, the European
consortium, sold more airplanes than Boeing. But the 747
represented a market for which Airbus had no plane to match Boeing.
Now, with the A3XX, that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Emirates said it planned to use the A3XX to accomodate passenger
growth on routes from Dubai to London, the Far East, and North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The A3XX will also enable us to carry more passengers to and
from congested airports with limited take-off and landing slots,''
said Emirates chairman Sheikh Ahmed bin Saeed Al-Maktoum, in an
Airbus press release.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service reports were used to prepare this article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
