   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   NY-WEST-NILE (New York) _ The first mosquitoes in the city
infected with the West Nile virus have been found in Central Park,
forcing the city to close the park overnight to spray in its battle
against the mosquitoes. Among the casualties of the war against the
West Nile virus is a concert by the New York Philharmonic, a
planned Roadrunner's run, softball games and all the usual
impromptu activities. By Eric Lipton. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   NY-CONVICTIONS-OVERTURN (New York) _ It is difficult to overturn
a conviction in New York, even in the face of powerful new
evidence, as the story of David Lemus and Olmado Hidalgo reveals.
Trial judges and state appeals courts have always been reluctant to
reverse a jury's verdict, and in 1996, Congress sharply limited the
rights of defendants to take their appeals to federal court. By
Jane Fritsch and David Rohde. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ In its 14th day, the Camp David
peace negotiations intensify as President Clinton plunges into the
nitty-gritty of issue-by-issue deliberations. After meeting until
almost dawn with Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, he then
oversaw a day and night of what officials said quietly was the
exercise of drafting the skeleton of an agreement. The White House,
which is overseeing a news blackout on the sensitive talks, would
not confirm that a document was being drafted. By Deborah Sontag.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REVOLUTION (San Vicente Del Caguan, Colombia) _ The
dream of a Marxist-Leninist revolution remains improbably alive
amid the rolling cattle pastures and steamy coca fields of southern
Colombia. By Clifford Krauss. (The story has moved in ``i'' news
file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   HEROISM-RECONSIDERED (West Paducah, Ky.) _ Ben Strong was said
to have displayed remarkable courage when he disarmed Michael
Carneal, the 14-year-old killer who opened fire on a prayer group
at Heath High School here on Dec. 1, 1997. But as new information
about the events that morning emerges because of a civil lawsuit,
some people here are openly challenging the portrait of Strong as a
hero. His story shows how chaos and panic can distort the accounts
that witnesses give of the rampage killings that periodically
horrify the country. It may show, too, how the stories of the
killings are often shaped by the powerful desire of reporters and
everyone else involved to find some good news in horrible,
inexplicable events. By Alex Berenson. (The story has moved in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   GA-MILLER (Atlanta) _ Roy Barnes of Georgia appoints former Gov.
Zell Miller to fill the Senate seat left vacant by the death of
Paul Coverdell. By Kevin Sack. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HMOS-MEDICARE (Washington) _ More than 900,000 elderly and
disabled people will soon be dropped by health maintenance
organizations pulling out of the Medicare program, the Clinton
administration says. By Robert Pear. (The story has moved in ``w''
news file.) 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PRISONERS (London) _ Michael Stone, a Protestant
guerrilla who killed three mourners in a Belfast cemetery during an
IRA funeral in 1988, leaves prison, the first of 88 jailed fighters
who will be freed this week in the last wave of early releases
mandated by the Northern Ireland peace accord. By Warren Hoge. (The
story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-NY-TICKETS (New York) _ The Manhattan district attorney and
the New York state attorney general announce the indictments of
more than a dozen people on ticket-scalping charges involving the
Yankees and Mets. By Katherine E. Finkelstein. (Scheduled to move
by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
