<SLUG> BC-COLO-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUSH FIRE THREATENS INDIAN CLIFF DWELLINGS IN COLORADO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Five hundred firefighters struggled Monday to get in
front of a blaze that had already burned some 20,000 acres of brush
in the Mesa Verde National Park and was closing in on the park's
famous ancient Indian cliff dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   Fierce winds had already pushed the fire to within four miles of
the 1,000-year-old cliff homes. And Justin Dombrowski, information
officer with the Rocky Mountain Incident Command Team, which is
overseeing the operation, said, ``Even if the flames don't touch
the sites, there is concern for damage from the scorching heat of
the fire.'' The authorities are also concerned about erosion now
that thousands of burned acres lack the brush to soak up rain.
</P>
<P>
   The fire at Mesa Verde _ a 52,000-acre park in far southwestern
Colorado _ was touched off by lightning Thursday. All visitors to
the park, some 700 people, and many park employees were evacuated
that day. But about 50 remaining employees and their families did
not leave until early Monday, after the blaze jumped the access
road, which fire crews felt was safe to use again.
</P>
<P>
   The fire tripled in size on Sunday when a huge plume of smoke
could be seen for miles around and ash rained down on surrounding
towns. By Monday it was nine miles long.
</P>
<P>
   The fire has generally moved to the west, in the direction of
the cliff dwellings. But the wind has been so erratic, and the fire
so dangerous, that the crews have had a hard time getting in front
of the flames to try to halt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is that it's a very explosive fire, and it's at
the point where they can't do much in front,'' Dombrowski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire is so intense,'' he added, ``that it generates its
own weather, creates its own wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the hardship confronting the crews is the weather:
temperatures there have been in the 80s and 90s, and there is no
rain in the forecast.
</P>
<P>
   After a fire approached the Indian dwellings in 1996, park
workers removed overgrown brush around them. Dombrowski said the
hope now was that this preventive measure would slow the fire and
allow it to be contained.
</P>
<P>
   Park archaeologists learned after the fire in 1966 that there
had been some advantages to it: previously unknown archaeology
sites were uncovered when the pinyon and juniper bushes were burned
away.
</P>
<P>
   But at those sites ``they aren't discovering anything to the
extent'' of the cliff dwellings, Dombrowski said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
