<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-EXECS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGEMENT SHAKEUP AT IBM 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMONK, N.Y. _ In the seven years since he took over IBM, Louis
V. Gerstner Jr. has led a striking revival in the fortunes of the
world's largest computer company. Yet Gerstner, the chairman and
chief executive, has decided that what the company most needs now
to accelerate its growth and achieve its goal of being the leading
supplier of technology and services for the Internet economy, is a
good shakeup.
</P>
<P>
   So IBM Corp. announced a sweeping management overhaul Monday
that includes elevating Samuel J. Palmisano, a senior vice
president, to president and chief operating officer. The move seems
to make Palmisano, 48, the heir apparent to Gerstner. The
58-year-old Gerstner, who joined IBM in 1993, when the company was
reeling, has an employment contract that calls for him to remain in
charge ``at least until he turns 60 years of age,'' or until March
2002.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy interview here at the company headquarters,
Gerstner acknowledged that the announcement was certain to focus
attention on the issue of management succession at IBM. But he
noted that the elevation of Palmisano was just one of several
promotions of younger executives in the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new generation of leaders is starting to emerge at IBM,''
Gerstner said. ``And certainly Sam is part of that, but so are a
lot of other people here.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Gerstner noted, he has no intention of stepping back
anytime soon. ``I'm still here,'' he said. ``I'm not going
anywhere, and my job hasn't changed. And the board has not chosen
my successor as CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot you should read into this about me
leaving,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, IBM named John M. Thompson, another senior vice
president, to become vice chairman of IBM. Under the new setup,
Thompson will guide the company's efforts in promising new areas of
growth like wireless communication, network storage systems, life
sciences and Internet software. Yet Thompson is 57 and, given the
IBM tradition of having senior executives retire at about 60, seems
to be a less likely successor to Gerstner than Palmisano. Gerstner
praised Thompson as ``a rare talent,'' and a gifted manager of
technical workers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company promoted five other executives, all in
their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   While Thompson focuses on the future, Palmisano will be in
charge of daily operations in all the company's product and service
businesses. In an e-mail memo to IBM's senior management team
Monday, Gerstner wrote of Palmisano: ``Sam has consistently
demonstrated the aptitude perhaps most critical to leadership
success: He sets tough targets and then meets them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Gerstner said that the reorganization had less
to do with succession than with retooling the company's management
structure to execute its Internet strategy more effectively.
Indeed, the lingering question about the transformation at IBM
under Gerstner's leadership is whether, despite all the progress to
date, it is moving into the future quickly enough to offset the
decline in some of its traditional businesses, like mainframe
computers.
</P>
<P>
   In its second-quarter financial results, reported last week, IBM
beat the earnings estimates of Wall Street analysts, but its
revenues declined.
</P>
<P>
   For the IBM success story to be complete, it must deliver
growing sales. In a bulletin last week to the firm's clients,
Steven Milunovich, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., wrote that
the key to IBM's future as an investment was ``figuring out if IBM
is a new technology or an old technology stock. It's some of both
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gerstner's view, the table is set for growth at IBM, based on
its strategy of being a leading supplier to companies trying to
make the transition to e-commerce, which IBM calls ``e-business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Gerstner noted that revenues for its
e-business consulting grew 78 percent, that its specialized
microchips for cell phones and other wireless communications were
sold out and that it was straining to keep up with demand for the
big hub computers, called servers, that shuttle data from and to
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The company's e-business strategy, set in place over the last
few years, was working as planned, he said. ``The business is
exploding underneath us,'' he said. ``And we need to have a very,
very focused execution capability within the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerstner called Monday's announcement the ``third turn of the
wheel'' in terms of corporate strategy since he took over in 1993.
The first stage he characterized as the survival stage, and the
second involved putting the e-business strategy in place. The
third, he said, was the execution stage. Gerstner, once a partner
at McKinsey &AMP; Co., explained that one of the most important lessons
he learned from ``my McKinsey days'' was the crucial ``linkage
between structure and strategy, and that you really don't implement
an effective strategy without a structure that reinforces and
compliments that strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the shakeup, Gerstner says, was also influenced in part by
one of his more instinctive beliefs about corporate management. ``I
am a big believer in forcing change on large institutions just for
the sake of forcing change,'' Gerstner said. ``The longer an
organization stays intact, the less successful it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been absolutely convinced that you've got to blow things
up and start over again every few years, and that puts a whole new
face on people's jobs. It gets people focused externally rather
than internally.''
</P>
<P>
   The management organization, he explained, is intended to
``sharply delineate'' the two major tasks facing IBM: ``The
execution of today's e-business strategy, which will be led by Sam
Palmisano, and that development _ the rapid development _ of the
new e-business world that John Thompson will lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he joined IBM, Gerstner said that the company,
given its dire straits at the time, did not need a grand technology
``vision'' for its future, a comment that brought waves of
criticism and ridicule from industry analysts. He said he had been
widely misquoted, and that what he had tried to emphasize then was
that the company most needed to right itself before gazing toward
the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   But there seemed to be plenty of talk about vision at the top on
Monday. Gerstner spoke of Thompson's job as helping to guide IBM's
``billions upon billions of dollars'' of investment in
next-generation ``intelligent infrastructure'' for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's networked world is primitive compared to what it's
going to look like in three to five years,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
