<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICESTREAM-DEUTSCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICESTREAM'S ANTICIPATION OF GROWTH RIPE FOR DEUTSCHE TELEKOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also VOICESTREAM-DEUTSCH-REACT) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As much as anything in Deutsche Telekom's $50.7 billion offer
for the VoiceStream Wireless Corp., the German company is betting
on John Stanton's legacy of building a wireless company with
national reach.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton, VoiceStream's chairman, is a former protege of Craig
McCaw, the creator of the first nationwide cellular network, and
his effort to transform VoiceStream from a relatively small,
money-losing company into a national player will be a key factor in
Deutsche Telekom's effort to expand in the United States as new
wireless technologies come into play.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton's success in attracting a bid for his company that is
nearly five times more than what AT&AMP;T paid for McCaw Cellular
Communications in 1994 has largely been based on going against the
grain of wireless strategies championed by corporate giants like
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   By almost any measure, VoiceStream's short history is indicative
of the window of opportunity in the wireless industry for
executives who know how to leverage a company's strengths. In
VoiceStream's case, its strengths had to do with a prescient bet
made by Stanton on the importance of having enough space to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 30,000 people in the U.S. each day are getting a cell
phone,'' said Mark Lowenstein, head of the wireless practice at the
Yankee Group, a telecommunications research and consulting firm.
``Stanton's being rewarded for his opportunistic efforts to put the
right pieces into place before this type of growth began to
occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar to McCaw Cellular in the late 1980s and early 1990s,
when Stanton was the company's chief operating officer and vice
chairman, VoiceStream was cobbled together from a varied network of
properties that, in a way, resembled a vast jigsaw puzzle. Only in
VoiceStream's case, the growth was more mercurial.
</P>
<P>
   Until May of last year, the company did not even exist. That was
when Stanton spun off digital properties he had begun acquiring
since 1995 from Western Wireless, his other company, into
VoiceStream. Stanton had formed Western Wireless in 1994 in
Bellevue, Wash., his home city, by merging two other companies,
Pacific Northwest Cellular and General Cellular.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton then embarked on an acquisition spree, buying the
OmniPoint Corp. of Bethesda, Md., for $2 billion, and Aerial
Communications of Chicago, for $3 billion. After a few months,
VoiceStream nearly had the national reach to compete with companies
like Verizon, the largest wireless carrier in the United States,
and AT&AMP;T Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Although VoiceStream is only the nation's eighth-largest
wireless carrier, with about 2.4 million subscribers, it has
licenses to potentially provide service to about 70 percent of the
population. Some of this reach came through its two takeovers last
year, but a substantial part was generated by Stanton's acquisition
of licenses since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the foresight to bid in auctions other people
ignored,'' said Tom Alberg, a former executive at McCaw who worked
with Stanton and now heads the Madrona Investment Group in Seattle.
``He excelled at all the details involved in planning strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise when Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, the
world's largest telephone company, sought out VoiceStream with the
intent of acquiring a minority stake. The Japanese company would
have joined Hutchison Whampoa Ltd. of Hong Kong and Sonera of
Finland as minority partners in VoiceStream.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Deutsche Telekom, second only in size only to NTT
among the world's telephone companies, that succeeded in courting
VoiceStream, despite the fact that the company has yet to post a
profit. VoiceStream lost $203 million in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the allure of the company is its choice of technology.
Unlike most other United States wireless carriers, which use
standards like TDMA, or time division multiple access, and CDMA, or
code division multiple access, VoiceStream operates under a
standard called GSM, or global system for mobile communications.
</P>
<P>
   GSM is the predominant standard in Europe, where wireless
services provided by companies like Deutsche Telekom are more
widespread than they are in this country. So, although GSM operates
on a different frequency in the United States, Deutsche Telekom
will have an easier time integrating the company with its network
in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   While the ability to provide subscribers with the opportunity to
``roam,'' or travel from one region or continent to another with
the same cell phone, is undoubtedly important for the companies,
their future clearly lies with next-generation wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   As the wireless Internet becomes more common, companies are
scrambling to provide services beyond the bland applications now
available, like receiving a stock quote or a short text message.
Over the next year or two, faster, more visual applications are
expected to come to the market.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like VoiceStream need additional spectrum that provide
them with the bandwidth needed for such applications. Part of the
deal with Deutsche Telekom would provide it with $5 billion to bid
in coming spectrum auctions to be held by the Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream still has gaps in its network in places like
California and the Southeast, so resources from the Deutsche
Telekom deal could also allow it to buy other companies with
operations in those areas. Powertel Inc., which is based in West
Point, Ga., has been mentioned as one takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the jigsaw puzzle now on a broader basis,''
said Stanton, who would head Deutsche Telekom's mobile operations
in the United States, in a telephone interview. ``I think the goal
now is to be global and wireless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
