<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1696 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-LIMP-BIZKIT25-COX     07-24 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMP-BIZKIT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Die-hard Limp Bizkit fans toe the line for free concert
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Morning commuters to downtown got a surprise Monday:
Thousands of suburban teens and twenty-somethings snaked around
nearly four city blocks, in chairs, on blankets or just sitting on
the sidewalks. Each wanted to be in the crowd Monday night for Limp
Bizkit's just-announced free concert at the 2,500-capacity
Tabernacle.
</P>
<P>
   Free?
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Napster, the online music-file-sharing software
company, the entire tour _ which started July in Detroit and ends
Aug. 14 _ is free. Part payback to its most faithful users and
reward to its most vocal spokesmen, the event is being paid for
primarily by Napster (to the tune of a reported $1.8 million) and
the Firm (Limp Bizkit's management). It's also perfectly timed to
build the buzz for the rapcore quartet's scheduled fall release,
``Chocolate Starfish and the Hot Dog Flavored Water.''
</P>
<P>
   When the band's frontman, Fred Durst, announced the tour on MTV,
he offered one rationale behind the convergence of Napster and Limp
Bizkit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could care less about the older generation's need to do
business as usual,'' Durst stated. ``We care more about what our
fans want, and our fans want music on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how it's been working: The tour's venues are announced
24 to 48 hours in advance on Napster's Web site and a local radio
station (in Atlanta, it was modern rock station 99X). Wristbands
are given away the day of the show _ one per customer. Atlanta fans
got the word Thursday and started queueing Saturday afternoon. By
Monday morning, the line snaked from the Tabernacle on Luckie
Street, down Spring and back to Cenntennial Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   Servicemen Chris Stiles, 22, and Victor Morales, 21, took time
off from the Naval Air Station in Smyrna to be first in line. They
arrived about 4 p.m. Saturday and waited while two other shows _
Kottonmouth Kings on Saturday and the Spitkicker Tour on Sunday _
came and went. ``We've been living on Vienna sausage and Beenie
Weenies,'' said Stiles on Monday morning, ``and going to the
bathroom anywhere we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Campers brought coolers, blankets, towels, folding chairs,
pillows and even a removable car seat. Tim Evans and Tracy
Nicholson of Smyrna got to the Tabernacle at 5 a.m. Sunday, set up
camp near the front of the line and survived a Sunday afternoon
downpour. ``We had a tent,'' Nicholson said, ``but we took it down
because it was drenched.''
</P>
<P>
   A big fan of the band's rap-rock hybrid _ the couple have seen
the band twice _ Nicholson was nevertheless a minority. There were
women in line, but they were far outnumbered by young men, Limp
Bizkit's core audience. (At Woodstock '99, thousands of Bizkitheads
turned the band's rendition of their anarchic anthem ``Break
Stuff'' into a melee.)
</P>
<P>
   In the hour before the wristbands were handed out, some in the
crowd were getting a little bit rambunctious _ but closer to the
front, folks were mostly looking haggard. ``I tried to sleep,''
said Corey White, 17, of Dunwoody. ``But this place is like a trash
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right about the mess. When the gaps in the line closed
up, the streets looked like a tornado had torn through a garbage
dump. City cleanup crews had the streets back to normal by noon.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans would find that their experience wouldn't be as free
as they thought. Wreckers were lining up, towing away illegally
parked vehicles, as the crowd vainly chanted, ``Give it back!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B: More about Limp
</P>
<P>
   Bizkit and Napster:
</P>
<P>
   www.limpbizkit.com and www.napster.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
