<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NORTEL-BAYSTATE-BOS &LR;      07-24 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-BAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL PLANS TWO MAJOR PLANTS IN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world leader in the red-hot optical networking market is
investing $1.9 billion to stay out in front of rivals, and a large
part of that investment will be spent in the Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Nortel Networks Corp. said Monday it will build two
major facilities in Wilmington and Billerica and hire about 1,800
workers to staff them. The plants are part of a massive worldwide
expansion by Nortel, aimed at locking down its lead in the market
for systems that use pulses of light to transmit information much
faster than traditional copper wires.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion will build upon recent Nortel investments in
Massachusetts. Nortel picked up its Billerica site as part of its
1998 acquisition of Bay Networks Inc. for $7.2 billion in stock.
And just last month, the company paid out $1.43 billion in stock to
acquire CoreTek Inc. of Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Chahram Bolouri, president of global operations for Nortel, said
that the company will build a 100,000-square-foot addition at the
CoreTek plant, which will employ 775 people. CoreTek manufactures
tunable lasers that are capable of sending multiple frequencies
along the same fiber. In addition, it will build a new ``optical
system house'' in Billerica to put together entire systems that
will employ 1,050 people.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, Nortel presently employs about 2,500 people in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   When the 18-month expansion is complete, Nortel expects to have
doubled its production of optical networking systems. ``We are
fueling much of the demand for optical components and have been an
industry leader in this market for some time, so it makes sense for
us to aggressively pursue growth opportunities,'' said Nortel CEO
John Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Those opportunities have grown in tandem with the rapid increase
in Internet use. ``Electrical systems don't have the capacity to
handle the kind of traffic the Internet has created,'' said Thomas
Valovic, who studies the optical networking market for
International Data Corp. ``All of the big pipes need to get
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nortel equipment achieves this through a technology called
dense wavelength division multiplexing, or DWDM. With this process,
a pair of optical fibers, each the width of a human hair, can
transmit 10 billion bits of data every second.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies offer similar technologies, but Nortel has
managed to secure a dominant position in the marketplace. According
to the investment firm of Robertson Stephens, the market for
optical networking equipment will grow to $23.6 billion this year,
and Nortel is expected to garner about 46 percent of this market.
The company's nearest rival, New Jersey-based Lucent Technologies
Inc., will hold just a quarter of the market.
</P>
<P>
   News of the Nortel expansion campaign came as the Wall Street
Journal reported that the company is in talks to combine its
optical networking product line with that of Corning Inc. The
combination could be worth more than $100 billion, the newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cited concerns that Corning shareholders emerge with
just a minority stake in the new firm, and said that could be a
major obstacle to a deal. ``I would evaluate the probability of
such a transaction occurring at less than 50-50,'' analyst Lawrence
Harris of Josephthal &AMP; Co. said.
</P>
<P>
   Some expect a merger between Corning and Nortel might be driven
by other consolidation in the industry. Earlier this month, for
instance, optical-components maker JDS Uniphase Corp. said it would
pay $41 billion for another Silicon Valley company, SDL Inc.
Corning lately has emphasized the production of fiber-optic cables
using thousands of strands of glass. Wall Street has been
enthusiastic about the shift, driving up Corning's shares sharply
since last year to give it a market capitalization of nearly $70
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Using that currency, Corning has spent more than $5 billion,
mostly in stock, to buy Massachusetts fiber firms. Since last year
it has taken control of Oak Industries in Waltham, NetOptix of
Natick, and NZ Applied Technologies of Woburn.
</P>
<P>
   It also plans to expand manufacturing capacity at its Bedford,
Mass.-based Lasertron unit to create 1,150 more jobs, though
Corning hasn't determined where those positions will be located.
</P>
<P>
   But Corning competitors like Lucent and Italy's Pirelli still
make more of the high-margin equipment used to transmit data
signals across fiber lines; some analysts see the gap as an
appropriate opportunity for a deal between Corning and Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's much more value if either of these companies can
deliver these optical products as an end-to-end business
solution,'' said Sanjay Mewada, director of Yankee Group Inc.'s
telecom e-business practice. Depending on its final structure, he
said, for Nortel a deal could ``fill out the gaps in its
portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York Stock Exchange trading Monday, Nortel shares fell
81.25 cents to close at $80. The shares have more than tripled in
the past year. Corning shares tumbled $34.75 to close at $249.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
