<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-BRAVES-HOMERS0725     07-24 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-HOMERS0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Twenty-seven years ago, offense was in such decline
that the American League stooped to instituting the designated
hitter. But here in Atlanta, the Braves put on a three-man
pyrotechnic demonstration that endured almost the rest of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson, who never before or after the 1973 season even
reached 20 homers, Hank Aaron, who broke Babe Ruth's record early
the next year, and Darrell Evans all reached 40 home runs that
season.
</P>
<P>
   Their mark, equaled in Colorado in 1996 and 1997, is being
threatened by several teams this year, and surprisingly, the Braves
are one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a chance,'' objected Andruw Jones, the Braves
home-run leader with 25. ``Now, Toronto, they have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As does Anaheim. But the Blue Jays have an opportunity to become
the first club with four players with 40. Toronto is destined to
put up the best four-man totals in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying back in spring training that we got five guys in
the lineup that can hit over 30,'' said Galarraga, part of both
Colorado clubs that matched the Braves' mark. ``Guys can do it
anytime. They can go on line drives, solo shots, opposite field.
It's more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973, only five Atlanta players have reached the 40-homer
mark _ Chipper Jones, 45 in 1999; Dale Murphy, 44 in 1987;
Galarraga, 44 in 1998; Jeff Burroughs, 41 in 1977; and David
Justice, 40 in 1993. ``We have the ability to manufacture runs,''
Chipper Jones said. But I think the three guys we have up in the
20s right now, they're more concerned with picking up runners in
scoring position, regardless of how they do it, whether it be a
homer or a bloop single.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, if you had two guys hit 40 in the whole league,
that was a big deal,'' said Braves coach Glenn Hubbard. ``That was
just one of those seasons. The other guys were going to hit theirs,
but (Johnson) didn't miss one of his pitches. He hit every ball
you're supposed to hit.'' ``I don't think anybody on this team has
a goal that they want to hit 40 home runs,'' Andruw Jones said.
``Whatever home runs we hit, when the season's done, that's what we
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
