<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1702 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-STODA0725-COX     07-24 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-STODA0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods continues to amaze, with endless possibilities in sight
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Too often in the wake of one or the
other of his fabulous shows, it seems the Tale of Tiger Woods is
written against the backdrop of history or the vagaries of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   How strange.
</P>
<P>
   That he is, after Sunday's stunning British Open victory at St.
Andrews, in possession of all four of golf's major championships is
amazing. That as a 24-year-old he is the youngest holder of the
career Grand Slam _ victories in the Masters, U.S. Open, British
Open and PGA Championship _ is remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   And comparison of Woods' record at this stage of his life to
Jack Nicklaus' records at the same stage of his is fun. So is
extrapolating what Woods has done in his sport's headline events
and measuring the possibilities opposite the pace Nicklaus set on
the way to winning a monumental 18 professional major titles.
</P>
<P>
   What gets lost in all of that is what's happening right now. Not
so much what's happening to Woods, but to the poor souls trying to
compete against him in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Woods stands with Gene Sarazen, Ben Hogan, Gary Player and
Nicklaus as the only men to win golf's four most important
tournaments? Wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Woods could demolish the standard of excellence established by
Nicklaus? Again, wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   But how about an examination of Woods vs. his peers?
</P>
<P>
   Woods has won each of the majors once, and is currently holding
the title in all of them except the Masters. How dominant is he?
There are by my count only four players 35 or younger who have won
more than one major _ Lee Janzen, John Daly, Jose Maria Olazabal
and Ernie Els.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen turns 36 next month, and Daly and Olazabal are both 34.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen's two majors have both come in the U.S. Open. The same is
true for the 30-year-old Els. Olazabal's two majors have both come
in the Masters. That leaves Daly (PGA Championship, British Open)
as the only player under 35 with major titles in different
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   More startling still is the fact that 28-year-old Justin
Leonard, with a single British Open title, is the only player under
30 other than Woods to win even one major.
</P>
<P>
   The players generally regarded as the three best who haven't won
a major championship _ 28-year-old David Duval, 30-year-old Phil
Mickelson and 37-year-old Colin Montgomerie _ must realize by now
how drastically Woods' presence reduces their chances of ever
getting one.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus frequently has made the point that Woods' greatest
challenger might well turn out to be someone yet to make any mark
on professional golf. He should know. Nicklaus is the only player
to have won each of the four majors more than once (he has a career
Grand Slam triple), and was 26 when he completed the first series
with a victory in the 1966 British Open.
</P>
<P>
   The two players who subsequently became the greatest threats to
Nicklaus' reign were Johnny Miller and Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   In that summer of 1966, Miller and Watson were teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither ever conquered Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to imagine anyone doing it to Woods, either.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
