<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-BAXTER0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Circumstances in '92 Senate election have similarities to today
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Before taking off full-wing into the race to succeed
him, it's worth recalling the unusual circumstances under which
Paul Coverdell got to the Senate in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He'd been weakened, seemingly, by a bitter primary battle with
Bob Barr, and came up about 35,000 behind incumbent Democrat Wyche
Fowler on the same day Georgia voted, by a narrower margin, for
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In another state, that would have been the end of the story, but
the presence of three other candidates in the race meant Fowler was
forced into a runoff with Coverdell, right before Thanksgiving,
when the Democrats were shopping for turkey and the Republicans
were just getting their mad on about the new administration.
Coverdell won a low-turnout race by 17,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are in another presidential year, with a non-partisan
primary to succeed the late Republican senator.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a regular Senate race, the winner would need to get
only 45 percent, because the rules were changed after the Coverdell
upset.
</P>
<P>
   But non-partisan primaries still require a runoff if no one gets
a majority.
</P>
<P>
   This makes the political task ahead for Zell Miller pretty
clear.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has everything going for him in this race: Gov. Roy
Barnes' blessing, speedy access to campaign money, a potentially
divided Republican field, perhaps the most recognizable political
name in the state.
</P>
<P>
   He is the one Democrat who might figure to win an outright
victory on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   He had better do that, or he will have to come back and win a
runoff on the Tuesday after Thanksgiving, when there will be no
Democratic get-out-the-vote effort on the scale of the presidential
election. And when whichever Republican is left standing will be
shouting, ``Remember '92.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have a mechanism, through Barnes's appointment,
for arriving at a nominee in this race which is nonpartisan in name
only. The Republican do not, and there is high anxiety over the
ripple effect if more than one GOP House member decides to get in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   The upside to Miller's appointment, said state Republican
chairman Chuck Clay, is that his presence may cause the Republicans
to gel more quickly around a single candidate _ something he
devoutly wishes will come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Unifying behind a single Republican is ``the only way we will
hold on to that seat. No ifs, ands or buts,'' Clay said.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP isn't going to get national financial help if it can't
focus on one candidate, Clay said. On the other hand, the greater
the number of Republicans on the Nov. 7 ballot, the harder it could
be for Miller to capture a majority.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Republicans defy expectations and field just one
candidate, we have not yet heard from the Greens, the Reforms or
the Libertarians. Or from some maverick Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger the field, the larger Miller is going to look
standing in it. But any combination that denies the former governor
an outright majority raises the dread specter of a
post-Thanksgiving rematch - which is how we got here to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Political editor Tom Baxter provides opinion, analysis and
commentary for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
