<HEADLINE>
GORE URGES UNITY AMONG UNIONS AND ENVIRONMENTALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ohio, Ill.)   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. _ With three weeks left before the
Democratic National Convention, Vice President Al Gore turned his
focus Monday to uniting two important Democratic groups that have
at time been at odds: environmentalists and labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   At an event on the tree-lined banks of the Grand River, Gore
picked up the endorsement of the Sierra Club, one of the most
politically potent environmental groups in the country. But the
audience was filled with union workers, and Gore devoted much of
his speech to assuring them that strong environmental policies
would not necessarily hurt companies and their workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here today to tell America that as we move toward a
cleaner, safer healthier environment, we are going to create more
jobs, not fewer jobs for American families,'' Gore told the crowd
of nearly 200 people. ``A stronger economy and better environment
go together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is trying to win the endorsement of the United Auto
Workers, a political powerhouse in this closely contested state.
The group's leaders have been angry with the vice president over
his strong support for global trade. And some union leaders also
worry that administration policies intended to reduce air pollution
and slow global warming could drive up the cost of cars and hurt
the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, Gore has had several conversations with
Stephen Yokich, the UAW president, to try to work out their
differences, Democratic officials said. Gore's aides are hoping
that the union's executive committee will vote to endorse him at
its next meeting, on Aug. 8, six days before the Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, Gore also took a poke at Gov. George W. Bush,
his Republican opponent, for attracting intense media attention to
his efforts to choose a running mate. Gore suggested that the Texas
governor had played out his deliberations in public to build
excitement about his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've handled my process differently than the Bush campaign has
handled theirs,'' Gore told reporters. ``I've kept it private and,
I hope, dignified out of respect for the individuals, the men and
women, who are under consideration. And I am going to continue to
approach it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   But just minutes before, in what seemed like a clear attempt to
stoke interest in Gore's own deliberations, the vice president's
aides notified reporters that he would be meeting on Tuesday
morning with Warren Christopher, who is helping Gore cull his list
of potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what qualities he was looking for in a running mate, Gore
replied, ``I'm going to pick the person who I believe can become
the president on a moment's notice, if necessary. Who also has a
good working relationship with me, or the prospect of one. And who
shares my values, someone who's willing to fight for people and not
the powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was still considering announcing his pick
immediately after Bush unveiled his, but added that he was more
likely to reveal his choice several days before the Democratic
convention, which begins on Aug. 14. He added that his list was
``short,'' but he would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   After his Sierra Club event Monday, Gore flew to Ohio, where he
campaigned at a construction site and then met with steelworkers
and the head of the state's police union in Cleveland. On Tuesday,
he will give a speech in Washington hailing the Americans With
Disabilities Act. And on Wednesday, he flies to Chicago to address
the Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Robert Cox, the president of the Sierra Club, picked
up on a theme Gore has been sounding recently, arguing that Bush's
record as governor of Texas proved that he would support federal
policies that would help corporate polluters and ruin the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fail to elect Al Gore, if George Bush becomes president,
we could face a very different America,'' Cox said. ``We could face
what the people of Texas face now. Air pollution, water pollution,
toxic waste, record numbers of violations of our clean air and
clean water standards. Environmental laws unenforced and corporate
polluters unchecked and out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks at the Sierra Club event, Gore said he had been
ahead of his time in understanding environmental problems, having
learned about the dangers of pesticides and soil erosion as a boy
on his father's farm in Tennessee and about global warming as a
college student.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Gore said, ``If you believed in global warming,
people thought you were part of the flat earth society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
