<SLUG> BC-BBO-NY-TICKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GRAND JURY INDICTS 16 IN BASEBALL TICKET-SELLING SCAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They may not patrol the outfield like Bernie
Williams, or strike out batters like Mariano Rivera. But the ticket
agents at Yankee Stadium have some raw power of their own: Their
kiosks are the first stop for fans who want to see their World
Series winners in action.
</P>
<P>
   And as the Yankees have prospered in recent years as the
dominant team in baseball, so, too, have some of the ticket agents,
according to prosecutors, who say agents capitalized on the huge
demand for tickets to divert some to scalpers in return for bribes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, at some of the most popular games _ including
opening day and Old-Timers' Day _ the agents at the kiosks told
fans the games were sold out. But while some fans went home
disappointed, others were able to buy tickets at four times the
regular price from scalpers who hustled them nearby or in the
stadium parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the scheme, the ticket agents went home richer,
Manhattan and state prosecutors said Monday, one driving an
eight-cylinder BMW, another sinking money into a Hamptons beach
house, though they only earned about $30,000 a year in their
regular job.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that seven ticket agents employed by the
Yankees, and one who worked for the Mets, were involved in the
scheme, in which they diverted blocks of tickets to unscrupulous
scalpers. In some cases, $35 playoffs tickets were scalped for
$140, while $150 World Series tickets were scalped for $1,000,
according to investigators, some of whom posed as brokers and
bought the tickets from agents involved in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly the unholy, illegal alliance between box-office
workers and unlicensed brokers which conspires to shut out the real
fans from being able to get a ticket to a playoff game,'' said
Eliot L. Spitzer, the state attorney general, whose office worked
with the Manhattan district attorney on its investigation. ``It
doesn't matter how long fans wait on line or how many times they
call. Thanks to bribery at the box office, the tickets are gone
even before they go on sale.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, 16 people have been indicted in the scheme, 10 of whom
were arrested at Yankee Stadium on Sunday before and during the
home game, investigators said Monday. Among the tickets agents
arrested were the president and a senior officer of Local F-72 of
the ticket agents' union. There is no evidence the union itself was
involved in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees and Mets officials, who said the teams were cooperating
fully with the investigation, referred questions Monday to the
Manhattan district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' chief operating officer, Lonn Trost, added that the
team had appointed a new acting ticket supervisor and planned to
overhaul its system of ticket sales. ``We will be working
internally, with professionals and with Ticketmaster, to make sure
that fans are adequately protected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the loosely organized scalping ring, which prosecutors
say operated for more than five years, ticket agents sold thousands
of tickets to unlicensed brokers in blocks under false group names.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that the scheme's ringleader, Stephen Mootoo,
41, bribed one Yankees ticket agent to sell him blocks of season
and partial-season tickets, which then guaranteed him a large
number of seats to scalp at the most popular games, including those
against traditional rivals like the Boston Red Sox and the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Mootoo, who lives in Manhattan, bought a total of $300,000 in
tickets, charging them to the credit cards of his girlfriend and
others, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a ticket agent sold 300 season tickets under the
name of Linden's Cookies Inc., a company in Congers, N.Y., that
bought no tickets and employs only 30 people. ``We could bring all
of our families and we wouldn't need that many,'' said John Kramer,
the company's sales manager. ``I guess these guys weren't as smart
as they thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the ticket brokers, known by the group as the ``Three
Amigos,'' worked out a deal with ticket brokers that allowed them
to return any tickets they couldn't scalp. As a result, tickets for
some games that were supposedly sold out ``magically'' appeared,
said one person who was briefed by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Monday about the difference between a reputable
ticket broker and an unlicensed one, Daniel Castleman, chief of
investigations for the Manhattan district attorney said, ``Most
reputable brokers work out of their office and not their station
wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that the investigation resulted from complaints
by a fan, who before a game bought a ticket from a scalper who was
selling them near one of the kiosks at Yankees stadium. After the
game, the fan returned to the advance ticket window to buy tickets
for subsequent games, and found that the ticket agent behind the
window, James Hirsch, was the same scalper who had sold him a
ticket just hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The fan testified before a grand jury and made the jurors ``so
angry'' about the scalping, recalled the person who was briefed by
investigators. ``He told stories about how obnoxious Hirsch was,
how he berated people at the window who wanted tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Though his lawyer could not be reached for comment, Hirsch
pleaded not guilty Monday and his bail was set at $25,000,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors characterized the tickets agents as young and
brazen, in some cases cold-calling brokers to offer their services
in diverting tickets for a price. They said that some pulled in
``tens of thousands'' in profits through the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Handwerker, a lawyer representing one of the ticket
agents, called the prosecutors' allegations ``overblown'' and said
that the investigation was actually started two years ago by
Yankees' officials, who hired private detectives to examine
allegations of fraudulent ticket sales by one ticket agent in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Why why did the Manhattan district attorney, Robert M.
Morgenthau, handle a case involving Yankee Stadium, which is in the
Bronx? Morgenthau said Monday that the home plate at the Bronx
stadium fell within his jurisdiction, because it is less than 500
yards from the water mark that divides the Bronx from Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
