<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-CONVENTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONVENTION PLANNED AS A MINI-SERIES, BUT WILL VIEWERS TUNE
IN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related CONVENTIONS-MARKETING, which will move in `f' business
file) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT2 and NYT6 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Reinventing or in some cases abandoning the
rituals of party gatherings past, the Republican National
Convention that begins on Monday will more than ever amount to a
lavish multimedia spectacle that pushes controversy to the
sidelines in favor of an unabashed celebration of the goals and
vision of the party standard-bearer, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Those expecting angry debate on issues like abortion, gun
control and school prayer will be sorely disappointed. In its
place, the convention will beam ``compassion videos'' onto three
high-tech screens hanging over the stage in the First Union Center
here. They will document the healing power of social programs in
places like Cleveland and El Paso, Texas, that were developed with
little or no government support.
</P>
<P>
   Missing, too, from the rostrum will be the usual parade of
elected officials introducing other elected officials for the kinds
of lengthy speeches that act as television-audience repellent. A
few politicians will still have oratorical roles, and it will still
be the remarks by Republican stars like former Gen. Colin L. Powell
and Sen. John McCain of Arizona that are likely to dominate the
window of network news coverage that on most nights will open at
about 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But most other speeches will be five minutes or less and mere
embroidery for each evening's elaborate ``story line'' modeled on
Bush's proposals for education, defense and Social Security and
featuring ordinary Americans talking about their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Officials even say the Republican whipping boy, President
Clinton, may rarely be invoked. ``This convention really is about
George Bush,'' said Andy Card, general co-chairman and chief
conceptualizer of the $63 million event. ``Other conventions were
more about the party and less about the candidate. This on every
single night is about Governor Bush. It's about what he stands for.
It's about people who symbolize what he stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   If political conventions long ago stopped picking nominees and
started selling them, the Republicans are intent this summer on
refining the tone of the sales pitch and imposing an unparalleled
degree of message discipline on the proceedings. They are able to
attempt this thanks to an extraordinary level of solidarity this
year. The Republican base is so firmly in Bush's corner, organizers
say, that they have less worries than the Democrats about
reassuring party regulars.
</P>
<P>
   That has freed them to tailor their appeal during the four-day
convention more directly to Democrats and independents. Though Card
says that some speakers will pointedly contrast Republican and
Democratic policies, the accent will remain on the positive. Even
the convention's slightly abstract theme _ ``Renewing America's
Purpose. Together.'' _ has the ring of gentle, communal
housecleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense that one thing was to make this not about
the party, but about the issues the party stands for,'' said
Russell Schriefer, a Bush media consultant who produced the videos
for the convention. ``To make it broader, and more inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   The unanswered question in this serving up of politics on a
satin pillow is whether anyone beside the delegates, the news media
and Bush's extended family will pay much attention. Lacking any
``story line'' with inherent conflict, the Republican proceedings
are in danger of being dismissed as irrelevant by much of the
public. In a recent poll by Harvard's Vanishing Voter project, 43
percent of respondents said they would not tune into the political
extravaganza here, while 38 percent said they would not watch the
one staged by Democrats in Los Angeles next month.
</P>
<P>
   In unorthodox ways, the organizers, aware of the public's waning
enthusiasm, are trying to turn the four-day convention into better
television. It is a strategy that Card, an ebullient Massachusetts
Republican who served as transportation secretary under Bush's
father, himself calls ``high risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great challenges,'' Card said, ``is to get people
to pay attention to the convention who were turned off by past
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The language of television seeps into almost every conversation
about what will transpire in the First Union Center, where workers
are affixing the stars-and-stripes motif to the stage and finishing
the installation of 330 speakers, 650 lights and 6,600 miles of
fiber-optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view this as a mini-series that has to be told over four
nights,'' Card said, referring to the themes that will roll out in
nightly installments, like ``Strength and Security with a
Purpose,'' on the second night, which also happens to coincide with
the 10th anniversary of Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, the impetus for
Operation Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the evening will include a remote transmission from the
deck of the USS New Jersey, anchored on the New Jersey side of the
Delaware River, where former Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf will talk
by satellite to the conventioneers. The episode has an added
potential advantage of reminding voters of the high-water mark of
the senior Bush's term in the White House. The second night will
also play off the notion of America's strength in other areas, like
trade policy.
</P>
<P>
   Card said the nightly themes were enlargements of signature
issues for Bush, as derived from his stump speeches. Monday's theme
is ``Opportunity with a Purpose: Leave No Child Behind''; on
Wednesday, ``Prosperity with a Purpose''; and Thursday, when he
delivers his acceptance speech, ``President with a Purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of doing `bio' just on one night, we're doing `bio'
throughout,'' is how Schriefer put it.
</P>
<P>
   The look of the convention hall itself, a four-year-old sports
arena, will give the proceedings more of a variety show feel. The
old-fashioned dais has been banished, replaced by a wide stage with
a podium that retracts into the floor. More speakers will be
announced by an offstage voice, and musical interludes will occur
more frequently. ``We're trying to be a little bit more
entertaining, a little faster-moving,'' said David J. Nash, the
convention's executive producer and once the producer of Radio City
Music Hall's Easter and Christmas productions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will be the program's roving eminence, broadcast into the
hall each night by satellite from somewhere on the campaign trail.
His speech _ alone now on Thursday night, the vice presidential
nominee's having been moved this year to Wednesday night _ will be
the de facto keynote address, as Card and the other organizers
opted not to designate one. Thus far, McCain is the only one of
Bush's opponents from the primaries who has been invited to give a
prominent address.
</P>
<P>
   To a minority of viewers, who watch the proceedings unfiltered
on, say, C-Span, which is supplying the pool coverage, or on one of
the cable networks that will often be concentrating on the stage,
the gist of the Republican story might be apparent. Everyone else
may have a hard time following the script, and those in charge of
creating it say the problem is unavoidable. In fact, the odd
reality of the conventions is that the harder the parties work to
woo network coverage the less the old line networks are apt to put
them on the air.
</P>
<P>
   And that, the organizers say, has compelled them to become even
wilier about the electronic tricks of television _ the satellite
feeds and the narratives on video, for example _ to sell their
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Academy Awards,'' Schriefer said. ``You go to
the clips.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
