<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CENSORS BEWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., double parens in next-to-last graf should be set as
brackets) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ I witnessed a wild debate in Jordan the other
day.
</P>
<P>
   It went like this: A Syrian recently tried to hijack a Jordanian
jetliner flying to Damascus. A security guard shot the hijacker,
who almost set off a grenade. The public was outraged at the
security lapse, and none other than Prince Ali bin Hussein, the
brother and security chief of King Abdullah, was called on the
carpet by Jordanians who wanted to know how this lapse could have
happened, with some even calling the king's brother by his first
name, Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Where was this debate? It wasn't in the Jordanian Parliament or
media. It all happened online on Jordan's biggest Internet portal,
Nets.com.jo, where Jordanians, using their real names, raked Prince
Ali over the coals over the Web, and Ali came online to personally
defend ``against all those who trash our Armed Forces and Security
Services.''
</P>
<P>
   Message: While all eyes are on the Arab-Israeli peace process,
there is a whole other process _ democratization _ percolating in
the Arab world, in which the Internet and globalization are acting
like nutcrackers to open societies and empower Arab democrats with
new tools. But don't kid yourself, anti-democratic countertrends
are also flourishing, and there's no telling who will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   But at least now there's a lively battle. Check out the Web site
of The Cairo Times, a feisty new English-language Egyptian paper
published out of Cyprus. The Egyptian government censors The Cairo
Times when it comes into Egypt. And what do the editors of The
Cairo Times do? They now print in bright red letters on their Web
site (cairotimes.com) everything the government takes out, in a
section entitled: ``The Forbidden File _ See what the censor has
cut from our print edition. ... These articles were chopped apart.
. . .'' You can then call up the original of, say, ``A Sweetheart
Economy? Just How Bad Is Corruption in Egypt?'' and see just what
the censor didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's new young King Abdullah, who understands globalization
better than any Arab leader today, recently decided to privatize
the Jordanian press because he felt his kingdom could never
modernize without newspapers with real news. While Arab Internet
sites are still confined to the elites, in most Arab countries
today 70 percent of the populations are under age 30, and they are
getting wired remarkably fast.
</P>
<P>
   But Arab democrats have their work cut out for them. In a
shameful move three weeks ago, Egypt arrested an American
University of Cairo democratization specialist, Saad Eddin Ibrahim,
on some nonsensical charges. Even worse, several Jordanian
commentators wrote editorials supporting Ibrahim's arrest _ because
he was funded by the European Union in his election monitoring and
because he had supported normalization with Israel. Some Arab
pundits still hate Israel and the West more than they love
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news was that Rami Khouri, a courageous Jordanian
columnist and democrat, wrote that for Egypt's regime _ which lives
off U.S. aid _ to be arresting an Egyptian intellectual for
receiving foreign funding for election monitoring was the height of
hypocrisy. Khouri denounced the ``Arab states' moral drift,
self-serving judicial thuggery and political heavy-handedness'' and
denounced his colleagues who supported the Ibrahim arrest as
``confused and insecure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank, Palestinian democrats are now resisting Yasser
Arafat. Palestinian journalists have started a Web site, Amin.org,
to publish all the articles censored by local editors or Arafat
goons. As the Palestinian intellectual Khalil Shikaki put it: With
Yasser Arafat ``we have a one-man ruler, who won't share power or
recognize civil society. ((His attitude is)) `I will give you a
state and you run it as you like. When I die, take my thumb and
sign whatever you want, but until then let me get a state.' So we
need a state to end the legacy of the PLO _ its legacy is
authoritarianism, secrecy, security courts and lack of
accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th century, the Arab states thrived by developing oil.
In the 21st century they will thrive only if they develop their
people, and the only way to do that is by democratizing. The battle
is on, and thanks to the Internet and globalization the Arab
democrats finally have some artillery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
