<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSCOW-EXECUTIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDITORS CLEAR RUSSIAN EXECUTIVE OF EMBEZZLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Boris Berezovsky, the top Russian executive and
one-time insider, who has denounced a Kremlin crackdown on rich
businessmen, received a measure of vindication Monday when
international auditors exonerated one of his companies in a
long-running investigation into embezzlement and money-laundering.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities here intend to press ahead with the
investigation anyway, one of several that reflect an intensified
scrutiny under President Vladimir Putin of the wealthy oligarchs
that control much of the business in post-Soviet Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which has been pursued by officials in Switzerland as
well as Russia, centers on whether companies including the
Swiss-based Forus Services embezzled at least $200 million from the
Russian airline Aeroflot. Forus, a company Berezovsky helped found,
hired PricewaterhouseCoopers to examine its transactions with
Aeroflot.
</P>
<P>
   The auditor said Monday it had found no evidence that funds were
illegally funneled to the Swiss company.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of former President Boris Yeltsin, Berezovsky wielded
tremendous influence in the Kremlin and boasted that he controlled
decisions at high levels. But since Putin succeeded Yeltsin at the
turn of the year, Berezovsky has been pushed out of
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Berezovsky resigned from Parliament, forfeiting the
immunity from prosecution the post provided. The step was
interpreted as a final break with the new Russian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has brought some of the country's richest men under
scrutiny, part of his campaign promise to loosen the grip of big
business on government policy. He is scheduled to meet with a group
of top Russian businessmen on Friday. Berezovsky is not on the list
of those invited, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   A special investigator, Nikolai Volkov, will travel to
Switzerland on Wednesday to obtain documents on the case from Swiss
authorities, Reuters reported. Last year, Swiss prosecutors raided
the offices and froze bank accounts of Forus and another company
linked to Berezovsky, Andava SA, which have provided Aeroflot with
cash management, loans and other financial services.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Swiss high court rejected a request by
Berezovsky's lawyers to unfreeze the companies' bank accounts,
Reuters said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian prosecutor's office has been investigating the case
for more than a year. A criminal case against Berezovsky was opened
under former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who sought to reduce
the businessman's influence in government. The case was later
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky has vast business holdings, though their size remains
sketchy. Companies he controls own stakes in the Russian television
channel ORT. He is also linked to the Sibneft oil company and owns
a car dealership, Logovaz.
</P>
</TEXT>
