<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1713 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH-CHENEY0725-COX     07-24 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheney has a wealth of experience inside the Beltway
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Dick Cheney, at 59, is only five years older
than Texas Gov. George W. Bush. But the former defense secretary
for Bush's father would bring a quarter of a century of Washington
D.C. experience with a wunderkind resume: congressional aide, Nixon
staffer, chief of staff for President Ford at 34, and a
congressional career with the credentials to reassure the GOP's
right wing.
</P>
<P>
   But like his prospective boss, Cheney would bring a genial
personality that makes his conservatism more palatable in the halls
of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney is absolutely first class,'' said former U.S. Rep.
Charles Wilson, D-Lufkin, who served on the House Intelligence
committee with Cheney in the 1980s. ``If you went through Congress,
you'd find it hard to find someone who doesn't like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Rep. John Bryant, one of Congress' most liberal
members, is less charitable. ``The impression I got, he was a very
intense guy who internalized a lot of anger at the Democrats.''
Bryant sizes up Cheney: ``He's as conservative as any one in the
(Republican) party, but he wasn't a screamer like the (Newt)
Gingrich crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Congress from Wyoming from 1979 until 1989,
Cheney opposed the Equal Rights Amendment and abortion rights while
supporting a balanced budget amendment and prayer in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you view his voting record, it's rock-ribbed
conservative,'' said U.S. Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who has known
Cheney since they started out 30 years ago in President Nixon's
Office of Economic Opportunity, the remnants of Lyndon Johnson's
War on Poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very conservative,'' Leach said. ``But he believes you've
got to make government work. He's not mean-spirted about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Rothenberg, a political consultant, agrees:
``Stylistically, he's moderate.'' That could fit with Bush's claim
of working well with Texas Democrats _ a bipartisanship he has said
he'd like to take to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Among Washingtonians, Cheney is also considered an intellectual.
He finished all his requirements for a doctoral degree in political
science at the University of Wisconsin except his dissertation.
With his wife, Lynne, he co-wrote a book about U.S. House Speakers,
``Kings of the Hill.'' He is known as a quick study.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the smartest guy I ever worked with,'' said John B.
Torinus Jr., a former journalist who was a congressional fellow
with Cheney in 1968. ``I was a news guy, so you are not going to
hear me get euphoric about many politicians. But he was head and
shoulders above the rest in that crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush, who only made a ``gentleman's C'' at Yale, is
intimidated by Cheney's academic reputation, he can remind Cheney
of his brief stint at Yale. He flunked out. ``I had a lack of
direction,'' Cheney told Business Week in 1998. ``But I had a good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Yale, Cheney returned to Casper, Wyoming, climbing
utility poles for the local power company. That encouraged him to
get serious about school, graduating from the University of
Wyoming, before pursuing his doctoral degree at Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The careers of Cheney and Bush have come from different
directions. While Cheney was quickly rising through the ranks of
Nixon and Ford administrations as a young man, Bush was in Texas
pursuing his fortune, first in oil and later as a baseball team
owner.
</P>
<P>
   When Jimmy Carter defeated President Ford, Cheney returned to
Wyoming to begin his congressional career. It was during that first
campaign in 1978 that Cheney had the first of three heart attacks.
Some have speculated that Cheney's ambitious drive contributed to
his health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques B. DePuy, who was a graduate student in political
science with Cheney at the University of Wisconsin before both
became Congressional Fellows, says Cheney's friendly demeanor
covered a very hardworking intensity even then.
</P>
<P>
   DePuy said that when Cheney was working at the White House, ``we
used to hear that he would sometimes spend the night on the couch _
that he worked so hard he wouldn't get home some nights. That kind
of fit with my recollection of how intense he was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, citing a recent health exam, says Cheney is
healthy enough to serve if asked.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, President Bush tapped Cheney as his secretary of
defense. He oversaw Desert Storm _ the defeat of Iraq and the
high-water mark of Bush's presidency. After Bill Clinton defeated
the elder Bush in 1992, Cheney worked in a Republican think tank
for a couple of years before _ like George W. Bush _ he sought his
fortune in Texas and in oil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Cheney became CEO of Halliburton Company, the world's
largest oil services company based in Dallas. He led the company on
a growth spurt his first two years, but in the first quarter of
this year the company has suffered a 12 percent drop in revenues as
the oil and gas industry struggled. Last year, Halliburton paid
Cheney $1.9 million. Last month, Cheney sold nearly half of his
interest in Halliburton stock for about $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush began looking for a running mate, Cheney was the Bush
family loyalist picked to screen the candidates. He knew the
stakes. After all, in 1992 when some questioned whether Vice
President Dan Quayle was hurting the Republican ticket, Cheney was
briefly considered as a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   However, his longtime friend, Leach, said Cheney did not expect
to return to national politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he assumed public service was behind him,'' Leach
said. ``But when a potential president asks you, you are obligated
to consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
