<SLUG> BC-FARRAKHAN0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Two marches. One goal.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Farrakhan, Martin Luther King III and Al Sharpton were in
Atlanta on Monday promoting the ``Million Family March'' and
``Redeeming the Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 26, Sharpton, the president of the National Action
Network and King, president of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, will stage ``Redeem the Dream,'' to fight racial
profiling. On Oct. 16, Farrakhan, the leader of the Nation of
Islam, will hold the Million Family March, to strengthen the
family.
</P>
<P>
   The three were in town promoting their marches independently
before banding together to seal the alliance and unite their
causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not draw away from each other,'' said Farrakhan. ``We
will complement each other and not let the forces of division
obscure the real cause of both of the marches.''
</P>
<P>
   They each agreed there is no coincidence the marches will be
held before the November election and Farrakhan hinted that he may
use it as an opportunity to endorse a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsing a politician is part of a new Farrakhan, mellowed
since his life-threatening bout with prostate cancer. He said he
feels about 85 percent, and while he is cancer-free, radiation
treatments still weaken him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank God for the prayers that I have received,'' said
Farrakhan. ``That is why I have recommitted my life not only for
black people, but for all people who struggle. The message has
evolved and the man has evolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan said he hopes to visit Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, who is
in jail and has been charged with the shooting death of Fulton
County Deputy Ricky Kinchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It grieves me that anyone's life is lost,'' Farrakhan said of
Kinchen. ``But we need to find the facts and judge brother Jamil.
If Jamil is in error, then he must pay the price of his error. If
Jamil is an innocent victim, he must be allowed freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
