<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CONE SOLD HIS SOUL TO THE DEVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
   Like Shoeless Joe from Hannibal, Mo., David Cone from Kansas
City, Mo., sold his soul to the devil. There is simply no other
explanation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The suspicion arose initially last season and has heightened
with each of Cone's starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone thought anything of it at the time, but Cone
himself provided the critical clue in the aftermath of the perfect
game he pitched a year ago against Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a 1996 performance in which he pitched seven
hitless innings but was not allowed to remain in the game, he said:
``I've wondered if I'd ever get a chance again. Going into the
latter innings today, that was running through my mind, about how
many times I've been close and how this might be the last chance I
get.''
</P>
<P>
   And so sometime in the seventh or the eighth, maybe even the
ninth inning of the game against Montreal, when Cone could taste
not just his no-hitter but his chance at perfection, he did it. He
made the pact, and he has been paying for it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   In 31 starts since his perfect game, Cone has won three times
while losing 14. The Yankees have staggered to an 11-20 record in
his post-perfection starts. This is no way to gain another chance
to win another World Series.
</P>
<P>
   That is, unless George Steinbrenner made a similar pact a few
years ago but with different terms over a much longer period. In
coveting the perfect game, Cone was looking only at the moment. Had
he to do it over again, he undoubtedly would give more
consideration to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, on the other hand, doesn't think in small steps.
Don't settle for one World Series championship when four
championships are better. Don't settle for one all-star when three
all-stars are available. Don't settle for success for yourself when
you can guarantee failure for someone who's getting too close for
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Is anyone so naive to think it was just a coincidence that Ken
Griffey Jr. and Barry Larkin both declined to be traded to the
Mets? It's possible that Larkin would have been amenable to the
idea, but after Juan Gonzalez said no to the Yankees and they
wouldn't pay the ransom the Chicago Cubs wanted for Sammy Sosa, no
way was Steinbrenner's satanic playmate going to allow the word
``yes'' to pass Larkin's lips.
</P>
<P>
   As for the messy Sosa business, notice that Ed Lynch is no
longer the Cubs' general manager and that Andy MacPhail, the club
president and chief executive officer, has had to regress in his
career and play general manager. Think maybe a fuming George called
ole Beelzebub and said, ``And one more thing ... ''?
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud has gone to Seattle, Rey Ordonez is out for the
season, Robin Ventura is on the disabled list and having a poor
season to boot _ no more ``best infield in baseball'' for the Mets.
Roger Clemens hits Mike Piazza in the head, says he didn't mean to.
Maybe he didn't. Maybe the hand of Steinbrenner-induced fate guided
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees trade for David Justice, Denny Neagle and Glenallen
Hill. They don't refuse to come to New York. The Braves trade for
Andy Ashby. He happily moves to Atlanta, the Mets' personal hell.
</P>
<P>
   Every other contender wants to shore up its corps of starting
pitchers. The Braves and the Yankees already have the best
rotations in their respective leagues, but they secure the best
starters available. As soon as they join their new teams, Ashby and
Neagle each win two games. One of Ashby's victories, a 1-0
decision, comes against the Mets in a game that has a two-game
swing in the standing. No surprise there, bub.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, meanwhile, struggle to bolster their chances of
reaching the playoffs. Mike Bordick to play shortstop and steady
the infield? Manny Ramirez to play the outfield and drive in a ton
of runs? Curt Schilling or Mike Mussina to solidify the starting
rotation?
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, shouldn't be
surprised if just as he is about to complete one of those deals,
his telephone goes dead and the other team turns elsewhere.
Baseball is a game of inches and timing. This is Steinbrenner time,
even if it might be the end-of-Cone time. When Clemens was on the
disabled list last month, Steinbrenner supposedly told Clemens what
he needed to do to start winning. Steinbrenner has refused to say
what he said, but Clemens won his first four starts after leaving
the disabled list, the first time he had won four straight starts
in a season and a half with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner obviously put the fear of the devil in him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
