</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-INDIA-$ADV30-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF THE RAJ   AT A LAVISH NEW SPA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Winds thrashed the lush, towering
sal trees, thunder rumbled over the Himalayas and the rains rushed
across a broad clipped lawn where British aristocrats once thwacked
a tennis ball. In the shelter of a Raj-era, colonnaded musical
pavilion, a yoga teacher showed me how to twist, stretch and
balance myself in the ancient poses, or asanas, of the cobra, the
tree, the cow face and the dead man.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We enacted this ritual of guru and disciple on the grounds of a
palace built around the turn of the century by the Maharajah of
Tehri Garhwal as a playground for the British viceroy. With its
Victorian balustrades and Mughal archways, the palace now furnishes
the public rooms for an opulent, new $50 million spa that spills
across 100 acres in the foothills of the Himalayas.
</P>
<P>
   As the yoga session proceeded, the rains built to a lashing
fury, making a curtain that enclosed the pavilion in a watery
intimacy. Then they were gone as quickly as they came. While I lay
back on the white marble floor, clearing my mind of thought and
relaxing each body part, the only sounds were of frogs, crickets
and birds.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was an escape from the heat and dust, the noise
and the teeming cities of India, this is surely it. Perched 3,280
feet above sea level, with majestic views of the town of Rishikesh
and the mighty Ganges River about 160 miles northeast of New Delhi,
Ananda in the Himalayas offers austere luxury for the sybarite,
hiking, squash and rafting for the athlete and yoga, meditation and
Ayurvedic massage therapies _ among many other treatments _ for the
stressed out.
</P>
<P>
   The spa's construction was still in the final stages of
completion when I was there last month _ and plenty of
imperfections were yet to be sanded away. The water in the showers
and the Jacuzzi bath was not hot enough. The restaurant menu was a
jarring mixture of light fusion cooking and spicy Indian meats and
curries. The staff was sometimes overly solicitous when all you
wanted was to be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Ananda's designers have managed to graft a modern,
well air-conditioned, 21,000 square-foot spa and 75-room hotel,
decked out with minibars, walk-in closets and cable television,
onto a terrain haunted by India's ancient and colonial history.
</P>
<P>
   The spa sits in a region of the Himalayas that for millenniums
has been a place where sadhus _ the ascetic, bearded holy men of
Hinduism _ wandered the forests, meditated in caves and practiced
Ayurveda and yoga.
</P>
<P>
   The maharajah's personal palace still stands sentinel at the
entrance to the Ananda in all its decayed splendor, and the current
maharajah, Manbendra Shah, retains a staff there. But he has leased
the adjoining Viceregal Palace and 100 acres to a group of
hoteliers and investors for at least the next 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   The spa was developed by a joint venture of Indian Hotels and
Health Resorts on one hand and Rafael Group Hoteliers on the other.
The Rafael group is an international operator of luxury hotels, but
it recently merged with the Mandarin Oriental Hotel Group and the
Ananda is expected to become one of its properties. Mandarin
Oriental runs hotels of that name in Hong Kong, Jakarta, Manila and
London, as well as the Mark in Manhattan, among many others.
</P>
<P>
   In the viceroy's palace at the Ananda, guests will be able to
play billiards on an antique pool table made in Calcutta, take yoga
in a grand ballroom where the children of the British colonialists
went roller-skating and _ when the hotel obtains a liquor license _
sip Cognac in an Art Deco-inspired lounge lined with autographed
photographs of royals and viceroys.
</P>
<P>
   What struck me most when I arrived at the Ananda, however, was
not the history, but the quiet and serenity, which are elusive
qualities in this nation of one billion people _ and in my life,
for that matter. My husband, Barry Bearak, and I are raising two
young sons and covering a fifth of humanity here in South Asia as
correspondents for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   When I picked up the lucky penny of this spa assignment, I
wanted to find a way of getting there that gave me a head start on
attaining that rarest of states: relaxation. So I chose to fly.
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   But in this part of the world, travel is anything but
predictable or easy. I boarded a 40-minute Indian Airlines flight
to Dehra Dun one sultry afternoon, flies buzzing in the cabin of
the 20-seat propeller plane, and buried my nose in the Ananda's
brochures.
</P>
<P>
   I had never been to a spa before, never had a facial or a body
wrap, never taken yoga. I spent the flight selecting the ways I was
going to pamper myself. Would it be the Detox Papaya Body Polish?
The Seaweed Hydrotherapy Bath? Or maybe Pizhichil, an Ayurvedic
treatment in which two therapists pour warm oil all over your body?
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   At one point, I looked up and saw that we had entered what
appeared to be an endless cotton ball. Unconcerned, I went back to
reading. When I glanced up again, I saw the pilot waving to a
stewardess and felt the plane bank sharply. My shoulders squeezed a
notch tenser as I realized we were turning back to Delhi.
Visibility was zero because of premonsoon rains.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the evening in Delhi was spent scrambling for a
ticket on the train, scarce this time of year because so many
pilgrims and people seeking escape from the capital's beastly heat
head for the hills. But I managed to get a first-class seat on the
Shatabdi Express at 7 the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   The station swirled with travelers. Coolies threaded through the
crowds with stacks of luggage balanced on their heads. As I walked
down the platform, I choked on the stench of human excrement that
was heaped along the track. Toilets aboard are just stainless steel
holes that empty onto the ground rushing beneath you.
</P>
<P>
   Once I settled into the air-conditioned first-class cabin,
though, with its wide, comfortable seats, the five-hour ride was
quite pleasant. As the train gathered a gentle, rocking momentum, I
watched rain-drenched fields flash by. At the Saharanpur station, I
looked across the tracks into a car without air-conditioning where
a beautiful little girl, her hair shorn like a boy's, her dark eyes
outlined in thick smudges of kohl, swung gaily on the bars of an
open-air window.
</P>
<P>
   Images such as this one are the unbidden pleasures of a journey
through India. I felt myself letting go of the need for a tight
schedule. Travel here teaches a kind of fatalism: accept the
slippage of time, or sacrifice all peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
