<HEADER>
A1718 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-FAITH-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      07-24 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAITH-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A faith-based welfare reform program pushed by
Gov. George W. Bush has crossed the line into evangelical Christian
proselytizing, a lawsuit filed Monday claims.
</P>
<P>
   A consortium of Christian churches in the Brenham area of
Washington County used state tax dollars last year to buy Bibles
and urge the poor to build a relationship with Jesus, according to
the complaint of the American Jewish Congress and the Texas Civil
Rights Project.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Travis County district court against the
Texas Department of Human Services, is believed to be the nation's
first constitutional challenge asserting that a faith-based welfare
reform program violates separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of Texas does not pay for religious training or
religious materials or proselytizing,'' said Bush spokesman Mike
Jones. ``The state of Texas has a long history of contracting with
faith-based organizations for a wide range of services, everything
from nursing homes to child care.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which also names DHS Commissioner Eric Bost as a
defendant, asserts otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   It says the churches in Washington County that run a local jobs
program for the needy used state taxes to ``promote religious
doctrine'' and ``subsidize religious discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit includes documentation showing that an August 1999
state evaluation of the program makes clear Biblical instruction
was central to the Job Partnership of Washington County's work
readiness lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biblical references are used to teach subjects such as
self-identification, relationships, authority, attitude, integrity,
communication, conflict resolution, stewardship of time/money, and
excellence in all things,'' the DHS ``Texas Works'' program report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another court exhibit in the lawsuit is entitled ``Biblical
Curriculum: Keys to Personal and Professional Success.''
</P>
<P>
   It shows God as a central figure in the classes. The lesson for
week five asserts ``to work is to serve God and man'' while the
next week students learn that ``all authority comes from God.''
</P>
<P>
   DHS officials said late Monday that the program's state contract
expired in December 1999 and was not renewed. The consortium had
received $666 a month from the state or up to $8,000 a year,
however.
</P>
<P>
   By turning state tax dollars over for such purposes, the lawsuit
suit contends, DHS is violating the Bill of Rights, the Texas
Constitution and the First Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asks the court to declare the state's contract with
the jobs program unconstitutional. It also asks the court to
prohibit public support of the program in the future and to order
the jobs program to return the money it received.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Bost pointed out that participation in the program is
not mandatory, since those moving from welfare to work can chose
instead a secular program sponsored by the Texas Workforce
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Bost added that DHS earlier looked into the program but found no
evidence for the complaints in the lawsuit. He said he would be
highly concerned if the allegations are true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of any of those allegations,'' he said. ``If
indeed after we get the lawsuit and I see what it says, we will
thoroughly talk with (the churches) and investigate and make some
determination of what exactly is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   On the presidential campaign trail, both Bush and Vice President
Al Gore have embraced the concept of religious groups administering
government programs for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Texas ``has made the most deliberate attempt to
push charitable choice,'' said Marc Stern, assistant executive
director of the Jewish American Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contends that the program taught students, many who
have been forced off the welfare rolls, that they need to ``change
from the inside out, rather than from the outside in, and that can
only be accomplished through a relationship with Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
