<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1719 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-INDIA-SPA-$ADV     07-24 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-INDIA-SPA-$ADV30-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: peace of mind.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A white-suited driver from the Ananda met me at the Haridwar
station with a cold face cloth. We drove through town, past
jangling horse and buggies, pushcarts loaded with mangoes, ragged,
bearded sadhus and hawkers selling ripe cherries in twists of
newspaper. The drive to the hotel took about an hour, much of it
through the Rajaji and Chilla national parks, with a final snaking
ride up a mountainside to the Ananda.
</P>
<P>
   As a golf cart took me down a steep, densely forested incline to
my room, I breathed in the cool, fresh air, scented by pine trees
planted to make the British overlords feel at home. The hotel
itself curved along a ridge that afforded spectacular views of
Rishikesh. The town was laid out in the valley below, along the
banks of the Ganges, which was the color of milky masala tea.
</P>
<P>
   To an American, the hotel and spa, with their red-tiled roofs
and cream-colored stucco exteriors, looked Mediterranean. But Ingo
R. Schweder, one of the hoteliers who conceived this project in
1997, said at the end of my stay that the design was characteristic
of the Himachal region of India.
</P>
<P>
   My quarters _ standard in the hotel, which I visited anonymously
_ included a medium-sized, uncluttered bedroom, decorated with
soft, muted fabrics, hardwood floors and hand-painted tantric art.
It had a wall of glass with a gorgeous view of mountains and
valley. The commodious bathroom had its own striking picture window
above a big bathtub. On the balcony, the only reminder of the
hurly-burly below was the occasional growl of a truck grinding up
the mountainside. Yellow butterflies fluttered in the updraft like
pieces of tissue paper.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch on a teak deck high in the treetops, I enjoyed a tangy,
refreshing banana lassi _ a yogurt drink _ a salad of greens with
roasted eggplant from a nearby organic farm, and a modest, zesty
bowl of linguine with a roasted tomato sauce. It was the first in a
series of meals that were not all as satisfying as this one.
</P>
<P>
   But for a hard case like me _ whose mind churned with a
phantasmagoria of other things I ought to be doing _ the Ananda
provided a respite, as it appeared to as well for the
multigenerational Indian families who were enjoying its pleasures
while I was there. It has many beautiful spots in which to sit and
read, a first-rate gymnasium and separate areas for men and women
that offer a sauna, Jacuzzi bath, steam room, foot bath, chilling
plunge pool and relaxation room.
</P>
<P>
   My most memorable experiences, though, were in the hands of the
Ayurvedic therapists, Vidya Mohan and Shetcy George, and the yoga
instructor, Rishi Bharadwaj.
</P>
<P>
   Mohan and George, who were recruited from the southern state of
Kerala, gave me an extraordinarily sensuous couple of hours one
afternoon in one of the spa's 13 treatment rooms. I lay on a long
wooden table made from a neem tree. For an hour, the two of them _
the Esther Williamses of massage _ kneaded me from head to toe in
synchrony. The treatment is called Abhyanga. The cost is $22.50.
</P>
<P>
   For the following 45 minutes, I underwent the Pizhichil therapy
(cost: $40). Mohan continuously poured warm sesame oil, earthily
scented with 23 herbal essences, through the spout of a brass cruet
all over my body, gently rubbing it in, while George reheated the
oil that flowed off the table for reuse.
</P>
<P>
   For someone like me, who is always chiding my sons, Max, 10, and
Sam, 5, to eat over their bowls of salad so they don't drip
vinaigrette on their shirts, submitting to this oil bath took some
getting used to. But I did it, and it was unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   I came back the next day for another session with Mohan and
George, but did not like the Shirodhara treatment at all, though
they performed it beautifully. I was nearing the end of my stay,
and perhaps I had had enough pampering.
</P>
<P>
   For half an hour, they poured a steady stream of herbal oil on
my forehead. Cost: $40. This is supposed to pacify the mind and
body, but I felt restless and kept wanting to leap from the table
and dance when a particularly catchy Hindi movie tune came on the
stereo. I also felt as if my head was turning into a mop, with my
hair absorbing huge, gooshy quantities of oil.
</P>
<P>
   But you never know what you'll like unless you try it. Yoga, I
liked. Schweder, the hotelier, found Bharadwaj, the yoga
instructor, in Bombay, where he was a favorite of the city's rich
socialites. This lithe young man, age 25, has big ears, a clean-cut
look, a direct, understated manner and a hypnotic voice that
resonates like a tuning fork when he says ``ohm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rishi is very popular among the rich and famous of Bombay,''
Schweder said. ``He has a huge sensitivity to teaching different
levels of yoga.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: He makes out-of-shape, middle-aged people feel
good.
</P>
<P>
   Most mornings and evenings, Rishi gave a class at the musical
pavilion and all but once I was his only pupil. He calmly explained
the positions, the breathing techniques and the philosophy of yoga
and meditation.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the hour, when I lay on my back in the dead man
pose, he padded around me in his white pajama and bare feet,
telling me to concentrate on the tip of my nose or my breathing. At
these moments, I felt an emptiness of mind and a welcome stillness
of spirit.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; BASICS
</P>
<P>
   Ananda in the Himalayas, the Palace Estate, Narendra Nagar,
Tehri Garhwal, Uttar Pradesh, 249175 India. Telephone (91-13)
782-7500 or (91-11) 689-9999, fax (91-13) 782-7550.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for the 70 standard rooms are $225 single and $275 double
per day, which includes breakfast and one spa treatment each day.
The Ananda has five suites, ranging from $425 to $850. Visitors
should note that listed prices for rooms, suites and spa services
do not include 5 percent tax.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel and spa has a double-occupancy ``rejuvenation
retreat'' package for a two-night stay. It costs $675 and includes
daily breakfast, at least one spa treatment and a daily yoga or
aerobic session for each person. Either person can take one beauty
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for a single treatment session or massage range from
about $20 to $56.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner for two, not including wine, costs about $40 to $45.
</P>
<P>
   There are monsoon rains in August, and the tourist season gets
under way in September.
 &UR; GETTING THERE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A 50-minute flight from New Delhi to Dehra Dun on Indian
Airlines leaves on Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays. Round-trip
fare is $200. The flight to Dehra Dun is followed by a 45-minute
taxi ride to the spa costing $18, at 44.6 rupees to the dollar. If
you phone ahead, Ananda will fetch you in a spa car for $34.
</P>
<P>
   One can also arrange with the Ananda for a private helicopter or
plane to pick you up in New Delhi and drop you off near the spa.
The cost ranges from $250 to $280 each way.
</P>
<P>
   The train from New Delhi to the town of Haridwar takes four to
five hours, followed by an hour's drive to the spa. A first-class
train ticket is $22 each way.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
