<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-POLL-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS SEE SHARP DIFFERENCES BETWEEN BUSH AND GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With ELECTION-POLL-METHOD) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE and JANET ELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush prepare to
frame their messages at the upcoming national conventions, most
Americans say they already perceive pronounced differences on how
they would handle health care, taxes, the environment and the
selection of Supreme Court justices, the latest New York Times/CBS
News Poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   For all the focus on how both contenders are dashing toward the
center politically, and in some cases sounding alike, more than
seven out of 10 Americans say there are genuine contrasts between
them. More than half of the public thinks those differences are
more over issues than the contenders' personal qualities.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, 58 percent of Americans say that if Gore is
elected president, he would make health care more affordable for
everyone; 36 percent say that of Bush. Forty-four percent say Bush
would be more likely to reduce taxes; 25 percent say that of Gore.
Seventy percent say Gore would be likely to make real progress in
protecting the environment; 44 percent say that of Bush. Sixty-two
percent say Gore would likely pick Supreme Court justices who would
vote to keep abortion legal; 43 percent say Bush would do the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest split came on the issue of abortion. Sixty-two
percent say Gore would likely pick Supreme Court justices who would
vote to keep abortion legal; 43 percent say Bush would do the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   But while the impressions of the candidates seem to be taking
shape, voters are far from having made up their minds. Several
signs, in fact, point to a fiercely competitive contest. About a
third of voters say they could switch their loyalties before
Election Day. And significant portions of each candidate's
supporters say they have reservations about their current favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continues to lead Gore among all registered voters, but his
advantage falls just within the poll's margin of sampling error. If
the election were held today, and it were a two-person race,
registered voters say they would back Bush over Gore by a margin of
46-to-40 percentage points. In a four-way competition, with Ralph
Nader, the Green Party nominee, and Pat Buchanan, the expected
Reform Party nominee, Bush would draw 44 percent; Gore, 38 percent,
Nader, 5 percent and Buchanan, 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide telephone poll was taken Thursday through Sunday
with 953 adults, including 743 registered voters. The survey has a
margin of sampling error of plus or minus three percentage points
in either direction. The margin of sampling error among registered
voters is plus or minus four percentage points for each candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out with this campaign,'' Samuel Hathaway,
36, a poll respondent from Vancouver, Wash., said in a follow-up
interview. Explaining that he plans to back Gore but could change
his mind, he added, ``I just want to hear more from the campaign
itself. Right now I usually vote Democratic. Al Gore has been
around for eight years as vice president so I'm sure he knows how
to do the job. But I also like the Reform Party and I want to hear
them out as well.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll respondent who backs Bush, Kay Wimberly, 47, also said
her leanings are by not means irreversable. ``The primary reason I
might change my mind is because it's so early on in the campaign,''
said Wimberly, a graphic designer from LaCrosse, Wis. ``A lot of
things can come to the surface between now and then. The candidates
will make their positions more well known as the election draws
nearer. Education is an important issue to me and to the future of
this country. I'm not entirely sold on Bush's position because I
feel some of his claims are somewhat vague.''
</P>
<P>
   In another finding that carries significant implications for the
battle for control of Congress as well as the presidential
campaign, the poll found that the Republican Party has mounted a
successful recovery from the negative standing it had after the
impeachment proceedings against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a heartening sign for Gore as both candidates compete for
independent and moderate voters is that the public's impression of
Bush's ideology _ while once equally divided between moderate and
conservative _ is increasingly conservative. By contrast, the
perception of Gore is that he is moving more from liberal to
moderate.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Americans, 54 percent, now hold a favorable
opinion of the Republican Party. During the impeachment
proceedings, only 33 percent held a positive view of the party.
Democrats had hoped to use public distress over the Republicans'
handling of the impeachment as a campaign issue in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also underscored that critiques that Republicans and
Democrats have made about their opponents may not be convincing to
the American public. Efforts by Republicans to link Gore to the
scandals of the Clinton administration do not seem to have worked.
A plurality of voters say the coming election is not about Clinton.
And majorities give Gore high marks for personal integrity and
character _ something they never did for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The argument of many Democrats that Bush lacks sufficient
command of issues does not seem to be working either. Despite
Gore's eight years of intimate involvement in policy at the White
House, that has not convinced voters that he is any more prepared
for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-six percent of Americans say Bush has strong qualities of
leadership; 55 percent say that of Gore. More people think Gore
understands the complicated problems a president has to deal with,
but the difference is not especially significant. Eighty-four
percent say Gore understands those problems; 73 percent say that
about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And while even Bush has acknowledged that ``my foreign affairs
experience is Mexico,'' voters say they have as much confidence in
him as they do in the vice president's ability to deal wisely with
an international crisis. For both candidates, voters were roughly
split on whether they were confident or uneasy about how they would
handle foreign crises.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's biggest strengths is that people still see hin as
eminently likeable, while one of Gore's best assets is that he is
seen generally as being on the right side of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush drew high marks for straight talk, leadership and
trustworthiness, while Gore was viewed as caring more about the
needs and problems of voters.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, the differences were largely of degree. For
instance, both men were seen by a majority of voters as pandering _
saying what they think voters want to hear. But Gore was viewed so
by a larger majority.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continues to be seen favorably by a majority of voters who
have formed an opinion of him. Gore is seen equally favorably and
unfavorably, but that is a small improvement from the primary
season.
</P>
<P>
   While the Times/CBS Poll shows no appreciably tightening of the
race, other national polls have shown that Gore has made some
progress recently in reducing Bush's advantage. For example, the
most recent Gallup Poll measured 48 percent for Bush and 46 percent
for Gore. Earlier in July, the margin was nine percentage points.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gore's supporters say they are marginally more certain about
sticking with the vice president than Bush's backers. But four in
10 of each candidates' supporters say they have reservations about
their candidate. One bright spot for Gore is that he has made
significant inroads in the Northeast since May, when the last
Times/CBS poll was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Gore cannot seem to shake a nagging perception that he
is the inevitable loser. Only 29 percent of the voters polled said
they expected him to win, compared to 49 percent who said Bush
would triumph.
</P>
<P>
   For all the differences between Bush and Gore, the one issue
where the public sees them both as responsible is on the economy.
Roughly three-quarters of Americans think either Gore or Bush would
likely make sure that the country's economy remains robust.
</P>
<P>
   The public continues to put health care, Social Security and
Medicare at the top of the list of problems they want the next
president and Congress to work on. Those issues are all viewed as
Democratic strong points.
</P>
<P>
   But taxes, an issue Bush has championed for months, is beginning
to make its way on to the public's list of most pressing concerns.
</P>
<P>
   While the survey found that the Republican Party has rebounded,
Democrats, too, are held in high esteem, with 56 of those polled
registering a favorable view of the party.
</P>
<P>
   More people said they would vote for the Democratic House
candidate in their district than said they would vote for the
Republican. But the spread _ 41-to-37 percent _ is well within the
margin of error. And national polls cannot predict an election in
an individual district. But they can provide some insight into the
general trend.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party continues to hold the advantage on many
issues that voters say they are concerned about, including Social
Security, making the tax system fair, improving education,
providing affordable health care, protecting the environment and
caring about the average person. The Republican strengths,
according to those polled, are keeping the military potent and
preserving family values.
</P>
<P>
   The two political parties that have not fared well are the
Reform Party and Green Party. Both are seen negatively by most
people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
