<HEADER>
A1723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEAR-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      07-24 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAR-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: BEAR STEARNS RALLIES AMID TAKEOVER TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Let the bidding begin for the last free-standing
properties on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of UBS AG's agreement this month to buy the
PaineWebber Group for $12 billion, executives of the few remaining
independent financial-services firms are worrying about being left
alone at the dance. Monday, shares of Bear Stearns Cos. leaped 7.7
percent, to their highest level in almost two years, on an
analyst's report that the firm might be for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns officials have not publicly announced an interest
in selling the firm, and the analyst's report, which was published
Monday, said no deal appeared to be imminent. Neither James Cayne,
the firm's chief executive, nor the author of the report, Guy
Moszkowski, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, responded to phone
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some traders and investors bought shares on the hope that
the management of Bear Stearns would be willing to listen to
offers. The firm's shares rose $3.4375, to $49.75, on the New York
Stock Exchange. More than 3 million shares changed hands, about
five times normal daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that it's a very cheap stock apart from whether
there's a deal or not,'' said Larry Sondike, a portfolio manager
with the Mutual Series funds in Short Hills, N.J. ``We think we're
getting the possibility of consolidation for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Sondike would not say whether the Mutual Series funds, formerly
run by the activist investor Michael Price, had put any pressure on
Bear Stearns management to improve returns on the firm's lagging
stock. ``I trust that Bear Stearns management and board will do
what's right for all Bear Stearns shareholders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the report that lighted the fire under shares of Bear Stearns
on Monday, Moszkowski broached the subject of a buyout, saying that
Cayne seemed more receptive than ever to the idea. But he added
that Cayne had thrown out a minimum purchase price of four times
the firm's book value, the value of its assets minus liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   That amounts to about $120 a share, or about $19 billion, for a
firm whose stock had not traded above $50 in almost two years. UBS
snapped up PaineWebber for 3.5 times book value, and some boutique
investment banks have sold for steeper prices.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts said they doubted Bear Stearns would command a
premium like those even from a foreign bank seeking an instant
presence on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on the outside looking in and want to gain an
investment-banking footprint, it gets you into the game but you're
still a notch below'' the biggest investment banks like Goldman
Sachs Group, said Dean Eberling, an analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP;
Woods. ``Four times book is unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the wave of mergers and buyouts that has swept the
securities industry over the last several years, Bear Stearns has
been viewed as an iconoclastic holdout. A midsize investment bank,
it makes a lot of money in some businesses that other Wall Street
firms shun. Most notable among them is the clearing, or processing,
of trades for other, usually smaller, brokerage firms and hedge
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing is perennially profitable for Bear Stearns, which has
one of the biggest clearing operations, but it has taken on more
risk in recent years as regulators have sought to hold firms like
Bear Stearns responsible for the actions of the small brokerage
firms that make up their clearing clientele. Processing trades is
also much less alluring than the high-fee investment banking
practices of underwriting stocks of new companies and advising
corporations on mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Cayne ``believes strongly that the
firm's biggest problem is its image.'' It alluded to the firm's
role as clearing broker for A.R. Baron, a defunct brokerage firm
that prosecutors charged with bilking investors, and a recent court
order that the firm pay $111 million to a former customer.
</P>
<P>
   After that judgment reduced Bear Stearns' second-quarter
earnings by $96 million, Eberling lowered his rating on the firm's
stock from ``buy'' to ``market outperform.'' Eberling said he was
troubled by the firm's plan to spend heavily to build its
investment-banking operation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Moszkowski, in contrast, rates Bear Stearns a ``buy'' and says
he expects its price to rise to $60 within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth far, far more than $50 a share,'' said Sondike, who
manages the Mutual Shares fund and co-manages the Mutual Beacon
fund. Together those funds own about 4 million shares, or about 1
percent of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear tends to really not get any respect,'' Sondike said.
``People erroneously tend to think it's a trading shop taking a lot
of risk. These are smart, risk-averse, profit-seeking people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was also attracted by the high level of inside
ownership of the firm. Cayne, he noted, owns about 4 million
shares. Monday, the value of those shares rose nearly $15 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
