<P>
   &UR; JEWRUSALEM? OR JERUSALAAM?: CAMP DAVID'S DISPUTED CITY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHOSE-JERUSALEM?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``This is really, really hard,'' groaned President
Bill Clinton in the early hours of July 20, as he left Camp David _
a day late _ for the weekend G8 summit in Okinawa. For nine days
Clinton had been talking around the clock with Israelis and
Palestinians in one final pursuit of a Mideast peace treaty. One of
the greatest obstacles yet to overcome is the future status of
Jerusalem _ the deeply symbolic, coveted stone-built city which is
claimed by both Israelis and Palestinians as their capital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICA: LEGISLATE, DON'T LITIGATE, TOBACCO PUNISHMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STOP-SUING-TOBACCO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Even the judge could hardly believe his eyes. ``A
lot of zeros,'' he chuckled. True enough, this was the largest
civil-damages verdict in history. After a two-year trail, a Miami
jury decided on July 14 that America's largest tobacco companies
should pay $145 billion _ yes, folks, that's billions, not millions
_ in punitive damages to thousands of Florida smokers for damaging
their health. By awarding such an absurd figure, the jurors _ quite
inadvertently _ sent an important message: that it is high time
Americans abandon their misguided attempt to ``punish'' the tobacco
industry through lawsuits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...and Tobacco-State Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA'S NEW REALISM ABOUT WHERE ITS REAL INTERESTS LIE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN-G8-DREAMIN'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Russia has long thought of itself as a singular
power. At the G8 summit of rich, democratic nations, which opens in
Okinawa on July 21, it will indeed be the odd one out. While the
other seven leaders from North America, Europe and Japan fret about
the digital divide, and the poor health and bad debts of the
world's hard-up nations, Russian President Vladimir Putin, by his
own admission, is struggling to avoid his country's relegation from
the big-power table to the ranks of the Third World. Putin knows
that, if Russia is to grow strong again, it needs to link its
future with the world's rich democracies _ the folk around the G8
table _ not the world's few surviving dictators. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GET READY FOR CAMPAIGN 2000'S UNCONVENTIONAL CONVENTIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `SHADOW'-CONVENTIONS-ECONOMIST-400&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Republicans and Democrats are not the only people
who are feverishly preparing for next month's conventions in
Philadelphia and Los Angeles. For the first time in American
political history, the two main party conventions will each have
their shadows. These are parallel conventions designed to highlight
issues that the establishment would rather sweep under the carpet _
above all, inequality, money politics and the ``war on drugs.''
There are no fewer than seven alternative conventions in the works,
including a homeless convention and an anarchist gathering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 75-word optional trim; 1,050 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OY VEY! IS HILLARY CLINTON REALLY ANTI-SEMITIC? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OY-VEY-HILLARY!-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Big Apple's media are easily bored, and the
Senate race between Rick Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton was in
danger of being written off as the mother of all snores. So it was
with relish that they seized on reports that Hillary had once
called somebody a ``(expletive) Jew bastard.'' The New York Times
suggested that racist obscenities were unlikely to have been
uttered by ``one of the most politically correct people on the
planet,'' even if she has a foul temper. But Hillary still has
plenty of reason to worry: before the recent controversy, polls
showed her winning only 54 percent of the Jewish votes to Lazio's
34 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LONE SMOG STATE: GOV. BUSH'S DISMAL ENVIRONMENTAL RECORD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOXIC-TEXAS-BUSH-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LA PORTE, TEXAS _ The Texas Independence Trail, a dreary stretch
of road on the outskirts of Houston, is lined with some of the
state's largest oil refineries and petrochemical plants. The trail
ends in the murky town of La Porte at the monument to the Battle of
San Jacinto. In the smog that hangs over this hallowed ground, it
is hard to conjure up images of 1836, when Texas soldiers crying
``Remember the Alamo!'' defeated the advancing Mexican army. If Al
Gore has his way, this place will generate a new rallying cry in
the closing the months of the 2000 presidential campaign:
``Remember La Porte!'' In its bid to undermine George W. Bush's
record as governor of Texas, the Gore campaign is painting a grim
picture of the state's environmental woes on Bush's watch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
