<P>
   &UR; CALIFORNIA'S NEW GOLD RUSH: HOUSING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CALIF-HOUSING-SQUEEZE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although America remains, on average, a cheap
place to live by European standards, it has pockets where the
dynamism of the economy has fuelled not only tremendous growth in
wealth, but also steep inflation in the cost of living. The
sharpest price rises have come in the heartland of the new economy,
California's Silicon Valley. The average monthly rent for a
one-bedroom apartment in Palo Alto is $1,900, and the prices in
some complexes have jumped from $1,550 at the beginning of the year
to $2,200 in June. Buying is just as daunting: the median house
price in San Francisco's Bay Area is $370,000, compared with
$135,000 for the country at large. &QL;
</P>
