<HEADLINE>
JEWRUSALEM? OR JERUSALAAM?: CAMP DAVID'S DISPUTED CITY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 725-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``This is really, really hard,'' groaned President Bill Clinton
in the early hours of July 20, as he left Camp David, a day late,
for the weekend G8 summit in Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and Palestinians were to stay on and keep talking.
Nobody could fault the negotiators for failing to give peace their
best try. Neither side wanted to be the first to give up.
</P>
<P>
   For nine days they had been talking around the clock, without
reaching a conclusion. They had not yet found a way past the main
obstacles that have for so long barred Israelis and Palestinians
from equably sharing their tiny, deeply symbolic, bit of the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most enduring obstacles has been Jerusalem, the
beautiful stone-built city resting in the hills, central to
believers in the three monotheistic faiths, which is claimed by
both Israelis and Palestinians as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, it is where the Temple was built to hold the Ark of
the Covenant. For Muslims, it is where the Prophet left his
footprint on earth when he ascended. For Christians, it is where
Jesus redeemed mankind on the cross.
</P>
<P>
   The religious monuments of all three faiths are mostly within
the walled Old City. But the future of the Old City is probably the
easiest part of the Jerusalem story to resolve. Control over the
Holy Places can be shared out; freedom to worship is an
uncontroversial doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Far trickier problems _ to do with sovereignty, demography and
politics _ haunt the city that spreads out beyond the ancient
walls.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 20 years, between 1948 and 1967, Jerusalem was
divided. A mantra, often repeated by Palestinians as well as
Israelis, is that it should never again have a formal, impassable
line running through it.
</P>
<P>
   The splitting, after Israel's war of independence, was ugly.
Palestinians, who may have owned the greater part of West
Jerusalem, were driven from their homes; Jews were unable to
worship at their holy sites in East Jerusalem, which came under
Jordanian control.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1967 war, Israel reunited the city, annexing its
eastern part. In 1980, it declared Jerusalem to be its eternal,
undivided capital.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel did not only annex East Jerusalem. It also extended
it to about three times its original size, designing careful new
boundaries that maximized the land area while minimizing the number
of Palestinians who lived within the city's extended borders.
</P>
<P>
   It then built residential colonies for Jews which, together with
their linking roads, became fortresses between the West Bank and
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The policy of successive Israeli governments was to increase the
population of Jews in East Jerusalem until they outnumbered the
Arabs. They nearly succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and Palestinians in East Jerusalem are now roughly
equal at about 200,000 each. This has been achieved partly by a
factory-line of Israeli houses, partly by making it intensely
difficult for Palestinians to accommodate their growing families by
enlarging their houses, let alone building new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Netanyahu, when he was prime minister, tried to hurry
the process along by banning ``absentee'' Jerusalemites, but this
backfired as Palestinians hurried home to preserve their
residential status.
</P>
<P>
   The current Israeli government hoped that the Palestinians might
be satisfied with control over their (Muslim and Christian) holy
places, plus a capital in Abu Dis, an Arab suburb just beyond the
municipal border, where Yasser Arafat is in fact building himself a
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians insist on East Jerusalem, not Abu Dis, being
their capital, drawing the scattered parts of their putative state
together, giving it a solidity and resonance that it otherwise
lacks.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, many outsiders think, is a second redrawing of the
city's boundaries, no less creative than the first.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem, capital to both peoples, would be open to both; a
joint council would take care of joint affairs. A Palestinian-run
East Jerusalem, including some of the excluded Arab villages, such
as Abu Dis, would be devised.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli-run Jerusalem would be expanded to include the vast
settlements just outside municipal limits _ and the Israelis would,
at long last, obtain international recognition that their cherished
city was indeed their capital.
</P>
<P>
   These are not impossible thoughts. But they have not, as yet,
been accepted by the tired negotiators at Camp David. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
