<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1742 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-POSTAL-REVENUE0725-CO     07-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTAL-REVENUE0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Postal Service makes Web push
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Patrick deVerona would seem to be a promising recruit
to the U.S. Postal Service's drive to supplement its longtime cash
cow, first-class mail, with an online bill-paying service.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Georgia State senior and his five housemates
share a high-speed digital subscriber line at their duplex, and
even order most of their groceries online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pay my bills online,'' says deVerona. ``The only check I
write each month is for rent.''
</P>
<P>
   But deVerona says he probably won't be paying the Post Office to
pay his bills any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be no reason for me to go to their service,''
deVerona says, because he can use his bank's and credit card
company's equally secure services for free.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service is spending millions of dollars on
television, print and direct mail advertising and offering six
months of free service to entice customers to try its new eBillPay
service, which allows customers to receive and pay bills online.
</P>
<P>
   After six months, the monthly charge is $6 for up to 20
payments, or $2 a month plus 40 cents per bill payment.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Atlanta-based CheckFree Corp., the Postal
Service launched the service in April in a bid to replace part of
its first-class postal service. Last year, first-class mail
accounted for almost 56 percent of the Postal Service's $62.7
billion in operating revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But the postal service's cash cow has been looking skinny lately
because of growing competition from e-mail and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   According to a General Accounting Office report released this
year, first-class mail volume is expected to peak in 2002 and show
``substantial declines'' this decade. About $17 billion spent on
mailing bills and return payments _ about half of first-class
revenues _ is ``at risk'' of being displaced by e-commerce, the GAO
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Postal Service develops some new services, the GAO
warned, it may once again face financial and performance strains
after years of operating surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service hopes its move into e-commerce will
capitalize on its well-recognized brand and a tradition of private,
reliable deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bring our brand and all the trust and security that
Americans have come to expect'' over 225 years of service, says
Greg Frey, a Postal Service spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service is one of the 10 most recognized brands in
the world, according to Young &AMP; Rubicam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our offering is very competitive and brings a whole
series of attributes that are unique to our service, including
trust,'' he says. ``That clearly is missing from some of these
companies that have brand-new names.''
</P>
<P>
   But a six-month free promotion and nods to its long history may
not be enough to set the Postal Service apart in the crowded world
of e-commerce, say industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the Postal Service doing anything all that
innovative. They're just another service provider,'' says Avivah
Litan, research director for payment systems at Gartner Group, a
Stamford, Conn., consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests the Postal Service spend less money on advertising
and more on free e-mail, a longer introductory promotion and other
incentives to draw people online.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics are needed, she argues, because a majority of banks
already offer online bill paying. About 60 percent waive fees for
such services for their most valuable customers, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the head start, customers haven't exactly swamped banks
with demands to pay their bills online, says Litan. Only about 4
million to 5 million people pay at least some bills online.
</P>
<P>
   The main holdups seem to be customers' concerns over the cost of
the services and about the privacy and security of their accounts
and financial information.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Gartner Group survey of Internet users, almost half
said they didn't want to receive their bills online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe this application will roll out over the next
5 to 10 years. It just makes too much economic sense,'' she says.
But companies have a ``long, long way to go to convince
consumers,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Neither banks nor the Postal Service will be able to reduce
costs until more billers join the system, says Chris Musto, vice
president of research for Gomez, an e-commerce consultancy in
Lincoln, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Postal Service, most banks also contract out to
CheckFree to operate their bill payment services.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the time, CheckFree must cut and mail paper checks
to pay billers that haven't contracted with it.
</P>
<P>
   But that proportion is constantly dropping as CheckFree reaches
agreements with more billers, says Matt Lewis, a CheckFree
executive vice president. The firm says its collection of billers
that accept payments electronically has doubled during the past
year, to 121, while its subscriber base has grown by almost 1
million, to 3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis predicts that number will swell rapidly thanks in large
part to the Postal Service's heavy marketing push, which he thinks
will goad banks to become more aggressive as well.
</P>
<P>
   Between the banks' and the Postal Services' efforts, he predicts
that about 30 percent of consumers will be paying their bills
online within three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very similar adoption curve to ATM usage,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
