<HEADER>
A1748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLEE-BAILEY25-COX     07-24 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEE-BAILEY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judicial referee urges Bailey disbarment
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Lawyer F. Lee Bailey violated half a dozen
ethics rules during an international drug-smuggling case and should
be disbarred for life, a Florida Supreme Court referee reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it is difficult for this referee to conceive of a
more egregious set of circumstances than those which Mr. Bailey has
brought upon himself,'' Collier County Circuit Judge Cynthia Ellis
wrote in a biting, 23-page report.
</P>
<P>
   Any of the charges made against Bailey by the Florida Bar _
misappropriating and misusing $6 million of his client's stock,
trying to influence a judge, lying in court _ would be enough for
disbarment, Ellis wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, she said, they ``plainly warrant permanent
disbarment.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Supreme Court follows her recommendation, it would end
the career of one of the 20th Century's most famous defense
lawyers. In 40 years, Bailey has seldom been out of the headlines _
or trouble _ as he fought for clients such as Dr. Sam Sheppard,
Patty Hearst, the Boston Strangler and O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   If he's ousted in Florida, Bailey also would face disbarment
proceedings in the federal court system and in Massachusetts, where
he was admitted to the Bar in 1960. He was admitted in Florida in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   The disbarment recommendation adds another bump in a bad stretch
for Bailey, personally and professionally. His wife and mother both
died within the past year, he underwent hand surgery and he faces a
contempt of court charge in another high stakes case in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, 67, who lives in Manalapan and has an office in West
Palm Beach, said in a statement he would fight to keep his license.
</P>
<P>
   ``Objections as extensive as the rules may allow will be filed
in the Supreme Court of Florida,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's statement noted that the recommendation isn't a
judgment and that he's free to practice law until the Supreme Court
acts, which could take months. He said he'll give his clients a
copy of the recommendation so they can decide whether they want a
different lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall continue to represent my existing clients with all
appropriate vigor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In classic Bailey style, he used the statement to complain that
Ellis refused to admit results of polygraph tests taken by himself
and one of his witnesses, and that a witness and two lawyers on the
other side of the case had refused to take such tests.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey tried to persuade Ellis during a weeklong hearing in June
that he and federal prosecutors had a ``sneaky deal'' to
out-maneuver the French government in the 1994 case of Claude
Duboc, kingpin of a $600-million drug-smuggling ring. Bailey was to
turn over $100 million of Duboc's assets _ houses in France, a
yacht, cash and stock _ to the U.S. government in exchange for a
lighter-than-life sentence for Duboc.
</P>
<P>
   For his services, Bailey said, prosecutors agreed to let him
keep 607,000 shares of pharmaceutical company stock, then worth $6
million. When it went up to $18 million in early 1995, he said, the
government reneged, said he was only keeping it ``in trust'' and
demanded it back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bailey had borrowed against the stock and sold some.
A federal judge in Gainesville jailed him for 44 days until he
could borrow enough to repay the difference. Bailey has sued Duboc
_ who got a life sentence _ in the U.S. Court of Claims to try to
reclaim the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis was merciless in her condemnation of Bailey's actions and
his behavior during the Duboc case and in his own defense
afterwards. She said he had compromised his client by writing to
the federal judge before sentencing in a ``brazen attempt'' to
protect his financial stake in the case and prevent Duboc from
hiring another lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   His ``statements, assertions, claims and testimony about these
matters are patently false,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said the violations were made worse by aggravating
factors, which she listed as Bailey's long experience in practicing
law; a pattern of misconduct; a dishonest or selfish motive;
multiple offenses; making false statements, and refusing to admit
he'd done anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time ... did (he) either personally or through counsel
acknowledge the wrongful nature of any aspect of his behavior ...
`` she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Bailey had been censured in Massachusetts and
suspended for a year in New Jersey 30 years ago, Ellis quoted from
the findings of judges who had disciplined the young lawyer then.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is unwilling to concede that he could have been wrong,''
the Massachusetts judge wrote. ``He studies rules and judicial
orders with a purpose of evasion rather than with a will to comply
with their spirit for the general good.
</P>
<P>
   ``These attitudes bespeak a self-esteem of such proportions as
to challenge description ... a philosophy of extreme egocentricity
for the defense of criminal cases involving the use of news media
... ``
</P>
<P>
   It's plain that ``very little has changed'' in the 30 years
since that was written, Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
