<HEADLINE>
QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 375-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; REALITY BITES: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is, I'm leading in some of the polls. The bad
news is, the election isn't tomorrow.'' (George W. Bush, U.S. News
&AMP; World Report, July 24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOWN AUSTIN WAY (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many oil executives in Texas lack health
insurance, but I can tell you this, a lot of children in Texas
do.'' (Al Gore, Washington Post, July 16) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOWN AUSTIN WAY (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``If this election is decided on my effectiveness as a governor
and on the record of Texas, I'll win by a landslide.'' (George W.
Bush,``This Week,'' ABC, July 16) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUNNY GIRL: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Sanchez, a Democratic congresswoman from California,
will hold a reception for 600 at the Playboy mansion in Los Angeles
during the Democratic convention next month. The aim is to raise
money for Hispanic Unity USA, a political-action committee. Al Gore
disapproves and will certainly not be going. (Washington Post, July
16) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LABOR PAINS: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission reported that labor unions have
given nearly $15 million in soft money for this year's election,
almost all of it to Democrats. This is 50 percent more than in the
last election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAINT PRAISE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment he'd be a better president than George Bush,
because a Democrat is what we need in the White House for all the
issues that I care about.'' (Bill Bradley's red-hot endorsement of
Al Gore, Baltimore Sun, July 14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARS IN HIS POCKET: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Responsive Politics, Al Gore has
received campaign donations from 17 Oscar-winners, including Jack
Nicholson and Robert De Niro. (Salon.com, July 18) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HYDROPOLITICS: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In attempts to maintain the ``excitement'' of the conventions up
to Labor Day in September, Al Gore plans to cruise the Great Lakes
and the Mississippi ``to tap into the romance and symbolism of
those mighty bodies of water.'' Bush is planning a train trip.
(Washington Post, July 17) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDICATOR OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ty Corporation, the maker of Beanie Babies, reported that sales
of its elephant, called ``Righty,'' have outpaced sales of its
donkey, called ``Lefty,'' by three to two. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
