<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONVENTIONS-MARKET-AR     07-24 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTIONS-MARKET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY CONVENTIONS MORE ABOUT MONEY THAN POLITICS FOR CITIES AND
BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
NYT16 is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Philip Morris, the imminent political conventions are not so
much about nominating presidential candidates and building party
loyalty as they are about, well, macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   Macaroni in the shape of donkeys. Macaroni in the shape of
elephants. Macaroni the company plans to hand out to delegates.
</P>
<P>
   This is macaroni with a purpose: to tell the assembled opinion
makers and power brokers that Philip Morris is not just a tobacco
company and hasn't been for some time, that it also sells other
products _ Kraft macaroni among them.
</P>
<P>
   For many, conventions have little to do with politics and a lot
to do with business _ polishing civic and corporate images,
exploiting marketing opportunities, courting influence and turning
what has long been an exercise in democracy into a huge corporate
festival. The dazzling corporate sideshows put this year's
gatherings _ next Monday through Aug. 3 for the Republicans in
Philadelphia and Aug. 14-17 for the Democrats in Los Angeles _ in a
class with the Olympics and the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just major corporations like Philip Morris, which has
bigger plans for the Republican gathering but is not ignoring the
Democratic one. Cities, too, see a chance to bask in the spotlight.
Armed with studies putting the economic benefits of playing host to
a political convention at $100 million or more, over a dozen cities
_ including New York, Indianapolis and San Antonio _ lined up to be
picked, offering millions of dollars in support. This largess comes
on top of the $13 million the federal government gives each party
to hold its four-day convention.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in this head-long marketing rush, many are concerned. Some
contend the economic benefits are vastly overblown, while the risk
to a city's image is underrated. Others call the conventions orgies
of cash, providing yet another route for corporations to buy
political access. Still others say that as conventions have
increasingly lost their political role of nominating candidates and
rallying the party faithful, corporations have stepped in to fill
the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventions have become Super Bowls of the influence of
money on politics,'' said Charles Lewis, executive director of the
Center for Public Integrity, a Washington nonprofit group. ``These
are gala events where the most garish examples of excess appear.''
</P>
<P>
   The cities selected mounted all-out attacks to land the events
along with promises of raising $35 million to $50 million in local
funds for support services, mainly transportation, decorations and
civic improvements. Tax-deductible contributions come to each
city's host committee as cash or goods _ pagers from Motorola,
software from Microsoft, discount tickets from US Airways and UAL's
United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Local governments kick in cash as well. Los Angeles donated $4
million to close a last-minute gap for the Democratic convention.
Philadelphia's effort is supported with $17 million from the states
of New Jersey and Pennsylvania and the city government, along with
a $20-million letter of credit.
</P>
<P>
   To critics of campaign financing like Lewis, host committees
have become a gray zone _ a way for parties to benefit from
millions of unregulated dollars, raised with minimal disclosure and
given out of civic pride as well as a desire to help one candidate.
Even so, some cities, like Los Angeles, have struggled to raise
enough money.
</P>
<P>
   Critics may rage, but cities that have landed conventions _ both
now and in the past _ are thrilled. Even also-ran cities like
Indianapolis say they benefited. And corporations on both coasts,
local suppliers to national brands, are bubbling with enthusiasm
about their plans for the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fabulous opportunity,'' said Patrick McGranaghan,
vice president for marketing at Dale Carnegie Training &AMP;
Associates, which is training thousands of corporate volunteers for
Philadelphia. ``We are putting Dale Carnegie in front of every
major corporation in the Delaware Valley and showing them what we
do. It gives them a taste of Dale Carnegie training, and we hope
they will come back and ask for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy's MicroBatch Ice Cream, a 3-year-old Philadelphia company
that recently produced the first beer-flavored ice cream, plans to
donate $10,000 worth of its product to the media center, where
15,000 reporters will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it gets hotter than blazes, so people will want
something cool and refreshing,'' said Michelle Peranteau, a
spokeswoman. ``There will be hundreds of thousands of people
descending on our city. That's hundreds of thousands we could turn
into MicroBatch lovers.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
