<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1753 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-BANKROLLING-PEACE-ECO     07-24 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKROLLING-PEACE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL AMERICA BANKROLL A CAMP DAVID DEAL?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 550-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A ghost at Camp David has been America's Congress.
This week, as musing turned to the monetary rewards for peace, the
speaker of the House of Representatives, Dennis Hastert, wrote to
President Bill Clinton, tartly reminding him that Congress is the
sole authority for spending money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to be kept fully apprised of all aspects of the
negotiations prior to entering into any commitments,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch McConnell, the head of the Senate subcommittee that would
have to propose any aid package that formed part of a peace deal,
says, ``The chances of the Congress approving (the money) this year
are pretty slim, probably even nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   His opposite number in the House, Sonny Callahan, worries that
``a lame-duck president looking for a legacy might be willing to
write a blank check to get an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   America bankrolled the first Camp David agreement, between
Israel and Egypt in 1978. If there should be a second deal, might
Congress scupper it? The possibility seems real.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has come under unprecedented attack in Congress lately,
meaning that bipartisan backing for a deal signed by the Israeli
government can no longer be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, congressmen of both parties have
criticized Israel for its proposed sale of an airborne radar system
to China, and have been only partly mollified by the deal's
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when the Israelis suggested that a peace deal
with Syria might cost America around $17 billion, largely for
splendid new military equipment to offset the loss of security once
Israel had withdrawn from the Golan Heights, congressmen were
openly unsympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   But that sum pales into insignificance compared with the alleged
costs of any likely Palestinian deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians are said to have claimed that it will take
something like $40 billion to resettle or compensate the refugees
who were evicted in 1948 from what is now Israel, plus other forms
of compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is also claiming vast amounts of money, partly to rehouse
those of its settlers who will have to leave the West Bank, partly
to buy yet more splendid military equipment to offset the loss of
security from handing over control of the Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The grand total may be $70 billion or even more, of which
America's share could be in the order of $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers at this stage are plucked from the sky. But given
that this is an election year in America, the potential for
grandstanding is endless. Campaigning politicians are bound to say
that this is money for a Clinton legacy, and that it would be far
better spent on health care.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, the chances are that if the negotiators were to
reach a deal that was accepted in Israel and Palestine, Congress
would approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Congressmen are being disingenuous in claiming to be out of the
loop. Although the negotiations are secret, both the National
Security Council and Israel's ambassador have been busy briefing
congressmen, to prepare the ground should there be a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Clinton will be out of office by the time any bill is
presented to Congress _ which should mean a Congress less strongly
influenced by anti-Clintonian sentiments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONVENTIONS-MARKETING     07-24 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTIONS-MARKETING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: MicroBatch lovers.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a bigger scale, companies like Philip Morris, Motorola,
McDonald's and Microsoft have donated money or products, or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the opportunity to showcase our technology,'' said
Norm Sandler, head of government relations for Motorola, which has
supplied conventions since 1952 and will play host at a party to
honor the House speaker, Dennis Hastert, the Illinois Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris gave $250,000 to the Philadelphia host committee,
but the Los Angeles committee does not accept tobacco
contributions. In Philadelphia, where the company will ``sponsor''
a downtown street to be temporarily renamed for the company, it
will join other corporations in giving parties for politicians and
delegates and it is giving away lots of food-related products.
Besides the animal-shaped macaroni, it plans to stock hospitality
suites and delegate ``goody bags'' with Altoids mints, Toblerone
chocolates, Maxwell House coffee, Miller Beer and Philadelphia
cream cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are in a business that has some controversial
aspects,'' said Peggy Roberts, the company's director of
communications, ``it is important to our shareholders and employees
that we try and build relationships in venues that are important to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when civic fund-raisers approach corporations, the
pitch is often more about business than politics. After all, if a
company wants political access, some say, it would be better off
giving directly to the parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to sell it as a marketing experience and not as a
political contribution,'' said Eli Broad, chief executive of
SunAmerica and co-chairman of the L.A. 2000 Host Committee. Broad
gave $1 million to the effort, along with $1 million from
SunAmerica's parent company, AIG.
</P>
<P>
   Each city has its own reason for seeking the spotlight. For
Philadelphia, it is an opportunity to show off a spiffed-up
downtown and a new convention center, and to promote itself as a
place to visit, do business and live. Los Angeles hopes the
convention will erase memories of earthquakes, urban rioting and
the O.J. Simpson trial and show the world that the city actually
does have a downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had fires, rains and floods, everything but locusts,''
said Noelia Rodriguez, chief executive of the host committee. ``Now
we've turned the city around and we believe it's our moment to
shine.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Buchholz, president of Philadelphia 2000, added, ``Getting
this convention is like a seal of approval for Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the motive of civic pride is money. The Federal Reserve
Bank of Chicago estimated in a study there would be a direct
financial benefit to Chicago of $132 million from the 1996
Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing is to get people to come to your city in the
first place,'' said Geoffry J.D. Hewings, a University of Illinois
professor and the study's author. ``Hopefully, they will be
attracted to it and will come back. And there is a lot of ego
associated with these conventions. Lots of people enjoy the
nonfinancial benefits of being close to power.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the benefits are overrated and risks underplayed.
Many cities already have a thriving hotel business in August that
must be subtracted from any convention revenues. Besides, it is
hard to imagine cities like Philadelphia or Los Angeles needing to
raise millions of dollars to market themselves. And a backlash is
possible if baton-wielding police crack down on unruly
demonstrators. Cities can have their images tarnished, as Seattle
found after the riots at the World Trade Organization meeting in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the convention make people say, `Gee, I didn't know Los
Angeles was there, maybe I'll go visit?''' said Andrew Zimbalist,
an economics professor at Smith College. ``If you have a lame
convention and fairly soporific candidates, it seems unlikely you
would say, `Boy, let's go see where Al Gore got nominated.'''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Noll, an economics professor at Stanford University added,
``It seems crazy for anyone to claim that the image of New York or
San Francisco or Chicago hinges on getting any of these kinds of
events.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities that have been convention hosts, or came close, disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The event was fabulous for the city,'' said Susan Golding,
mayor of San Diego, which hosted the 1996 Republican convention.
``It brings a great deal of public attention and a general feeling
that if you can handle a national political convention, well, you
can handle just about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Sainz, former Republican convention planner and now head of
the San Diego convention center, said cities craved the visibility
more than the dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When reporters get bored with the conventions, as they do,
they will write stories about the city,'' he said. ``Larry King
going live with the bay and the skyline and sitting there in a
short-sleeved shirt in cool August breezes _ that does a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis was a finalist for the 2000 Republican convention,
and Michael McDaniel, chairman of the state Republican party, said
the city had benefited anyway. ``We've had bookings in Indianapolis
for events just as a result of being a finalist,'' he said. ``They
thought they should check us out for conventions. There is no way
to put a price tag on that ripple effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the perceived benefits, raising money isn't easy.
In the days before the 1996 San Diego convention, the city had
fallen about $5 million short, causing a worried Dole campaign to
tap its donor list. In Philadelphia, while the host committee
boasts of raising more than $40 million, only about $10 million of
that is cash from corporations.
</P>
<P>
   And fund-raising problems in Los Angeles have been the stuff of
local headlines. Only two months before the convention was to
begin, the host committee was still around $11 million short. The
city contributed $4 million, and President Clinton came to Los
Angeles to raise money, as well as lending his top fund-raiser,
Terry McAuliffe, to twist arms. As of early July, the city was
still $4 million short.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, when Rodriguez, head of the host committee, was
interviewed earlier this month, she said Mayor Richard Riordan was
in her office. What was he doing there? He was on the phone, she
said, asking donors for money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
