   NY-CONVICTIONS-OVERTURN (New York) _ It is difficult to overturn
a conviction in New York, even in the face of powerful new
evidence, as the story of David Lemus and Olmado Hidalgo reveals.
Trial judges and state appeals courts have always been reluctant to
reverse a jury's verdict, and in 1996, Congress sharply limited the
rights of defendants to take their appeals to federal court. By
Jane Fritsch and David Rohde. (Scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
