<HEADLINE>
WILL AMERICA BANKROLL A CAMP DAVID DEAL?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 550-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A ghost at Camp David has been America's Congress.
This week, as musing turned to the monetary rewards for peace, the
speaker of the House of Representatives, Dennis Hastert, wrote to
President Bill Clinton, tartly reminding him that Congress is the
sole authority for spending money.
</P>
