<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1757 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-NYT &LR;      07-24 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENCIES UNDERESTIMATING FLIGHT DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1988, the two government agencies that track airline
delays have underestimated the amount of time lost by passengers by
a total of 247 years, according to a study scheduled for release
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Department of Transportation's inspector
general found that the major airlines increased their scheduled
flight times on hundreds of routes over the last decade in order to
improve their on-time statistics. As a result, 130 million minutes
of extra travel time was tacked on to airline schedules between
1988 and 1999, the study found, even before counting delays, which
have soared during the corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
   The report was requested last summer by Sen. Richard Shelby, a
Republican from Alabama who is chairman of the appropriations
subcommittee on transportation, after the country suffered the
worst airline delays in history. This summer has turned out to be
even worse. The report is sure to fuel the growing debate about an
air system that many say is approaching gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby asked the inspector general to examine what causes flight
delays and cancellations, a question often asked by tens of
thousands of frustrated travelers. But the report, which is
scheduled to be released at a hearing of his subcommittee Tuesday,
concluded that the government does not collect enough information
about the causes of delays to answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   It also found that the conflicting ways that the Federal
Aviation Administration and the Department of Transportation define
delays has made it impossible for the government and the airlines
to agree on what causes them.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines blame the FAA and weather for most delays, while
the FAA cites weather and the high number of flights as the main
culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be a surprise that they are having a hard time
coming up with what the solutions are when they can't figure out
what the causes are,'' Shelby said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has acknowledged the problem and is in the process of
coming up with a new method to more accurately measure delays and
their causes. In addition, the latest congressional appropriation
bill ordered the Transportation Department to compel the airlines
to disclose more accurate information about why planes are late and
get canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the FAA says a plane is delayed if it takes off 15
minutes or more after the pilot radios a request to the tower to
taxi out to the runway. If the plane sits at the gate for an hour
before asking for clearance to taxi, it is not considered late.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Transportation Department counts a plane
as delayed if it leaves or arrives at the gate more than 15 minutes
after its scheduled departure or arrival time. If the plane sits on
the tarmac for an hour but arrives at its scheduled time, it is not
considered late.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines say that they have stretched their schedules in order
to account for the inefficiency of the country's aging air traffic
control system, and to make their schedules more predictable for
passengers. And they do not hide the practice. United Airlines,
which has been plagued by delays, recently announced that it was
adding an average of four minutes to each of its 2,400 daily
flights.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the report found that airline delays last year would have
been 25 percent higher, as calculated by the Transportation
Department, if the airlines had kept the scheduled flight times
they used in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the airlines' efforts to make planes appear on time,
delays increased 11 percent between 1995 and 1999, according to the
FAA. About 83 percent of those delays were on the ground, the
report found, up from 60 percent in 1996. Ground delays of an hour
or more have also become more frequent, increasing 130 percent in
the last five years, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   Cancellations have also soared during the period, increasing 68
percent. Certain routes, such as Newark to Chicago, San Francisco
to Los Angeles and Washington to Boston, had cancellation rates
that were more than five times higher than the national average of
2.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without good causal data,'' the report concluded, ``it is
unlikely that the current debate within the aviation community will
end, nor the increasing number of flight delays and
cancellations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
