u a BC-TEEN25-COX     07-24 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    14-year-old charged in girl's death
 &HT;    By Colleen Mastony
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ A 14-year-old boy has been charged with
vehicular homicide in connection with the death of a 12-year-old
girl who was a passenger in the car he was driving at high speed in
May when it crashed and landed in a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Singh faces a ``definite possibility'' of being tried as
an adult and a maximum 15-year prison sentence if he is convicted,
Assistant State Attorney Tom Bakkedahl said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Singh turned himself in to Port St. Lucie police late Monday
afternoon. He is taken to the St. Lucie Regional Juvenile Detention
Center in Fort Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Kaily Pittman was killed in the May 14 crash, and Jeanna
Collins, 15, and her sister, Carly Ann, 12, were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Singh was driving his parents' car without their knowledge,
according to police. When police tried to pull the car over about 2
a.m., Singh sped away, making a series of high-speed turns in a
residential neighborhood, at times traveling up to 80 mph, and
eventually failed to see that the road ended in a T-shaped
intersection at Twylite Terrace and Ferris Drive. Singh drove
through a vacant lot and crashed into a drainage ditch. The car
flipped over a chain-link fence and crashed in a backyard pool,
according to police reports.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol was not a factor in the crash, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Singh told investigators he tried to stop for police but that he
couldn't find the brakes and when he did hit them, they didn't
work. Police later tested the car's brakes and found that they were
working normally.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Monday that Jeanna and Carly Ann Collins yelled at
Singh to stop the car but he said he was going to try to lose the
police.
</P>
<P>
   When Jeanna tried to grab the keys out of the ignition, Singh
punched her twice ``into a state of unconsciousness,'' according to
the investigation report.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Kaily was wearing only her lap belt, and that she
had put the shoulder strap of her seat belt behind her when she got
into the car. She died of internal injuries caused by the intense
pressure exerted by the seat belt's lap strap during the crash,
according to Associate Medical Examiner Charles Diggs.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanna Collins suffered a broken back which required 15 hours of
surgery, and recovery in a plastic body cast, according to officer
Darin Howie, and Carly Ann Collins suffered from bruised ribs and
lungs. Both girls are out of the hospital. Singh suffered two
fractured ankles and some broken bones in his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
