<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKINAWA-SUMMIT-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
G8 EXPECTATIONS: CAN OKINAWA SUMMIT LIVE UP TO ITS BILLING?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Okinawa G8 summit, July 21-23)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 825-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This year's summit of the rich world's leaders
suffers no shortage of symbolism. It marks the 25th anniversary of
the first such summit; the first of the new millennium; and
President Bill Clinton's eighth and last.
</P>
<P>
   It is taking place between July 21 and 23 on the Japanese island
of Okinawa, home to 26,000 American troops and site of a vicious
battle in the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   Keen as it is to flex its muscles on the international economic
stage, Japan is determined to make the summit a big deal. The goal,
say the Japanese hosts modestly, is to set the stage for ``greater
prosperity,'' ``peace of mind'' and ``world stability'' in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is less imposing. Since all the world's big
economies, except Japan's, are in relatively good shape, there is
no impetus for the economic navel-gazing and criticism that has
long characterized these get-togethers _ especially since, as
hosts, the Japanese will be determined to deflect talk away from
their own, still shaky, economic performance.
</P>
<P>
   So there is little chance of big breakthroughs on big
international controversies. The chance of an announcement of a big
new trade round, for instance, is close to zero.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the summiteers will try to divert attention away from
their differences by talking grandly about development. The hot new
topic will be the ``global digital divide.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be much speculation about the potential for
information technology to accelerate development, and much
hand-wringing that so many poor countries are not wired.
</P>
<P>
   Of an estimated 332 million Internet users, fewer than 1 percent
live in Africa. Only about 2.7 million of Africa's more than 600
million people use the Internet, and most of those are in South
Africa. That compares with an average in North America and Europe
of one user for every four people.
</P>
<P>
   Less obvious is how to bridge this divide. Mimicking its efforts
to increase computer- and Internet-access among poor Americans, the
Clinton administration is keen on partnerships with the private
sector. So several business stars, including John Chambers of Cisco
Systems and Nobuyuki Idei of Sony, were invited to the pre-summit
discussion in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, much of the burden of implementing fine-sounding
ideas will fall on multilateral institutions, so the heads of the
United Nations Development Program and the World Bank were also
invited.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's approach to the divide, as so often in development, is
to throw money at it. It has announced a $15 billion aid package
over five years, although it is unclear whether this is new money,
or what exactly it will be spent on.
</P>
<P>
   Doubtless, the gathering will yield more headline-grabbing
initiatives. There is, for instance, to be an ``Okinawa Charter''
on information technology. But there are few signs that anybody
knows how best to address the divide, or even whether information
technology is the right place to concentrate development efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Those uncertainties do not plague the summiteers' two other
development priorities: education and health.
</P>
<P>
   The heads of government will reaffirm their determination to
reach the international goal of universal primary education by
2015. They will stress the importance of educating girls. Some
60-70 percent of the more than 100 million children who are not in
school are girls.
</P>
<P>
   On health, there will be more talk about tackling the spread of
infectious diseases, especially AIDS. Specific targets for reducing
the number of young AIDS victims over the next decade by, say, 25
percent, are likely.
</P>
<P>
   Here again, Japan has already pledged $3 billion to fight
infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   These deadlines and promises should all be taken with a pinch of
salt. After all, it was only a year ago that the summit in Cologne
announced, with great fanfare, a package of enhanced debt relief
for the poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   So far only nine countries have received relief, worth about $15
billion in total.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the enhanced Heavily Indebted Poor Country (HIPC)
program argue that the process is too slow, and that conditions
attached to debt relief are still too burdensome. Neither argument
is entirely convincing. Many of the countries potentially eligible
for debt relief are deeply corrupt or at war.
</P>
<P>
   More disturbing is the fact that some rich countries, notably
the United States, have not yet made good on their commitments to
finance debt relief. Assistance for Honduras and Bolivia has
already been held up for lack of American contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the exaggerated expectations, the summit's focus on debt
relief has expanded and accelerated the process. The same could be
true of this year's areas of concern.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is still a nagging suspicion that the global
digital divide is the wrong priority for the world's richest
countries.
</P>
<P>
   If they really wanted to help the poorest, the summiteers would
do far better to focus on opening up their markets. But sadly,
trade liberalization costs political capital. Grand words come
cheap. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
