<SLUG> BC-BOEING-FARNBOROUGH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE BIG ORDERS, BOEING REMAINS IN AIRBUS SHADOW AT AIR SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Boeing Co. announced orders at the Farnborough
International air show Monday for more than 110 new jets worth
about $12 billion at list prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the Seattle-based aerospace giant still found itself being
elbowed out of the spotlight on the world aerospace stage by Airbus
and its A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   The super jumbo is intended to break Boeing's 30-year monopoly
that it has enjoyed with its flagship 747, and talk of the A3XX is
dominating this year's air show.
</P>
<P>
   With a standing-room-only crowd of reporters and photographers
pressing in, Airbus signed the first two customers for the A3XX _
Emirates and Air France _ and all but guaranteed it would launch
the 555-seat jet by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Noel Forgeard, chief executive officer of Airbus, said at a news
conference that the European airplane maker would match Boeing in
new orders this year, even though Airbus is now behind. He said
Airbus would announce orders for as many as 200 planes at the
Farnborough show this week and end the year with more than 500.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the orders announced Monday by Airbus were firm, and
a spokesman said they will not be added to this year's Airbus
totals until they are firm.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the air show, Boeing had 326 firm orders to 239 for
Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's orders Monday also are not completely in the bag,
though they are a lot closer to being firm than those announced by
its archrival.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing orders were for the 777, including two new ultra long
range versions known as the 777-300X and 777-200X, and for the next
generation 737, which is having a strong sales year.
</P>
<P>
   All but six of the Boeing orders were by leasing giants GE
Capital Aviation Services and International Lease Finance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital said it had signed an agreement to buy up to 143
Boeing jetliners, which includes options.
</P>
<P>
   President Henry Hubschman said GE Capital will buy 10 of the
777X jets, which were launched earlier this year. In addition, GE
Capital will buy five of the current model 777-200ER.
</P>
<P>
   The 777-200ER has an average list price of about $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   The leasing company did not specify the mix of the 10 777X jets
that it will order. The 777-300X has an average list price of about
$215 million, and the 777-200X an average list price of about $190
million.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital also took options and purchase rights for 10 more
777X jets and seven 777-200ER jets.
</P>
<P>
   Its biggest order was for 45 of the next generation 737s. And it
exercised options for 14 more of the popular twin jets.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the model, the average list price of a next
generation 737 can range from about $42 million up to about $60
million.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital took options for another 52 next generation 737s.
</P>
<P>
   The 74 firm orders and exercised options are worth about $5.5
billion at list prices, Boeing said.
</P>
<P>
   Hubschman said a firm agreement to buy the 74 jets from Boeing
should be completed within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate any problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The big order with Boeing, he said, ``fills out our order book
for several years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   International Lease said it will buy up to 40 Boeing jetliners,
including eight of the 777X jets and 25 of the 777-200ER models.
</P>
<P>
   Delivery is scheduled from 2002 through 2009.
</P>
<P>
   It also plans to order seven next generation 737s, to be
delivered between 2003 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The order is worth nearly $7 billion at list prices.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Udvar-Hazy, president and chief executive officer of
International Lease, said he expects to sign a firm agreement with
Boeing for the 40 planes in the next 45 to 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mulally, president of Boeing commercial airplanes, said the
large 777 order from GE Capital and International Lease is further
evidence that Asia, a significant market for that plane, has
recovered from its economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   The new long range 777X jets are primarily targeted for Asian
airlines that need to fly 300 or more passengers up to 10,000 miles
nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   One other 777X order was announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   All Nippon Airways said is will buy six of the 777-300X jets.
Four of those are conversions from a previous 777 order.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the blockbuster order day, Boeing found itself
overshadowed by Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Following a morning news conference during which he said Airbus
has proved it is Boeing's equal, Forgeard could not wait to get
back to the Airbus press chalet for the first A3XX order
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Emirates, the flag carrier of the United Arab Emirates, became
the first airline to officially commit to the A3XX project, which
has been years in the making and is still not officially launched.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, which plans to use the A3XX on trunk routes from
its Dubai hub, including service to London, the Asia-Pacific region
and North America, said it will order seven A3XXs and took options
for an additional five.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new airliner offers a level of comfort and space never
seen before in the airline industry,'' Emirates Chairman Sheik
Ahmed bin Saeed Al Maktoum said as he signed the memorandum of
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard said any orders for the A3XX can't be made firm until
the plane is officially launched.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven planes ordered by Emirates, five are passenger
versions and two will be freighters.
</P>
<P>
   The Emirates chairman put the value of the order at $1.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger version of the A3XX has an average list price of
about $230 million. The launch customers are believed to be getting
discounts of as much as 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Deliveries of the passenger versions will begin in February
2006, with the freighters to follow in the spring 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman said Emirates could use the aircraft today on some
routes, including London and Bangkok. The airline is experiencing
rapid growth and would double the number of passengers it carries
over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   After the Emirates announcement, Air France said it signed a
letter of intent for 10 A3XXs, which it plans to use initially on
five routes, including those from Paris to New York, Montreal and
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Cyril Spinetta, Air France's president, said the aircraft
would enter service on five of the airline's busiest
intercontinental routes and should cut costs by between 15 and 20
per cent.
</P>
<P>
   A firm order will depend on capacity at some airports, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus also announced that CIT Aerospace, an operating unit of
the CIT Group, has signed a letter of intent to buy 35 single-aisle
Airbus jets and 15 of the 330 model widebody planes.
</P>
<P>
   Air France and Emirates were two of nine customers that
expressed an initial interest earlier this year in a total of 52 of
the planes. Three of the possible customers have not been
identified by Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines, Qantas, Virgin Atlantic and leasing company
International Lease Finance Corporation have also said they are
interested in the super jumbo.
</P>
<P>
   At the morning news conference, Forgeard said he was confident
Airbus would secure enough orders _ probably about 50 _ to launch
the A3XX by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard said Airbus plans to turn disclosed letters of intent
for 22 of the 52 A3XX into memos of understanding at this week's
air show.
</P>
<P>
   While Airbus was signing up customers for its A3XX, Boeing was
sharing its latest market forecast with reporters. It questions the
need for very many planes the size of the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing believes the market is only about 87 planes the size of
the A3XX over the next 10 years, said Randy Baseler, Boeing's vice
president of marketing for commercial aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Baseler said Boeing sees the dominant part of the market being
served by intermediate-sized, twin-aisle aircraft, particularly in
the next three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   The world fleet is projected to more than double, to 31,755
aircraft in the next 20 years, from about 13,670 in 1999, Baseler
said.
</P>
<P>
   That increase means airlines will need 22,300 new airplanes by
2019, worth about $1.5 trillion, Baseler said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Boeing expanded its market forecast to
include aviation services (including maintenance, training and
updates for planes), an area that Boeing views as increasingly
important in its business plans.
</P>
<P>
   The total market, including planes and services, will be worth
more than $4 trillion over the next 20 years, Baseler said.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial services market will be worth more than $2.6
trillion of that amount, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
