<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-FUGITIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED PHILADELPHIA KILLER IS ORDERED EXTRADITED TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The prime minister of France has ordered the extradition to the
United States of Ira S. Einhorn, once a charismatic leader of
Philadelphia's counterculture who was convicted in absentia of
murdering his girlfriend 22 years ago, legal authorities announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given his track record, I am still concerned that he is going
to flee,'' the Philadelphia district attorney, Lynne Abraham, said.
With a final legal challenge still possible, she noted that Einhorn
has been a fugitive for 20 years and has vowed never to return to
his home city where he had been celebrated as a leading hippie
advocate of peace, mysticism and environmentalism.
</P>
<P>
   The extradition was ordered by French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin, said Abraham, who had no estimate on when American
authorities hoped to regain custody of Einhorn, now 60. He has been
fighting extradition since he was discovered three years ago, after
an extensive search across Europe, living under an alias in
Champagne-Mouton in the Bordeaux region of France.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn jumped $40,000 bail and disappeared as he was about to
go on trial in the 1977 killing of Holly Maddux, a Bryn Mawr
College alumna who had been his lover. Police found Maddux's body
stuffed in a steamer trunk in Einhorn's apartment 18 months after
she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn's transition from counterculture guru to accused
murderer caused a sensation in Philadelphia. He denied committing
the murder, saying the Central Intelligence Agency, KGB or other
``large intelligence agencies'' sought to frame him because he had
uncovered classified mind-control experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn has 60 days to appeal with the Council of State,
France's highest administrative tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after lengthy legal maneuvering, the French Court of
Appeals ruled that Einhorn could be extradited to the United States
provided that he would be granted a new trial and would not face
the death penalty. The court decided to reverse its earlier order
protecting Einhorn after Pennsylvania passed a law in 1998 granting
people convicted in absentia the right to a new trial if they
returned and demanded one.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn's lawyer, Theodore Simon, said Monday there was no way
to guarantee a retrial. The 1998 law, he said, was clearly
unconstitutional because it would violate the separation of powers
in having a state legislature attempt to force a retrial on the
court system.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn has been free since he was arrested three years ago. He
was required to report weekly to authorities in France where he
lived in a remote millhouse with his Swedish-born wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
