<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1765 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-LOTTO25-COX     07-24 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-LOTTO25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf club group hits green with winning Lotto ticket
 &HT;    By Molly Hennessy-Fiske
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Russ Kelly had a new house he was struggling
to pay for as a golf club manager. Cathy Wilson dreamed of owning
her own home, but could barely scrape together gas money to get to
work at the club Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Kelly is planning a trip to Australia, Wilson
may get that house after all, and everybody in town knows why: Bent
Pine Golf Club is the ``home'' of the $65 million jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew,'' Robin Kelly, 30, said of the hours after
staff discovered the office pool won the lottery Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we could even tell them,'' Russ Kelly, 34, said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that they live in a small town, or even in the same
part of town. The group is diverse, ranging in age from 19 to
50-something. Many in the pool of 26 are young (Kelly pegs the
average age at 28), some just hired a few months ago. All but one,
a florist who contracts with the club, work there, but with so many
people moving in different circles, Kelly said, word got around.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the pats on the back at restaurants, 29 phone messages
in a morning, and a pressing need to organize. Since a club
dishwasher spotted the winning numbers _ 9-10-14-26-34-42 _ in a
newspaper and called the clubhouse early Sunday, the group has met
twice to discuss their strategy. They are dividing the money
roughly evenly _ about $2.5 million apiece _ with slight variation
depending on how long individuals paid in. The pool has been going
for five years, and when Joanne Dowling purchased the winning
ticket Thursday afternoon, it was with $2 from each player.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the Bent Pine group has 80 days to claim their winnings
as a lump sum (about $32.1 million, according to a lottery
spokesman), 180 days if they choose a 30-year series of payments.
Kelly, the unofficial spokesman for the group, said that after
meeting Monday afternoon and trooping over to a local bank to place
the unsigned ticket in a safe deposit box, they remain undecided.
According to current state lottery figures, 75 percent of recent
winners chose the lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Kelly said, the group will put the money in a trust
fund. Then those who gathered Monday with stories of the cars and
boats they spotted on the lots that morning are on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vero resident H. Roy Kaplan, author of ``Lottery Winners:
How They Won and How Winning Changed Their Lives,'' said pools can
often lead to infighting among winners. But compared to those he
studied in the 1970s and 1980s, Kaplan said recent winners benefit
from more accessible financial counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today people are more savvy and you've got the Internet,''
Kaplan said during an interview from his Tampa office. ``Certainly
everyone talks about investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the group, Russ Kelly said he will be back at
work this week. The state's newest millionaires will be washing
dishes and sorting files until they charter that bus north to
redeem their ticket in Tallahassee next week. And Kaplan said
things could stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even large winners, they look for something to do, and work is
the glue that binds us to society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly admits the workplace atmosphere may have to change with
club staff and guests suddenly on equal financial footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely a concern,'' he said, ``I mean, do you want
millionaires working for you?''
</P>
<P>
   For now, co-workers are satisfied with collective
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do, we vote,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Schlitt is looking into college. Siblings Heather and
Nathan Kovatch are spreading the word to their family. Wilson is
looking for a home her kids would like, and the Kellys are planning
a cookout _ after an appearance on Good Morning America. In the
end, six little numbers were more of a big relief than a big win.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kelly: ``At least now we can afford to live where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
