<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BACH-CHORAL-REVIEW-NY     07-24 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACH-CHORAL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: A SUMMER TRIBUTE TO BACH IN SONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New England)   By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Conn. _ Much of the music world heads for the hills of
New England during the summer, and so, in a Bach year, does Bach.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he is a regular visitor in concerts of the New England
Bach Festival at Marlboro, Vt., among others. But the activity has
stepped up markedly this year, the 250th anniversary of the
composer's death, with events like the ``Bach 2K'' concerts this
weekend at the Norfolk Chamber Music Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The first concert here, on Friday, offered the ``Brandenburg''
Concertos, with some performers (the Tokyo String Quartet) more
surprising in this repertory than others (like the harpsichordist
Kenneth Cooper). But alas, that enticing prospect conflicted with a
Marlboro concert offering cantatas, as the Saturday concert here
also did.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Bach Festival, in its 32nd year, was founded by
Blanche Moyse, herself a venerable institution: a founder of the
Marlboro Festival 50 years ago and a longtime Bach adept. On Friday
she conducted the Blanche Moyse Chorale and the festival orchestra
in three cantatas at the Persons Auditorium of Marlboro College.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, she conducted when needed. In small-scale movements,
involving a singer and continuo with, perhaps, an obbligato player,
she sat and beamed on the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as frail as she looked, there was no lack of vitality in the
performances. In the delightful duet ``Nun verschwinden alle
Plagen'' (``Now all torments vanish'') from Cantata No. 32,
``Liebster Jesu, Mein Verlangen'' (``Dearest Jesus, My Desire''),
her quick clip nearly outstripped the abilities of her talented
fiddlers.
</P>
<P>
   The rich mix of cantatas ranged from the unfamiliar No. 60, ``O
Ewigkeit, Du Donnerwort'' (``Eternity, Thou Thunderous Word''),
with its inventive use of duets, to the famous No. 147, ``Herz und
Mund und Tat und Leben'' (``Heart and Lips and Deed and Conduct''),
with the ``Jesu, Joy of Man's Desiring'' chorale descending twice.
(Bach knew a good thing when he found it.) In addition, Steven Paul
Spears, a tenor, sang the ``Benedictus'' from Bach's Mass in B
minor, a bonus enhanced by the flute playing of Paula Robison.
</P>
<P>
   Hyunah Yu, a soprano, was the most impressive of the vocal
soloists, with clear, secure tone. Randall Scarlata, a fine
baritone, lacked the bass notes occasionally needed.
</P>
<P>
   Moyse's chorus, 22 strong, achieved what good intentions could.
The basic sonority is that of so many amateur groups: fuzzy and
unfocused, with little core or bite.
</P>
<P>
   The Norfolk concert on Saturday avoided any such problem by
having the four vocal soloists sing the choruses. There being only
two choral movements, opening and closing Cantata No. 8, ``Liebster
Gott, Wenn Werd Ich Sterben'' (``Dearest God, When Will I Die?''),
this practice may well have been merely an economy of chamber
scale.
</P>
<P>
   But it also carries the cachet of advanced musicological
thinking; Joshua Rifkin and others maintain that Bach probably had
only one voice per part in most of his own choral performances. In
any case, it worked well enough here: remarkably so in view of the
weakness of individual voices (including a veritable caricature of
a countertenor), as revealed in solo numbers.
</P>
<P>
   By far the finest vocalist was Richard Lalli, a baritone, who
also contributed the solo Cantata No. 82, ``Ich Habe Genug'' (``I
Have Enough''). His approach seemed a bit dry and reserved at times
in this warmest of outpourings, and the addition of ornaments in
the repeat of the central aria ruffled the inherent serenity of
this lullaby, but Lalli won the listener over in the end, rejoicing
with Bach and the text at the prospect of death.
</P>
<P>
   The Norfolk concerts were dedicated to the memory of Ronald
Roseman, an oboist and Bach specialist who worked at the festival
for more than a quarter of a century before his death in February.
Roseman took a hand in programming this death-haunted concert, Joan
Panetti, the festival's director, said from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, he quickly proposed ``Ich Habe Genug,'' as
well he might have, with its prominent oboe solos in the first and
last movements. As it was, Randall Wolfgang played them ably, and
Jennifer Grim was a deft, smooth flute soloist in ``Liebster
Gott.''
</P>
<P>
   The extras here were highly variable. David Connell, an
organist, and a brass quintet offered three chorales to start, all
well and good.
</P>
<P>
   Less to the point, the guitar virtuoso Eliot Fisk opened the
second half with a lute prelude and his arrangement of the Chaconne
from Bach's D minor Violin Partita. If the steady tread and the
cumulative magnificence of that great movement can be achieved on
the guitar, they were not apparent here.
</P>
<P>
   Another brass quintet ( this one sorely undercut by trombone
playing woefully out of tune) performed a movement from ``The Art
of Fugue'' and another chorale. And the sour notes extended to
Panetti's introduction, with recourse to the hoary myths of these
as last works and of dictation by the composer from his deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the Bach year should be an occasion to dispel myths once
and for all and set the record straight. Happily, a tool is readily
at hand: Christoph Wolff's magisterial new biography, ``Johann
Sebastian Bach: The Learned Musician.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
