</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MOSCOW-THEATER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WILY DIRECTOR ENERGIZES RUSSIAN THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT10  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a city that takes theater very seriously, Kama
Ginkas was arguably the most successful director of the season that
just ended. He certainly was the busiest.
</P>
<P>
   Five of his plays were staged through the year, each one in its
own way a hit. His ``Pushkin.Duel.Death'' was considered the best
original work to come out of last year's nationwide Pushkin
extravaganza. This spring he picked up a Golden Mask prize for `'A
Room of Laughter,'' a popular one-act play that he directed for
Oleg Tabakov's studio. And the premiere last fall of `'The Black
Monk,'' a striking dramatization of Chekhov's mystical short story,
dazzled even Moscow's jaded critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is that Ginkas has hit his peak,'' said John
Freedman, an American scholar and critic of the Russian theater.
``He is racing to keep up with his abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   By early summer Ginkas, 59, was rehearsing another play, based
on Oscar Wilde's ``Happy Prince.'' Watching Ginkas in rehearsal is
like watching his actors perform: the process begins and ends with
an intensity that radiates both heat and clarity. No detail, no
object, no movement is too small to escape his attention; every
prop, every gesture, takes on meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your fingers!'' he shouted during one rehearsal, pointing
accusingly to an actress' right hand. ``Your fingers are moving.
That makes it a mise en scene, a fact. It could mean many things.
It could mean you are bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Boredom is not something Ginkas usually worries about. His plays
are not the kind that let the audience off the hook. For one thing,
audience and actors are typically packed into small spaces. In
``The Black Monk,'' the stage is put on the theater's upper
balcony, with the audience wrapped around three sides. Two of his
other plays are staged in a rehearsal room, with the audience
acting as a prop. ``A Room of Laughter'' takes place on the main
stage, but in a box.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly it is a very human drama that keeps the audience's
attention riveted as Ginkas works his way in and around the
emotionally dense landscape of his characters, some of them drawn
from masterpieces of Russian literature and moments of Russian
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plays arouse catharsis, shock, even hysteria, but there are
viewers who would rather not be touched,'' he said. ``I can't say
that I am speaking to the whole of humanity, or even all of Russia,
or Moscow, but I am speaking to the audience of those people for
whom these things are interesting.'' Whether it is the tortured
tragedy of the Dostoyevskian character of Katerina Ivanovna in
``K.I. From Crime,'' or the complex mesh of grand and petty motives
that drove Russia's greatest poet to his death in
``Pushkin.Duel.Death,'' his plays ensnare the spectator the way a
spider's web catches a fly. In ``The Black Monk'' the audience is
left poised on the edge of a balcony, gazing into the blackness of
a theater that becomes the haunt of a mysterious creature who is
either a source of genius, of madness or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Ginkas, indifference is a catastrophe,'' says Anatoly
Smelyansky, a scholar of the Russian theater, who is head of the
Moscow Arts Theater school studio. ``He has been playing this game
for many years. It is always a bit of a game: some naturalism, some
aspect of real life, and characters that he stretches to their
limit. For all of this love of theatrics, jokes and games, he has a
taste for reality, for the raw stuff of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginkas' characters are intense but they are also nuanced, which
he says is one of the legacies he inherited from his first teacher,
the great Leningrad director Georgi Tovstonogov. ``He found humor
in tragic moments,'' Ginkas said. ``There was realism, but the
eccentricities were all inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Born Jewish in Lithuania on the eve of the Nazi occupation,
Ginkas was one of a handful of children who were saved from being
shipped off to Auschwitz. He is also a cultural survivor, one of
the few members of a generation of Soviet theater directors who
came of age just as the Khruschchev-era ``thaw'' was coming to an
end, and who managed to stick it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation started work at the end of the 1960s, at the end
of the thaw,'' he said. ``We were not shot; we were not sent into
exile, but we were battered by shrapnel. Many simply left the
profession and did something else. Many were so strongly poisoned
that they never worked to their potential. Those before us managed
to accomplish something during the `thaw,' before getting hit on
the head. We were like idiots. We rushed right out, stuck our necks
out, and wham _ we got hit before we even had a chance to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child Ginkas survived because his parents managed to hide
him in a Roman Catholic convent. As an individualist in the
Brezhnev era, he also lay low, ducking the radar of Soviet cultural
orthodoxy. For a time, he was a director of a state theater in
Krasnoyarsk in Siberia, but even there his free spirit was more
than the authorities could tolerate. He returned to Leningrad,
where he staged shows in private apartments and built a reputation
as a theatrical dissident.
</P>
<P>
   At the first glimmering of cultural liberalization in the early
1980s, he was lured to Moscow, where he was invited to the Moscow
Art Theater and Mossoviet, before settling at the Young Spectators
Theater where his wife, Genrietta Yanovskaya, was made artistic
director.
</P>
<P>
   As a student of Tovstonogov, Ginkas is firmly fixed in the great
Russian tradition of psychological theater, which began with
Konstantin Stanislavsky and Vsevolod Meyerhold. Their photographs _
together with portraits of Joseph Brodsky and Andrei Sakharov _
adorn the office at the Young Spectators Theater that he shares
with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanislavsky, Meyerhold, Vakhtangov, they were the titans,''
he said. ``Then there were the gods: Tovstonogov, Yuri Lyubimov''
(director of the Taganka Theater). ``The task of the gods was
different. The titans had to create the foundations, to create
heaven and earth from the cosmos. Our generation is the heroes: our
job is to conserve and refine, make it more usable, combine the
uncombinable.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending several years abroad, mostly in Helsinki, Ginkas
returned to Moscow in 1994 with a production of ``K.I. From
Crime,'' a disturbing and moving play about a character in ``Crime
and Punishment.'' In 1997 it won a prize at France's theater
festival in Avignon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are watching what happens to a person,'' Ginkas explained.
``It is not clear whether she is insane or if the actress is
provoking the audience. There are circuslike movements, but she is
no clown. There is an element of the game, but it is nuanced and
paradoxical.''
</P>
<P>
   Having survived its long bout with Socialist Realism, Russian
theater is now emerging _ battered but not defeated _ from its
first decade of laissez-faire capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100 theaters in Moscow alone _ and another 400 in
the rest of the country _ Russian theater has survived, in large
part because Russians refuse to let it die. ``There were several
times when Russian theater should have fallen flat on its face, but
it has survived every crisis with flying colors,'' said Freedman,
who is the theater critic for the English-language Moscow Times.
``Russians cannot imagine themselves without theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginkas describes theater as one of Russia's few ``brand-name''
products. ``Theater is one of the few things we can still export,''
he said. ``Russian theater is like Sony. It is still the real
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
