<SLUG> BC-SENATE-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS PUSH PANEL CHAIRMAN ON HIS OWN MEDICARE DRUG BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Fla., Okla.)   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying the chairman of the Senate Finance Committee
appeared to be dragging his feet, Democrats urged him Monday to
take action on his own proposal to establish prescription drug
benefits under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the chairman, Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del., the
Democrats on the committee prodded him to convene the panel ``as
early as possible, perhaps before the August recess,'' to vote on
legislation adding drug benefits to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Roth unveiled his proposal on July 10. Democrats said they liked
many of its features, including benefits that would be uniform
throughout the country, fully integrated into the Medicare program
and administered by the government, not by private insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators, including Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the
assistant majority leader, gave Roth's proposal a cool reception,
saying they feared that the costs could explode after a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Roth is in a tight race for re-election, running against Gov.
Thomas Carper, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Roth had reaped favorable publicity with his
proposal two weeks ago. But now, they said, they see no evidence
that he will try to push it through the Senate or even through his
own committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny Flynn, a spokeswoman for Roth, said he was revising his
proposal and would describe the changes at a meeting of the
committee behind closed doors on Thursday. But, she said, the
committee will not formally take up the legislation or vote on it
before the recess, which begins at the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show that drug prices and the need for
prescription drug coverage are major concerns of many voters.
</P>
<P>
   James M. Jordan, political director of the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, which coordinates efforts to elect Democrats to
the Senate, said Roth's proposal was ``a cynical political move''
that had little chance of success in the Senate, now controlled by
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But several Democrats on the Finance Committee commended Roth's
effort, which would provide $40 billion over five years for drug
benefits. The Democrats said more money was needed and available,
now that the Congressional Budget Office has increased its estimate
of federal budget surpluses over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said: ``Sen. Roth deserved the kind of
commendation he received for his original proposal. It took
considerable political courage for him to break from the mantra
that this had to be done through private health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed last month by the House would give subsidies to
insurance companies to entice them to provide drug benefits to
people on Medicare _ an approach opposed by President Clinton and
by most Democrats in Congress, who say it is unlikely to work.
</P>
<P>
   Under Roth's proposal, beneficiaries could stay in the original
Medicare program, with existing premiums and benefits, or they
could enroll in a high-option plan, which would provide drug
benefits but would also charge more for certain services, including
home health care and skilled nursing care.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Graham said: ``I don't think you ought to
create a disincentive for people to elect prescription drugs by
forcing them, and them alone, to bear the additional costs. The
people likely to need prescription medicines are the very ones most
likely to be using home health care and skilled nursing homes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
