</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK VISITS THE GETTYSBURG BATTLEFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  THURMONT, Md. _ The Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, is known
back home for his love of military history. As chief of staff of
the Israeli army, he dazzled _ and disarmed _ parliamentary
committees with his knowledge of warriors from Alexander to
Napoleon. So with cabin fever intensifying at Camp David, Barak _
who was reported in the Israeli press to be in a gloomy mood and
confined to reading in his suite _ decided to take a break. He
requested a trip on Sunday to the Civil War battlefield at
Gettysburg.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In doing so, Barak was repeating a somber excursion arranged by
President Carter at his Camp David summit meeting for the Israeli
leader, Menachim Begin, and the Egyptian president, Anwar Sadat.
Carter later wrote in his memoirs that as the mediator between two
tough adversaries, he wanted to demonstrate the high cost of war.
</P>
<P>
   And what better place to do it than the site of one of the
deadliest battles in American history, where 51,000 men were killed
or wounded. To drive home the point that peace is preferable to
war, Carter led the two men to the spot known as High Water Mark on
Cemetery Ridge and personally explained what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Barak ended up at the same spot. He was accompanied by Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright. They traveled in a motorcade around
the battlefield, alighting at only two places: Round Top and High
Water Mark.
</P>
<P>
   There Barak learned the story of how Maj. Gen. George E.
Pickett's Confederate troops were shredded by the Union forces
under the command of Maj. Gen. George Gordon Meade.
</P>
<P>
   Pickett led a final assault _ known as Pickett's charge _ on the
Union lines. About 13,000 soldiers set off down Cemetery Ridge and
into a meadow with Pickett's units in the middle. About 350 of his
men reached the focal point of the attack _ the High Water Mark _
before being engulfed on three sides by Union forces.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of Barak's impressions of the military
strategy _ just a photograph of Barak examining a cannon.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat opted for a more sedate outing. He has been the
guest of Albright on several occasions at her smart Georgetown home
this year, and on Saturday, Albright invited Arafat to her Virginia
farm. Recently, Albright said that being hostess to Arafat, who for
so many years was a pariah in Washington, was one of the things she
least imagined doing as secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   But she enjoyed entertaining him at lunch during his Washington
visits and he liked to ``chill out'' in the informality of her
home, she said. In Virginia, the visit was really informal.
Albright and Arafat took a strenuous walk through the long grass of
her fields. A photograph showed Albright in casual white pants and
T-shirt and a blue baseball cap striding alongside the former
guerrilla leader dressed in his fatigues, trailed by a posse of
Palestinian bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   PASSION AND ATTRITION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The descriptions of the atmosphere at Camp David by the
presidential spokesman, Joe Lockhart, have been so clinical that
they almost defy belief. There has been little hint in his accounts
of temper, frustration or stubbornness. Lockhart seems fairly
precise in describing the president's stamina, however. Clinton has
gone to bed at 5 a.m. on each of the last few days he has been at
Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Uri Savir, an Israeli legislator who negotiated with the
Palestinians in secret over 1,100 days at the landmark Oslo talks,
said he was not surprised by the horrible hours. He describes peace
talks as a process of ``attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You work around the clock,'' he said. ``Generally there is a
combination of creativity and brinkmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Successful negotiators, Savir said, possess a combination of
passion and patience. And as the mediator-in-chief, Clinton had the
right psychological touch: the compassion to understand the
different personalities of Arafat and Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian likes to extend deadlines as far as possible;
the Israeli favors putting proposals on the table and cutting a
deal. Thus, it is not surprising that so far, the two adversaries
have not met face-to-face very much at Camp David, although they
did sit on either side of Clinton Monday night at dinner _ with
Chelsea on the other side of Barak.
</P>
<P>
   But the members of the three negotiating teams have seen each
other, day in and day out. The Americans, the Palestinians and the
Israelis have all known each other from painstaking negotiating
since the Oslo accords of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   So when Clinton announced last Wednesday night that the peace
talks were over, emotions took over. With motorcades in position
ready to drive down the mountain from Camp David, Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators began hugging and kissing each other.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHART'S DEADLINE
</P>
<P>
   The most frequent question now: when will the talks end? They
have gone far longer than most expectations. The Republican
Convention begins next Monday. Could Clinton let the summit meeting
cut into George W. Bush's crowning? Lockhart said Monday that Bush
had been gracious, saying that partisan politics should not
interfere with the work toward peace. But it was highly unlikely,
Lockhart suggested, that it would be useful to string out the talks
for another week. A rumor swept the elementary school that has
served as the press headquarters Monday afternoon that Clinton was
looking for a Wednesday wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart had another date in mind. ``There is an informal
deadline,'' he deadpanned. ``All parties want to be available to
watch Kathie Lee Gifford's last show on Friday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2110EDT &QL; 
