<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-24 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. selection process ensures fairness
</P>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ When one of his star athletes did not
qualify for the U.S. Olympic team because of injury a few years
back, gymnastics coach Bela Karolyi was asked how such a thing
would be handled in his homeland of communist Romania.
</P>
<P>
   How would the Olympic team be selected?
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi licked the tips of his fingers, clapped his hands and
started pointing at an imaginary row of gymnasts lined up before
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell them, `You, you, you, you, you and you,''' Karolyi
said, popping his finger at the phantom gymnasts. ```You're going.
You, you and you, you're staying.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of what happened in Sunday's Olympic Trials
200-meter final, you just might be thinking right about now,
``What's a little old-time Soviet-bloc selection politics among
friends?''
</P>
<P>
   USA Track &AMP; Field czar _ and we use the term czar loosely _
Craig Masback probably wishes he could indeed handpick the
200-meter Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   After Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene suffered a
double-whammy hammy in Sunday's highly hyped Trials finale, it was
Masback who looked most strained.
</P>
<P>
   After all the anticipation ended with Johnson and Greene
grasping at the backs of their legs, Masback put his frustration
about the flop bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, reality sucks,'' Masback said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you're John Capel, Floyd Heard or Coby Miller _
the athletes who did qualify in the 200 _ those are not exactly the
inspiring words you like to hear from the highest-ranking official
in track and field.
</P>
<P>
   Now, get out there and try not to embarrass us, guys! Go for the
bronze!
</P>
<P>
   Masback also likened the absence of what may be America's best
two sprinters in the 200 to a ``Shakespearean tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's no tragedy. It's the American way.
</P>
<P>
   In simplest terms, Johnson and Greene did not qualify in the 200
because they did not have what it took to do so.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reasons, their hamstrings cramped and strained. No
matter their stature, no matter their rankings, they could not make
it through the rounds unscathed. Capel, Heard and Miller did.
</P>
<P>
   Make excuses all you want _ the heat, the pressure, the hype,
the mere 1{ hours between semifinal and final races. Johnson even
fell back on the age-old copout: When in doubt, blame the media.
</P>
<P>
   But would anything be different in Sydney? The Trials are laid
out in the three-race, two-day format for a reason. That's how it's
done at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Under any other system in which the higher-ranking sprinters
could earn byes through the early rounds or not race at all, the
glittery stars might shine. But would medals?
</P>
<P>
   Racing only once or twice or getting handpicked for the Olympic
team does not offer the test of stamina and resilience that the
Trials do.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson in fact spoke some foreboding words to women's 200
sensation Marion Jones on the warmup track shortly after the
semifinal races Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who will participate in her first Olympic Games this
year, wondered to Johnson, ``Are they trying to kill us with the
finals an hour and a half after the semis?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson responded: ``Get used to it. That's how it is in the
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Trials are the ultimate track and field meet on
U.S. soil and the ultimate _ and only _ way to choose a U.S.
Olympic team. Maybe Johnson breezed through this same system four
years ago and went on to unprecedented double gold in Atlanta, but
that was four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is indeed sad to see such talents as Johnson and Greene
having to sit out. But they did race, and they did lose.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Johnson and Greene probably miscalculated
their pace through two days of heats and in Sunday's final. Capel,
Heard and Miller paced themselves nicely through the rounds and
then flashed to a sizzling final.
</P>
<P>
   Capel's 19.86, Heard's 19.88 and Miller's 19.96 marked only the
second time in the sport's history that three sprinters broke the
20-second barrier in the same race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Michael could have won if he didn't get hurt,'' Capel
said, smiling. ``But maybe he wouldn't have. You know, that was a
pretty fast race we ran.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet only moments after the final, some already were wondering
about the long-talked-about ``wild card'' entries for runners such
as Johnson and Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Why couldn't America's best sprinters be placed on the team in
circumstances of injury?
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Johnson said he would not accept such an
invitation. And what exactly would you tell Capel, Heard and
Miller, all of whom did everything right?
</P>
<P>
   As Tom Hanks said in the movie A League Of Their Own, ``Of
course it's hard. The hard is what makes it great.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
