<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1772 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SMITH0725     07-24 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SMITH0725 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emmitt Smith one of the last of the old-time Cowboys
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ While Emmitt Smith runs with the
football, technicolor images of old teammates flicker on the big
screen of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Freeze frame. Michael Irvin does his best Spiderman imitation.
</P>
<P>
   Freeze frame. Daryl Johnston delivers a headfirst block in the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Freeze frame. Deion Sanders falls to his knees and reminds the
world he's the baddest man around.
</P>
<P>
   Freeze it.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to that old gang? Nate Newton and Jay Novacek have
gone forward with their lives. Mark Tuinei has lost his. Rodney
Peete and Jason Garrett play in enemy colors.
</P>
<P>
   No more Playmaker, Moose or Prime Time.
</P>
<P>
   All good things must come to an end, and Smith knows his day
will come soon enough. He and Troy Aikman are about the only Dallas
Cowboys who have been teammates since George W. Bush's dad was
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the last of the Mohicans,'' Smith said on a sultry
afternoon in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is a constant reminder of a different time. Before the
Cowboys won their three Super Bowls in the 1990s, they drafted a
fresh-faced, bright-eyed kid from Florida who hasn't stopped
running. At 31, he ranks No. 3 on the all-time list of NFL rushers.
He needs 1,306 yards to reach Barry Sanders and 2,764 to pass the
late Walter Payton at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Barring injury, he will surpass Payton in 2002 or 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's down the road,'' Smith responds. ``Right now I'll deal
with today. We'll evaluate my situation at the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something different about this season, and it showed on
Smith's face when he was asked about the players who have come and
gone through the Cowboys' franchise. Without Irvin and Sanders,
this is a quieter team. Smith misses the rapid-fire talking from
their corners of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   They were friends, teammates, brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a key word here _ family,'' Smith said. ``They talk
about family. This is real. Working with a group of people for a
common goal of one team _ win and lose together, sweat and cry
together. And bleed together. When you see (teammates leave), it
hurts, it's tough. It's like part of your family saying it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, they are moving on to their real lives. But in the
sport, it's like a person has died. They are with you in spirit,
but they are no longer with you in body.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all part of a revolving-door business called the National
Football League. Smith said he has ``mourned'' after players leave
the team, but 2000 beckons. There are new challenges this year,
beginning with a new coaching staff, a new offense and perhaps
renewed enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmitt's going to have a chance to do what he does all the
time, and that's to make plays when the ball is in his hands,''
first-year Coach Dave Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   The direction of the offense was questioned when Campo and new
offensive coordinator Jack Reilly installed a pass-friendly offense
designed to get the football to Joey Galloway and Rocket Ismail.
The receivers have never been fast, never been this deep Will
Smith's role change in his 11th season in the league?
</P>
<P>
   No, Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I thought we were probably high in the run end,''
Campo said. ``I still believe the way to win football games is to
be balanced. Every game is going to be different. It depends on how
the defense plays you.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has been remarkably consistent, rushing for 1,332 yards in
1998 and 1,397 in 1999. He is not the reason the Cowboys did not
make a reasonable playoff run during that span.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas finished 24th in the league in passing offense last
season, a major reason the Cowboys improved their stock of
receivers in the off-season. To help compensate for the loss of
Irvin, the Cowboys acquired Galloway, perhaps the fastest player in
the NFL, and Tennessee tight end Jackie Harris. Ismail, former
Texas Longhorn Wane McGarity, Jason Tucker and David LaFleur have
given Aikman the deepest group of receivers during his 12 years
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't respect this, we'll open it up and pass the
ball down the field,'' Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of an air show should prolong Smith's career. Smith
ranks second in NFL history in total carries, quite an achievement
for someone who has been in the league only 10 seasons. It has
amazed some that Smith is still effective after taking a pounding
every year. He has averaged 324 carries a season, translating into
about 21 a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' reliance on Smith has resulted in some incredible
feats:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Smith was the first player in history to rush for 1,400 yards
five straight years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He owns the NFL record of 136 rushing touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sanders and Smith are the only players with nine 1,000-yard
rushing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 10 years, Smith has missed only three games because of
injury.
</P>
<P>
   He owns postseason records for rushing touchdowns (19),
consecutive games with a rushing touchdown (nine), 100-yard rushing
games (seven) and total rushing yards (1,586).
</P>
<P>
   Smith sees no reason why he cannot continue to build good
rushing seasons. He runs behind a good offensive line, led by
All-Pro left guard Larry Allen. Flozell Adams has developed into a
terrific left tackle, and the right side should be solid if Erik
Williams returns from his holdout.
</P>
<P>
   There are enough good pieces to the puzzle to reach the Super
Bowl again. St. Louis made a dramatic improvement to win this
year's championship, and the Cowboys now run the same wide-open
offense the Rams have used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why a Super Bowl can't be a realistic goal for
any team,'' Smith said. ``You just try to win as many games as you
possibly can to get into the tournament. If you can play your best
ball, you can go a long way. I don't think a Super Bowl is
unachievable.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys reach it this year, they will do it with a cast
that is dramatically different from the one that won the Super Bowl
in 1996. Only nine players from that team are still around. Before
long, Aikman and Smith, along with Allen, Williams, Darren Woodson,
Kevin Smith, Chad Hennings and Leon Lett will be gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   So, before Smith takes his last step, before he scores his final
touchdown, he wants to create some more images. Just because most
of his friends have moved on, there is no reason to quit bonding
with new guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only going to get caught up in what I need to get done
today, tomorrow and this year in order to help this team win,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Rick Cantu at rcantu(at)statesman.com..
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
