<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SEAL-SURFERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE SEALS   CAPTIVATE   A BEACH IN HAWAII 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL X. WEISSMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent birth of an endangered Hawaiian monk seal on a
popular public beach in Kauai, Hawaii, has pitted conservationists
against the organizers of a surfing event at a festival to be held
there next week.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists feared that the added noise, light and traffic from
the festival would cause the mother to abandon her two-week-old pup
before it was weaned, leaving it to die.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks of negotiations between the Kauai Surfing
Association, the event organizer, and the federal, state and local
authorities, the association decided to move its festivities to
Prince Kohio Beach about two miles west of Poipu Beach, where the
mother and pup are.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 1,300 existing monk seals living on the remote
northwest Hawaiian Islands steer clear of people. Only about 50
frequent the main Hawaiian Islands, and a birth on such a popular
beach is rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 1,000 people a day visit the beach, which lies between
two resorts,'' said Bradley Ryon, a wildlife technician with the
Hawaiian Monk Seal Program of the National Marine Fisheries
Service. ``Normally the moms will go to more remote beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother seal hauled up onto the beach on the evening of July
5. Early the next day passers-by heard her barking and discovered
that she had given birth.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ryon and about 30 volunteers have guarded the pup
and mother 24 hours a day, trying to persuade tourists not to use
flash bulbs, to stay clear of the seals and to keep noise down.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the seals was piqued by an article on July 17 in the
local Garden Island newspaper, which reported that festival
organizers were reluctant to move their event.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben Balmores, president of the Kauai Surfing Association,
denied that his group had been anything but cooperative with the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``As surfers and oceangoers who live in Kauai, we totally
understand the importance of monk seals,'' Balmores said. ``Once we
found out the entire situation, we immediately pulled out of the
park.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
