<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS REPORTED TO BE DRAFTING OUTLINE OF PEACE AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS-NOTEBOOK) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The Camp David peace negotiations intensified on
Monday as President Clinton plunged into the nitty-gritty of
issue-by-issue deliberations. After meeting almost until dawn with
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, he then oversaw a day and
night of what officials said quietly was the exercise of drafting
the skeleton of an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which is overseeing a news blackout on the
talks, would not confirm that a document was being drafted. But
Israeli and Palestinian officials said that negotiators, under the
direct supervision of Clinton, were engaged in forging a working
agreement in an effort to establish concrete points of accord and
highlight the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially imposing another informal deadline on the process,
the White House announced that Clinton, whose departure for Japan
last Wednesday almost collapsed the talks, would leave Camp David
at noon Tuesday to attend a funeral in Arkansas. He is to return at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Israeli and Palestinian officials said they expected it
to become clearer on Tuesday ``whether we are moving forward or at
a standstill,'' as Amnon Lipkin Shahak, a senior Israeli negotiator
inside Camp David, told Israel's Channel Two television on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman, offered his
least guarded assessment of the 14 days of talks, saying that the
pace and intensity of the president's schedule suggests that, five
days after talks nearly collapsed, Clinton believes there is a
prospect for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hesitate to use a phrase like hopeful because these issues
are so difficult,'' Lockhart said at a briefing at a press center
several miles from Camp David. ``But obviously the last time I
stood here it was an hour or so removed from the collapse of
discussions. The fact that it's continuing is a positive thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that the American president, who held up crossed
fingers as he boarded his helicopter to return to his Catoctin
Mountains retreat on Sunday, was engaged in a ``rolling
assessment'' of the probability of success. He said that a final
deadline would not be ``calendar-driven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While the president believes the discussions are substantive,
he will remain here and keep the parties here,'' Lockhart said.
``The fact that he was up to 5 a.m. working through issues in a
very personal hands-on way and back at it this morning should lead
you to believe that he thinks staying here for the time being is
worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview played on Israeli television, a
reporter asked Shahak, Israel's transportation minister, to
estimate, by percentage, the chances of an agreement. Shahak said,
``It's either zero or 100. There is no middle ground.''
</P>
<P>
   That remark and a similar one made by a senior Palestinian
negotiator, Abu Mazen, on Sunday indicate that the Israelis and the
Palestinians are for now discounting the possibility of a partial
agreement that would leave aside the potentially deal-breaking
issue of Jerusalem's status.
</P>
<P>
   But other officials say that the draft agreement has not yet
touched Jerusalem, and that the Americans may still try to persuade
the parties to reach an accord without resolving the city's
contested status.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ground rules at Camp David, nothing is agreed until
everything is agreed, and a senior Palestinian official said on
Monday night that the dispute over Jerusalem has caused the parties
to retreat from offers that were on the table last week.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that the Palestinians' mood was soured after
Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, asserted that he would not
feel bound by compromise positions reached at the summit if it ends
in failure.
</P>
<P>
   After his early return from Japan, where he attended a meeting
of the leading industrial nations, Clinton met on Sunday night with
Barak and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat. Some 30 American,
Israeli and Palestinian delegates shared a dinner in which Clinton
sat between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, around midnight, Clinton convened the senior
negotiators from each side, leaving aside the two leaders. After
breaking near dawn for a nap, he cut short a White House staff
meeting to rush back into the talks with the negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Over a total of nine hours, Clinton worked with various teams
specializing in different issues, recessing before an expected
evening meeting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
