<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1776 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-2NDTAKE     07-24 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THURMONT, Md.: evening meeting.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An official photograph from inside Camp David showed Clinton
with two Israeli negotiators on one side and two Palestinian
negotiators on the other.
</P>
<P>
   All are taking furious notes, and Dennis Ross, the Middle East
peace envoy, holds a large folder in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   Uri Savir, an Israeli lawmaker who served as a senior negotiator
of the Oslo interim peace agreement of 1993, said he viewed the
photograph as an illustration of document drafting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging from my experience in these things, there would be no
reason for Clinton to spend this amount of time with the
negotiators themselves for any other reason,'' Savir said. ``And
that's a very good sign. Generally when you finish writing, you
discover the gaps are wider than you thought. But in a very real
sense, you are launched in the dynamic of an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle East, those whose fate rests on the deliberations
seize each day's limited news from Camp David with a mixture of
anxiety and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone there who has lived through the ups and downs of the
conflict awaits the end in a protective zone of skepticism for what
would be the amazing news _ exhilarating for some, gut-wrenching
for others _ that the 52-year, blood-soaked conflict was to be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, a poll published on Monday morning showed that 59
percent of Israelis surveyed hoped that the summit would end in
agreement, even knowing full well the ``painful compromises'' that
would be entailed.
</P>
<P>
   This reflects what Barak has been arguing, that, despite the
defection of rightist parties that left him with a minority
government this month, the public supports his peacemaking and
would endorse an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he should sign an agreement,'' said Dalia Itzik, the
environment minister, ``he will present it as, ladies and
gentlemen, the agreement you always dreamed of: the end of the
conflict in return for a few Arab neighborhoods that you personally
have never visited and have no interest in.''
</P>
<P>
   No Israeli leader had ever broached the idea of sharing
sovereignty in East Jerusalem with the Palestinians until last
week, when word leaked out of the talks that Barak was considering
it. The official rhetoric always called for a united, undivided
Jerusalem under Israeli sovereignty even though most Israelis know
that on the ground, Jerusalem is a segregated city.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say that, as the morning's polls indicate,
Israelis may be prepared to absorb a changed outlook relatively
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling that we are at a turning point in public
opinion'' toward Jerusalem, said Dr. Tamar Hermann, director of the
Tami Steinmetz Center for Peace Research at Tel Aviv University.
``The moment the taboo was removed on even discussing the issue of
dividing Jerusalem, it created an opening.''
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Palestinian official said that the idea of sharing
sovereignty in East Jerusalem is now off the table, having been
rejected by both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
