r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-24 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: Xxxxxxxxxxx Xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GEORGE W. PUTS THINGS IN ORDER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; G &LR; 
 &UR; eorge W. Bush &LR;  last week unveiled his new Web site, which features
a list of the Republican presidential contender's top three
priorities, reports the Washington Post. On www.georgewbush.com:
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 priority is ``reforming Social Security''; No. 2 is
``lowering personal income tax''; and No. 3, third, is ``putting
education first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DEATH AND HOBBIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; J.K. Rowling &LR; , author of the Harry Potter books, told the Times
of London recently that her hero is the late  &UR; Jessica Mitford &LR; , who
was born a British aristocrat, lived in Oakland and whose first
best-seller was ``The American Way of Death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She had courage,'' Rowling said of the muckraking author.
``She didn't just talk it, she lived it.'' Rowling said she named
her daughter after the writer.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Reviewing Rowling's latest Harry Potter book in the New
York Times on Sunday,  &UR; Stephen King  &LR; wrote that he is worried about
the forthcoming movie version, which he fears may fail in bringing
``Rowling's scatty wit and vibrant imagination to the screen. ...
Perhaps Harry Potter's place is in the imaginations of his readers.
And if these millions of readers are awakened to the wonders and
rewards of fantasy at 11 or 12 ... well, when they get to age 16 or
so, there's this guy named King.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. As to the British way of death,  &UR; Benedict le Vay &LR; 's
``Eccentric Britain'' (Globe Pequot; $17.95) notes that funeral
trains at Ripley, Derbyshire, are aimed at filling the needs of
``dead steam-train enthusiasts.'' Specially built tracks carry the
deceased and mourners on a two-mile ride ending at a special
platform at the edge of a new cemetery. Wakes are held in the
buffet car. The late are buried purposely close to the tracks so
that passing trains rattle their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
O.J. UNINVITED
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Barbara Walters &LR;  was going to have  &UR; O.J. Simpson  &LR; on ``The
View'' Wednesday, but canceled plans when viewers and staff members
protested. Simpson was touting a Web site that would allow users to
pay to ask him questions and would sell Simpson memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received more very unhappy phone calls from viewers than I
have in a very long time,'' Walters told the New York Times. ``That
was not the defining thing, but that troubled me.'' Co-hosts
 &UR; Meredith Vieira &LR;  and  &UR; Joy Behar  &LR; had said on-air they were unhappy
about Simpson's planned appearance;  &UR; Star Jones  &LR; said she was eager
to talk with him.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson's making the rounds, with appearances scheduled this
week on the ``Today'' show, Court TV and the Fox News cable
channel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
