</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-SLEEP-SORENSEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST SUMMER RECREATION: SLEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, July 25, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By WILLIAM SORENSEN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRONXVILLE, N.Y. _ We are in what's advertised as the season of
snorkeling, roller-coaster riding and cross-country hikes. But with
jobs and work places getting more intense by the day, an old truth
about vacations may be truer than ever: They're about rest. Whether
it's at the beach, in the mountains or in the Tuscan hills,
sleeping in can be better than venturing out.
</P>
<P>
   Most people may be sheepish about admitting this, but not my
family. We are serious sleepers, and proud of it. We even compare
notes. When my sister, my three brothers and I talk long-distance,
before discussing our kids' grades, our spouses' foibles or our
parents' knee replacements, I always ask: ``Have you had any great
sleep lately?'' When the answer is yes, I fluff the sofa pillows,
take off my shoes, stretch out and demand details. Where? When?
How?
</P>
<P>
   An acquaintance once bragged to me about landing a temporary job
at a sleep research clinic, where he got paid to sleep. I was not
impressed. No one in my family would consider sleeping while
attached to electrodes and monitors. Even if it meant napping away
the working hours as well as the ones in between, this wouldn't be
quality sleep. Duration alone won't do.
</P>
<P>
   But, then, quality alone won't do, either. A blissful childhood
memory of mine is of summer nights sleeping in the open air with my
siblings, on the big second-floor balcony of our family's cabin in
the Uinta Mountains of Utah. Don't imagine us curled up in smelly
old sleeping bags; we had discovered that beneath piles of quilts
on our old four-poster beds at the cabin lay mattresses, circa
1940, that could be folded over and easily, gleefully, carried out
to the balcony, where there was plenty of room to spread them out. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; On those chilly, pitch-dark nights, we'd drift off in our
cushiony beds, lulled by the soothing noise of a nearby rocky
river. It was the highest-quality sleep. But it never lasted long
enough. We grumpily ran for cover as the sun came up.
</P>
<P>
   The true vacation challenge isn't rock climbing or tennis games.
It's finding the ideal combination of unstructured and
uninterrupted time for sleep and a quiet, airy and light-controlled
setting.
</P>
<P>
   My siblings and I had both quality and duration when we left our
mattresses on our beds, which were in our mountain cabin's sleeping
loft. For the adult vacationer, looking for the perfect spot to
book a good rest demands asking questions about not only
pine-scented air and distance from noisy roads, but nonintrusive
housekeeping services and gap-free Venetian blinds.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal way to wake up, of course, is the way we always did in
the Rockies: to the aroma of fresh-brewing coffee and sizzling
bacon. And not a minute before, let's say, noon.
</P>
<P>
   (William Sorensen is a producer at CNBC.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
