r f BC-WIRELESS-PHONEFLAWS-S     07-24 1886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-PHONEFLAWS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INTERNET PHONES LEAVE ROOM FOR IMPROVEMENT  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Stewart Lin has mixed feelings about his
Internet phone.
</P>
<P>
   Lin, a San Francisco computer consultant who is often on the
road, said the phone is ideal for scanning e-mail and checking San
Francisco Giants baseball scores. He even logged on from the 14th
hole of the Pebble Beach golf club and watched the practice round
for the U.S. Open last month.
</P>
<P>
   But navigating the Internet is practically impossible. And
sending a long e-mail message, using a nubby telephone keypad, can
be a nightmare. To type a message, Lin must hit each key on his
telephone pad multiple times until the right letter or symbol
scrolls by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear it took an hour to write three sentences,'' said Lin,
28, recalling his efforts to send a note from the links. The
experience was especially annoying because it costs him 39 cents a
minute to use the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the downsides, many pundits and tech magazines are
hyping the wireless Internet as the next big thing. The Yankee
Group in Boston predicts that 60 million people in the United
States will have Net access from cell phones in 2005, up from fewer
than 200,000 in December.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry players are already beginning to sense a
backlash, as early users complain that it's not as simple to use a
Net phone as it is to flick on their home computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have used the Internet from their desktops expect
it to be the same thing,'' laments Greg Heumann, a marketing
executive at Phone.com, the Redwood City, Calif., firm that
provides the microbrowser for most Net phones. But ``it's not a
smaller version of the PC.''
</P>
<P>
   Heumann said many people are disappointed because the phones
can't possibly live up to all the hype. ``The industry and media
tend to conspire together and always end up oversetting peoples'
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, users can also increasingly access the Net from
laptops and handhelds. But experts say cell phones are especially
key because they are so common. In addition, because phones
generally have tinier screens and don't work with a stylus, it also
raises trickier issues about how to adapt the technology to the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't to say Internet phones aren't useful. Lin is
still generally a fan. And enthusiasts say the phones are still
ideal to scan e-mail and receive tiny, targeted bits of news _ like
stock quotes or sports scores _ while out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade, for instance, figures that many active investors will
set up their accounts to automatically shoot them ``alerts'' about
major stock swings or news related to companies they are tracking.
</P>
<P>
   ``An alert isn't valuable if it isn't getting to people wherever
they are,'' said Jim Safka, who oversees the wireless strategy for
the Menlo Park online brokerage. ``If you come back to your PC a
couple hours later, it's too late. You can't respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, logging on to Web sites is more cumbersome with a phone
than a PC. For one thing, only a handful of sites are set up to
handle hits from cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, typing in URLs (Web site addresses) can be clumsy on a
telephone keypad.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways to get around the problem, of course. Experts
recommend that you first create a list of online bookmarks on your
PC (with help from Web sites like  &LR; mobile.yahoo.com &LR;  or
 &LR; www.cellmania.com &LR; ). Then you can point your microbrowser to the
list of links and store the address. ``You should never have to
enter a URL into your phone,'' Heumann says.
</P>
<P>
   Experts figure users might take the trouble to enter an address
for their online broker or e-mail provider. But generally,
customers will likely stick to the standard menu of sites featured
on their phone _ what analysts call ``the walled garden.'' And it
might be difficult to escape. Some of the manuals that come with
Web phones do not even contain instructions on how to scale the
garden walls and access other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are likely to be blocked in'' as a cell phone customer,
said Andrew Cole, head of the wireless practice at Renaissance
Worldwide, a Boston technology consultancy.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at America Online, said Yankee Group analyst David
Berndt. Roughly 70 percent of AOL subscribers never venture out
onto the Web, relying on AOL's expansive online service.
</P>
<P>
   If that holds true with Net phones as well, it means wireless
carriers could demand hefty fees or commissions to feature an
Internet site on their exclusive list. Companies such as E-Trade
and Fidelity are already paying undisclosed sums to show up on
wireless screens.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewees declined to comment about the going rate to be
featured on a phone. They said the deals vary widely. In fact,
Yahoo, the Santa Clara, Calif., Web portal, said it actually
receives money from AT&AMP;T and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Because Yahoo is the most popular Web site in the world, cell
phone carriers want to use the name to peddle their services,
explained Drew Lanham, Yahoo's senior director of business
development. And the longer users stay online, the more telephone
companies can charge in connection fees. ``We drive up their
usage,'' Lanham said. The most popular features include e-mail,
stock quotes, news headlines, sports scores and weather.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you might have trouble recognizing the telephone
versions of popular Web sites such as Yahoo and Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   To make them work, programmers have to strip them down to just a
few lines of text _ like making a jazzy billboard into a puny
classified ad.
</P>
<P>
   Just consider Amazon's Web site. In addition to its trademark
logo, the site features dozens of icons (including one of a
shopping cart) and pictures of book covers and albums.
</P>
<P>
   But click on the phone version and you'll likely see just the
name of the site and a few options like books and records. No
logos. No pictures. Not even any unusual fonts.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say graphics will come eventually, as phone companies
develop faster connections and update the standards Web sites use
to tailor their sites for mobile users.
</P>
<P>
   One problem not likely to go away, though, is the lack of a
keyboard. To get around the problem, experts strongly advise users
to type in as much information ahead of time from their PC.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites like Yahoo, for instance, let registered users enter
their zip codes, favorite sports teams, key stocks and other
personal information in advance. Then when they log onto that site
from their phones, the page can automatically show them their local
weather, the stock quotes they are interested in and scores for
their favorite teams. Or users can program the sites to
automatically send out the information in the form of alerts.
</P>
<P>
   One downside, of course, is that users still have to log on to
each and every site _ using the clumsy keypad to type in a name and
password _ to access the info. But cell phone companies are trying
to work out ways to let users log in just once _ giving them entry
to all their partners' sites. They are also considering offering
``electronic wallets'' that let customers make purchases without
having to type in their credit card numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Experts' opinions differ, though, on just how frequently
customers are likely to use phones for shopping. Heumann said he
has bought books and records several times from Amazon.com on the
spur of the moment _ figuring that if he scribbled down the title
to make the purchase later, he'd probably just lose the information
or forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Yahoo's Lanham says: ``I don't believe that you are going to
buy substantial purchases from these phones.''
</P>
<P>
   Ad agencies are already pondering how to make money from
Internet phones. However, Yahoo and Redwood City, Calif.'s
ExciteAtHome said they're jumping into the online game mainly as a
convenience to consumers and to encourage them to register with the
site and give them personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts say the wireless telephone companies are in
the catbird seat because they can track where users go and feed
them targeted ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a saying that he who owns the customer information,
controls the customer,'' said Cole, the Renaissance analyst. ``We
are extremely bullish'' on wireless firms.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy watchdogs, however, are increasingly worried that phone
companies may not adequately safeguard customers' personal
information.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS stoked concerns earlier this year after a Seattle
software developer noticed that his phone automatically transmitted
his phone number to any Web site he visited. Sprint denied it was a
problem, but promised to eliminate the practice in the new version
of its software.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, an AT&AMP;T spokesman initially confirmed that AT&AMP;T
phones worked the same way, then insisted they were different.
``AT&AMP;T's Pocketnet service does not transmit phone numbers to Web
sites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a disclaimer, bundled with AT&AMP;T Internet phones, warns users
that their personal information including the ``mobile number''
will be transmitted to other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The disclaimer shocked privacy advocate Jason Catlett, president
of the Junkbusters in New Jersey, when he stumbled across it after
buying an AT&AMP;T Internet phone. Catlett said it is always worrisome
when companies assign Net users a unique ID, because it lets Web
sites track individuals, but using a phone number raises even more
red flags. ``I have friends who don't give out their cell phone
number,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokesman Ritch Blasi said the phone company plans to
update its software in the next 30 to 60 days to scramble the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Other privacy issues lurk on the horizon. Federal regulators,
for instance, have ordered phone companies to find ways to identify
the precise location of a user, so 911 dispatchers can quickly find
anyone who calls in for help.
</P>
<P>
   The information could also potentially be used by wireless Web
users to find the location of the nearest ATM machine or get
directions if they are lost. But Catlett worries that cell phone
companies could sell the information to Web operators, who hope to
target customers with ads for nearby stores. Catlett called it
``cookies on steroids.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the alarms, most analysts predict wireless Net
technology will become nearly ubiquitous in a few years, as more
telephones come ready-armed with Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the service has already taken off in some other parts
of the world. More than 7.8 million Japanese, for instance, use NTT
DoCoMo's iMode service to go online. In Asia and Europe, the
service is especially popular for sending short digital notes to
friends and colleagues, like sending an instant message on America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Lin, the San Francisco user, said he's already a fan. But Lin
was quickly shocked by bills of $100 to $150 a month after he first
started using his Net phone.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms have a flat rate for $7 to $20 per month. But others,
such as Sprint, charge the same price for navigating the Web as
they do for regular voice calls.
</P>
<P>
   So, until the price comes down, Lin said he can only afford to
log on if he is expecting an urgent e-mail or if the Giants are
playing in a crucial game and he's dying to see the score.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
