<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1798 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DIGITALMUSIC-0725-COX     07-24 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITALMUSIC-0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time Warner executive likens Napster site to the devil
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time Warner President Richard Parsons made it clear
Monday how he feels about free digital music downloads on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He hates them. He really, really hates them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he knows there is money to be made from
digital music distribution and he wants his company to make it.
</P>
<P>
   This quandary is at the core of the heated debate at the 5th
Annual Jupiter Plug-In music conference. More than 1,600 artists,
record executives and Internet business people are sharing the
auditorium with a news corps gathered to witness the fight.
</P>
<P>
   In his keynote address, Parson compared the popular
file-swapping site Napster to the devil, pirates, thieves and even
Communists out to destroy artists' and record companies' right to
be compensated for their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital music is illegal,'' said. ``They are ripping off
artists and hiding behind third-party neutrality. The music being
passed around on the Internet is stolen, and the artists have a
right to be paid.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Time Warner and other major music distributors
will continue their legal efforts to stop sites like Napster and
MP3.com from distributing free music. A judge is expected to rule
this week if the record companies are right and Napster could be
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience as a lawyer says that the courts will speak
forcefully and say ripping off music is a crime whether you do it
in the store or on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, borrowing liberally from President Kennedy, he further
emphasized his company's commitment to fighting free music
distribution on the Net: ``The music industry will pay any price,
bear any burden, undergo any hardship and oppose any foe to protect
the copyrights of their companies and the copyrights of their
artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Parson said that no musician, artist or filmmaker was going to
invest years of work in something that will bring them nothing and
that will be ``universally and instantly pirated.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if it weren't for Napster, the conference might still
be held at its initial digs in a basement in Greenwich Village.
Illegal though it may be, Napster has stirred more interest in the
recording industry than anything in the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of simple technology, a community environment
and the availability of songs for free has proved irresistible to
music lovers of all ages and demographics.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter analyst Adam Sinnreich told the group that online music
industry continues to grow despite the fact that it is illegal, but
the average music lover doesn't want to steal music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online music is now a mainstream phenomenon, with 500,000
simultaneous music users online every night,'' Sinnreich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the labels are fighting it, it's really a net
positive for them,'' he said noting that a Jupiter poll of Napster
users said that 45 percent were more likely to increase their music
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Sinnreich said that in the United States, online music will
generate roughly one-fourth of the total music market reaching $5.4
billion in 2005. Sinnreich said what nearly every analyst and
developer has been saying for years _ to grow their business,
record companies can't ignore the Internet and must make the shift
from a product-based model (CDs and tapes) to a service-based
business model. That model would use the Internet to deliver music
digitally and provide users with a range of goods and services,
such as artist information, ticket sales, merchandizing and
streaming audio and video concerts and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   A sneak preview of the Virgin Megastore's new Web site aired at
the conference revealed the scope of the problems faced by
companies trying to sell digital music legally. While the Virgin
site will sell nearly any CD produced, its range of digital
downloads available for sale is quite limited.
</P>
<P>
   Sinnreich and Jupiter advocate a subscription mode, similar to
some agreements music retailers are working on, to deliver digital
music to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subscriptions deliver on the value of music,'' he told the
group. ``A la carte (one song at time) sales do not. Buying a la
carte downloads make no sense. Consumers like volume discounts.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Time Warner's merger with America Online, even
Parsons can't deny the great opportunities presented by the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet offers us a chance to offer our unmatched stable
of artists to anyone, anywhere at any time,'' he said, echoing the
mantra of Amazon.com's Jeff Bezos, as well as AOL's ``anywhere''
strategy for delivering content to users over a variety of devices.
``Music will benefit from the intimacy it provides consumers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Parsons said adequate copyright protection is key. The
industry would have to come up with digital copyrights and
watermarks that would protect the copyright holders. Lastly,
despite his strongly worded comments about Napster and
``underground'' digital distribution in general, he also said he is
keenly aware that Napster or Napsterlike technologies are extremely
popular and nothing but litigation can shut them down. In the
meantime, the major labels have to figure out a way to get into the
game and get in fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must embrace the Internet and the digital technology,'' he
said. ``I would be the first one to acknowledge that the legitimate
players are missing in the online world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
