<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-VP25-COX     07-24 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VP25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush closer to announcng running mate
 &HT;    By Jena Heath and Elizabeth Barchas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush is expected to announce as
early as today that he will name Richard B. Cheney, former defense
secretary, congressman, family loyalist and the man in charge of
the vice presidential selection, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Monday that he had made his decision, but he declined
to reveal it. The Washington Post and the Associated Press,
however, declared Cheney as Bush's choice, based on comments that
Cheney made to friends. The choice is largely viewed as relatively
unrisky even if it lacks the drama of a Gen. Colin Powell, who CBS
News said still was being considered on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good, solid choice that no one in the party can carp
at and I think it'll give Bush a nice bounce in Philadelphia,''
said Scott Reed, who managed former U.S. Sen. Bob Dole's 1996 White
House campaign. ``Remember, this is an issue for about 72 hours and
then all the focus goes back to the top of the ticket. That's who
people vote for.''
</P>
<P>
   Choosing Cheney would be a ``strategic decision,'' that
indicates Bush has, ``a lot confidence in the way the campaign is
setting up and he's reaching out to somebody who is acceptable to
conservatives and brings a lot of heft and weight to the national
ticket.'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his thinking, Bush maintained the mystery, telling CBS
News anchor Dan Rather in an interview at the Governor's Mansion
Monday that he had made up his mind late Sunday, but had not yet
told anyone, including his wife, Laura, or his parents. He
responded to reports that he had made a last-ditch appeal to
Powell, saying that Powell made it clear early he wasn't interested
in the job and contending that talks didn't get much farther.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was reportedly preparing to offer Cheney the job Monday
night, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm guarding my decision very carefully,'' Bush said. ``I have
made up my mind. ``
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, after returning from a weekend in seclusion at his
ranch, Bush told reporters staked outside the Governor's Mansion:
``No news today. I will let you know soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation zeroed in on Cheney during the weekend, following
news reports that he changed his voter registration from Texas to
Wyoming to comply with the Constitution, which says that the
president and vice president cannot be registered in the same
state. He also reportedly got a clean bill of health and discussed
the possibility of joining the ticket with associates at
Halliburton Co., the Dallas energy giant where he serves as chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The guessing game reached a frenzy as news reports veered back
and forth between Cheney and Powell, an undisputed knock-out ticket
had Bush been able to convince him to join the ticket. CBS News
reported that Bush and his father had pursued Powell to the end and
that Powell's wife, Alma, had dropped long-held objections to a run
for national office. By late afternoon, Powell's office was denying
that any such conversations took place and Hughes all but shot down
the possibility of a Bush-Powell march to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Gen. Powell specifically has made it very clear
that he is not interested in serving as the vice president,''
Hughes said. ``He said that very consistently and I think he's said
that very unequivocally.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes confirmed that Bush had asked his father to call Dr.
Denton A. Cooley, a Houston cardiac surgeon and family friend, to
request that Cooley would consult with a Cheney physician to
determine if Cheney is strong enough to run. Cheney suffered three
mild heart attacks in the seventies and eighties, and had bypass
surgery in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is that Gov. Bush asked his father to call
Dr. Cooley as part of his vetting process because his father is a
friend of (Cooley's) and he asked, if he were called, if he would
be willing to offer an opinion and that was the extent of his
father's involvement,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Directly or indirectly, there is no doubt that the elder Bush is
playing a major part in his son's march to the White House, despite
Bush's contention Friday that his father has been acting as a
sounding board who doesn't need to be first in line to hear the
vice-presidential choice.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, 59, a Nebraska native, served as defense secretary in
the Bush administration. Before resigning to take that post in
March 1989, Cheney served six terms in Congress representing
Wyoming. He was White House chief of staff under President Gerald
Ford from 1975-1977. So trusted is Cheney in the tight Bush circle
that, last year, George W. Bush asked him to spearhead the search
for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign team also includes, among others, Condoleezza
Rice, a former Stanford University provost and adviser to President
Bush, who is serving as foreign affairs and defense adviser to his
son and George P. Shultz, who served as secretary of state in the
Reagan-Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas political scientist and
longtime Bush watcher, said choosing Cheney is in character for
Bush, for whom comfort and loyalty are paramount.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing it says is that you go with the sure, the safe
and the comfortable,'' Buchanan said. ``By that I mean the stuff
that matters most to him, 'Yes, I like this guy. I feel like I can
trust him. I feel like he has the capabilities to help me and his
loyalty is proven because he links back to my dad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta pollster Whit Ayers said Cheney is a good choice, ``a
man who's conservative in his views and moderate in his rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic pollster Mark Mellman gave a hint of how Democrats
might seek to exploit Bush's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting two Texas oilmen on the ticket doesn't exactly send
the best message to the rest of the country,'' Mellman said. ``The
folks in the oil fields of Texas may be jumping for joy, but I'm
not sure the rest of the country is.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said the challenge now is for the Bush campaign to
re-introduce Cheney _ a consummate Washington insider _ to voters
during the Republican National Convention set to begin in
Philadelphia next week. And he credited Bush with his handling of
the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``The V.P. selection is the one time the candidate is totally in
control of his own campaign,'' Reed said. ``He calls the shots,
keeps his circle of advisors really tight and can have a little
fun, sending signals, putting his arm around people and totally
dictating the timing and the terms of the debate. It looks like
Bush is enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
