<HEADER>
A1800 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON &LR;      07-24 2164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH 21: ZANY ELECTION SITES AMUSE ON THE NET  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the Republican convention opening in less
than a week, the election season is now in full bore, and this year
the Web will play a central role in reporting and interpreting the
campaign's dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   The ``2000 Elections'' category in Yahoo's directory includes a
mind-boggling 1,214 sites (or so Yahoo says _ I confess I didn't
count).
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't, however, include my current favorite, a site called
``Billionaires for Bush (or Gore)''
( &LR; www.billionairesforbushorgore.com &LR; ). You don't have to be quite
as jaded as I am about our major-party candidates to get a kick out
of this one.
</P>
<P>
   The site's slogan is ``Because Inequality Is Not Growing Fast
Enough,'' and one highlight is a ``Candidate Price/Performance
Analysis'' page. There's also a stirring call to join ``Million
Billionaire Marches'' at the two conventions (``For too long we
have ruled the country from behind the scenes. It's time for us to
come out of the closet.'')
</P>
<P>
   I liked some of the proposed slogans, too, like ``The rich,
united, shall never be defeated'' and ``Who needs day care, hire an
au pair!''
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in a more-serious look at the thinking of
some of the protesters who will be in the streets of Philadelphia
and Los Angeles, try the Whirled Bank site ( &LR; www.whirledbank.org &LR; ).
This one has a bit of humor, too, mainly in the section dedicated
to the First Church of the Almighty Dollar. (I'm not sure they're
really entitled to call themselves first, but whatever ...)
</P>
<P>
   Most of the site, though, is devoted to analysis of World Bank
policies and their consequences. The ``In Our Own Words'' section
includes some interesting documents, such as a 1991 memo by
Lawrence Summers, then the bank's chief economist and now U.S.
secretary of the Treasury, making the case that industries that
pollute enough to cause death and disease should be moved out of
the United States and into less-developed countries.
</P>
<P>
   (His reasoning: The economic costs of health-impairing pollution
can be measured by the total amount of earnings foregone as a
result of increased disease and death. Because people in
less-developed countries earn less than Americans, ``the economic
logic behind dumping a load of toxic waste in the lowest wage
country is impeccable.'')
</P>
<P>
   And if you're up for a long but (at least to me) surprisingly
readable critique of the economic assumptions both major parties
have embraced, check out the text of a farewell speech by Herman
Daly, a former senior economist at the bank (World, not Whirled).
It's profoundly radical fare, especially considering where it comes
from.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that you don't find stuff like that on the
mainstream political sites, but you might expect at least an
independent perspective from a site headed by former Washington
Post reporter Carl Bernstein. (Footnote for those too young to
remember the mid-1970s: Bernstein and his colleague Bob Woodward
played a central role in exposing Watergate and related Nixon
administration shenanigans.)
</P>
<P>
   The site, Voter.com, does seem to have a large selection of
information and commentary on the campaign, including some
interesting ways to ``follow the money''
( &LR; www.voter.com/home/candidates &LR; 
 &LR; /contributions/0,3496,2--,00.html &LR; ). And its ``Compare
Candidates'' page does encompass more than just Shrub and Bore _ if
you take the time to use the pop-up menus, you'll find nine other
candidates listed.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's virtually no material on any of the
third-party candidates, and nearly everything else on the site
comes right out of the two-party mainstream. An article in the New
York Times last week helps explain why: It turns out that Voter.com
charges the campaigns to post information in its candidate
sections. It also has contracts with the two parties under which
they pledge to ``advise Voter.com on ways to maintain `balanced
partisanship''' and to promote the site.
</P>
<P>
   DECONSTRUCTING BENCHMARKS: ``Lies, damn lies and benchmarks,''
Mark Twain might have said if he had been at last week's Macworld
Expo, unless of course he happened to be a true Mac believer.
(Remember, he was a techie in his time _ one of the first writers
to adopt a new invention called the typewriter.)
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly many PC loyalists, and probably even a few Mac
users, reacted with similar sentiments to Apple Chief Executive
Officer Steve Jobs' demonstration of a standard 500-megahertz Power
Mac G4 handily outperforming a Windows box with an Intel Pentium
III running at 1 gigahertz, or twice the Mac's processor clock
speed, in a sequence of demanding operations in Adobe Photoshop.
</P>
<P>
   All the more so for the follow-up demo of the new high-end model
introduced last week, with two of the 500-megahertz G4 chips,
crushing the same PC, and Jobs' contention that his dual-CPU system
is equivalent to a 2-gigahertz Pentium PC _ a system that won't, he
predicted, be available for another year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mac zealots will no doubt take these claims as the whole
truth; PC enthusiasts will probably dismiss them as nothing more
than marketing hype.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is somewhere in between. And the issue, I think, is
worth exploring because benchmark-based performance claims are so
much a part of the technology scene.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly true that benchmarks can be manipulated in a
variety of ways, including improper or unequal configuration of the
machines being tested. But that's not the most profound problem
with comparative benchmarking, and I'll assume it wasn't an issue
in Apple's Expo exploits.
</P>
<P>
   The core issue is that the performance of a computer system,
whether it's measured with a real-life application like Photoshop
or a synthetic testing tool like Ziff-Davis's widely used WinBench
and MacBench, is a function of many different components within
that system _ processors, memory, buses (the channels through which
data is transported within the system), drives, graphics card, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Even tests that focus specifically on processor speed must, if
they're to be at all meaningful, include a variety of operations,
so they can measure the speed at which the chip can carry out the
many different kinds of tasks it's capable of.
</P>
<P>
   And when you're dealing with products that are anywhere close to
being competitive, you're not likely to find that one outperforms
the other on every dimension _ typically, each will have strengths
and weaknesses of its own.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true when you're comparing Macs and PCs, which
_ even though both now have many components in common _ remain
based on radically different chips and internal architectures. If
you measured finely enough, you'd find that the Mac and its G4
processor leave the PC and its Pentium in the dust on some
operations _ and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the overall outcome of a benchmark test is a function of
the combination of tasks that go into it _ not just the program,
but the specific commands and operations used in the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   If the test is weighted toward tasks where the Mac excels, it'll
win; if the exercise involves a lot of routines where the PC is
best, then  &LR; it  &LR; will come out on top. When the end result is total
time, as is the case with most computer benchmarks, a major
difference in one or two long operations can wash out the effects
of smaller differences on dozens of other tasks.
</P>
<P>
   I don't for a minute believe that Apple rigged its demo. Anybody
else doing the same test on the same hardware would almost
certainly get identical results.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm equally certain that among all the jobs that could be
used to compare the performance of the two platforms, Apple
deliberately chose one that showed its products at their best.
Using almost any application other than Photoshop would have
changed the dual-processor picture, because it's one of only a
handful of Mac programs that take advantage of multiple chips. Even
within Photoshop, a different sequence of operations might have
produced significantly different results.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing surprising or unethical about that. After all,
Jobs was pitching his products, not conducting a scientific
experiment. Intel or any PC-maker would do the same on its turf.
</P>
<P>
   And both tests could have been representative of real life _
just of different aspects of its complexity.
</P>
<P>
   PS5BENCH: My own attempts to compare Mac and PC performance
might make all this more concrete. Back in April, when I reviewed
three of the first gigahertz PCs for The Chronicle, I added a
sidebar noting that my 450-megahertz Power Mac G4 beat them all on
a series of Photoshop series routines somewhat similar to the
sequence Apple used last week. My tests involved basic Photoshop
commands: rotating and resizing a test image, changing color modes,
``despeckling'' the image, and applying common effects such as
``Gaussian blurs'' and ``unsharp masks.''
</P>
<P>
   These operations are both commonly used in the graphics world
and pretty demanding in terms of processing power. I'm no Photoshop
expert myself _ I hardly use the program except for benchmarking _
so Adobe and several graphics professionals helped me pick them out
years ago as a good indicator of overall performance in the
program. I've used the same set of tests for years in Mac and PC
reviews for other publications, before I came to The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   But I got tons of e- mail about the sidebar (nobody seemed to
care about the actual review of the PCs, just the cross-platform
comparison). Many of these messages were childish ``flames,'' but
others cited some real evidence that my results were wrong or at
least unrepresentative. So I agreed to go back and do further
testing with a wider set of tests.
</P>
<P>
   For that I turned to something called PS5bench, a Photoshop
``actions file'' _ a set of routines designed to be run as an
automated sequence _ that was developed for benchmarking purposes
and runs on both Mac and PC. (If you have Photoshop 5, you can
download it and try it for yourself - it's at
 &LR; www.geocities.com/Paris/Cafe/4363/ &LR; . There's also a version for
Photoshop 4.)
</P>
<P>
   The PS5bench sequence involves all the routines in my own
personal test suite, but it also includes a number of others
-effects like Lens Flare and Pointillize. Altogether, it
encompasses 21 operations.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have room here to go into all the details, but the end
result is interesting. Basically, this test confirmed my original
results _ for the operations I'd benchmarked. The Mac still came
out ahead in 13 of the 21 tests.
</P>
<P>
   But the addition of the other effects changed the balance
noticeably, because on some of them _ notably a filter called
Radial Blur _ the PC turned out to be much faster. The net effect
was that the Hewlett-Packard Pavilion with a 1-gigahertz PC edged
out my Power Mac G4.
</P>
<P>
   By then, however, Apple had lent me a 500-megahertz G4 for
testing, and the extra megahertz made just enough difference to put
the Mac back in front.
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite true, as one reader claimed in May to me, that
you can make any computer look faster than any other by choosing
the right tests _ short of outright fraud, my first computer, a
Commodore 64, wouldn't beat a Power Mac or a Pentium PC no matter
how you slice it. But as my PS5bench results show, exactly what you
benchmark can make a dramatic difference.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the reality is that today's Macs and PCs are
roughly competitive _ they're both pretty fast for most things, but
in the most demanding applications both still keep you waiting.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the companies who make its PowerPC chips _
IBM and Motorola _ haven't been able to improve their clock speeds
much during the past nine months, even as Intel and rival Advanced
Micro Devices have raced ahead to the gigahertz mark and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   With Intel's Pentium 4 due this fall and expected to give PC
performance a nice boost, Apple could soon have faced real trouble,
at least for that part of its customer base that cares more about
performance than elegance or ease of use.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs' decision to put two G4s in every high-end Mac is a clever
preemptive response. As the Expo demos showed, it's likely to be
effective with the Photoshop crowd, and they're the heart of
Apple's professional market.
</P>
<P>
   It's an expensive solution, though, even if _ as I'm sure is the
case _ Apple is getting the chips at a bargain price. (It is, after
all, the only real customer for the desktop versions of the
PowerPC.)
</P>
<P>
   For the long haul, Apple and its PowerPC partners will have to
get their chip back on a performance curve parallel to Intel's, or
even loyal Mac artists might again be tempted to jump ship.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as one cynic sitting near me at the Jobs keynote put it,
``Next year we'll be sitting here listening to him tell us four
processors are going to come in every Power Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
