u p BC-BUSH-CHENEY-2TAKES-NY     07-24 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDER BUSH KEPT A WATCHFUL EYE OVER SON'S CHOICE FOR NO. 2
</HEADLINE>
 By FRANK BRUNI with ERIC SCHMITT 
   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the main lobby of the George Bush
Presidential Library, about 90 miles east of here, Dick Cheney has
a prominent place in an enormous oil painting that is the first and
pretty much only thing to catch a visitor's eye.
</P>
<P>
   It is a portrait of former President Bush in the Oval Office
during perhaps the most critical juncture of his presidency, the
Persian Gulf War, and Cheney, his defense secretary, is in a huddle
of advisers helping to guide Bush through those geopolitical
straits.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cheney is back in the picture, back in the center of
another Bush's political career and poised once again to provide
his loyal assistance at a pivotal time. A senior Republican
official said Monday said Gov. George W. Bush, the
soon-to-be-crowned Republican presidential nominee, had decided to
choose Cheney as his running mate, and would announce his choice as
early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That development, prophesied for several days, showed that
Cheney had become as important to the son as he was to the father.
And to some degree, it undoubtedly reflected the high regard in
which former President Bush had long held Cheney, a level of
respect that was almost bound to be inherited by the Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has told reporters that he spoke repeatedly with his father
as he pondered his choice of a running mate, and there were other
hints that the former president maintained a watchful eye over the
process, and maybe put a finger or two in it as well. On Friday,
for example, the elder Bush called a cardiac surgeon in Houston who
is a family friend to enlist his help in determining whether
Cheney, who had suffered mild heart attacks more than a decade ago,
was up to the rigors of a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, Chase Untermeyer, the director of presidential
personnel during the Bush administration, recalled a conversation
that occurred about a month ago in Kennebunkport, Maine, between
the former president and Brent Scowcroft, who served as his
national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   According to Untermeyer, Scowcroft told Bush that he had talked
to Cheney in the previous two weeks, and that Cheney had decided he
was interested in the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember President Bush making a powerful mental note of
that,'' said Untermeyer in a telephone interview Monday. ``He
expressed great interest and surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the former president and advisers to the Bush
campaign said that they did not know if former President Bush and
Cheney had spoken directly over the last few weeks, and the precise
nature and extent of the former president's involvement in his
son's selection process is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But the former president apparently knew more than even some of
the governor's advisers did. A close friend of the Bush family said
that for several days now, the father could not resist making
friends and associates aware that he possessed the inside scoop on
who his son's running mate would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been teasing us unmercifully,'' said the friend.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the former president's involvement, it was also
clear that his son forged his own bond with Cheney long before the
last few months, when Cheney supervised a vice presidential
selection process for the Texas governor that ended, oddly enough,
with Cheney as the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Former Secretary of State George P. Shultz recalled an evening
in early 1999 when he and Cheney, a chief executive with
Halliburton, an energy company based in Dallas, were invited to the
Texas governor's mansion here for dinner and an overnight stay. The
governor was then pondering a presidential candidacy, and he wanted
their advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat around for two to three hours in the evening, just
talking about everything under the sun from foreign policy to
domestic politics,'' Shultz said in a telephone interview Monday.
``Governor Bush was forever turning to Cheney, asking him what he
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor likes him,'' Shultz said. ``He has his confidence
and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Cheney, Bush turned to someone whose history with
the Bush family is a long, rich and active one. And that history,
several people who know the governor said, gave the Texas governor
the kind of comfort in Cheney that he almost insists on having in
his closest political associates.
</P>
<P>
   But with Cheney's selection, Bush also summoned the shadow of
his father, and was sure to rekindle debates in the coming days
over just how firmly his political fortunes were tied to his
patrimony. Additionally, Bush, who has used his status as a
governor to style himself as a candidate who would bring an
outsider's perspective to Washington, ultimately cast his lot with
the ultimate insider, someone who spent more years inside the
Beltway than perhaps anyone else on Bush's list of vice
presidential prospects.
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of a century ago, Cheney served first as
deputy chief of staff _ and then chief of staff _ for President
Gerald Ford. Cheney, who was only in his mid-30s, was obviously a
rising Republican star. Bush, who was director of the CIA under
Ford, took ample note of that, his friends said.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Bush noticed that Cheney was a keeper,'' said one
close friend. ``President Bush collects people. Smart people do
that. Smart people collect people.''
</P>
<P>
   After Cheney ran for, and was elected to, a congressional seat
from Wyoming in 1978, he quickly became one of the leading
Republican voices in the House. As vice president from 1981 to
1989, Bush played a leading role as President Ronald Reagan's
liaison to Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until Bush was elected president and picked
Cheney to be his defense secretary that the two men truly became
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't really close to the dad until after the 1988
election, when he joined the Cabinet,'' said one of Cheney's
associates. The associate said that Cheney, who always sat on
Bush's left during Cabinet meetings, proved his loyalty and
discretion, two qualities prized in the Bush family as much as any
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to who Bush senior could rely on for total
discretion, there was Brent Scowcroft and Dick Cheney,'' the
associate said.
</P>
<P>
   But what sealed their bond, friends and associates said, was the
Persian Gulf War. Bush's friends and associates said that he
considered the challenge of managing that conflict to be a defining
moment not just in his political career but in his life. The former
president, in his recently published book of letters and diary
entries, wrote about the solace he derived from Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is constant,'' Bush wrote in a diary entry from
Feb. 20, 1991. But he added that ``oddly enough,'' with Cheney,
among others, at his side, ``I still feel content.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Bond, a former chairman of the Republican National
Committee who knows Bush well, said, ``They all went through the
soul-searing experience of a war, and they got even closer.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the former president said that there were parameters
to the relationship, given that Cheney was Bush's subordinate and
so much younger. When the former president, now 76, held a 75th
birthday party for his wife, Barbara, in Kennebunkport last month,
Cheney, 59, was not among the nearly 200 people who were invited.
</P>
<P>
   But Jean Becker, the president's current chief of staff,
nonetheless described them as ``close friends.'' She noted that in
the winter, when Bush lives in Houston, he occasionally goes
hunting with Cheney, who lives in Dallas. They took a hunting trip
together earlier this year, Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent Republicans in Washington said that it would
be easy to make too much of the relationship between Cheney and the
elder Bush as a factor in the Texas governor's decision. They noted
that because the former president had such a long, varied and
prominent political career, many of his son's prospective vice
presidential selections had ties to him.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. John C. Danforth of Missouri, for example,
vigorously defended President Bush's nomination of Clarence Thomas
to the Supreme Court. And Elizabeth Dole was President Bush's
secretary of labor.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, advisers to the Texas governor said that the
younger Bush's path crossed with Cheney even after the end of his
father's administration in early 1993. The fact that Cheney had
become a prominent businessman in Texas by the time Bush was
elected governor in 1994 guaranteed that they would run into each
other, these advisers said, and the two men did, in ways that
apparently left an impression on the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush talked about him over the years,'' one adviser said.
``He'd say, `Cheney said this. Cheney said that.' It was clear they
talked to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   And during the early stages of Bush's presidential candidacy
last year, the adviser said, Bush sometimes alluded to Cheney
himself considered running for president in 1996. ``He would say,
`This is how Cheney approached the issue in 1995,''' the adviser
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Several advisers said that the emphatic lack of interest that
Cheney initially stated about the No. 2 job, a resistance that
apparently began to soften faster than was previously believed,
probably only heightened the governor's interest in him as a
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush takes pride in what he sees as the charming, persuasive
effect he can have on people who spend enough time around him, and
Cheney may be proof of his prowess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
