<HEADER>
A1803 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INVESTING-DOMASH-SFCH     07-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-DOMASH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ONLINE INVESTING: DAY TRADERS DON'T SET STOCK PRICES  &HT;     By HARRY DOMASH 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Judging from media hype, you would think day
traders are primarily responsible for moving stock prices. Wrong.
It's really mutual funds and other institutional investors such as
trust funds and pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Quest Diagnostic, a provider of clinical laboratory
services. Shares in the company moved from a low of $23 in October
to about $100 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Quest has 44 million outstanding shares. Of those, almost 23
million, or more than 50 percent, are owned by 135 institutional
investors. According to Morningstar, the Vanguard Health Care Fund
alone held 2.4 million shares as of March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 400,000 shares of Quest trade on an average day. That
means institutions hold more than 50 times the average daily
trading volume. So a small amount of buying or selling on the part
of institutional holders can significantly influence the stock
price.
</P>
<P>
   The same math keeps funds and other institutions from moving
quickly in and out of a stock. A fund wanting to take a new
position in Quest would have to move slowly to avoid pushing up the
stock price with its buying. In practice, it can take a fund
manager a couple of months or longer to establish a new position or
to move out of an existing position in a stock.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, you can make better investing decisions if you know
which stocks the institutions are buying and selling.
</P>
<P>
   LionShares.com ( &LR; www.lionshares.com &LR; ) can help you find out.
Institutional investors are required to periodically file reports
with the Securities and Exchange Commission detailing their stock
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   LionShares.com maintains a database of institutional stock
holdings extracted from these filings. Use of the site is free, but
you have to register to access most of the data.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. Register first so you can follow along with
me.
</P>
<P>
   I'll use Fidelity as an example. Fidelity operates more than 300
mutual funds. Although each fund usually has an individual manager,
a common research department supplies the same analysis to all
managers interested in a specific industry.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, a stock favored by a research analyst will
probably be held by a number of Fidelity funds. Conversely, most
fund managers will unload stocks out of favor with its sector
analyst. ``Once in, Fidelity funds tend to hold positions for a
considerable time,'' said Glenn Tanner, LionShares.com's general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see what we can learn by examining Fidelity's holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Start by typing ``Fidelity'' into the data box at the top and
click Search. Be sure the ``by holder name'' search choice is
selected. Click on ``Fidelity Management &AMP; Research Co.'' from the
list.
</P>
<P>
   Scroll down and you'll see the top 15 combined holdings of all
U.S. Fidelity funds, in terms of market value.
</P>
<P>
   When I looked last week, Cisco Systems, General Electric,
Microsoft and Intel comprised Fidelity's top four holdings. The
``Position'' column listed the number of shares held as of March
31, and the ``$ Mkt Val'' column showed the market value of those
shares as of June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where it gets interesting. Click on ``Position Change,''
the change in the number of shares held during the three-month
period. The largest additions to Fidelity funds' combined
portfolios were in Cisco Systems, Nortel Networks, Micron
Technology and Texas Instruments (ignore lines without ticker
symbols or market value numbers, those are debt instruments).
</P>
<P>
   Although already considered highly valued by many experts,
Fidelity managers were still loading up on those stocks during the
first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Click on the arrow to the left of the ``Position Change'' column
header to sort the list in the opposite direction. Now stocks
Fidelity managers sold the most during the quarter are listed
first. Topping the list when I looked were WorldCom, Philip Morris,
FleetBoston Financial and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``Sector Summary'' in the middle column above the stock
list to see the market value of Fidelity's holdings by industry
sector. Technology and Communication Services were the only sectors
with increases in market value in the March quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Beware. That doesn't mean Fidelity's managers added shares to
those sectors during the period. The market value could have
increased solely because the share prices increased.
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``Health Care'' to see a list of industries within the
overall health care sector. As you may recall, biotech stocks took
a wild ride early this year, soaring in January and crashing in
March. Click on ``Biotechnology'' to see what Fidelity's managers
were doing in the biotech sector in the March quarter.
</P>
<P>
   You'll see that Fidelity fund managers were busy reducing most
of their biotech positions. Click on ``Position Change'' to sort
the list so the stocks with the largest purchases are listed first.
Fidelity managers added 3 million shares of Medarex and about 2
million shares each of Supergen Cor Therapeutics and Alexion
Pharmaceuticals to their cumulative holdings during the first three
months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   You have to think Fidelity managers saw something positive in
these companies to load up on shares while they were dumping the
sector in general. It's intriguing information. By itself, this is
not a signal to buy the stocks. But these are good research ideas
if you're interested in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio information compiled by LionShare.com can be
months out of date. The value of the data depends upon how fast the
funds change their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Funds with high turnover rates probably won't own the same
stocks by the time you see the data.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be better off looking at fund families with low turnover
rates. These, along with Fidelity, should give you a good start to
using institutional buying to spot invest ment candidates. They
are: Firsthand Capital Management, Janus Capital Group and Oak
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Harry Domash lives in Aptos, Calif., and publishes the Winning
Investing newsletter. You can read his columns at
 &LR; www.winninginvesting.com &LR;  or contact him at
 &LR; hdomash(AT)winninginvesting.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
