<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1805 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-CART-RACE-HNS &LR;      07-24 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-RACE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CART leader Andretti knows he has miles to go
</P>
<P>
   By TERRY BLOUNT
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Michael Andretti has been around long enough to know that
holding a slim points lead in July is a long way from winning a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti took over the top spot in the standings for the CART
FedEx championship with his second-place finish to Juan Montoya in
the Michigan 500 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leading the points right now isn't the biggest thing,''
Andretti said. ``Finishing well each race is the most important
thing. I said that Michigan and Fontana (California) are two races
where we had to do well, and we're halfway there now.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti was only about five feet away from earning four more
points, falling four-hundredths of a second short of Montoya at the
checkered flag in one of the most exciting finishes in CART
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disappointment to lose such a close finish,''
Andretti said. ``But it's big consolation for us to take the points
lead for the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, who drives the Texaco Ford-Lola, entered the race two
points behind Roberto Moreno but now leads Moreno by 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno had gearbox problems in the Visteon Ford-Reynard and
dropped out of the race early, finishing 23rd. It was the second
consecutive race in which Moreno failed to score a point, allowing
Andretti to gain 36 points on him in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sad day for us,'' Moreno said. ``We've had two bad
races in a row, so hopefully the bad luck is out of the way. We'll
be competitive in Chicago (this weekend).
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is strong, and there's no reason to believe we won't
stay in contention. I'm confident we'll be back stronger than ever
and fighting for the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   With nine races remaining on the 2000 CART schedule, four
drivers are within 30 points of Andretti, and five others are
within 44 points, the total number of points a driver could earn in
two races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked up some points (Sunday) and kept some momentum going
into Chicago,'' said Paul Tracy, who finished seventh at Brooklyn,
Mich., and held his No. 3 spot in the championship, 24 points
behind Andretti. ``We didn't lose touch with the (points) leaders,
and that's the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who has battled his way back into contention is Montoya,
the defending FedEx champion. The 24-year-old Colombian has
overcome a slow start and moved up to fifth in the standings, only
30 points behind Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our second podium finish, and we won both those
races,'' Montoya said. ``Obviously, if we can start finishing more
races, we will be right up there for the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti believes Montoya will be a force down the stretch and
probably will be near the top by the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid is really good,'' Andretti said of Montoya. ``He
deserves the praise he's getting. He's definitely for real. When he
goes to F1, I believe he is going to give Michael Schumacher a run
for his money.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya won the CART title on a tiebreaker last season. Dario
Franchitti earned the same number of points as Montoya, but Montoya
won the championship because he had more victories.
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti, who finished third at Michigan, has weathered a
disappointing season and ranks 11th with 58 points. He probably is
out of contention but isn't giving up yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been near the top much this season, but we saw last
year that the championship can go down to the last lap of the last
race,'' Franchitti said. ``This is going to be close all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the drivers in the top 10 seem to agree with Franchitti
because no one has dominated the series this season. Three drivers
_ Montoya, Andretti and Gil de Ferran _ have won twice, and five
other drivers have won once.
</P>
<P>
   ``With nine races still to go, things are so close that anything
can happen,'' said Adrian Fernandez, who finished sixth at
Michigan. ``We scored some points (Sunday) and moved up in the
championship battle. That's what you have to do every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti agrees. His only championship came in 1991, but he has
been the series runner-up five times and believes he has learned a
thing or two about what it takes to end up on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to finish,'' Andretti said. ``We might not win every
race the rest of the way, and we might not be on the podium for all
of them, but if we keep having strong finishes, we're going to be
there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the drivers in the top 10 have yet to win a
championship, including Tracy, who feels a CART FedEx title is the
one thing that would make his career complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual achievements are great,'' Tracy said. ``I've won a
lot of races, and I've got a lot of things in the (record) book
that are nice. But the championship is what it's all about. That's
what we're all here to do.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
