<SLUG> BC-BOFA-HIERARCHY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LAST GASP FOR BANK OF AMERICA ENTITIES  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At Bank of America, the final power grab is
under way.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, NationsBank bought the San Francisco
financial giant and took its name. Now, executives of the North
Carolina bank are seizing control of the last stronghold of the old
BofA _ the global, corporate and investment banking division based
here.
</P>
<P>
   The division's chief, Michael Murray, was the lone survivor from
the old BofA among the combined bank's top-ranking leadership. A
month ago, he announced his retirement, paving the way for a
sweeping shift of control from old BofA managers to their
NationsBank counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Murray stepped down, his replacement, longtime
NationsBank corporate banker Ed Brown, unveiled a far-reaching
reorganization of the unit.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a subtle plan. All four of Brown's key deputies are
now former NationsBank executives. And all top managers from the
old BofA find either that their authority has been slashed or they
have been assigned new bosses lower on the corporate totem poll _
or both.
</P>
<P>
   Now BofA watchers are asking whether the next shoe to drop will
be the move of the global division's headquarters to North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   If so, that would break the promise NationsBank made when it
bought BofA _ to keep wholesale banking headquartered here. And it
would leave San Francisco as no more than a regional outpost for
the bank, on par with Jacksonville, Fla., and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is based in San Francisco and the city officially remains
the division's headquarters. ``I'm here and I'm staying,'' Brown
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most executives based in San Francisco were effectively
demoted and all of the unit's other key officers now work
elsewhere, raising the question of whether the city will be the
division's headquarters in name only.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flow of power and responsibility continues to go east or,
better said, (to) the Southeast,'' said John Wilson, a recruiter
with the executive search firm Korn/Ferry International.
</P>
<P>
   The global, corporate and investment bank is one of the world's
largest wholesale banking operations. It does business in 38
countries, vies with Chase Manhattan for the title of largest U.S.
corporate lender and owns the former Montgomery Securities, renamed
Bank of America Securities, a major investment bank. More than
2,000 people work for the division in the Bay Area, many of them in
the securities unit.
</P>
<P>
   You might say what's happening to the division is deja vu all
over again, duplicating NationsBank's take-charge tactics in
consumer banking during the takeover's early days.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first fights between the old BofA's chief executive,
David Coulter, and his NationsBank counterpart, Hugh McColl,
concerned the appointment of a NationsBank executive to run retail
operations in the West.
</P>
<P>
   It took longer for NationsBank to make its move in the wholesale
arena because the old BofA was by far the bigger of the two banks
in the business. Before the takeover, NationsBank had only a
nascent overseas operation and was far behind BofA in accounts with
big corporations.
</P>
<P>
   When the banks divided top jobs in 1998, there was little debate
about giving the global and corporate portfolio to Murray, the old
BofA manager. Brown became his deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 56, originally planned to hand power over to Brown
sometime in 2001. But he decided to advance his departure because
he was beginning to feel like ``a fifth wheel,'' he told The
Chronicle in an interview last month.
</P>
<P>
   Once Murray was out of the way, Brown put his own people in
place. As his key reports, he selected four NationsBank executives,
two based in North Carolina and one each in Chicago and New York.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco executives from the old BofA were the big losers.
International banking chief Robert Morrow, for example, lost
responsibility for Europe, which was transferred to Charlotte
executive Tom Bunn. Morrow, who formerly reported to Brown, now
works for Bunn.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, San Francisco executives Timothy Bottoms, who manages
North American credit products, and Richard Harris, who runs the
bank's leasing unit, previously reported to Brown or Murray. Now
their bosses are more-junior executives.
</P>
<P>
   And Jeremy Fair, formerly chief of U.S. corporate banking, lost
his job to NationsBank executive Graham Denton. A bank spokesman
said Fair will be offered another senior position.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brown said he didn't care whether managers came
from the BofA side or the NationsBank side when he handed out
assignments. And he said he wants everyone to stay. ``Everybody has
been offered a job. No one has been asked to leave,'' he stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically about Morrow, Brown said Bunn was the logical
choice to manage European operations because he already manages
leveraged finance, the bank's top-priority product on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   The division's shifting center of gravity is paralleled at Bank
of America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   With its home office in the Transamerica Pyramid, the old
Montgomery Securities was a mainstay of San Francisco's Financial
District. Lewis Coleman, formerly the unit's chief in San
Francisco, now reports to New York executive Carter McClelland.
</P>
<P>
   While New York executives now manage investment banking, San
Francisco will remain the base for brokerage operations for the
foreseeable future, Brown said. Securities sales and trading
operations are anchored here because the bank opened a
state-of-the-art trading floor in the Pyramid a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
