 REGULATORS PLAN RULES TO SIMPLIFY PHONE BILLS  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ State regulators in California plan to propose a
new set of rules Monday to force telephone companies to simplify
their bills and disclose key terms to customers.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Los Angeles, the National Association of
Regulatory Utility Commissioners is expected to unveil the
``truth-in-billing guidelines,'' which could serve as a model for
each state.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, which must still be formally approved by the group
later this week, are similar to guidelines already approved by the
Federal Communications Commission. The move underscores the growing
role of state regulators in protecting consumers from phone
companies, including interstate long-distance companies and
cellular giants.
</P>
<P>
   States need their own rules because they don't always have the
authority to enforce federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, California joined five other states in suing
WorldCom for false advertising and improperly billing customers.
And several states also sued AT&AMP;T and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really happening is that enforcing (telecommunications
rules) are falling more and more to the states,'' said Joan Smith,
a commissioner with the Oregon Public Utility Commission, who is
scheduled to field questions at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the FCC is increasingly looking to the states for
help because complaints are soaring against long-distance
companies. A recent study found that complaints against WorldCom
and AT&AMP;T tripled over the past three years nationwide. And growing
competition has also boosted the number of companies selling
service. ``There is no way (the FCC) can handle it all alone,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC has also specifically taken action to give states more
authority to go after long-distance companies for slamming, or
switching customers' service without permission. In the past,
states often had to refer complaints to the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Chairman William Kennard, who is from Los Angeles, is also
scheduled to appear at the news conference. ``It's a signal that he
sees a very important role for the states,'' said Carl Wood, a
commissioner with the California Public Utilities Commission, who
will also attend.
</P>
<P>
   California is already in the process of hammering out its own
guidelines as part of a Telecommunications Bill of Rights. Indeed,
the national group borrowed its preamble almost entirely from a
California staff report on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, William Schulte, director of the state PUC's
consumer services division, helped craft the national guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the proposals, included in a draft of the document,
include making sure that telephone companies use the same name on
the bills as they use to market the service. Companies would also
be required to highlight any new services or changes in rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overarching goal ... is to help the consumer understand
better what is sold to them and not be confused,'' said William
Gillis, a commissioner with the Washington Utilities Transportation
Commission, who heads the regulatory group's consumer affairs
committee.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
