the Web will play a central role in reporting and interpreting the
campaign's dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   The ``2000 Elections'' category in Yahoo's directory includes a
mind-boggling 1,214 sites (or so Yahoo says _ I confess I didn't
count).  &UR; COLUMN BY HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BIOSCOPE (COLUMN) _  &LR; Leading consumer and environmental groups are
fuming because the Clinton administration has appointed a former
Monsanto Corp. lobbyist to represent U.S. consumers on a
transatlantic committee set up to avoid a trade war over
genetically engineered foods.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. farmers have planted millions of acres of corn and other
crops that have been genetically engineered to resist pests, and
the growers want to export such produce freely. But in Europe,
where genetically altered crops have been dubbed Frankenfoods,
governments have imposed labeling rules and safety tests that have
restricted U.S. imports.  &UR; COLUMN BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WIRELESS _  &LR; Stewart Lin has mixed feelings about his Internet
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Lin, a San Francisco computer consultant who is often on the
road, said the phone is ideal for scanning e-mail and checking San
Francisco Giants baseball scores. He even logged on from the 14th
hole of the Pebble Beach golf club and watched the practice round
for the U.S. Open last month.  &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FCC _  &LR; State regulators in California plan to propose a new set of
rules Monday to force telephone companies to simplify their bills
and disclose key terms to customers.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Los Angeles, the National Association of
Regulatory Utility Commissioners is expected to unveil the
``truth-in-billing guidelines,'' which could serve as a model for
each state.  &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
