<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-24 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE NEW YORK WAY OF LIFE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Talk magazine editor  &UR; Tina Brown &LR;  went to the Four Seasons _ the
in-crowd's hangout _ in Manhattan the other night, &LR;  and came upon
former Mayor  &UR; Ed Koch &LR;  chowing down with former Police Commissioner
 &UR; William Bratton &LR; . According to New York magazine, she stopped by
their table and mentioned they might like to read Talk magazine's
July story about  &UR; Rudolph Giuliani &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   They each told her that they would check it out as soon as
possible. ``By the time dessert was served,'' says New York, ``a
messenger arrived at the restaurant with copies of Talk that Brown
had ordered expressly for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Harper's Bazaar reports on the shopping habits of
people who always get their ways and their things. ``This is what
happens,'' says  &UR; David Ingram &LR; , fashion consultant at Barneys New
York. ``The weather changes radically in the middle of the day, and
suddenly they're no longer dressed right. They'll call from the
street, tell me what they're wearing, and I'll run around the store
to find something better by the time they get here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, this can work only with someone whose wardrobe I
know so well she can say, `I'm wearing the pistachio capri pants.
Can I come up?'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AND THE SAN FRANCISCO WAY OF LIFE  &LR;  _ The Friends of the
Bancroft Library at University of California at Berkeley has just
published ``Uncertain Country'' ($20), a series of letters written
by  &UR; Benjamin Wingate &LR;  and his family 150 years ago, selected and
edited by &UR; Stephen Vincent &LR; . Wingate worked as an accountant in San
Francisco from 1850 to 1854; he wrote to his family in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a young man, I should certainly settle here,'' he
wrote in 1852. ``... I can get everything I want to eat, drink or
wear, here, as well as in New York, or Boston. The market is well
supplied with everything. Indeed it is much better furnished with
some things, than is desirable. Cards, dice, painted women, obscene
prints, gin cock-tails and brandy-smashers are in large demand and
full supply. But then to meet and oppose them, there are churches,
Sabbath schools, active temperance societies, libraries, reading
rooms, many good families and a large number of well-principled and
consistent men. ... Many sanguine and successful persons describe
California as a Paradise. Others of a sour and bilious temperament,
who are disappointed and homesick, paint it as the hot-bed of
iniquity, from which all good men should escape. ... The truth lies
between them.''
</P>
<P>
   - Reading ``Westward Tilt: The American West Today,'' written by
 &UR; Neil Morgan &LR;  and published in 1961,  &UR; Steve Finacom  &LR; came across
this description of a typical ``new San Franciscan'':
</P>
<P>
   ``He is often pictured as a crew-cut young man on Montgomery
Street, an apprentice financier, perhaps, or an advertising man.
... He is pleasantly titillated about the contemporary city, and he
finds it in vogue to be alarmed by the new freeways which obstruct
some views of the bay and disgorge great traffic jams into
downtown. He is knowledgeable about restaurants and a bit of a jazz
buff.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been big change since then, of course. The freeways are
down.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AROUND TOWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Pianist and connoisseur of popular music of days gone by  &UR; Peter &LR; 
 &UR; Mintun &LR;  announced at a 50th birthday party  &UR; Nancy Hamon  &LR; threw for
him last week that he is moving to New York. Mintun, who was born
in Berkeley and is a fourth-generation Californian, has a
61/2-months-a-year gig at Bemelmans cq &LR;  Bar at the Carlyle Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shirley MacLaine &LR; , who was in town promoting her new book,
``The Camino,'' went to ``Beach Blanket Babylon'' on Friday, told
the cast she'd been conversing with the late  &UR; Steve Silver &LR; , who
created the show, and had dinner at the North Beach Restaurant
afterward with Mayor  &UR; Willie Brown &LR; ,  &UR; Charlotte Shultz &LR; ,  &UR; Ann Caen &LR; 
and  &UR; Stanlee Gatti &LR; , all of whom have had many lives.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at a soiree that Tiburon literary agent  &UR; Kimberley &LR; 
 &UR; Cameron  &LR; threw for  &UR; Larry Ashmead &LR; , the HarperCollins head
described his first ``nocturnal submission'': his discovery of a
book manuscript an agent had tucked into his bed during a party
he'd once had in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And peace must be at hand: On the eve of last week's opening of
the Jewish Film Festival _ three films of which are co-sponsored by
the Arab Film Festival _ four women from the Arab festival hosted
four women from the Jewish festival having their hands painted with
henna.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Promoting his novel, ``American Rhapsody'' last week on
``Talk of the Nation,''  &UR; Joe Eszterhas &LR;  said he is 50 years old. A
chum who used to be the same age says the writer, who's been
scornful of Hollywood lies and hypocrisy, seems to have misplaced a
half decade.
</P>
