<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VOICESTREAM-DEUTSCHE-     07-24 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICESTREAM-DEUTSCHE-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE TELEKOM HIRING LOBBYISTS IN QUEST FOR VOICESTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (With VOICESTREAM-DEUTSCHE) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Deutsche Telekom's bid to enter the United States
begins a political battle over tricky regulatory questions and
fundamental trade policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications company whose majority stockholder is the
German government was scheduled Tuesday to formally announced its
intention to buy VoiceStream for $50.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But political opposition to the deal began to foment in
Washington during the publicized negotiations with VoiceStream,
including a legislative initiative in the Senate to block the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom has responded by retaining Lloyd Cutler, the
former White House counsel to Presidents Clinton and Carter.
Cutler's law firm, Wilmer, Cutler &AMP; Pickering, is engaged in a
three-pronged attack on behalf of its new client. It must persuade
Congress not to intervene, the White House to approve the deal and
the Federal Communications Commission to approve the transfer of
wireless telephone licenses.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the deal and the legislative and regulatory
fight said Cutler had turned to his golden Rolodex, urging
lawmakers and other officials not to stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telecom and VoiceStream have also hired more than half
a dozen lobbying and law firms with former White House officials
and congressional aides. They include Pat Griffin, the former top
White House lobbyist in the Clinton administration, and Dan Tate
Jr. of Cassidy &AMP; Associates, a former White House official and aide
to Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbying effort has begun to pay off. The White House
announced its opposition Monday to two separate pieces of
legislation drafted by Sen. Ernest F. Hollings and supported by
many top lawmakers that could derail the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the Communications Workers of America, a significant
lobbying force in its own right, recently sent a letter to Congress
supporting the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The deal's fate, though, will probably not be in the hands of
President Clinton or William Kennard, the FCC chairman, who Monday
again promised he would scrutinize the acquisition closely. Since
reviews by the FCC and a host of other government agencies almost
certainly cannot be completed before 2001, it will be up to the
next president and the next chief of the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   The primary issue is the ownership of Deutsche Telekom. More
than half of its stock is controlled by the German government, and
even after the deal is completed, the government's stake will be 45
percent, far more than the 25 percent limit generally permitted by
federal communications law.
</P>
<P>
   But the company and some lawyers say the law also contains an
important exception for deals deemed to be in the public interest _
a test, they say, that is satisfied because the German government
belongs to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom plans to convey a message that at a time of
rapid consolidation, the deal brings a new player to the table,
increasing competition by lowering prices and encouraging
innovation in the wireless telephone market.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives at the two companies said Monday in a telephone
interview that they would come to Washington this week to convey
that theme to the Federal Communications Commission and to other
officials who have expressed skepticism about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the rhetoric about the transaction in Washington is
merely an attempt by our large competitors to keep us from having
access to resources to become competitive,'' said John Stanton, the
chief executive of VoiceStream. ``This is pro-consumer and
pro-competitive. It will create another large national competitor
in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Deutsche Telekom plan to pump $5 billion in new
investments into VoiceStream even before the deal is completed to
participate in an upcoming auction over spectrum licenses is widely
hailed as good news at the FCC, which has been trying to stimulate
as much interest, and as many large bids, as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory battle pits a pre-World War II federal
communications law aimed at discouraging foreign investment in the
United States against a 1997 World Trade Organization agreement on
telecommunications services that was meant to do the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that the FCC appears to have the authority to
approve the deal, even though the law is murky. But Congress is
flirting with changing the law and eliminating any ambiguities.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Hollings, a Democrat from South Carolina, renewed his
criticism of the deal and vowed to press forward with legislation
supported by a number of congressional leaders, including the
majority and minority leaders, that would block the deal. Hollings
has sponsored two measures that would block the deal.
</P>
<P>
   One is a rider to an appropriations bill that would prevent the
FCC from approving the deal for a year. A second bill would
permanently block the deal as long as the German government owned
more than 25 percent of Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollings' legislation suffered a setback when the White
House announced that it could not support the legislation because
it was unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that these various regulatory and antitrust reviews
can address the senator's concern and new legislation is not
necessary,'' said Jake Seiwert, a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Deutsche Telekom's potential rivals in the United States
have urged lawmakers to step in, maintaining that it would be
unfair to permit entry in the United States of a foreign company
that enjoys the backing of a foreign government. The competitors
have laid low, congressional aides say, in part because they have
interests in possibly expanding abroad and in part because they
want to leave the door open to foreign investments in their
companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
