A1812 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-NIEMAN-BOS &LR;      07-24 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NIEMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILES TO BE NAMED HEAD OF NIEMAN FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Giles, 67, the former Detroit News editor and publisher
whose candidacy reignited resentment over the five-year old Detroit
newspaper strike, is expected to be named curator of Harvard
University's Nieman Foundation Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Harvard nor Giles was available for comment Monday. But
word of his appointment to head the nation's most prestigious
journalism fellowship program was posted on the online version of
Editor &AMP; Publisher Monday. Another source, who requested
confidentiality, informed the Globe of Harvard's decision to choose
Giles, whose selection as curator had seemed imminent several weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Giles, senior vice president at The Freedom Forum, saw his
bid threatened by a lobbying campaign conducted by unions and
journalists critical of his role during the strike. In late June,
Metropolitan Detroit AFL-CIO president Donald W. Boggs and
Newspaper Guild president Linda K. Foley sent letters asking
Harvard President Neil Rudenstine to reject Giles as curator,
complaining that he was a polarizing figure during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper Guild of Detroit president Lou Mleczko said Monday
that the ``local is very disappointed'' to hear that Harvard had
put the leadership of ``such a venerable and respected program in
the hands of what we feel is a mediocre candidate, at best.'
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the union complaints, some of Giles's colleagues
began weighing in on his behalf. Sandra Mims Rowe, editor of The
(Portland) Oregonian, told the Globe that the attack on Giles's
strike record was ``unjust'' given his ``substantial contributions
to journalism.'' And four officers of the American Society of
Newspaper Editors recently signed a letter to Rudenstine supportive
of Giles.
</P>
<P>
   Giles's appointment would end Harvard's tortuous efforts to
replace Bill Kovach, the respected former editor of the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, as Nieman curator. The school failed to land
several of its top candidates, Globe columnist Ellen Goodman and
new Los Angeles Times editor John Carroll. At one point, the
National Association of Black Journalists suggested that Harvard
consider several minority candidates, adding that the process could
benefit from a ``diverse pool'' of contenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
