<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-NETHERLANDS-CO     07-24 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NETHERLANDS-COAST-$ADV30-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING AWAY, THE DUTCH WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   In summer
when the local population is augmented by the swarm of tourists
that descend on Amsterdam, walking the web of streets and alleys
that crisscross the canals can be exhausting. At any time of year,
this densely populated city can feel crowded.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those who want a bit of an escape, there is a serene
counterpoint to the city's bustle just a half-hour out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Volendam is a fishing village on the coast of what was called
the Zuider Zee until 1932, when the Dutch government built a dike
that closed it off from the sea. Visitors can get there either by
car or by bus, which runs every 30 minutes from Amsterdam's Central
Station _ a 15-minute walk from the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   Volendam's harbor is ringed with two- and three-story houses
painted in cheerful tones of green, black and red, their windows
immaculately trimmed in white. Larger European harbors are often
crowded with speed boats, but there was only one docked in Volendam
the day my son, David, and I visited last summer. Instead, small
modern sailboats or old wood-bottomed fishing boats rested at the
slips. Their owners still earn their living catching herring, eel
and shrimp. The day we sat drinking koffie verkeerd _ the Dutch
version of cafe au lait _ ``The Mermaid,'' a double-masted old wood
clipper, sailed into port, manned by local fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Volendam's boats were only part of the pleasure. The real treat
was watching the Dutch sky, with clouds rapidly bunching and
dispersing, hiding and revealing the sun. A sailboat glided into a
sunlit sliver of sea that darkened to black as a cloud bank swept
across.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, Anne, who lives near Utrecht, advised us to go in
the morning when the town was likely to be most tranquil, and it
was relatively deserted (on weekends, it is a popular excursion
from Amsterdam).
</P>
<P>
   After watching the boats, we boarded the half-empty ferry for
the 30-minute ride to Marken, an island until 1957, when it was
joined to the mainland by a causeway. Creating the causeway
provoked outrage among Marken's independent and ecologically minded
citizens. The deeply religious Calvinist population lives a life
somewhat less removed from that of its mainland counterparts than
it once was. The 3,000 inhabitants used to support themselves as
fishermen; today many commute from their small wooden homes to
surrounding towns to work in a variety of trades. The day I
visited, the tiny town was quiet, and there was little traffic.
Residents have all painted their wooden homes either a somber green
or black. But the interiors of the little two-story houses are
generally bright yellow and blue.
</P>
<P>
   Marken, which is ringed by ice in winter, had no electricity or
heat until 40 years ago, and in the Marker Museum, a spare, small
house museum at the port, the rigors of that earlier era are made
clear. Delft tiles telling biblical stories surround the fireplace
from floor to ceiling. The family depended on heat from the stove,
and all slept in a single room: the parents on the top of a
double-decker bed, and the children in a small bed beneath them.
</P>
<P>
   It is the queen's custom to visit one Dutch town on her birthday
each year. The guide, who was dressed in the traditional long gown
with a lace bodice, explained proudly that three years ago Queen
Beatrix had chosen to visit Marken.
</P>
<P>
   Though the weather was clear, the winds were so strong that the
hot chocolate on the ferry going back was welcome, even in summer.
</P>
<P>
   From Volendam, it was only a two-mile drive to Edam, home of
Edam cheese. Tour buses usually include Edam in their trips. We
drove, but the buses that leave Amsterdam's Central train station
every half hour for Volendam go on to Edam, which is also a port.
If you have the inclination, you can rent a bicycle and peddle your
way as many Dutch do.
</P>
<P>
   Edam is far wealthier than Volendam or Marken, and the houses
that line its main canal are substantial stone residences, though
some tilt slightly. Just across the broad arched pedestrian bridge
on Damplein _ the main square _ stands the Speeltheatre, an
18th-century building that recalls the town's once lively cultural
life.
</P>
<P>
   Edam's history began in the 12th century, when the Dutch settled
along the little Ye River _ hence ``Yedam.'' In its heyday as a
shipbuilding center, Edam's shipyard built the Halve Mann used by
Henry Hudson on his 1609 foray to find a northern route to the
Orient. He ended instead on the island of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Local stores will arrange to ship cheese almost anywhere in the
world, but before addressing any shipping slips, we tasted (at no
charge) a number of varieties of Edam at one of the several cheese
stores along the Damplein. The most prevalent Edam here comes in a
yellow wrapper and has a far sharper flavor than the red-packaged
version that is a staple in the United States. My favorite was the
aged Edam. The wedge we bought was gone by the time we returned to
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   If Volendam and Marken are quiet counterpoints to Amsterdam,
Haarlem is a sophisticated but diminutive version of its larger
neighbor and has become a popular residential area for wealthy
Dutch who work in Amsterdam. We made the half-hour drive by car,
but trains leave Amsterdam's Central Station every 10 minutes for
the 20-minute trip.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape painters Salomon van Ruysdael and his nephew Jacob
van Ruisdael (who spelled their surnames differently) were born
here. Frans Hals spent most of his career in Haarlem, painting
everyone from the local power elite to common folk in the pubs.
Today there is a good-sized museum in Haarlem that houses nine
important Hals paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling main square, where one is likely to see residents
arrive on bicycles built for two, is just five minutes from the
train station. It sits in the shadow of St. Bavo, a church built
between 1400 and 1550, the successor to one first mentioned in
1313. Though its exterior is dark and foreboding, the interior is
surprisingly light with white stone walls and 24 massive columns.
It is dominated by an organ built in 1738 by Christian Muller,
which has a special mystique because Mozart played it on a visit to
Haarlem in 1766. Lovers of organ music can check with the church
for a schedule of recitals, which are fairly frequent.
</P>
<P>
   The square boasts a fish market and a town hall. But before
stopping for coffee or lunch, meander over to the Frans Hals
Museum. The former orphanage, converted to a museum in 1913, is
built around a garden with clipped hedges and orange trees.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's great cache is a series of five Hals portraits of
the men who were then part of the local civil guards _ hung in a
single room. The subjects exhibit the robust energy and optimism
that is the hallmark of Hals' work. Unfortunately they are hung so
far above eye level it is difficult to examine them closely.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite was Hals' group portrait of the Governesses of the
Oudemannenhuis, an old men's house in Hals' day. That portrait is
in a separate room where the only sound was the whirring of the
humidifier as I studied the mean-spirited faces of the women who
once ran the hospice. So nasty are their expressions that it was
long believed, incorrectly, that Hals had been under their
supervision as a patient. However, he did paint the group portrait
when he was more than 80 years old, in 1664.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also houses portraits by other artists of the
Netherlands of the period including Jan Verspronck, Jan van Scorel
and Cornelis Cornelisz, offering a chance to study how Hals was
influenced by his predecessors and contemporaries _ and in relative
peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Following the winding Spaarne River brings you to the oldest
museum in the Netherlands, founded by a wealthy Mennonite silk
merchant and banker, Pieter Teijler. The Mennonites believed in
accumulating wealth, if it was used for noble causes. Teijler's
will created a foundation to promote religion, encouragement of the
arts and sciences and help for the poor. The Teylers Museum, built
shortly after the patron's death in 1778, houses his collection of
fossils, metals, scientific instruments, books and drawings by
Raphael, Rembrandt and Michelangelo, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Those with an interest in science will like the heliograph, an
astronomical telescope built in 1874 to observe and photograph the
transition of Venus over the Sun. It is housed in the most charming
room of the museum, a double-story space with a library on the
second floor.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Frans Hals Museum, this one fits easily into its
neighborhood, so that a visitor can sit in the pleasant cafe and
look across the backyard into neighboring houses, some still
cheerfully uncurtained as they were in the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   From the Teylers, it is only a short walk to the train station,
but I was tempted to stop by the Hals Museum once more. While
Marken had a naive charm, Volandam some lovely vistas, Edam its
prosperous homes and its cheeses, Haarlem offered both charm and
the chance to ponder some of the great art of the Netherlands in
welcome tranquillity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
