<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PUSHES FOR MIDEAST ACCORD 
 

</HEADLINE>
 TALKS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton kept pushing Israeli and
Palestinian leaders to make peace Monday as the Camp David summit
entered its third week and the parties continued to search for
common ground on which to build an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Just back from a whirlwind trip to Japan, Clinton plunged into
marathon negotiating sessions with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. After a few hours sleep, he
went back to it again hoping to persuade the long-time enemies to
compromise over their competing claims to Jerusalem, which has
become the major stumbling block to a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart described the talks as
``exhaustive and exhausting'' and said the president still believes
there is ``a realistic chance'' that an agreement can be reached.
But he acknowledged that controversial issues remain that will be
extremely difficult to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hesitate to use a phrase like `hopeful' (that an agreement
is near) because these issues are so difficult, and I don't know
that I would be able to back that up with any substance,'' said
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``the fact that these discussions are continuing
is a positive thing...and as long as we're here and discussing
things, there is a prospect for reaching an agreement. But it's
impossible to predict the likelihood of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to take another break from the talks today
to attend the funeral in Arkansas of Diane Blair, a close family
friend. He planned to return to Camp David tonight.
</P>
<P>
   After attending the economic summit in Japan, Clinton returned
to the talks on Sunday evening and went immediately into separate
meetings with Arafat and Barak. Later he had dinner with the two
leaders, and at midnight launched into another round of joint talks
with Palestinian, Israeli and U.S. negotiators that lasted until 5
a.m. At 10:30 a.m. Monday, he was back at it trying to force
concessions from both sides, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he was up until 5 a.m. working through the
issues in a very personal, hands-on way, and that he was back at it
again early this morning should lead you to believe that he thinks
staying here for the time being is worthwhile,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lockhart said the parties know ``that there is a balance
here between taking the time to work through the issues and taking
too much time that will never lead to an agreement.``
</P>
<P>
   The negotiating teams continued to maintain their vow of secrecy
in keeping with the news blackout that was imposed when the talks
began on July 11. But Israel's chief negotiator, Shlomo Ben-Ami,
told Israeli army radio that a ``final clarification'' of where the
talks stand will be made by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While shying away from any discussion of substance, he said the
parties had agreed Sunday night on Clinton's return to begin
around-the-clock negotiations aimed at forcing a final agreement or
an end to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   While Lockhart said that some ``areas of agreement'' have been
found by the Palestinians and Israelis, reports out of the Middle
East indicated that competing claims to Jerusalem, which is home to
holy sites for Jews, Muslims and Christians, remains the biggest
obstacle to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is demanding that the Palestinians be given sovereignty
over all of East Jerusalem, which was captured by the Israelis in
the 1967 war and annexed a year later. But so far Barak has
indicated that Jerusalem must remain undivided with the
Palestinians getting control of only some of the Arab neighborhoods
in the old eastern part of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Tayeb Abdel-Rahim, a senior Arafat aide who spoke with reporters
in Gaza Monday, said the talks have yet to resolve other core
issues as well, including where the final borders of a Palestinian
state will be drawn, the fate of Palestinian refugees and Israeli
settlers in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   But Abdel-Rahim acknowledged that if the Jerusalem question
could be resolved the other issues would be easier to address.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solution is very simple _ give full sovereignty of East
Jerusalem to a Palestinian state,'' Abdel Rahim said, adding that
Arafat would guarantee all faiths with access to the holy sites in
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready to have Jerusalem as an open city for all
religions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, however, Barak may not be able to take that step.
He entered the talks with his government in a precarious position,
having lost several of its coalition members who resigned over the
prospect of the Palestinians winning control of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show that most Israelis still view East Jerusalem
as their ``eternal undivided capital'' and oppose any concessions
that would give Palestinian control over any part of it. And Barak
is reminded nearly every day by his opponents of the danger of
being the first Israeli leader to make concessions on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, former Israeli foreign minister Ariel Sharon told
Israeli radio that ``no prime minister has the right to make
concessions over Jerusalem. Jerusalem is the birthright of the
Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart declined to speculate on how the talks are progressing
on Jerusalem, and at one point even admonished reporters for
raising questions about the ``moods'' of Barak and Arafat on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that in the 21st century how you feel is often more
important than what you do, but not here,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
