<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-GUARANTEE-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK'S NEW APPROACH COMES WITH A GUARANTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Train late? Service staff rude or unhelpful? Cafe
car out of food? Amtrak says it wants to make things right, and, if
it fails, wants to make sure passengers get their money's worth, by
giving them a certificate for future travel.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new policy announced this month, passengers _ whom the
railroad now refers to as ``guests'' _ are asked to make their
complaint on the spot, to a conductor or other Amtrak employee. But
even if a disgruntled passenger eels shortchanged and calls the
national reservation number instead, the railroad will offer a
certificate to take the trip again free, said George Warrington,
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no small print,'' he said. The railroad may give away
some certificates for trivial complaints, he acknowledged, but it
will build loyalty among riders. ``This is about the long haul, not
about short-term hand wringing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about the long haul is a change for Amtrak, which has
led a hand-to-mouth existence for the last few years, its recent
history a ``Perils of Pauline'' saga in which the onrushing train,
not the damsel on the tracks, is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Its strategy, as described by Warrington, was to ``cut its way
into profitability'' by slicing off more and more service. Instead,
the railroad, created by Congress in 1971 as a way to preserve the
passenger service that the investor-owned railroads were closing
down, was decimating itself, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Amtrak has recently shifted its focus, deciding to add
trains and readjust schedules to permit connections, making its
system work like an integrated network, as the airlines do. The
satisfaction guarantee follows training for its 25,000 employees in
customer service, and a long effort to make sure its trains are
``right and ready'' for each run.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes at a time of success for the railroad, which is
beginning to partake of the travel boom that has come along with
sustained national prosperity. Bookings are at a nine-year high,
the railroad said, with passenger loads up 7 percent for the four
months ending June 30, compared with a year earlier. Passenger
traffic on its four daily all-electric Acela Regional trains
between Washington and Boston is up 40 percent over the older
trains they replaced, the railroad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real bump up,'' said Mortimer Downey, the deputy
secretary of Transportation. The additional passengers are coming
out of planes and automobiles, not other trains, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad intends to introduce its high-speed Acela service,
with a top speed of 150 miles an hour (30 mph faster the current
top speed), later this summer. That had been scheduled for last
year, but a variety of problems surfaced in the new trains during
testing. In recent post-test inspections, for example, some bolts
were missing from the new trains, but technicians have installed
longer, stronger ones, Downey said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that aside from a late start to the new service,
they did not expect any significant problems.
</P>
<P>
   Railroad officials also say, without mentioning the airlines
directly, that it is not hard to do better at customer service than
their main competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers want travel that's going to improve their quality of
life,'' said Warrington, discussing the new guarantee with
reporters. That means warm personal contact, he said, and help that
can sometimes be quite simple. If a train is running late, he said,
it could be something like giving out a phone card so the passenger
can call ahead, at Amtrak's expense, to tell waiting relatives of
the delay.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that Amtrak said showed the policy was working, ticket
sales in the first 15 days after the guarantee announcement were
$57.6 million, up $8.3 million, or 17 percent, above the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak has been promising free tickets to dissatisfied customers
for the last three years on a single train, the Coast Starlight,
which runs between Los Angeles and Seattle. It has given them to
fewer than one passenger in 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   But that train is ``one of our gems,'' as Warrington put it, and
railroad officials expect far higher rates systemwide. They are
aiming for one in 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 15 days, the railroad issued 2,987 service
guarantees, or about 3 for every 1,000 passengers. They were worth
$228,000, about 0.4 percent of sales. The average value of a
certificate was $76. The most common reason was lateness, said Bill
Schulz, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines sometimes placate irate passengers with discount
coupons for future travel, or a gift of frequent-flier miles, but
industry experts doubt any will follow Amtrak's lead with a
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Margins are so tight,'' said David A. Fuscus, a spokesman for
the Air Transport Association, a trade group, who said that if an
airline makes a profit of 5 cents per dollar of revenue, ``people
are doing cartwheels down the middle of the street.'' The airlines
are hundreds of times bigger than Amtrak, he said, so offering
guarantees could mean enormous liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
