<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BOOKS-RONWRONG25-COX     07-24 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-RONWRONG25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dumb ideas? She wrote the book on them
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jane O'Boyle did what any of us could have done with a particle
of imagination and an ounce of follow-through: She compiled
``Wrong!'' (Plume, $11.95), a collection of the biggest bonehead
predictions, pronouncements and decisions ever made, and offered
them to the public in an 88-page, soft-cover book.
</P>
<P>
   The result is _ well, two kinds of reading satisfaction. The
first is relief in knowing that it wasn't you who committed the
big-time gaffe. The second is the perverse pride of authorship when
you know that your own stupidity has surpassed the examples given.
</P>
<P>
   It's that second reaction that interests me. If, on reading the
following examples from ``Wrong!,'' you find yourself saying, ``Ha,
that's nothing. Why, I remember the time I ... ``
</P>
<P>
   The time you what?
</P>
<P>
   You bet your friend that he could run over your foot with his
front tire and that it wouldn't hurt? Came up with a foolproof
roulette system?
</P>
<P>
   Write or e-mail me an example of the wrongest you have ever
been, and if I judge your entry the best, the book is yours.
Otherwise, you will have exposed yourself to taunts and ridicule
for nothing, and how dumb is that?
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, some of your memories are repressed. Let's see if
some examples from O'Boyle's book bring them to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   After Elvis Presley's first Grand Ole Opry appearance, manager
Jim Denny was guarded in his praise for the new talent: ``You ain't
going nowhere. ... You ought to be back to driving a truck.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1859, oil distributor Edwin L. Drake set about devising ways
to go into the ground and get crude. He consulted professional
water-well drillers, who assessed his proposal in these words:
``Drill for oil? You mean drill into the ground to try to find oil?
You're crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing for Albert Einstein to be dismissed as nothing
special when he applied to the Munich Technical Institute. But how
do you account for Ernest P. Rutherford, a guy smart enough to be
first to split the atom in 1933, who then tut-tutted the feat as
hardly worth the trouble? Afterward, the Cambridge physics
professor declared: ``The energy produced by the atom is a very
poor kind of thing. Anyone who expects a source of power from the
transformation of these atoms is talking moonshine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Olson, president and founder of Digital Equipment, was more
or less wrong when he said: ``There is no reason anyone would want
a computer in their home.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, when Joe DiMaggio came up from the New York Giants farm
team, he limped from a knee injury. Giants manager Bill Terry took
a look at the rookie and saw enough to offer the following
congratulations to farm team director George Weiss: ``You bought
yourself a cripple.''
</P>
<P>
   In the marketing game, O'Boyle neglects the famous marketing
mistakes, such as Ford's Edsel and New Coke, to remind us that
there's wrong _ and then there's real wrong. Like when Ivan
Petrovich Pavlov decided it wasn't enough to make a dog salivate by
ringing a bell, not when he could corner the lucrative dog spit
market. This is not a joke. Pavlov demonstrated that maybe there
was a reason Russians showed no early aptitude for capitalism: ``It
is less well known,'' O'Boyle reports, ``that Pavlov tried to
market his discovery by bottling dog saliva and selling it as an
appetite stimulant.''
</P>
<P>
   In business, sometimes you need somebody to tell you when you
have a bad idea. Fred Smith had the benefit of a Yale business
professor, who told him just that after he submitted his senior
thesis for what later became Federal Express: ``The concept is
interesting and well-formed, but in order to earn better than a C,
the idea must be feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it is time for you to put on the hair shirt and tell me the
wrongest you have ever been. To bolster your courage, remember that
no matter how wrong you have been, you couldn't have been any
wronger than Gen. Douglas MacArthur, who stated in 1940, ``Japan
will never join the Axis.'' The day after his statement, Japan
announced it had done exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   And you certainly couldn't be any wronger than I was when I was
5 and tried to boost myself on the back of a mule-drawn wagon by
sticking my foot on a rising spoke. Dragged under the wagon, I was
smacked against the ground and the bed about eleventy-nine times
before my foot came free.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
