</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORMROOMS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What grows in a dorm room?
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could give Sam Pasley a hard time about ``The Chickster.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, how many college freshmen do you know who sleep with
a stuffed chicken they've had since childhood? But then again, do
you really want to tangle with a 6-foot, 3-inch guy who weighs 300
pounds and played offensive tackle for Delray Beach's Atlantic High
School?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already got The Chickster dressed up in FSU gear,'' says
Pasley, now a Florida State University freshman who recently moved
into a dorm room _ with The Chickster _ for summer session. ``All
my friends give me a lot of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Teasing aside, Pasley's like most young adults heading off to
college: They look forward to living independently but still want
their home-away-from-home to be just that _ homey. And most schools
try to make the transition easier, too. Most notably, they don't
even call them dormitories anymore. ``Residence halls'' is the
preferred term.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to dispel the old image of the big, impersonal
environment,'' says Christine Brun Abdelnour, an interior designer
and author of ``Big Ideas for Small Spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a science to it; to capture those young freshmen
and make them comfortable, because this is their prime
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides The Chickster, Pasley took along some family photos and
a few favorite posters of sports stars like Nolan Ryan and Barry
Sanders to help him feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   LeAnn Barkey, a recent graduate of Lincoln Park Academy in Fort
Pierce who heads off to the University of Tampa next month, will
carefully stick some glow-in-the-dark stars on her ceiling to
remind her of her little brother, Will, who loves them. (Of course,
she'll use a tacky putty so as not to damage the ceiling and get
hit with those pesky repair fees.)
</P>
<P>
   But, like all college students living in residence halls, Barkey
has already found certain elements of uniformity that can make
settling in tricky _ like the ``extra-long twin sheets''
phenomenon. Barkey and her mom, Kathy, finally gave up searching
for the sheets at local stores and ordered a hunter green set
through the college. (Many schools use extra-long twin beds in
residence halls so that even the tallest students can fit in them.)
</P>
<P>
   To make her room cozier, though, Barkey settled on a warm color
palette of hunter green and burgundy to complement the sheet set.
She found a burgundy and white plaid throw rug to help cushion what
will surely be a hard-surfaced floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do hope it'll be cozy,'' Barkey says of her room, ``because
it'll be a hard transition to go from being at home at night to
being somewhere where your only comfort is someone (a roommate)
who's a stranger to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
