u l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN25-COX     07-24 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After Big Tobacco, we need a class-action world
 &HT;    By Practical Man
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The practical man lit up last week.
</P>
<P>
   When he heard the tobacco verdict.
</P>
<P>
   No, he has nothing against tobacco companies. In fact, the
practical man puts them on par with coffee growers and Scotch
distillers, for he knows the tasty truth about cigarettes: They're
yummy.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they're also dangerous, but for years the practical man
deemed those mouth-watering Marlboros worth the risk. Eventually,
an older, wiser practical man nixed nicotine for good, but when he
smoked, he smoked because he liked it, not because anyone made him.
And if he'd gotten sick, he would have blamed himself, not some
marketing meathead he knew was lying anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the practical man has had little sympathy for folks who
sue Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before he saw the practical applications.
</P>
<P>
   The light bulb went off when a Miami jury awarded 500,000 sick
smokers $145 billion because cigarette makers lied about their
product. Cash for corporate lies? The practical man did some math.
</P>
<P>
   Say you see a commercial for a blockbuster movie. The trailer
makes it look great, but when you go see the show, it stinks. Don't
just write it off as the way the world works. Do the right thing
for humanity: File a class-action suit! If you make $15 an hour,
you're due $30 for the two hours you wasted watching that sorry
flick, and if 10 million others saw it as well, BOOM! That's a $300
million verdict. Hammer Hollywood with a handful of those and watch
how fast movies improve, and misleading commercials disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Or, say your teenage daughter spots Cindy Crawford caking crud
on her face in a magazine ad. She buys a tube of goop, but _
surprise! _ the makeup doesn't make her look like Cindy. It makes
her look like your daughter goobered in goo. Don't waste your
breath arguing cosmetics with a 16-year-old. Improve the world!
Your kid and 15 million other young women will spend an average of
132 hours this year applying ``beauty'' products that won't make
them beautiful. If a teenager's time is worth $6 an hour (yeah, the
practical man knows that's a stretch), then WHAM! That $12 billion
judgment ought to make makeup makers think twice before lying to
little girls.
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea. A couple of big-buck verdicts will clear the
air of preposterous automobile ads when sports-car drivers discover
they're still bald, beer-bellied bumpkins, not the suave
sophisticates they saw in the commercial. Sic a hungry lawyer on
the fast-food industry and feel a nation's arteries unclog when he
turns up 2 million heart patients who munched a Big Mac a week for
years. Target ads for insipid TV shows and the tobacco judgment
will look like chump change _ and television might become tolerable
at last.
</P>
<P>
   If we can't be just, let's be practical. If we're no longer
willing to blame consumers for being stupid, let's start blaming
corporations for treating them that way. We'll not only get rid of
the lies. We might even pick up enough jing to spring for a case of
brew. The commercials say that stuff's a chick magnet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
