<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1831 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     07-24 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CASE OF EMERGENCY   ...   DEFIBRILLATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., Wash., Britain)  
 (For release Sunday, July 30)   By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Heart defibrillators are likely to
be required aboard all big United States airliners within three
years. The Federal Aviation Administration, acting on the basis of
a one-year survey of 15 airlines' in-flight illnesses among
passengers and crew, concluded that the devices, which can save
lives of people who are unconscious in cardiac arrest, would be
worth the cost.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In May, the FAA said it had drafted a rule requiring airlines to
buy battery-driven defibrillators for all planes able to carry at
least 30 passengers and one flight attendant. After 120 days for
public comment, the rule _ which may be modified in that time _ is
scheduled to take effect in September. The airlines are allowed
three years to buy the devices and train crew to use them, although
they can also be operated by untrained people because an electronic
voice gives instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 major United States airlines, eight either have
defibrillators on all their planes already or expect to by the end
of the year. Only Trans World Airlines and America West have not
begun the process.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines, which was in the vanguard of domestic
airlines with defibrillators, began putting the devices, about the
size and weight of a desk dictionary, aboard its planes in 1997.
According to John Hotard, a spokesman, all of its planes were
equipped by March 1999. Alaska Airlines has completed the process,
as have Delta and United. US Airways is 97 percent complete,
according to David A. Castelveter, a spokesman, with fewer than 10
planes without defibrillators. All of the line's 50 new Airbuses
have the devices, he said. Northwest Airlines reports it is about
50 percent complete and expects to finish by the end of the year.
Southwest Airlines says the same, as does Continental, which adds
that all of its 777s are now outfitted.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has not begun the process. Christine Kelly, a spokeswoman,
said: ``TWA is evaluating various equipment options to determine
the specific characteristics offered by the various manufacturers
so that should the rule be officially issued, we would be ready to
comply.''
</P>
<P>
   America West likewise has not begun installation, although it
has selected the model it will buy. Its spokeswoman, Janice
Monahan, said it expected to have installation on its 135 planes
completed ``by the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is keeping formal track of foreign airlines with
defibrillators, although Dr. Claude Thibeault, the medical director
of Air Canada, said that an informal group of airline medical
directors had a general picture of which lines were equipped. He
said that Qantas, Virgin Atlantic, British Airways, Air Zimbabwe,
Swissair and Varig were known to have them. Air Canada is in
process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the forthcoming regulation in a radio speech in
May, President Clinton said that the FAA survey of in-flight
illnesses from July 1998 through June 1999, which was initiated by
the Aviation Medical Assistance Act of 1998, showed automatic
external defibrillators' value. ``AEDs have proven effective in
saving lives,'' he said, ``and I believe that all airline
passengers should have access to this life-saving technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In defibrillation, the restarting of a heart that has stopped or
has begun ineffective beating, known as ventricular fibrillation,
time is of the essence. Medical studies show that chances of
survival decrease 10 percent with each minute that passes without
circulation of blood. Quick application of cardiopulmonary
resuscitation, or CPR, can force blood into the body, particularly
the brain, as a holding action, but the heart must be started
again. The defibrillator does that, and all the television dramas
showing interns running to a bedside with equipment emphasize this
need for speed. Diversion of an airplane to the nearest airport may
help in other cases, but takes way too long to help in cardiac
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen airlines carrying 85 percent of American domestic
passengers contributed data to the one-year Government study; they
submitted 188 usable ``medical event'' reports: 177 that occurred
on board planes _ in flight, at the gate or in taxiing; 10 in the
boarding ramp or the terminal, and 1 in a cab to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 177 events, 119 were thought to involve the heart; the
average age of these passengers was 62. Sixty-four of the 119 died;
10 were known to have survived, and the other outcomes were
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   While the study was going on, of course, airlines were phasing
in defibrillators. In 14 on-board events and 3 on the ground, the
devices were used, and four of the victims survived; the FAA
checked later and found these passengers still alive. For the
on-board cardiac events, the report said, an AED was reported ``not
available'' in 40 cases and ``not needed'' in 12. There were 74
aircraft diversions reported because of passenger medical
emergencies; 52 involved cardiac events.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines gathered data before and after the Government
study. Dr. David McKenas of its corporate medical department,
testifying in Congress, said that defibrillators saved 11 lives
over three years. He said the results were ``spectacular'' in
comparison with those that emergency medical services on the ground
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Despite gaps in its data, the FAA said it concluded that
``deaths occur on air carriers and certain medical interventions
... may change the outcome for some.'' Projecting
``conservatively'' against a potential total of 7.58 billion
passengers in the next 10 years, it concluded that 55 outcomes of
future medical events might be changed by defibrillators.
</P>
<P>
   The draft rule also requires additions to the standard medical
kit carried on board. It also carries a good Samaritan provision
protecting those who help from random prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA voiced some caution about its steps. ``The intent of the
regulation is to provide options for treatment,'' it said, ``not to
raise expectation in the passenger or physician community regarding
the level of medical care available in flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments on the draft regulation may be mailed in duplicate to
Department of Transportation Dockets, Docket FAA-2000-7719, 400
Seventh Street SW, Room Plaza 401, Washington, D.C. 20590.
Instructions for electronic filing may be found at dms.dot.gov/.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, two overseas airlines, British Airways and
Virgin Atlantic, which both have defibrillators on their fleets,
announced plans to add an additional medical device, one that can
transmit an electrocardiogram by satellite from a conscious but ill
passenger to a medical center on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Bagshaw, head of medical services for British
Airways, said that the Micromedical Biolog monitor, about the size
of a deck of cards, could be linked to the seatback telephone that
transmits to a satellite and then to a 24-hour medical team in
Arizona called Medlink. The team may recommend aspirin,
nitroglycerin or diversion of the plane, Bagshaw said. The Biolog
device is distributed by Medtronic Physio-Control in Redmond, Wash.
Virgin Atlantic is using a device called Tempus 2000, made by
Remote Diagnostic Technologies in Hampshire, England.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
