<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1832 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-GATECHPREVIEW0725     07-24 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECHPREVIEW0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech football looking at life without Joe Hamilton
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOT SPRINGS, Va. _ Life after Joe begins officially at Georgia
Tech next week. For the first time in four years, George O'Leary's
Yellow Jackets will play a game without Heisman Trophy runner-up
Joe Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Leary says the surrounding cast for the player who winds
up behind the center is the best he has had during his tenure at
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be as potent without Joe on offense, but we're going
to be pretty good,'' O'Leary said from the ACC's annual football
kickoff meetings. ``We've got more weapons than we've had. I'm very
high on this football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Five offensive starters return, including All-America candidates
Kelly Campbell at flanker and Chris Brown at tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Tech also has an inordinate number of quarterbacks on
scholarship. The Yellow Jackets will open fall practice with six.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, redshirt junior George Godsey is the starter, but
the situation could change. ``I think (Andy) Hall can make more
plays, but he makes more mistakes, too,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Godsey and Hall, Jermaine Crenshaw and Brian Camp
open camp for their second year. The freshmen are Mark Logan and
Brandon Sumner.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tech has a couple of holes to fill on the offensive
line, the skill positions are deep. Campbell leads a receiving
corps with speed to burn. Behind Campbell, who broke every Tech
receiving record with 69 catches for 1,105 yards and 10 touchdowns,
are sophomore Will Glover and senior Brett Basquin. At split end,
Jon Muyres beat out Kerry Watkins for the starting spot. Watkins
caught 33 passes for 476 yards and six scores last season.
</P>
<P>
   The backfield is the ACC's deepest. Sophomore Joe Burns, junior
Sean Gregory, and sophomores Gordon Clinkscale and Sidney Ford are
fighting for playing time at running back. With freshman Jimmy
Dixon (6-2, 215), the Jackets also have a power back. Gregory had
837 yards last season, while Burns was the leading rusher in 1998
before missing most of 1999 with a broken leg. Ford rushed for 49
yards and a score against N.C. State.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Ed Wilder, 6-2, 259, is perhaps the most underrated
player on the team as a powerful runner, blocker and receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surrounding cast is so much better, it's not even close
(to) when Joe took over four years ago,'' O'Leary said. ``We've got
to find the quarterback who has the most flexibility and
maneuverability. We need to find out who can take a bad play and
make something good out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Godsey is the starter today, he might not be later.
``That job is his for one snap,'' O'Leary said. ``His job is to
keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense graduated only two starters, but that might not be
good news.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets had one of the worst defenses in the conference and
ranked 100th in the NCAA in total defense. Only Tech's ability to
outscore opponents kept it out of deep trouble. The 1999 defensive
unit gave up 333 points, an average of 30.3 per outing.
</P>
<P>
   The linebacker slots should be improved, with Matt Miller
returning from a knee injury. He is joined by Recardo Wimbush and
two super freshmen who will play immediately. Keyaron Fox (6-4,
220) out of Westlake High in Atlanta and Hobie Holiday (6-4, 235)
from Houston County are too good to sit.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive line remains undersized, but it got a boost when
O'Leary moved Nick Rogers from linebacker to defensive end.
Sophomore Greg Gathers and Felipe Claybrooks will anchor the other
end, with Gathers moving inside at times to give the line more
speed and mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Tackles Guenter Kryszon and Merrix Watson started last year and
are adequate. With a front four weighing 260, 255, 250 and 280 at
times, the Jackets are sure to get pushed around.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive backfield is led by two excellent safeties. Chris
Young will open at strong safety after an All-ACC year last season
with 89 tackles. Sophomore Jeremy Muyres will be at free safety
after starting seven games as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets have had problems at cornerback. Senior Jamara Clark
and sophomore Marvious Hester are the starters, but incoming
freshmen Jonathan Cox from Chicago and Tony Hollings out of Twiggs
County will get early looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (defensive coordinator) Ted Roof I needed to get him
better players,'' O'Leary said. ``I think we've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
