<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-ONLINE-BANKING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS ARE SLOW TO MOVE ONLINE, BUT SO ARE THEIR CUSTOMERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    (ART ADV: One B&AMP;W illustration is available in JPEG format by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By PATRICK MCGEEHAN  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In the early rounds of the online banking competition, the
surprising outcome is that the big commercial banks have not been
beaten to the punch by nimbler young challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the brokerage titans of Wall Street that steadfastly
refused to recognize the threat posed by Internet-based stock
trading competitors, commercial banks have been wrestling with the
Web for years. But the results of those efforts have ranged from
modest success to spectacular failure.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that, unlike online stock trading, online banking
has not, so far, been a killer app. Consumers have been just as
slow as the banks to accept the Internet as a medium for managing
everyday money matters.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 percent of American consumers bank online. Last
year, about 8.3 million people shopped the Internet for mortgages
and other loans, but only one in eight even started the
loan-application process online, said Robert Sterling, an analyst
with Jupiter Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The real challenge to established banks may just be arriving, in
the form of companies that combine banking with other services
online. Control of consumers' financial information is so critical
to establishing bonds with them that it has attracted a host of
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ETrade Group, the electronic brokerage firm, is
making a big push for its ETrade Bank, which was known as Telebank
before ETrade bought it earlier this year. ETrade also bought a
network of more than 8,800 automated teller machines. The company
eventually hopes to link those ATMs with its Web sites so that
customers can withdraw cash from bank or brokerage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional banks take some comfort in ETrade's moves because
they reinforce the belief that Internet-only banks have limited
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advent of Net-only banks seems so exciting,'' said Bruce
Zimmerman, a senior vice president of Chase Manhattan Bank. ``The
reality is, there aren't many customers who want to do everything
only over the Net. That's why you've seen that Net-only models
haven't been successful.''
</P>
<P>
   To build business quickly, most Internet banks have taken
advantage of their slim cost structures by paying higher interest
rates on checking accounts and certificates of deposit.
</P>
<P>
   But, analysts say, paying above-market rates to attract deposits
has never been a path to profits. Indeed, that tactic contributed
to the failure of many savings and loans in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The people most likely to shop for the best rates are retirees,
Sterling said, and they are unlikely to shop online.
</P>
<P>
   Among Internet banks, the most visible disappointment has been
WingspanBank.com, the electronic bank created by the Bank One Corp.
After spending about $35 million on advertising for Wingspan, Bank
One put it up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup's Citibank has also struggled with its Internet
strategy. Even with its latest electronic offering, called Citi
f/i, Citibank, the nation's largest bank, trails Wells Fargo and
Bank of America in the number of online accounts.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for the slower migration online for
bank customers compared with investors, according to analysts and
industry executives. One of the most important is that electronic
discount brokerages opened up a simple, affordable route for
investors. Another is that investors were not accustomed to
visiting brokerage offices with any regularity, while many bank
customers still stop at their neighborhood branch regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Big banks are following a trail that was blazed in the brokerage
business by Charles Schwab: They are working toward making their
services available online, over the phone and in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe people will want a choice of how they access the
bank,'' Zimmerman said. ``And we believe customers will value a
seamless financial relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are not so smooth just yet. Traditional banks are ahead
of the game if they have made all account information accessible to
customers online, said Matt Cone, senior vice president of
marketing for the Corillian Corp., a provider of Internet banking
software in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of financial institutions that still have
yet to get to first base,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Cone said that making account information available
electronically was a step toward offering what customers really
want: a single, online source of up-to-date information about their
finances, including savings and checking accounts, credit cards,
mutual funds and other investments.
</P>
<P>
   On that score, banks are facing new challengers: upstarts that
want to give people one place on the Web where they can check on
accounts scattered among several companies, from savings at a bank
to brokerage accounts to frequent-flier mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies, such as Yodlee.com and X.com, are offering to
gather account information from disparate sources and compile it
for a quick survey. The technology that these companies use is
known as ``screen scraping'' because it requires them to use
customers' account numbers and passwords to collect confidential
data posted by other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are hoping that most consumers will not trust other
companies, especially new dot-com ventures, with access to such
important personal information.
</P>
<P>
   The faith that most consumers place in traditional banks is a
powerful competitive advantage, Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem banks have had historically is that they rely on
that and so they could take their sweet time to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
