<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1844 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CONVICTIONS-OVERTU     07-24 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONVICTIONS-OVERTURN-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL REPORT: MURDER CONFESSION FAILS TO FREE 2 MEN WHO CLAIM
INNOCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE FRITSCH and DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was something about Joey Pillot that made a
federal prosecutor ask if he was telling the whole truth about his
violent past. Joey seemed uncomfortable, as if he was hiding
something. There would be no deal, the prosecutor warned, if Joey
did not come clean.
</P>
<P>
   Pillot, a member of a drug-and-extortion gang, sighed, then
spilled out a startling story: Two innocent men were in prison for
a murder that he committed. Later, he conceded that his best
friend, James Rodriguez, known as Spanky, had also been involved.
</P>
<P>
   That was six years ago. The men convicted of the crime, David
Lemus and Olmado Hidalgo, are still serving sentences of 25 years
to life for the murder of a bouncer at a Manhattan nightclub, the
murder Pillot says he and his friend committed.
</P>
<P>
   It is a case that has frustrated lawyers for Lemus and Hidalgo,
who said they had been certain their clients would be released, or
granted a new trial. They acknowledge that some evidence points to
their clients, but say that there is much more evidence that Pillot
and Rodriguez were the real killers.
</P>
<P>
   For Steven M. Cohen, the former assistant U.S. attorney who
extracted the confession from Pillot, the intervening years have
been troubling. Now in private practice, he wonders whether he did
enough. ``This is the only case I left behind that keeps me up at
night, that plays on my conscience,'' Cohen said. ``There are real
questions about whether the right guys are in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to overturn a conviction in New York, even in
the face of powerful new evidence. Trial judges and state appeals
courts have always been reluctant to reverse a jury's verdict, and
in 1996, Congress sharply limited the rights of defendants to take
their appeals to federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a state judge in Manhattan refused to allow a new
trial, saying he found Pillot's confession unbelievable, and state
appeals courts refused to intervene. Lawyers filed an appeal in
federal court two years ago, but they are not optimistic about its
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   So Lemus, now 32, and Hidalgo, now 34, pace the yard at Green
Haven Correctional Facility in Stormville, seemingly as baffled as
their lawyers. They guard against false hope now. Lemus, the only
son of a single mother from the Bronx, is still able to summon
tears if he is questioned closely about the course of his life.
Hidalgo, an immigrant from the Dominican Republic, where his wife
and two children remain, has the lifeless eyes of one who long ago
detached himself from the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is not lost on them that there is a wave of interest in death
penalty cases. They can see it on the television set mounted in the
prison yard; even the smallest irregularities are debated. But
their case, with sentences just a notch less harsh, generates
little interest, for all its contradictions and unanswered
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Why, for instance, did the police think that two men who
apparently did not know each other, who came from different worlds
and spoke different languages _ Lemus only English and Hidalgo only
Spanish _ would commit a murder together? And why, if he was
innocent, did Lemus tell a girlfriend that he had committed the
crime?
</P>
<P>
   TIPS TO POLICE POINT IN TWO DIRECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   It was Latin night at the Palladium on Thanksgiving in 1990, and
more than 1,000 people showed up to drink and dance at the
nightclub on East 14th Street. By 1 a.m., only a few bouncers
remained outside. That is when the trouble started. A man left the
club and argued with a bouncer, who punched him in the face.
</P>
<P>
   The man and his friends left, and at least two retrieved guns
from their cars and returned. One fired a semiautomatic pistol, but
it jammed. The other fired a revolver, hitting Jeffrey Craig, the
security supervisor, in the leg. Another bullet ripped through the
chest of Marcus Peterson, 23, a bouncer and an aspiring
body-builder. He died, but Craig survived.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting was widely reported, and within hours, the police
got their first tip. An anonymous caller to their Crime Stoppers
line said Spanky and Joey, from 550 East 139th Street in the Bronx,
had done it. That was the address of the C &AMP; C gang, a group of
violent extortionists. The police briefly looked into Rodriguez, a
C &AMP; C member, and one of the bouncers identified him from a
photograph as one of the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   But a few days later, another tip sent the police in a different
direction.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A woman who had been picked up for on prostitution charges told
the police that her friend knew who had committed the Palladium
shooting. So the police interviewed the friend, Delores Spencer, a
married mother of three. The man she was having an affair with, she
said, had told her that he had done it. That man was David Lemus.
</P>
<P>
   So the police compiled a photo array and showed it to four of
the bouncers. Two picked out Lemus. About two months after the
shooting, he was picked up and put in a lineup. Three bouncers,
including Craig, the survivor, identified him; three others said
they could not. Lemus was charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the police showed four bouncers a set of photographs
that included Hidalgo. Neither the detectives nor prosecutors have
ever explained why they thought he was involved. Three bouncers
picked out Hidalgo, but a fourth picked out another man.
</P>
<P>
   Lemus and Hidalgo said they rejected plea bargains for shorter
prison terms. They told their lawyers that they had never even seen
each other until they were brought to court. And each said he had
not been at the Palladium on the night of the murder _ and had
alibi witnesses to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the shooting, their trial began, but the defense
cases quickly fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Craig testified that he was now certain that Hidalgo was one of
the gunmen. He said he had no doubt that Lemus was the other. Two
years earlier, Craig had said only that Lemus could have been one
of the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Three other bouncers identified the defendants, but their
accounts differed in some key details, like who was wearing what.
And one reversed the roles that each had supposedly played. Several
said that both gunmen had slight Spanish accents. Lemus speaks like
a native New Yorker. And three bouncers said they believed there
had been a third gunman, although they disagreed about whether he
fired his gun.
</P>
<P>
   But all the bouncers agreed on what led up to the shooting. A
man who had come with a group of friends left the club, and asked
for permission to go to his car and then re-enter. The bouncer
refused, the man shoved him, and the bouncer punched him. The man's
friends came outside, the whole party left, and at least two men
returned with guns.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's testimony was devastating. She said that Lemus had
left a message on her answering machine after the shooting, saying,
``Call me, I'm in trouble.'' She did not, however, save the tape.
When she called him, he said he had shot a bouncer at the
Palladium, she testified. But the account he gave her was quite
different from that of the bouncers: He had been at the club with
another woman, and the trouble started inside the club when someone
pinched her bottom. He got into a fight and was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Then the prosecution produced a knockout punch. After Lemus was
charged with murder, he kept calling Spencer, unaware that she had
spoken to the police. She was frightened, she said, because he kept
demanding that she come to his house alone. So she arranged with
investigators to secretly tape his calls. The hour or so of
recordings contained no such demands, just banter and flirtation,
except for an exchange in which she said, ``Why should I be afraid
of you?''
</P>
<P>
   Lemus answered, ``Because you know that I know that you know,''
and made three popping sounds. She said it was a reference to the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Lemus' lawyer, Eric M. Sears, asked that he be allowed to play
another portion of Spencer's tape, in which Lemus said that he
stood to win a large legal settlement because he had been jailed
for a crime he did not commit. The judge refused.
</P>
<P>
   Lemus' alibi defense fell through, Sears said, because the
girlfriend who he said was at home with him on Thanksgiving night
had given contradictory accounts to the police and would not have
made a convincing witness. Several of Lemus' friends had stopped by
that night, Sears added, but their testimony would have forced him
to put the girlfriend on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo was in equally bad shape. Just before closing arguments
were to begin, his lawyer, Andres Aranda, said he had two alibi
witnesses, explaining that he had been unable to locate them
earlier. But Gold said it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated for a day before convicting both men of
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING A THUG LIFE AND PAYING THE PRICE
</P>
<P>
   It is no mystery to David Lemus why a jury convicted him. He had
contributed a good share of the evidence. But, in his view, it is a
great injustice that he is still in prison. He is guilty, he says,
only of being an immature jerk and a braggart.
</P>
<P>
   He was 22 when he boasted to Delores Spencer that he had been
involved in the Palladium shooting. She was eight years older, and
``liked the gangster type and thugs,'' he said, ``and I portrayed
myself as one.'' In reality, he said, he had seen a report about
the shooting on television.
</P>
<P>
   He has been in prison for nearly seven years now, and no one
visits or writes anymore, except for his mother, Nilsa Huertas.
Perhaps not surprisingly, she says he was a good son, except for
the time when he was 16 and was caught driving a stolen car.
Huertas' right wrist bears the scars of a suicide attempt shortly
after he was convicted of the murder; she says she is better now.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she was allowed to visit her son for a weekend. They
shared a trailer with a little kitchen, took long walks on the
prison grounds and watched movies on a VCR. He made the mistake, he
said, of showing her ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' in which an
innocent man is imprisoned for life. She cried for 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo seems to have found a way to cope with the long, empty
days. He rarely hears from anyone, and no one visits. Relatives in
New York send money to his family in the Dominican Republic now; he
used to send them about $300 a month. He, too, was not a saint,
having been arrested twice for illegal possession of a gun.
</P>
<P>
   They are good friends now, Hidalgo having assumed the role of
elder brother, helping Lemus to keep the good news and the bad in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
