</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0495 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1847 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CONVICTIONS-OVERTU     07-24 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONVICTIONS-OVERTURN-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: in perspective.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A GANG MEMBER LIES TO PROTECT A FRIEND
</P>
<P>
   The C &AMP; C Gang controlled every aspect of life around Brook
Avenue and 139th Street in the Bronx in the early 1990s, enforcing
its rules with murders and kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   When a state and federal task force began rounding up C &AMP; C
members, it fell to Cohen, the federal prosecutor, and Robert
Addolorato, a veteran New York City police detective, to interview
Joey Pillot. They were trying to decide whether to offer him a plea
bargain in exchange for his testimony against other gang members.
Over several days in 1994, Pillot admitted to two murders and an
assortment of other gang-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember saying to him,'' Cohen recalled, `` `Whatever it is
that you think we will never find out, you had better tell us now,
because if you don't, and we find out, I promise you that you will
spend the rest of your life in prison.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pillot replied, ``You mean the Palladium murder,'' Cohen
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Cohen said, ``tell me about that.'' He had never heard
of the Palladium murder.
</P>
<P>
   At first Pillot said he had done it alone, but later conceded
that his best friend, Spanky Rodriguez, had been the gunman. His
own gun had jammed, Pillot said. He had lied, he said, to protect
Spanky.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he and Addolorato became convinced that Pillot was
telling the truth. He knew details, like the jamming of the gun and
its caliber, that only a participant would be likely to know. And
he had implicated his closest friend.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Cohen contacted Stephen Saracco, the assistant
district attorney who had prosecuted Lemus and Hidalgo, and Saracco
told the defense lawyers, who were granted a new hearing before
Gold in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Pillot testified that he and some friends had gone to the
Palladium on Thanksgiving in 1990, and that Spanky had had too much
to drink. Spanky left the club, and a bouncer would not let him
re-enter. The bouncer finally punched Spanky.
</P>
<P>
   The group, four men and four women, went to their cars, Pillot
said, and he and Spanky returned with their guns. Pillot said his
misfired, but Spanky's didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Pillot's wife, Millie, testified that she had been there, too,
and the judge peppered her with questions about the bands that had
performed and the songs they had sung. She said she did not
remember. And two C &AMP; C members testified that Pillot had admitted
his involvement shortly after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The judge asked both sides to submit briefs. Sears pointed out
the call to the Crime Stoppers line six years earlier that had
named Joey and Spanky. And he argued that there was ``absolutely no
motive'' for Pillot to confess to a crime that he did not commit,
or to implicate his best friend on behalf of two men he said he had
never met.
</P>
<P>
   Saracco, the prosecutor, argued that Pillot had made up the
whole story, and had gotten many details wrong. Pillot said, for
instance, that he and Spanky ran from the scene after the shooting,
while witnesses said the gunmen had walked away. Pillot's story,
Saracco wrote, could have been concocted from reports relayed to
him by a gang member who had met Lemus in prison. And Pillot,
Saracco argued, believed he had a deal with Cohen and would not be
prosecuted, and therefore had nothing to lose. (Pillot never got an
immunity deal from federal prosecutors.)
</P>
<P>
   Gold agreed. He called the testimony of Pillot and his wife
``entirely unworthy of belief.'' Pillot, the judge wrote, had
confessed to placate Cohen. Gold would neither set the defendants
free nor order a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Not much has happened in the case over the last four years,
except that prosecutors changed their argument about Pillot's
testimony, and seem to give it some credence. In a brief filed in
federal court last year, they said there was ``no dispute'' that
Rodriguez _ who was picked out of a photo lineup in 1990 but never
charged _ was involved in the shooting. Pillot, they said, could
have learned the details of the shooting from his friend.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy E. Little, a Legal Aid Society lawyer who is handling the
appeal, said prosecutors were scrambling to make the new evidence
fit. ``They came up with a new theory to plug up one gap, but in
doing so they opened up all these other gaps,'' she said. One of
the biggest is the lack of explanation for how Rodriguez knew
either Lemus or Hidalgo, or how Lemus and Hidalgo knew each other,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Sears met with Saracco to discuss an immunity offer
for Rodriguez. His testimony could reopen the case. Rodriguez's
lawyer, Richard Verchick, said his client would testify in return
for a promise that he would not be prosecuted, but no such offer
has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who was convicted of extortion in 1996 for his role
in the C &AMP; C gang, is set to be released from federal prison in
Fort Dix, N.J. on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Pillot, who pleaded guilty to a gang-related murder in 1996, is
serving a sentence of 15 years to life at the Shawangunk
Correctional Facility in Wallkill.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney's office is willing to review
any new evidence in the case, said James M. Kindler, the chief
assistant district attorney. He would not comment on discussions
regarding Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   There is little the defendants and their lawyers can do but
wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
