<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1851 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-WEST-NILE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-24 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WEST-NILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL PARK CLOSED FOR SPRAYING AS INFECTED MOSQUITOES ARE FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nation's most famous urban park was closed Monday
night, and a New York Philharmonic concert postponed, after city
officials announced that they had found mosquitoes infected with
West Nile virus in Central Park and would spend the night
blanketing the 843-acre refuge with pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   The park was scheduled to reopen Tuesday morning, with the
concert rescheduled for Tuesday night. But the city was prepared to
postpone the spraying in the event of rain.
</P>
<P>
   The pesticide spraying will be extended on Wednesday night to
much of Manhattan, from 23rd Street to 110th Street, between the
East River and the Hudson, as the city escalates its response to
the mosquito-borne virus that killed seven people in the region
last year and made 55 others sick. No infections of humans have
been reported this year.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Dr. Neal
L. Cohen, the city health commissioner, sought to reassure city
residents that even if they were bitten by infected mosquitoes, the
likelihood that they would become seriously ill was remote.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to be panicking in the park Monday. Although
hundreds of people who had arrived early for the concert were
packing up, joggers, bikers and roller-bladers continued to enjoy
the park into the early evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a huge scare,'' said Gerald Ginsberg, an East Side
physician who was taking his daily 3-mile walk through the park.
``You know what would have been more frightening to me? If they had
found deer and deer ticks with Lyme disease in Central Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and the health commissioner urged city residents and
tourists not to be apprehensive about visiting the park after the
pesticide treatment has been completed. But they added that with an
estimated 30,000 people expected for the Philharmonic's annual
summer concert, they felt it was best not to tempt fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances, the risk, is very, very small,'' Giuliani said.
``But to risk 30,000 people in the park, sitting there for two or
three hours of music, that is another thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we're disappointed, but public health is the primary
concern,'' said Eric Latzky, a spokesman for the New York
Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   City officials also canceled a weekly youth track and field
program scheduled to be held in the park Monday night, and asked
teams playing at 16 ballfields to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   The extreme steps were taken Monday after officials learned that
a sample of mosquitoes collected on July 12 in the Park, near 63rd
Street and Fifth Avenue, had tested positive for the virus. Two
mosquito samples collected this month on Staten Island also tested
positive, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They were not the first infected mosquitoes to be found in the
state. In the last week, mosquitoes in Westchester, Suffolk and
Orange Counties have also been found to be carrying the virus.
Throughout the New York region, more than 40 infected birds have
also been found, with Nassau County added to a list Monday that now
includes nine New York, New Jersey and Connecticut counties in a
circle around the city.
</P>
<P>
   The growing list of West Nile confirmations, while disconcerting
to the public, are to an extent an illustration of what city and
state officials consider a successful public health campaign. By
intensifying monitoring of birds and mosquitoes and then quickly
moving to spread pesticides in surrounding areas, officials hope to
prevent or at least limit the spread of the disease to humans this
year. People over 50 are at the highest risk of severe disease, but
young children and people with weakened immune systems are also
more susceptible, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The city this year has mosquito traps in 90 locations. None
other than two in Staten Island and one in lower Central Park has
turned up infected insects. City officials did not detect infected
mosquitoes last year in Central Park, but the surveillance then was
not nearly as intense. Still, the city chose to spray the park with
pesticides last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the virus probably was present in the area of the
park last year, because an elderly man who lived on Central Park
South was made sick by the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not send everybody out of their homes and close down
the area,'' Giuliani said, emphasizing that it should be safe to
return to the park once it has been treated with pesticide.
``People should just go about their lives normally, except for one
night, stay out of the park, let us spray it and it will be back to
normal.`
</P>
<P>
   The city has already sprayed on Staten Island. More spraying is
planned for Tuesday night in Queens and bordering sections of
Brooklyn. Spraying has also taken place or is planned in many
surrounding communities, although some, like Nassau and Bergen
Counties, are holding off. Pesticide campaigns _ using crews of
city contractors that have sprayers mounted on trucks _ had already
been planned Monday night in northeastern Queens and on Staten
Island, in response to the infected birds confirmed last week.
</P>
<P>
   The city is using synthetic pesticides, Anvil and Scourge, that
officials say are similar in composition to a natural pesticide
produced by chrysanthemum flowers, and that quickly break down when
exposed to sunlight or water or air. But the heavy reliance on
spraying is evoking increasing protest from some environmental
groups that say the mayor is overreacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is taking an irresponsible course of action,'' said
Kimberly Flynn, a researcher for the New York Environmental Law and
Justice Project.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Cohen rejected those concerns. The spraying, Cohen
said, should kill about 90 percent of the mosquitoes present, which
means that a certain number infected with the virus may survive.
</P>
<P>
   While city residents and visitors should continue to use Central
Park without hesitation, he said, they should wear bug repellent
and consider wearing long-sleeved shirts, long pants and socks. The
recommendations are particularly important for the elderly and
young children, who are more susceptible to the virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
