<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-MILLERPROFILE0725-COX     07-24 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLERPROFILE0725-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   After exiting the political stage, Miller makes a re-entrance
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Judd
</P>
<P>
   c, 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Zell Miller thought his work was done when he returned
to his beloved North Georgia mountains last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had my hour and more upon the stage,'' Miller said
shortly before leaving the Capitol, where he served eight years as
governor and 16 as lieutenant governor. ``If I were 10 years
younger, I would have wanted to go to Washington, probably.''
</P>
<P>
   But a year and a half later, the 68-year-old Miller is, indeed,
headed to Washington. Capping an extraordinary week in Georgia
politics, Gov. Roy Barnes on Monday appointed Miller _ a fellow
Democrat but sometimes adversary _ to the U.S. Senate to replace
the late Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the appointment was a difficult decision for Miller,
friends say. It takes him away from his native Young Harris, Ga.,
at a time when he was enjoying not just teaching college courses
but also making a good living serving on seven corporate boards.
It's a life that Miller and his wife, Shirley, craved as he
completed a 39-year political career last year. But setting aside
his reservations to replace Coverdell, friends say, illustrated
Miller's lifelong dedication to public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're to be commended for giving up what they're going to
give up,'' said Bert Lance, the former Carter administration budget
director who has known Miller since they attended elementary school
together. ``They've got a great life, with family close by, with
none of the hassles and frustrations that go with doing the
public's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller conducted the public's business more than half his life,
beginning in 1960, when he was elected to the state Senate at 28.
It was a remarkable accomplishment for a young man raised by a
single mother after his father, dean of Young Harris College, died
when the baby was 17 days old.
</P>
<P>
   Miller remained in the state Senate two terms, then worked in
the administrations of two very different governors: Lester Maddox
and Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   He won his first run for statewide office, lieutenant governor,
in 1974. After winning a second term, he took his first shot at a
higher office _ the U.S. Senate _ but lost to incumbent Herman
Talmadge in a bitter primary. Ultimately, he served four terms _ 16
years _ in the state's second-highest office before finally getting
his chance for the top job in 1990. That year, he won the
Democratic gubernatorial primary by defeating former Atlanta Mayor
Andrew Young and Barnes, then a state senator. He easily won
election that fall over Republican Johnny Isakson.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, he championed a state lottery and its popular
payoff _ the HOPE scholarship program, which covers college tuition
for every Georgia child who graduates from high school with a B
average or better. The program would become the centerpiece of
Miller's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   But he also took on a controversial issue that would almost be
his political undoing. In 1992, Miller proposed removing the
Confederate battle emblem from Georgia's state flag. Conservatives
protested, and few of Miller's fellow Democrats supported the idea.
Miller's proposal died in 1993 without gaining passage in the
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, in an election season dominated by Republicans,
Miller barely won re-election over his GOP challenger, Guy Millner.
Chastened by his close call, the governor focused on safer issues
in his second term: welfare reform and tougher criminal sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he retired, he had become one of the most popular
governors in Georgia's history, with an approval rating as high as
85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, he remained a passionate spokesman for issues
affecting North Georgia, and responded quickly when he perceived
any slight toward the mountains or their people. In 1998, he said,
only partly in jest, that one of his greatest regrets was that he
never challenged ``someone at the Atlanta newspapers to duel over
their never-ending bigotry toward rural mountain people.''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the governor's office, Miller has taught at Young
Harris College, Emory University and the University of Georgia,
said Toni Brown, a longtime aide. He also has served on the boards
of seven corporations, she said: Georgia Power Co., Gray
Communications, Post Properties, Law Companies Group, United
Community Bank of Blairsville, ezgov.com, and Coleman USA.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the return from private to public life, Miller may face a
difficult transition in Washington, said Charles Bullock, a
political scientist at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may find it frustrating,'' Bullock said. ``Governors who
move on to the Senate often do. They are used to making
pronouncements and things will happen. ... He's going to be the
least senior member of 100 members, and he's going to be the least
senior member of the minority party. And he's never been part of
the minority party.'' But Lance predicted a distinguished Senate
career that will last as long as Miller wants: ``I'm sure he
intends to be a fully functioning senator, starting whenever he's
sworn in and ending whenever he decides it's time for him to come
back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
