u s BC-GLF-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-24 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THREE MAJORS IN A ROW NEXT TEST FOR WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Thanks to Tiger Woods, a ticket to the
2000 PGA Championship will be one of golf's hottest items.
</P>
<P>
   Before Woods started making history, this year's PGA
Championship was in danger of being overshadowed by the other three
majors. The Masters is the Masters. And both the U.S. Open and the
British Open were played at two of golf's most fabled locations _
Pebble Beach, Calif., and St. Andrews, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens at Valhalla Golf Club in Louisville, Ky., from
Aug. 17-20 will hold the attention of anyone interested in sports.
After dominant victories at both the U.S. Open and the British
Open, Woods can join Ben Hogan as the only other player to win
three consecutive modern majors if he wins at Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a golf genius, like Woods, to like his
chances at Valhalla. Think about it. He has won the last two major
championships by a total of 19 strokes. Instead of watching the
final round of both Opens to see if Woods would win, many people
watched just to see how many he would win by.
</P>
<P>
   His peers have been left in various states of admiration and
frustration. But the message is clear. Woods is changing golf, both
inside and outside the ropes, like no one else who has come along
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's thrown all these old myths out the window, that you can't
physically train for golf, that you can't be strong or you are
going to lose your touch,'' said Nick Faldo, a three-time British
Open champion, who finished tied for 41st behind Woods, who won
Sunday at St. Andrews by eight strokes over Ernie Els and Thomas
Bjorn. ``Through the '90s and through science, you can train for
golf. The knowledge that I have after 25 years, you'd love to be
starting again. All these 15 year-olds have to stop eating the
doughnuts. They have an incredible opportunity to go out and chase.
It's no good sitting back and thinking, `I won't go and practice
because it's raining.' If you are going to go out and beat Tiger,
you have to be out there doing as much, if not more.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods is special not only due to athleticism and work
habits. He has passion for his profession. Woods loves golf. He
loves to practice. He loves to play tournaments. And he loves to
win.
</P>
<P>
   After Woods' triumph Sunday, someone asked Woods if he might
grow tired of winning. Woods had to smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-uh,'' said Woods.
</P>
<P>
   What great athlete gets tired of winning? They may grow tired of
training, traveling, forcing their body to do things as they grow
older. But who gets tired of winning?
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem facing Woods' competition. He is only 24
years old, and he is not going away anytime soon. He will not grow
bored with golf to pursue other interests, because golf is his main
interest. And he is playing a sport that will him to perform at the
highest level well into his 40s, particularly considering how well
he takes care of himself. Woods has won three of the last four
majors, and 13 of his last 23 starts on the PGA Tour. If he wins
the PGA Championship, imagine the anticipation that will lead into
next year's Masters, when he would be shooting for his fourth
consecutive major.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' victory somewhat overshadowed another great champion,
Karrie Webb, who won the U.S. Women Open on Sunday, proving she is
still the best player in women's golf. Webb has won three of the
last four women's majors, and in Annika Sorenstam and Juli Inkster,
Webb has two formidable rivals who will keep her from resting on
her laurels.
</P>
<P>
   However, Woods has no real rival, yet it does not seem to deter
is drive. Those who fear that Woods' domination will be bad for
golf should think again. The Boston Celtics won 11 championships in
13 years when Bill Russell played, and the National Basketball
Association kept going strong. The Yankees have had several
dominant runs during different decades, and they still call
baseball the national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is great for golf, not only because he is attracting new
fans, but because he is not distracted by the money or the fame.
When Woods comes to a tournament, he comes to win. And playing an
individual sport gives Woods the freedom to set his own schedule,
to take time off when he needs it, and to arrive at every
tournament feeling as if he can perform his best.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what achievement had most surprised him since turning
professional, Woods cited his consistency. He has only missed one
cut in four years, or two cuts if you insist on counting the
weather-delayed 1998 Pebble Beach tournament, when he elected not
to return for the final round in August, six months after the
tournament began.
</P>
<P>
   Other players realize that right now, Woods rules. Remember when
the Detroit Pistons had The Jordan Rules, a serious of defensive
schemes designed to contain Michael Jordan? There are no Woods
rules in golf. People have talked about Tiger-proofing courses, but
the harder you make a golf course for Woods, the harder it is for
everyone else. And by retooling his swing over the past several
years, Woods now has the control to succeed on tight courses, the
power to succeed on long courses, the short game to recover from
bad shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really stinks is that you can't control him, said Paul
Azinger. ``In every other sport, you can control your opponent.
Except this sport. You can only focus on your own game.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Woods plans to remain focused. He is scheduled to play
in the Buick Open in Michigan two weeks from now, followed by the
PGA Championship the next week.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Woods can savor another milestone. And at age 24,
his best may be yet to come. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
