<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; CALPINE:  &LR; Heat waves and the threat of blackouts have made
Californians anxious about the cost and supply of electricity, but
it's Christmas in July for Calpine Corp., the San Jose power
producer. &UR; BY KELLY YAMANOUCHI &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SOCIAL:  &LR; It's a classic case of woulda, coulda, shoulda.
</P>
<P>
   If all the taxes that American workers paid into the Social
Security system during its 65-year history had been invested in the
stock market, the system would be abundantly overfunded today. Its
future viability would not be a bone of contention between
presidential candidates George W. Bush and Al Gore. &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; ARTHUR LOUIS &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MP3:  &LR; The high cost of making peace with the recording industry
showed up on MP3.com Inc.'s bottom line Monday as the Internet
music portal posted a whopping $177.1 million loss for the second
quarter. &UR; BY BENNY EVANGELISTA &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MONEYBAG: &LR;  Q: &LR;   &LR; I am a widow, age 72, and don't have much income. I
have been advised to re-invest the $57,000 in my individual
retirement account, which is in a certificate of deposit paying 7
percent and expiring soon. I was told to put the money in a
growth/income mutual fund that would pay me about $100 permonth
more on the same money. Should I take the risk?
</P>
<P>
   A: You put your finger on the key point when you mention
``risk.'' The value of a CD will never decline. The value of a
mutual fund might go down, and might stay down for a long time.
 &UR; BY HENRY NORR &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
