<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1858 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-VP-HNS &LR;      07-24 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE COMPILES SHORT LIST OF VP CANDIDATES 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as he criticized his Republican rival for
conducting a too-public search for vice president, Democrat Al Gore
Monday divulged more details about his own search, saying he had
met with a number of potential running mates and had compiled a
short list of contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had meetings with some people and I will have meetings
with some people before I reach my conclusion,'' Gore told
reporters on Air Force Two en route to Washington after a campaign
swing in Ohio and Michigan, where he received the endorsement of
the environmentalist Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   To help him make the decision, Gore said he will meet this
morning with Warren Christopher, the former secretary of state who
is helping him vet vice presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   While the vice president would not mention any names he made it
clear that he had made progress on his search, saying he had
whittled down the list of possible contenders to a short list.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been some speculation that he would name his
running mate shortly after the end of next week's Republican
convention, Gore said he is more likely to make his choice public a
few days before the Democratic convention, which begins Aug. 14 in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Among the candidates Gore is reported to be considering are
Florida Sen. Bob Graham, former Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell of Maine, Indiana Sen. Evan Bayh and Connecticut Sen.
Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Gore criticized Texas Gov. George W. Bush's search for vice
president, suggesting that the intense media speculation about GOP
running mates over the past week has violated privacy of some of
the potential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've handled my process differently than the Bush campaign has
handled theirs. I've kept it private and I hope dignified out of
respect for the individuals, the men and women who are under
consideration. And I am going to continue to approach it that
way,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to comment on Bush's apparent choice, former Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney, or any others who had been mentioned as
possible contenders.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear that the Democratic contender wanted to share
in some of the media spotlight that has been intensely focused on
Bush's selection process.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president ostensibly came back to the media area on Air
Force Two to announce that he talked to Zell Miller, the former
Georgia governor just named to fill the Senate seat left vacant by
the death of Paul Coverdell. But he fielded numerous questions
about the status of his search for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore's staff alerted reporters to the scheduled meeting with
Christopher at the vice president's official residence. Previous
meetings between Gore and Christopher have not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Gore received the official backing of the
Sierra Club, the nation's largest environmental group, at an
outdoor event in Grand Rapids, Mich., along the Grand River that
runs through the political battleground state.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said he expected to be criticized by his
political opponents and industry officials for his strong
environmental stands.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he had heard that copies of his 1992 environmental
tome, Earth in the Balance, had been selling well in Philadelphia,
where Republicans are preparing to hold their national convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the polluter and special interests are coming after
me,'' he said. ``I wear their attacks with a badge of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeated his belief that environmental protection could
co-exist with economic growth. While not mentioning Bush, Gore
suggested that his critics would undermine the environmental
protections enacted by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to beat back the special interests who want to
mine and drill and clear cut our national heritage into oblivion,''
he said. ``We're not going to let them do it. This earth is not in
a liquidation sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore left the most scathing criticism of Bush and his Texas
record to Dr. Robert Cox, the president of the Sierra Club, who
told reporters ``I have no doubt he (Bush) would be an
environmental disaster as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that under Bush Texas has become the leading source of
industrial toxic emissions in the country. And he faulted the
governor for promoting increased logging in national forests and
opening up the arctic wildlife refuge for oil drilling.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra president said that Bush's election would mark a
return to the policies pushed by the Reagan administration, which
was despised by environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said even the candidate's father, President Bush, was better
on environmental matters than his son would be in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be worse than his father,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club endorsement follows a long period of debate that
highlighted the schism among environmental leaders over Gore's
green credentials. During the primaries a few vocal Sierra board
members were reluctant to back Gore, claiming the administration
had not lived up to all of its promises.
</P>
<P>
   Gore already has been endorsed by another large environmental
group, the League of Conservation Voters. But Friends of the Earth
has been more critical of the vice president and suggested it might
back Green Party nominee Ralph Nader. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
