<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1859 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MP3-LOSS &LR;      07-24 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3-LOSS </SLUG>
  
 MP3.COM HIT WITH HUGE LOSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY BENNY EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The high cost of making peace with the recording industry showed
up on MP3.com Inc.'s bottom line Monday as the Internet music
portal posted a whopping $177.1 million loss for the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The loss included $150 million that the San Diego company has
set aside to settle copyright infringement lawsuits filed by the
five biggest record companies.
</P>
<P>
   The amount also includes enough money to pay legal fees and
anticipated royalties to music publishing companies and smaller
record labels that have not filed lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Executive Officer Michael Robertson said the company,
which also generated a record $20.2 million in revenue for the
quarter ended June 30, could afford the loss because it has $360
million in cash reserves and no debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's a lot of money, but it's the cost of doing business
in the music industry today,'' Robertson said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com angered the record world earlier this year when it
launched My.MP3.com, a service that enables members to listen to
their MP3-formatted music files online.
</P>
<P>
   For the service, MP3.com copied about 45,000 CDs into the MP3
format, giving music fans a vast virtual library of popular songs
they could access from any Internet-connected computer.
</P>
<P>
   However, a federal judge ruled in April that the service made
MP3.com liable for copyright violations and billions of dollars in
fines. Last month, MP3.com announced it had reached settlements
with BMG Entertainment Inc. and Warner Music Group, and is close to
similar deals with Universal Music Group, EMI and Sony Music.
</P>
<P>
   Although terms have not been officially disclosed, industry
sources say MP3.com will have to pay about $20 million to each of
the five labels.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the company hopes to relaunch the My.MP3.com
service, which it suspended after the judge's ruling, as soon as
the remaining three suits are settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of all this turmoil and the lawsuits, we're still
executing in our numbers, which is testimony to our solid business
model,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com's net loss amounted to $2.71 per share. But the
company's $20.2 million in revenue for the second quarter compared
with just $1.9 million for the same quarter in 1999, when it posted
a loss of $6.3 million, or 22 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 million songs were downloaded or listened to online
from MP3.com during the quarter, about 26 million more than the
previous quarter. That helped boost traffic to the site to about
578,000 unique visitors in June alone.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Philip Leigh of Raymond James Financial Inc. said the
quarterly loss, while still big, at least sets MP3.com up to offer
legal songs in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a heck of an admission ticket to get access to that
content,'' Leigh said.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of its revenue comes from advertising, which
Leigh said could be stronger once the portal can resume drawing
music fans to its site with the My.MP3.com service.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at bennye(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;   &LR;
</P>
