<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of
tonight's New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 07/24/00.
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MARIETTA, Ga. -- July 24, 2000 --
BEER-CAN-COLLECTORS-COX -- Collecting beer cans is something most
would associate with determined recyclers or serious suds swillers.
But there are approximately 5,000 people across the nation who simply
like the color, the nostalgia, the thrill of discovery, or the basic
"guy-ness" of amassing and displaying large numbers of beer cans.
Bill Beaudin, takes a look at part of his inventory of approximately
5000 beer cans that line the walls of a den in his basement in
Marrietta, Ga. Beaudin is co-sponsoring a "canvention" in
Cartersville, Ga., the last weekend in July, which will feature
collectors from around the south. (John Amis/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PHILADELPHIA -- July 24, 2000 --
CONVENTIONS-MARKETING-2 -- For many, the political conventions have
little to do with politics and much more to do with business.
Polishing civic and corporate images, making money and exploiting
marketing opportunities have turned conventions from what was an
exercise in democracy into a huge corporate fest. Philadephia's City
Hall, in the background, is reflected in the windows of the Loews
Hotel as chief engineer Ken Allmond straightens out red, white and
blue banners set up in honor of guests attending the upcoming
Republican National Convention. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- July 24, 2000 -- FBI-CARNIVORE --
Lawmakers of both parties grilled FBI officials Monday over the
bureau's use of "Carnivore," a device designed to monitor and capture
e-mail messages in a criminal investigation. From left: Dr. Donald
Kerr, director of the Laboratory Division of the Federal Bureau of
Investigation; Larry Parkinson, general counsel, FBI; Kevin DiGregory
and Chris Painter, of the Deptartment of Justice, during their
testimony Monday before the House Subcommittee on the Constitution.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- July 24, 2000 -- DIABLO-PUBLICITY -- While
Harry Potter and his creator, J.K. Rowling, have won praise around
the globe for drawing videogame-crazed and television-besotted young
people back to reading, games like Diablo II, a Dungeons &AMP;
Dragons-like  computer game that sends players to battle evil knights
and monsters and  save the world from a demon, have drawn
condemnation for ensnaring players in a morbid worldview and gluing
them anti-socially to a computer screen. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- July 24, 2000 -- NY-WESTNILE-SPRAY --
Mosquitoes carrying the West Nile Virus have been found in Central
Park, prompting city officials to order the park closed Monday night
and canceling a concert that had been expected to draw 30,000 people.
People turning up for the concert faced barricades Monday. (Librado
Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) GREENHAVEN, N.Y. -- July 24, 2000 --
NY-CONVICTIONS-OVERTURN -- David Lemus, right, and Olmado Hidalgo,
are still in prison serving sentences of 25 years to life for the
murder of a bouncer at a Manhattan nightclub, despite a confession by
another man that he was the killer. The case has frustrated Hidalgo
and Lemus's lawyers who said they had been certain their clients
would be released, or at least granted a new trial following the
confession. Though they acknowledge that some of the evidence points
to their clients, the lawyers say that now there is much more
evidence that others were the real killers. Hidalgo and Lemus at
Greenhaven Prison where they are serving their sentences. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MOSCOW -- July 24, 2000 -- SUB-MOSCOW-THEATER -- In a
city that takes theater very seriously, Kama Ginkas was arguably the
most successful director of the season that just ended. He certainly
was the busiest. Ginkas at the Theatre of the Young Spectator during
rehearsals of "Happy Prince" based on the work by Oscar Wilde. (James
Hill/The New York Times) EDS: This photo was retransmitted to correct
the photo number.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 24, 2000 -- BAR-STUDY -- Patrick
Lawless, 34, a recent graduate from Forthdam University Law School,
studies for his first, and what he hopes his only, try at the New
York State Bar Exam in the library of New York University Law School,
Monday. The exams begin on July 25. (Vincent Laforet/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- July 24, 2000 -- TV-WGBH-BOS -- Nova Paula
Aspell, seated, executive producer of Nova, with Carl Charlson, a
producer of the science documentary series, with the Emmy Awards the
program has won in the offices of WGBH. The Boston station produces
or coproduces nearly 35 percent of PBS's prime-time lineup, an output
rivaled only by WNET-TV in New York. (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CRAWFORD, Texas -- July 24, 2000 -- BUSH-CHENEY --
Gov. George W. Bush, the probable Republican presidential nominee,
with Dick Cheney, former secretary of Defense under President Bush,
at Bush's ranch earlier this month. Cheney, who has lead the search
for a vice presidential running mate for Gov. Bush, is himself
thought to be a possible candidate for that post. An official
annoucement from Bush is not expected until at least Tuesday.  (Laura
Skelding/Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PHILADELPHIA -- July 24, 2000 --REPUBS-CONVENTION-2 --
Reinventing or in some cases abandoning the rituals of party
gatherings past, the Republican National Convention that begins
Monday will more than ever amount to a lavish multi-media spectacle
that pushes controversy to the sidelines in favor of an unabashed
celebration of the goals and vision of the party standard-bearer,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Kate Kinsey, a volunteer, paints signs
in the First Union Center, site of the upcoming convention, Monday.
The sign she is working on reads in Spanish: "The Stars Shine For
Bush."  (Dith Pran/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PHILADELPHIA -- July 24, 2000 -- CONVENTIONS-MARKETING
-- For many, the political conventions have little to do with
politics and much do with business _ polishing civic and corporate
images, making money, exploiting marketing opportunities and turning
what has been an exercise in democracy into a huge corporate fest.
Chocolate elephants  in honor of the upcoming Republican National
Convention await buyers in a booth in the Reading Terminal Market
earlier this month. Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN DIEGO, Calif. -- July 24, 2000 --
SCI-EARTHQUAKES-HOMES -- Scientists testing wood frame houses with
earthquake simulators are finding that wood isn't as earthquake
resistant as previously thought. However houses with stucco did
surprisingly well in the tests, which could either be due to the
stucco or the house's simple box shape. Further testing is needed.
Structural engineers evaluate minor damage to the test home
reinforced with stucco. (Frieder Seible, UCSD Structural
Engineering/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOULDER, Colo.  -- July 24, 2000
--SCI-CHILD-VEGETARIANS -- More and more children are decided to be
vegetarians, whether for supposed health reasons or out of fear of
eating "Babe." Some doctors are wary, but others say it can be done,
though sufficient planning must be undertaken in order to ensure
children get proper nutrition. Lauren Pierpoint, who chose to become
a vegetarian after seeing "Babe," a movie about a talking pig, serves
asparagus for the family dinner. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PHILADELPHIA -- July 24, 2000 --REPUBS-CONVENTION --
Reinventing or in some cases abandoning the rituals of party
gatherings past, the Republican National Convention that begins
Monday will more than ever amount to a lavish multi-media spectacle
that pushes controversy to the sidelines in favor of an unabashed
celebration of the goals and vision of the party standard-bearer,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Kevin Rauch, left, an electrical
worker, calls to his colleagues as they pull miles of cable along a
raised platform outside the First Union Center in Philadelphia
earlier this month. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 24, 2000 -- VITAL-SIGNS --
Researchers found that just breathing in the allergens off of seafood
caused a reaction in those allergic to fish and reported this in the
Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology earlier this year. The
study also said, hypersensitivity to fish is a significant problem in
several European countries. The Fulton Fish Market in downtown
Manhattan. (John Sotomayor/The New York Times)
</P>
