<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0512 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1871 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SOCIAL-INVESTING &LR;      07-24 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-INVESTING </SLUG>
  
 PROPOSALS ATTEMPT TO SHORE UP SOCIAL SECURITY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's a classic case of woulda, coulda, shoulda.
</P>
<P>
   If all the taxes that American workers paid into the Social
Security system during its 65-year history had been invested in the
stock market, the system would be abundantly overfunded today. Its
future viability would not be a bone of contention between
presidential candidates George W. Bush and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, not a penny of Social Security money has been
invested in stocks. Virtually all of it has gone into U.S. Treasury
issues, which are risk-free but yield relatively low returns.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, according to government actuaries, the overburdened
Social Security system has a date with bankruptcy, perhaps before
the middle of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Bush, figuring that later is better than never, has
proposed letting workers establish individual investment accounts
in which they could directly invest an unspecified portion of their
future Social Security taxes in stocks or stock mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   He claims this would help forestall the need for sharp cuts in
Social Security benefits or sharp increases in Social Security
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Gore initially scoffed at the proposal, saying that it
was too risky. Later, he proposed an investment plan of his own,
which would be kept outside the Social Security system but
subsidized with generous grants from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security system itself, Gore says, can be shored up
with inflows from the trillions of dollars in budget surpluses that
are expected in the years just ahead.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of evidence that a stock-market tie-in could be
just the tonic Social Security needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely the way to go,'' says John Goodman,
president of the National Center for Policy and Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the hypothetical example of a wage earner who is
approaching retirement today after 40 years in the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   If that person paid the maximum Social Security tax each year,
and if all the money had been invested in the equivalent of a
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fund, the value of the payments would
have ballooned from a total of roughly $60,000 to more than
$700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Upon retiring, our hypothetical worker could have collected the
$700,000, invested it conservatively in long-term certificates of
deposit paying interest of more than 7 percent, and enjoyed an
annual income of $50,000. And there would be that $700,000 nest egg
to draw upon in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   (This assumes _ perhaps too hopefully _ that the money amassed
through taxation would not be taxed again upon withdrawal.)
</P>
<P>
   The figures would be twice as impressive if one added in the
payments made to Social Security by the retiree's employers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Employers' Contributions
</P>
<P>
   Because the employers had to match the employee's tax payments
dollar for dollar, the theoretical nest egg could have grown to
$1.4 million, pushing the worker's risk-free retirement income to
$100,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, under the real-world system, if someone were to
quit work today at age 65, the annual pension from Social Security
would amount to a piddling $18,000 or so. And there would be no
nest egg to tap when the annual payments proved inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Why the humongous difference?
</P>
<P>
   Market historians who have looked back more than a century say
that the return on stocks _ including reinvestment of dividends _
has outpaced inflation by an average of more than 6 percent
annually. By contrast, Treasuries have outpaced inflation by less
than 2 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   With compounding over many years, the spread of more than 4
percentage points translates to the difference between feast and
famine for many individual workers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Happy Times for Investors
</P>
<P>
   The past 40 years have been kind to stock investors. The average
annual return during that period has been in the neighborhood of 12
percent, dividends included.
</P>
<P>
   However, the period encompassed severe bear markets in every
decade, the worst being the one that sent the S&AMP;P 500 skidding
nearly 50 percent between January 1973 and October 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But bear markets also present spectacular buying opportunities
for the venturesome. Every $1,000 invested in the average stock at
the end of 1974 would be worth about $50,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it would not be practical nowadays to let workers channel
the full amount of their Social Security taxes into individual
stock-market accounts.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial portion of those taxes are needed to fund the
pensions that are being paid to current retirees, or have been
promised to future retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security currently boasts reserves of $750 billion, says
Gary Burtless, a senior fellow with the Brookings Institution. But
the value of payments promised to workers who have a stake in the
current system totals $10 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not specified what portion of Social Security taxes
would be diverted into the personal investment accounts that would
be created under his program. The scuttlebutt is that it would be
around 2 percent of the wages that are taxable under Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in proposing the plan, Bush cited the 2 percent figure
when giving an example of how it would work.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean 10.4 percent of taxable wages _ including the
contributions from employers _ would continue to go into the
traditional Social Security structure.
</P>
<P>
   Salting away 2 percent of taxable wages in the market may not
seem like much _ it would amount to a maximum of about $1,500 this
year _ but over time it could produce tremendous growth.
</P>
<P>
   A worker who had put 2 percent of taxable wages into the S&AMP;P 500
every year starting 40 years ago would have amassed about $300,000
by now from a total investment of somewhat more than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says the program would be voluntary _ evidently because the
workers would have to surrender part of their current, guaranteed
benefits to participate. (Bush has not explained it exactly that
way, but he has implied as much in an official policy statement.)
</P>
<P>
   Fears of Depleting Program
</P>
<P>
   The main beef against the Bush plan is that it might divert too
much money away from the current benefits program. Burtless
estimates that if the Bush plan were implemented, Social Security
could run out of funds to pay traditional pensions in 15 or 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters dispute this, claiming that the Texas
governor's plan could relieve much of the burden on Social Security
by causing people to rely more on their own resources and less on
the government. Bush claims that under his plan, the system would
remain viable for at least 75 years. Dallas Salisbury, president of
the Employee Benefit Research Institute, notes that Bush's proposal
would provide the greatest relief to people in the higher income
brackets, while Gore's is targeted at those in the lower brackets.
In short, the candidates are following party tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The present Social Security system, by levying a higher tax on
people with higher incomes, causes those people to subsidize
workers with lower incomes, Salisbury points out. That's because
the annual pension benefits are roughly the same for all income
groups.
</P>
<P>
   By creating private investment accounts, Bush would divert some
of the high-income money away from the poor, and allow the
high-income people to reap whatever benefits that money produces.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore's investment program _ which strictly
speaking cannot be called a Social Security plan because it would
be administered apart from Social Security _ heavily favors the
poor and near-poor.
</P>
<P>
   People earning less than $30,000 annually would be entitled to
government grants of $3 for every $1 they invested. The matching
grants would be scaled down to nothing for people earning more than
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   For those in the lowest income brackets, the $3-to-$1 match
would present a rare and potentially bountiful opportunity to build
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   If such a program had been available 40 years ago, and if
someone had used it to invest a mere $100 in the average stock each
year, with the government chipping in $300 more, the total value of
that person's account would have grown to roughly $500,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Take your choice, voters.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at alouis(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
