<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MUTUALS &LR;      07-24 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MUTUALS </SLUG>
  
 NOTHING CERTAIN IN MUTUALS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: &LR;   &LR; I am a widow, age 72, and don't have much income. I have
been advised to re-invest the $57,000 in my individual retirement
account, which is in a certificate of deposit paying 7 percent and
expiring soon. I was told to put the money in a growth/income
mutual fund that would pay me about $100 permonth more on the same
money. Should I take the risk?
</P>
<P>
   A: You put your finger on the key point when you mention
``risk.'' The value of a CD will never decline. The value of a
mutual fund might go down, and might stay down for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the fund performs well, the value of your
investment will increase.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to predict with certainty which will happen.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's a matter of how comfortable you feel with the risk. Is
the promise of an extra $100 per month worth the uncertainty and
possible instability of the fund investment? Would making this
change pass what investment professionals call the ``sleep test'' _
by which they mean: Will you lose a lot of sleep if you do it?
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, you might want to take a closer look at that fund
investment. You say that it would pay you $100 per month more than
a 7 percent CD.
</P>
<P>
   I'm wondering whether the payout you describe comes strictly
from dividends and interest, or whether capital-gains distributions
are included.
</P>
<P>
   If capital gains are included, that's fine _ as long as the fund
continues to earn capital gains. But if the fund's investments go
south, those capital gains might dry up. That would leave you in a
real pickle, sitting on shrunken capital and receiving a smaller
annual payout than you expected.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention who recommended the mutual fund. Was it
someone who will receive a commission if you buy shares in the
fund? If so, take the recommendation with at least one grain of
salt.
</P>
<P>
   IRA Withdrawal
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an individual retirement account containing $25,000,
and I own my own home. My daughter is a teacher, doesn't own her
own home, would like to _ but can't afford it. Can I withdraw money
from my IRA without penalty and give it to her to help her make a
first-time home purchase?
</P>
<P>
   A: Internal Revenue Service spokesman Bill Steiner says you can
do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Money to purchase a first home qualifies for the exemption from
the 10 percent early-withdrawal penalty if it comes from an IRA
held by the home buyer, the home buyer's parent or the home buyer's
grandparent, among other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   However, to avoid any penalty, each withdrawal is limited to a
maximum of $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   While that may not seem like much in the overheated Bay Area
housing market, your daughter conceivably could get penalty-free
withdrawals from more than one relative, each of which could amount
to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   If you give her $10,000, and your spouse gives her $10,000, and
a grandparent, say, gives her $10,000, she will have a good start
toward a down payment on a lower-priced home.
</P>
<P>
   Taxable or Not?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been putting money into IRAs since 1977, and my
accounts have become rather tangled. I started out with deductible
IRAs, then switched to nondeductible, and I have done some
rollovers from one institution to another. When I retire and start
to withdraw the money, how can I figure out how much of the money
is taxable and how much isn't?
</P>
<P>
   A: The institutions that hold your IRAs now should have a
running record of your transactions, including those that occurred
when the accounts were held by other firms. When you begin making
withdrawals, they should be able to pinpoint how much is taxable.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, distributions from traditional IRAs into which you
made nondeductible contributions are partly taxable and partly
nontaxable. IRS spokesman Bill Steiner says, for example, that if
you have $10,000 in a traditional IRA and you made $6,000 in
nondeductible contributions to that IRA, then $6 out of every $10
you withdraw would not be subject to tax.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
