<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUDE-DANCER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury awards ex-stripper $2.4 million
 &HT;    By Jim Dyer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vanessa Steele Inman never drank, smoked or took
drugs. And the 33-year-old former stripper also refused to allow
one of the coordinators of the 1997 Miss Nude World International
pageant to lick whipped cream off her naked breasts in a photo
shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Her unwillingness to partake in ``extra-curricular activities''
during the weeklong contest held at a strip club angered the
coordinators, who she said immediately began fabricating stories
that she stuffed the ballot box and cheated her way to be one of
the lead contestants. They eventually disqualified her.
</P>
<P>
   She sued the club, the Pink Pony, its Las Vegas owner and
pageant organizers, claiming they violated Georgia's beauty pageant
statute and state racketeering laws.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a Fulton County jury awarded Steele $2.4 million in
damages agreeing that the pageant organizers not only rigged the
contest but systematically destroyed her career by blackballing her
from nightclubs around the country owned by the Pink Pony's owner,
Jack Galardi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm elated,'' said Steele, as she prefers to be known. ``It
isn't even about the money. Now people believe what I had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele, now a model living in Pittsburgh, proved she actually
had won the pageant by salvaging judges' ballots from the Pink
Pony's Dumpster, which showed she had the highest score among the
contestants. After disqualifying Steele, the judges gave the top
honor to the spokesmodel for the Pink Pony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rigged,'' said Steele, who claimed her chances of
winning were erased after she refused to be auctioned off to a
group of drunken male golfers, do lap dances on a tour bus with wet
bars and beds, or allow Galardi to lick whipped cream off her naked
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Galardi) got very angry when I refused,'' she recalled. ``He
said: `Do you know who I am?' I didn't care who he was. I wasn't
going to let anyone touch or fondle me.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the three defendants _ Galardi, Jack Pepper, and
The Pink Pony, Deep Six Inc. _ declined to comment except to say
they would appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The verdict was contrary to the evidence,'' said Galardi's
attorney, O. Jackson Cook. During closing statements, Cook had
implored the jury to forget awarding punitive damages because the
$835,000 in compensatory damages he and his co-defendants lost in a
judgment last Friday was already excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll jeopardize the ability to collect what you've already
awarded,'' he told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury disagreed, hitting Galardi with $1 million in
punitive damages and his co-defendants with $300,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors said that their decision came easily, that Steele was
credible and that defendants gave conflicting accounts of what
transpired. Jurors said the amount of money they awarded Steele was
not excessive, considering what she lost.
</P>
<P>
   Steele, who normally earned $1,800 to $2,400 a week dancing,
said winning the pageant could have tripled those earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the dancer who won the pageant received great exposure
by being featured in magazines and on several TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   Steele, who once headed a school to help young aspiring dancers
cope with an industry she says is fraught with intimidation,
extortion and physical and sexual abuse, said she hopes the jury's
decision sends a message that will change the industry. ``It's been
a long, three-and-a-half year battle, but I'm very happy with the
outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
