<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-OVERNITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVER SAYS HE WAS PAID TO STAGE VIOLENCE TO TAR TEAMSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Tenn., Va.)   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A driver for a company involved in a strike by the Teamsters for
the last nine months has come forward to say that officials of the
company, Overnite Transportation, paid him $10,000 to damage
property and falsely accuse Teamster supporters of wrongdoing so
they would be fired.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the strike, the company has repeatedly accused
union members of shooting at company trucks and smashing truck
windows and has said it is spending hundreds of thousands of
dollars a week on security.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Holly, a driver based in Tennessee who has worked for
Overnite for three and a half years, said in an affidavit presented
to federal officials that the company's managers, upon hearing of
his financial problems, wired $10,000 to his bank account in return
for his agreeing to certain misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The company denies Holly's accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted me to break windows; they wanted me to do other
things,'' Holly said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Holly insisted that he did not break windows although he said he
gave company officials the impression that he had. Holly said he
had lied to company officials and the National Labor Relations
Board about the actions of two outspoken Teamster supporters,
saying they threatened him with violence for crossing the picket
line. Overnite fired those two drivers, Kyle Brooks and Paul
Holder.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Holly said he regretted having falsely accused
the two men of threatening him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ashamed for doing what I've done,'' he said. ``Overnite
had me brainwashed. I thought the Teamsters were crooked Mafia and
gangsters. As I got to know them, I saw it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Ira Rosenfeld, an Overnite spokesman, denied that the company,
based in Richmond, Va., paid any workers to commit violence or
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overnite has never given anybody any money to destroy company
property,'' Rosenfeld said. ``We have never asked one of our
employees to damage Overnite's property. It is a lie if anybody
says anything different.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld acknowledged that the company wired Holly $10,000, but
he said that was a loan, not a gift. In his affidavit, Holly said
the money was a payment, not a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld said the company occasionally lent money to its
workers, explaining that Holly received a loan because he was in a
financial bind.
</P>
<P>
   Holly said he agreed to lie and engage in violence because he
was worried he might be fired if he refused. He said he also feared
that his father, who had worked for Overnite for 25 years, might
lose his pension.
</P>
<P>
   In his affidavit, Holly indicated that there were other favored
Overnite workers, considered company men, who received payments to
damage trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld said Holly should not be believed, noting that he
admitted lying previously to the National Labor Relations Board.
Rosenfeld also noted that the Teamsters were paying Holly's legal
bills and had found him a new job and given him child support
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Teamster officials said union members voluntarily collected
$1,200 to help with the child support.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters and Overnite, one of the nation's largest nonunion
trucking companies, have been locked in one of the nation's
bitterest labor battles. As one of his chief goals, James P. Hoffa,
the union's president, has vowed to unionize Overnite 8,200 drivers
and dockworkers.
</P>
<P>
   In the public relations war between union and company, the
Teamsters have sought to show that the company was responsible for
much of the violence that the union has been accused of. Teamsters
made available to The New York Times a copy of Holly's affidavit
and a copy of bank records showing a $10,000 deposit into his
account on Oct. 28, four days after the strike started.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters have given the NLRB information about Overnite's
payments to Holly as well as other evidence the union says
demonstrates that Overnite had anti-union workers engage in
violence to embarrass the union. The NLRB has forwarded that
information to the U.S. attorney in Memphis, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Sykes, a spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney in Memphis,
said her office would not comment on Holly's accusations.
</P>
<P>
   At several Overnite terminals the drivers and dockworkers voted
to unionize more than five years ago, but they still do not have a
contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
