<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1879 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-COVERDELL-MILLER0725-     07-24 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-MILLER0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's newest U.S. senator plans to be in Washington by
week's end
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Pressed out of political retirement, former Gov. Zell
Miller said Monday he will be in Washington before the end of the
week to begin his job as Georgia's newest U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 68, was appointed Monday by Gov. Roy Barnes to fill the
vacancy created by the death of Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he also will seek election to serve the remaining
four years of Coverdell's term
</P>
<P>
   The popular former governor's presence on ballot in the
nonpartisan Nov. 7 election is expected to give a boost to Democrat
Al Gore's presidential campaign in Georgia, Emory University
political scientist Merle Black said.
</P>
<P>
   But for Republicans still trying to overcome the death of
Coverdell, 61, from a cerebral hemorrhage last week, Miller's
appointment only increases the pressure. They must determine _ and
quickly _ which, if any, of their eight members of Congress in
Georgia will abdicate relatively safe House seats to enter a Senate
race against Miller, who left office two years ago with an 85
percent approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles (R-Okla.) said he wasn't
surprised by Barnes' choice of a Democrat, particularly Miller. But
he predicted a ``competitive race'' in November.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that, Republicans have to decide how to unite the
party behind a single challenger. The GOP delegation is expected to
meet today in Washington to assess their response. Four Georgia
congressmen _ Bob Barr, Saxby Chambliss, Jack Kingston and Johnny
Isakson _ are said to be considering the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a test for the Republican Party,'' Georgia GOP
chairman Chuck Clay said. ``If we get out there with two, three or
four candidates running against Zell, we're going to look foolish.
We'll almost squander our chance to win the seat.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the party's most conservative members are expected
to balk at backing a candidate such as Isakson, who represents the
party's moderate wing.
</P>
<P>
   Some GOP leaders even advise against anointing a single
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are better off letting it be a wide open field.
The more the merrier,'' said state Senate Minority Leader Eric
Johnson of Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   The state has yet to set the qualifying period in which
candidates must register for the nonpartisan election.
</P>
<P>
   Already the GOP is testing campaign strategy against Miller,
promising to make an issue of his close ties to President Clinton,
whom Miller helped win the Democratic presidential nomination in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton immediately praised Miller as ``one of the
greatest governors in Georgia history....I believe he will be a
great United States senator, and I look forward to working with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Miller said he ``strongly resisted'' the call at
first.
</P>
<P>
   But in a press conference akin to a coronation, he accepted
Barnes' appointment to fill the office temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an obligation to give but one response when my governor
asks me to sert issued late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment was not without critics. Leaders of Jesse
Jackson's Rainbow/Push Coalition in Georgia, who lobbied Barnes to
name an African-American to the Senate seat, called the selection
``a terrible decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a golden opportunity to show appreciation to people
that put him in office,'' said Rainbow/Push regional director Joe
Beasley. ``If we didn't have qualified people, that'd be one thing.
But to bring in someone that should be retiring...it's very
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Labor Commissioner Michael Thurmond, state Attorney
General Thurbert Baker and former U.N. Ambassador Andrew Young were
among the African-Americans discussed as possible appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's ability to hold the seat for Democrats should overcome
any reservations among African-Americans that Barnes did not choose
a minority, said U.S. Rep. John Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The black 5th District congressman, who said last week he would
``gladly accept'' appointment to Coverdell's vacant seat, on Monday
called Miller ``the strongest voice in the Democratic stable.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the beginning, Miller was widely speculated to be the
frontrunner for the appointment _ if he were willing to accept it.
Miller had been often touted as a potential Washington appointee in
the Clinton administration. And some party leaders wanted him to
challenge Coverdell in 1998. In each case, Miller demurred.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to his hometown of Young Harris to teach
college, Miller said: ``The fires of political ambition that had
burned so long and so strong within me had finally cooled. These
last 18 months with Shirley and our family have been the happiest
of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Mark Sherman and Andrea Jones contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
