<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1880 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-FUND-RAISING-     07-24 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUND-RAISING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JUSTICE INQUIRY, CLINTON DENIES SEEKING FINANCIAL HELP FOR
HUBBELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA JR. and JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a wide-ranging interview with a senior Justice
Department prosecutor in April, President Clinton denied asking
political supporters to assist Webster L. Hubbell, his close friend
who received $300,000 from friends and Clinton associates after
resigning from the Justice Department in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The 155-page transcript of Clinton's April 21 interview with
Robert J. Conrad Jr., the Justice Department's chief
political-finance prosecutor, was released Monday night by White
House lawyers. The transcript is the first time that Clinton's
testimony on a wide array of campaign finance issues has been made
public.
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong company controlled by an Indonesian businessman,
James T. Riady, paid Hubbell $100,000 on June 27, 1994. Just four
days earlier, on June 23, Riady met with Clinton at the White House
after meeting that morning with Hubbell for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the interview was devoted to questions about
Clinton's lengthy relationship with Riady, a political patrons of
Clinton in 1992 and who, the prosecutor suggested, bragged about a
``direct pipeline'' to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's line of questioning about Riady and Hubbell is
noteworthy because James Riady has been under pressure in recent
weeks to accept a plea bargain with the Justice Department's
campaign finance task force. Conrad has actively investigated
Riady's activities in connection with contributions he and
employees of the Lippo Group, the $12 billion Riady family
conglomerate, made to Clinton's campaign in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he could not recall discussing Hubbell with Riady.
``At this time, there was a lot of kind of, you know, a lot of
people who knew Webb were expressing some sympathy for him,''
Clinton said. ``And, you know, if James Riady said to me, I'm going
to try to help him, he could have said that, I wouldn't have _ and
I mean, it wouldn't surprise me if he did, but I do not remember
him saying that to me. And, you know, he might have deliberately
avoided saying anything to me, thinking it wouldn't be appropriate
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the interview, Clinton again denied talking to anybody
about Hubbell's being paid. ``I want you to understand two
things,'' he said. ``No. 1, I believe the people that helped Webb
Hubbell did it because, like me, they believed he was innocent. No.
2, I believe Webb Hubbell was persistently persecuted by the
independent counsel because he would not lie about me or Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, Clinton added, ``If he wanted to say something
bad about me, he'd have to make it up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, that would have made Starr happy,'' he said, a reference
to the former independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr. ``But he did
not know anything. The man has been punished more than he otherwise
would have because he would not lie, not because I had any role in
getting him any business contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides questions about the Riadys and the Lippo Group, Clinton
was confronted with a wide array of campaign finance issues, from
his relationship to the fund-raisers John Huang and Yah Lin Trie to
his ``livid'' reaction after he discovered the Democratic Party had
accepted millions of dollars in contributions from foreign citizens
and foreign corporations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is that I was livid about it, because, No.
1, it was, it was embarrassing,'' Clinton said. ``Number _ and I
thought it was wrong not to vet these things. I thought that it
was, it put all of us in a very bad position.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview was the third since 1997 that Clinton has given to
Justice Department prosecutors investigating campaign finance
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Siewert, a White House spokesman, said the White House
decided to release the transcript Monday night because they had
turned it over to the House Committee on Government Reform earlier
in the day. ``We're not going to give people on the Hill the
satisfaction of making an issue out of a non-issue,'' Siewert said.
``There is no issue here.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the interview, which occurred in the Treaty Room on
the second floor of the White House residence, a White House
official said Clinton was not a target of the criminal inquiry and
that he cooperated fully with investigators.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tone of Clinton's interview differed significantly from the
caustic confrontation between Vice President Al Gore and Conrad,
which occurred on April 18. Gore's interview focused on what the
vice president knew about a 1996 luncheon at a Buddhist temple that
was used to raise money for the Democrats. Gore denied that he knew
it was a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad also questioned Clinton about his dealings with many of
the figures at the center of the 1996 campaign fund-raising
investigation, including Trie, Chung, Pauline Kanchanalak and David
Chang, all of whom were charged with violations of federal campaign
finance laws. clinton was asked about letters and gifts he received
from these individuals and their foreign business associates and
whether Clinton knew they were raising money illegally from foreign
nationals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied any knowledge of illegal fund-raising by these
Asian-Americans for the Democratic Party. ``You've got to
understand,'' Clinton told Conrad. ``I know this may look
incredibly naive, but I had a lot of things going on. I believed
that all these people knew what the law was.'' Clinton added, ``I
was aghast when I found out about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He did say he thought Chung was ``kind of hustling,'' and
worried about having photographs taken with Chung's business
associates. But Clinton said he was ``not worried about them being
illegal givers or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was extensively questioned about White House coffees he
hosted for Democratic supporters. Like Gore, who was also
questioned at length about the coffees by Conrad, Clinton denied
that the events were fund-raisers or that there was a price to
attend them. Clinton defended the White House coffees, telling
Conrad that he regretted ``that they got a bad rap in the end,
because I enjoyed them and found them helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   While denying that there was any stated price to attend the
coffees, he said: ``Obviously, we weren't naive. You know, I wanted
these people to help us. I wanted them to give us money. But, to
the best of my knowledge, nobody was given a price tag to come to
coffee at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was also asked whether Gore was truthful when he
testified that the coffees were Clinton's idea. ``I wouldn't
disagree with that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's answers to Conrad's questions were reminiscent
of the tortured wordplay he used with investigators for the
independent counsel in the Monica S. Lewinsky investigation. When
pressed about his testimony about whether anyone at the Democratic
National Committee had told him that there was a price to attend
the coffees, Clinton responded, ``Now, I'm not sure that anybody
ever explicitly said they weren't saying what you said.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was questioned about matters large and small, including
his decision to keep a picture frame of little value given to him
by a business associate of Kanchanalak. ``My guess is it was a nice
picture frame worth $50 or something and you can look around
here,'' Clinton said. ``We never have enough picture frames.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about glitches in the White House e-mail system,
Clinton said he knew nothing about the problems until they were
reported by the news media. He said he never sends e-mail. ``And I
don't do it because _ I mean, I leave, I've got a big paper
trail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
