<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NORTEL-INVEST-NYT &LR;      07-24 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL IN TALKS WITH CORNING ON OPTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN and CLAUDIA DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The telecommunications equipment giant Nortel Networks is
discussing a complex transaction to sell its fiber optics
components business to Corning Inc., the leading supplier of glass
fiber, according to people familiar with the negotiations. But some
analysts and industry executives say the plan is so cumbersome, and
expensive, that the deal may never get past the talking stage.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms being discussed, Corning would acquire Nortel
Networks' fiber optics unit through a ``reverse merger'' that could
effectively make Nortel Networks the parent of Corning. The deal
would value Nortel Networks' fiber optic unit, which is expected to
have revenue of $2.5 billion, at more than $100 billion. That is
more than Corning's total stock market value and would make Nortel
Networks a majority shareholder of Corning.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company would comment. But executives close to the talks
said that both companies are seeking a corporate governance
structure that would allow Corning to operate independently of
Nortel. In fact, according to the executives, the deal would be
contingent on that assurance.
</P>
<P>
   Each company is trying in its own way to respond to the
consolidation in the fiber-optics components field. JDS Uniphase
has emerged as the leader in that field through acquisitions that
include a deal two weeks ago to acquire SDL for $41 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a further sign that the Corning talks may be only tentative,
Nortel announced Monday that it planned to invest $1.9 billion to
more than double its fiber-optics components manufacturing capacity
in Australia, Britain, Canada and the United States
</P>
<P>
   If it did complete a deal with Corning, Nortel would be
attempting to capitalize on the increasing value of fiber-optics
components, while enabling itself to concentrate on designing and
building networks using its own multimillion-dollar switching
equipment. Corning would be attempting to expand its
fiber-components line to remain competitive with JDS Uniphase.
</P>
<P>
   But the risk to Corning and to Nortel, which competes
head-to-head with the larger Lucent Technologies, would be for the
rest of the industry to perceive the two companies as so closely in
league that their rivals might be reluctant to do business with
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, customers might be loath to buy from a company
owned by the major competitor,'' warned Lawrence M. Harris, an
analyst who follows Corning for Josephthal &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Corning's shares, which had nearly doubled in the last year,
tumbled on news of the talks with Nortel, first reported Monday in
The Wall Street Journal. The stock fell 12 percent, closing at
$250, down $33.25 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel's stock barely budged, closing up 75 cents to end at $82
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   While it remains unclear whether the two companies can reach a
deal _ and people familiar with the negotiations stressed that the
talks could be abandoned at any point _ the discussions underscore
the increasing pressure on manufacturers of fiber optic products to
consolidate as the components end of the business becomes
increasingly one of largely undifferentiated commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the talks with Nortel fall through, Corning is unlikely
to give up its dream of becoming an end-to-end optical components
supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, speculation has been rife on Wall Street that Corning
might be seeking a deal with Lucent, or with one of two European
companies, Perelli and Alcatel. All three have operations that
could help fill out Corning's product portfolio. But few analysts
expect Lucent to sell its components business and Perelli has
already sold a 10 percent stake to Cisco, a data network equipment
company that increasingly competes with Lucent and Nortel. Alcatel,
meanwhile, has been talking about spinning off its fiber optics
business as a tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, capacity is so constrained throughout the optical
network industry that customers are forced to buy amplifiers and
lasers and other components wherever they can find them. But most
producers are ramping up capacity, to the point where many analysts
assume that, three or so years down the road, supply may exceed
demand. At that point, the components makers in a position to
survive would be those with a full line of wares they can produce
and sell in large volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Corning, once known primarily for housewares, bailed out of that
business entirely three years ago, in order to focus on
high-technology businesses like photonics _ the lasers, amplifiers
and filters that blast signals down the fiber optic pipelines of
modern telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Its entree may have been glass fibers, but Corning has been on a
buying spree, spending more than $6 billion on acquisitions in the
last year alone, as the company has become the leading supplier of
optical amplifiers, cables and fibers. It recently announced a
joint venture with Samsung, called Samsung Corning Microptics, that
will work on automating the manufacture of so-called dense
wavelength division multiplexing devices, which split signals into
different wavelengths, or colors, of light and thus enable fibers
to carry far more data. And earlier this year it bought out
Siemens' 50 percent stake in Siecor, Corning's longtime
joint-venture fiber cable company, and acquired the rest of
Siemens' fiber operations.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Corning had 17,000 employees. Today it has 33,000.
Most came with the acquisitions, but it has been on a hiring spree
as well, bringing in as many new research scientists as it can
find. Analysts said that Corning has doubled its research and
development budget over the last five years. This year Corning
expects to hit $7 billion in revenues, with 70 percent coming from
communications products. But most of its products are so-called
passive products, items that manipulate and route the signal after
it has been generated. What the Nortel deal would provide is entree
into the active part of the process _ the lasers, receivers and
modulators used to actually generate the laser signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three items are the big hole keeping Corning from having
an end-to-end product portfolio, and there's no small independent
player that Corning could buy that would provide them with all
three,'' said Hasan Imam, who follows Corning for Donaldson Lufkin
&AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Nortel and Corning are already joined at the hip.
Nortel is Corning's largest buyer of optical amplifiers, the
devices that keep signals strong as they travel long distances. And
it is Corning's largest independent supplier of pump lasers _ a
main component of the amplifiers it sells back to Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   After Nortel, Corning's main outside supplier for pump lasers is
SDL. In fact, Corning tried to buy that company, but got trumped
when JDS Uniphase, Corning's main competitor, came in with its $41
billion offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
