<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, JULY 25 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-G8-CLINTON-NYT (Moved on Saturday, July 22)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, July 22,
about the Group of 8 summit meeting in Japan referred incorrectly
in some copies to an adviser to President Clinton on international
economic issues, who commented on the meeting. The adviser, Lael
Brainard, is a woman.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TRAINS-HORNS-NYT (Moved on Tuesday, July 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, July 18,
about a proposed federal regulation requiring trains to blow their
horns at railroad crossings misstated the title of John V. Wells at
the Federal Railroad Administration. He is deputy administrator,
not administrator.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WIZARDOFOZ-CENTENNIAL-NYT (Moved on Saturday, July 22)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, July 22,
about a festival in Bloomington, Ind., to celebrate the publication
centennial of ``The Wizard of Oz'' gave a misspelled surname in
some copies for an actor who played a Munchkin in the later movie.
He is Clarence Swensen, not Swenson. In some copies the article
also misspelled the name of the theater where a play, ``Oz,'' was
staged as part of the festival. It is the Buskirk-Chumley, not
Bushkirt-Chumley.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SOPRANOS-CASTCALL-NYT (Moved on Saturday, July 22)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, July 22,
about a casting call for the HBO television series ``The Sopranos''
misspelled the surname of a co-producer and production manager in
some copies. He is Henry Bronchtein, not Brunchtein.
</P>
<P>
   BC-RECORD-BOOK-ADVANCE-NYT (Moved on Wednesday, July 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July
13, about the $7.1 million book advance reportedly being paid to
John F. Welch Jr., the chairman of the General Electric Company,
referred to the precedents incompletely. While the advance is
apparently a single-book record for North American nonfiction
rights, higher amounts have been paid for worldwide English rights.
Pope John Paul II reportedly received an $8.5 million advance in
1994 for his book about Roman Catholicism in the modern era. The
sale of Mr. Welch's worldwide English rights is expected to add
millions to his North American advance.
</P>
</TEXT>
