<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VICE-PREZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IS SET TO NAME CHENEY AS PARTNER ON TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Wyo.)   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush has decided on former
Defense Secretary Richard Cheney as his running mate and could
announce his selection as early as Tuesday, a highly placed
Republican official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the expected Republican nominee, did not tip his hand as
he arrived at the Texas governor's mansion Monday afternoon after a
weekend of deliberations. But only formalities appeared to stand in
the way of an announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republicans said that Bush planned to make the offer of
the second spot on the Republican ticket either late Monday or
Tuesday. Karen Hughes, Bush's director of communications said on
CNN's ``Larry King Live'' Monday night that Bush would make the
offer Tuesday morning, though she did not say whom he would call.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing Cheney, a respected party elder who had been running
Bush's vice presidential search, Bush made a risk-free and
respectable choice that was cheered by many party stalwarts. Cheney
has a wealth of government experience and a government resume more
far-ranging that Bush's own six years as governor. It includes a
Cabinet stint as defense secretary under Bush's father during the
Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   By age 34, Cheney was already White House chief of staff,
helping President Gerald Ford with the difficult transition after
the Watergate scandal that drove Richard Nixon from office. He
later became a Republican congressman from Wyoming, rising in party
ranks to the leadership post of whip.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was a staunch supporter of Ronald Reagan with a
conservative voting record, he was uncomfortable with the sharply
partisan style of Rep. Newt Gingrich, who was also rising in the
party hierarchy and sought sharp confrontations with Democrats as a
method of bringing Republicans into the majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney meets all of Bush's criteria as someone who could step in
as a commander in chief, someone compatible and loyal. Republicans
said that Bush's father had also strongly supported the selection
of Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides had hoped to keep the vice presidential selection
under wraps until Bush himself announced it. And the governor kept
his own counsel as his motorcade arrived back at his mansion Monday
afternoon. In shirt sleeves, looking relaxed, even bemused, Bush
shouted to the hordes of reporters: ``No news today! No news
today!''
</P>
<P>
   For months speculation over whom Bush would select had focused
on an array of governors and senators as well as former Sen. John
Danforth of Missouri. But many had some liability.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, for example, was a strong
supporter of abortion rights, a stand that could alienate the
party's conservative base. Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma drew
complaints from some Republicans that he was too conservative to
attract swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska was not well known. Rep. John
Kasich of Ohio appeared too boyish. And though some Republicans
were pressing for Sen. John McCain of Arizona, Bush's chief primary
rival, relations remained raw between the two camps.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it seems significant that when he named Cheney to
lead his search, Bush did not rule him out as a possible running
mate. But Cheney himself said that he did not want the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolutely no desire to go back to government,'' he
said in May. ``I've done that. I am set in my ways at my stage. I'm
59, and I didn't leave anything in Washington. I have no plan,
intention, desire, under any circumstances to return to
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that Cheney's thinking turned as he worked
closely with Bush and many in the party asked him to reconsider.
And on Friday, Cheney suddenly emerged publicly as the
front-running candidate for the ticket after he flew to Wyoming to
change his voter registration to avoid a constitutional problem.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th Amendment bars members of the Electoral College from
selecting ``inhabitants'' of their state as both president and vice
president. Cheney, a resident of Texas, also has a home in Jackson
Hole, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   By then, a senior Republican said, Bush had already decided
Cheney was his leading choice, but he wanted to consider his
decision once more over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, chairman and chief executive of the Halliburton Co., an
energy services and construction concern based in Dallas, told his
directors on Thursday that he might be offered the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a history of three mild heart attacks and bypass
surgery, he also took a physical examination and received a clean
bill of health. At the request of Bush and his father, the former
president, the heart specialist Denton Cooley reviewed Cheney's
medical records and said he was fit for the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
