<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: IMMIGRANT DEATHS
</P>
<P>
   The police discovered the bodies of a man and a woman in waters
off Spain's southern Mediterranean coast and they were believed to
have drowned in a new surge of clandestine emigration from North
Africa. At least three dozen illegal aliens were picked up Monday,
the day after authorities apprehended 311 people, mostly Moroccans
and sub-Saharan Africans, trying to cross the Strait of Gibraltar
in a record one-day total.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: CUBAN'S ARREST ORDERED
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Chavez has ordered the arrest of a man who says
he is one of 1,500 Cuban intelligence agents sent by Fidel Castro
to promote Communism in Venezuela but now wants to defect. The
detention order came in the heat of the campaign for the July 30
presidential election in which the friendship of Chavez, a
left-leaning populist, with Castro has been criticized by
opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: LEFTIST OVERTURE
</P>
<P>
   The leftist Party of the Democratic Revolution, which had kept
president-elect Vicente Fox at arms-length since the July 2
election, said it will seek a dialogue with Fox about major
national issues. Fox needs an alliance with the left or with the
defeated governing party if he is to pass congressional
initiatives. It remained unclear whether leaders of the leftist
party would agree to Fox's invitation to help him form his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR: MILITANTS ANNOUNCE CEASE-FIRE
</P>
<P>
   Four months after India said it was ready to talk to Kashmiri
rebels if they abandoned violence, the Hizbul Mujahedeen
unilaterally declared a three-month cease-fire and expressed
willingness to negotiate with the Indian government. Hizbul
Mujahedeen is the second militant group to declare a cease-fire.
The Jammu and Kashmir Liberation Front did so in 1994. About 30,000
people have died in the insurgency against Indian rule since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: POLICE ON STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   About 18,000 junior police officers in the eastern state of
Bihar began a weeklong strike, demanding compensation for the
families of officers killed in the line of duty since 1995, an end
to political interference in the running of the police force and
the renovation of police buildings. The state government has
declared the strike illegal and suspended more than 150 officers.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IVORY COAST: CONSTITUTION'S APPROVAL EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   Ivoirians continued to vote on a draft constitution that would
determine the rules of coming elections a day after the military
government extended voting to a second day because of widespread
problems and delays. Early results indicated that the constitution,
which all major parties endorsed, would be approved.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: WAGE PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   The country's largest trade federation threatened to hold a
three-day strike this week if the government refuses to increase
the minimum wage. The government offered to increase the minimum
wage by 16 percent, to $34 a month. The federation, the Mozambican
Workers' Organization, says that is inadequate and is demanding an
increase of 30 percent.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
