u p BC-GA-MILLER-NYT &LR;      07-24 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA GOVERNOR APPOINTS HIS PREDECESSOR TO FILL COVERDELL'S
SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes on Monday appointed his popular
predecessor, Zell Miller, to succeed the late Paul Coverdell as
U.S. senator, a choice that instantly changed the partisan
political calculus both in Georgia and in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a 68-year-old Democrat who left office in early 1999
after two terms, will serve as senator on an interim basis and then
run in a nonpartisan special election in November to fill the
remainder of Coverdell's term, which extends until January 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's acceptance of the offer to succeed Coverdell, a
Republican who died last week, was a huge relief to Barnes, a
Democrat, and to party leaders around the country, including
President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. Several officials
close to Barnes said the governor was convinced that Miller was the
only Georgia Democrat who could hold on to the seat in November,
particularly given the scarcity of time to raise money and organize
a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in his Capitol office this evening, Barnes
made it clear that Miller, who rebuffed pleas from President
Clinton to run against Coverdell in 1998, was not easily persuaded
to abandon his position as a college professor in the north Georgia
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end,'' said Barnes, who was lobbied by Democratic
aspirants virtually from the moment that Coverdell died last
Tuesday after a stroke, ``the one who didn't want it was the one
who had to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a career politician who left office with approval
ratings that hovered near 80 percent, said ``the fires of political
ambition that had burned so long and so strong within me had
finally cooled.'' But he said he ultimately accepted the job
because of his devotion to his state and the sense of obligation he
developed as a marine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept this mission,'' he said, ``with a heavy heart and a
profound sense of duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell was secretary of the Senate Republican conference.
Miller's appointment narrows the Republican margin in the Senate to
54 to 46, and provides an unanticipated boost to Democratic hopes
of winning control in either this November's general election or in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this year's campaign, Democrats had been given a far
greater chance of taking control of the House than the Senate. But
Coverdell's death and Miller's appointment, coupled with close
Senate races in several states with either open seats or Republican
incumbents, have given the Democrats renewed hope.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republicans remain favored to retain control of the
Senate, Miller's appointment means the Democrats could take over by
picking up a net of five seats in the event of a Republican
presidential victory, or by picking up four seats if Gore wins the
presidency in November. That is because a four-seat gain would
result in a partisan deadlock in the Senate that could be broken by
Gore's Democratic vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's appointment also could help Gore in his quest to win
Georgia in the presidential election. The state, which has become a
partisan battleground in recent years, is considered to be leaning
toward Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive Republican
nominee, but not by enough to keep Gore from contesting it
aggressively. Gore will presumably benefit from get-out-the-vote
efforts by Miller and Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush will have to spend more time in Georgia if he
expects to carry the state,'' said Merle Black, a political
scientist at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Black said that Miller was ``the strongest possible candidate
that Gov. Barnes could have chosen'' and that he would easily unite
Georgia's various Democratic factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he said, ``it's really hard to see how anybody
could beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Whitfield Ayres, a Republican pollster based in Atlanta,
agreed that Miller was the strongest Democratic choice, but
minimized his potential influence on the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zell Miller is popular in part because independent and
Republican-leaning voters have supported him in the past,'' Ayres
said, ``but those same voters are more likely to prefer George Bush
than Al Gore. And I don't know that Zell Miller on the ticket
generates any substantial increase in turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection leaves Georgia's Republicans in a quandary. Before
Monday's announcement, several of Georgia's eight Republican
congressmen had been considering entering the race to succeed
Coverdell. But Miller's apparent strength is likely to chill the
ambitions of many, particularly since the congressmen would have to
resign their relatively safe seats to run for the Senate. Aides to
several of the Republican House members said they planned to meet
on Tuesday afternoon to discuss their options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off of eight years of service, he's obviously a
formidable candidate,'' said Rep. Johnny Isakson, one of several
Georgia Republicans considering the race.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Clay, the state Republican chairman, said it was vital for
his party to unite quickly around a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   There is no limit to the number of candidates who can compete in
the nonpartisan special election, meaning the Republicans might
split the conservative vote if more than one runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we cannot do is shred our vote between two or three
candidates and let a Democrat walk into Paul Coverdell's office,''
Clay said. ``What a travesty that would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay criticized Barnes for not appointing a caretaker senator
who would be faithful to Coverdell's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gone back to what they know best, which is power
politics,'' he said of the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who lost a gubernatorial primary to Miller in 1990,
countered that Miller was clearly the most qualified candidate of
either party.
</P>
<P>
   Miller wasted little time in appealing Monday to independent and
Republican voters, pledging to adopt the ``spirit of dignity,
integrity and bipartisan cooperation that were the hallmarks of
Paul Coverdell's career.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who has run for statewide office seven times, is best
known for bringing the lottery to Georgia and devoting the proceeds
to college scholarships and universal pre-kindergarten programs.
His education strategies have been emulated by several other
governors and by Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
