<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REFORM PARTY
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN IS CHALLENGED ON BALLOTS: John Hagelin said Monday that
Pat Buchanan, his rival for the Reform Party's presidential
nomination, should be disqualified from running because he appeared
to have committed ``massive election fraud'' in seeking voter
support. Hagelin said his rival's campaign ignored party rules in
acquiring primary ballots for nonparty members. The list of names
that Buchanan came up with was far too large, he said _ 262,314
Republicans in 10 states. Hagelin said he came up with 9,169 names
for those states. Party rules permit candidates to request ballots
for supporters but require that nonparty members initiate the
requests. Hagelin accused Buchanan of stretching that provision.
Buchanan's campaign countered that it had worked with the party's
nominating committee to ensure compliance with the rules.
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   SURVEYS OFFER MIXED RESULTS: Gov. George W. Bush continues to
lead Vice President Al Gore in a pair of new Research 2000
presidential preference polls from Washington state and Idaho and
in a Opinion Dynamics poll from Ohio. But Gore remains ahead in a
new Research 2000 polls from California. In Washington, the new
poll, covering 605 voters between July 7 and July 10 with a margin
of sampling error of plus or minus 4 percentage points, gives Bush
43 percent to 39 percent for Gore, with Ralph Nader at 7 percent
and Pat Buchanan at 2 percent. The Idaho poll, of 601 voters from
July 5 to July 8 with a margin of sampling error of 4 percentage
points, has Bush still ahead of Gore 57 percent to 21 percent, with
Buchanan at 4 percent and Nader at 2 percent. In the Ohio poll,
covering 501 registered voters on July 19 and July 20 with a margin
of sampling error of 4 percentage points, Bush leads Gore 43
percent to 34 percent, with Nader at 6 percent and Buchanan at 5
percent. The poll in California surveyed 827 voters from July 17 to
July 19, with a margin of sampling error of 3.5 percent, and has
Gore ahead of Bush 44 percent to 37 percent; Nader draws 8 percent
and Buchanan 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORT FOR GUN CONTROL: Handgun Control Inc., a nonprofit group
that advocates gun control, released a poll Monday showing that
voters strongly favor toughening the nation's gun laws and would be
more likely to vote for candidates who support such laws. The poll,
conducted by Peter Hart, a Democratic pollster, found that roughly
six of 10 voters strongly favor licensing handgun owners, selling
guns with safety locks and requiring buyers at gun shows to undergo
background checks.
</P>
<P>
   _ By James Dao
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
