</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiger marching over past, present, future
</P>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ After all these years of griping about
not getting the really, really big bucks because they were born too
early, members of golf's older generation now realize they can
relax in the comfort of their advanced age.
</P>
<P>
   Though they won pennies on the dollar by comparison, paving the
way for the current zillionaires was a small price to pay for being
able to avoid the Tiger Woods era.
</P>
<P>
   Would any of them _ Tom Watson, Fred Couples, Greg Norman, Nick
Faldo, even the great Jack Nicklaus _ really want a second chance
with Tiger Woods running around winning everything? It's like
deciding what you'd do if you were up to the big question on Who
Wants To Be A Millionaire and got asked something you had no clue
about.
</P>
<P>
   You'd take the money you already had in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my majors on the wall,'' said Faldo, who has won six
of them. ``But if I were setting out now, I'd be looking for
absolute perfection.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than risk it, the ones who have been there and done that
a few times are content to sit back now and watch Woods make his
relentless march past all of their numbers and all of their
records.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mark O'Meara, the neighbor and good friend of Woods, has to
be happy he got his two majors in '98, when Woods was rebuilding
his swing. That was the window of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   At least O'Meara got to have some laughs before Woods'
onslaught. After winning the British Open on Sunday by a mere eight
strokes _ down seven from his runaway in the U.S. Open last month _
Woods truly is worthy of all the accolades anybody wants to throw
at him. He's won three of the past four majors, and given that he
gears his schedule around the four biggest tournaments of the year,
who's to say that's not an average he won't keep up?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has ever won all four of them in the same year, but
that must be Tiger's ambition now,'' Faldo said. ``He has the game
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows that better than O'Meara. Peer pressure can be a
positive thing sometimes, and in the case of two pals from Orlando,
Fla., it has worked wonders as they now have matching Claret Jugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, Tiger is an exceptionally talented young man and a
tremendous player,'' O'Meara said. ``I spent a lot of quality time
with him last week, and it doesn't surprise me to see what he did.
I know that he is capable of doing it. And I know how badly he
wanted that championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows when I won (the British) in '98, and I brought the
Claret Jug back on the plane with Tiger, he looked at it. He held
it and knew that he wanted it someday. I think he was happy for me
that I'd won as a friend, yet I think he realized in his mind that
he wanted to see his name printed on that trophy very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   But it's impossible for any of his challengers to hold a grudge
against Woods. Yes, he has all the money anybody could ever dream
of, a supportive mother and father, a lovely girlfriend, and a
support team that takes as much pressure as possible off him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet everybody in golf knows he is good for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is just so good,'' O'Meara says. ``I play with him, I
practice with him, and I know him probably as well as anybody
besides his mom and dad and maybe his girlfriend. But he is one of
those sports figures that doesn't come along very often.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, who had been No. 2 in the world for so long before
Ernie Els passed him on Sunday with a runner-up finish to Woods,
said everybody who plays golf for money knows they owe a debt of
gratitude to Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made it cool to be a golfer,'' said Duval.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara is sure that has happened. He also knows that the way
Woods is performing, it should come as no surprise to anybody if he
cranks out major after major after major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly this year, after the way he played at the U.S. Open
and then coming here to the Open Championship at St. Andrews, he
knew it would be special,'' O'Meara said. ``He knew he would be the
heavy favorite. And sometimes that amount of pressure is just
tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he played with a lot of poise. He handles himself
exceptionally well on a golf course, and I'm proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the younger players _ the Duvals, Mickelsons, Elses and
Garcias _ who must wonder what to do. When Woods didn't oversleep
and didn't eat that alleged foodstuff called haggis, it was pretty
much a formality that he would win the British Open on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was everybody else who was left sick to his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
