<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-POLICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE POLICE CHIEF NOMINEE OUTLINES PRIORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gil Kerlikowske outlined two of his top priorities Monday as
Seattle's soon-to-be highest-ranking police official: bolstering
morale and championing community policing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give the guidance, directions and parameters to
be not one of the best departments in the country, but the best,''
Kerlikowske said at a City Hall news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Paul Schell, who introduced his nominee as ``the right
person for Seattle,'' said the choice was almost a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``His strengths match perfectly with what Seattle and the
department need in their next police chief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor lauded Kerlikowske, 50, for having the communications
skills needed to build a bridge between the department and the
community, and the breadth of national experience to usher city
policing into a new century.
</P>
<P>
   Hinting at one of the reasons why he had an edge over two other
finalists _ Madison, Wisc., Police Chief Richard Williams and
William McManus, an assistant police chief in Washington, D.C. _
Schell noted that Kerlikowske had experience running a ``big city''
police force.
</P>
<P>
   After commanding the Buffalo, N.Y., police force for four years,
Kerlikowske left in 1998 to work as a deputy director of the U.S.
Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   That experience appears to have earned Kerlikowske the respect
of the nine-member City Council, which is expected to unanimously
endorse the mayor's selection over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be 9-0,'' predicted Jim Compton, chairman of the
nine-member council's public safety committee. ``There's nobody
I've talked to who isn't really excited about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Councilman Peter Steinbrueck admitted Monday he would
have preferred to see Schell hire Williams, who is African
American, in part to ease police distrust in the minority
community.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Steinbrueck said the council should give Kerlikowske a
thorough going over before confirming him.
</P>
<P>
   Compton, however, said extensive backgrounding of the candidates
means no surprises will likely emerge about Kerlikowske before the
full council votes on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   After all, his endorsements go all the way to the Clinton
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno commended Schell on his selection of
Kerlikowske, whom she termed a ``champion of community policing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gil Kerlikowske has been a dedicated leader,'' Reno said in a
prepared statement. ``I am sorry to lose Gil from the department,
but delighted he has seized on the opportunity to serve the people
of Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday Kerlikowske unveiled some of the tasks he looks forward
to as Seattle police chief, beginning with revamping the way the
department uses community policing and improving morale.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked at the news conference by his wife, Anna Laszlo, and the
mayor, Kerlikowske said he hopes to get a jump start on both issues
when he participates in Block Watch ``Community Night Out'' events
around the city on Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   First, he wants to integrate community policing throughout the
Seattle force, turning a patrol-level policy into one that
encompasses the department's many investigative squads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than a special unit. It's more than officers on
bicycles,'' Kerlikowske said. Eventually he'd like to introduce
aspects of community policing to detectives in robbery and traffic
detectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission isn't to keep the status quo at all _ we're going
to need to move forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He took his first steps toward improving morale by publicly
proclaiming that the department he'll take over isn't one that
needs fixing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exemplary in many ways. ... They need to hear that from
the chief,'' he said of officers. ``I picked Seattle because of its
reputation for integrity and for not having systemic corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees better morale taking root in an accessible chief who is
clear about accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly going to be a vocal supporter when they're right
and take responsibility when they make mistakes, or I make
mistakes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his two priorities, Kerlikowske will face his first big
decision in September, when he helps implement the new Office of
Professional Accountability.
</P>
<P>
   After scrapping an eight-month search for a civilian director,
the city has renewed its search for an outsider to oversee internal
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Kerlikowske said he plans to address reports that blacks in the
city get a disproportionately high number of traffic tickets, and
abolish unfair treatment of any of the city's citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Training, too, will receive attention that has been lacking, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When confirmed, Kerlikowske will earn $140,000 a year, nearly
$20,000 more than retired Chief Norm Stamper earned and the pay
ceiling the job was advertised at, according to city spokesman Dick
Lilly.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly attributed the discrepancy to Kerlikowske's ``longer
resume'' and keen negotiating skills.
</P>
<P>
   Kerlikowske's top priorities reflect Schell's concerns, as does
the full schedule he's imposed on himself over the next few weeks
__ meeting officers at roll call, connecting with communities,
learning what the department needs.
</P>
<P>
   That work comes naturally, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a human-service, public safety job. The uniforms and the
patches are different, but it's really the same job where ever you
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
