<HEADER>
A2016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SCHOOL-SUIT-NYT &LR;      07-24 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SCHOOL BUDGET OVERHAUL IS URGED  

</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WYATT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The plaintiff in a lawsuit challenging New York
state's system of allocating money to school districts has asked a
state judge to order a thorough reassessment of how much it costs
to provide a sound basic education to all of the state's public
school students.
</P>
<P>
   The Campaign for Fiscal Equity said on Monday in its final
written arguments that the state's system for allocating education
money had put New York City at so large a disadvantage that only an
overhaul of the budgetary process could correct the situation. The
group's argument relies in part on the results of 19 successful
lawsuits challenging the education aid programs of other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a fair study that focuses on the costs of education
essentials and a way of delivering those services,'' Michael A.
Rebell, executive director of the campaign, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   New York City, which has 38 percent of the state's students,
receives 35.5 percent of the state's education aid, according to
the campaign, a coalition of advocacy groups. Because of the
demographic makeup of New York City's pupil population, the group
said, using the state aid formulas has meant that, on average,
minority-group students get less financial support than other
students.
</P>
<P>
   The state said in its final written arguments that no such
overhaul was needed, citing its finding that even the city's most
disadvantaged students fared no worse on standardized tests than
similar students in urban and rural districts across the state. The
state also said the city misspent hundreds of millions of dollars
of aid each year, citing mismanagement, corruption and
administrative waste.
</P>
<P>
   The statements were submitted on Monday afternoon in State
Supreme Court in Manhattan. Closing arguments before Justice Leland
DeGrasse will take place on Thursday. A decision is expected this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff's proposed remedy would be likely to increase
school funds in districts with large numbers of minority-group
children, or with high failure and dropout rates. The change could
increase state education costs by $3 billion above the present $13
billion, some experts believe.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff also asked the judge to expand a higher court's
definition of a ``sound basic education.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 decision that allowed the current case to proceed to
trial, the Court of Appeals, the state's highest court, said a
sound basic education ``should consist of the basic literacy,
calculating, and verbal skills necessary to enable children to
eventually function productively as civic participants capable of
voting and serving on a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs said that definition should be expanded to
include the skills needed to ``sustain competitive employment.''
</P>
<P>
   In its argument, the state said the educational opportunities
available in New York City schools ``substantially exceed
constitutional minimums.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state argued that the plaintiffs had failed to
prove that the city's schools fell short of preparing students for
the job market or that such deficiencies could be traced to the
state's aid decisions.
</P>
<P>
   If the New York City Board of Education needs additional
support, the state concluded, it should come from local sources,
not from the taxpayers in other parts of the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
