<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2020 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-FUND-RAISING-     07-24 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUND-RAISING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JUSTICE INQUIRY, CLINTON DENIES SEEKING FINANCIAL HELP FOR
HUBBELL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs for writetrhu.)   By DON VAN NATTA JR. and JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an interview with a senior Justice Department
prosecutor in April, President Clinton denied any recollection of a
pledge for a $1 million campaign donation by the Indonesian
businessman James T. Riady and denied asking Riady to help
financially the former Justice Department official Webster L.
Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments were contained in a 155-page transcript of
his April 21 interview with Robert J. Conrad Jr., the department's
chief political-finance prosecutor. The transcript was released
Monday night by White House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time that Clinton's testimony on a wide array
of campaign finance issues has been made public. The release came
at a time when it was likely to be overshadowed by the impending
news of Gov. George W. Bush's vice presidential selection, but a
White House spokesman denied any connection. The spokesman, Jake
Siewert, said the White House was concerned that the transcript
would be released by Republicans on the House Government Reform
Committee. The Republicans received it, under subpoena, earlier
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the interview was devoted to questions about
Clinton's lengthy relationship with Riady, a generous political
patron of the president who, the prosecutor suggested, had bragged
to Indonesian government ministers that his family enjoyed a
``direct pipeline to the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's line of questioning about the Riadys and
Hubbell is noteworthy because Riady has been under pressure in
recent weeks to accept a plea bargain agreement from the Justice
Department's campaign finance task force. Conrad has actively
investigated Riady's activities in connection with campaign
contributions made by him and employees of the Lippo Group, the $12
billion Riady family conglomerate, to the president's campaign in
1992 and his dealings with Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong company controlled by Riady paid Hubbell $100,000 on
June 27, 1994, after Hubbell resigned from the Justice Department
and faced a criminal inquiry over law-firm billings. Just four days
earlier, on June 23, Riady met with the president at the White
House after meeting that morning with Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he could not recall discussing Hubbell's need for
paid work with Riady.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, there was a lot of kind of, you know, a lot of
people who knew Webb were expressing some sympathy for him,'' the
president said. ``And, you know, if James Riady said to me, I'm
going to try to help him, he could have said that, I wouldn't have
_ and I mean, it wouldn't surprise me if he did, but I do not
remember him saying that to me. And, you know, he might have
deliberately avoided saying anything to me thinking it wouldn't be
appropriate to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the interview, Clinton again denied talking to anybody
about Hubbell's financial distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to understand two things,'' he said. ``No. 1, I
believe the people that helped Webb Hubbell did it because, like
me, they believed he was innocent. No. 2, I believe Webb Hubbell
was persistently persecuted by the independent counsel because he
would not lie about me or Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was also asked about a limousine ride he took in August
1992 with Riady in California. John Huang, a former Democratic
fund-raiser who pleaded guilty to campaign finance violations last
year, told federal investigators that Riady promised to give $1
million and that ``President Clinton's reaction was one of
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president told Conrad in the interview that he did not
recall the ride or the offer. ``I don't have a specific
recollection of what the conversation was, or this fact of the car
ride,'' Clinton testified. He added that he recalled seeing Riady
``sometime in '92 after I became the nominee,'' and that Riady had
offered to help his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Riady and Lippo gave more than $1 million to the Democrats in
1992, and that money is the subject of the current criminal
investigation of Riady.
</P>
<P>
   The president was pressed again about whether he could
specifically recall Riady's $1 million pledge, but he said he could
not recall it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he said a million, I'm surprised I don't remember it,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides questions about Riady, the president was confronted with
a wide array of other campaign finance issues, from his
relationship to Huang and Charlie Trie to his ``livid'' reaction
after he discovered the Democratic Party had accepted millions of
dollars in contributions from foreign citizens and foreign
corporations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is that I was livid about it, because, No.
1, it was, it was embarrassing,'' Clinton said. ``And I thought it
was wrong not to vet these things. I thought that it was, it put
all of us in a very bad position.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The interview was the third since 1997 that the president has
given to Justice Department prosecutors investigating campaign
finance issues. The transcripts of the earlier two interviews were
not subpoenaed by congressional investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Siewert, the White House spokesman, said there was nothing in
the transcript to cause the president worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to give people on the Hill the satisfaction of
making an issue out of a nonissue into an issue,'' Siewert said.
``There is no issue here.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the interview, which occurred in the Treaty Room on
the second floor of the White House residence, a White House
official said the president was not a target of the criminal
inquiry and that he had cooperated fully with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   At several points in the interview, Clinton portrays himself as
a victim who has been hounded for years about questions of
overzealous Democratic fund-raising. The tone of the president's
answers, which veered between genial and terse, where he often
failed to recollect fund-raising details, differed significantly
from the caustic confrontation between Vice President Al Gore and
Conrad, which occurred on April 18 at the vice-presidential
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the president's answers to Conrad's questions were
reminiscent of the tortured wordplay he used with investigators
from the office of former independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr
during the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad also questioned Clinton about his dealings with other
figures at the center of the 1996 campaign fund-raising
investigation, including Johnny Chung, Pauline Kanchanalak and
David Chang, all of whom have been charged with violations of
federal campaign finance laws. The president was asked about
letters and gifts he received from these individuals and their
foreign business associates and whether Clinton knew they were
raising money illegally from foreign nationals.
</P>
<P>
   The president staunchly denied any knowledge of illegal
fund-raising by these Asian-American fund-raisers for the
Democratic Party. ``You've got to understand,'' Clinton told
Conrad, ``I know this may look incredibly naive, but I had a lot of
things going on. I believed that all these people knew what the law
was.'' The president added, ``I was aghast when I found out about
it.'' He did say he thought Chung was ``kind of hustling,'' and
worried about having photographs taken with Chung's business
associates. But the president said he was ``not worried about them
being illegal givers or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad asked Clinton about whether his policies and visits to
foreign countries were influenced by fund-raisers. The president
said they had not been.
</P>
<P>
   The president was extensively questioned about White House
coffees he held for Democratic supporters. Like Gore, who was also
questioned at length about the coffees by Conrad, the president
denied that the events were fund-raisers or that there was a price
to attend them. The president defended the White House coffees,
telling Conrad that he regretted ``that they got a bad rap in the
end because I enjoyed them and found them helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   While denying that there was any stated price to attend the
coffees, he said, ``obviously, we weren't naive. You know, I wanted
these people to help us. I wanted them to give us money. But, to
the best of my knowledge, nobody was given a price tag to come to
coffee at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was questioned about matters large and small, including
his decision to keep a picture frame of little value given to him
by a business associate of Kanchanalak. ``My guess is it was a nice
picture frame worth $50 or something and you can look around
here,'' Clinton said. ``We never have enough picture frames.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about glitches in the White House e-mail system,
Clinton said he knew nothing about the problems until they were
reported by the news media. He said he never sends e-mail. ``And I
don't do it because _ I mean, I leave, I've got a big paper
trail.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
