<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELTON'S ROCKY ROAD TO RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We live in the Atomic Age of baseball statistics, in which
almost any achievement at the plate can be shrugged off as a
mutation, the batter shunned as if radioactive.
</P>
<P>
   Cozier ballpark dimensions, creative balls-and-strikes umpiring,
protein-packed sluggers, expansion-thinned pitching staffs and
tighter-wound baseballs have turned the fans' fabled love of
numbers to apprehension. Can a .380 batting average be trusted
anymore? Can it be compared to a .380 batting average from decades
past? Or is it really a .280 average set aglow by unnatural
science?
</P>
<P>
   These days you need more than a calculator to evaluate the
leading hitters. You need to know, for instance, that Denver's
altitude and arid air cause batted balls to carry 11 percent
farther at Coors Field than at the typical park, as somebody
actually calculated.
</P>
<P>
   And how does it feel to be the object of such study, as is
Colorado Rockies first baseman Todd Helton, the National League's
top batter (.381)?
</P>
<P>
   ``It about makes me want to slug you upside the head,'' Helton
said last week when I brought up the topic of his apparent
home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Helton said this flatly, in a tone neither threatening nor
humorous. It seemed that Helton would simply prefer to be known as
a batman, not as an X-Man, a freak.
</P>
<P>
   Helton, 26, came into his third full major-league season as a
star in the making, having improved on his .315, 25-home run,
97-RBI season in 1998 with .320-35-113 in 1999. But he was in
danger of becoming a star with an asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he batted .385 at Coors, where the ball flies as if
from a missile launcher and easily finds gaps in the league's
deepest outfield. But he batted .252 on the road. He hit 23 homers
at home, 12 away.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody doubted that Helton had the tools to be great _ the body
of a former University of Tennessee quarterback and a studious
nature _ but it was natural to wonder if the Coors effect was
making him look better than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I've got to apologize for the place I play,'' Helton
groused during the Rockies' visit to Dodger Stadium last week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Helton is not the first Colorado hitter to go under
this microscope. The Rockies, who came into being in 1993, have
produced an unnerving number of league leaders _ Andres Galarraga
(batting, 1993; homers and RBI, 1996; RBI, 1997), Dante Bichette
(hits, homers, slugging and RBI, 1995; slugging, 1998), Ellis Burks
(runs and slugging, 1996), and Larry Walker (homers and slugging,
1997).
</P>
<P>
   Helton is, though, one Colorado hitter who has set out to do
something about the Coors questions, something more constructive
than complaining about them.
</P>
<P>
   He has become a .300 hitter on the road this season. His road
average stands at .314 as the Rockies host the Dodgers this week.
That improvement is a big reason he made his first All-Star team
earlier in the month.
</P>
<P>
   Helton is a bright man and he knew he had holes in his game. His
hitting against left-handed pitchers was a hole. His hitting on the
road was a gaping hole.
</P>
<P>
   Since his two-sport days at Tennessee, where the Knoxville
native was Baseball America's 1995 college player of the year, he
has recorded every at-bat in a notebook for later analysis. The
notebooks aren't as detailed as they were when he took down every
pitch. But they helped him sort out his problem.
</P>
<P>
   He figured out there wasn't anything tangible tamping down his
numbers on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I look at an at-bat and say, 'I made an out
there because the ball broke sharper,' '' Helton said, referring to
the notion that curveballs bend less in the thin Denver air. ``It's
mental. It's about transferring the feeling I have at home to the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   One theory says that for a player who's new to Coors Field, the
home-field advantage is nearly offset by the shock of returning to
the road and to reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys develop a tremendous comfort zone (at home),'' said
Clint Hurdle, the Rockies' hitting coach. ``(Coors) is
hitter-friendly. It might be the !ital!most hitter-friendly. They
know if they get a good swing on a good pitch, there's reward from
foul line to foul line.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've tried to stress to them is that they've got to take
that swagger on the road. Certainly (Helton's) numbers are
indicative of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd has been able to eliminate a lot of the questions that
were presented to him in his first couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about his power, gone. Questions about handling
lefties, gone. Questions about hitting on the road . . . going.
</P>
<P>
   Of his 24 home runs this season, 17 have come at Coors. Of his
72 RBI, 54 have come at Coors. And although he has made himself a
.300 hitter on the road, he has raised his average at Coors exactly
as much, to .447 going into Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   If it bothers him to have the disparity pointed out, the
solution is obvious. He's going to have to find a way to hit worse
at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
