<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR'S CORRECTION: CHENEY'S HEALTH `GOOD,' BUT HEART FUNCTION NOT
`NORMAL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUSH-CHENEY) By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dick Cheney's personal cardiologist said Monday night that the
man Gov. George W. Bush has apparently chosen to be his running
mate was in good health and had no symptoms of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, the physician, Dr. Jonathan Reiner of
Washington, took issue with part of a statement released Monday by
a cardiac surgeon in Houston and friend of the Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, the Houston surgeon, Dr. Denton A. Cooley,
said: ``In a recent checkup by Dr. Reiner, he declared that Mr.
Cheney is in good health with normal cardiac function.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiner said that Cooley had called ``about a week ago'' to
discuss Cheney's medical history. Cheney has had three heart
attacks, but none since he underwent a quadruple coronary bypass
operation in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In their conversation, Reiner said he told Cooley that ``Mr.
Cheney is in good health, leads a vigorous professional and
recreational life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reiner said he ``did not characterize (Cheney) as having
normal cardiac function.''
</P>
<P>
   Heart attacks destroy muscle cells that cannot be replaced. The
amount of heart function lost after an attack, or series of
attacks, depends, in part, on how much heart muscle has been
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley had said he ``conveyed to Governor Bush that in my
opinion Mr. Cheney's health problems in the past should not
interfere with a strenuous political campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiner said Monday night that Cheney could withstand a strenuous
campaign. He declined to provide details about Cheney's medical
condition until he received permission. He said he expected such
permission would be forthcoming if Bush named Cheney as his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley said he had agreed to review Cheney's heart records after
a call from former President George Bush ``and presumed approval of
Gov. George W. Bush.'' Cooley did not say whether Cheney had given
his permission.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say who authorized him to make statements about
Reiner's recent examination and other aspects of Cheney's medical
records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0538 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SPORTS-MONARCHS &LR;      07-24 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SPORTS-MONARCHS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MONARCHS OF THEIR SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 25:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are few obvious analogies between endurance cycling and
professional golf. Tour de France cycling, for all its strategic
interest, is consummately a physical sport, while professional golf
is consummately a strategic sport, though its young players are
growing physically stronger and stronger. Perhaps the greatest
similarity between Lance Armstrong, who won his second consecutive
Tour de France on Sunday, and Tiger Woods, who won the British Open
at St. Andrews, Scotland, on the same day, is their ability to
demoralize the competition, to leave everyone else playing for
second place.
</P>
<P>
   But to each man his own victory. Like his win last year,
Armstrong's triumph in this year's Tour de France is made more
significant by the fact that he is a cancer survivor. It attests
not only to his own remarkable talents but also to a personal
courage that he shares with other cancer survivors. As for Woods,
his win at St. Andrews _ following his victories in the U.S. Open,
the PGA Championship and the Masters _ amounts to a kind of
canonization. By the time he sank his final putt on Sunday evening,
the Old Course at St. Andrews was knee-deep in hyperbole, all of it
true.
</P>
<P>
   When David Duval, playing with Woods on the final round, found
himself in a deep bunker on the 17th hole, he faced the nearly
impossible task of trying to fly his ball out of the sand and over
a six-foot wall a foot away. It took him four shots to get out, and
it felt to many viewers, and perhaps many players, as though that
wall were somehow Tiger Woods, a resolute, uncanny obstacle in the
path of every professional golfer. Duval's struggle, which was
heart-rending in itself, gave us an opportunity to witness, yet
again, the dignity with which Woods carries himself. As Woods and
Duval left the 18th green, bareheaded, Woods rested his right hand
on Duval's right shoulder. There was not much he could say, but the
gesture meant everything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
