<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-HOLLYPK-LADN-(SLA     07-24 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HOLLYPK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKEL WINS TITLE WITH CLOSING KICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Bobby Frankel's horses _ and the Hall of
Fame trainer himself _ put on a big finish Monday at Hollywood
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Starmaniac rallied from next to last in a field of 10 to win a
starter-allowance race and The Seven Seas surged from last in a
field of seven to win the $136,375 Estrapade Stakes. Their
victories on closing day vaulted Frankel to a record ninth training
championship at the Hollywood Park spring-summer meet.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Frankel was fourth in the standings, trailing
leader Bob Baffert by six wins. Going into Monday's races, Frankel
was still third, having saddled 21 winners, one behind Baffert and
Cliff Sise.
</P>
<P>
   Sise's only runner Monday finished fourth. Baffert's pair of
entrants finished fourth and fifth. Frankel sent out a third-place
finisher before winning with his last two starters of the meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't mean that much at this stage of my career,''
said Frankel, 59, who cares more about lucrative stakes victories
nowadays, and was elected to the Racing Hall of Fame in 1995. ``I
had what, 23 wins? When I won the title here in 1972, I had 60
wins. That's a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't plan this. The only time I started to think about it
was in the last four or five days.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's 60 wins in 1972 remains a Hollywood Park record. That
was the first of his six consecutive titles at the Inglewood track
after his arrival from New York as ``King of the Claimers.''
</P>
<P>
   His ninth spring-summer title broke a tie with Bill Molter, who
led for the last time in 1956. This was Frankel's first
spring-summer title since he finished in a tie with Mike Mitchell
in 1982. Frankel also has two titles at the Hollywood Park autumn
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's 27 titles on the Hollywood Park-Santa Anita-Del Mar
circuit put him one behind Farrell Jones, whose last was at Oak
Tree in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The Seven Seas ($5), a 4-year-old filly ridden by Alex Solis,
gave Frankel his fourth stakes victory in July, following
Happyanunoit (Beverly Hills Handicap), Honest Lady (A Gleam) and
Euchre (Bel Air).
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's earlier winner Monday, Starmaniac, was ridden by
Victor Espinoza, the 28-year-old Mexico City native who had
clinched his first major riding title on Saturday. Espinoza
finished the 65-day meet with 62 wins, 11 more than Corey Nakatani
and 19 more than Laffit Pincay (who raised his record career wins
total to 8,949).
</P>
<P>
   Off the track, management was happy with a surge in business,
beginning after the Lakers' championship run, that resulted in a
nearly 5 percent rise in on-site wagering from last year, the first
increase at the spring-summer meet since 1993. Overall wagering
rose nearly 6 percent to a record $10.3 million-a-day average.
</P>
<P>
   But average attendance slipped by about 2.5 percent to 9,820
on-site and 22,062 including off-track facilities, marking the
track's seventh consecutive decline.
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar opens a 43-day meet Wednesday at 2 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
