<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS SLIDE ON WORRIES
</P>
<P>
   About Computer Shipments Stocks dropped, pushing the Nasdaq
composite index below the 4,000 level as a report that growth in
personal computer shipments slowed in the second quarter led to a
slide in shares of computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 112.88 points, or 2.8 percent,
to 3,981.57. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 48.44 points,
or 0.5 percent, to 10,685.12. The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index sagged 15.90 points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,464.29.
</P>
<P>
   MERCK AND PFIZER POST SOLID GAINS
</P>
<P>
   The drugmakers Merck and Pfizer posted strong gains in
second-quarter profit. Net income at Merck rose 16 percent, beating
Wall Street estimates, while profit from operations at Pfizer
gained 21 percent, in line with forecasts. Shares of Merck rose
$5.875, to $69.625, while Pfizer closed at $47.5625, up $1.6875,
before it announced its results.
</P>
<P>
   ROTH URGED TO ACT ON DRUG PROPOSAL
</P>
<P>
   Saying that William V. Roth Jr., the chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, appeared to be dragging his feet, Democrats
urged him to take action on his proposal to establish prescription
drug benefits under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   DEMAND FOR KING E-BOOK FALLS SHORT
</P>
<P>
   Demand for Stephen King's new electronic book fell far short of
his last, an event in March that seemed to foretell a revolution in
publishing when 400,000 fans jammed computer servers to download it
in the first two days.
</P>
<P>
   SALE SPECULATION LIFTS BEAR STEARNS
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the UBS agreement this month to buy PaineWebber
for $12 billion, executives of the remaining independent financial
services firms are worrying about being left alone at the dance.
Shares of Bear Stearns leaped 7.7 percent on an analyst's report
that the firm might be for sale. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   STATE FARM IS FOCUS OF AN INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Insurance Commissioners said that it
had begun investigating reports that State Farm, the largest auto
insurer, improperly denied claims for treatment of injuries in
accidents nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   BP AMOCO SEEKS TO REVAMP IMAGE
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco is undertaking a $7 million rebranding campaign that
seeks to reposition the company from an old-economy gas station
giant into a progressive, environmentally friendly retailer that
goes, in the company's own words, ``beyond petroleum.'' The
campaign includes a new green, yellow and white BP sunburst-shaped
symbol and a new type of gas station, called BP Connect, where
customers will be able to check the forecast for an impending
thunderstorm on a small screen at the pump, buy a bottle of wine
and some fresh-baked croissants. Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   AIR DELAYS CALLED UNDERESTIMATED
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, the two agencies that track airline delays have
underestimated the amount of time lost by passengers by a total of
247 years, according to a study to be released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   To extend its contract with pilots, American Airlines said that
it would drop its claim to a $45 million fine for a job action in
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   $15 BILLION MADE IN PLANE ORDERS
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Airbus Industrie announced more than $15 billion in
orders at the air show in Farnborough, England.
</P>
<P>
   H &AMP; R BLOCK SETTLEMENT REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has rejected a proposed $25 million settlement
in a class-action lawsuit that accuses H &AMP; R Block and a lender of
being unfair to customers who received tax refund anticipation
loans.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN COMPANY CLEARED IN INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   In a long-running inquiry into embezzlement and money
laundering, international auditors have exonerated one of the
companies of Boris A. Berezovsky, the top Russian executive and
onetime insider who has denounced a Kremlin crackdown on rich
businessmen.
</P>
