<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-SURHOFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURHOFF IS THE NEXT OBJECT OF YANKEES' ARDOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Leery of trading their best prospect to get Rondell
White from the Montreal Expos, the New York Yankees are negotiating
to make a deal for B.J. Surhoff, Baltimore's veteran left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from the teams exchanged a handful of possible trade
combinations Monday afternoon. The Yankees offered David Walling, a
Class AA right-hander who was their first-round draft pick last
year, as well as a second prospect, to be picked from a list of
three: the Class AA shortstop Erick Almonte, the Class AAA pitcher
Ryan Bradley and the Class AA pitcher Brian Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Through Sunday's games, Surhoff, 35, was batting .294 for the
Orioles, with 12 homers and 56 runs batted in. He is considered by
scouts to be a solid if unspectacular outfielder, not blessed with
extraordinary range or throwing ability but sure-handed and usually
in the right place at the right time. He is widely respected for
his intensity; his on-field demeanor is similar to that of Paul
O'Neill, the Yankees' right fielder. Surhoff is essentially a
contact hitter, with only 44 strikeouts in 388 at-bats, with 29
walks.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff is making $3 million this year and will make $3.5
million next year. He has a vesting option for the 2002 season for
$4.5 million that he should easily qualify for, meaning that if the
Yankees make a deal for him, they know he may be with them for
another two years. Surhoff's contract contains a limited no-trade
clause, but the Yankees are not among the teams Surhoff can block.
The Mets are among those teams, perhaps the result of a frustrating
end to negotiations between Surhoff and the Mets after the 1998
season, when the Mets were negotiating with Surhoff and Robin
Ventura at the same time and signed Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles have been trying to trade Surhoff for months, but
their preference has been to keep him close to his Maryland home,
where one of his children is enrolled in a special-needs program.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Surhoff would give the Yankees four left-handed
hitters and two switch-hitters from positions No. 3 to No. 8 in the
lineup, a situation other teams would try to exploit. But few
contender actually have quality left-handers: Boston has reliever
Rheal Cormier, Seattle has Jamie Moyer and John Halama, the Chicago
White Sox field Jim Parque and Mike Sirotka, the Toronto Blue Jays
have David Wells. The majority of pitchers the Yankees will face
are right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   When the Chicago Cubs were asking for several prospects for
Sammy Sosa last month while the principal owner George Steinbrenner
pushed for a big trade, club executives desperately searched for a
less-expensive alternative that nonetheless could have some impact
on the team. They found David Justice, swapping three young players
instead of the five for Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees' executives seem to be working in a similar circumstance
now. The Montreal Expos are ready to deal White, who has repeatedly
been on the disabled list, and have asked the Yankees for Alfonso
Soriano, the most developed prospect in the organization. The Red
Sox are believed to be involved, as well, perhaps offering third
baseman Wilton Veras and another prospect. Again, Steinbrenner is
pushing for action, wanting to address the left-field vacancy that
was created when Shane Spencer blew out his knee July 9.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees can complete the negotiations for Surhoff _ and
the chances of that have improved because the Orioles appear to
have backed off their long-standing demand for Soriano _ then
Surhoff, like Justice, would represent a less-expensive compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have other options for left field, such as trading
for Philadelphia's Ron Gant, Pittsburgh's Wil Cordero and John
Vander Wal, or making a deal for Texas' David Segui. But those are
all imperfect fits, because they are all poor defensive
outfielders; trading for Cordero, for instance, would require
Justice to play left field more than the Yankees want, with Cordero
serving as designated hitter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
