u a BC-NJ-GIBSON-INDICTED-NY     07-24 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GIBSON-INDICTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER NEWARK MAYOR IS CHARGED WITH SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Kenneth A. Gibson, who as Newark's mayor for 16
years was the first black elected to lead a major northeastern
city, was indicted Monday on federal fraud, bribery and conspiracy
charges in connection with his consulting firm's management of a
$50 million school construction project in Irvington.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the 18-count indictment of the former mayor and two
associates in his Gibson Associates engineering firm, Robert J.
Cleary, the U.S. attorney for New Jersey, said Gibson had ``ripped
off'' the Irvington Board of Education by overbilling it for some
work done and falsely billing it for work that was never done.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Gibson, 68, had bribed two board members and used
his Newark firm, which he has run since leaving office in 1986, as
a ``personal, tax-free piggy bank'' to funnel the money into
personal investments and expenses. In the end, Cleary said, it was
the children of Irvington who suffered, as the project managed by
Gibson's firm ran out of money in 1995 before it was completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our view, there is a public trust even given his current
role, in which he has a fiduciary responsibility to provide honest
services,'' Cleary said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   When he was elected mayor in 1970, Gibson became a national
spokesman for the plight of older cities, and in 1982 he almost won
the Democratic nomination for governor. But after four terms in
City Hall, he was defeated in 1986 by the current mayor and a
former ally, Sharpe James.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, Gibson attempted a comeback, but narrowly
lost in his bid to unseat James W. Treffinger, a Republican, as
Essex County executive, despite a Democratic edge in voter
registrations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his name recognition, the contacts he made while in
office and the political history his tenure evokes have aided
Gibson, who is trained as a civil engineer, in winning consulting
contracts with public agencies like the Essex County Improvement
Authority and the Passaic Valley Sewer Authority, as well as a
number of local governments in the state and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Indicted with Gibson on Monday were Camille Savoca, 53, of
Newark, the vice president and co-owner of the firm, and Gibson's
companion, and William Bernowich, 53, of Washingtonville, N.Y., who
was project manager on the Irvington job. The three co-defendants
were not arrested; they will be arraigned at a date yet to be
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Bernowich would not comment on the charges. Gibson and Savoca
issued a statement through their lawyer, Cathy Fleming, calling the
indictment ``unfortunate and unwarranted,'' but one they were aware
might be coming as a result of a four-year investigation by the
Federal Bureau of Investigation and the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, associates of Gibson described him as unsurprised and
seemingly unperturbed by the charges, in part because of the many
investigations he has survived.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview when he was mayor, Gibson, asked about
investigations his administration faced on matters from its hiring
practices to its purchasing and housing programs, observed, ``In my
13 years in office, there has never been a month when we're not
being investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the Essex County prosecutor, George L. Schneider,
charged him with giving out a no-show job. Gibson was acquitted
after a six-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations into Newark's political leadership have continued
in the last decade, leading to the convictions of nine sanitation
officials in the Gibson administration, two members of the City
Council and the top aide to Mayor James.
</P>
<P>
   Two former members of the Irvington Board of Education were
mentioned in Monday's indictment as unindicted co-conspirators,
said Ralph J. Marra Jr., an assistant U.S. attorney. The indictment
charges that in 1992, Gibson met with the two board members and
proposed to pay them each $3,000 to $4,000 to show his appreciation
for receiving the construction contract, and that he later paid at
least one. Marra would not name the members or say whether they
were cooperating with the prosecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
