<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0544 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CONFEDERATE-AZR &LR;      07-24 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-CONFEDERATE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ``CONFEDERATE'' NAME IS LIKE DRAWING FLAK(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BETTY BEARD(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Mesa, ARIZ.) - The name of the Confederate Air Force Museum in
Mesa has become such an embarrassment that its brochures only use
``CAF.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We play down the Confederate part because of problems we're
having with the Confederacy name,'' said Milt Moenich, wing leader.
``We've lost some corporate donations because they're connecting us
with the Confederacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa museum at Falcon Field, started in 1978, is a branch of
the nationwide Confederate Air Force Museum founded in the
mid-1950s to restore and preserve old military aircraft. It has
nothing to do with the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The national Texas-based organization is asking its members to
approve a name change. But because of the bylaws, that will take
two elections. A change, if approved by 75 percent of those who
vote, would take place in January 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Some names suggested already are Commemorative Air Force, which
would let the group keep its CAF initials, or Ghost Squadron, its
longtime nickname, said Tina Corbett, marketing and communications
director for CAF in Midland.
</P>
<P>
   She said there are rumors that the group is being pressured to
change its name but said that the impetus comes from the members.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``Confederate'' has become especially controversial in
the light of an economic boycott launched by the NAACP of South
Carolina because of a Confederate flag that has flown over or near
the Statehouse dome in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Corbett said the Confederate Air Force includes Black members.
CAF volunteers in Minnesota are painting a P-51 Mustang in the
colors of the Tuskegee Airmen, a squadron of Black pilots who flew
about 15,500 missions during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it's called, the organization is dedicated to restoring
and preserving old military aircraft and honoring the thousands of
pilots who bravely climbed into cramped plane compartments, flew
into the frigid skies where temperatures fell to minus-40 or below
and risked their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep alive the memory of all the men who gave their
lives to keep this country free,'' said Moenich, 75, who volunteers
at the museum four days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you see some old gentleman saying he flew one of
these aircraft. You see tears coming out of his eyes. This is quite
emotional. This is our pay,'' said Moenich, tears gathering in his
eyes. ``I get choked up when I talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate Air Force Museum in Mesa has nine aircraft, plus
some others on loan. Its two featured aircraft, a fully restored,
flyable B-17 Flying Fortress Sentimental Journey and a German
Heinkel-111, are gone now on their annual summer tours to cooler
climates.
</P>
<P>
   Although the museum draws about 60,000 visitors a year, it has
few visitors now because the lack of air-conditioning turns the
hangar into a sauna. The museum is attempting to build a larger $2
million museum but has only collected about $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   The museum treats visitors to flights in the B-17 (at $350 a
person) and lets them climb into several planes, an experience that
shows visitors just how awkward and frightening it would have been
for World War II pilots, with bullets flying at them while they
shivered.
</P>
<P>
   Moenich wasn't a pilot but performed electrical repairs on
aircraft in the war. Still, he has talked to enough veterans to
know what it was like.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were trapped. You couldn't get out in the face of bullets
and shrapnel flying by. You were cold. Even though you had a heated
suit, your face was not heated.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Moenich said many vets clammed up about their war
experiences because ``it was something they wanted to forget.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at betty.beard(a)arizonarepublic.com or
(602) 444-7982.
</P>
</TEXT>
