<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBINSON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY BELIEVED TO HAVE RAISED CHILD LINKED TO ROBINSON PLANS TO
MAKE STATEMENT  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY SCOTT CANON, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo., _ The family who raised the baby police
believe to be the daughter of Lisa Stasi plans to make some kind of
public statement in the next few days. Lisa Stasi disappeared after
meeting serial-killing suspect John E. Robinson Sr. 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The family's attorney said over the weekend that the family was
``anticipating making a statement...in a few days.'' He would not
indicate what sort of public comment the couple planned other than
to say it would probably not contain much detail.
</P>
<P>
   So far the girl's adoptive parents, a couple known to Robinson,
have declined comment other than to say they are ``cooperating
fully with law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The family's plan to make a statement comes as authorities are
apparently near to amending the charges against Robinson, perhaps
accusing him in the kidnapping of Lisa Stasi's daughter, Tiffany
Lynn, now 15 years old. That charge would be added to five existing
murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Stasi's blood relatives have been told by prosecutors
that they expect the charges to be amended by next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and investigators, sensitive to how the case could
disrupt a teen-ager's life, have declined to publicly discuss their
progress in identifying Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   A blood sample, which could be used to confirm whether the
teen-ager is Tiffany, was taken from her maternal grandmother early
last week. Results of a test to match DNA were not yet complete.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany was 4 months old, the daughter of 19-year-old Lisa
Stasi, when in-laws reported them missing in early 1985, days after
Lisa accepted an offer of shelter and job training from Robinson.
Friends and relatives have not seen Lisa Stasi since.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, mainly from Johnson County, are looking into
whether Tiffany was raised under a new name by a middle-class
family living in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Last month The Kansas City Star found the family thought to be
raising Tiffany and learned that she had just finished her freshman
year in public high school.
</P>
<P>
   The case holds myriad legal and ethical riddles because the girl
is a minor.
</P>
<P>
   The case _ where a girl is raised by strangers in what could
stem from kidnapping and the possible murder of her mother _ has
only vaguely similar precedents. But discoveries in other parts of
the nation _ children switched at birth or where a biological
parent contests an adoption _ have set off tangled custody fights.
Missouri records indicate this adoption was off the books.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Stasi married Lisa Stasi about a month before Tiffany was
born on Sept. 3, 1984, in Kansas City and is listed as her father
on her birth certificate. He has told The Star he is not eager to
disrupt the life of a teen-ager he has never really known. He now
lives in Kirksville, Mo., has remarried and is the father of
another daughter, a toddler.
</P>
<P>
   The search for Tiffany Stasi had been stymied for years. It
picked up again this summer with the discoveries of five women's
bodies stuffed in barrels on Robinson's property. He was charged
last month with five counts of capital murder, all involving women
who appeared to have died in recent years. But at least three other
women, Lisa Stasi among them, disappeared in the 1980s after making
contact with Robinson. He faces no charges involving those women.
 &LR; tag1:To reach Scott Canon, national correspondent, call (816)
234-4754 or send e-mail to scanon &LR; kcstar.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
