<SLUG> BC-INSUR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS FORFEITS $2.6 MILLION EARMARKED FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JOHN A. DVORAK, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As thousands of Kansas children go without health insurance, it
would seem the state could make good use of $2.6 million earmarked
by the federal government to fight the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But say goodbye to the money.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas could not spend it, so Kansas will lose it. Some of the
funds are, in effect, headed for Missouri to help the state budget
there.
</P>
<P>
   Slowness by the Kansas Legislature contributed to the snag.
</P>
<P>
   To forfeit $2.6 million is ``obviously a shame,'' said one
activist for children in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The predicament centers on the Children's Health Insurance
Program, which Congress passed three years ago to offer free or
reduced-price coverage for children whose families could not
otherwise obtain it.
</P>
<P>
   Each state operates a version of the program, and some of the
money comes from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas officials defend their program, saying they have achieved
considerable success despite leaving some of their money unspent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all wish we could have had all these children
covered and spent every last dime,'' said Bobbie Graff-Hendrixson,
who oversees the program as a senior manager at the Kansas
Department of Social and Rehabilitation Services, in Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she said, the program resulted in 39,000 children
receiving health-care protection in less than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done quite well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet thousands of children who could benefit do not. According to
U.S. Census Bureau estimates, as many as 20,000 Kansas children may
still lack insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had been able to find more children, we could have spent
more money,'' said Marcia Boswell-Carney, who monitors the
program's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what happened:
</P>
<P>
   States that did not get their programs running quickly enough,
or did not enroll enough children quickly enough, have federal
money left over from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   States that moved faster and enrolled lots of children promptly
spent all their money.
</P>
<P>
   Those states are slated to get a share of the leftover money,
according to the federal government. Missouri is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1998, when the children's insurance issue arose, Kansas
and Missouri took different approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates showed that 60,000 Kansas children lacked health
coverage, but the Kansas Legislature was not swift to act.
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucrats were unsure how to proceed. Different committees
conducted studies. Jousting over abortion affected the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature finally passed the necessary law.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri acted faster and developed its program differently than
Kansas did.
</P>
<P>
   By September 1998, Missouri was taking in children. Kansas did
not start until January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In all states the programs are aimed at the poor and at people
who work but do not have access to insurance through their jobs.
Income guidelines apply.
</P>
<P>
   Some states face a much bigger loss of funds than Kansas does.
Texas, which acted slowly on the children's insurance issue, is
slated to lose $450 million of federal money. Several states will
lose more than $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Melvin Neufeld, who helped set up the Kansas program,
said he was not upset about the loss of $2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what the Legislature believed was the correct thing to
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially the Legislature decided to set up a new program for
children's insurance. Missouri decided to operate through Medicaid,
an existing program to help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld, who lives in southwestern Kansas, said some people
attached a stigma to Medicaid, considering it welfare and not
something they wished to use.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neufeld acknowledged that if the Legislature had acted
faster, Kansas might have spent more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little slow getting going,'' said Gary Brunk,
executive director of Kansas Action for Children, a Topeka-based
activist group. ``It's obviously a shame that we need to return the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But the state has been doing a good job signing up children, he
said. ``I'm pretty happy with how things have progressed,'' Brunk
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas tries to publicize its program widely. The state even
used billboards to inform families that insurance was available.
</P>
<P>
   People fail to join for a variety of reasons. They may not have
heard about the program, may not think they are eligible or may not
like to ask for government aid.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, 17,447 children are enrolled in the program. Missouri
has 64,250. In addition the Missouri program resulted in children
signing up for Medicaid who were not getting help before.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vadner, who oversees children's insurance as director of
the Missouri Division of Medical Services, in Jefferson City, said
his state set out in 1998 to develop its program as rapidly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Additional funds from other states, he said, would go to offset
a tax that hospitals paid in Missouri to defray the cost of
children's insurance. Indirectly, he said, the money will help
hospitals provide indigent health care.
</P>
<P>
   How much Missouri might receive was not yet known.
</P>
<P>
   Vadner did not comment directly about the loss of money in his
neighboring state.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said: ``We certainly would be able to use that. It would
be a good thing for Missouri.''  &LR; tag1:To reach John A. Dvorak,
Kansas government and politics reporter, call (816) 234-7743 or
send e-mail to jdvorak &LR; kctar.com  &LR; brfhed:How to get medical
insurance for children
</P>
<P>
   Your family, depending on its income, may qualify for free or
reduced-price health coverage for children. Kansas and Missouri run
separate programs. Both operate somewhat like HMOs. Both cover
young people up to age 19. Monthly premiums may be charged.
Applying is not difficult. Missouri residents should call 1 (888)
275-5908. Kansas residents should call 1 (800) 792-4884.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
