<HEADER>
A2052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COMICS-TO-FILM-2TAKES     07-24 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMICS-TO-FILM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMIC BOOK HEROES DON'T ALWAYS SUCCEED ON-SCREEN   
</HEADLINE>
 
(Critic's Notebook)   By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 1965 book, ``The Great Comic Book Heroes,'' which
features the best essay ever written on the subject, the cartoonist
Jules Feiffer described comics as ``movies on paper.'' Both art
forms exploit action and express character through movement. These
peculiarly American forms of juvenilia have probably forever
changed the fantasy lives of children, giving them the superpowers
to defeat the monsters in their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   In the preface to ``Justice League of America,'' a collection of
comic-book stories, Salman Rushdie reflects on how inspirational he
finds the adventures of these heroes. The touchingly faithful movie
adaptation of ``The X-Men,'' which leapt to a $54 million gross on
its opening weekend, proves that there's an appetite and an
audience for comic-hero movies. And its $23 million second weekend
ensured that more are to come; in the film business, nothing
succeeds like excess. The problem is that moviemakers take comics
too seriously, or not seriously enough.
</P>
<P>
   The pleasures that comics and movies provide are so similar that
it's criminal that so few films have managed to find the right
balance in adapting comic book superheroes to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Though many movies have been inspired by comics in subtle ways,
some of the best action movies haven't been based on comics. ``The
Matrix,'' of course, is the finest example. It ingeniously steals
from so many sources _ Homer and the Bible, to name just two _ that
one couldn't find a docket big enough if charges were preferred.
</P>
<P>
   The film's writers and directors, the brothers Andy and Larry
Wachowski, used the pictorial vitality of comic books as the
movie's foundation. The action is orgiastic, as it often is in
comics, an energy that can't be contained. (The comic-book artist
Geof Darrow worked on ``Matrix'' 's'' visual scheme, and the
Wachowskis themselves have written comics.)
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Smith has unabashedly shown his love for comics in his
films; he even made the Marvel Comics mainstay Stan Lee the
onscreen voice of wisdom in ``Mallrats,'' a reason to forgive the
movie. Smith's ``Dogma,'' which ponders the vagaries of faith
within a ragtag group at various stages of belief, is a tribute to
Matt Wagner's comic ``Mage,'' which touches on the same issues but
with comic-book dynamism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mage'' is the Arthurian legend updated, in which Excalibur is
a baseball bat in contemporary Philadelphia. It is such a well-told
story that it is a natural for the movies, one that avoids the
dicey problem of costumes because none of the ``Mage'' characters
suit up for action in tights. Probably the reason ``Mage'' remains
unsullied by movie-industry hands is that Wagner isn't stupid; he's
seen the crummy treatment that film adaptations of comics have
received and has elected to save himself the humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Moviemakers look down on comics, fixating on their traditional
appeal to children instead of on the way the medium has matured in
the last 30 years. This sophistication has largely come from Marvel
Comics (birthplace of ``The X-Men'') and its creative powerhouses,
Lee and the artist-writer Jack Kirby. In the 1960s, they came up
with a black superhero _ the Black Panther, who was an African
prince and a totemic representation of his mythical country _ years
before Hollywood took its black audience seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who received the writing credits for most of the Marvel
superhero titles (the extent of his authorship has since been
called into question) got the connection between movies and comic
books years ago. During the 60s, he cunningly dropped the names of
the directors Alain Resnais and Federico Fellini into Stan Lee's
Soapbox, his pop-pop-pop self-promoting column that appeared in the
back of every Marvel comic. Lee wrote that these film artists made
a point of visiting Marvel's offices when they were in New York to
express their affection for what Marvel _ and Lee _ were doing for
the medium.
</P>
<P>
   The directors became as familiar to readers of ``The Uncanny
X-Men'' or ``The Amazing Spider-Man'' or ``The Incredible Hulk'' or
any of the other adjective-ridden Marvel superheroes as Marcello
Mastroianni was to Fellini aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   In responding to the often vapid print adventures of his
competitors, Lee was incredibly canny in the way he shaped
comic-book heroes and subverted the idiom. In the days when most
comic-book heroes had a sidekick or ward to function as a reader
surrogate _ apparently, adoption agencies in the Gotham City area
were quite lenient about allowing wealthy playboy bachelors to
adopt little boys _ Lee recognized that young readers didn't want
to stand next to the superheroes. They wanted to be the
superheroes.
</P>
<P>
   By exploiting this wish, Lee forged a strong rapport with his
readers; imagine that the teen-age protagonists in John Hughes
movies had superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Marvel heroes could catch a break, and the
grandiosity of their pain had a peppery bite. You can see why
Fellini would go for these stories, with their blend of fairy-tale
derring-do and proscenium-arch soap opera. Resnais, with his
silvered formality, got a kick out of the volatility of the art:
battles royal that sprawled all over the page and captured readers
with their surreal sensationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Lee, loyal Marvel fans like me, kids for the most
part, were exposed to film directors who accomplished, in their
way, what Marvel had managed for comics: they changed the
parameters of what was often considered a throwaway medium.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since Fellini and Resnais reached out to Lee to
express their admiration, movie adaptations of comic book heroes
have practiced a reverse alchemy. The evidence is that dusty aisle
in your local Blockbuster, with forgotten videos like ``Swamp
Thing,'' ``Spawn'' and ``Captain America.''
</P>
<P>
   For every ``Blade,'' which was very smart about the parts of the
comic book worth preserving and the ones that needed to be thrown
out, or ``Men in Black,'' which took a little-known comic book as a
point of departure, there was a ``Spawn,'' which was overblown and
inert. Or a ``Batman Forever'' and a ``Batman and Robin,'' which
seemed determined to return Batman to the triviality to which the
campy 60s television series had consigned him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM HERE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can work comics fans into a sweat on the coldest day of the
year by bringing up that incarnation of Batman. It's the series in
which Adam West slipped into a pair of tights that did nothing for
his figure, used that stop-and-start cadence that was often the
province of 60s television stars (did he and William Shatner take
the same correspondence course?) and engaged in playground versions
of fistfights with actors who were as out of shape as he was. Cesar
Romero, as the Joker, had so much contempt for his character that
he didn't even bother to shave his upper lip. With all that white
makeup covering his mustache, he looked like the inventor of the
``Got Milk?'' advertising campaign.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM HERE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Dark Knight was an object of ridicule long before that
60s series, with its Pop Art ``Pow!'' and ``Biff!'' In ``The Great
Comic Book Heroes,'' Feiffer dismissed him by noting, ``Batman had
to take off his rich idler's street clothes, put on his Batshirt,
his Batshorts, his Battights, his Batboots; buckle on his Batbelt
full of secret potions and chemical explosives; tie on his Batcape;
slip on his Batmask; climb into his Batmobile and go fight the
Joker who in one punch (defensively described by the author as
maniacal), would knock him silly.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the 1989 ``Batman'' movie by the director Tim Burton to
wash the bad taste out of the mouths of fans and prove that anyone
with an understanding of comics and film could get a comics movie
right.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Keaton, whose casting sent fans scurrying to write
letters of disapproval (they seemed incapable of grasping the
concept of acting range) gave an intense, subtle performance of the
type rarely seen in big-budget action spectaculars. His Bruce
Wayne, Batman's alter ego, was almost swallowed whole by anguish.
Burton's gift for art direction _ his animation background gave him
the visual instincts of a comic-book artist _ soothed the pain for
comics cognoscenti and gave Batman entry into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Batman'' was still deeply flawed _ its longueurs may
show too much of a Resnais influence _ it got all the surface
details right; Batman's devices seemed to have come from an Eastern
European Sony store. Keaton's heat gave the film's midnight-blue
coldness a volcanic center, and the movie's box-office assault sent
producers into comics stores looking for more champions of Truth,
Justice and the American Way.
</P>
<P>
   If Batman could be salvaged in the movies, as Superman was years
before, then anything was possible.
</P>
<P>
   What makes comic-book superheroes ideal material for commercial
movies may be the unbridled optimism of most of the classic
characters. The sunny disposition of Superman and Christopher
Reeves' adroit comedic performance in the movies epitomize why
comic books and movies are often called particularly American. When
they work, they belong together.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled lives of comic-book characters that Lee opened up
drifted into nihilism, which is now an intrinsic part of comics.
That grimness is best depicted by British writers, and a couple of
their dank British characters _ Judge Dredd and Tank Girl _
surfaced in motion-picture adaptations and sank quickly. They were
crushed by the films' obviousness: the producers thought that
audiences would understand the movies only if the characters were
oversimplified. That's the problem in making a movie about
characters who aren't as well-known as Superman or Batman. It's
thought that the characters have to be explained, instead of just
letting them define themselves through their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Moore, who is the most dazzlingly gifted writer in this
subculture, created the comics title ``The Watchmen,'' an
apocalyptic turn on superheroes that attracted directors like Terry
Gilliam. Budget considerations brought the project down; apparently
it would have cost almost as much to end the world on a movie set
as it would in real life. Another Moore concept that would have
been much cheaper to realize on screen, and is far more
interesting, is ``Miracleman.'' Essentially, it is Superman as a
horror story. And Moore even had the good sense to ridicule the
Miracleman's flamboyant costume.
</P>
<P>
   The ``X-Men'' comics, too, eventually veered toward gloom _ and
this aspect is the least interesting one of the ``X-Men'' movie _
though most of the heartstring plucking was closer to ``Days of Our
Lives'' than ``Triumph of the Will.'' Still, the ``X-Men'' movie
works harder than any other comics-hero film to lay out the
filigree that comics fans love. There has never been as much
material lifted straight from the comics and put in a picture as in
that movie, and fans are delirious because of it.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``X-Men'' in movie theaters will pave the way for
another wave of superhero films. Other Marvel characters, whose
cheeks are tear-stained beneath their masks, will soon make their
way into theaters. A second ``Blade,'' to be directed by Guillermo
del Toro (``Kronos'') is being readied by the writer David Goyer,
who also wrote the script for the first movie. And, finally, after
years of flirtation with filmmakers like James Cameron and a
rights-ownership battle straight out of ``The Producers'' _
hundreds of people seemed to own 50 percent of the property _ ``The
Amazing Spider-Man'' is not far from production.
</P>
<P>
   Spidey was Marvel's most popular character before the X-Men
eclipsed him, and still defines the medium for most readers.
There's even talk of defibrillating the moribund Batman franchise
for the movies, with Darren Aronofsky (``pi'' and the forthcoming
``Requiem for a Dream'') behind the camera.
</P>
<P>
   In the Spider-Man comics, when the hero approaches a crisis
point _ which is more often than the A train does _ he has to
remind himself that with great power comes great responsibility.
These might be watchwords for the film industry with an eye on
comics as well, minding the slippery slope between inspiration and
slavish devotion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-00 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000724.0554 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-YOUNG-VOTERS-KAN &LR;      07-24 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-VOTERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF POLITICAL INTEREST BY YOUNG PEOPLE BOTH EXASPERATES,
FRIGHTENS  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVE KRASKE, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Steve Majors has seen the statistics. He's
heard the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   His generation does not care about politics. It doesn't care
about government or community affairs or helping neighbors. Voting?
You've got to be kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Majors, 20, doesn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become too complacent,'' Majors says, taking dead aim at
his peer group of 18- to 21-year-olds, 14 million of whom will be
eligible to vote for president for the first time in November. ``We
haven't faced a crisis. We haven't looked death in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to give,'' he says. ``Or something needs to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Majors, a 1998 graduate of Kearney High School, certainly is not
complacent. This week he flies to Philadelphia, where he will take
his place as one of Missouri's 35 delegates to the Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   There he will rank as one of the three or four youngest of the
2,066 GOP delegates. But while getting involved comes as naturally
to Majors as taking a shower, most young people remain wholly
disengaged.
</P>
<P>
   Some statistics:
</P>
<P>
   - In 1972 half of all 18- to 24-year-olds voted. In 1996 only a
third did. In 1998 the total dropped to fewer than one in five,
perhaps the lowest in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   - Even with changes that have made voter registration easier,
only 49 percent of 18- to 24-year-olds were even registered to vote
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   - Being involved in democracy and voting is ``extremely
important'' to only 26 percent of young people, according to one
1999 survey.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys also show that voters between 18 and 24 are surprisingly
conservative in their political outlook. A poll released Monday
showed that young people preferred Texas Gov. George W. Bush over
Vice President Al Gore by 44 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That is heartening to Majors, and he is confident that Bush will
inspire some of his contemporaries to get involved. But it may not
be that simple.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Secretaries of State and other
groups have studied youth attitudes toward voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people today lack interest, trust and knowledge about
American politics, politicians and public life generally,'' noted a
nationwide survey the association released last year. ``In these
and other respects, the future for American democracy seems gloomy
indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey concluded that young people suffer an ``information
and skill deficit'' about the process of voting and of what it
means to be a citizen in a democratic society. The United States,
the report said, is in danger of becoming a divided nation of
voters and nonvoters.
</P>
<P>
   A new generation is coming on the scene that has never voted
before and has never seen its parents vote. That could lead to even
more desultory vote totals in years to come, said Kansas Secretary
of State Ron Thornburgh, who has overseen much of association's
young-voter project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very likely that voter turnout will plummet to 20
(percent) to 30 percent in the next two decades,'' he said. That
could pose hazards, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a 20 percent turnout, it becomes very easy for fringe
elements to control elections,'' Thornburgh said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall turnout has been dropping as well. In 1960, for example,
63 percent of the voting-age population cast ballots for president.
In 1996 49.1 percent did.
</P>
<P>
   The association study, however, also found reasons for hope. Six
in 10 respondents in its poll said government should help families
achieve the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   Still others noted that voluntarism rates had soared among young
people, though many of the most popular volunteer activities did
not involve politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is here that one sees the possibility of democratic
renewal,'' the association report said.
</P>
<P>
   But work still must be done on finding ways to reconnect young
voters to public life. One idea: Get candidates to focus more on
issues that concern younger people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one universal thing I got out of kids during nine days on
the road, and I heard it over and over again, is young people said
they weren't being listened to,'' said Erica Terry, a member of
MTV's Choose or Lose team that traversed the country this year
talking to young people. On Sunday, MTV will broadcast ``Choose or
Lose: Why Care?'' focusing on the youth vote.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of voters tune out when a candidate shows up on campus and
talks about school vouchers or improving elementary education,
Terry said. They would rather hear their needs addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids need money for school, to pay off their loans,'' she
said. ``Those are the things politicians should come to my town and
talk about. Not about whether grandma should get her prescription
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Another impediment, noted Karenna Gore Schiff, daughter of the
vice president, is the political system itself. Writing in
Newsweek, the 26-year-old Schiff said her contemporaries hesitated
to get involved because many assumed that the system was rigged in
favor of well-financed special interests.
</P>
<P>
   That, and the difficulty in obtaining objective information
about candidates, ``push us to take refuge in ironic detachment,''
she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political leaders should understand young people's
nonparticipation as a strong message in itself: The system needs to
be cleansed of special-interest money and made more accessible to
the grass roots of young America,'' Schiff said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though, candidates are not likely to focus on
young voters when their turnout remains so abysmal. Their attention
naturally drifts toward the 67 percent of Americans older than 65
who vote.
</P>
<P>
   At MTV, Terry said young people had to take the first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a better job of hammering home this point: If
you don't vote, the politicians are not going to pay attention,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Majors, a junior at Truman State University in Kirksville,
his decision to get involved was instinctive. Although his parents
are not active politically, Majors was drawn into public affairs
because of his interest in how institutions work.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative, he worked for Republican presidential candidate
Alan Keyes earlier this year. Why didn't he back Bush then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I should answer that one,'' he said before
pointing to Bush's ``too soft'' rhetoric on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he is grateful just to have an opportunity to
demonstrate that not all 20-somethings are apolitical. He wears his
involvement like a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important,'' Majors said, ``not to get too big a head on
these things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
