<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
AS MOVIE EXHIBITORS PUSH TOWARD AN UNCERTAIN ENDING, AMC IS
CONFIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- AMC -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JENNIFER MANN, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street has written a hold-your-breath cliff-hanger for the
movie exhibition business that, unlike many movies, isn't neatly
tied up in a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Penciled into the plot is the dreaded word ``bankruptcy.'' And
no one knows for sure who's going to be left standing when the
credits roll.
</P>
<P>
   One movie exhibition firm, United Artists Theater Circuit Inc.,
which defaulted on a loan payment in April, is teetering on the
edge of the cliff and is expected to plunge into Chapter 11
bankruptcy any day.
</P>
<P>
   The question then becomes: Is there someone who comes after
United Artists? And if so, who is most likely to be next into the
bankruptcy chute?
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kuzio, fixed-income analyst for KDP Investments, said that
based on a ranking system his firm uses, Kansas City-based AMC
Entertainment Inc. has a 25 percent likelihood of defaulting on its
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Kuzio likened the exhibition industry to the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't make any money if you're flying around with empty
seats,'' Kuzio said. ``And in exhibition, there's too many seats
and not enough people to fill them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Brown, chairman of AMC, is scripting a different
ending for his company _ and it's a happy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of dials that are flashing `warning' right now
on Wall Street,'' Brown said. ``I think we're all getting painted
by the same brush ... but we have a whole different situation than
many others.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition industry knows it has too many movie screens. The
rule of thumb is one screen per 10,000 people, so there should be
about 28,000 movie screens in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the screen count is somewhere between 35,000 and 38,000
screens, translating into a 25 percent to 37 percent capacity glut.
</P>
<P>
   Blame for the overbuilding, some say, belongs to Stan Durwood,
the longtime chairman of AMC who died a year ago. Durwood
revolutionized the industry when he pioneered the multiplex _ the
modern movie theater complex.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, Durwood had opened a megaplex, the Grand 24 in Dallas,
a movie house with 24 screens. As the Grand 24 drew droves of
moviegoers, competitors took notice.
</P>
<P>
   Soon everyone with a stash of cash or a credit line was jumping
on the megaplex bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Now the biggest players in the industry, including AMC, are
sagging under the glut of smaller theaters rendered obsolete by the
megaplexes. They're also trying to stay in the pack of those
building the mammoth movie houses. And building megaplexes and
taking outdated theaters out of commission are both costly.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, most exhibitors are losing money. For
instance, in the fiscal year that ended March 30, AMC lost $55.2
million, compared with a loss of $16 million the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The four largest exhibitors in the United States _ Regal, Loews
Cineplex Entertainment Corp., Carmike Cinemas Inc. and AMC _ as a
group lost $340 million in their most recent fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the huge losses, analysts on Wall Street have sharply
downgraded their debt ratings for almost every big exhibitor. The
only exception is Cinemark, and it is up for review soon with, in
the analysts' terminology, ``negative implications.''
</P>
<P>
   On just one day last month, Russell Solomon of Moody's Investors
Service axed ratings on $4.425 billion in debt held by the big four
exhibitors. Those cuts pushed everyone's debt deeper into the junk
bond pile.
</P>
<P>
   And just last week, AMC reported it had lost $13 million for the
quarter that ended June 30. Adjusted earnings before interest,
taxes, depreciation and amortization _ a number that analysts study
to determine whether an exhibitor has enough money to service its
debt _ fell to $24.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brown blames the bad showing on the last three weeks of June,
when film product petered out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just pure wind shear, those last three weeks,'' Brown
said. ``Until then, we were in the game in terms of making our
projections.''
</P>
<P>
   So what could happen once a film exhibition company files for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization?
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
